<SLUG> BC-VODAPHONE-MANNESMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VODAFONE, STOCK PRICE RISING, PRESSES MANNESMANN TALKS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT _ Faced with the near certainty of succumbing to a
$160 billion hostile takeover against Vodafone AirTouch PLC,
Mannesmann AG continued to negotiate Wednesday for a peaceful
surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gent, Vodafone's chief executive, remained in Duesseldorf,
Mannesmann's hometown, as negotiators for the two companies worked
past midnight on a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are talks under way,'' Gent told the German television
network NTV tonight. People close to Mannesmann said the talks were
still about the price, but those differences have narrowed because
the value of Vodafone's all-stock offer has surged as a result of
the rise in Vodafone's own share price.
</P>
<P>
   So negotiators have been focusing instead on comparatively
technical management and structural issues. Mannesmann's embattled
chief executive, Klaus Esser, scheduled a meeting of the company's
supervisory board for Thursday afternoon though it was unclear
whether a deal would be ready by then.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann has sought a deal that could be presented as a merger
of equals. Until recently, Esser had been insisting that Mannesmann
shareholders receive more than 50 percent of the shares in the
combined company. Vodafone, which has a larger market
capitalization than Mannesmann, is offering 47.2 percent but has
said it would sweeten the offer to 49 percent if Esser agreed to a
friendly deal.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Esser has almost no room for maneuver. Vodafone shares,
which climbed nearly 7 percent in London trading Wednesday to 3.855
pounds, are now so high that its all-stock offer for Mannesmann is
worth 342 euros a share or $333.69 at current exchange rates. That
is more than twice the price that Mannesmann shares traded at six
months ago and is virtually equal to the level of 350 euros a share
that Esser had contended reflected the true' value for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann shares, meanwhile, soared again Wednesday for the
third consecutive day. climbing 9.7 percent, to 325 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the extraordinary surge in Mannesmann shares
reflected a nearly universal conviction by investors that Vodafone
would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, people close to Mannesmann say that Esser is prepared to
resign as chief executive and has no interest in remaining with the
company if Vodafone takes control.
</P>
<P>
   Esser has come under intense pressure from some members of
Mannesmann's supervisory board, as well as from his own
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Board members like Henning Schulte-Noelle, the chairman of the
insurance conglomerate Allianz AG, and Juergen E. Schrempp,
chairman of DaimlerChrysler AG, have been pushing Esser to accept a
friendly deal.
</P>
<P>
   Esser's dwindling hopes of retaining a majority of shareholders
were all but shattered on Sunday, when Vodafone negotiated a new
alliance with Vivendi SA, the French media and utilities group.
</P>
<P>
   That move derailed Esser's own hopes of negotiating a merger
with Vivendi, which would have given Mannesmann control of France's
second largest wireless network as well as a major stake in Canal
Plus SA, Europe's biggest pay-television company.
</P>
<P>
   Lars Berg, the head of Mannesmann's core telecommunications
group, confirmed Wednesday what people close to the companies
indicated more than a week ago: that Mannesmann had hoped to
negotiate a full merger with Vivendi until it was outmaneuvered by
Vodafone.
</P>
<P>
   Had Esser been able to at least announce an agreement in
principle with Vivendi, he could have laid claim to control of
wireless networks covering more than two-thirds of Europe's
population _ in Germany, Italy, Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
   As if that were not enough, Vodafone and Vivendi also appeared
poised to unravel Esser's other major defensive initiative: a major
alliance with America Online's European business.
</P>
<P>
   Esser has been feverishly negotiating a deal in which he would
acquire part of Bertelsmann AG's 50-percent stake in AOL Europe.
But Wednesday, Vivendi announced that it was in talks with AOL
Europe as well.
</P>
<P>
   American depository receipts of Vodafone _ each representing 10
shares of the British company _ rose $4.125, or 7 percent, to $63
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The recent rise in Vodafone shares suggests that many investors
and analysts accept Gent's vision of the benefits that will come
when his company controls Mannesmann. As a result, analysts have
raised their projections for both Vodafone and Mannesmann. Andrew
Moffat, telecommunications analyst with ABN Amro in London, said
Vodafone shares have received an added boost from a technical
side-effect of the merger. If Vodafone acquires Mannesmann, its
weight within FTSE index of leading British stocks would rise from
6 percent to 12 percent. That would then trigger heavy buying from
investment funds that reflect the index.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
