<HEADLINE>
TROJANS LEANING ON FIVE PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One starter averaged seven minutes per game last
season. Another barely hit 30 percent of his shots from the field
in conference games. A third struggled just to be the best player
on his high school basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   And almost all of them were either ignored or lightly recruited
by what most would consider the major college basketball schools.
</P>
<P>
   But USC has managed to stun skeptics by clinging to a share of
first place in the Pacific-10 Conference with five players and
little else. How much longer the Trojans (13-6, 6-1) will stay
among the Pac-10's elite is unknown, but few observers thought they
could get this far.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people probably figure we'll crack at any moment, but
I don't think it'll happen any time soon,'' shooting guard Jeff
Trepagnier said.
</P>
<P>
   If there are skeptics, it might be for the fact USC has
basically become a five-man team since leading scorer Sam Clancy
(broken foot) and top reserve Jarvis Turner (broken ankle) went
down two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Henry Bibby played his starters 39 minutes against
Oregon State last Saturday, waiting until 57.2 seconds remained
before making his first substitution.
</P>
<P>
   It might sound crazy to think five players could survive the
final 11 conference games, but other Pac-10 coaches are not ready
to write off the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it takes is five players,'' Arizona State coach Rob Evans
said. ``If you take a look at most people's rosters, most play five
guys with maybe a sixth or a seventh getting a few minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   So who are these five guys, who are relatively unknown outside
the lightly populated world of USC basketball fans? Here's a look
at the players with whom USC is making its unlikely run toward the
NCAA Tournament:
</P>
<P>
   JEFF TREPAGNIER
</P>
<P>
   The 40-inch vertical leap aside, the 6-foot-4 Trepagnier is
making an impact this season with his defense, notably his 3.8
steals per game (second-best in the nation), and his rebounding
(6.7 per game).
</P>
<P>
   Another second-tier player in high school, he was plucked by
Bibby away from schools like Washington State and Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a kid who couldn't make a jump shot to save his life but
never stopped shooting,'' Bibby said. ``That's good. You can't
teach athleticism, but you can teach shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff might take some bad shots, but he will make it up with a
deflection or a tip or a steal. The kid basically plays hard every
night. I can't complain about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier's shooting has sometimes been a sore spot, but in
Pac-10 play, he's made 7 of 15 3-pointers. And he hasn't lost his
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was relieved to hit all three of his 3-point shots
against Oregon State last week, Trepagnier said: ``It really didn't
matter because I was going to keep shooting anyways.''
</P>
<P>
   BRANDON GRANVILLE
</P>
<P>
   Although the injury to Clancy was viewed as devastating because
he led the Trojans in scoring and rebounding, the one player USC
relies on most is the 5-9 Granville.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one player they simply cannot afford to lose for
any reason,'' Pac-10 TV analyst Dan Belluomini said.
</P>
<P>
   Granville runs USC's offense and is averaging 40.1 minutes in
conference play, including one overtime game. He has six
double-doubles this season and nine double-digit assists
performances.
</P>
<P>
   When Bibby offered him a scholarship two years ago, he was
mulling offers from West Coast Conference schools such as Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has been inspiring about this team is other guys besides
Scalabrine are getting better,'' Bibby said. ``Brandon Granville is
better than last year. He had 21 points and 11 assists against
Oregon State. He didn't have too many games like that last year.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also shooting 40 percent this season, after a disastrous
30.2 in Pac-10 play last season.
</P>
<P>
   BRIAN SCALABRINE
</P>
<P>
   If the Trojans had a go-to guy, it would be the 6-9 Scalabrine.
But even he was barely recruited out of high school and attended
junior college in Washington. He committed to USC before most major
colleges were able to figure out he was a big-time player. He has
been the heart of the team since Clancy's injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see now is what you will see 10 years from now from
Brian Scalabrine,'' Bibby said. ``Brian Scalabrine plays as hard as
he can play every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his scoring and rebounding, Scalabrine provides
invaluable help for point guard Granville because his dribbling
skills are impressive for a post player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scalabrine is a good ballhandler,'' Oregon State coach Eddie
Payne said. ``I think you can try to press them some, but I don't
think that will have the desired effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine has also improved an aspect of his game, making 47
percent of his 3-pointers this season.
</P>
<P>
   DAVID BLUTHENTHAL
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the 6-7 forward could barely crack USC's rotation,
averaging 7.2 minutes a game, which placed him behind nine other
players. Bibby said he should have redshirted him, and he was the
one player last season who didn't get a fair chance.
</P>
<P>
   But Bluthenthal has recovered nicely from a lackluster freshman
year and made huge strides in Pac-10 play. He rarely takes poor
shots and is USC's third-leading scorer (15.7 points) in conference
games.
</P>
<P>
   His turning point probably came two weeks ago, when he tied a
school record with 28 rebounds against Arizona State, and followed
up two nights later with a career-high 26 points against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids sometimes need one or two breakout games to get their
game going,'' Bibby said. ``His last four or five games have been
his best games.''
</P>
<P>
   NATE HAIR
</P>
<P>
   This is where USC's season really gets strange. Last year, the
6-4 Hair didn't even make the Orange County All-Area team after an
inconsistent senior season at Capistrano Valley High. He then
suffered a stress fracture in his knee during the fall and Bibby
considered it doubtful he would play this season.
</P>
<P>
   He was a little-used substitute before seizing an opportunity
after injuries devastated the Trojans. In the two Oregon games last
weekend, Hair averaged 13.5 points, five rebounds and 3.5 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he had the ability,'' Trepagnier said. ``We just told
him to just keep shooting it. But I thought he was going to
redshirt. He thought he would redshirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Hair isn't afraid to shoot, but he also understands his role on
the team, which means not forcing bad shots but taking open
jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what my job is, I'm the fifth option,'' Hair said.
</P>
<P>
   On this Trojan team, that's as good as saying the final option.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
