<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG RECRUITING DAY FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Paul Hackett was more excited Wednesday than he
had been on his two previous signing days as USC's head coach.
</P>
<P>
   And he had reason to be, if you listen to the recruiting
experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``USC looks like they're going to win the Pac-10,'' said Rick
Kimbrel, e ditor of PrepStar recruiting magazine. ``They're No. 1
in the Pac-10 without question.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans signed 17 players to national letters of intent,
along with three junior college players who have already enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely delighted,'' Hackett said. ``The coaches did a
fabulou s job of finishing. I think that's what was different than
a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   USC won several late battles, getting Mater Dei of Santa strong
safety Matt Grootegoed, who had UCLA as his No. 2 choice, and
Harvard-Westlake tight end Alex Holmes, who had been considering
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' class could be even better, but they were still
waiting for Mira Mesa of San Diego linebacker Amon Gordon and
quarterback Teyo Johnson to make their decisions. Neither player is
expected to announce before next week.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett was already gushing about the impact Holmes and
Grootegoed would make next season.
</P>
<P>
   On Grootegoed: ``We have needed a signature leader in the
defense. This guy is the ideal football player in my mind. The way
he plays the game will affect our entire football team. This was a
guy we had to get.''
</P>
<P>
   On Holmes: ``I think Holmes will challenge (starter) Antoine
Harris for playing time and puts USC in a two tight-end offense
much, much, more than last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett even said USC could go to a three tight-end offense with
Woodlan d Hills Taft signee Gregg Guenther also in the mix for
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   For immediate impact, though, the player who could make the
quickest splash is cornerback Chris Cash of Palomar College. Cash
is already tentatively slated to start at cornerback, with starter
Kris Richard lik ely to move to free safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, Chris Cash was the best corner in the nation,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans also added a vital wide receiver in Oxnard Hueneme's
Keary Colbert. With not much else besides their three freshman
receivers returning, Colbert will get plenty of playing time.
</P>
<P>
   This class also included five offensive linemen and three
defensive linemen, areas Hackett said have been shorthanded for two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a huge step to build the lines here at USC,'' Hackett
said. `` We did what I said two years ago was so important -- to
build a foundation on the offensive and defensive lines.''
</P>
<P>
   The star of the line is Anaheim Servite tackle Joe McGuire,
which one service listed as its No. 1 prospect in the state at any
position.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a downside, it was that USC signed only one
tailback, Chris Howard of Wilmington Banning, after Hackett said
the position would be his No. 1 priority a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we would have liked another runner. It's more of a
premium fo r next year,'' Hackett said. ``But I'm very excited
about Chris. We're loo king at who's going to be the future guy
running the football.''
</P>
<P>
   USC lost out on getting tailbacks Marcus Houston (Colorado) and
Maurice Morris (Oregon) in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   One player who did not show up on USC's list of signees is
defensive tackle Sagan Atuatasi of Los Alamitos. Atuatasi is
currently attending Cypress College and has reaffirmed his
commitment, but he is not require d to sign a letter of intent.
</P>
<P>
   With every high school recruit a Southern California native,
Hackett sai d he would scale back further on national recruiting,
after trying to recr uit in Florida, Louisiana and Texas the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Trojans are expected to add another junior-colleg e
recruit to complete this class. . . . Wide receiver Troy Garner of
Notre Dame High in Sherman Oaks will take a medical redshirt,
Hackett said, because of a knee injury suffered last spring. . . .
Tight end Jacob Rog ers has been switched to offensive line while
defensive back Sandy Fletcher has been moved to wide receiver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
