<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4978 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     02-03 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS COULD HAVE DONE BETTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the first time in three years, signing day at
UCLA did not include a string of superlatives, a top-five ranking
or program-alteringtalent. In other words, the class of 2000 is a
step below those of 1998 and 99 - if not in quality then certainly
in quantity.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had 18 scholarships available and signed just 14
players. That's not necessarily a problem - the roster's loaded
with underclassmen - and it might be a blessing. With 12 seniors
next season, the four remaining scholarships will be applied
towards Signing Day 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We easily could have signed 18, but we decided not to go after
a bunch of guys that would be fill-ins,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they signed several prep all-somethings to fill
pressing needs at defensive back (Ben Emanuel), receiver (Tab
Perry) and punter (Chris Kluwe). Other top prospects include
LaMirada offensive lineman Paul Mociler, Carlsbad linebacker
Brandon Chillar and Saugus fullback Patrick Norton. When the
recruiting ink dries, it seems, UCLA's class probably will stand as
one of the 25 best in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But it could have been better. The Bruins had 14 commitments
secured weeks ago, then failed to land four top players in the
final days:
</P>
<P>
   - Denver tailback Marcus Houston, brother of UCLA sophomore
Lovell, who signed with Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   - Sherman Oaks defensive end Travis Johnson, who signed with
Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   - North Hollywood tight end Alex Holmes, who chose the immediate
playing time available at USC. (The Bruins return their top-three
tight ends, Gabe Crecion, Bryan Fletcher and Mike Seidman.)
</P>
<P>
   - Santa Ana safety Matt Grootegoed, who picked USC after hinting
for months that he'd sign with UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players UCLA got are definitely of good quality, but they
only got 14 of them,'' said Greg Biggins, a recruiting expert for
Student Sports Magazine. ``They're usually trying to find
scholarships. This year, they couldn't give them away. They're
probably still a top-20 class, but they didn't finish very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo attributed the unused scholarships to selective
recruiting and the highly-ranked 1998-99 classes. In addition,
receiver Brian Poli-Dixon and cornerbacks Jason Bell and Marques
Anderson will muddle the depth chart after redshirtng in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all was said and done, some (recruits) were scared off,''
Toledo said. ``I'm a little surprised because I thought we'd get
somebody (in the final weeks), but they were all high-profile guys
and you're not going to get them all. They see who's on the team
and who has committed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins did not sign a quarterback or a defensive lineman,
long their weakest unit but now a position of strength.
</P>
<P>
   They also lost Long Beach City College defensive end Scott
Parkhurst, who chose Nevada-Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told him there were some classes he needed to take, and he
wasn't willing to take them,'' Toledo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 0022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
