<HEADER>
A4979 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN     02-03 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLD RICE A GOOD RECIPE FOR FOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Glen Rice's minutes and production are decreasing.
Rick Fox's minutes are increasing. Rice seems at odds with coach
Phil Jackson, and at times, with teammates.
</P>
<P>
   And, by the way, the Rice trade rumors are heating up again.
</P>
<P>
   That last fact might have nothing to do with the others, but the
timing is hard to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Laker officials, both publicly and privately, continue to insist
Rice will not be traded, even though he might walk away as a free
agent this summer. But speculation around the league the last few
days has Rice being offered to Chicago for Bulls forward Toni Kukoc
or to Philadelphia for second-year guard Larry Hughes and forward
Tyrone Hill.
</P>
<P>
   As per usual, the Lakers are not commenting.
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing unclear about what's happening on the
court. In two straight games, Rice has struggled early and been
benched late. He made just 3 of 14 field-goal attempts in those
games, both Lakers losses.
</P>
<P>
   Rice expressed irritation at not getting scoring chances Sunday
at Houston. Jackson responded that Rice perhaps ``didn't deserve''
the scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jackson sat Rice for the entire second and fourth quarters
Tuesday at San Antonio. He played just 23 minutes, his
second-lowest total this season, and the fewest minutes he's played
in a loss.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Lakers need to keep Rice as a third scorer behind
Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, he's failing in that role. Rice
finished with five points at Houston and seven points at San
Antonio _ the first time this season he's failed to score in double
digits in consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fox _ who could regain a starting job if Rice is
traded _ is getting longer stints on the court. He's still playing
less than 20 minutes per game, but Jackson is now playing Fox for a
quarter at a time.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to have helped Fox's game. He played the first nine
minutes of the second quarter Sunday and got six points en route to
an 11-point game (his first double-digit total in 14 games). He
played all but one minute of the second quarter Tuesday and came up
with four points, two assists, a steal and a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Scoring) grooves in short minutes come and go,'' Fox said.
``And wanting to contribute in some fashion while I'm out there has
always been the focus. Unfortunately, we haven't as a team been
playing the way we've been capable of playing, and that's more
frustrating than anything. So, glad to be out there but I'd like to
see a better outcome for us as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Respite: Jackson gave the Lakers, losers of six of their last
nine games, the day off Wednesday, musing that perhaps they needed
time away from each other.
</P>
<P>
   They'll try to avoid their first three-game losing streak of the
season when they play host to the Utah Jazz on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just kind of in a rut,'' O'Neal said. ``We're not
playing well, we're not hitting shots, we're not playing good
defense, so we just have to look in the mirrors at our individual
selves and just pick it up.... But I'm not worried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 0022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4980 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a N.H.WINBOOSTSMCCAINCOFFE     02-03 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 N.H. WIN BOOSTS MCCAIN COFFERS  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Money, the lifeblood of a politi cal campaign, came gushing in
to Sen. John McCain's presidential bid at a record pace Wednesday
on the strength of his huge victory in New Hampshire's Re publican
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions were expected to total $500,000 within 24 hours of
the Arizona senator's 19 percent age-point drubbing of Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, said Wes Gullett of Phoenix, deputy campaign
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the ease of credit card giving over the Internet,
donations flowed faster, reached a higher total and came from a
wider range of sources than ever before in a presidential race,
McCain's campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question,'' said Dan Schnur, communications director at
McCain's national headquar ters in Alexandria, Va. ``It's in
credible.''
</P>
<P>
   The donations likely will prove to be worth an additional
$300,000 in federal matching funds, Gullett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Response was immediate'' af ter the magnitude of the victory
became clear shortly after polls closed, Schnur said. ``We raised
$20,000 in the first hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, 5,000 visitors to the Web site signed up throughout
the day as volunteers in the campaign, swelling the ranks of 72,000
grass-roots supporters by 7 percent, Schnur and Gullett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to presidential poli tics 2000,'' beamed Doug Cole,
McCain's press secretary in Ari zona. ``This is a new era. You can
have a major political event and have that type of immediate
interactive response.''
</P>
<P>
   The volume of traffic on the Web site, www.mccain2000.com, was
so heavy Wednesday that it overloaded and shut down one of the five
computers feeding the Web site across the Internet, Cole said. A
backup computer was pressed into service, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of more conven tional fund-raisers, such as
$1,000-a-plate dinners in several major cities, also are in the
works for McCain. But some events will have an additional twist or
two. Satellite television hookups to similar gatherings in other
cities are planned, and some will feature transmissions over the
Internet to supporters who pay $100 for a password to log on to the
Webcasts, campaign officials said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's Internet fund-raising had been running at about $10,000
a day through mid-De cember, Gullett said, and totaled about $1.5
million by the time of the pivotal New Hampshire pri mary. That
means the total leaped by about one-third in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   Other McCain staff members had been more skeptical than Gullett
about the power of the Internet but now have realized its
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schnur said, ``we haven't figured out anything that Ama
zon.com didn't figure out a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has attracted the most money of any presidential
candidate, has received $260,000 over the Internet throughout the
campaign, spokesman Scott Mc Clellan said in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Bush's setback Tuesday night had triggered any
change in the pattern of giving, McClellan said, ``We're continu
ing to receive strong support from people across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The speed with which e-contri butions become available means
they can be put to work imme diately, Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
   Gullett estimated that in previ ous elections, the lag time be
tween an attention-grabbing victory in New Hampshire and the
receipt and processing of mailed checks was two to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you're talking about half a dozen clicks,'' Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
   Although one explanation for the surge of contributions is
people's natural desire to back a winner, a larger influence was
Tuesday night's proof that Bush's nomination was far from inevita
ble, Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
   Many contributors had said they wanted to support McCain, but
only if his candidacy proved viable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The demographics underlying the surge of Internet contribu tions
buoyed McCain staffers.
</P>
<P>
   Donations were averaging around $114, and Schnur said the
largest group was in the 25-to-44 age bracket, much younger than
traditional donors. Forty percent had never given to a presidential
campaign before, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been refreshing to us all to see that we're bringing new
people into the political process, which is one of the important
things that John McCain's candi dacy is all about,'' Gullett said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 0023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
