<HEADER>
A4985 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-03 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE voice on the other end of the telephone line belonged to a
University of Houston football recruiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stuck in traffic,'' the recruiter told a local high school
coach in 1997. ``I'll be there as soon as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   The recruiter never showed.
</P>
<P>
   At another local high school in 1998, a Houston football
recruiter arrived late for a spring football game. He was given a
videotape of the game and watched about an hour's worth. Then he
scribbled a few names on a Post-It, stuck the paper on the head
coach's office door and left without saying a word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need more information on these kids,'' the note said. The
Post-It was trashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy made me feel like I was bothering him,'' the coach
said. ``He wouldn't give me the time of day.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the way during Kim Helton's tenure as Cougars
head coach, things went terribly wrong. One local coach called it
``recruiting by proxy.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton's coaching staff knew its way around Florida, or the juco
trails, but not Houston. Helton's heart might have been in the
right place, but his recruiters were lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to where I never even saw U of H guys,'' a longtime
high school head coach said. ``They might have been recruiting
hard, but I didn't see it. They never walked out their own back
door to see what was out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana Dimel, on the other hand, is trying to kick the son of a
gun in, to paraphrase legendary local coach Bum Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Dimel is anything but legendary on the local high
school scene. In fact, of the five high school coaches who on
Wednesday offered their opinions on UH football recruiting 2000,
exactly one knew Dimel's name four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But today, while the Texas Longhorns make more national
headlines with their latest super-stud class, and Texas A&AMP;M
promises to put the Wreck back in its Crew with an arsenal of
defensive talent, Dana Dimel is simply making a name for himself.
</P>
<P>
   And that means something to the people who matter most _ local
high school football coaches, who for the first time in years feel
welcome among the Cougars' football staffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know Dana Dimel from anybody,'' said North Shore
coach David Aymond, who saw two of his players, Mark Hopkins and
Justin Davis, sign with UH on Wednesday. ``But he came out here and
talked. We just talked _ nothing to do with X's and O's. From that
first day on, I knew his style and demeanor were winners. He talks,
and he listens. He is genuinely interested in the high school
programs in the area. He's linking the gap that was there before.''
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, during Helton's tenure the gap between this
town's high schools and the university that carries this town's
name was monstrous. In 1999, just six of the high school recruits
signed by Helton were from the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his recruiting focus, or lack thereof, Helton
pointed to A&AMP;M and Texas' dominating presence, or talked of needing
a quick fix via the junior-college ranks.
</P>
<P>
   It was astounding to imagine that while virtually every major
program in the country considered Houston a vital stop, UH was
unimpressed. Those most astounded: local high school coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never could put a finger on why they didn't emphasize our
area,'' La Marque coach Larry Walker said. ``I guess they thought
the major guys got everybody. But if you draw a circle around the
Greater Houston area and count the number of football players, it's
a whole bunch. There's no way (the big schools) could get
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, they didn't. Dimel's first Cougars recruiting class
certainly made no national top-10 lists, but it was good and deep
and varied, covering virtually every position.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, it made inroads among the fraternity of
local coaches. And as much as that means now, it will mean more
later. Some 11 of the 13 high schoolers in the class of 19 UH
signees are from area schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't just talk the talk,'' Dimel told an enthused crowd
of alumni Wednesday at the Cougars' signing party.
</P>
<P>
   UH recruiters didn't make a lot of plane reservations, either,
and that was the best news of all for the Cougars faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think this is the best place I've ever been in terms
of being successful,'' Dimel said. ``Everything's in place. There
might be a few players out (of state) that might have connections
here. But it's not in my best interests to leave the state of
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Heck, he has only been here a few months, and Dimel already
knows the key to it all: The Cougars don't even need to leave town.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
