<SLUG> BC-VICTIMS-ACCEPT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES, FRIENDS PAINFULLY ACCEPT LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the search for Flight 261 survivors abandoned, families of
the 88 passengers and crew prepared to visit the crash site in
hopes of easing their grief.
</P>
<P>
   They included Fred Ost, who traveled from Skokie, Ill., to be
closer to where five relatives died Monday when the ill-fated
Alaska Airlines flight plunged into the Santa Barbara Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would have been too much. For it to be five - I cannot
even describe it,'' said a tearful Ost, 47. ``I want to go out on a
boat and reflect, remember and place a flower.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines will help bus families to the shore Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to be doing is promoting silence, a moment of
prayers, a moment of thought of those families and friends,'' said
John Kelley, the airline's chief executive officer. A memorial is
scheduled for Saturday, at a time and place to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   As the reality of their tremendous losses began to set in,
family members braced Wednesday for the grim task of working with
coroners' investigators to identify loved ones. In a private
meeting with about 100 people, investigators said they would ask
families for dental records, hair samples and other information.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of crying,'' said Greg Ford, a brother-in-law
of one victim, Bob Ost, 39, a San Mateo firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Ost was killed with his wife, Ileana; their 4-month-old
daughter, Emily; Ost's mother, Jean Permison, 73, of Scotts Valley;
and her companion of 10 years, Charles Russell.
</P>
<P>
   The five had gone to Puerto Vallarta last week to celebrate
Permison's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my mom's 73rd birthday, and Bob thought it would be
nice to take her and Charlie away for a couple of days,'' said
Janis Ost Ford, 36, Permison's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said she expected her mother to return in time for a
birthday dinner Tuesday with Russell. Instead, she grieved their
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is going to make me a different person. Our life
is going to be very different from now,'' she said in between
floods of tears at her hotel room. ``I just want to know that our
family members didn't suffer and it was fast. To lose your family
nembers, you always think this stuff happens to other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Janis Ford said closure will take time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work with kids all the time and I'm up all the time, but I
don't feel a smile in here,'' she said, holding the edges of her
mouth with her hands. ``And I miss my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Another victim in the crash, Renato Bermudez, was described as a
well-liked firefighter whose mother had recently bought a house in
Granada Hills. He was heading home from a visit to his girlfriend,
who was spending the winter near Puerto Vallarta.
</P>
<P>
   Based in San Francisco, Bermudez was named Firefighter of the
Year in 1999 for rescuing an elderly man from the second floor of a
burning building in the Mission District on July 3, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a passionate, literate man who loved his work and was
proud of the team he was part of,'' said Jim Gallagher, a retired
firefighter who worked with Bermudez. ``He used to volunteer his
time training other firefighters and trainees in a running program
we had in Golden Gate Park.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Dominic Berbeo contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
