<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO SUNNY FOR A GOOD CLAMBAKE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARMEL, Calif. _ The weather here sucks. Blue skies, gentle
breezes, the sun glinting off $300 sunglasses and sunscreened
face-lifts. They're trying to play the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National
Pro-Am starting Thursday, and so far we're staring at the gloomy
prospect of five days of perfect hair for Kevin Costner.
</P>
<P>
   Bing Crosby, can you please talk to someone up there and get
this straightened out? Otherwise it's just the Tucson Open with a
cooler water hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the tournament officials will come to their senses and
postpone play until we can get a decent typhoon or hailstorm.
</P>
<P>
   It's not really the Crosby (as old-timers still call the
tourney) until the first celebrity gets blown off the 17th green
and onto the rocks below, a sacrificial offering to the gods of the
Clambake (as really old-timers still call the tourney).
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is the greatest golf tournament in the world,
because it transcends golf, which can use some transcending. The
format is for each pro player to be paired with a celebrity. The
pros think of this as Take a Doofus to Work Week.
</P>
<P>
   It makes for some amazing situations, such as a couple years ago
when Tiger Woods was paired with Costner, and Woods complained
because too many people were taking snapshots.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that!
</P>
<P>
   If you invented a tournament like this today, the golfers' union
would shoot it down in an instant. Golfers today are much more
serious than brain surgeons, because brain surgeons get mulligans.
</P>
<P>
   But they put up with it, and the fans love it. You throw in the
celebrity element, and now you've got stuff to talk about other
than Davis Love II's short irons.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this year's celebrity field is thinner than
Calista Flockhart after a tofu souffle. The dropouts included Bill
Murray, Michael Jordan, Michael Douglas and Jack Lemmon.
</P>
<P>
   Carmel this week is the only place in the world where you can
hear people say, ``Gee, I sure miss that nutball Donald Trump.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity field, frankly, could use some shoring up. No
offense to any of the AT&AMP;T's regular cast, but would you rather
follow Glen Campbell or John Rocker?
</P>
<P>
   Or how about Bill Clinton, or the Spice Girls?
</P>
<P>
   Or any woman. There's not a female in the field. I can't believe
they couldn't have landed a Cameron Diaz or Janet Reno or Oprah
Winfrey or Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was the all-celeb day, a five-hole mini-tourney with
the 10 biggest celebrities playing together in one big clump. It
was cute, but also disillusioning, like when Tommy Smothers
out-drove Hercules.
</P>
<P>
   One way to improve the tournament would be to require the celebs
to dress in costume. Who wants to see Hercules in a golf shirt?
Make Kevin Sorbo dress like Hercules, and let's see Clint Eastwood
as Dirty Harry, sneering at the gallery. Jerry Rice, put on some
pads and a jersey.
</P>
<P>
   On the first tee, the rule for the celebs was ``Hit 'til you're
happy,'' which is also the rule at any of the singles bars in
Monterey and Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   John Elway out-drove everyone else by about 100 yards, and it's
painfully obvious this guy wasted the best years of his golf career
tossing around a football.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Romano took some toupee-sized divots, and the buzz behind
the fairway ropes was that ``Everybody fears Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday is the real thing, which means that the entire event
has boiled down to two words: Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, most of the golfers considered him the greatest
player on the tour. Then he took his game up about two notches,
grooved his swing and started lifting weights.
</P>
<P>
   And he was already the Mark McGwire of golf. He has changed the
game. Now when you hear someone at Pebble Beach talking about the
17-Mile Drive, they're referring to a Tiger tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has won five tournaments in a row and is on such an
incredible roll that any day now, the rest of the pros are going to
show up wearing T-shirts that say ``Tiger's Caddies.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's ``celebrity'' partner is Jerry Chang, who is famous for
being one of Tiger's teammates at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Chang) won't get in the way, he won't be chit-chatting or
talking,'' Woods said Wednesday. ``He will be serious. ... That's
something that's nice and refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   And dull. Tiger's got this tournament on his shoulders. He's the
most watchable pro  &UR; and  &LR; the celebrity with the most star quality.
He's the show.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger is even rooting for bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just something that I've always enjoyed, that type of
challenge,'' he said. ``You have to grind it out, and more
importantly, it separates a lot of players. Some of the guys don't
want to be out there'' in bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers are the most pampered of athletes, and you have to love
a guy who roots for harsh conditions.
</P>
<P>
   That makes two of us rooting for a monster storm to blow in off
the Pacific Thursday, with heavy swells crashing against the cliffs
edging the 18th green. Ah, I love the smell of salt brine and
golfer's fear in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Call me Ishmael.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
