<SLUG> BC-CALIFORNIA-CAMPAIGNING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS' BIG CONTEST IS IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Fresh from the battlefields of New Hampshire,
Democratic presidential candidates Al Gore and Bill Bradley are
rushing to California this week to kick off what is expected to be
a tough _ and potentially nasty _ fight to round up support in this
critical state.
<P>
   Vice President Gore was scheduled to arrive Wednesday night in
Los Angeles, and planned a late-evening forum with undecided voters
at Los Angeles City College. Thursday morning, he is expected to
head to Venice, where he will visit a local firm and discuss
economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Former New Jersey Sen. Bradley is scheduled to arrive in San
Francisco Thursday for a noon rally at the Ferry Building at the
foot of Market Street and the Embarcadero. In case of rain, the
event _ which is open to the public _ will be held at nearby
Gabbiano's restaurant, the campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he's coming straight to San Francisco is a
statement of his respect for California voters,'' said Bradley
strategist Gale Kaufman Wednesday. ``It's a way of giving all of
our supporters a moment with him as we begin actively and
aggressively running our campaign here.''
</P>
<P>
   In a measure of the highly competitive nature of the California
race, both campaigns _ even before the candidates set foot here _
urged them to plunge into issues that matter most to California
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The senator is going to do what he's doing repeatedly, which
is talk about issues which are very important out here, such as
health care,'' said Kaufman. ``He's the only candidate who's
calling for the registration and licensing of all handguns,'' and
has repeatedly spoken on issues such as offshore oil drilling,
education, race relations and abortion, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's campaign said that the vice president has long
cultivated the state, and that he intends to remain a regular
visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president has been to California more than 60
times,'' Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said this week. ``California
is a state where his particular policies, and his particular
agenda, play into good politics _ the environment, the economy,
guns and high-tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``His fights that he's waged over the last several years will
serve him well when he gets into the (state) primary,'' Lehane
said.
</P>
<P>
   In California, ``Al Gore is going to fight every single day, 24
hours a day, for every single vote he can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's California supporters include Congresswoman Anna Eshoo
(D-Palo Alto) and San Francisco Supervisors Tom Ammiano, Gavin
Newsom and Michael Yaki.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is backed by most major Democratic politicians in the
state, including Gov. Gray Davis, Sens. Dianne Feinstein and
Barbara Boxer, Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante and San Francisco Mayor
Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bradley will return to the state next weekend, to
address the California state Democratic convention in San Jose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
