A4995 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-DAVIS-SPENDING-SFCHRO     02-03 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-SPENDING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE-KNOWN LAW LETS DAVIS FUND PROGRAMS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Using an obscure state law to skirt legislative
approval, Gov. Gray Davis is trying to spend at least $39 million
on new programs or programs that the Legislature didn't earmark
money for.
</P>
<P>
   The law gives the governor the authority to spend more on state
programs than the Legislature allowed in the budget _ but only in
emergencies or when an unforeseen cost increase occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers say Davis has used the law to create new programs
without legislative approval or, in other cases, provide money for
programs the Legislature did not approve funding for.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't how the system is supposed to work,'' said
Assemblyman George Runner, R-Lancaster, the lower house's chief GOP
budget negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the system is supposed to work is if you've got a
legislative initiative, you go through the process and go through
the constitutional requirement of a two-thirds vote and then it
gets funded,'' Runner said.
</P>
<P>
   A Davis spokeswoman said the governor's requests ``were
important programs that fall within the purview of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But Runner and other lawmakers say the move by Davis is a test
to see how much the Legislature will let him get away with. They
say that by spending money without their authorization, the
governor is violating the constitutionally established roles of the
Legislature and the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the Department of Corrections, Davis wants to
create $5.6 million in new programs, including $1.6 million for
more guards at high-security cells at Pelican Bay Prison and $1.1
million to increase medical services for female inmates.
</P>
<P>
   But several legislative budget-writers note that with a $4.4
billion budget, the corrections department could direct $5.5
million to these programs until a new budget is approved this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``These may be good policies, but they must have legislative
input, like a bill authorizing creation of the programs,'' said
Runner. ``All these programs in corrections had no legislative
overview or authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis also seeks $7.8 million to create a new bureaucracy to
regulate the health care industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Managed Care does not open until July 1 _ the
start of the state's new budget year. The bill lawmakers approved
last year to create the department contained no money to staff it
the department &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In part, this was because no money was needed until the next
fiscal year and because the bill said Davis would issue an
executive order to transfer personnel from another bureaucracy to
create the department's initial staff.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has yet to sign the executive order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Davis administration wanted to get that department up and
running so when doors open July 1, important work could start,''
said Hilary McLean, a Davis spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Another expense Davis wants paid is $15.4 million for increased
costs of 911 services and higher operating expenses for the Oakland
state building.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative budget writers said the Davis administration was
aware of the higher costs and should have sought the money through
the normal budget process.
</P>
<P>
   None of the requests by Davis that lawmakers object to have been
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Meetings are scheduled for next week with key legislative
budget-writers like Sen. Steve Peace, D-Chula Vista, chair of the
Joint Legislative Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Peace, who decides which of Davis' proposals are legitimate, did
not return a phone call Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If lawmakers don't raise an objection, the governor's requests
take effect 30 days from his notifying the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Budget overruns approved by the Legislature are paid late in the
year with what is known as a deficiency bill, which ties up loose
budget ends.
</P>
<P>
   But because the bill spends money, it requires a two-thirds
vote, which means GOP lawmakers must back it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 0106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
