<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4996 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBO-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-03 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY TRADE INEVITABLE; BUT HISTORICALLY SPEAKING, DON'T DO IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If there was any question which previous honoree WON'T
be attending the P-I's 65th Sports Star of the Year banquet
Thursday night, the 1989 award winner answered it Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The front office, the fans and the media, everybody's ripped
me,'' Ken Griffey Jr. told the P-I at Pebble Beach, Calif. ``Think
I can come back (to Seattle)?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, if that's how you feel ... can I have your dinner roll?
</P>
<P>
   Wait. That's a little too cynical. I will miss Junior. So will a
whole lot of Puget Sound baseball fans who have watched quietly
through most of last season and this winter as Griffey's Seattle
saga unraveled awkwardly.
</P>
<P>
   Most haven't ripped Griffey. They just don't like the ending.
</P>
<P>
   Who gives a standing ``O'' to divorce?
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake; dissolution is pending. All this talk about a
Griffey return to the Mariners was posturing by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   If Griffey's words weren't plain enough about his feelings, some
who have had off-the-record contact with Howard Lincoln say the new
Mariners CEO is tired of the Griffey tail wagging the franchise
dog. He wants Griffey gone by spring training, recognizing the
obvious folly of any other option, and has so directed his new
hire, GM Pat Gillick.
</P>
<P>
   Though a trade is the only plausible outcome, that doesn't mean
it is a worthy idea. Call me a sentimental silly, but I've had this
notion that trading the best player of a generation isn't a smart
thing. I keep remembering what was said in Boston about trading
Babe Ruth, what was said in Milwaukee about trading Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar, and what was said in Baltimore about trading John
Elway:
</P>
<P>
   NOOOOOOO!!!!!
</P>
<P>
   As with those three, as well as the more locally familiar Randy
Johnson episode, there is not a single good sports reason for the
trade. Inevitably, value is never received in return, and the
franchise never recovers (see the trophy cases of the Red Sox,
Bucks, Colts and Mariners).
</P>
<P>
   Setting aside the pure sports rationale, such trades come about
for reasons economic and personal, which almost always means the
player and the team will get sideways.
</P>
<P>
   That's where we are in the Griffey/Mariners divorce. Each side
takes the other's statements or position as ignorant, a challenge
or an insult.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to find someone who isn't sick of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have adroitly manipulated that inevitability into a
subtle demonization of Griffey, making him the bad guy. And Griffey
played into the strategy by going back on a commitment made by his
agent during the November trade request: To cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners fans have no interest in why Griffey cut his list of
acceptable teams from four to just Cincinnati. They just know that
because he did, the Mariners are about to be hijacked in whatever
deal comes down with the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   It can't be overemphasized that Griffey's 10-and-five rights (10
years in the majors, five with the same team) on the eve of his
free agency make the degree of difficulty in this deal
extraordinary. Baseball is the only sport with such a privilege,
and it is almost never exercised with a 30-year-old superstar in
his prime.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey is so young, so good, so expensive, so close to free
agency, and played his 10-and-5 card so hard, that the Mariners
have virtually no market for him. They might have to take from the
Reds a bat rack and two 16-year-old prospects from Belize.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the Mariners were playing poker with a guy
who's seen all their cards. To their credit, they protected
themselves with shrewd free-agent acquisitions around their exposed
hand. They filled most of their roster shortcomings without
proceeds from a Griffey deal. And they still have until July 31 to
trade Alex Rodriguez, whose trade rights they control.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners strung out Griffey throughout the off-season in the
hope of pressuring the Reds by stirring up another trade rival, or
at least a third partner, partly because Gillick and his Reds
counterpart, Jim Bowden, have grown to dislike dealing with each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Such a three-way deal could happen. But regardless of the
components, the Reds probably will end up ladling out mere gruel
for Griffey. Yet the Mariners still will be favorites for the
American League West title.
</P>
<P>
   And for whatever it's worth, they can posture themselves as
victims of the baseball system and Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   But the region will be without Griffey, the defining figure of
the franchise who might end up recognized as one of the best
players in two centuries of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   To those focused on the unpleasantness of the past few months,
Griffey's departure will be at least a relief, if not a joy.
</P>
<P>
   But to some of us at Thursday's banquet who have a chance to
celebrate 65 years of unusual athletes and extraordinary
accomplishments, Griffey's imminent absence makes a hole in sports
history's soul.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 0108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
