<SLUG> BC-BBO-GRIFFEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLFING GRIFFEY SHRUGS OFF TRADE QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ With trade rumors wafting from coast to
coast, Ken Griffey Jr. spent Wednesday in relative seclusion at the
AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am, playing a practice round on
near-empty Spyglass Hill Golf Course.
</P>
<P>
   After putting out on the 18th green, the Mariners centerfielder
was quizzed by the Post-Intelligencer about the possibility of a
trade to the Cincinnati Reds taking place this week.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to answer. Several times.
</P>
<P>
   However, that didn't stop him from talking.
</P>
<P>
   For 15 minutes, Griffey railed over and over about how he is a
hated man in Seattle because he wants to be near his family.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Mariners' six free-agent signings since the season
ended had done anything to change his thinking about a trade,
Griffey responded with a question of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The front office, the fans and the media, everybody's ripped
me,'' he said. ``Think I can come back?''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey said several Mariners officials, general manager Pat
Gillick, president Chuck Armstrong and vice president Lee
Pelekoudas, as well as media outlets, have requested meetings with
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to come see me and see what's in my head,'' he
said. ``I'm not talking to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that the Mariners finally were making long overdue
changes and spending more money, Griffey curiously defended former
Mariners general manager Woody Woodward. Griffey next criticized
Woodward's replacement, Gillick, for releasing third baseman Russ
Davis and pitcher Bret Hinchliffe rather than moving them in
trades.
</P>
<P>
   For much of his Mariners career, Griffey has stated the only
thing that mattered to him was getting a World Series championship
ring; his father has three of them. Reminded of this Wednesday and
pegged about the possibility of a much improved Mariners team,
Griffey only reiterated his latest mantra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's mad at me because I want to be near my family,''
he said. ``I want to give my son something my father never gave
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey jumped into a waiting sports utility vehicle after he
was urged several times by his impatient caddy to end his
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   At Spyglass, Griffey has played golf with the PGA Tour's Mark
O'Meara and John Cook. No more than a dozen people watched the
baseball player dunk an occasional shot in the water or demonstrate
a deft touch around the greens.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey complied with every autograph request. He was playful at
times, throwing a ball from the elevated tee onto the green of the
125-yard, par-3 15th hole, the ball landing 10 feet from the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey has maintained a relatively low profile his first two
days at the popular AT&AMP;T golf event. That will change Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:20 a.m. on Poppy Hills Golf Course, Griffey will tee it up
with O'Meara. The rest of their foursome is filled out by Tiger
Woods and a college friend.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' original choice for an amateur partner was Michael
Jordan, who backed out of a week at Pebble Beach once he became
part owner of the Washington Wizards and started working in their
front office.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
