<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-THRASHERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFELESS STARS EDGE THRASHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The expansion Atlanta Thrashers didn't exactly inspire
the Stars last night the way rivals St. Louis and Edmonton did the
past two home games. And the limp play wasn't exactly endearing to
coach Ken Hitchcock as the Stars readied to catch a flight to
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the patient _ maybe too patient _ Stars pulled out a
rather ho-hum 2-1 victory at sold-out Reunion Arena. The Stars
managed only seven shots in the final two periods and needed a
monster third period from backup goalie Manny Fernandez, who made
17 saves in the final period and missed his first career shutout by
a little more than two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played one period of hockey, that's about it,'' a disturbed
Hitchcock said. ``I thought the biggest difference in the game was
their workers outworked our workers. We had no physical play after
the first period from the people we needed it from, in particular
\RKirk\S Muller's line and it put us behind the eight-ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory still provided two points and gives the Stars a
chance to tie the Phoenix Coyotes for the division lead tonight,
the final game before the All-Star break. The Coyotes are expected
to get Keith Tkachuk back in the lineup, and the Stars fully expect
a playoff atmosphere inside America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we understand what strengths we have and how we play
as a team,'' Stars center Mike Modano said. ``What's given us
success in the past is something we all understand, we all can do
as players. That's the way it's going to have to be tomorrow. The
sooner we understand that, the better we'll be.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Stars fired 13 shots on goal without scoring in the
first period they seemingly took the rest of the night off. They
sent only two shots in the direction of Atlanta goalie Norm Maracle
in the second period. The second shot, a Modano wrister from the
right side off a pass from Brett Hull, put the Stars ahead, 1-0.
Darryl Sydor set the play in motion with a breakup in the Dallas
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Modano's goal was his 21st of the season and the 332nd of his
career, moving him past Dino Ciccarelli on the Stars' all-time
goals list. He is only 10 goals behind Stars franchise goal-scoring
leader Brian Bellows.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars added the clincher at 11:16 of the third on Guy
Carbonneau's short-handed goal, with due credit going to Thrashers
winger Jason Botteril. Blake Sloan led a two-on-one breakaway down
the left side and passed to Carbonneau in the slot. The puck hit
off Carbonneau's skate backward, and Botteril, sliding on his
stomach head first toward the goal, sent the loose puck off his
helmet and past his own goalie for a 2-0 Stars lead.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Brunette spoiled Fernandez's shutout bid when he fought
off Jamie Pushor near the crease and shoved the puck past
Fernandez, who nearly kept the puck out with a sweep of his glove
along the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   The goal didn't tarnish a magnificent game for Fernandez, who
ended a personal two-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just happy to get the win,'' Fernandez said. ``I was
worried when they scored because there was still a lot of time left
and they seemed to come at us real hard at the end of the third.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
