<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5001 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s BC-CAYARD-AMERICAONE-SFC     02-03 3061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAYARD-AMERICAONE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAONE'S INTENSE SKIPPER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By JIM DOYLE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ Moments before the start of the first
high-stakes showdown with his Italian rival, Paul Cayard pulled one
of the most aggressive maneuvers of the America's Cup trials _
suddenly rounding a race committee boat by only a few feet and
ducking inside the Prada, which was trying to block AmericaOne's
way.
<P>
   It was a purely instinctive move, not one found in the team's
playbook. Pushing hard on the wheel of AmericaOne with almost
maniacal confidence, the 40-year-old skipper scared the daylights
out of Prada's crew _ and his own. ``For every other member of the
team, their life probably passed in front of their eyes,'' said
strategist Gavin Brady. ``It was a critical time in this regatta. A
critical two seconds. It was a desperation move.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was unneeded that time. Halfway up the first leg of that
race in the semifinals last month, Prada's 10-story-tall carbon
fiber mast snapped in two, and AmericaOne went on to win.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the same two teams are going head to head in the Louis
Vuitton Cup finals, a best-of-nine series for the right to
challenge Team New Zealand next month for the America's Cup. Cayard
was down 3-1, but came back strong, and the series is tied at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul is the most focused man I've ever met,'' said crew member
Jim Nicholas of San Diego, who has known Cayard for 20 years.
``He's probably a genius. His whole career has been setting up for
this one _ the America's Cup is like war. There's diplomacy,
intelligence and the battle. Some of our races have been brilliant.
I've been in five cup campaigns, and this is the best chance I've
had to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Half a world away from the salt air and jade-green waters of the
Hauraki Gulf, and long before the greatest battle of his life, Paul
Cayard was just another middle-class San Francisco kid. His family
lived on a foggy Twin Peaks street where Paul gave his parents a
fright by skateboarding down the steep hill.
</P>
<P>
   The lanky boy with searing brown eyes _ who one day would start
an America's Cup campaign on his own _ attended Clarendon
Elementary School and played basketball and football. But he was
always different.
</P>
<P>
   His father, a French immigrant, was a boy when the Germans
invaded Paris. Pierre Cayard, who made sets for the San Francisco
Opera, built his 8-year-old a sailboat _ an El Toro, a wooden
dinghy that his proud son would describe decades later as ``a
beautiful work of art made from seven types of wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul's buddies teased him mercilessly when he began to sail.
There was no question that the boy, an only child, had an affinity
for the wind. He also liked getting out of the house, out of reach
of the criticisms of his hard-driving parents. He sailed every
other weekend on Lake Merritt in Oakland and still recalls how
scared he felt when his boat capsized and he had to be rescued.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 11, Paul's father and mother, Frances, a disability
evaluator, joined San Francisco's Lake Merced Sailing Club. Two
years later, his mother donned a wetsuit and crewed for her son on
San Francisco Bay's freezing waters.
</P>
<P>
   Sailboat racer and ESPN commentator Gary Jobson recalls how,
when he visited the St. Francis Yacht Club nearly three decades
ago, a friend pointed out a 12-year-old sailor named Paul Cayard
and said, ``Watch this kid.''
</P>
<P>
   At 15, he won the North America championships in the El Toro.
</P>
<P>
   The boy wonder was not exactly plucked off the streets of San
Francisco and presented with the keys to the city's most exclusive
yacht club, but he certainly latched on to some fine-feathered
friends. Doug Holm, a sailboat racer who now sells marine
insurance, met Paul Cayard at the St. Francis Yacht Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a kid from San Bruno (where his family had moved)
who came through the junior sailing program,'' Holm said. ``Paul
was rough around the edges. He was just driven to win sailboat
races _ he never expected to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The yacht club provided Cayard with boats to sail, took him to
regattas up and down California and flew him to Rio de Janeiro for
the world championships in the Laser class, a single-handed racing
boat.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard attended San Francisco State University, working his way
through college by building sets for his father. He got his degree
in business management.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Cayard could never quite grasp his son's obsession with
sailing. He was supportive but would have preferred that Paul take
up a more stable profession, like dentistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul is like a bulldog. Once he bites onto something, he never
lets go,'' says Pierre Cayard, who now follows his son's races on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard found kindred spirits in those early years who showed him
the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Blackaller, a San Francisco sailing maverick known for his
killer instinct, was among the first yacht-racing heavyweights to
take the young sailor under his wing. When Cayard was only 18,
Blackaller asked him to sail with him. He was the youngest guy on
the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, in 1983, Blackaller asked him to be a sail
trimmer on Defender, which sailed in defense of the America's Cup
for the New York Yacht Club. Cayard's sailing buddy the future best
man at his wedding, Ken Keefe, was also on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard says he learned from Blackaller ``when to go for it. Any
risk-taking tendency I have came from him.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was the year that John Bertrand's Australia II, with
its revolutionary winged keel, took the trophy away from the New
York Yacht Club, where it had sat for 132 years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Cayard married Icka Peterson, a stylish and
warm-hearted Swede who is the daughter of Pelle Peterson, a world
champion sailor. The couple, who now live in Kentfield, settled
first in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later came a turning point in Cayard's career: He
began working full time for Italian billionaire Raul Gardini,
overseeing his sailboat racing program.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Cayard, his wife and their two children moved to Italy,
where Cayard ran Gardini's $100 million America's Cup campaign. In
1992, helmsman Cayard drove Il Moro di Venezia to the America's Cup
finals, but lost 4-1 to Bill Koch's America3 in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   He had won the world championship in the Star class in Buenos
Aires in 1988. He tried twice to qualify in the Star boat for the
Olympic Games, but fell short _ dashing his dream of winning a gold
medal.
</P>
<P>
   But inch by inch, Cayard was retooling himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wild and out of control during my first America's Cup
campaign,'' he said. ``When Mr. Gardini hired me, I shifted gears
and became very serious. It's because I know it's who I need to be
to excel _ I've probably gone too far and become more extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, American sailing legend Dennis Conner selected Cayard
as his helmsman on cup defender Young America. But that year, Team
New Zealand's Black Magic sailed away with a 5-0 victory in San
Diego and took the cup to Auckland. It was a heartbreaking loss for
Cayard, but he walked away from the regatta with a positive
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the most important lessons to learn is how to
lose and come back stronger the next time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After getting skunked in the 1995 America's Cup, Cayard lay on
the beach _ without a team or boat, yet looking ahead at the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   He could have signed up as a helmsman with an established
syndicate, but he decided to start from zero with his own group. So
he flew down to San Diego and crewed for Doug Smith _ a lawyer and
friend from the yacht club _ on a Star boat. On the tow-out to the
racecourse, the two secretly worked on the business plan for an
America's Cup team, sorting out the organizational and legal issues
of running a multilevel business campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When AmericaOne's formation was announced in May 1996, Smith
became one of the syndicate's board members, and the St. Francis
Yacht Club was listed as the official sponsor. The next step would
be begging for dollars to finance the team's $32 million budget _
and locking up key team members, including veteran America's Cup
boat designer Bruce Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hand-to-mouth existence, and then came the first body
blow to Cayard's campaign: In early 1997, Netscape Communications
Corp. founder Jim Clark backed away from his pledge to give $6
million to the team. The next blow came soon after, when veteran
cup manager Laurent Esquier jumped ship and took a job with Italy's
big-budget Prada syndicate. Cayard's team was on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   That is when Larry Finch, who owns an investment capital firm
with offices in San Francisco and Boston, stepped up to form the
Founder's Club _ a vehicle for seeking contributions from St.
Francis Yacht Club members and others. Finch himself gave $2
million, and they quickly raised $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1998, AmericaOne made an overture to
Hewlett-Packard Co. HP would invest $5 million in cash in the
syndicate, plus several millions of dollars in goods, services and
related marketing programs. HP not only helped the team set up its
California and Auckland operations, but also lent the team the use
of supercomputers to help sift through thousands of potential boat
designs. In return, HP's logo would be prominently displayed on the
boat, and Cayard agreed to speak at HP events.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Cayard signed sponsorship deals with Ford Motor Co.,
SAIC, United Technologies, Visteon Racing and Telcordia
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly but surely, an organization was being built. Once fully
assembled, it would be 70 people strong, including 26 sailors (for
16 slots on the racing boat) plus tender operators, crash boat
drivers and weather spotters. The shore crew would consist of boat
builders, boat doctors, sail makers, chefs, a marketing and public
relations staff, an administrative staff, office workers and
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   An America's Cup syndicate is like a traveling circus _ a
mammoth operation that can easily become a logistical nightmare.
AmericaOne's solution: ``Buddha'' Bob Billingham, an Olympic
medalist and the team's affable chief of operations, who set up its
training compound in Long Beach and base in Auckland.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard drew no salary the first two years and negotiated a
$200,000-a-year contract for each of the past two years _ an amount
that he calculated was less than half what he could have commanded
had he hired on with another syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he took one of the biggest gambles of the AmericaOne
campaign by deciding to skipper a 60-foot sailboat in the Whitbread
Round the World Race _ the Mount Everest of sailing. Rather than
stay focused on his America's Cup campaign, Cayard reasoned that
his syndicate would gain valuable publicity if he competed in the
high-profile event.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected him to do well. Cayard and his crew were buoy
racers, not blue water sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the Southern Ocean off Antarctica, his boat encountered
30-foot waves and 45-knot winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a point in the race when I wondered whether I was
doing the right thing,'' Cayard said the other day. ``I had this
vision of my wife and kids curled up on a couch before the
fireplace in Kentfield. But there we were, planing down 20-foot
waves in the dark, and I didn't know if we might get pasted into an
iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard won, the first American skipper to be victorious in the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``As usual, the skipper gets the lion's share of the glory, but
there were 11 other guys who did a hell of a job,'' Cayard said.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitbread victory ``showed us that anything was possible,''
said AmericaOne marketing pro Jen McHugh.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was now set for Cayard's ultimate challenge. On July
17, 1999, the boat USA-49 _ sporting Michael Vanderbyl's dynamic
design of gunmetal gray and green shards _ sat in a cradle before a
crowd of 500 guests at the Port of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I christen thee AmericaOne,'' said Icka Cayard, breaking a
bottle of champagne against its bow. It was an emotional high for
what was becoming a close-knit family of sailors.
</P>
<P>
   But once christened, USA-49 still was not ready to sail.
Winifred Feifel, a Boeing Co. scientist who has designed everything
from cruise missiles to gliders, was putting the finishing touches
on the boat's secret keel.
</P>
<P>
   The sailors, stuck with training in a slower Australian boat
from the 1995 cup races, felt grumpy and stranded. All had strong
egos and winning records. The sunrise workouts under
Australian-bred sailor Billy Bates were grueling. The crew wanted
to sail on a fast boat, not wear themselves down.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them also began to wonder if the man they privately
nicknamed ``The Mustache'' had made the right decision to train in
Southern California. America True, their San Francisco rival, was
already sailing its new boat in Auckland. And the Italians, who
seemed far ahead in the game, would soon be sailing there with two
new boats.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard has a nimble touch at the wheel _ his long, tanned
fingers lightly steer the 75-foot yacht through rolling seas. He
glances from time to time at the digital numbers on his Nike watch.
In his foul-weather gear, leather and canvas boots, Oakley
sunglasses and mustache, he looks like a cutout from a Marlboro
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   But near the start of a race, Cayard begins to breathe loudly,
unconsciously, as if his pulse is racing at more than 120 mph.
</P>
<P>
   By far, the helmsman-tactician relationship is the most
potentially volatile on AmericaOne. John Kostecki is not only a
world-class tactician, but also a brilliant skipper in his own
right. At times, the two have crossed swords because of Kostecki's
need to call tactics during a race and Cayard's need to exercise
the helm without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good, if uneasy, collection of people out there,''
said grinder Jim Nicholas, 46, one of the oldest members of
AmericaOne's sailing team and one of the boat's musclemen who
operate the winches. ``Paul tends to run a little hot, and Kostecki
tends to keep him cool. We all try to keep him light.''
</P>
<P>
   To get around the racecourse, the 16 crew members on an
America's Cup sailing team have to work in unison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like in football, when a play is well executed,
it's}ooRdh,/l92 said. But, he acknowledges, ``Sometimes I'm too
overbearing with the crew.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have been a major general in the Army, leading
troops, right there in the bunker, not behind the lines,'' said
Roger ``Clouds'' Badham, the team's barefoot meteorologist.
``Mentally, he's like lightning. He sees the big picture, but he
also understands the little pieces _ it'll probably kill him. It
killed his mentor, Tom Blackaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackaller died of a heart attack at 49 in 1989 while doing laps
at Sears Point Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   In the America's Cup trials that started in October, crew
loyalty would be tested to the limits. The team would either come
together or splinter apart.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Conner's Stars &AMP; Stripes collided with AmericaOne in the
first qualifying round _ almost knocking Cayard over the side and
causing structural damage to the boat's transom.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing czar Gina von Esmarch called the incident a ``stomach
cruncher.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be a lot of damage before we even get to
the semis,'' Cayard told a group of supporters during a dinner at
the Royal New Zealand Yacht Squadron. There, he sipped a glass of
wine and remarked how good it tasted, but he never took another
sip.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-November, nearly half the AmericaOne team had the flu,
and crew members felt they were being pushed too hard _ often
rising at dawn and working for the next 14 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever they come up with new technology _ a new wing on the
keel or whatever _ we have to build it. And that can become a drain
on morale,'' said strategist Morgan Larson of Capitola. ``At this
stage of the game, it's time we're up against. A year ago, it was
money. The America's Cup is a marathon. If you start sprinting,
maybe you'll have legs that will get you the whole way, and maybe
you'll run out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard was looking ahead _ anxiously awaiting the arrival of his
second wind-powered rocket ship, the USA-61. On November 8, the
team's new boat arrived in Auckland inside the belly of a Boeing
747. Still, the skipper was unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sailing as well as I can and not as well as I have in
the past,'' Cayard said.
</P>
<P>
   During the Christmas holiday, he studied videotapes of the early
races _ dissecting the starting tactics of his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   At a team meeting, the skipper told his troops: ``I go home at
night and sit in my bed or wake up in the morning and visualize how
we're going to win the America's Cup. My vision of winning was not
clear three or four months ago; now it's getting clearer. We're
going to be on top of our game.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, AmericaOne faced Prada again _ a match that Cayard
would later describe as a ``s_ fight.'' On the final downwind leg,
the two wind-driven chariots dodged and scraped against each for
the lead _ with both skippers yelling their lungs out in protest to
on-water umpires. Cayard, fearing that Prada skipper Francesco de
Angelis was trying to push him off course, screamed over and over:
``Improper course! Improper course!'' AmericaOne won the race by
nine seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have preferred to be more low-key. I got overly
excited. I regret that,'' Cayard said afterward. But his crew
seemed stoked by his performance _ happy to see the brutally
competitive wild man resurface.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell that he's recharging. It helps to know that he's
got the killer instinct back,'' bowman Curtis Blewett said.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the competitive animosity between the crews that
are now competing in the finals boiled over, when AmericaOne
returned to the dock after losing its race against Dennis Conner's
Stars &AMP; Stripes. Prada's shore team greeted Cayard by wearing
Pinocchio noses, suggesting that he had thrown the race to reduce
the Italians' chances of getting into the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to lose at anything. I fear failure,'' he said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   If he pulls off a win, he would become an American sailing hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of winning is expecting to win,'' Cayard said.
``The test is, can we be as hungry tomorrow as we were today? Those
who pass the test win the America's Cup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
