<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOPPE-OBIT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 VETERAN CHRONICLE REPORTER AND COLUMNIST ART HOPPE DIES  &HT;     By STEVE RUBENSTEIN, LEAH GARCHIK and JANICE GREENE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Art Hoppe, the gentleman humorist whose sharp
pen crafted a peerless column of political and social satire that
appeared in The Chronicle for more than 40 years, died Tuesday
night in a San Francisco hospital of complications from lung
cancer. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Hoppe, who told readers in December of his disease and wrote
movingly about his battle against it, was a much-beloved member of
The Chronicle staff who skewered political targets on the left and
right with eloquence, insight and joy.
</P>
<P>
   He deflated the pompous, tweaked the powerful and weighed in
passionately on such issues as Vietnam, Watergate, the death
penalty and the inability of America to produce low-fat cheesecake.
</P>
<P>
   His death came eight weeks after he told readers that he was
being treated for lung cancer. In characteristically upbeat
fashion, he wrote that he was ``impressed with my own worth on
being told my insurance company would be billed $4,000'' for a
particular test. He also said he planned to die after being hit by
a truck, many years in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Hoppe gave birth in his column to a cast of whimsical characters
_ confused redneck Joe Sikspak, lowly Private Oliver Drab, an
earnestly unelectable Harvard-educated gorilla, the all-knowing
expert Homer T. Pettibone, the celestial Heavenly Landlord and a
presidential candidate named Nobody _ who assisted their creator in
his self-described lifelong campaign of tilting at windmills.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Editor William German called his friend ``the best
reporter The Chronicle ever had _ he wrote with wit, intelligence
and eloquence, and he could find information and convey it clearly,
in a manner that made the reader want to read it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Art Hoppe was a great satirist and Bay Area institution, and
his death is a profound loss to all of us,'' said Chronicle
Managing Editor Jerry Roberts. ``In an age of bombast, he was a
writer of tremendous civility and grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein (D-Calif.) said Hoppe was a ``journalist
of style and substance (who) captivated the Bay Area for years with
a wonderful blend of humor, satire and grace. He was a fun-loving,
caring man who will be sorely missed.''
</P>
<P>
   His half century at The Chronicle seemed to amaze everyone but
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've now put in 50 years at The Chronicle,'' he wrote in July.
``Please don't send congratulations. It's not an accomplishment to
be proud of. If you show up with some regularity for work and don't
get hit by a truck, eventually you are bound to reach the same
chronological pinnacle.''
</P>
<P>
   He joined The Chronicle as a copy boy in 1949, at a salary of
$35 a week. Seven months later, he was promoted to reporter. He
spent a week as a bum on skid row, trekked to a snowbound passenger
train in the Sierra and journeyed to Europe to explain to readers
the foreign policies of Liechtenstein, Monaco, San Marino and
Andorra. At the height of the space race, he was dispatched to the
African nation of Zambia, where he described how astronauts were
being trained by being rolled downhill in barrels.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, he was among the horde of reporters at San Francisco
City Hall to cover the wedding of Joe DiMaggio and Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joltin' Joe DiMaggio wedded the girl of his and many other
men's dreams yesterday,'' he wrote _ a deceptively simple sentence
often quoted by journalism teachers as an example of how to start a
news story.
</P>
<P>
   His feature stories were models of sharp writing and keenly
observed details that eluded lesser reporters. In 1957, he wrote a
moving account of being among the witnesses at an execution at San
Quentin prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to see Burton Abbott die,'' he wrote. ``There were
53 of them _ official witnesses. All were men. Women are not
allowed to see a condemned man die ... They gathered in front of
the main gate to San Quentin at 9 a.m. yesterday. No one was
late.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, he covered the presidential race between John Kennedy
and Richard Nixon, overhearing the idle chat between the two men
just before one of their historic debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither said anything for a moment,'' Hoppe wrote. ``Then
Kennedy, in what seemed like one of those desperate efforts to make
small talk, said, `When are you going out again?' `I leave first
thing in the morning,' Nixon said. `Oh,' Kennedy said. After a few
moments, both turned to talk to others, just as you do at a
cocktail party when you run out of conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   His columns from the 1960 campaign trail led to his regular
humor column, which eventually appeared five days a week and was
syndicated in more than 100 newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   His columns spanned the presidencies of Just Plain Jack, Elbie
Jay, Nick Dixon, the Scoutmaster, Jiminy Beaver, Sir Ronald of
Holyrude, Mr. Lifestyles of the Rich and Humble and Billy Boomer,
Boy President.
</P>
<P>
   Like many humorists, he was grateful for the 1968 election of
such handy subjects as Nixon and his Vice President Spiro Agnew,
whose photographs he kept on his office wall and whose
resignations, he often moped, robbed him of years of additional
copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always thought, and still do, that Mr. Nixon's basic
problem over the years was his, forgive the word, insecurity ... He
always seemed ill at ease. His suits _ he never wore anything else
_ didn't fit quite right; his sense of humor was nonexistent; he
had no capacity whatsoever for small talk. He was the boy you let
play only if it was his ball...''
</P>
<P>
   With passion, eloquence and common sense, he argued against the
Vietnam War, racial intolerance and capital punishment. In 1971, at
the height of the war in Southeast Asia, he stunned readers with a
frank, difficult admission:
</P>
<P>
   ``The radio this morning said the Allied invasion of Laos had
bogged down. Without thinking, I nodded and said, `Good.' And
having said it, I realized the bitter truth: Now I root against my
own country. This is how far we have come in this hated and endless
war. This is the nadir I have reached in this winter of my
discontent. This is how close I border on treason. Now I root
against my own country.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers often wrote ill-tempered letters taking issue with such
statements. To many, he was fond of replying that if any more such
letters were received, the newspaper would be forced to cancel the
letter writer's subscription.
</P>
<P>
   To other hecklers, he would send a one-sentence reply: ``The
cookbook you have ordered will arrive under separate cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his friends were fellow humor columnists Russell Baker and
Art Buchwald. Together, the three writers formed an ephemeral
society they called the American Academy of Humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose,'' Baker recalled Wednesday, ``was to keep
everybody else out. We excluded a number of people. We finally let
in Erma Bombeck, that was because Art was soft on Erma.''
</P>
<P>
   Another close friend, Chronicle Science Editor David Perlman,
called Hoppe ``the most graceful writer I ever worked with (and) a
true humanist. No human fault or achievement failed to evoke his
sympathy or his applause, and no public evildoer could escape the
kind of hilarious tongue-lashing that only Hoppe at his satirical
best could administer in print.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoppe died three years to the day after the death of his friend
and fellow Chronicle columnist Herb Caen, who frequently called
Hoppe ``a genius _ and an unsung one at that.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote two plays and eight books, including several
collections of his columns and a vivid 1995 autobiography titled,
``Having a Wonderful Time _ My First Half Century as a
Newspaperman.''
</P>
<P>
   That book was full of delightful anecdotes, such as his 1966
tour of Lyndon Johnson's ranch with the president himself at the
wheel and Hoppe in the very back of a bumpy station wagon. On that
occasion, Johnson introduced Hoppe to a deer named Charley, who ate
cigarettes, and Hoppe thanked the president profusely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's all right,'' Johnson replied. ``I didn't have
anything else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoppe's son, Nick, said that the books' modest sales were a
source of amusement to their author.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad always said,'' he recalled, ``that some people collect
rare books and that he writes them.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-deprecating remarks were a specialty. The best thing about
being a columnist, he once wrote, is being ``able to say exactly
what I think ... I've always claimed that I enjoy the utmost in
freedom of the press because the publisher doesn't read my
output.''
</P>
<P>
   But the publisher did read Hoppe's column, and so did the rest
of Hoppe's colleagues, with admiration and awe.
</P>
<P>
   Hoppe, the son of a lawyer and a social worker, was born in
Honolulu and moved to San Francisco at the age of 5. He was a
graduate of Presidio Hill School and Lowell High School in San
Francisco and of Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, he served as a pharmacist's mate aboard a
destroyer in the Pacific. He was fond of telling his wide-eyed
children and grandchildren that, in the line of duty, he
``single-handedly dispatched millions of our country's enemies'' _
by dispensing antibiotics to kill the germs in a sailor's sore
throat.
</P>
<P>
   He was a world traveler, primarily to places with golf courses
and tennis courts, and he was an abstract artist whose painted
masterpieces were less well known than his written ones.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the California Tennis Club and the Claremont
and Lagunitas country clubs, where his shots frequently traveled in
unintended directions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, on his 60th birthday, Hoppe expressed his gratitude in
print to one of his favorite readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, God, I've had a marvelous time. I thought it time
to write a thank-you note to my host or hostess, as the case may
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a wonderful party, God, absolutely wonderful. It was
the guests who made it. I can't say I liked all of them. A few were
stuffed shirts, a few were wet blankets and a few badly misbehaved.
But they were the exceptions. All in all, it was a grand bunch ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I never quite believed in your wrath. I see you as a kindly
and benevolent host concerned with my well-being. I like to think
that your pine beetles and your storms and your malevolent microbes
have been placed in my path to remind me that it isn't all fun and
games. Nor should it be. So thank you dear God for the deserts, for
Texas and for the pine beetles.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, I've had an absolutely marvelous time.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 53 years, Gloria, whom he met in
high school, by his son Nick Hoppe of Mill Valley, by his daughters
Andy Gonzalez of San Francisco, Leslie Hoppe-Wormhoudt of Greenbrae
and Prentiss Van Den Berg of Kentfield.
</P>
<P>
   He is also survived by 11 grandchildren: Scriv and Thibault
Hoppe-Glosser and Annie and Charlie Wormhoudt, of Greenbrae; Laura
and Elena Gonzalez of San Francisco; Kelly, Taryn, Will and Brett
Hoppe, of Mill Valley; and Jessica Buerger of Ross.
</P>
<P>
   (A memorial service will be held on Monday at 11 a.m. at St.
Luke's Episcopal Church, Van Ness Avenue at Clay Street, San
Francisco. The family requests that donations be sent to the
American Cancer Society, 235 Montgomery St., Suite 320, San
Francisco, CA 94104 or to CARE International, 41 Sutter St., Suite
300, San Francisco, CA 94104.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
