<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-ART-1     02-03 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHERS FIND `BLACK BOX' IN ALASKA AIRLINES JET CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT HUENEME, Calif. _ Searchers on Wednesday recovered one of
the ``black boxes,'' the cockpit voice recorder, from the Alaska
Airlines jet that crashed on Monday and said they had heard
electronic pinging from the other, officials said on Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard ended its search for survivors on Wednesday.
Given the water temperatures, which were in the mid-50s, and the
time that has expired since the crash, ``we have far exceeded our
estimates of survivability,'' Vice Adm. Tom Collins of the Coast
Guard said.
</P>
<P>
   The recorder will be shipped immediately to the board's
Washington offices for analysis, said Ted Lopatkiewicz, a spokseman
for the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   At a news briefing on Wednesday night, Capt. Terry Labrecque of
the Navy, commander of the amphibious group carrying out recovery
work, said technicians had lowered a robot submarine into the water
to test it and ``as luck would have it, almost literally true, as
soon as they got down to the bottom, they found the first box.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hammerschmidt, the safety board member assigned to the
accident here, said at the briefing that investigaors had
inteviewed three pilots who saw the plane fall from the sky. He
said the three had used terms like ``tumbling, spinning, nose down,
continuous roll, corkscrewing and inverted.''
</P>
<P>
   He said none of the pilots had seen smoke or fire or saw any
parts fall off the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the safety board said it was looking into a news
report of trouble on a flight earlier in the day on the same type
of plane as the one that crashed, killing 88 people.
</P>
<P>
   And another plane of the same model, an MD-83, made an emergency
return to Phoenix on Wednesday after the crew said it had problems
with the stabilizer trim, the same system that the crew of Alaska
Airlines Flight 261 told air traffic controllers in Los Angeles
that they had had problems with shortly before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators did not disclose anything that made the cause of
the crash clear, but they did mount an intense effort to recover
parts of the plane. The searchers, who covered 4,400 miles with 38
vessels and 9 aircraft, crossing back and forth over an area about
the size of Rhode Island, found more floating debris from the MD-83
but no additional human remains. Four bodies were found on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The second black box, the flight data recorder includes data on
the position of the horizontal stabilizer, the airline has told the
safety board.
</P>
<P>
   The second MD-83 that reported a problem with its horizontal
control system was American Airlines Flight 1538, which took off
from Sky Harbor Airport in Phoenix at 8:20 a.m. with 59 passengers
and crew members. The cockpit crew reported an intermittent problem
with the stabilizer trim while the plane was climbing to 13,000
feet, people involved in the incident said. The crew was able to
return the trim to a position appropriate for landing, and the
plane returned safely to Phoenix at 9:03 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   After major airline crashes, reports of similar problems from
other crews are common. After the pilots of Swissair Flight 111, an
MD-11, reported smoke in the cockpit before crashing into the
Atlantic Ocean off Halifax, Nova Scotia, on Sept. 2, 1998, killing
all 229 people aboard, several planes made emergency landings
because of smoke. But reports of trouble from other planes have
also helped investigators solve crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board took the Phoenix
plane's flight data recorder, and mechanics began looking at the
electric motor that drives the stabilizer trim, people involved in
the incident said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect part on the MD-83 is the forward two-thirds of the
horizontal stabilizer, the wing-like section of the tail. It is
driven by an electric motor and a jack-screw, similar to the kind
that raises and lowers garage doors. Pilots use the stabilizer to
enable the plane to climb, cruise or descend; for quick changes,
they use moveable parts, called elevators, that make up the rear
third of the horizontal stabilizer.
</P>
<P>
   The crew of Alaska Flight 261, bound from the Mexican resort of
Puerto Vallarta to San Francisco and then to Seattle, had reported
that its horizontal stabilizer had jammed, the safety board said.
Pilots who fly the MD-80 series said on Wednesday that the
stabilizer could have jammed soon after takeoff, but the autopilot
might have masked the problem for a time by using the elevators.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch of the plane _ the nose-up or nose-down attitude _
changes with the plane's speed and its center of gravity, which
changes as the plane burns fuel. Pilots said that if the Alaska
Airlines plane gained speed and burned fuel, reaching the point
where the autopilot could no longer compensate, it would switch
off, leaving the crew to determine through their instruments or by
looking out the window what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flying along fat, dumb and happy, and then the autopilot
kicks off and everything is kind of, boom, boom, boom,'' one MD-80
captain said. ``In flight simulators, when we train for this, this
is one of the more deceptive onsets of a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The degree of threat posed by a jammed stabilizer may depend on
the position in which the stabilizer is jammed, pilots say. Many
planes have recovered from such jams. The first line of defense
would be the elevators, which on the MD-80 series are operated by
cables that run back to the pilots' yokes in the cockpit, and also
have hydraulic boost pumps.
</P>
<P>
   If the device jammed in a nose-up position, a crew could
temporarily compensate by banking and putting the plane into a
turn, which would turn the lifting force of the wings somewhat to
the side, making the nose fall.
</P>
<P>
   Hammerschmidt said investigators were checking into a news
report that the crew that flew the plane to Puerto Vallarta had
reported ``some mechanical discrepancies.'' He said that he did not
know if the report was true but that investigators wanted to
interview the crew as soon as possible. Such interviews are
standard procedure after crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Hammerschmidt said the board expected to interview the Puerto
Vallarta ground personnel Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After planning an emergency approach to Los Angeles, the pilots
of Alaska Flight 261 radioed that they were going to
``reconfigure'' the airplane. It was their last transmission.
</P>
</TEXT>
