<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5014 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HEAT-CELTICS-BOS     02-03 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT EDGE CELTICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You take the bruises and the disappointment and you put them in
the memory bank. Maybe you allow yourself another look, but you
know there will not be another chance. Not until the next time.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Celtics took away from Wednesday night's
crusher, a 105-103 loss to Miami that, like the night before in
Indiana, went down to the last shot. They rallied from a 12-point
hole in the fourth quarter and had two shots in their final
possession to tie or win the game.
</P>
<P>
   The first, by Paul Pierce, rimmed out. The second, a deliberate,
step-back trey by Antoine Walker, was short. The horn sounded and
the Celtics were again left to explain how they someday soon might
learn from this.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't,'' Pierce said, ``it's going to be a long
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the Celtics' fifth in six games and second to Miami
in eight days. They missed a chance to pick up ground on the
Pistons, who continue to leave the door wide open. They missed a
lot of things.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, for instance. He had 35 points, 7 rebounds, 4 assists,
and was booed. The reason? He missed five free throws in the fourth
quarter and after the fifth miss, the rebound came back to him and
he unhesitatingly squeezed off a 3-pointer. It boinged away.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce seemingly played three or four games in one. He was
almost invisible in the first quarter and almost unstoppable in the
second, when he made 8 of 9 shots and had 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he missed his next seven shots and bricked 9 of his last
10. But he also made a huge trey with 1:28 to play that brought the
Celtics all the way back and tied the game at 101.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the Heat were reeling. They had gone more than
seven minutes without a field goal in frittering away their
12-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   But they never lost the lead. Pierce's trey electrified the
crowd, but also jolted Miami out of its offensive stupor.
</P>
<P>
   On the Heat's next possession, Clarence Weatherspoon popped open
and hit a 12-footer with 1:08 left. Kenny Anderson, who had another
strong game, tied it with a second-chancer with 37.8 seconds left.
Then the resolute Alonzo Mourning, whose shot was not dropping all
night, coaxed in a jump hook after bobbling the pass. There were
15.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a random play,'' Tim Hardaway said. ``It turned
out to be a good play.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino had a timeout available, but he decided not to use
it. Pierce hoisted his shot, but it was wide left. Then Walker got
the rebound on the baseline. He had two choices: go back up and try
to tie the game or dribble back to international waters and try to
win the game. He chose the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good decision,'' mused Anderson. ``It shows he has (guts).
He'd have won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Pierce, ``I have total confidence in him taking that shot.
I'd want him to take it 10 times out of 10. I thought it was going
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the Celtics could look at many areas from which they
could learn something. How, for instance, not to start a half. They
opened the third quarter missing their first 10 shots and turning
it over three more times. They fell behind by 16.
</P>
<P>
   That was the hole from which they could not extricate
themselves. They trailed by 10 entering the fourth, only the
seventh time in 23 home games this season that they have been in
arrears after three quarters. They managed to win three of those
games, including the last time when they were in such a position
against Toronto a fortnight ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Miami drought. After Mark Strickland opened the
quarter with an alley-oop dunk, the Heat missed their next 10
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played hard,'' Hardaway said. ``We couldn't get anything
going. We turned it over. That's how they got back in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But in doing so, the Celtics also made it unnecessarily hard on
themselves. Walker missed the five free throws. They shot 36
percent from the field. But in spite of themselves, they got a
chance to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tremendous, tremendous effort,'' saluted Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   The effort got them back. It wasn't enough to get them all the
way back. Miami didn't make a lot of plays in the quarter, but it
made the big ones in the final 70 seconds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
