   NY-BOTANIC-GARDEN (New York) _ Swirling snow, cars turned to
soft lumps on the street, the city as silent as a Vermont woods. I
felt an irresistible need to go to the Brooklyn Botanic Garden. I
bundled up as if I were in the north country and walked a mile to
the garden, pleasantly disoriented because familiar landmarks were
veiled by the storm. Yet other perceptions were sharpened: how the
long hill, which rises from the sea in Red Hook, crests at Court
Street and then rolls down to the Gowanus, where it starts its
long, slow climb to Park Slope. By Anne Raver.
