<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-RECRUITING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU `BUMPS UP' STATURE WITH QUALITY RECRUITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ To the victors go the spoils. Considering
the victories on the football field for TCU the past two seasons,
the Horned Frogs are spoiling themselves rotten.
</P>
<P>
   TCU coach Dennis Franchione waited patiently for 3 1/2 hours
yesterday morning as faxes from 18 future Frogs streamed into the
football office. Sixteen of the 18 compose the 2000 recruiting
class, with one looking to join the team in 2001 and another in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Frogs had only 16 scholarships available because of
their small senior class, the 2000 class isn't lacking in flash.
Seven members are rated among the /Star-Telegram/'s State Top 100
recruits and two _ Irving tailback Tyson Thompson and Carrollton
Newman Smith defensive tackle Brandon Johnson _ are among the
nation's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``This class may lack a little bit in the quantity in numbers,
but it has great quality,'' Franchione said. ``We feel like we have
bumped our recruiting up a notch to a level higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and Johnson tower as the class of this class.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who rushed for 5,758 yards and 51 touchdowns in his
Irving career, made /Parade/ magazine and /USA Today/ first-team
All-America. Rivals100.com ranked Johnson as No. 20 nationally
among defensive tackles. Franchione said their early commitments
made it easier for others to choose TCU.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the high-profile kids, our success with the back-to-back
bowl victories, the conference championship and back-to-back
winning seasons, it has gotten easier for them to say, `I'm going
to TCU,' '' said Franchione, 15-9 in two seasons at TCU. ``Much
more so than it was probably a couple years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Consecutive postseason victories _ the Sun Bowl in 1998 and
Mobile Alabama Bowl this past December _ helped greatly, Franchione
said. The Frogs went 8-4 last season, claimed a share of the
Western Athletic Conference title and finished just outside the
AP's final Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, TCU is definitely a program on the rise,'' said
Johnson, who turned down several suitors, including Michigan,
Miami, Texas and Texas A&AMP;M. ``Some of the schools I visited are
already established, and I decided I wanted to be part of a
tradition I helped build.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione and his staff are building that tradition largely
with Fort Worth-Dallas area talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten or 11 of our guys are probably within 100 miles of the
Metroplex,'' Franchione said. ``So we are continuing to make an
impact and make a strong presence in this area, which is home base
for us. It's important for us to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson couldn't resist the lure of having his family in the
stands for every home game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your family is your biggest supporter, and you want to share
something with them,'' Johnson said. ``I wanted them to see me
play.''
</P>
<P>
   On defense, TCU concentrated on tackles and safeties, areas
Franchione said they struggled to recruit a year ago. San Antonio
Taft safety Marvin Godbolt (6-1, 188) and Galveston Ball linebacker
Derrick Pope (6-0, 195) might find themselves playing key roles as
early as next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione's philosophy is to redshirt freshmen whenever
possible. Of the 22 members of the 1999 class, he redshirted 20,
and only starting quarterback Casey Printers saw significant
playing time. Of the current group of 16, Franchione expects only a
handful to get on the field this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Darrell Catlin of Waco is headed to junior college
with hopes of re-signing with TCU in two years. Weatherford
quarterback Zack Moore is planning to enroll at TCU in January 2001
and will count against the 2001 scholarship limit.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, Franchione wanted tailbacks in the mold of
record-breaker LaDainian Tomlinson as well as bigger wide
receivers. Franchione got the tailbacks he wanted in Thompson and
Omaha Pewitt's Kenny Boyd. Thompson still hasn't qualified
academically, but will be accepted as a partial qualifier if he
doesn't reach the required test scores. Wide receivers Reggie
Harrell (6-3, 200) and Reuben Randle (6-5, 200) offer Printers some
big targets.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
