<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5018 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-NATIONAL-REPORT-T     02-03 1813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NATIONAL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRACUSE STILL ROLLING AFTER CUPCAKES SLATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stop me if you've heard this one before:
</P>
<P>
   A team mostly ignored in the preseason, playing in an Eastern
time zone conference that has taken some hits in the respect
department, gets off to an undefeated start thanks to a soft
nonconference schedule featuring a bunch of home games that leads
to talk of a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a summary of Virginia Tech's football season, right?
Well, Syracuse is doing a fair basketball imitation of the Hokies.
The Orangemen weren't considered national title hopefuls before the
season. And, despite producing national champion Connecticut last
season, the Big East Conference has dropped a peg or two on the
national scene.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Boeheim set up a cupcake home schedule that helped his
team fast-break to a 10-0 record. Now, the Orangemen are 18-0 and
ranked No. 4. They appear headed for a No. 1 seed and have become
one of the favorites to succeed the Huskies as national champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't pay attention to the hype, whether it's good or
bad,'' said senior center Etan Thomas, a product of Tulsa's Booker
T. Washington High School. ``When you're playing well, everyone
loves you, and Dick Vitale goes crazy about you. When you're going
bad, everyone brushes you off to the side, saying you need to do
`this' differently or you need to do `that' differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is that this team is really not paying
attention to it, either way. You can't. You'd drive yourself crazy.
If you have a bad game, the papers kill you. Have a great game,
they hype you to where you're the next \RMichael\S Jordan. You have
to be level-headed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen have two impressive victories against Big East
contenders Connecticut and St. John's. Syracuse has a veteran point
guard in Jason Hart, athletic wing players and a tough front court.
The 6-foot-9, 260-pound Thomas controls the middle. He leads a
balanced scoring attack with nearly 14.9 points a game. He's making
64.3 percent of his shots, averages 8.6 rebounds and 4.1 blocked
shots a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are rolling pretty well right now,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   There are even some good omens. When Syracuse reached the Final
Four in 1987 and 1996 _ playing in the championship game each time
_ the Orangemen played in the Great Alaska Shootout the following
seasons. Syracuse has agreed to play in next season's Great Alaska
Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   And Hart is wearing a pair of throwback orange-and-white Nikes,
the kind worn by point guard Sherman Douglas during the 1986-87
season. Though Hart's teammates want to put him on the worst
dressed list, he points out that emulating Douglas is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ended up playing in the national championship game,'' Hart
said.
Spotlight
Florida State's big man creating noisy practices Last season,
Florida State's practices were quiet around the basket. This
season, there are quite a few more grunts and groans. It's not
exactly a WWF Throwdown, but it's quite a bit more physical when
the Seminoles bump and grind.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons for the extra contact is that coach Steve
Robinson has some post players. And one of the newcomers is big.
Really big. Freshman Nigel Dixon is 6-10 and ... well, he's now
down to 375 pounds. When practice started in October, Dixon _
nickname: Big Jelly _ weighed in around 425 pounds. He wears a size
22 shoe and his uniform pants had to be custom-tailored.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's contributing quite a bit and not all of it are his grunts
and groans,'' Robinson said. ``I like to hear that noise. And one
of the reasons for that is Nigel. He's tough to get around
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson considered redshirting Dixon, but instead has been
playing him in short hockey-like shifts that last about two
minutes. Dixon has had to lose weight and increase his conditioning
so that he can keep pace with the Atlantic Coast Conference
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been pleased with the progress Nigel's been making,''
Robinson said. ``He's starting to understand just how competitive
the league is and how competitive you have to be every time you
step on the floor. We've given him more and more opportunities to
get out there on the floor, and he's really responded well. We've
got to keep giving him those chances and see how he handles that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to continue to get in shape and get in better shape.
Nigel's in the best shape he's probably ever been in as far as
playing basketball. He has a very large frame, trying to move that
frame around at the pace that we go takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon, who is from Orlando, Fla., averaged 14.9 points and 11.1
rebounds per game last season at Edgewater High School. This season
for the Seminoles, he's averaging 4.7 minutes, 1.4 points and 1.7
rebounds per game.
Fast breaks A tough sell Northwestern coach Kevin O'Neill, who had
successful coaching stops at Marquette and Tennessee, is regarded
as one of the nation's top recruiters. He gained the reputation as
an assistant coach at Arizona. But he is facing perhaps his
greatest challenge in trying to make the Wildcats into a Big Ten
Conference contender.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Wildcats have four freshmen starters and six
freshmen among their top eight players. They're 4-15 overall, 0-7
in the Big Ten Conference. And when it comes to selling tradition,
O'Neill has little ammunition at his disposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely the biggest thing is recruiting against
tradition,'' O'Neill said. ``We've had three postseason bids in our
history. Every time we get down to the last two \Rschools\S, on
recruiting like we did four or five times in the fall, everybody
says: `Look at their record over the last 50 years. ... You're
going to go there and lose.''' Riding a Green Wave Sometimes, a
single shot can make the difference in a season. That's been the
case with Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Wave opened with a 9-1 nonconference record, then lost
its first three Conference USA games. They were headed for an 0-4
start, trailing at Southern Mississippi. But senior forward
Sterling Davis of Duncanville sank a buzzer-beating 3-pointer for a
54-53 victory.
</P>
<P>
   That victory has helped boost Tulane _ which was a disappointing
13-15 last season _ into NCAA Tournament contention. The Green Wave
is 15-4 overall and leading C-USA's National Division with a 4-3
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think we were an 0-3 team at that time,'' coach Perry
Clark said of the Southern Mississippi victory. ``I'm pleased with
the way we've handled the opportunity that shot has given us. The
chemistry has really been the biggest thing for us. The chemistry
on the court and in the locker room is a lot better.''
Layups The Mountain West and Western Athletic conferences should
regain their NCAA Tournament automatic bids for the 2001
tournament. The NCAA Management Council forwarded a proposed rule
change that would redefine a ``new'' conference. The NCAA's Board
of Directors will consider the rule change in April. The new rule
would waive the five-year waiting period needed to earn an
automatic bid.
</P>
<P>
   California spent $65 million to renovate Harmon Gym and turn it
into Haas Pavilion. Apparently, some of that money was spent on
super-sensitive smoke detectors. Three times this season, the
building has been evacuated when light smoke from concession stands
has set off the alarms. The Bears are 3-0 in those games.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford freshman forward Casey Jacobsen has a problem most
teen-agers can relate to. He's an 18-year-old with acne. That means
that Jacobsen often gets special attention from opposing fans. At
Oregon, fans in the student section chanted ``Oxy 10.'' At
California, students held up a blown-up mug shot of Jacobsen with
the word ``Zits'' written above it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's retire the worst postgame news conference question award
right now. After South Carolina lost to Vanderbilt on two free
throws by Dan Langhi with three-tenths of a second remaining,
Gamecocks coach Eddie Fogler was asked if he wanted to
intentionally foul Langhi, who is making 88 percent of his free
throws. ``That's the worst \Rexpletive\S questions I've ever
heard,'' Fogler said. Agreed.
Trash talk Arizona State freshman guard Tanner Shell on the team's
four-game losing streak:
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate losing. Losing is worse than death pretty much. You
have to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina junior center Brendan Haywood remembering how
Dean Smith was criticized for three consecutive conference losses
during his final season, and the current heat on coach Bill
Guthridge:
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all that Dean Smith did for the program and the
university as a whole, people were saying Dean Smith needed to
retire; they were basically asking for Dean Smith to be fired
because he lost three games. You can expect no less now. It's
unfortunate and definitely unfair, but that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins, responding to a comment by South
Florida coach Seth Greenberg, who compared the Bearcats to the 1990
and 1991 Nevada-Las Vegas teams:
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Seth get hit in the head? I don't see that, but I see my
guys every day. I kind of know. I think Seth's quote in the paper
was he hadn't watched a lot of film on us. That's kind of
obvious.''
Numbers game 2-15 _ Louisiana State's record in Southeastern
Conference games against Arkansas after the Tigers' 96-75 defeat of
the Razorbacks. Arkansas' 15 victories have been by an average of
11 points.
</P>
<P>
   4 _ Number of walk-on players on Rhode Island's roster, which is
down to only eight scholarship players. Two years ago, the Rams,
now 5-16, were just minutes away from reaching the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   5-14 _ The Big East Conference's record against ranked
opponents. Connecticut, which has three of those five victories,
plays Saturday at No. 8 Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   21-19 _ Purdue coach Gene Keady's record against Indiana and
coach Bob Knight. The Boilermakers, who play at Indiana on March 1,
have won eight of their past 10 meetings with the Hoosiers.
</P>
<P>
   65 _ UT-Pan American's NCAA-record road losing streak that ended
with a 79-62 victory at Oral Roberts on Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   $139.20 _ The per-game price for the 44-game suspension given
UCLA forward JaRon Rush by the NCAA. Rush reportedly accepted
$6,125 worth of benefits from a summer league basketball coach.
</P>
<P>
   724 _ Career victories for Fresno State coach Jerry Tarkanian.
He needs one more to tie former DePaul coach Ray Meyer for ninth on
the all-time list. The Bulldogs play tonight at San Jose State.
Inside the numbers Duke goes into tonight's game with North
Carolina having won 29 consecutive Atlantic Coast Conference games,
a league record. Here are the top league winning streaks in four
other conferences: Conference Team Streak Southeastern Kentucky 51
Pacific-10 UCLA 50 Big Ten Indiana 37 Big East Connecticut 19
nn
</P>
