<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUITING-ANALYSIS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Texas wins decisive edge in Big 12 recruiting 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few truths are self-evident in the inexact world of recruiting.
But this one is clear-cut, based on yesterday's influx of national
Top 100 signees to Big 12 football programs:
</P>
<P>
   Texas landed a haymaker with its most recent signing class.
Comparatively speaking, no one in the South Division punched back.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there were plenty of heralded recruits who signed with
South Division rivals, most notably Oklahoma and Texas A&AMP;M. But one
statistic screams louder than the rest: Of nine players from the
``Star-Telegram'' National Top 100 list who signed with South
Division schools, seven selected Texas. No other school had more
than one.
</P>
<P>
   When push comes to shove, these are the difference-makers who
decide championships. And it has been many a moon since Texas
lapped the field so thoroughly against its closest conference
rivals in collecting the bluest of the blue-chip players.
</P>
<P>
   Even last year, when the Longhorns' recruiting class was rated
as the nation's best by most analysts, Texas A&AMP;M answered with a
class that ranked fifth nationally. In 1999, Texas landed eight
members of the national Top 100 and A&AMP;M signed four.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the disparity widened. Texas' 23-player class is
considered a consensus top-five by recruiting analysts. A&AMP;M needed
two 11th-hour signatures from a pair of heralded defensive linemen
to squeeze into the Top 25. Oklahoma, with its best showing in
Texas since 1994, cracked the Top 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to say Texas clearly won this year,'' said
recruiting analyst Bobby Burton, director of the Rivals100.com Web
site. ``They had a great follow-up year. It was almost impossible
for them to match (1999). But, with very few exceptions, they did a
tremendous job.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowning achievement was a sweep of the state's top three
receivers: B.J. Johnson, Roy Williams and Sloan Thomas, all three
national Top 100 prospects. All three fit Texas' most pressing need
on offense. All three were highly coveted by A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum,
who identified receiver as ``the one area where we had some
disappointments'' in the Aggies' 22-member signing class.
</P>
<P>
   Burton pointed to the Longhorns' sweep of the heralded trio as
``the story of the year'' on the local recruiting front. Others
might focus on the fact that A&AMP;M's nine-player haul from the state
Top 100 list ranks as the Aggies' skimpiest since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, this is A&AMP;M's least-heralded class in Slocum's
12 years at the school. But it's still good enough to crack the
national Top 25, which gives you an idea how high the bar has been
set.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, the dropoff will be greeted with angst by some A&AMP;M
fans who sense the state's recruiting pendulum swinging toward
Texas. It's a viable concern, but one that recruiting analysts deem
premature ... for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to raise the flag of surrender,'' said Jeremy
Crabtree, director of Big 12 Blitz, a recruiting site for
Rivals100.com. ``But this was the first time in a long time that
we've seen some major separation between the two \Rclasses\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum, for one, considers the Aggies' haul undervalued by
outsiders. Just the same, most analysts rank A&AMP;M's class as
fifth-best in the Big 12 _ behind Texas, Nebraska, Oklahoma and
Colorado. A&AMP;M is downgraded for a lack of offensive firepower, with
wide receiver Robert Ferguson considered the only dangerous
playmaker among the signees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't pay attention to those rankings,'' Slocum said.
``I've been recruiting long enough to know that a whole lot of this
is a guess, anyway. We don't claim to be authorities. But these are
guys who we feel good about.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska coach Frank Solich would be feeling better this morning
if the Cornhuskers had not lost two Texas-based recruits to other
schools yesterday. San Antonio native Carlyle Holiday signed with
Notre Dame, leaving Nebraska without a quarterback in its
recruiting class, and safety Adrian Mayes, a Houston resident,
broke his Nebraska commitment and signed with Louisiana State.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the defending conference champs pieced together a class
ranked among the nation's top 10. Texas was the only other Big 12
school among that group, a status embraced by Longhorns coach Mack
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year's class has been as good as celebrated,'' Brown
said. ``We feel like this year's class can be every bit as good. To
reach our goal of winning every game and being the best team in the
country, we need to continue to bring in full classes like we have
the last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   By all available measuring sticks, Texas certainly widened the
gap between itself and its South Division peers yesterday.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
