<HEADLINE>
RODMAN EXPECTED TO SIGN WITH MAVS, BUT DEBUT UNCERTAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dennis Rodman doesn't yet have a one-year contract for
a place to play, but he does have a four-month lease on a place to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, expected to sign with the Mavericks today and possibly
play tonight against the Charlotte Hornets at Reunion Arena, has
accepted Mark Cuban's offer to stay in his 4,000-square-foot guest
house adjacent to his Preston Hollow mansion.
</P>
<P>
   The price? $3,000 per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the salary-cap rules, I've got to charge him
something,'' Cuban, the Mavericks' owner pending NBA approval, said
yesterday afternoon while shooting baskets on his outdoor court.
``He can stay through the end of the season if he wants. But it's
not just him. I made that offer to any player.''
</P>
<P>
   Having already made unprecedented concessions allowing Rodman to
show up for games later than teammates and ride a stationary bike
during practice, Cuban defended his latest red-carpet treatment of
the 38-year-old cross-dressing forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not special privileges,'' Cuban insisted. ``I'm flying
the guys \RMichael Finley, Dirk Nowitzki and Hubert Davis\R and
their families to All-Star Weekend in my plane. I'm letting Greg
Buckner pay to drive one of my cars. I'd do anything to make my
players feel more comfortable and more productive. That's the
bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Making Rodman more cozy started yesterday with one of Cuban's
assistants going on a Rodzilla shopping spree. Not surprisingly at
the top of the list: dark, block-out-the-sun curtains.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can do whatever he wants to, stay out all night long,''
Cuban joked. ``As long as at games he helps us win, and I know he
can and will. There won't be any curfews or bed checks, and if he's
late with the rent, I'll just charge him some interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, who is host to agent Steve Chasman in his new digs this
week, passed his physical yesterday and began the process of
returning to basketball shape. He could be ready tonight or, more
likely, next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether he still has the same skill level he
had when he played with the Bulls,'' coach/general manager Don
Nelson said. ``I imagine he has lost a little, but we would still
think he is good enough and dominant enough at what he does to be a
major factor. It is kind of a no-brainer on picking up a
potentially very good player for our team for really nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's contract for the remainder of the season will be
$463,410 if he signs before tonight's game, or minus $12,195 for
each game afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said Rodman's debut will occur without the glitzy media
blitz usually associated with the NBA's most tattooed player and
ferocious rebounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to minimize the distractions until he starts playing,''
said Cuban, who indicated Rodman would be introduced at a game
instead of a pregame news conference. ``The first time you'll see
him, he'll be grabbing a rebound in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks could use some; they are being outrebounded by an
average of 8.8 per game. But how will Rodman's defensive abilities
fit on the NBA's fifth-ranked scoring offense?
</P>
<P>
   ``The offensive part is real simple because all of our plays
take place on the weak side,'' Nelson said. ``It is real simple to
set screens on the weak side and go to the glass. That is what
\RRodman\S does anyway. We'll make it real simple on the offensive
end for him and let his skills take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson also said NBA rules limiting contact in the paint won't
affect Rodman's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new rules limiting physical play at the beginning of the
season is history,'' he said. ``As we go into the middle of the
season, it is more the same-old same-old.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
