<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS, MARINERS TALK ABOUT EDMONDS DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Angels are talking with the Seattle Mariners about a
possible trade of center fielder Jim Edmonds, which would be
contigent on the Mariners first trading Ken Griffey Jr. to the
Reds.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are seeking pitching and prospects from the Mariners
for Edmonds, but the price might be too high for Seattle GM Pat
Gillick considering Edmonds, according to a source, would not
re-sign with Seattle once the 2000 season is over and he is a free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Mariners players the Angels are interested in is
pitcher John Halama, who went 11-10 in his rookie season last year.
Ironically, he was one of the players the Houston Astros gave up
for Randy Johnson, only to lose Johnson to free agency after the
season. The same thing would happen to the Mariners if they trade
for Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds' agent Paul Cohen would not speak specifically on a
potential trade with the Mariners or any other team, but said
Edmonds is looking forward to the upcoming season and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, he and I are both planning that in seven months
he'll be a free agent,'' Cohen said. ``Having said that, he's going
to give 110 percent to the fans and his teammates if he's here. But
the concept of playing in Anaheim is not appealing because a lot of
issues have not been handled properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen would not be specific on what issues, but when asked if
they were issues directly pertaining to Edmonds or were team
issues, he said: ``Both.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds continues to work out rigorously in preparation for the
season, including skating at Disney Ice to build up his legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's enamored with the fans and he's loyal to his teammates,''
Cohen said. ``If he's here, I expect him to have a fantastic
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels GM Bill Stoneman said he continues to talk to teams about
possible trades, but said he feels no pressure to get something
done before spring training opens in less than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a deal is available to help us, we'll do it,'' Stoneman
said. ``I'm not worried about when we do it. You can speak of
ideals, but we don't live in that world. We continue to have
discussions and there are a lot of them being discussed now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 0202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
