<HEADLINE>
TOMMIE SMITH: SNAPS FROM   A STRUGGLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Please, have a seat and make yourselves
comfortable. Our slide show will begin shortly. But first, a brief
explanation, lest you're wondering why we've brought you to this
tired old room inside the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The floor outside the door has been a launching pad for many of
the world's finest sprinters over the years, all participants in
the Los Angeles Invitational that will take place for the 40th year
in this building later this month.
</P>
<P>
   We are privileged to have in our midst one of the greatest
runners ever to scorch the Invitational's straightaways. He is
truly one of the more remarkable athletes and activists of our
time, an African-American man who let his conscience be his guide
and in doing so helped make the world safe for Michael Jordan's
signature sneakers and Ricky Williams' dreadlocks; Ken Griffey
Jr.'s marketability and Tiger Woods' popularity.
</P>
<P>
   We're speaking of Tommie Smith, who broke 11 world records in
his day. He has amazing acceleration, but that's probably not what
you remember. Most people recognize him for something he did while
standing still as the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1968 Olympics in Mexico City, Smith won the 200 meters,
then raised his black-gloved right fist to the sky on the awards
podium during the playing of the U.S. anthem.
</P>
<P>
   That picture, which found its way into papers and magazines all
over the world, launched a thousand tirades, not to mention
hundreds of rocks, bottles and coins and a few death threats. It is
the lasting image many people have of Smith. He'd prefer that you
picture him as the college-educated son of a sharecropper or a
longtime teacher and coach at Santa Monica College.
</P>
<P>
   But if the black glove fits, you can't quit addressing it.
Especially on the third day of Black History Month. Isn't that
right, Tommie?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is indeed. So that's where I might as well start.''
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)Click(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems most everybody I meet has seen this picture. I'm on
the Olympic awards podium in Mexico City in stocking feet, my head
bowed and my right fist raised. My teammate John Carlos, who
finished third, is standing behind me, also in stocking feet with
his left fist raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``What many people don't realize is, this wasn't a spontaneous
act of rebellion. We had been planning some kind of civil-rights
protest for a year and a half. People think it was a gesture of
hate, but it wasn't. It was a gesture of frustration over the
social inequities that existed in this country at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved my country and I wanted it to be well, more perfect.
But a lot of people looked at me like I was a malignant piece of
humanity for doing what I did. It was really tough. I was shunned
for years after the Olympics. I had a hard time finding work.''
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)Click(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a picture from my Olympic 200 semifinal heat. What a
lot of people don't realize is how close I came to not even being
able to run in the final. I slowed down as I was crossing the
finish line in the semis and pulled a groin muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I didn't know what had happened. There had been so
many threats in the months leading up to the Olympics, my first
thought was that someone had shot me. I was sure of it. I felt a
sharp pain in my groin and I looked down to see if there was any
blood. When I didn't see any, I was filled with relief.''
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)Click(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the house in San Jose where I was living with my wife
and young son after the Olympics. Notice the front window is
shattered. People kept throwing bottles and rocks through it. It
was scary. I had to go to night school at San Jose State because I
was too scared to go during the day.''
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)Click.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am at my computer reading my e-mail. Everybody knows
where I am now, so I can't hide. I get e-mail from women, men, in
their 60s, 70s, and 80s who tell me how their views of me have
changed over the years. One guy, he was 82, he explained in an
e-mail how much he hated us for disgracing America. But over the
years, he said he has come to see why we did what we did and that
I'm now his hero.''
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)Click(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a picture from the 1992 Olympics, 24 years after
Mexico City. U.S. basketball superstar Michael Jordan, who is paid
by Nike to wear its shoes and sportswear, has draped himself in the
American flag, to cover the Reebok insignia on his sweats. These
days, that's what passes for controversy. It's not a social
struggle anymore, it's all about financial gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't begrudge Michael Jordan and the others what they're
doing. I just hope they're positioning their finances so the needy
are receiving some of the benefits of their greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)Click(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am, in my broom closet of an office at Santa Monica
College, with a recruit visiting from Canada. He is looking at a
picture of me that was taken at the 1968 Olympics. It was so funny.
He asked me, `Have you ever met that guy?' When I told him that guy
was me, he went berserk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
