r s BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LAD     02-03 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD D EARNS AN A-PLUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The UCLA Bruins might not defeat Stanford tonight
at Pauley Pavilion. They might not play well and they might not
play hard. They might not rebound well, pass well or defend well,
but they'll probably score.
</P>
<P>
   As in, make a basket.
</P>
<P>
   As in, avoid a shutout.
</P>
<P>
   This is no joke. Stanford's defense is that good.
</P>
<P>
   Through 18 games, the Cardinal has the best statistical defense
!ital!in college basketball history!off!. Opponents are shooting
33.1 percent against Stanford. The NCAA record for field-goal
defense is 35.8 percent, set by Marquette in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Only three opponents have shot better than 40 percent against
Stanford this season. No one has shot better than 50.
</P>
<P>
   The second-ranked Cardinal (17-1, 6-1) leads the Pac-10 in
scoring defense, field-goal defense, 3-point field-goal defense,
rebounding, rebounding margin, defensive rebounds and blocked
shots. It has made 30 more free throws than its opponents have
shot.
</P>
<P>
   But again, the Bruins probably aren't in danger of a shutout.
After all, Washington State scored 38 points on the Cardinal.
Oregon State scored 45. Tenth-ranked Auburn scored 58.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do it partly out of necessity,'' Stanford coach Mike
Montgomery said. ``We're not always real smooth offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Montgomery's first dynamite defense; Stanford held
opponents to 38 percent shooting last year, a Pac-10 record for six
more weeks. But it's unquestionably his best _ a perfect
convergence of talent and tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery's defense is nearly risk-free. The Cardinal does not
fall for pump fakes and it does not gamble for passes. (Stanford
was last in the Pac-10 in steals last season and it's last this
season.) Instead, the guards are instructed to play sound, nose-to-
nose defense, put a hand in the shooter's face and prevent
penetration.
</P>
<P>
   Those principles aren't unique. What makes Stanford's defense
different is the responsibility given to the big men. The guards
are not allowed to help when the ball enters the low post, there
are no double-teams, and switching is forbidden. That means
opposing guards are never open on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   With 6-8 Mark Madsen, 6-10 Jarron Collins, 6-11 Jason Collins
and 6-11 Curtis Borchardt, Stanford has the shot-blockers to make
the system work. (It leads the league with 6.11 blocks per game.)
There are arms everywhere. Opposing big men can't see the basket
and opposing guards constantly have defenders in their faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a couple things going for them,'' Cal coach Ben
Braun said. ``They're very smart. They don't gamble. They don't
give you a lot of opportunities and they play great position
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the guys inside... they don't need to double-down, so
there aren't a lot of open looks. You have to make a play. And with
their depth, they can use fouls, which enables them to play more
physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the NCAA record for fewest points scored in a game (six)
isn't in danger tonight. But considering the Bruins' production
against ranked teams _ 43 points against Gonzaga, 61 against
Arizona, 58 against Oregon _ (begin ital)they(end ital) are.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up steam: After a slow start that included a brutal
schedule and lofty expectations, Gonzaga has found its groove. The
'Zags have won eight straight and are rolling toward another West
Coast Conference title. With a few more wins, they'll clinch an
at-large berth (in case they don't win the WCC tournament).
</P>
<P>
   The difference: perimeter shooting. The 'Zags made 6 of 37
3-pointers in a loss to Temple _ a typical performance for them in
December _ but guard Richie Frahm has sparked a sweet shooting
surge. In eight January games, Frahm averaged 19.6 points and shot
57.1 percent from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Pac-10: Delusional but true: Washington State has
installed a parquet floor in Friel Court. Imagine the reflection of
all those NCAA-championship banners.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's 26-point loss at Louisiana State was the largest
defeat in coach Lute Olson's 16 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats scheduled the game so senior Eugene Edgerson, a New
Orleans native, could play before his hometown fans. One problem:
Edgerson is redshirting this year for academic reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Cal center Nick Vander Laan (10.1 ppg, 6.8 rpg) is one of the
league's most surprising freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 has two nonconference games left: Washington State
against Texas-Pan American and UCLA against Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   And finally: Stanford has three starters from Southern
California (Casey Jacobsen, Mike McDonald and Jarron Collins), and
UCLA has two (Billy Knight and Jason Kapono). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
