<HEADLINE>
RED WINGS A TRUE TEST FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Kings know the Detroit Red Wings are not the
New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   They know that Tuesday's 5-2 victory over the Islanders, who are
last in the Atlantic Division, was two points they needed. But in
their minds the Red Wings, who visit Staples Center for the first
time tonight, are the best team in their conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others may challenge them, but year in and year out there is
no one who can say they are better,'' Kings coach Andy Murray said.
``They have four great lines and terrific defensemen. Oh, and they
have quite a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Scotty Bowman has eight Stanley Cup rings. The Kings
are just trying to make the playoffs. The Red Wings, who lost 5-3
Monday night in Phoenix, are second in the conference with 69
points, one behind St. Louis. The Kings are seventh with 54, but
just two points ahead of the 10th place Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings (22-21-7) have played Detroit tough this year, a
1-1 tie in early November and a 3-1 loss Dec. 10 that included an
empty net goal by the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot of speed and talent, but we stayed after
them,'' Murray said. ``I really believe that we are a team you
don't want to face in the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   Opportunity: Donald Audette hoped to be back from his sprained
left ankle by the last road trip. Now, it is anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Audette, sidelined almost a month, suffered a setback Monday
during practice. Now, Murray is using rookie Jason Blake in
Audette's spot on the second line beside Bryan Smolinski and Glen
Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not certain when Donald will be back,'' Andy Murray said.
``I thought Jason had played well recently and I like the jump he
brings to the ice. He works well with the veteran players.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray says one reason is because Blake has become a more
well-rounded player. He was a scorer in college and thought he
needed to duplicate that role here. In his first game with the
Kings last year, Blake scored a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just figured it would be the same here,'' Blake said. ``I
learned in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   He learned a lot Nov. 6 when he replaced Jozef Stumpel as the
first-line center, Blake's natural position in college.
</P>
<P>
   There he was regularly beaten up by Flyers center Eric Lindros,
who is nine inches taller. Blake was back on the bench the next
night and Len Barrie was called up from Long Beach to take his
place.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said Blake right now seems better suited to the wing than
center. ``Defense is the hardest position to learn followed by
center,'' he said. ``Playing the wing is more instinctive. I like
the chemistry he has with the other two.''
</P>
<P>
   Audette hopes to be back after this weekend's All-Star break,
but he has been optimistic before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets better then it gets worse,'' Audette said of the
ankle. I've been going out of my mind with boredom. This is the
worst.''
</P>
</TEXT>
