<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS STUMBLE AS VISITING BULLS EARN NINTH VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sonics center Horace Grant was the last to get
dressed. He needed extra time to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Grant had been injured Wednesday night. But the 13-year
veteran likened the Sonics' 88-81 loss to the Chicago Bulls to
being punched in the stomach. And the analogies went on and on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like someone went and took food off my table,'' Grant
said. `` ... It's a sickening feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in case the point needs to be made clearer, this was the
Sonics' worst loss this season. The Sonics brought relatively
nothing to Key-Arena against the league's worst team.
</P>
<P>
   No rebounding power.
</P>
<P>
   No intensity.
</P>
<P>
   No focus.
</P>
<P>
   So much for a solid victory Tuesday night at Utah.
</P>
<P>
   That was all but negated as the Sonics (29-18) allowed the 9-34
Bulls to dictate the tempo and control the game down the stretch.
Chicago snapped its four-game losing streak, while the Sonics lost
for the fifth time in the past seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're only as good as you play,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal
said. ``We beat Utah and we think we're good. Then, we come in here
and lose to Chicago and that's who we are. ... It shouldn't have
been a close game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were lulled into a half-court game and never
distanced themselves from the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Tied at 71 with 6:03 left in the game, the Bulls outscored the
Sonics 17-10 the rest of the way. Bulls rookie Ron Artest (24
points, 14 in the fourth) made eight of nine free throws in the
final three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Toni Kukoc did the most damage, scoring a game-high 31 points on
13-of-21 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics had several chances to a claim the victory in the
game's final minutes. But they unraveled. Trailing 80-78, Bulls
rookie Elton Brand pierced the Sonics' defense and sank a 7-foot
jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gary Payton was called for an offensive foul on the next
play. The Sonics fouled Artest, and before he stepped to the line,
Payton drew a technical foul. Artest converted all three foul shots
to put the Bulls ahead 85-78 with 27.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one sticks with you a little bit, knowing we could have
been the third team in the league with 30 wins,'' Sonics guard
Brent Barry said. ``We could have taken another step forward. But
this was probably two steps back.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the type of bad losses that hurt playoff positioning.
And the Sonics felt a drastic blow Wednesday night. They entered
the game fourth in the tough Western Conference standings.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Sonics from that perch to sixth behind
Sacramento and slightly ahead of Minnesota and the Phoenix Suns,
who visit KeyArena Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics never led the Bulls by more than seven points in the
first three quarters. The game was knotted at 40 by halftime. The
Sonics' biggest lead was 62-55 in the third. They led by five
points heading into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls took their first lead late in the fourth quarter when
former Sonics guard Hersey Hawkins' layup gave them a 71-69 lead
with 6:21 left to play. Hawkins played his first game in Seattle
since he was traded to Chicago during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'm extremely proud and happy,'' Hawkins said. ``The
young guys really played great basketball. I told them I may buy
them all dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls were the aggressors _ particularly on the boards _
most of the night. Chicago held a 13-1 advantage in offensive
rebounding by halftime, and won the rebounding battle, 39-34, for
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just sleepwalking in the first half. It was
pathetic,'' said Westphal, who wrote 13-1 on a board in the locker
room at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was on deaf ears, so to speak,'' said Grant, who along with
Baker finished with seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Baker led the Sonics with 19 points. Unfortunately for the
Sonics, it was an off-night for Payton. He struggled through
5-for-18 shooting with 10 assists and five turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said the only explanation for the loss is complacency.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not at his best, then other guys have to step up,''
Grant said. ``He did other things to help us. He shouldn't have to
score 30 points a night for us to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you don't match a team's intensity, I don't care who
they are and how bad their record is, you're going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
