<SLUG> BC-CPT-MAC-REPORT01-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Updated Internet Explorer will have major improvements
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the sale of Netscape to America Online, you
probably thought the Internet browser wars were over. Think again.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft may now be the clear leader, but it is readying to
release a new version of its Internet Explorer browser for the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Called Internet Explorer 5.0, this version sports a new look, a
faster engine to draw pages and an easier-to-use search feature.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes built-in automated support for those
participating in Internet auctions. The browser's Auction Tracker
feature will keep you posted on how your bid is faring.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Netscape is also readying a new version for
the Mac, but it looks like Explorer is going to be the first to
market, sometime early this year.
</P>
<P>
   As always, both Netscape Navigator and Explorer are free. You
can download the new versions from various sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a close look at some of Explorer's top new features:
</P>
<P>
   What Microsoft seems proudest of, based on the hype in its
promotional material, is something called Tasman. That's the code
name for a new software engine that builds the Web pages you see
within the browser.
</P>
<P>
   Tasman represents a complete rebuild of how Explorer constructs
Web pages. In doing so, Microsoft not only sped up its browser but
added lots of new technologies. For example, Explorer will provide
better support of tables, cascading style sheets and the latest
version of HTML.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, these improvements will work across both platforms.
No longer will a page that works on a PC fail to display on a Mac.
Or so Microsoft claims.
</P>
<P>
   What's received the most media attention in Explorer 5.0 is
Auction Tracker, and it's a pretty cool feature. Basically, once
customized by a user, it will automatically track a bid you've
made. Auction Tracker will alert you if you've been outbid,
enabling you to either drop out or raise your offer.
</P>
<P>
   Auction Tracker is set initially to support 10 of the
most-trafficked auction sites.
</P>
<P>
   While not as publicized, the new Search Assistant will be
appreciated by a lot of users, especially those new to the
Internet. In essence, what it does is reduce Internet searching to
understandable, everyday language.
</P>
<P>
   All the mechanics of searching are hidden from the user. You
tell Search Assistant what you're looking for, say a name, price or
company, and it fires up the appropriate search engine.
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in learning more about Explorer 5.0, check
out Microsoft's promotional material at www.microsoft.com
</P>
<P>
   /mac/ie/default.htm. The site also has an interactive demo of
the product.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-31-00 1049EST &QL;
</P>
