<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-TOOLS01-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Wine CD-ROM tells more than you may want to know
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I should preface this review of a CD-ROM called Oz
Clarke's Ultimate Wine Guide by saying that I am no student of the
grape, nor much of a consumer of it. Put a glass of it in front of
me and I'll try it. If it doesn't cross my eyeballs I'll be polite
and drink most, or even all, of it, but I'll rarely have a refill.
</P>
<P>
   So when I plugged in this CD from DK, the first thing that
caught my eye on the opening page was a section called ``When to
Drink Wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps I'm just drinking it at the wrong time, I thought, an
hour too early or something like that, so I double-clicked there.
What resulted was a page entitled ``When to Drink Wine: a Guide to
Laying Down.''
</P>
<P>
   It would seem evident that if you need a guide to lying down,
your problem is not when to drink but when to stop drinking.
Personally I am well-versed in the art of lying down, seldom
missing an opportunity to do so, and was about to depart the page
when I realized my misapprehension. Clarke was talking about the
best time in the life of a wine to drink it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, one thing led to another, and finally to the annual
vintage reports from New South Wales, Australia, where one learns
that in 1999, the Hunter Valley had rain at the wrong times and it
wasn't a memorable year for red varieties (no Brokenwood Graveyard
Shiraz will be produced) and Orange and Mudgee also had a wet
vintage and rot was a big problem.
</P>
<P>
   Well, enough of that. On to Mr. Clarke himself.
</P>
<P>
   He is well represented here by numerous video clips and proves
to be a man much given to lip-smacking, gestures of epicurean
ecstacy and all the other things that seem to be required of a wine
connoisseur. I suppose if you are going to get into wine
appreciation you have to learn to say things like ``buttery spice
wrapped around a warm, mouth-filling center of very ripe sweet
fruit. Powerful, long finish.'' You probably also need to
understand them.
</P>
<P>
   All that aside, this CD seems to be an extremely useful tool for
those who want to learn a lot about wine and its accouterments.
Clarke leaves no stone that I can see unturned. There is a section
on matching wines with food and a long dissertation on the art of
wine tasting (which, stupidly enough, I imagined to involve nothing
more than getting it into your mouth, tasting and and then
swallowing or spitting it out, as warranted).
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who merely wish to avoid embarrassment at
dinner, the Wine Selector is just the ticket. Here you can click on
food match, and by selecting from a list and then from variations,
get very close to the kind of food you intend to serve. You don't
have to be into cordon bleu dishes, either.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you're going to serve chili, and you're enough of a
twit that you want to serve a wine with that. Clarke won't let you
down. Unless you narrow the search further by specifying the
location from which your wine should emanate, you get a selection
of 52 wines, every last one of them two stars out of three. For
instance: Steele Catfish Vineyard Zinfandel, a spicy blockbuster
red, which tastes like brambly fruit with ripe spice flavors, full,
smoothly textured and capable of some age, with a list of its best
years. If you then go to the search screen and enter Steele, you'll
find these wines range from moderately priced to very expensive.
</P>
<P>
   It would be more useful to put the price range with the rest of
the information, since you may not want to break the bank on
something with which to wash down chili. Nonetheless, making up a
list of possibilities from the selector, printing them out and
taking them to the store will at least save you a conversation with
some fruity-flavored, full-bodied, long-finished wine peddler.
</P>
<P>
   For ordering information, call (877) 884-1600.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-31-00 1049EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
