<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-CENTERPIECE-BLIND01-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Connecting to the blind
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta's Center for the Visually Impaired is focusing
on using the computer to give employment and independence to blind
citizens who want to work.
</P>
<P>
   In that connection, the center, located in downtown Atlanta,
works on computer skills and communicates with businesses that may
be able to adapt data-processing and other jobs to the skills of
the blind.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the kinds of skills being developed at the center,
which is funded by the state and private agencies such as the
United Way, blind people work at companies like BellSouth Mobility,
Federal Express, Wachovia Bank, Marriott, MARTA and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, if human resources people look beyond the supposed
handicap, they will see dependable employees who are likely to
stick for a long time because they value their opportunity,'' said
Susan Bernardo, the center's adaptive technology coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   For people interested in the center's programs, Bernardo said
the guidelines are few but important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good typing skills, not the hunt-and-peck variety, are very
important,'' said Bernardo. The center has its own typing or
keyboarding classes.
</P>
<P>
   Good typists are then introduced to special computer software
that can translate text to speech, which is the primary means the
blind person uses to process material on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the partially blind, the mouse is put aside in favor
of keystrokes for opening, processing, closing and organizing
files.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sighted people don't even realize it, but nearly everything
done with the mouse can be done from the keyboard,'' Bernardo said.
</P>
<P>
   Paper documents that come to the blind worker can be scanned on
a machine adjacent to the computer and converted quickly to
electronic files, which then can be handled by the worker.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are exceptions, most blind workers can work only
on text files because it is harder for them to process files with
pictures and graphics _ although some programs can help the blind
operator identify pictures though they cannot see them.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, with the help of the staff at the Center for the
Visually Impaired, many of the information or data-processing jobs
in business can be adapted to the software learned by the blind at
the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can adapt the processes, or companies can contract out that
work to others,'' Bernardo said.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Zibula, marketing and public relations assistant at the
center, said there is a challenge in helping businesses understand
the capabilities of the blind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sighted person looks at her computer, then closes her eyes
and imagines being blind and shakes her head, certain that the
machine cannot be operated without sight,'' Zibula said. ``But that
is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Blind people, either through experience or training, learn to
memorize better than others the organization of files in the
systems they use. They therefore depend less on random searching
and other common procedures used by sighted workers to find and
organize their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-mail, which is the most common form of computer
communication, is used a lot to send work and receive work from
blind workers,'' Bernardo said, partly because it is formatted in a
familiar way and can be adapted to many tasks.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a satisfying skill because it opens communication
between the blind person and fellow workers and with family
members.
</P>
<P>
   Zibula, who is blind, carries around a remarkable device, not
much larger than the now-familiar PalmPilot, called a Braille Lite,
which operates on the Braille system to fetch files from computers
and then allows her to read them, process them and store them in
computers as regular text files.
</P>
<P>
   It can store and manage about 2 megabytes of material at once,
about equal to two floppy disks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I carry this everywhere with me; I'd rather dispose of my
microwave than this machine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While agencies like the Center for the Visually Impaired expand
their daily work to put the blind into the work force, others such
as the Graphics, Visualization &AMP; Usability Center in Georgia Tech's
College of Computer Science work the frontiers to create new ways
for the blind and other people with disabilities to work with new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, advances are being made in translating not only
text but various kinds of graphics into auditory form, which will
further expand the abilities of the blind to work and function.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it would be very helpful to the blind if people would
simply realize that computers allow them to work and carry
responsibility in practically any kind of organization or
company,'' said Zibula.
</P>
<P>
   ``An estimated 75 percent of the blind are either unemployed or
underemployed, but with the computer that record could be
improved.''
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITES
</P>
<P>
   www.access2020.com
</P>
<P>
   Access 20/20: The only Internet site that translates text into
Braille online
</P>
<P>
   research.umbc.edu/(tilde)roswell/blind-access.htm
</P>
<P>
   Web Access for the Blind: A collection of links to sites that
offer resources, software and advice to assist the blind in using
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   www.mdtap.org/tt/1999.03/1-art.html
</P>
<P>
   Your Legal Rights to Assistive Technology: Explains the rights
that blind (and other physically challenged people) have when it
comes to the government and employers.
</P>
<P>
   www.nfb.org/computer.htm
</P>
<P>
   Computer Resources for the Blind: A text list of computer
products and software intended for use by the blind.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
