<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-GAMER01-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Just one of new critters you're sure to encounter in Half Life &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   With football winding down, it's time to once again concentrate
on basketball as our primary sport of choice. Just in time for the
switch is 989 Studios' NBA Shootout 2000 ($50; www.989studios.com).
This Playstation game is a definite improvement over its
predecessor. The newest version has great graphics and rim-rocking
action. Where a lot of the basketball games lack in action (how fun
could running up and down a court shooting and scoring really be?),
Shootout 2000 excels with its Total Control shooting _ each shot is
made on a graphic meter where you measure your shot. There is also
a cool ``create-a-dunk'' feature where you design how you want your
players to crush the ball into the net. If you're looking for
handheld b-ball action, look no further than Nintendo Gameboy's NBA
3 on 3 ($30, www.nintendo.com, for the Gameboy). This is NBA action
in the palm of your hand that plays incredibly well for its smaller
format. In the game, you pick three NBA team players to go up
against another team's. The game has a fun season function that is
automatically continued every time you turn on the game. Also, look
out for those monster jams. This game does a close-up of player
taking the ball to the hole.
</P>
<P>
   You know who Lara Croft, the busty heroine of the ``Tomb
Raider'' games, reminds us of? Roger Moore. Roger Moore made his
entire career off of being James Bond. All he was _ or ever will be
_ is James Bond. As a result, everything he has acted in since
``Live and Let Die'' has been some sort of minute twist on James
Bond. He never changes his character, and that's what's so annoying
about him. It is also the problem with Lara Croft. Tomb Raider: The
Last Revelation ($50; www.eidos.com) is the fourth game in a video
game franchise that has won the hearts of prepubescent boys across
the nation. Unfortunately, the game hasn't changed much since it
was introduced three years ago. This time, Lara is back in Egypt
and accidentally unleashes an evil Egyptian god. She must quash the
god before it's too late. Just like Moore reciting that annoying
line (``Bond, James Bond''), the Tomb Raider game hasn't changed:
she looks the same, she sounds the same and the controls are the
same. The one saving grace is that this game harkens back to the
first ``Tomb Raider.'' It is action-packed and less dependent on
the puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   Combining addictive, chesslike game play with atmospheric
settings and an interesting menagerie of monsters, Odium ($40;
www.lith.com; for the PC) doesn't try to break ground in the
turn-based role-playing genre but rather tries to create a game
that's a whole lot of fun. At that goal it succeeds admirably.
Guide a small international team of soldiers into a
post-apocalyptic Russian nightmare where monsters and secrets lurk.
The downside: Amateurish voice acting, thin characters and
plotting, some interface clunkiness and tiresome cinematic scenes
that must be endured between actual game play. The upside: A
well-paced and challenging game that requires careful resource
management and some fairly deep thinking. Bottom line: What could
be higher praise than finding yourself awake at 2 a.m., emotionally
involved in Odium and struggling to find the next secret or defeat
the next set of monsters?
</P>
<P>
   Half-Life, the stunning horror-adventure game that still has us
intrigued two years after its release, has finally gotten the
sequel treatment _ well, sort of. Half-Life: Opposing Force ($40;
www.sierrastudios. com; PC only), the first official add-on to
Half-Life, is likely the most complete expansion pack to a game
we've ever seen. Instead of just adding a few levels or new weapons
to the original game, the folks at Sierra Studios instead unleash a
new adventure that takes the original premise _ escape from the
Black Mesa research lab as scientist Gordon Freeman _ and
flip-flops it. Now you play as one of the marines sent in to
eradicate Freeman. The game runs along the same timeline as the
original Half-Life and explores some of the same locations,
inserting new pieces to the story's plot. Adding to that new
monsters, new weapons and new characters to interact with, Opposing
Force takes the concept of the add-on pack and raises the bar as
far as Half-Life did for PC games. Is it worth what you'd pay for a
brand-new game? For fans of the original, Half-Life is still one of
the best single-player games in existence, and Opposing Force is
more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
