<HEADLINE>
BOXER URGES PERMANENT BAN ON INTERNET TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly rundup of computer features)   By JUDY HOLLAND   
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Barbara Boxer on Tuesday urged a federal
advisory panel to permanently ban sales taxes on the Internet,
warning that such a tax would be ``a gamble with our nation's
prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the 19-member Advisory Commission on Electronic
Commerce, Boxer also argued that exempting Internet sales from
taxes wouldn't give Internet merchants an unfair advantage over
more traditional retailers because the e-commerce merchants have to
deal with shipping costs but store-based merchants don't.
</P>
<P>
   Taxing Internet sales ``would be a dangerous and unnecessary
gamble with our nation's prosperity,'' the California Democrat
said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel was created to advise Congress on how to deal with the
issue of whether sales transactions conducted on the Internet
should be subject to sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Sales over the Internet, known as e-commerce, have exploded in
recent years, hitting about $20 billion during the 1999 Christmas
season. E-commerce is expected to triple every year for the next
four years, according to the National League of Cities.
</P>
<P>
   Because sales taxes are the lifeblood of state governments, many
state governments say they are losing tens of millions of dollars
in sales taxes as e-commerce mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   California's budget analyst Elizabeth Hill said earlier this
week that untaxed Internet sales may be costing the state as much
as $200 million a year in lost sales tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   In urging that e-commerce remain untaxed, Boxer argued that
technological innovation has created high-paying jobs and that
taxing e-commerce would jeopardize economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe we should risk having this growth stymied by
imposing sales taxes on Internet transactions,'' Boxer said.
</P>
<P>
   She said sales taxes are intended to pay for such services as
police, fire, sewer and water for retail merchants. But, she
argued, those public service costs don't apply to sales on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional retailers complain that they can't compete with
cyberspace merchants who aren't subject to sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But Boxer noted that Internet sales require that the e-commerce
merchant ship the product to the customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore,'' Boxer wrote, ``the argument made by
brick-and-mortar stores that Internet sellers have an unfair cost
advantage is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Her comments came a day before the Senate Budget Committee is
scheduled to hold a hearing on Internet taxation.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory commission was created by Congress last year to
make a recommendation on Internet tax policy. The panel's members,
who come from local, state and federal government and from the
e-commerce indwstry, are scheduled to present their recommendation
to Congress by April.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that a state can't force an
Internet seller or catalog to collect sales tax unless it has a
presence in that state, leaving it to Congress to make any changes.
In 1998, Congress imposed a moratorium on new Internet taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., said Tuesday she is awaiting
the commission's findings before making a judgment on Internet
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not in a position to tell the commission what to do,''
Feinstein said. ``I have supported the moratorium and I believe we
should take no precipitous action.''
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
</P>
<P>
   Judyhearstdc.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-01-00 1852EST &QL;
</P>
