<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5158 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV06-C     02-03 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: BILL GATES GOES WINDOWS SHOPPING
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Feb. 6.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVOS, Switzerland _ Co-founding what has become the world's
largest software company has made Bill Gates the richest man on
Earth. But it hasn't made him content.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Microsoft will launch the latest version of its
operating system for personal computers, dubbed Windows 2000. But
Gates knows that even if it proves to be a hit, Microsoft has but a
few years' grace before the computing multitudes seek more robust
and simpler-to-use products.
</P>
<P>
   Gates came to this snow-covered Alpine ski resort to brief his
fellow entrepreneurs, as well as assorted ``media leaders,'' on his
newly self-anointed ``visionary'' role as Microsoft's chief
software architect.
</P>
<P>
   He told the globalizers: ``I think the evolutionary approach
won't get us where we really want to be. And so it's the same type
of bet that was made when we bet the company on the graphical user
interface, (and) when we bet the company on the Windows NT code
base.''
</P>
<P>
   In Windows 2000, the durable NT (for new technology) corporate
version melds with the automated plug-and-play routines of the
Windows 95/98 consumer versions. Microsoft sees the new software as
having a useful sales life of perhaps 36 months.
</P>
<P>
   Those three years, Gates said, will be spent trying to
seamlessly blend Microsoft's crown jewel with a wide range of still
emerging Internet functions. A voice interface is also in the
works. All that, Gates added, will require ``quite rational''
research spending of $3 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Gates also believes that Windows 2000, as ``the largest systems
project in the history of the planet,'' creates a judicial bulwark
against the Justice Department's antitrust suit, which brands
Microsoft as a bullying monopolist. Should the trust-busters seek
to challenge Windows 2000, he suggests they would need to start
from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   But Joel Klein, the government's chief trust-buster, isn't
buying. He thinks the House of Microsoft may defeat itself under
the weighty burden of its inflexible ego-driven leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Such tendencies were evident when a columnist asked Gates over
ice cream why Microsoft had hired a lobbyist in a vain bid to get
Congress to cut Klein's operating budget. Gates stared back in a
cold fury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an outrageous characterization,'' Gates said. All
Microsoft had in mind was trimming back Klein's publicity budget,
he said. He alleged that Justice was using the funds to leak
damaging stuff as the case wound its way through federal court.
</P>
<P>
   While the snowflakes fell evenly on both Gates and Klein in
Davos, Klein was the guy in the white hat. Justice spends less than
$100,000 a year on its antitrust PR; Microsoft sought to cut
millions. (What truly enraged Gates were Klein's trips to such
places as Britain and Brazil, where Microsoft does business, to
coordinate antitrust work.)
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take $3 billion in annual research funds to figure
out that Gates has also bet the company by stubbornly playing
hardball with the feds. From his new spot on the mound as starting
software pitcher, he still seeks to throw strikes at the legal
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
