<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5173 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-KY-GA-SCHOOLS04-COX     02-03 1958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KY-GA-SCHOOLS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia may adopt school `councils', following Kentucky's lead
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFORT, Ky. _ To see what could be in store at public schools
all over Georgia, look at the way teachers and parents sit down
together every month in decision-making bodies called school
councils in almost every school in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   From the hollows of Appalachia to cities of the Bluegrass to
farmlands on the Mississippi River, these elected councils are
changing the old relationships of parents, teachers, principals,
superintendents and local school boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely changed our role from that of manager or
supervisor to that of facilitator,'' said Karen Cheser, a central
office administrator in the 12,000-student Kenton County school
system, in northern Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky's 1,224 school councils, which typically appoint larger
committees to study anything about a school's operation that seems
important, control each school's budget with a near autonomy that
was backed up by a sweeping Kentucky Supreme Court decision in
1994. District school boards can no longer meddle in hiring or
other matters at individual schools, curtailing powers that some
say school boards had no business exercising anyway. Others say
that many principals and superintendents quietly undermine the
councils by controlling who is on them and how much information
they get.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's proposed school councils wouldn't have the power
Kentucky councils have. But the purpose is similar _ to create more
substantive parent and community involvement, according to Gov. Roy
Barnes' education reform bill. The bill would require all 180
school boards to set up seven-member councils in every school
during the next three years. This is Barnes' answer to critics of
his bill who ask, ``What about parent accountability?''
</P>
<P>
   Experts told the governor's education reform commission last
year that for the state to hold schools accountable for their test
scores, it must give them more authority to control how they are
run and how teachers teach. Involving parents and teachers in
decision-making can lead to stronger policies, they said. Barnes
borrowed the idea of school councils from Kentucky, known for
having the oldest and strongest system of school councils as part
of its bold reform law of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on student achievement has been hard to measure, said
Jim Watts, a school reform expert with the Southern Regional
Education Board, a consortium advising Southern governors. But, he
said, ``Ultimately, reform is the responsibility of school people
and the communities that they serve. At some point in time, this
stuff has to be embraced by local people.''
</P>
<P>
   The basic idea for Georgia's school councils is the same as
Kentucky's, with budgets, curriculum and hiring put under the
scrutiny of a representative body at the school chaired by the
principal. In both versions, councils hire principals from
nominations sent by the superintendent or school board. But there
are a few differences.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia bill puts two business representatives alongside two
parent representatives, giving the community outside the school the
dominant majority. Kentucky's five-member school councils have
three teachers, two parents and the principal.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky parents sometimes complain that they should have more
of a voice to balance the three teachers, especially since the
teachers can be controlled by the chair, who is also their boss.
Others stick with the original thinking behind the teacher majority
_ teachers are the ones on the front line, under Kentucky's
accountability system.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmingly, though, the experience in Kentucky is that
successful councils work with a consensus that makes the exact
representation irrelevant. ``When they work on a common goal, they
work wonderfully,'' said Cindy Hinds, a parent who nonetheless lost
some bitter fights as a member of the Caywood Elementary School
council in Kenton County. But she doesn't blame Kentucky's council
policies, which she said work well most of the time; she blamed a
lack of leadership at the school.
</P>
<P>
   The key to a successful council, and a successful school in
general, is a strong principal, agreed Robert Sexton, director of
the Prichard Committee for Academic Excellence, a nonprofit
Lexington-based school advocacy group that has helped shape much of
Kentucky's reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Good principals, these days, know that school improvement can't
be commanded from on high, say council advocates. ``Decisions are
made better if the people doing the work are part of the
decision,'' Sexton said. ``Their purpose is to organize the school
so that student achievement increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky councils have learned from experience that this means
not wasting time arguing about school parking spaces or where to
put the soft drink machine. Getting school councils and their
committees to focus on student achievement requires that they have
student test results and a plan to do something about those
results, said Susan Perkins Weston, director of the Kentucky
Association of School Councils, which represents just under half
the state's councils. Once they have a plan with a time line, they
can make decisions about anything from class sizes to staffing
without being second-guessed by the district's central office.
</P>
<P>
   Another essential requirement for successful school councils is
intensive training, Weston said. Such training not only teaches lay
people how to conduct meetings and reach group decisions, but also
how to understand school operations and student-achievement data in
deep enough ways to connect these two things. Since establishing
councils, Kentucky has added a requirement for six hours of
training for each new member, and three hours yearly for each
re-elected member. Weston said she'd like as much as 15 hours, and
a stronger training curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Weston was dismayed to see the lack of training requirements in
Georgia's education reform bill. It gives local school boards the
charge of developing the training, although Barnes said he could
easily move that responsibility to the state school board. The bill
also says nothing about the hours or content of training. If that's
all that Georgia's reforms offer on training, Weston said, then
Barnes is not serious about school councils. ``It's a fraud,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Others in Kentucky disagree, saying a comprehensive reform bill
doesn't have to get everything right at first, as long as it gets
everything on the table. ``Even if they make mistakes because of a
lack of training, I'd rather see that than to miss that
opportunity,'' said Bill Stearns, of the Office of Education
Accountability, an arm of the Kentucky Legislature with authority
to investigate and prosecute anyone who circumvents the
decision-making powers of school councils.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is whether Georgia's councils would have any
meaningful decision-making powers at all. Confined by the language
of the state constitution, Barnes' bill makes the councils advisory
_ but with a twist. Every council recommendation stands _ in other
words, becomes controlling policy _ unless the school board
overturns it under the public scrutiny of an open meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, this is like having an appeals process for council
decisions, something the Kentucky School Boards Association has
lobbied for, said association head David Keller. ``If our boards
had that kind of safety hatch, I think there would be a lot less
concern about what happens if the council makes bad decisions,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Without the power to make real decisions, say council
supporters, Kentucky would not have some 3,700 teachers and 2,500
parents sitting through exhausting meetings in school libraries
without pay _ and that's not counting the thousands more who do the
grunt work in committees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know they have the authority, and it's not going to be
advisory, and it's going to do things for children,'' said Charles
Edwards, who oversees school-based decision-making for the Kentucky
Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   A possible weakness for Georgia councils, rather than a lack of
power, may be what some think is a lack of flexibility at the
school level. Carl Glickman, a University of Georgia education
professor who helped advise Barnes' reform commission last year,
said he is distressed over the way the reform bill dictates
policies such as the size of classes and the structure of the
councils. If a school decides to have some above-maximum class
sizes, perhaps using teacher aides, to free up money for other
things that should be a school-based decision, Glickman said. If it
wants a larger council with other sectors of the community
represented, that should also be a school decision, he said.
Glickman said he supports strong accountability from the state, but
coupled with equally strong autonomy at the school level.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' aides say that giving school councils the power and
flexibility they need will have to happen gradually, as they prove
themselves to school boards. To start out, Barnes sees school
councils as setting the pattern for achievement. ``They will be a
drum major for change, created in every school,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kentucky, school councils can expand as long as the
proportions of teachers, parents and principals remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   The council at Woodlawn Elementary, a 600-student school outside
Danville, has been given waivers by Kentucky to have 16 members and
be chaired by a teacher, rather than the principal.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent council meeting, parent Erin LeMay, council
secretary, brought up the kind of question that could blow up at
another school, where teachers aren't used to having their policies
questioned by parents. One of the council's six standing
committees, the assessment committee, had successfully recommended
throwing out letter grades in kindergarten through third grade,
replacing them with such indicators as ``SP'' for ``steady
progress'' and ``AP'' for ``accelerated progress.''
</P>
<P>
   LeMay said she and several parents she had heard from were
unhappy seeing their children's latest report card because they
felt teachers were giving out too many undeserved APs. Annette
Cooper, the teacher who chairs the assessment committee, defended
the grading system, saying it was an attempt to get away from
having children compare themselves to their peers. LeMay stood her
ground. Another mom said children were well aware of how many APs
their classmates were getting, so they were still comparing
themselves to others. A third mother, a music professor at Centre
College, suggested tabulating the number of APs and SPs that each
teacher gives, as is done at Centre College.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers did not like that idea _ at all. Principal Max Pope
came to the teachers' defense. ``Some of those APs might be
deserved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're highly deserved,'' Cooper said somewhat icily.
</P>
<P>
   No decision was reached. The principal will talk to the teachers
again about the grading system, to try to make it more consistent,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the oddly different perspectives of parents and teachers
were shared, and each side listened to the other respectfully.
That, say council supporters, is a huge step forward for public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   They say that the time and effort it takes to turn those shared
conversations into school governance is well worth it. Otherwise,
some suggest, the best state reforms will never reach the
classroom. Pope agrees, quoting something he had read from a
historian about American democracy: ``As someone said, the
government that governs best governs slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5175 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN04-COX     02-03 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You take your chances with judicial elections
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When you get right down to it, Texas judicial
races are a lot like a back-room craps game. In both, a wrong move
can have dangerous consequences, and people trust an awful lot to
luck.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, an important distinction between judicial
elections and back-room craps games: You may get to know some of
the players in the back room. In a judicial race, most voters
haven't the slightest notion who the candidates are or what they
believe. So, when you get right down to it, you make a surer bet at
the back-room table.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial races make the eyes glaze over on most voters, but talk
about changing things and you're in for a fight as bruising as any
you're liable to get into in that back room.
</P>
<P>
   This is a result of a combination of inertia, politics and
absence of major scandal.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Tom Phillips, chief justice of the Texas Supreme
Court, has expended a lot of his considerable intellect on the
issue of judicial selection. And for years, not much has happened.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Texas voters, the state's judiciary is by and
large populated by good and dedicated people at all levels.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, however, we roll snake eyes.
</P>
<P>
   People whose Texas political memories stretch back a couple of
decades will recall the Don Yarbrough fiasco. He got elected to the
Supreme Court (some say because his name was similar to the late
Ralph Yarborough, who served in the U.S. Senate in the 1960s, and
unsuccessful gubernatorial candidate Don Yarborough) but resigned
as the Legislature was gearing up to impeach him. He was later
convicted of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the more recent story of Steve Mansfield, the Court
of Criminal Appeals judge who fudged just about everything on his
resume _ including where he was born _ and wound up in the
embarrassing position of having to answer a trespassing complaint
filed by the University of Texas. Seems the judge was scalping his
complimentary tickets to UT football games.
</P>
<P>
   Yarbrough wound up in prison. Mansfield declined to seek a
second term. Those two, however, are not the only errant judges in
the state's history.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to work at it hard to hear stories of judges who
are lazy, both physically and intellectually. You hear stories of
judges who suffer from what lawyers call ``robe-itis,'' a condition
caused by a belief that election to the bench is really an election
to the papacy.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the system like to point to those as examples of what
happens when you roll the judicial dice. Others shrug their
shoulders and say all that shows is that judges are just as human
anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has spearheaded efforts to change things, but setting
fund-raising restrictions has been about as far as his efforts have
been allowed to roll.
</P>
<P>
   A system of appointing judges has been advanced periodically but
seldom gets much attention. Gov. George W. Bush has been clear on
his preference for an elected judiciary, so there isn't much point
in wasting breath on it now.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, an array of amateur and professional observers say,
there is no incentive to go through all the hassle of a
constitutional amendment election _ necessary to overhaul the
system _ because there is no outcry for it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if you listen to judicial candidates at all you will
hear some bemoan the fact that good judges lose elections simply
because of party affiliation. Republicans have lost in Democratic
tides. Most recently, it has been Democrats drowning in a GOP tide.
</P>
<P>
   That raises a cry for nonpartisan judicial elections. Not a bad
idea, actually, but one that falls into the ``fat chance''
category. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans have worked for years to get to the point where
they can elect judges and they're not about to change things now,''
is the comment echoed by candidates and others who keep close tabs
on judicial politics.
</P>
<P>
   So that combination of inertia, politics and absence of major
scandal keep us at the craps table, and we keep rolling that dice.
</P>
<P>
   Let's wish ourselves luck.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the
American-Statesman. You may contact him at agarcia(at)statesman.com
.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
