r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX     02-03 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Offensive Confederate banner not actually the official one
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Back when I was protesting the segregation of my
native South, I used to wonder what I would have done at the same
age during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   My relatives called the terrible conflict the War of Northern
Aggression or the War Between the States.
</P>
<P>
   My ancestors fought for the Confederacy. They fought long and
hard. I sure hoped they did not fight to defend slavery. I wasn't
sure what that would say about me.
</P>
<P>
   Since my relatives also fought in the Revolutionary War, and
every other war that came along, I hoped that their efforts were in
defense of their families, friends and neighbors, certainly not
slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Lee was asked to head the army of the North. He
declined even though he abhorred slavery.
</P>
<P>
   William Faulkner, the Nobel-prize winning anti-slavery novelist
who chronicled the anguish and decay of the post-Civil War South,
said he also would have chosen to defend his home state of
Mississippi during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   If only a tiny minority of Southerners owned slaves, I know of
no uprising of Southern nonslave owners who struggled to overturn
slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Even 100 years after the Civil War, it was obvious to me that
precious few of my fellow white Southerners still were ready to
give black citizens equal access and equal opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   History books say the Civil War was fought between 1861 and
1865.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it seems as though the terrible war will never end.
The latest battle is over a Confederate battle flag that flies over
the South Carolina State House.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP has threatened a boycott of South Carolina if the
battle flag is not removed.
</P>
<P>
   So far the candidates representing the Republican Party, which
is the party that fought to defeat the slave-holding South, have
ducked the issue by saying the decision is up to the people of
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The battle flag is not South Carolina's official state flag nor
was it one of the three official flags of the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   The first Confederate national flag was the ``Stars and Bars,''
which turned out to be easily confused with the Union's ``Stars and
Stripes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate lawmaker who proposed the Southern Cross design
of the currently controversial battle flag could never win approval
to make it the national flag. Versions of that design were picked
up by some of the states and commanders as a battle flag. It also
was the Confederate Naval Jack.
</P>
<P>
   The Confederacy's second national flag was the ``Stainless
Banner,'' which didn't look like the Stars and Stripes, but it
contained so much white that it was confused with a flag of
surrender.
</P>
<P>
   The third and final national flag added a red bar to the flag
that contained the Southern Cross.
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate battle flag has become the adopted symbol of the
Ku Klux Klan, neo-Nazis and other assorted racists and bigots.
</P>
<P>
   That's a shame because it allows Americans to use this symbol to
advance their political agendas by keeping the divisions of Civil
War going from one generation to another.
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas state flag uses elements of the Confederate
Southern Cross battle flag, which is incorporated in the flags of
Mississippi and Georgia. Other Southern states have flags that were
derived from the Confederacy. All Southern states have monuments
and memorials commemorating Confederate soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago I suggested that people who want to honor their
Confederate ancestors use one of the official Confederate flags in
lieu of the Southern Cross battle flag that is highly offensive to
many Americans.
</P>
<P>
   I still think it is a good suggestion. And I still wonder what I
would have done had I been a young man during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
