<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5177 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN04-COX     02-03 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Hampshire voters showed they weren't up for barter
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ George W. Bush has won an election or two, so
don't call him a learner at this electoral thing. But Americans on
Tuesday were reminded of the difference between amassing a
political doomsday money machine _ capable of vaporizing any rival
_ and actually beating rivals on election day.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire's Republican lesson proves most elemental: Donors
help. But to win, you need voters.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's result also raises questions about the soul of the
Republican Party, or at least those who claim it. McCain won
challenging two seemingly fundamental GOP tenets: first, that
massive tax cuts are more important than debt reduction; second,
that the dispensing of big campaign dollars is a precious right,
and that to harvest it is as American as amber waves and Wheat
Thins.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that the big money didn't talk so loud in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Before we read too much into that and start discounting the role
of cash in politics, hear tolled the names of rivals Bush already
has squelched with his money: Elizabeth Dole, Dan Quayle, Lamar
Alexander and John Kasich _ all scared off before a single primary
was waged.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's monster stash effectively has won him the equivalent of
half a dozen primaries by narrowing the field, and that's
conservative. When all shakes down, it may have won him the
equivalent of 50, leaving McCain's New Hampshire coup as irrelevant
as ethanol in Iowa. Bush is en route to being able to refuse public
financing of his presidential campaign, freeing him of the spending
limits that come with it.
</P>
<P>
   In debates featuring McCain, Bush has taken a peculiar tack in
arguing against the kinds of controls contained in the campaign
finance bill co-authored by McCain and Wisconsin Democrat Sen. Russ
Feingold.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would ban soft money, the unregulated donations to
parties that serve as a dodge of campaign spending limits on
presidential campaign committees.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush response to McCain-Feingold? Rather than find the
highest ``high ground'' possible in defending the legal graft of
soft money _ the argument that campaign donations are patriotic
expressions on behalf of good government _ he took the purely
partisan route.
</P>
<P>
   His argument against McCain-Feingold, at least in front of
Republican audiences, was that it amounts to ``unilateral
disarmament'' _ taking away the GOP's means of amassing death-star
war chests from corporate soft-money donations while not taking
away the Democrats' advantages, principally with trade unions.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. McCain-Feingold would restrict unions just as it would
corporations. Unilateral it is not.
</P>
<P>
   Texans should have been surprised to see Bush address the
campaign-finance issue on a national stage as if only Republicans
were watching. Clearly the most commendable feature of Bush as
Texas governor has been his ability to be above partisanship. (Some
Democrats will say that rather than being magnanimous, Bush is just
crafty at co-opting his enemies.)
</P>
<P>
   It would seem that in New Hampshire such partisanship did not
play well, not even with rank-and-file Republicans. Though the
presence of independent voters joining the fray has been known to
skew results in New Hampshire, McCain defeated Bush among
registered Republicans as well as every demographic, income and age
group.
</P>
<P>
   A giddy McCain can be forgiven for an overstatement, that in
Tuesday's vote ``the Republican Party recovered its heritage of
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear where that heritage resides, and in what movement
it ever manifested itself in recent memory. But to such pillars as
Trent Lott, Phil Gramm, Tom DeLay, Mitch McConnell and the
still-front-running George W. Bush, campaign reform sounds as icky
as squid jelly.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
