<HEADER>
A5180 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HAIRSTYLE04-COX     02-03 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIRSTYLE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book of `mullets' pays homage to the hairstyle that always swims
upstream
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Some hairstyles are considered classics.
Witness the bob, the pageboy, even the crewcut. On the right head
and under the right circumstances, they hold up decade after
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the hairstyles that simply refuse to die, even
though they never looked all that great in the first place. Exhibit
A: The mullet.
</P>
<P>
   You know the mullet _ short on top, long in back. The haircut of
singer Michael Bolton, pitcher Randy Johnson and pro wrestler Hulk
Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime people think it's gone, it's back in some way,'' says
graphic designer Mark Larson. ``What's the power?''
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to answer that question, Larson has penned ``The
Mullet: Hairstyle of the Gods'' (Bloomsbury USA, $15) with his
friend, writer Barney Hoskyns. ``You don't go to the hairdresser
and say, `Give me a mullet.' It evolves.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's humorous, heavily illustrated book traces the
evolution of the mullet all the way back to Neanderthal Man, which
they say explains the use of the phrase ``Ape Drape'' as a synonym
for the hairstyle.
</P>
<P>
   The pair, neither of whom has a mullet of his own, also gives
ink to the many incarnations of the modern mullet, from the Midwest
Metal to the Fading Glory, from the Latin Soccer Mullet to the
Lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to the mullet is it's really two haircuts on one
head,'' says Larson, 48. ``It's not only bi-level, it gives you two
chances at life. It's that kind of good feeling when you've had
your hair cut, and then you also want to rock out and have long
hair.''
</P>
<P>
   The tongue-in-cheek book began as a lark. Half-joking, Londoner
Hoskyns asked Larson, who lives in Woodstock, N.Y., if he wanted to
travel the American West snapping black-and-white, Richard
Avedon-style portraits of real people with mullets.
</P>
<P>
   They never made that road trip, but the 128-page hardcover does
contain shots of 18 mullet wearers from Woodstock, as well as a
section on mullet care and feeding (''the trick is to shampoo the
top tier more often than the lower level''), mullet cuisine
(''Twinkie-Misu: an easy adaptation of the classic Italian
delicacy'') and tips on mullet lovin' (''Don't say: `Didn't I see
you on America's Most Wanted?'; Do say: `Thank God, a real man at
last!''').
</P>
<P>
   And there's a salute to movie mullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood works in metaphor, and the mullet is shorthand for a
certain kind of power, a certain kind of nonconformity,'' Larson
says.
</P>
<P>
   Examples: Mel Gibson in ``Lethal Weapon 3,'' Jean-Claude Van
Damme in ``Hard Target,'' Eddie Murphy in ``A Vampire In
Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We never denigrate the hairstyle,'' Larson says. ``We love the
hairstyle.''
</P>
<P>
   So much, in fact, that they mainstain a Web site
(www.mulletgods.com) and are working on a movie treatment of their
book.
</P>
<P>
   MEET THE ROYALTY OF THE FISHIEST 'DO
</P>
<P>
   Mark Larson can't help but marvel at mullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will say, `That's that '70s haircut.' Watch yourself
next week and see how many mullets you run into.''
</P>
<P>
   The mall might be a good starting point. That's where Larson
spotted a mulleted gent recently in Woodstock, N.Y. The man's
thick, chestnut hair was chopped short on the top and sides, but it
flowed like a horse's mane down his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at this guy, and his hair is beautiful,'' Larson
says. ``That's the bizarre thing about it. It was actually
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at that, and you realize he'd be an ordinary guy
otherwise. It makes him spectacular in his own way.''
</P>
<P>
   Which three celebrities have had the most spectacular mullets,
according to Larson, who co-wrote ``The Mullet: Hairstyle of the
Gods''? The first two are easy:
</P>
<P>
   _ David Bowie: ``If there's a king of the mullet, it has to be
David Bowie,'' Larson says.
</P>
<P>
   Bowie sported mullets over the course of a quarter-century, from
the mid-'60s to the early '70s and right on up to '87.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have one presently, but that doesn't mean he won't
have one again,'' Larson says. ``The Ziggy Stardust mullet was a
profound choice. He went in and said, `This is what I want to
do.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Billy Ray Cyrus: ``The crown prince,'' says Larson, who
visited Cyrus backstage with members of the country singer's fan
club, many of whom were wearing mullets too. ``The symbol of his
artistry is his haircut.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lou Reed: Actually ``third place is like a big tie,'' Larson
says. Other contenders in the book include Barry White, Paul and
Linda McCartney, Martina Navratilova and Buffalo Bill Cody.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
