<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-KORS _ Michael Kors is shopping, and no item of clothing
is safe from his dead-on sense of style, eye for quality and quick
wit. ``I love a baby T. How much is it? A dollar? Excuse me! The
Gap's too high.'' The designer, visiting Palm Beach for a personal
appearance at Saks and a charity fashion show at a private home,
has one hour to pull together three outfits from the thousands of
mismatched pieces at the South Dixie Goodwill. It's a gauntlet that
we've thrown down and he has gamely picked up.SS (Sturrock, Palm
Beach Post). 90. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-SURVEY _ After years of all but outfitting herself in a
nun's habit, Fashion is ready to play dress up. Bright colors, not
boring black and khaki. Beading and embroidery and ruffles, not
unadorned stretches of fabric. Ladylike high heels, not frumpy
flats. Tailored clothes, not torn jeans and T-shirts. A look
leaning more toward Grace Kelly sophistication than sloppy grunge.
But what do you wear? We have a survey for your readers. (Sturrock,
Palm Beach Post). 15. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   HAIRSTYLES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Some hairstyles are
considered classics. Witness the bob, the pageboy, even the
crewcut. On the right head and under the right circumstances, they
hold up decade after decade. Then there are the hairstyles that
simply refuse to die, even though they never looked all that great
in the first place. Exhibit A: The mullet. You know the mullet _
short on top, long in back. The haircut of singer Michael Bolton,
pitcher Randy Johnson and pro wrestler Hulk Hogan. ``Anytime people
think it's gone, it's back in some way,'' says graphic designer
Mark Larson. ``What's the power?'' (Sturrock, Palm Beach Post). 30.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-DREADLOCKS _ Photo-driven centerpiece in which Atlantans
who wear their hair dreadlocked share short testimonials on what
they hairstyle means to them. Adaptation of format used in the new
coffee book, Dreads, forwarded by Alice Walker. (Walton, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-DIAMONDS _ Trend report on the hottest wedding ring
styles. Written as a primer for guys, these supplies tips on
selection, price, financing and what's deemed fashionable now.
(Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TV-OTHERS _ ``The Others'' is a new series about paranormal
seers from NBC that's been heavily promoted. It's a pretty solid
drama that doesn't always go in the direction you expect. Grade: B.
(Atlanta Journal-Consitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   PARKS-QA _ Q&AMP;A with celebrated photographer, Gordon Parks. (Fox,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout will be available today by 3 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 0203 -- Why all this shake, rattle and roll
on television? For starters, nostalgia-waxing baby boomers who grew
up grooving to Elvis, the Rolling Stones and Motown now run the
networks. For them, rock 'n' roll and classic rhythm-and-blues
songs bring back memories of a rebellious, fun-loving era. And
everybody already knows the stories behind the songs. (Thompson,
Palm Beach Post) Art includes a 5-column color photo from ABCs new
Beach Boys movie, a 1-column photo from VH1's ``Two of Us,''6-pica
B&AMP;W photo from NBC's ``The Temptations,'' and a 6-pica color photo
from NBC's ``The David Cassidy Story.''
</P>
