2-column color photo from ``Tarzan.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ Reviews of new releases from Guy, Enigma and The
Madd Rapper. (Staff, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ When Nelson DeMille's novel, ``The General's
Daughter,'' hit the big screen, the film got some particularly
nasty reviews. The Long Island writer gets a small measure of
revenge in his new best seller, ``The Lion's Game,'' when he has
one of his characters talking about New York Times critic Janet
Maslin's ``tortured syntax.'' Maslin will have another shot at him,
however. ``The Lion's Game'' and his previous novel, ``Plum
Island,'' have been sold to Hollywood for $1 million each.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ Michael Skube on ``Life Stories: Profiles From
The New Yorker,'' edited by David Remnick, one of almost a dozen
new books published to commemorate the 75th anniversary of the
magazine this month. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR
SUNDAY. 31.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-WILLIAMGAY _ HOHENWALD, Tenn. _ It is a bitterly cold day
in this small, southwestern Tennessee town where explorer
Meriwether Lewis committed suicide. Turning up the collar of his
faded denim jacket, William Gay lopes across a near-deserted main
street and ducks into the local pool hall and cafe. Nodding briefly
to the locals, he waits for the woman behind the bar to flip a
hand-shaped hamburger patty on the grill and orders a beer. His
agent, Amy Williams, had described him as a cross between singers
Tom Waits and Lyle Lovett, and there is a resemblance. With a
tangled mass of dark hair and a face as lined as a Tennessee state
map, the 56-year-old Gay evokes the image of someone who has lived
hard and driven on a lot of dirt roads. Most folks in Hohenwald
know Gay as a carpenter and drywall hanger, but in the rest of the
South the self-taught writer is already being talked about as the
next Larry Brown or Cormac McCarthy. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 46.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GAY-BIO _ Bio box for William Gay, along with a short excerpt
from ``The Long Home.''(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-HOLOCAUST _ Review of Roman Frister's Holocaust memoir
``The Cap: The Price of a Life,'' newly translated from Hebrew.
(Thomas, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer; not for use by
NYTNS clients). 24.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Feb. 6.
