</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-WILLIAMGAY _ HOHENWALD, Tenn. _ It is a bitterly cold day
in this small, southwestern Tennessee town where explorer
Meriwether Lewis committed suicide. Turning up the collar of his
faded denim jacket, William Gay lopes across a near-deserted main
street and ducks into the local pool hall and cafe. Nodding briefly
to the locals, he waits for the woman behind the bar to flip a
hand-shaped hamburger patty on the grill and orders a beer. His
agent, Amy Williams, had described him as a cross between singers
Tom Waits and Lyle Lovett, and there is a resemblance. With a
tangled mass of dark hair and a face as lined as a Tennessee state
map, the 56-year-old Gay evokes the image of someone who has lived
hard and driven on a lot of dirt roads. Most folks in Hohenwald
know Gay as a carpenter and drywall hanger, but in the rest of the
South the self-taught writer is already being talked about as the
next Larry Brown or Cormac McCarthy. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 46.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Feb. 6.
</P>
