<HEADLINE>
SO YOU WANT TO BE A (WEB) ROCK 'N ROLL STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOUGLAS BAILEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All the analyses written on the corporate motives behind the
giant Time Warner-America Online-EMI mergers overlooked the most
obvious, darkly ingenious one: to prevent you from becoming a rock
'n' roll star.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. The great promise of digital music recording and
publishing via the World Wide Web was that anyone from a weekend
strummer to The Artist Formerly Known As Prince could bypass the
distasteful gatekeepers of the music business and market directly
to their audience. No more having to go crawling to record industry
weasels and publishing company turks, no more having to be
humiliated by sleazy managers and agents. The performer would
control all elements of the product, from conception to publishing
to recording to distribution.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I was counting on, and as soon as I wrote my Great
American Rock Anthem, I was planning to take advantage of the Web's
Marxist axiom.
</P>
<P>
   But look what has happened. The same gatekeepers who control
access to the major recording studios and the nation's CD bins now
_ or will soon _ control access to Web music. Suddenly, the company
that serves as the Internet gateway for more people than any other
in the world _ AOL _ merges with the company that owns the most
high-speed pipes _ Time Warner _ and buys the company that owns the
Beatles, Rolling Stones, and the Beach Boys, and hundreds of other
artists _ EMI. The merged company now owns song publishers, agents,
talent scouts, producers, and is already well on the way to
delivering its music catalog directly over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The result of this consolidation, which really began in 1998
when Universal Music Group bought Polygram Records, is
mind-blowing. The six big recording companies are now the four big
recording companies. And that may drop to two before the year is
over. Layoffs will come. Recording acts will go. Less music will be
recorded, not more. Fewer acts will be signed, and the barriers to
breaking into the business for artists will be ever higher. The
distribution of Internet music, which just four years ago looked
like it would be in the hands of upstart tech companies and
Internet visionaries, will now rest with hipsters Steve Case, Ted
Turner, and Gerald Levin.
</P>
<P>
   Already, record companies are trying to register the Internet
domain names of bands under contract in order to better control Web
distribution _ and reap the profits from it. Like bands who are
overlooked because they are deemed ``not MTV friendly,'' pop acts
of the future may go unsigned and unpromoted if they're unwilling
to relinquish their rights to Internet merchandising, T-shirts,
tickets, and lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make you give up the dream and put off buying
that DAT recorder and home mixer you were going to use to produce
your songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But wait,'' you say, ``what about www.mp3.com? That's a Web
site that was founded specifically as a place where artists could
post their own recorded music for free and sell their songs without
any middleman involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   You're right, I would say. But have you visited mp3.com lately?
While its Utopian motives are praiseworthy, the Web site is a
victim of its own success. The company could hardly be called a
little upstart with its $2 billion market capitalization. And right
now, according to the site, more than 31,000 independent artists
have posted nearly 200,000 songs. You'd have better luck trying to
become a pop star by skiffling on the nearest street corner than by
trying to be spotted among 31,000 other acts. It's like being on
the world's largest ``Star Search'' without Ed McMahon to guide the
audience through
</P>
<P>
   the rubbish.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the goal of most of the bands on mp3.com is not to
sidestep the recording moguls, but be discovered by them. But is
anyone really listening to this stuff? The record companies say
they have talent scouts who do little else but surf the site in
search of new acts. Few have been found. One executive from
Atlantic Records told Forbes Magazine last year that he gets better
music sent to him on tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Music fans aren't buying, either. While mp3.com receives a small
fee from song sales _ the rest of the money goes to the artist _ 85
percent of the company's revenue is coming from on-line
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Already the company has shifted gears and is trying to become a
vast warehouse of recorded music from established acts that is
being freely copied and openly traded among its members. But this
could be shut down at any moment if the record industry succeeds in
its lawsuits against mp3.com. Even if it fails on that front, when
the record industry finally gets its Internet act together and
stops worrying about illegal copying and bootlegging from sites
like napster.com, there's nothing to prevent it from hosting its
own mp3.com-like site (mp3.com owns no proprietary technology,
copyright or product). The major record labels could easily start
their own pseudo ``Star Searches'' and let unsigned bands post
recordings on their sites. If you had a choice between uploading
your homemade digital demo tape to mp3.com or to a Web site owned
by the company that has Mariah Carey and Bruce Springsteen under
contract, what would you do? Hello Sony, goodbye mp3.com.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it. The only thing a modern-day aspiring band or pop
singer needs is old-fashion advertising and promotion. And that's
the only element of the recording process that's still mostly in
the hands of the major companies. Home recording devices, mixers,
PC sound cards, rewritable CD drives, mp3 audio players, and the
vast distribution network of the Internet are all within easy reach
of the struggling artist.
</P>
<P>
   But no one will hear your music if they don't know where to find
you. The record companies can get behind an act and flood the Net,
the rock magazines, the airwaves and billboards with advertisements
for your latest song, CD, or video. Without that support, it
doesn't matter how good your songs are or even how big your name
is. The guy who used to be called Prince found that out last year
when he went over the heads of record company executives and
distributed his new CD on the Internet. It flopped, mostly because
few people knew where to go to get it (and partly because it was
just bad music).
</P>
<P>
   EMI last year did a survey of people who said they were fans of
Bonnie Raitt in an attempt to find out why her latest CD didn't
sell well. The most common answer was they didn't know she had
released a new CD.
</P>
<P>
   An even more stunning finding comes from the recording industry
itself: of the 34,000 CDs produced last year, just 94 sold more
than a half-million copies. If these artists, who are all signed to
labels, can't sell their music, what hope does an independent
artist have?
</P>
<P>
   The answer still could be on the Internet, if artists could
figure out how to harness its power to put people in touch with
music they want but don't know is out there.
</P>
<P>
   David Goldberg, a former Bain Consulting executive and former
director of new business for Capitol Records, thinks the
controversy surrounding Internet music distribution is old news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transmitting via the Internet is going to happen,'' he says.
``But distribution has never been a problem for this industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The real issue, Goldberg says, ``is hooking people up to the
music they want even if they haven't requested it.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago he co-founded Launch Media, one of the biggest
music information sites on the Web (launch.com). Goldberg says the
industry should stop obsessing about piracy and making copy-proof
CDs and audio files (``The only truly secure music is music you
can't hear, and no one will pay money for that''), and focus
instead on connecting with the vast buying public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of great music that people never hear, but
distribution is not the solution to that problem,'' he said. ``The
radios don't play new acts, MTV barely plays music at all, and
there's no way for a new artist to break through.''
</P>
<P>
   Launch, which has about 2 million registered users, lets
customers choose their music and set up personalized ``radio''
stations of varying genres. The site keeps track of the users'
tastes and eventually will recommend music by unknown artists that
the customer will likely enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   That, someday, might be how the Great American Rock Anthem will
get heard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
