<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-COMMUTE-HELP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S IN CHARGE HERE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M.E. MALONE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1999, the concept of working from home for yourself or an
employer came under fire:
</P>
<P>
   --Sociologists warned of the isolation and anxiety inherent in
working from home.
</P>
<P>
   --The federal government suggested that employers could be held
responsible for health and safety violations at the homes of
employees who telecommute _ a position that was quickly reversed.
</P>
<P>
   --Companies announced they were working on products designed to
keep a better eye on at-home workers' hours, feeding a perception
that telecommuters are slackers.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have tried them and studied them caution that
alternative work arrangements don't work for everyone and that
there are a variety of factors to consider, financial and social.
</P>
<P>
   Costs alone put teleworking out of the reach of many Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Conference Board, a business-backed research organization,
estimates that telecommuting and other work-family initiatives are
not an option for workers who earn less than $20,000 _ more than a
third of the US work force.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of telecommuters in November by the American
Management Association, about half said their employers loaned or
purchased the necessary equipment for them to do some or all of
their work at home.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of any additional phone lines needed was paid in full
or in part by the employer in just 36 percent of the cases. In a
survey by Computerworld last year, 59 percent of the 124
information technology managers responding said their companies
furnished telecommuters with all the equipment needed to work
remotely; 41 percent said those off-site employees supplied at
least some of their own equipment.
</P>
<P>
   At HireSystems, which relies on 300 part-time employees in their
homes, the workers supply their own computers and high-speed
connections to the Internet so they can work directly on the
company's servers.
</P>
<P>
   But most telecommuters report that the gains in their personal
lives outweigh any additional costs.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Barry, director of the Community Reinvestment Act/Fair
Lending program at FleetBoston Financial, uses two phone lines, a
PC, and a fax machine, all of which she purchased, to work from
home.
</P>
<P>
   Her decision to work at home once each week came about during a
study of flexible workplace options by the Radcliffe Public Policy
Institute, in collaboration with Fleet, more than two years ago. As
a manager working on the project, she decided to try being a
part-time telecommuter to aid her understanding of flexible work
schedules. She came to rely on the time away from the office for
strategic thinking and other work preparation and has continued to
telecommute every Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she likes the personal convenience associated with
being in her home once a week during the work week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that when I telecommute one day, the rest of my week
goes much smoother. I'm more organized,'' she said. ``But I think
it takes a special kind of person to do it. I'm very focused.
Sometimes, I work until 10 p.m. on Mondays.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Besemer of HireSystems agrees that not everyone is
suited for working at home. Usually, she said, the company and the
employee know within two months whether the arrangement will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that what doesn't work for some people is the lack
of a structured work environment. They had good intentions, but
find that with their schedules and other things, they just don't
get to (the work).''
</P>
<P>
   A host of Web sites offer resources, job listings (for
subscribers), and more information to help you decide if
telecommuting is for you:
</P>
<P>
   --www.pscw.uva.nl/sociosite/TOPICS/Telework.html(NU)USA
</P>
<P>
   From the University of Amsterdam, it has an extensive collection
of articles.
</P>
<P>
   --www.gilgordon.com/resources/reports.htm
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, a consultant, specializes in telecommuting issues. The
site also contains how-to resources and lists of new products.
</P>
<P>
   --www.businessweek.com
</P>
<P>
   Use its search engine and enter the word ``telecommute.'' It
will return over four dozen articles published in the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
   --cta.ca
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Telework Association's site is extensive. There is
a US-based nonprofit organization called the International Telework
Association and Council, but the Canadian organization's site is
up-to-date and offers advice for telecommuters and those who manage
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
