<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-VALENTINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSES ARE RED, VIOLETS ARE BLUE, E-COM ROMANCE IS FOR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those for whom Valentine's Day has become a marker for
love's disappointments or has come to symbolize a partner's soaring
expectations, there are no solutions.
</P>
<P>
   But now, at least, there is the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While cyberspace may not provide the definitive remedy it
certainly expands the possibilities. The offerings _ from gift
ideas and weekend getaways to bad poetry _ have caused an explosion
of romance-oriented Web sites this year. Virtual Valentine's Day
1999 was a plain affair. But, following a $5 billion e-commerce
Christmas, Internet consultants predict that Big Red is set to
become the next highly commercial holiday on line.
</P>
<P>
   The Valentine's Day cyberspace scene is so new there are no data
on sales or number of sites geared to the holiday. Still ``there
have to be hundreds, if not thousands of sites, that are doing
something special for Valentine's Day,'' says Alan Alper of Gomez
Advisors Inc., an e-commerce research firm in Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   The Web, with its links and hyperlinks from one site to the
next, seems constructed for love. Retail sites decked in red offer
seemingly endless gift suggestions for Valentine's Day. And there's
more. Lovingyou.com promises no less than the secrets of ``getting,
falling and staying in love.'' Thelovechef.com offers romantic
recipes (chicken rice pilaf anyone?).
</P>
<P>
   But Virtual Valentine's Day, like true love, requires
imagination. Finding the sites is easy but it's only a start. When
choosing the perfect gift for the perfect guy or gal, it's all
about message. A problem with the Internet is the bewildering
number of ideas and information that proliferate like kudzu.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one cannot recklessly plunge into buying a
bouquet. According to GeraldStevens.com every flower has a specific
meaning. That perennial favorite, red roses, should not be sent
lightly _ they represent ``love and desire.'' Pink roses are a
perkier kind of love, with ``perfect happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   For the brooding type, it becomes much more complex. Did anyone
realize that by sending wormwood, the source of absinthe, one is
transmitting passion and torment? Or, that apricot blossoms express
timid love, and clematis _ those airy purple flowers growing on
chain-link fences in summer _ express artifice. For a spouse of 50
years, send cactus, which show bravery and endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Stevens is at the very least an alternative to the subway
flower stand or Web florists, 1800flowers.com and FTD.com. The
company owns florists in 31 cities, guaranteeing freshness and
minimizing the likelihood of sending that special someone an
arrangement with a very unspecial plastic-heart balloon on a
pitchfork.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury gifts are in every nook of cyberspace now. I was drawn to
satiny red advertisements plastered on the sides of buses all over
Boston for RedEnvelope.com, which offers a mind-numbing range of
Valentine's Day choices. There are red roses _ make a statement by
sending three dozen, for $138. Or miniature roses to convey
miniature feelings, for $28. To express perfect love, try 10 pink
and white French tulips. If hipness is a consideration, there are
chocolate body paints for $24 (very in) or a rainbow of Pashmina
shawls for $295 (very out).
</P>
<P>
   With the Napa Valley picnic basket you can fly her to the Bay
Area _ or whisk her off to Revere Beach _ for $28 up to $159.
</P>
<P>
   For the adventurous soul, there are Valentine's Day weekend
getaways in the Green Mountains of Vermont or the blue Caribbean on
lodging.com. For wine lovers, there is wine.com with a cellar full
of Valentine's Day gift ideas.
</P>
<P>
   For guys, RedEnvelope.com sells four types of cuff links
(starting at $75): golf balls, footballs, sand timers, and _ my
personal favorite _ squares! For those lucky enough to have a
sweetheart who is a sea captain, there is an explorer's pocket
scope or a leather journal. And for those prone to seasickness, a
miniature yacht for floating on the pond.
</P>
<P>
   Men are difficult to buy for. It goes without saying that what
many may be most eager to receive can be found in the kama sutra
pleasure box, which has oils, balms and ``honey dust'' (?)'' for
$65. Perhaps the kama sutra weekend kit, for $22, will do. How much
oil can one couple use?
</P>
<P>
   For braver hearts, there are diamonds, diamonds, diamonds. Do
women actually wear those diamond or ruby heart pendants that are
de riguer on Valentine's Day jewelry sites this year, such as
diamond.com _ an Internet road map to diamonds, carats, and
auctions _ and mainstream jeweler denmans.com. High-end sites for
high-priced jewelry include mondera.com or tiffany.com, which I
recommend tackling with a neat glass of scotch and plenty of time
to wait for slowly unfolding images of floating white ribbons and
golden jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   A husband or boyfriend might go for jewelry, if it were a
vintage Rolex or Cartier watch offered on miadora.com. A very cool
gift for a guy, vintage watches range cost $2,000 to $28,000.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we're getting ahead of things. For those who haven't
found their soulmate yet, dating sites are claiming more success as
more people explore cyberspace. Think about it: the possibilities
for finding a mate are as infinite as gigabytes.
</P>
<P>
   Amid much anxiety about creating a perfect Valentine's Day,
there is overwhelming support for the holiday, according to a
survey of 1,009 singles by People to People (people2people.com), an
on-line dating service based in Boston boasting 960,000 members.
Those singles who made up the minority voted to cancel Valentine's
Day because it's too hyped, too expensive, and creates too much
pressure to find a date. Relax. Find a date by Valentine's Day on
the Internet. Everybody's doing it, People to People's survey
revealed: Nearly two-thirds of singles surveyed believe people will
meet a mate in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The undiscriminating can meet like-minded folk and strike
conversations in chat rooms that are a dime a dozen. I was lured by
pulsating red hearts that decorate the amateurish Cupid Connection,
mscupid.com. You can browse the site and click on potential mates
in three categories: women, men, or Alaskan men. Alaskan Men??!
Hmmm . . . Alaska, a place of ``stark beauty and rugged
wilderness,'' has another natural resource: ``the most wonderful
and eligible men imaginable!'' Bill, who plays bluegrass and wears
a funny hat, looks pretty eligible. Troy is a ``non-drinker,
non-smoker, no drugs, non-judgmental, positive outlook, and can
just take life day by day.'' It doesn't get any better than that!
</P>
<P>
   There are more private places to meet than plastering your bio
on the Internet equivalent of a bathroom wall. Match.com, which is
owned by Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch Inc., and Matchmaker.com
and are said to be popular with professionals who don't have much
time for a partner-hunting. America Online Inc. also has a dating
site, Love(at)AOL.com.
</P>
<P>
   To check out what's available on most dating services, you are
required to sign up. But interlopers
</P>
<P>
   are urged to sign up with a seven-day, free trial offer. So, I
did. What's to lose? Match.com promised me no less than the perfect
mate, right down to the color of a desired partner's hair _ dark or
light brown or salt-and-pepper _ and their emotional availability
or lack thereof. You click on the single/never married category or
divorced category. For that special temporary someone, you can
click on married or separated. (Wives may find this handier and
cheaper than hiring a private detective to spy on a wayward
husband.)
</P>
<P>
   Next, you fill in a list of preferred activities, a veritable
``walk on the beach'' of life's dating possibilities. (Is there
someone out there who does not like to walk on the beach?) To
match.com's credit, suggested first dates include novelties such as
``horseback riding on a dusty trail.'' In a section called ``My
friends describe me as. . .,'' there is room for the ``mildly
neurotic,'' the ``brainy/intellectual'' or the ``theatrical/life of
the party'' type, with lampshade I presume.
</P>
<P>
   You fill in the blanks, write up a scintillating profile of
yourself, and sit back and wait for the e-mails to flow in from
prospective partners. Trish McDermott, vice president of romance,
said 300,000 people have met someone on Match.com, resulting in 800
confirmed marriages. She believes the marriage figure is actually
higher. ``When people are successful they leave us.''
</P>
<P>
   As more people shop on the Internet for mates and bouquets of
flowers, there is a growing need to discern who or what is
legitimate, consultants warn. For example, you type in
``chocolate'' and lists of sites pop up, including
GiveChocolate.com, fowlerschocolates.com, rothschild-chocolates.com
(for truffles), grannyschocolate.com (``darn proud'' of its
chocolate candy roses), and virtualchocolate.com. In picking any
chocolate site, one fears that is precisely what one will get _
virtual chocolate. Valentines.com promises greeting cards, chat,
poetry, flowers, music, and, of course, chocolates. But, as of Jan.
24, the site was under construction _ perhaps awaiting financial
backers.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways to protect against Internet fraud, such as buying
from retailers that exist in the real world. Gomez Advisors
recommends that in buying jewelry, for example, you should get a
certificate of authenticity. ``It's a mating game. There's a
certain comfort level,'' Alper says.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to take no chances and still enjoy Valentine's
Day.
</P>
<P>
   For the cheapskate at heart, there's lots of free Valentine's
Day stuff on the Web. Cupids Corner promises ``everything you
need,'' including a history of Valentine's Day. According to myth,
under Emperor Claudius II, Rome was having difficulty signing up
soldiers who did not want to leave their families to go out and be
slaughtered, so marriages were stopped. But the ``good Saint
Valentine'' began secretly marrying couples until his head was cut
off on February 14th. Apparently, love and war have been
entertwined since the Roman Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Free greeting cards are jamming up traffic on the Internet.
Breakupgirl.com, a cheery site geared to teenagers, offers to send
candy hearts containing messages such as ``Fries with that'' or
``Other fish in sea'' or ``It's over.'' To send cards, there are
zillions of sites, from search engine Yahoo! to
BlueMountainArts.com and americangreetings.com. Valentine's cards
can be custom-made for, say, German Shepherd lovers on
fortunecity.com. One begins to understand why the Internet is often
a money-losing proposition. I liked the advice of of Michael Webb,
editor of the Romantic Newsletter. He suggests sending an actual
paper card via Loveland, Colo. The Chamber of Commerce will stamp
the town's name and a short poem on it. Webb also suggests
including one of Shakespeare's sonnets, which can be found through
any search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, you can write a poem with help from
www.nando.net/toys/cyrano/v2.1/loveletter.html. By answering
questions about your love's favorite food or article of clothing,
the site will elicit a full poem with lines such as ``Unliked with
hamburger hope that thou wouldst free/Your flannel shirt from a
dark slavery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
