<HEADLINE>
TALKING RATES: PRICE COMPARISONS ON-LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's OK to admit it: You think you want a cellphone, but all
those the ``best deal'' ads, with their 400-minute plans and free
nights and weekends, give you a headache.
</P>
<P>
   A new Web site can help.
</P>
<P>
   Called www.GetConnected.com and run out of offices in Cambridge,
Mass., the site offers a regularly updated, easy-to-use way to
compare wireless calling plans.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most useful features lets you specify the amount you
want to spend per month for a wireless phone, then see how many
minutes different carriers will sell you _ and with which
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I told the site I wanted to get a wireless plan in
metropolitan Boston that would cost no more than $40 a month, with
no charge for calls on nights and weekends.
</P>
<P>
   In half a second, the site informed me the most minutes I could
get would be 400, under a $39.99 Omnipoint plan. But it would also
squeeze me for a shocking 49 cents a minute for long-distance
calls. Yikes.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there were two other options, a $35 Cellular One
package (with 300 minutes and 25-cent long-distance) and a $40 AT&AMP;T
Wireless plan (with 300 minutes and 15-cent long-distance).
</P>
<P>
   If you think you know how many minutes a month you will use your
wireless phone, you can also have the site produce comparisons for
60, 120, or 300 minutes, or for anything up to 1,500 minutes
(that's almost an hour a day) in increments of 300 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, you can use the site to sign up immediately for a
plan, by clicking on an ``order here'' button. This means the
company offering the plan, such as AT&AMP;T Wireless or Bell Atlantic
Mobile, has paid an advertising fee to GetConnected.com. Clicking
on listings for nonadvertisers only tells you how to call them.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, that connection may raise red flags about whether the
site is really impartial, or whether its owners are tempted to
steer you toward advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials insist there is nothing unethical going on,
however. They know that, in the long run, savvy Net customers will
shun the site if they think GetConnected has gotten too connected
to its advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to providing consumers with free access to
comprehensive, unbiased information,'' said company cofounder Tracy
Lawrence, who graduated from Harvard Business School last June and
set up the company with classmate Sasha Novakovich.
</P>
<P>
   One place to go for a second opinion is www.contentunwired.com,
a San Francisco-based site that ranks the best three deals in each
of several different calling-plan categories. This site, however,
is far more general, less frequently updated, and nowhere near as
geographically specific as GetConnected.com.
</P>
<P>
   The wireless calling plan search, by the way, is one of only
several telecommunications shopping comparisons offered by
GetConnected.Com.
</P>
<P>
   By entering your hometown, you can also get a list of local and
long-distance telephone companies' plans and information about
Internet access, cable television, and companies such as ServiSense
and Essential.com, which sell ``bundles'' with other services, such
as heat and electricity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
