u a BC-TECHNO-COMMUTE-BOS &LR;      02-03 1549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-COMMUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELECOMMUTING 2000: STILL NOT PARADISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M.E. MALONE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fire up the personal computer, with its high-speed data line and
VPN access software _ don't forget the coffee maker and the
toaster, too _ then go to work, without ever leaving home.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommuting may not always be as easy as all that. But the
number of people who try it and the number of companies
accommodating such arrangements, even if only part time, is rising.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the trend are increasingly more sophisticated tools and
no shortage of entrepreneurs, who are looking to capitalize on the
at-home labor force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is one of the big enablers now,'' said Mary Porter,
a senior analyst for IDC Inc., a market research firm. ``Remote
access to the office on a high-speed line is helping to drive
telecommuting and working at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinning down the number of people who work partially or
exclusively at home is difficult. Government estimates are
considered conservative; private enterprises that publish estimates
use differing definitions of home-based work. Nearly all agree,
however, that telecommuting has not lived up to forecasts that a
much larger segment of the American work force would occupy
``virtual offices'' in or near their homes by now.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the predictions about telecommuting are made by those
of us who are advocates,'' said Wendell Joice, a research
psychologist with the General Services Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at almost any of the things that were predicted
when we switched from being an industrial society to an
information-based one, you'll see similar results. We're doing it,
but not going gangbusters yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, according to a 1998 survey by IDC, more than 10 million
American households have a member who worked from home for an
employer for at least three days a month in 1998 during normal
business hours, up from 9.1 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When home-based businesses and freelance contractors are
counted, the number might be closer to the 23.8 million households
that IDC projected contained a home office in 1999 that was used
for at least some income-generating purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Porter, who works from her Long Island home for the Framingham
company, said there is also evidence that small-business employees
may be contributing to much of the current buzz about
telecommuting.
</P>
<P>
   A January 1999 survey of owners of small businesses found that
almost 28 percent of employers with fewer than 100 workers had at
least one employee who worked from home on a somewhat regular
basis. That was up from 24 percent the prior year.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Besemer, president and CEO of HireSystems of Waltham,
Mass., runs a company where the number of telecommuters outstrips
full-time office workers almost 3 to 1. HireSystems dissects
resumes for clients who come to them for Web-based help in
streamlining their hiring. In addition to 110 in-office workers,
about 300 people are employed from their homes on an hourly basis
with work weeks that range from 10 to 35 hours. The majority of the
workers are stay-at-home mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real advantage to us is that it gives us an accordion-like
capability to expand or contract, based on the workload,'' Besemer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Home-based work ``allows us to grow at the rapid rate we're
growing, and it's wonderful to work at a company where the core of
the business actually thrives on this.''
</P>
<P>
   About one supervisor is needed for every 80 to 100 home workers,
she said, compared with one for every 10 to 15 office employees.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are working on the company's server, ``we can
always observe their work, keep track of their hours, and check on
their quality,'' Besemer said.
</P>
<P>
   I Belong Networks, based in Waltham, provides a laptop and a
cubicle with a large monitor to most of its 80 employees, but when
and where they do their work each day varies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very autonomous environment where people are
responsible for their own work,'' said Kirsten Lewis, who handles
public relations for the two-year-old company, which develops
portals for affinity groups. ``Whether you want to telecommute or
use flex time, the company really makes it easy for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Cui was recently hired as an engineer. With two daughters,
ages 1 and 9, she is able to shorten her time in the office two
days each week and pick up where she left off at home after the
girls are in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Using virtual private network (VPN) access software on her home
computer, ``it's exactly the same as working at my office.'' She
described this flexibility as ``a major reason that I joined this
company.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Cui takes advantage of the flexibility offered to help
with her family obligations, some employees juggle work with study
and other demands.
</P>
<P>
   June Langhoff, senior editor of Telecommute Magazine in
Pacifica, Calif., predicted that the competitive labor market and
high residential and commercial real estate prices near cities on
the East and West coasts will continue to feed the number of
workers who need or want to telecommute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have almost full employment in certain sectors'' of the job
market, she noted. ``Companies will do almost anything to attract
talent _ employers have to be a lot more flexible.'' There is also
a cost savings for many companies. In the case of HireSystems, the
cost of office space and computer equipment is significantly less
than it would be with an in-office work force of more than 400
full- and part-time employees.
</P>
<P>
   A study done for the International Telework Association and
Council last year concluded that employers also save money because
of increased productivity, decreased absenteeism, and greater
worker retention. There is no shortage of companies that see a
marketplace full of workers and small-business owners who will use
the Web and other technologies to work more efficiently and
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Some measures used by companies to accommodate telecommuters
have proven unpopular with workers. For example, ``hoteling,''
whereby telecommuters who periodically need to use the home office
reserve a cubicle for the purpose in advance, left many feeling
like second-class employees.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the capability created by high-speed, ``always
on'' connections to the Net through cable providers and digital
subscriber lines, a host of products in the design and
implementation stage will enable work to be conducted by a
dispersed work force.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual private networks allow employees engaged in business
from home to access the corporate network securely. Businesses that
run large customer service call centers _ from large utility
companies to catalog merchandisers _ can now use the Internet to
allow agents to answer large volumes of customer service calls from
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Web-based application service providers make it possible for
smaller, home-based businesses to rent access to the latest
software tools, without making large investments in the products.
And for those who work more from their cars than from a home or
office, both General Motors and Ford expect to have limited
voice-recognition capability in several 2001 model year cars to
enable workers to access their e-mail through their cellular phone
connections.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies are retooling their products or creating new ones
to target those who work without the supports typically found in an
office setting.
</P>
<P>
   TimeBills.com of Boston recently released new Web-based products
to help small businesses and independent contractors keep tabs on
their time, expenses, and client invoices without buying a series
of software packages or doing it manually. The company's vice
president of marketing, Jeff Hunt, said that 11 million service
professionals work for companies with fewer than 20 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are opening up shops of their own, especially
Web-related businesses,'' he said. ``This a group that will adopt
this kind of service; they have no distrust of on-line services.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited ``huge growth potential'' of this market as his company
seeks to increase its accounts from 13,000 to 100,000 by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Centra Software, of Lexington, Mass., has about 180 corporate
customers, many of whom are large, global companies that use their
software to collaborate with colleagues worldwide, using Internet
voicing technology to share conversations, presentations, and
applications. The company has adapted its technology to a new
Web-based product designed to allow smaller companies and
individuals to meet with clients and others with nothing more than
a Web browser and standard multimedia setup on their personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows you to collaborate with a business partner or client
very easily,'' said Ellen Slaby, who directs public relations for
the five-year-old firm.
</P>
<P>
   To Porter, the potential is there for telecommuting to mount in
popularity, most especially among workers in technology fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once people are really experiencing the type of speed and
connectivity they have at the office, then they really can do their
job from anywhere,'' she said. ``There is still a great desire on
the part of many employees to work at home _ though it is not
universal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
