<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Catholics, Jews face changing times
 &HT;    (For release Feb. 6, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the resurgence in religious fundamentalists within the
United States, these are not the best of times for them. Hypocrisy
and falsity hover over them like a plague.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, a Kansas City Star investigation uncovered what
it claimed to be several hundred Roman Catholic priests suffering
with AIDS. The interviews located victims, but they danced around
the root cause of the lethal disease. Anyone who can think with his
or her own brain can draw a picture of what caused it, even though
the church is saying everything but what it needs to say: the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the harsh stance the Roman Catholic Church has taken
vis-a-vis homosexuality, it is a grand dilemma. Not only does the
church consider homosexuality to be an abomination but it demands
celibacy of its priests. Vows have been broken.
</P>
<P>
   The years of openly condemning gay cohabitation and gay
marriages weigh heavily on the Catholic church. How can it create
an understanding of its own priests' foibles but not be
understanding of its parishioners'?
</P>
<P>
   A similar situation is dogging elements of Judaism. At a meeting
scheduled for March, the Central Conference of American Rabbis will
vote on a resolution that would permit Reform rabbis to perform gay
marriages.
</P>
<P>
   This more liberal wing of the Jewish faith several years ago
voted in favor of civil marriages of gays, but, if passed, the new
resolution would take them up the steps of the altar to stand
before the Holy Scriptures and be married.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this most interesting to me is the dogmatic practice
of most of these same rabbis in refusing to perform a
mixed-religion wedding. I will keep an eye on my own rabbi to see
whether he agrees to enact gay marriages while still refusing to
perform mixed marriages.
</P>
<P>
   My two sons both married Christian girls and my rabbi declined
to participate in the ceremonies. It left me scouring the
countryside for a Reform rabbi _ any rabbi _ who would stand
alongside the Christian minister and co-conduct the ceremony. They
are there; some of us call them Renegade Rabbis because they have
no temple. They just travel around performing ceremonies that other
rabbis will not. But there are not many of them.
</P>
<P>
   I assume something similar will happen with gay marriages. The
resolution to permit them likely will pass, but that doesn't mean
most rabbis will perform the services. Like mixed marriages, even
liberal rabbis have a line drawn somewhere. Gay marriages likely
would be for the Renegade Rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   The reform movement of Judaism is caught between two significant
factions. It never has been accepted by the Orthodox rabbis,
particularly in Israel, where it has been proclaimed that Reform
Jews are not really Jews. (So what am I?)
</P>
<P>
   Now, if it assents to validate gay marriages, whatever softness
there was in the Orthodox vs. Reform schism will grow harsh again.
The Conservative wing would be expected to side with the Orthodox,
which accepts that the Holy Scriptures consider homosexuality to be
an abomination.
</P>
<P>
   We live in different than biblical times. What the early rabbis
interpreted, and what Peter preached, is being overtaken by
real-life, complex experiences. Even dogmatism has its limits.
</P>
<P>
   If a rabbi, priest or minister wants to marry a gay couple,
that's their business. Whether the governmental sector looks upon
it as a legal marriage is another matter. But while the rabbis will
argue about that next month, don't forget that heartbreaking
embargo on mixed-religion marriages.
</P>
<P>
   They're not evil, just young kids in love.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
