u a BC-TECHNO-WIRELESS-BOS &LR;      02-03 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-WIRELESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLPHONES, HEADSETS _ WHAT ELSE IS NEW IN WIRELESS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next time you see someone walking down the street, talking
animatedly to no one, check to see if she has a wire dangling out
of her ear before you decide she's nuts and avoid eye contact. It
could be she's caught on to what seems to be the hottest fad in
wireless telephone gadgets: the cellphone headset.
</P>
<P>
   Such devices _ already a full-scale trend in the trendiest parts
of Los Angeles and Miami _ allow you to talk on your wireless phone
without using your hands. They are becoming hot sellers among local
wireless providers. You keep the phone in your pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be the most common thing we're seeing with new
subscribers,'' said Karin Olson, spokeswoman for the New England
operations of Omnipoint Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last two months, probably 20 to 25 percent of new
subscribers'' asked for them,Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   David Thomson of Bell Atlantic Mobile agreed: ``The biggest
trend we're seeing is headsets, both to promote safety and to
improve the convenience and clarity of conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of its rivals, Bell Atlantic Mobile offers headsets
for every phone it sells, ranging in price from about $15 to $30. A
headset plugs into an outlet on the telephone, so the subscriber
has two hands free to drive or work on the computer.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, a few different models:
</P>
<P>
   --``Ear buds'' have a little plug that fits inside the ear and a
miniature microphone that dangles from a wire.
</P>
<P>
   --Headsets with ``boom'' microphones, like
</P>
<P>
   you would see an airline reservation agent wearing.
</P>
<P>
   --``Ear caps'' slip over the top of your ear, which some people
find less annoying than having a little plug in their ear canal.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Bell Atlantic plans to roll out improved headsets
with volume controls and ``noise cancellation'' technology to focus
the sound of your voice _ not the kids' screams from the back seat
_ into the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Within two years, once problems with recharging batteries are
worked out, Bell Atlantic hopes to roll out the ultimate: a
wireless wireless headset, with no cord connecting the headset to
the phone.
</P>
<P>
   At least one motivation for the products seems to be largely
unproven but hard-to-extinguish concerns that using cellphones can
cause brain cancer or other illnesses. Even though current digital
phones use far less power and emit much less electromagnetic
radiation than the first-generation wireless phones of the 1980s,
many people prefer to keep their phones what feels like a safe
distance from their brains.
</P>
<P>
   A company called EarHugger in Lindon, Utah, on the Web at
Earhugger.com, sells a $15 improved wireless phone headset that has
no microphone. It picks up the sound of your voice through
vibrations transmitted through your jaw and works on Ericsson,
Nokia, and other units.
</P>
<P>
   Other popular new wireless gizmos include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A $90 desktop device that turns your wireless phone into a
speakerphone. Bell Atlantic plans to begin selling it locally later
this month, initially for the Motorola StarTac line of phones.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel Communications, whose phones with built-in two-way radio
capabilities make them popular with tradespeople, delivery fleets,
and public safety officials _ but a little pricey for average
consumers _ sells a range of Motorola phones that have a speaker
phone built in.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you still don't believe that wireless phones are not going
to turn your brain to microwaved mush, Consider spending $59 for a
Microshield sheath made of PVC plastic, wire mesh, and leather.
It's available at wavelengthonline.com. and includes a part that
covers the antenna, the source of most radiation emitted by the
phone while allowing you to see the screen clearly.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Howe covers New England telecommunications for the Globe's
business section.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
