his opinion about the people around him, seemed to trust Putin
absolutely, saying he was the man one could depend on in a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1993, during a rebellion by the deputies after
President Yeltsin had dissolved the parliament, a contingent of
combat tanks stormed the building. In that atmosphere of chaos,
Putin prudently met the mayor at the airport with a reinforced
security detail.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the 1996 presidential election, Putin led, on Sobchak's
orders, the St. Petersburg NDR (``Our Home Is Russia'') office.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1996 Putin ran Sobchak's election campaign and
also sued Alexander Belyayev, who was then the chairman of the
Legislative Assembly. At the height of a gubernatorial election
campaign, he alleged that Sobchak and Putin owned real estate
abroad and kept large amounts of money in foreign banks. Belyayev
had to apologize and soon disappeared from the St. Petersburg
political scene.
</P>
<P>
   After Sobchak's defeat in the gubernatorial election, Putin
flatly refused to work with the new team, saying that ``it would
look like an act of treachery.'' Sobchak's recent triumphant return
from self-imposed exile in Paris was largely attributed to Putin's
increased clout.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, only a short while ago it was rumored in St.
Petersburg that Putin might become the next governor. Yet,
responding to my question about the likelihood, Sobchak said that
Putin's potential was much bigger than that.
</P>
<P>
   One of Putin's former colleagues at Smolny recalls that he
always acted in an admirably manly style: ``If he was friends with
someone, that was great luck, but those he was down on were in real
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, when moving into a new office, Putin never initiated
any redecoration jobs, which never failed to stun some of the
bureaucrats. Thus in St. Petersburg, when he first entered Putin's
office, Sergei Tkachev, the office's former occupant just appointed
chairman of the Smolny External Relations Committee, could not hold
back his astonishment: ``Why didn't he have the furniture changed
at least?''
</P>
<P>
   Putin liked meeting with his friends at a suburban dacha which,
incidentally, burned down as soon as he moved to Moscow and has not
been rebuilt. His wife with two daughters immediately followed her
husband to Moscow. Putin's parents are dead.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in St. Petersburg, Putin has just a handful of friends, and
also his wife's relatives. And of course, the Neva River, the
Mariinsky Opera House and Vasilyevsky Island too.
</P>
<P>
   If Putin is a hero to anyone it is to the military. By his
edict, the defense budget will now have more money for guns and
less for nuclear bombs. At a government cabinet session on Jan. 27,
Putin said defense spending this year will be 50 percent higher
than last year. A bigger defense budget, he stressed, was a
``conscious choice,'' not related to the recent events in the North
Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem here runs deeper and it has to do with the fact
that the military has been underfunded for many years in a row,
which has led to negative consequences for the country's defense
capability,'' Putin summed up. He is the first Russian leader in
recent years to state bluntly that Russia intends to put more money
into weapons production and its armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by Putin's habit to carefully select the venue and
timing for such statements, his address at the cabinet session was
a well-calculated move that clearly had a specific target audience
_ above all, the Russian armed forces, who remain desperate for
support, and the outside world, which is concerned more about the
security of Russian nuclear stockpiles than about tanks.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in many years, the defense production and
arms-procurement program has been approved in January. Previously,
neither the Defense Ministry, which places production orders, nor
the defense production enterprises knew what to produce, or in what
volumes, until summer.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, 80 percent of all funds was spent on the
Strategic Nuclear Forces, with conventional weapons programs _
given the chronic underfunding of the defense sector _ getting just
a pittance. This year, according to Ilya Klebanov, vice premier in
charge of the military-industrial complex, 30 percent of the
defense budget will be spent on the nuclear forces while the
remaining 70 percent, on conventional weapons systems. Considerable
sums will be spent on R&AMP;D projects.
</P>
<P>
   Although Putin denies the new defense budget is linked to the
war in Chechnya, there is a link. The war has apparently affected
the military's kitty. After the outbreak of the second military
campaign in Chechnya, the state disbursed, as a matter of urgency,
an extra 4 billion rubles for arms procurement programs and
immediately raised the question of increasing the share of defense
spending in the 2000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   True, the government has yet to find the money _ not just on
paper. Before the operation in Chechnya began, the defense sector
received only 46 percent of the earmarked funding, whereas by the
end of last year this figure had grown to 86 percent, which is an
all-time record in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Putin remains a unique candidate on the scene. For the
first time since the 1917 Revolution, the next head of state in
Russia could be a person born in a capital city _ in Putin's case,
in Leningrad on Oct. 7, 1952. And not in snobbish Moscow either,
but in Europeanized St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Viktoria Voloshina and Olga Antonova Vremya are Moscow News
correspondents based in St. Petersburg.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
