<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5247 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-FORGET-PUTIN-RUSSIA-N     02-03 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORGET-PUTIN-RUSSIA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET PUTIN. ELECT PRIMAKOV 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Mikhail Gorbachev's
monthly column. To publish it as a ``separate buy'' article, please
contact your New York Times Syndicate sales representative: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax,
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 c.2000 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   I recently gave a live interview to Radio Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Callers one after another asked the same questions: What's
happening? What kind of person is Vladimir Putin? Has Russia turned
to some kind of ``hereditary autocracy,'' or is there still a
chance to restart the democratic process? How come everything has
been decided for us? Will Putin face any serious challengers in the
March 26 elections?
</P>
<P>
   It persuaded me that the people need a democratic option; they
are in a quandary. They are being asked to support Putin even
though he is a blank slate in terms of his social and economic
views.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's departure _ that is, his abrupt resignation on New
Year's Eve _ was not quite voluntary. One could say it was a
necessary step in the endeavor to ``hand over power to a reliable
man.''
</P>
<P>
   It was up to Yeltsin, of course, to take the final decision. But
his Kremlin entourage _ the bunch of relatives, political
associates, oligarchs and other hangers-on _ was pressuring him to
step down before the end of the year. They wanted to ride the wave
of Putin's popularity in hopes of perpetuating their own
opportunities for enrichment and power. Thus, the existence of
Acting President Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I support Yevgeny Primakov, the former prime
minister, for president. I believe that now and for the next four
years he would be the best choice for Russia _ not Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov has tremendous experience and proven ability. After
replacing Sergei Kiriyenko in September '98, with the economy in
drastic disarray, he governed firmly and democratically. Even then,
Primakov was able to unite and lead the people for the sake of the
national interest.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, I believe that a party of Social Democrats would
coalesce around Primakov. It would have grassroots appeal, growing
over time mostly from Russia's regions, which still keep the
country going. This party could become a serious political
contender by the time Russia holds its next parliamentary and
presidential elections four years from now.
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath of Yeltsin's policies is truly disastrous. They
have condemned 80 percent of the Russian people to life at the edge
of poverty. Russia has been humiliated and corrupted while its
courts are powerless. The industrial base that took decades to
build, as well as our education and health-care systems, are
decimated.
</P>
<P>
   It was conspicuous that Putin's first step was to pardon
Yeltsin. He issued a decree on ``guarantees'' to the former
president that is essentially unconstitutional. It grants Yeltsin
immunity from criminal or administrative responsibility and even
from being interrogated in the course of any investigation.
</P>
<P>
   One might think that we were returning to the times of
Soviet-style uncontested elections. During Yeltsin's
administration, and now Putin's too, decisions are being made by a
small group of power-hungry individuals for whom ``anything goes.''
Putin's promoters are looking for a ``blitzkrieg'' presidential
election campaign, with no time for anyone to seriously explain or
discuss the issues crucial to the country's future.
</P>
<P>
   A long, rambling article Putin published weeks ago, ``Russia on
the Threshold of a New Millennium,'' does little to explain his
views. It reads more like an eclectic hodgepodge of slogans and
bromides than a concrete program of action. Actually, Grigory
Yavlinsky, one of the West's favorite liberal reformers, was right
to call today's Kremlin with its new leader a ``black box.''
</P>
<P>
   To be blunt: Will Putin be able to sever the umbilical cord that
ties him to people like the media magnate Boris Berezovsky and
others whose power amounts to a virtual stranglehold over the
Russian political process?
</P>
<P>
   According to the bosses of the Unity Party, which was hastily
knocked together to drum up support for Putin, their candidate is a
shoo-in. No one, including Putin, however, should expect automatic
support or routine praise.
</P>
<P>
   The people already sense they are being deprived of any
influence on the course of events, of a chance to decide the
country's future. But Russia cannot succeed unless we give politics
back to the people.
</P>
<P>
   Surely it must be obvious to all that a lack of competition in
the political arena makes no sense in modern society; moreover, it
is a dangerous illusion. It is folly for Putin's allies to be
trumpeting up their mood of triumph, creating a sense of
all-but-universal approval.
</P>
<P>
   We are still far from a genuinely democratic system, but I agree
with those _ including Putin! _ who say that Russia will not return
to totalitarianism. Nor will there be a return to confrontation
with the West, despite the fact that the leading Western nations
have not yet matched their positive rhetoric with a proper respect
for Russia's interests.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever is elected in March, Russia's new president will offer
no ``free gifts'' to anyone. I am sure that Russia will be ready
for, and serious about, cooperating in good faith with all nations.
</P>
<P>
   Our partners need to understand that the time of Russia's
foreign-policy impotence is becoming a thing of the past. Frankly,
we have so far seen more understanding of this from the East than
from the West. Russia, like any country, has its national interests
with which others have to reckon.
</P>
<P>
   The most intelligent and responsible candidate _ and to my mind,
that is Primakov _ will heed what those interests are and what the
people of Russia expect of him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Translated from the Russian by Pavel Palazchenko &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union, who
resigned in December 1991 when Boris Yeltsin came to power, lives
with his daughter and granddaughter in Moscow and heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a social-policy and global environmental
think tank. Gorbachev is the author, most recently, of the
best-selling ``On My Country and the World.'' He won the Nobel
Peace Prize in 1990.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
