despite the galaxy of advisers he has consulted, he chooses to
overlook the Democrat who knows best how to run both as a
challenger and as an incumbent.
 &HT;    For his part, Clinton misses Gore's advice, presidential aides
say. Clinton trusted Gore to tell the truth and Gore was able to
use sarcasm to puncture Clinton's self-pitying or bombastic moods.
 &HT;    But Gore's advisers believe that the vice president had to
separate himself from Clinton because he is, in the campaign's
formulation, ``famous but unknown.''
 &HT;    The campaign found, for example, that most voters did not know
that Gore had ever been anything but a politician. They had to
