<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5257 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-TV-AMERICAN-ABROAD-NY     02-03 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AMERICAN-ABROAD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WHOLE WORLD ISN'T WATCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By A.O. SCOTT  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Once, homesick in Paris, a city that takes movies as seriously
as it takes itself, I saw ``Annie Hall'' at a packed theater.
 &HT;    Filing out afterward, I endured the contemptuous stares of the
rest of the audience because I had dared to laugh out loud at a
movie they found brilliant and important but not especially funny.
 &HT;    A few years later, at a well-appointed multiscreen theater in
Sarajevo, I sat with a raucous crowd watching Walter Hill's
``Streets of Fire,'' an unsung masterpiece about rival rock 'n'
roll motorcycle gangs who wield shotguns and firebombs in the
burned-out neighborhoods of a nameless American city.
 &HT;    My companions understood the movie, a demented, allegorical
updating of a classic B western _ with songs by the Blasters and Ry
Cooder _ to be a more or less naturalistic rendering of life in the
urban USA. (In retrospect, it looks more like a surreal premonition
of what their own lives were to become.)
 &HT;    Similarly, a few days later, when we went to see ``Witness,''
several of them assumed that Pennsylvania Amish country was a
magical land populated by mythical creatures, like the Munchkins of
Oz.
 &HT;    My point is not to poke fun at the Sarajevans' ignorance of the
realities of American social life. It can hardly, after all, have
matched my own ignorance about life in Yugoslavia, which at the
time (the mid-1980s) struck me as placid and hospitable and a cheap
place to travel.
 &HT;    My point is that while the products of American media _ a phrase
that may be even more tautological than, as Francois Truffaut
noted, ``American cinema'' _ may be washing up in every hamlet,
village and nomad's tent in the world, the way people choose to
understand them varies from place to place.
 &HT;    This is not just a matter of varying local interpretations of
Hollywood movies. In much of Africa, where American companies hold
monopolies over the distribution and exhibition of movies, it is
virtually impossible for audiences to see an African-made film on
the big screen.
 &HT;    But we should not therefore assume that African audiences have
been neatly assimilated into what some critics like to call the
global media monoculture.
 &HT;    In northern Nigeria, according to Faye Ginsburg, a professor of
anthropology at New York University, there is fervent demand for
Bollywood musicals, which are distributed by Lebanese businessmen.
Inspired by the romantic plots of those films, fans make and
circulate pamphlets.
 &HT;    In Ghana, some of the most popular entertainment consists of
low-budget horror movies, often incorporating traditional folkloric
and religious themes, that are shot on video and shown in makeshift
theaters.
 &HT;    And on television, resistance to American media hegemony has
even more faces, including Aboriginal producers on Australia's
indigenous television, the Inuit-produced programs that link
together the far-flung villages of Nunavut and the grown man in the
bumblebee suit whose predicaments are a staple of Mexican
broadcasting.
 &HT;    This bee's cartoon double occasionally turns up on that most
American of television shows, ``The Simpsons.'' Bart and Lisa, who
greet the bloody exploits of Itchy and Scratchy with howls of
laughter, are nonplussed by this striped figure, with his piteous
cries of ``No me gusta'' and ``Ay, que lastima!''
 &HT;    Bart Simpson himself is, of course, one of the half-dozen most
recognizable people in the world _ a living (or at least highly
animated) symbol of American pop-cultural triumphalism, and it is
his seigniorial prerogative simply to change the channel when
confronted with something he just doesn't get.
 &HT;    But at least one of the flesh-and-blood agents of the new media
empire may have, if you will, something of a bee in his bonnet
regarding the difficulties of cross-cultural programming.
 &HT;    In a CNN panel discussion that was shown back in the twilight of
a simpler, more innocent media age _ that is, a few weeks ago _
Gerald Levin, still merely CEO of Time Warner, observed that
``American television does not sell well outside the United States
anymore.''
 &HT;    It is a particularly remarkable development, since, like
American movies, American television programs boast much higher
production values than their foreign counterparts. The hegemony of
the Hollywood blockbuster has crippled the once-vibrant film
industries of a number of countries, where the capital to float
$200 million ocean liners is simply not available.
 &HT;    But a foam-rubber bee suit, the disco lights and spangled
costumes of an Italian variety show or the sparse furnishings of an
Egyptian soap-opera set cost less than a state-of-the-art fake
emergency room _ or even an episode's worth of Calista Flockhart's
tiny business suits. And that fact doesn't seem to diminish the
appeal of those shows to their intended audiences.
 &HT;    Television, much more than cinema, is a quintessentially
American medium: We invented it and we still do it best. And the
American style of distribution _ commercial, 24-hour, multichannel
_ is rapidly displacing the state-controlled public service model
that has been the norm in most countries.
 &HT;    So it may seem paradoxical that television, perhaps the first
truly global medium, turns out to be the one most responsive to the
whims of local viewers.
 &HT;    But the hegemony of American-style broadcasting has undermined
the dominance of American programming. The means of production are
cheaper and more widely accessible than ever, and more channels
mean a wider array of choices for viewers and programmers alike.
 &HT;    That's not to suggest that the opening of a global free market
in entertainment has created a utopia of unfettered choice and
individual expression. As any cable subscriber knows, more
programming does not necessarily mean better programming. Much of
what's on television, whatever its scale or country of origin, is
garbage.
 &HT;    I don't mean this judgmentally, but descriptively. And people
may just prefer the familiar stink of home-grown garbage.
 &HT;    Of course, even as disparate cultures can sample, and
appreciate, one another's stupidity, each one remains stupid in its
own way, and nobody's stupidity is inherently superior to anybody
else's. The fly in the ointment of the megamedia machine is that
ineffable quantity called taste _ bad taste, to be precise _ for
which there is, axiomatically, no accounting, not even by the CEOs
of a giant corporation.
 &HT;    In the global village, we are all village idiots, watching our
reflections in a box.
 &HT;     c.2000 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (A.O. Scott is a film reviewer for The New York Times.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; SIDEBAR: TOP-RATED EXPORTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most popular American-produced TV shows of 1998, in a
sampling of countries:
</P>
<P>
   _ TURKEY: ``Wheel of Fortune''
</P>
<P>
   _ HUNGARY: ``E.R.''
</P>
<P>
   _ POLAND: ``Dr. Quinn: Medicine Woman''
</P>
<P>
   _ ROMANIA: ``Dark Skies''
</P>
<P>
   _ AUSTRALIA: ``Friends''
</P>
<P>
   _ SOUTH AFRICA: ``Generations''
</P>
<P>
   (Source: Latest figures available, compiled by Eurodata TV.)
</P>
