<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5266 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-PELOSI-PRESS-HNS &LR;      02-03 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PELOSI-PRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PELOSI AMONG THE JOKESTERS AT CONGRESSIONAL DINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Nancy Pelosi was among the featured
entertainers at the annual winter bash for Congress and the press.
Her assigned humor topic was to explain why she wasn't running for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, addressing the audience of 1,000 diners Wednesday night,
responded to the challenge question: ``I haven't come to that
conclusion yet.''
</P>
<P>
   She told the story of the late Hugo Black, an Alabama politician
and future U.S. Supreme Court justice who told his wife that some
people were urging him to run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are those people?'' Mrs. Black asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me,'' Black replied, according to Pelosi, who joked: ``Some of
those same people are urging me to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi wryly related that one of her daughters had ``crossed
over.''
</P>
<P>
   No, that doesn't mean she's become a Republican, Pelosi
continued. ``She has joined the media,'' the congresswoman
continued, referring to her youngest daughter, Alexandra, who is
now working in television news.
</P>
<P>
   Going back to her assigned theme of why she isn't running for
president, Pelosi explained that the president was only the second
most respected person in town. ``After all, there's Michael
Jordan,'' former NBA superstar who's recently taken a management
job with the Washington Wizards, the local NBA franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi drew a distinction between being president and running
for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in public office wants to be president,'' she said.
But few are willing to put up with the rigors of running for the
job, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi also took a shot at President Clinton's long-winded State
of the Union speech. She told a tale about how Hillary Clinton was
showing her husband their new neighborhood in Chappaqua, N.Y., when
suddenly a Secret Service agent ran up to the car and rapped on the
window, saying her husband had fallen out of the car two blocks
back.
</P>
<P>
   Thank God, the first lady said, according to Pelosi, I thought
I'd lost my hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The master of ceremonies introduced Pelosi as a candidate for
majority whip in the House, the No. 3 leadership post. Her
candidacy assumes that the Democrats will regain control of the
House in the November election, triggering a shuffle of the
Democratic leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Four other members of Congress who tried their hand at stand-up
comedy were Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., Rep. Marcy Kaptur,
D-Ohio, Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, and Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va.
</P>
<P>
   The 56th annual Congressional Dinner was sponsored by the
Washington Press Club Foundation, the heir to the former Women's
National Press Club, founded in 1919 when women were barred from
membership at the National Press Club. In 1970 the women's club
changed its name to the Washington Press Club and invited men to
become members. That led the NPC in 1971 to allow women in. Several
years later the WPC disbanded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
