<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5296 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-03 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ILLUSIONS OF SAFETY BEHIND THE WHEEL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What is it about airplanes? They scare the hell
out of us, and even though we're often told they're safer than
cars, we never believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Flying is magic, something humans did in dreams long before the
Wright brothers. When the magic fails, very bad things happen, very
fast, to very many people.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody thinks driving is magic. Most people think they're in
control. After all, they're solidly anchored to the ground by about
12 square inches of rubber moving at 70 mph. They think bad things
can't happen to them.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else, I had heard statistics about how driving is
more dangerous than flying, but never quite believed them.
</P>
<P>
   We look at wrecked cars on the evening news, and it doesn't have
anywhere near the fascination of watching Coast Guard boats
circling for hours through a slick of jet fuel and bits of an
airliner.
</P>
<P>
   According to University of Southern California sociology
professor Barry Glassner, the author of ``The Culture of Fear: Why
Americans Are Afraid of the Wrong Things,'' there have been about
13,000 airline fatalities since 1914, the dawn of the airliner.
That's about a third the number of people killed on American roads
in one year.
</P>
<P>
   There is no comfort in those statistics for those who knew
someone on Alaska Airlines Flight 261 heading home from vacation.
</P>
<P>
   According to National Transportation Safety Board statistics,
during the last 15 years the worst year for airline safety was
1993, when there was 0.918 major crashes per million aircraft hours
flown. The best year was 1998, when there were zero major crashes
per million hours flown.
</P>
<P>
   There is no comfort in those statistics for the friends and
family of 88 people who lost their lives in an instant in the
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   We in the news media offer no comfort for friends and family of
crash victims either.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, television reporters and cameramen pursued
relatives of victims of the crash of Flight 261 as they left the
airport in grief. The reporters pursued the bereaved all the way to
the parking garage elevators, despite pleas for them to show some
compassion.
</P>
<P>
   This is disgraceful. The reporters' object, of course, was to
get film and go on the air to pull on heartstrings with all the
fake compassion they could muster.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday evening, I was on the road, flipping between radio
reports of the crash of Flight 261 and the traffic reports.
Northbound U.S. 101 was at a dead stop for two hours because of a
five-car crash near the Tiburon exit.
</P>
<P>
   Four people were injured in the crash, one of them critically.
After a struggle, highway patrol officers arrested a nude man
smoking a cigar on suspicion of driving under the influence of the
hallucinogen PCP.
</P>
<P>
   Naked motorists on PCP. That's just one example of what we face
every day on the rain-slicked roads. Even though it was a
particularly bizarre traffic accident, we accept it as part of the
price we pay for the freedom to get in the car and drive.
</P>
<P>
   We expect _ nay, demand _ perfection from airliners, though.
That has had the effect of making airline travel safer, which in
turn has made airline crashes more shocking.
</P>
<P>
   There's no use comparing car crashes with airliner crashes.
Fast-moving metal on the highway doesn't instill an abstract fear
in Americans the way feeling a plane leap off a runway does. Car
crashes are concrete and understandable.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago an 18-wheeler changed lanes on Interstate 80
right into my wife's Honda CRX. He wasn't aware her car was there
until the hub of his right front wheel ground a hole in her
driver's side door, slowing down his truck.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt. It was an everyday accident, a lost and tired
driver unable to see a tiny car. Drivers kept roaring by as fast
and dangerously as usual.
</P>
<P>
   We still haven't traded in that little car for a bigger, safer
one. Yet when I drove that same stretch of Interstate 80 to get to
Oakland Airport recently, I didn't think of getting crushed by an
18-wheeler. I worried about flying.
</P>
<P>
   We all worry about flying, and no amount of statistics can
overcome the sight of Coast Guard boats bobbing amid debris and jet
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor families, having to watch that,'' said a woman as I
was coming to work the day after.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing to say but best wishes to the family and friends
of those lost with Alaska Airlines Flight 261. It comforts us to do
so, even if it is not much comfort to them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
