<SLUG> BC-BORDER-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SECURITY FORCES ON ALERT FOR WINTER GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRENDAN LYONS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ Security along the Canadian border is being
tightened as police and counterterrorism SWAT teams move into Lake
Placid for the inaugural Winter Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said the heightened law enforcement presence is
precautionary because thousands of spectators and more than 500
athletes from around the world will arrive in the Olympic village
starting next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no perceptible (terrorist) threat to the Goodwill
Games yet, which isn't to say that one may not arise,'' said Maj.
William Warburton of the New York State Police. ``But we've planned
for all kinds of security contingencies. ... We're staying alert.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Police are bringing troopers from other areas of the
New York to beef up patrols during the four-day event, which begins
Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, FBI and State Police SWAT teams will be stationed
at a command post near the village outskirts. A counterterrorism
FBI unit in Washington, D.C., has been tracking any potential
threats to the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That threat assessment will continue right through the
games,'' Warburton said.
</P>
<P>
   Louie F. Allen, special agent in charge of the FBI's Albany
field office, said the FBI has worked at previous Goodwill Games.
This is the first Winter Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning we were going to be there because we
classify that as an FBI special event because a number of people
are going to be there from outside the country,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   At Canadian-border entry points, U.S. Customs agents already are
on alert. Much of the agents' work will be to get athletes across
the border swiftly, said Tim Meshinelli, assistant port director
for U.S. Customs in Champlain.
</P>
<P>
   As they did for the 1980 Olympic Winter Games here, numerous
athletes and spectators are expected to drive into Lake Placid from
Canada. A biathlete bringing a high-powered rifle across the border
for a competition might normally result in a bureaucratic delay.
But Meshinelli said agents have reviewed applicable tariff laws so
athletes with proper credentials will be processed quickly at the
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the security end of it, our people have been
briefed,'' Meshinelli said. ``They are aware and certainly are in
that (high-security) mode based on what they've been through.''
</P>
<P>
   Border security was heightened two months ago amid concerns
about terrorism tied to New Year's celebrations. The alert followed
the Dec. 19 arrest of a Canadian woman and an Algerian man at a
Vermont border crossing. The two were driving a car that
bomb-sniffing dogs indicated may have once carried explosives, and
the woman, Lucia Garofalo, has been linked to what federal
prosecutors have described as a terrorist group operating in Europe
and Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   For the games, several U.S. Border Patrol agents will be in Lake
Placid. Agents also will be deployed at isolated locations along
the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be logical to assume they increase security at the
points of entry,'' said Border Patrol Assistant Chief Mark Henry.
``It would also be logical to assume (any terrorists) are not going
to come through points of entry, but through the woods. ... We
believe we're prepared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
