<HEADER>
A5310 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SKI-FEAR-BOS &LR;      02-03 1696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-FEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARFUL WOMEN APT TO AVOID THE SLOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lisa Mercer loves to ski, except for those moments when fear
sneaks up and leaves her paralyzed, riveted to the slope. She
seldom falls despite learning just a year ago, but neither is she
inclined to take risks. She enjoys gentle cruising and is eager to
perfect her technique, but is skeptical at best about ever wanting
to ski the difficult, steep black-diamond trails.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of trapped at this (novice) level,'' said Mercer, a
46-year-old fitness instructor. ``I'll do a blue (intermediate run)
with the guidance of an instructor, but go back later with my
husband and say, `I can't do this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ask what she's afraid of and she replies: ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa has company.
</P>
<P>
   For the 40 percent of all skiers who are women, fear may be the
No. 1 issue. Whether more cautious by nature, unconditioned to
taking risks or simply stuck on the wrong equipment, say
specialists, women are much more likely than men to psyche
themselves out of becoming better skiers and, consequently, of
getting as much pleasure from the sport.
</P>
<P>
   But the fear can be conquered, sometimes quickly, by
understanding some of the many contradictions inherent to the sport
that seem to bedevil women more than men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men don't understand our fear. They're always like, what are
you afraid of,'' said Kim Reichhelm, a former member of the US Ski
Team and two-time World Extreme Skiing champion who runs women's
programs in Crested Butte, Colo. While women are thinking, ``I have
my job, I have my kids, I have all these other responsibilities and
pressures; I can't afford to get hurt,'' she said, men take the
attitude, ``If I break my leg, I break my leg. I'll worry about
that later.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony, she said, is that because so many women rarely push
themselves beyond their comfort zones, they hold themselves back
from making the breakthroughs that will lead to becoming better
skiers, which leads to more confidence, which leads to less fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you never fall, it's going to be very hard to improve
because you're always skiing within your limits,'' Reichhelm
warned.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, said instructor Ashley Fischer, is the specter of
regression. ``If they don't expand the comfort zone, it will
shrink,'' said Fischer, who runs the women's program at Sugarbush,
``so they find themselves taking the same lift and skiing the same
trails over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, the fear was not there originally, but stems from a bad
experience. ``Women get talked into something they can't handle and
then have a horrifying experience,'' said Reichhelm. Explained Pam
McAfee, co-director of the Women's Turn program at Sunday River,
it's one thing to push the envelope; another to rip it to shreds.
``Yes, we want to press the perimeter and once in a while we want
to step a little out of it,'' she said, ``but we don't want to step
way out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Men, meanwhile, may be just as afraid but react in a way that
doesn't interfere with their enjoyment of the sport. ``Instead of
either talking about it or pausing or not going down that run, men
will tend to go ahead and ski, so it doesn't look as though they're
afraid,'' said Dr. Patty Simmons, a psychiatrist who has worked
with Fischer on women's programs. ``From childhood, men are
encouraged to face their fears head on and just launch into it, and
I think that's what you see on the slopes.''
</P>
<P>
   Women, on the other hand, are more likely to stand at the top of
a challenging slope and strategize about how best to get down.
They're also more apt to concentrate on acquiring the proper skills
before venturing to the top of that slope in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are often more technically correct in skiing than men
because we have to be,'' said Claudia Carbone, author of
``WomenSki,'' first published in 1994. ``We can't just muscle our
way through a turn. If men screw up, they can just use their
muscles to save themselves, but we have to know how to do it
correctly. We know we can't fake it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, for some women, the root of the problem may lie not
in their heads at all but, rather, right at their feet. In skiing,
equipment that is fitted and tuned perfectly is critical: boots
that are too big or cut too high, or skis too long or stiff with
dull edges, will translate to a lack of control, which quickly
becomes fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a car with bald tires,'' said Carbone, who has been
skiing for more than 40 years and advocates custom-fitted
equipment, especially boots, even for beginners. ``A lot of women
will ski in their husband's hand-me-downs or their brother's boots.
What is that commercial for the hair? `I'm worth it?' They should
take that attitude. If I'm going to do it well and safely and have
confidence while I'm doing it, I'm going to need to go to the
basics, and the basics are equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many other ways to minimize fear:
</P>
<P>
   --Take lessons. Fear is not a character flaw: once you know how
to stop and turn quickly on a variety of conditions, you will have
less reason to be afraid. Ask to learn some ``survival skills''
such as the side-slip, which can get you down almost anything onto
which you might accidentally stray.
</P>
<P>
   --Accept the fact that you're going to have to relinquish
control to gain control. There's a phase of the turn ``where you
just have to let it go,'' said Fischer. ``It's OK, as long as you
know how to pull it out.'' That's where the lessons come in.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't expect too much of yourself. Acquiring skills is the
first step; practicing them is the next. ``You've got to get out
there and put in the miles,'' said Reichhelm. ``You need to do them
over and over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   --Don't blindly follow a companion, especially one with more
experience, around the mountain. Bring your own trail map and know
which lifts and runs are open so you can get yourself out of
situations you don't want to be in. ``It's a huge boost in
self-confidence not to be led around,'' said Reichhelm.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't be afraid to ask mountain employees for help. Say ``I'm
thinking of going from here to there but I don't want to get thrown
on a black diamond,'' suggested McAfee. ``They'll give you a minute
to help you out.''
</P>
<P>
   --Be aware of changing conditions. What on Saturday morning was
a sweetly-groomed blue might by Sunday afternoon have become an
icy, moguled black.
</P>
<P>
   --Pick the right time emotionally to try something new. Carbone
calls the combination ``fantastic'' and ``familiarity'': on a day
when conditions are good and you're feeling great, that's the time
to become familiar with a new run or circumstance (steeps, moguls,
ice, speed) that usually causes your stomach to churn and palms to
sweat.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't cede the buying and maintaining of your equipment to
someone else. ``It's kind of like we are with cars,'' said Carbone.
``We kind of defer to men to make the decisions. That's a huge
mistake. You're the one standing on those skis.''
</P>
<P>
   --Don't underestimate your ability. If you're a woman, you're
probably a better skier than you think you are; if you're a man,
the opposite is more likely.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't get down on yourself. A bad turn, bad run, bad day does
not make for a bad person. ``When I talk about fear, I tell women
fear is good,'' said Reichhelm. ``We need fear to keep us alive.
Don't get mad at yourself for being afraid: you need to figure out
what you're afraid of.''
</P>
<P>
   --Be honest with yourself about what you want out of skiing.
``Some women won't be happy until they're skiing black diamonds,''
said Simmons. ``Other women are paying lip service to it'' because
they're trying to live up to someone else's expectations. ``Rather
than give them formulas, I encourage them to do some
self-examination.''
</P>
<P>
   If that means you don't want to be like the guys who fall like
ragdolls down the slopes leaving a yard sale of equipment behind
them, only to jump up and pump their fists in glee (``Did you see
that, I ate it so bad''), is that really so bad?
</P>
<P>
   As McAfee put it: Rather than being more fearful than men,
``women might just be a little wiser.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you've taken lessons but felt intimidated or rushed by the
men in your class or clinic, you might want to try one of the many
women-only programs offered at resorts throughout New England.
Programs and dates are always subject to change, so call ahead. A
sampling:
</P>
<P>
   --Sugarloaf USA in Maine offers Women's Turn Programs for skiers
and snowboarders ranging from one to five days, including
on-mountain coaching, video analysis, guest speakers, social
programs and more. A Women's Week, for level 3 skiers and above, is
scheduled for Feb. 7-11, with a similar three-day clinic March
10-12. Call 207-237-2000 and ask for the Perfect Turn office.
</P>
<P>
   --Sunday River near Bethel, Maine, has events for women that
last from two hours to two days, including a weekend seminar (take
one or both days) on March 2 and 3. In addition, Wednesday
workshops are available through March 29 for skiers levels 4 to 8.
Call 207-824-3000, ext. 5184 or 5078.
</P>
<P>
   --Butternut in Great Barrington offers a variety of Women Only
programs on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Sundays, including lessons and
lunch. Call 413-528-2000, ext. 111.
</P>
<P>
   --Loon in Lincoln, N.H., is having a Women's Getaway from Feb.
7-9. for skiers who want to learn to parallel on intermediate
terrain to experts, plus snowboarders and adaptive skiers of all
abilities. Clinic includes lift ticket, registration breakfast,
on-snow coaching, wine-and-cheese party and farewell luncheon. Call
603-745-6281, ext. 5692.
</P>
<P>
   --Killington in Vermont has several possibilities, including a
Feb. 9-11 clinic featuring Donna Weinbrecht, Olympic gold medalist
in moguls. Call 800-621-MTNS.
</P>
<P>
   --Mad River Glen in Waitsfield, Vt., is hosting a one-day clinic
on March 4 and a two-day clinic Feb. 26-27 for alpine and telemark
skiers of all abilities, starting with a breakfast get-together
during which participants talk about goals and past skiing
experiences. Call 802-496-3551.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
