<HEADER>
A5313 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-WOODS-BOS &LR;      02-03 1801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS SETS HIS SIGHTS ON GOLF'S LEGENDARY PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Winding through the press room like a
confused motorist on 17 Mile Drive, the hushed whispers go in every
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing nine at Poppy Hills,'' but the report is met with
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, he's up hitting balls at the range.''
</P>
<P>
   More skepticism, for another report offers, ``He's over at
Cypress to get away from everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Confusion, for no one can be in three places at once. It just
isn't possible. Is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that you said wasn't quite possible he has pretty
much done,'' said Davis Love, discussing the topic _ Tiger Woods _
that dominates the PGA Tour these days.
</P>
<P>
   Like winning every week? Love was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember saying to my brother last year, `Do you realize if
(he) wins these last three tournaments (Disney, Tour Championship,
and American Express) how much money he is going to make?' My
brother said, `He can't possibly win the last three tournaments.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we were riding back (from Spain, where Woods won the
American Express) and I remember saying: `There goes $3 million
right there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Everything that you said wasn't quite possible he has
pretty much done.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Those three wins came on the heels of his win at the NEC
Invitational. So when Woods began the 2000 season with a stirring
playoff victory over Ernie Els at the Mercedes Championship, he
achieved something that had not been done in nearly half a century:
win five straight PGA Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   The names Woods chases with this streak (Byron Nelson, 11
straight wins in 1945; Ben Hogan, six straight in 1948) are
monuments in the sport, but Woods will have none of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more important to you guys, something to write
about,'' he said to a media horde that has arrived in full force
for this weekend's AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am, which begins
this morning. ``To be honest with you, I still don't really
consider it six, because it's all over two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just counting that I've won this year and trying to win
two in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Semantics, shemantics. Woods can deflect talk of the streak, but
not this: Going back to a European event in Germany last May, the
Deutsch Bank, Woods has teed it up in 13 tournaments sanctioned by
either the US or European PGA Tour and won nine of them. Toss in a
couple of wins in unofficial tournaments (the World Cup of Golf,
the PGA Grand Slam) and the reality comes into focus that, streak
or no streak, Woods has developed into a force of incredible
proportions in a sport that has always preached great depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has impacted all of us,'' said Love.
</P>
<P>
   On and off the course, it seems, for Woods has developed into
such a massive personality that he dwarfs other stars around him.
Here at the AT&AMP;T, for example, there has been very little commotion
as the cancellations have filtered in.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Murray, a cult figure at this tournament, chose instead to
play the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic two weeks ago. Jack Lemmon, one
of the few who bridge the era of the beloved Bing Crosby, is
recovering from surgery. Michael Douglas, Samuel L. Jackson,
William Devane, and James Woods aren't here, either.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a ripple.
</P>
<P>
   Then Michael Jordan phoned in his regrets. No problem.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Jordan withdrawal is being viewed as somewhat
symbolic, as if confirming that the world sports stage has been
passed on to Woods. Although no one dares suggest Jordan is no
longer a hugely marketable name, it is not a stretch to call Woods
a more powerful one. The transition is hard to dismiss: Jordan was,
Woods is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get 15 to 30 calls a day, on average,'' said Mark Steinberg,
Woods's agent at International Management Group. ``People asking
for Tiger. Can he come here? Can he do this?''
</P>
<P>
   Enough offers that Woods could be kept busy every waking moment,
but it is important to weigh endorsements that fit his image. An
image, Steinberg said, that is an easy sell because, ``What you see
is what you get. He's a tremendous gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Published money figures that no one is rushing to refute lend
support to the notion Woods is about to surpass Jordan as the
world's most marketable athlete. In 1999, just his third full
season as a professional golfer, Woods earned $50 million, of which
close to $40 million came from endorsements. That is well behind
the $69 million earned by Jordan, but with a new deal from General
Motors ($30 million for five years) added to his stable and Nike in
line to re-up (as much as $90 million for five years), Woods will
be closer to $69 million than $50 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the financial worth that he means to those riding
his wave of incredible success. ``He is worth 10,000 fans at every
tournament he plays. Bottom line,'' said one tournament director.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers look at his television value, because Woods in
contention means many more viewers. When Woods and Els went
head-to-head at the season-opening Mercedes Championship, it became
the most-watched golf telecast in cable history, garnering a 3.5
rating on ESPN. Not that it moved into Super Bowl territory, but it
serves as a subtle reminder that the blockbuster TV deal the PGA
Tour entered into was signed just weeks after Woods's historic romp
at the 1997 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   That TV money indirectly has gone to players, who, even if they
secretly are jealous of his success, cannot deny that Woods has
meant more money in their pockets. Purses are routinely $3 million.
So much more money has become available since Woods's arrival,
winning is no longer a necessity if you want to get rich. Being in
the top 25 will do just fine, thank you, a fact that extends to
even the game's superstars.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson, for example, went winless with just six top-10
finishes in 1999, but earned $1,722,681, more than he made in 1996
when he triumphed four times.
</P>
<P>
   Love also went winless in 1999, but that misery can be soothed
by the fact that he raked in $2,475,328 _ more than double what he
earned in 1992 when he won twice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But if winning is not essential to a healthy bank account, it is
for the competitive soul that beats in Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what competitor likes finishing second,'' said
Woods. ``I've never liked it. I don't understand why people are
satisfied with that.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Woods's competitors _ at least while he's been on this
frightening roll _ have had no choice. Such is the ferocity of his
spirit, the scope of his talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's aware of the streak, but that isn't what motivates him,''
said Butch Harmon, the swing coach who has instructed Woods since
being introduced to him seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There exists in Woods a burning desire to be the best who ever
played the game, said Harmon, which means one thing in pro golf:
surpass those feats put up by Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   Two US Amateur titles? Woods did Nicklaus one better, winning in
1994-96. Cross that off the list of challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen professional majors? OK, he's well short, having won
the 1997 Masters and last summer's PGA Championship. But keep in
mind he is just 24 years old, and history tells us he is on
schedule. In his first 71 professional tournaments, Woods won 16
times, including two majors; Nicklaus's numbers over that time
frame were 14 and three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was going to be great,'' said Harmon, ``but he has
far surpassed my expectations.'' It's mostly, said the teacher,
because Woods is ``such a great student. He learns quickly. He
listens.''
</P>
<P>
   Example: In the afterglow of that Masters win, Harmon said he
knew things had to change. The coach talked of a more compact
swing, better distance control, hitting more greens. Hogan's swing,
said Harmon: ``Study it.''
</P>
<P>
   So for two years Woods retooled a swing and never came close to
his Masters magic. He won the Western Open in July 1997, then
didn't win again until May of the next year, which happened to be
his only win in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The ``slump'' proved that he wasn't so dominating, said the
critics, though they failed to acknowledge that the ``slump''
consisted of two seconds, two thirds, and three other top-10
finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, said Woods. ``I know you guys looked at me like I was
crazy in '98, saying that I was better (then) than in '97, but it
was true. I was making progress. I was improving in a lot of
aspects of my game, and it finally came together last year.''
</P>
<P>
   At the expense of some pretty good players, a fact that should
not be discounted. In his current streak, though three of the
events have had limited fields, Woods has outplayed Mickelson, Els,
Love, Miguel Angel Jimenez, and Els again.
</P>
<P>
   Go back and look at two of his first three wins _ playoff
victories head-to-head with Love and Tom Lehman _ and you get a
measure of why his thirst for pressure is never questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my first four playoffs, and I was dreading them,'' said
Love, again searching to answer just how it is that Woods has
turned this PGA Tour into his own personal agenda. ``He probably
looks forward to them, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stripped of his incredible wealth and unmatched golfing skills,
Woods has an engaging side to him, which he isn't afraid to let
shine through. He said his pairing with Jordan here fell through
because ``he's got a job now and can't get off work, even though he
is the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Then toward the conclusion of Wednesday's practice round, Woods
agreed to some fun with playing partner Mark Calcavecchia. The
final hole would be alternate shot with the caddies as partners, a
$100 bet.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th hole at Pebble Beach is arguably the most famous tee
shot in golf, for you must start the ball out over a Pacific Ocean
that offers a continuous roar of waves.
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia's caddie hit first and launched it perfectly,
adding that much pressure onto Steve Williams, Woods's caddie. With
his player hoisting jokes in his direction, Williams tried to get
it over in a hurry and his swing produced a low screamer that hit
thick rough next to a red stake. An unplayable lie, just 85 yards
off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   With 458 yards to go, hitting his team's second shot, Woods
laughed. ``Man, I'm in trouble now.''
</P>
<P>
   He crushed a 3-wood to get his team back in play, but Williams
pushed the next shot into thick rough right of the green. Hitting
his team's fourth shot, Woods nearly holed out a soft lob, a shot
that led Williams to roar, ``I've got a partner,'' as the ball came
to rest a foot from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Woods laughed, even though he had lost the one-hole
match. No matter, for it didn't count for anything.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the streak. No matter what Woods says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
