<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5316 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DISCS-REVIEWS-LADN &LR;      02-03 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCS-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CD REVIEWS BY DAILY NEWS STAFF
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
Jackie McLean/``Nature Boy'' (Blue Note)
<TEXT>
<P>
   A quartet date of standards played in swinging style, ``Nature
Boy'' finds veteran alto saxophonist McLean teamed up with such
dependable old hands as drummer Billy Higgins, pianist Cedar Walton
and longtime trio bassist David Williams. Now into his fourth
decade as a leader, McLean still delivers passionate music in the
post-bop tradition and this disc finds him in a more relaxed mood
than other recent sessions. The collection opens with a mid-tempo
``You Don't Know What Love Is,'' moving on with an introspective
take on the title track, highlighted by McLean's spirited solo.
Although the track list is almost overly familiar _ ``Smoke Gets in
Your Eyes,'' ``What Is This Thing Called Love?'' ``I Can't Get
Started'' _ the players invest the material with surprise and
personality. 3 stars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster &QR; 
 &QL; 
D'Angelo/``Voodoo'' (Virgin)
</P>
<P>
   The eagerly anticipated sophomore set from sinewy urban soul
star D'Angelo has been delayed and rescheduled so many times you
almost wonder if someone put a bona fide hex on the project.
Definitely worth the wait and easily one of the most compelling r&AMP;b
albums in a long time, the 14-track ``Voodoo'' is a neo-soul
classic, a stirring mix of funk and hip-hop in that resonant,
easy-to-love style of Lauryn Hill. Recorded at Jimi Hendrix's old
Electric Lady studio in Greenwich Village, the record was clearly
inspired by the '60s guitar great, along with the spirits of early
Prince, Stevie Wonder (whose Fender Rhodes piano from the ``Talking
Book'' sessions was used), Marvin Gay and James Brown. The
groove-thick atmosphere lives up to the Hendrix-tinted album title
and a spare, earthy vibe pervades all corners, including a
slow-burning cover of Roberta Flack's 1974 hit ``Feel Like Makin'
Love.'' A low-lights beauty. 4 stars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ F.S. &QR; 
 &QL; 
Tina Turner/``Twenty Four Seven'' (Virgin)
</P>
<P>
   This should have been a memorable album for the flamboyant rock
'n' soul diva who recently turned 60. Sadly, ``Private Dancer''
it's not. Again, it's a problem of material. Turner invests all
tracks here with trademark full-throttle passion but she's working
with lackluster songs. Although Turner has dubbed the album a form
of modern gospel music, the tunes are rarely memorable or
compelling. A voice that could turn the Jerry's menu into a
foot-stomping raveup shouldn't be singing such piffle as ``Talk to
My Heart'' and ``Without You,'' two of the lesser cuts on display.
Better luck next time. 2 stars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ F.S. &QR; 
 &QL; 
Fela Kuti/``The Best Best Best of Fela Kuti'' (Universal/Barclay)
</P>
<P>
   At last those Universal Records dollars are bearing fruit. The
label's ambitious and long-awaited Kuti reissue project is under
way, and the first item off the presses is this excellent two-disc
anthology of some of the Nigerian Afrobeat legend's greatest and
hardest-to-find material. It's all here _ from the great
``Shakara,'' a jazz-tinged funk workout about a street
confrontation, and the equally brilliant ``Zombie'' to ``Coffin for
Head of State,'' the late Kuti's fiery condemnation of Nigeria's
former ruling party. Whether you care about politics or not, Kuti's
great grooves and the fine playing of his sprawling jazz-funk
ensemble will have you voting for this highly recommended
compilation. 4 stars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ F.S. &QR; 
 &QL; 
Amel Larrieux/``Infinite Possibilities'' (Epic/550 Music)
</P>
<P>
   As siren for New York's progressive r&AMP;b outfit Groove Theory a
few years back, Larrieux attracted attention for a voice that could
go from silky to gutsy in the space of a couple of lines. Using
hip-hop, funk beats and flashes of world-beat influences, her first
solo effort paints warm, infectious pictures. Perhaps the most
promising track is ``Down,'' a jazzy groove Larrieux puts across in
a husky lower register. 3 stars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ F.S. &QR; 
 &QL; 
Michael Brecker/``Time Is of the Essence'' (Verve)
</P>
<P>
   Long admired as a studio musician and guest player, Brecker has
finally come up with an album that matches his prodigious talents
on the tenor sax. Brecker has never sounded so loose and funky as
he does on ``Time's'' nine new compositions, and his liberation as
a player must, in part, be attributed to the presence of guitarist
Pat Metheny and organist Larry Goldings. Together with a revolving
trio of drummers (including Elvin Jones), the band creates vibrant,
straight-ahead jazz that is unpredictable without being
self-indulgent. An inspired effort, easily Brecker's best work as a
leader. 4 stars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Glenn Whipp &QR; 
 &QL; 
Sarah Chang, Wolfgang Sawallisch; Concerto for Violin and Orchestra
in D Minor Op. 8, and Sonata for Violin and Piano in E Flat Op. 18
by Richard Strauss (EMI Classics)
</P>
<P>
   This recording of two early, rarely performed works by Strauss
affords a fascinating study of the interplay between the
still-young composer's rapidly expanding musical vocabulary and
Chang's own beautifully lithesome, still-ripening solo work. By far
the more accomplished and subtle of these pieces is the violin
sonata, an elegantly rounded chamber work that echoes the bright,
chromatic exclamations of Strauss' ``Don Juan'' period (circa
1888). Chang and pianist Wolfgang Sawallisch (who also conducts the
violin concerto) suavely convey the composer's youthful ambition
and amazing structural confidence, particularly in a finale that
contains flashes of the fiery modernist yet to come. Op. 8, written
when Strauss was but 17, heaps dramatic notions and concise
mini-melodies like new-mown hay before settling into the achingly
pensive middle movement, followed by the high-spirited romanticism
of the rondo finale. A rewarding if not exactly indispensable disc.
2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reed Johnson &QR; 
 &QL; 
Chet Baker, John Barry, Chris Botti/``Playing by Heart'' (Decca)
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing by Heart,'' for those who don't remember (and that
would include just about everybody) was a little-seen ensemble film
that came and went this time last year. This album figures to have
a longer shelf life since composer Barry, working with pop/jazz
trumpeter Botti, has delivered a moody, expressive score that's
perfect for late-night listening. The album includes three prime
Baker cuts from his outstanding 1955 Paris sessions, and,
predictably, they overshadow the other music here. (Check out
``Chet in Paris, Vol. 2'' for the full program.) Still, Barry has
written some beautiful, melancholy music here, and fans of the
late, great Baker will undoubtedly appreciate this tribute. 3
stars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ G.W. &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
