<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS ALL DONE WITH MUSIC AND MAHOGANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do Camille Saint-Saens, a 15th-century Norman carved
mantelpiece and an Amish-trained cabinetmaker have in common?
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, these three elements came together to produce
a huge carved mahogany cabinet, an entertainment center that
promises to be an heirloom someday.
</P>
<P>
   It all began when Paul and Valerie Gilman, who live in a
castle-like house in Gloucester, Mass., complete with moats, called
cabinetmaker Michael Turkoc to see what he could do to build an
entertainment center, an eight-foot piece that would fit into the
Italianate castle, and house a TV, stereo, and the usual
components, including speakers, without looking out of place.
</P>
<P>
   The Gilmans wanted something Italianate, or maybe a white
cabinet in French provincial. So, said Turkoc, ``I offered them
something French.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gilmans showed me the house, and when I saw that
15th-century mantelpiece, which was originally a headboard, I
flipped,'' said Turkoc. What better design than one that is alreay
in the house? ``I touched the piece and said, `This is it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to make something beautiful, and this was my
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkoc, a partner in Artisans in Wood &AMP; Design of Rockport,
Mass., went back to his shop, a roomy, comfortable workplace with a
minimum of power tools (remember, he's Amish trained, from Ohio),
and an enviable collection of wood chisels. He even has a couple of
skew chisels, ones that cut at an angle, that he fashioned from old
tie rods.
</P>
<P>
   Turkoc took lots of pictures of the old mantelpiece, with plans
to carve something similar, or at least similar in spirit. He
touched that old mantelpiece, again.
</P>
<P>
   Then he got stuck. The muse abandoned him. It happens to all
artists, one time or another.
</P>
<P>
   Until . . . Until one day he was listening to WCRB, and Ray
Brown, one of the friendly announcers on that classical music
station, played Saint-Saens' ``Rhapsody D'Auverne.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried a little,'' said Turkoc, ``but I was also thrilled,
and had the design in two hours.'' While that did not take long, he
worked with templates for 100 hours before cutting wood.
</P>
<P>
   The design is Norman, with a non-Norman breakfront style (the
middle sticks out in front of the ends), large, solid, and
masculine, but with feminine touches in French curves at the ends.
And, an interesting addition, eight large bun feet. They make it
easy to stabilize the big piece on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The sides and top are plain, but accented by those French
curves. Another nice touch is the low height of the cabinet,
reducing its massiveness and allowing anyone reasonably tall to see
the incredibly smooth top with the ever-so-deep finish of eight
coats of lacquer without standing on tiptoe. Other surfaces have
five to eight coats of lacquer, which provide not only a pleasant
glow but also just the right color of the mahogany.
</P>
<P>
   Turkoc started out by buying a huge piece of wood from Holt &AMP;
Bugbee of Tewksbury. He thinks the old Norman mantelpiece is walnut
or French pear, both too rare to find the large piece he needed for
the sides. So, he opted for mahogany; besides, he had 600 board
feet of mahogany in the shop, and mahogany is more readily
available.
</P>
<P>
   That big slab of mahogany was 4 3/8 inches thick, 24 inches wide
and 9 1/2 feet long, and made fine sides.
</P>
<P>
   It was the doors _ one double and two singles, that provided the
challenge to Turkoc to create carvings similar to those on the
ancient mantelpiece.
</P>
<P>
   He came through, chiseling great slabs off the mahogany, even
using a router to get larger amounts off, continuing with a little
finer work with a Dremel tool, and ending up with hand chiseling
with the chisel marks showing, the only way carving like this will
work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Turkoc did a lot of sanding, but not on the flat part of the
panels.
</P>
<P>
   This carving technique left highlights on the panel, just as it
did 500 years ago on the mantelpiece. There are no overlays or
tacked-on or glued-on moldings or decor.
</P>
<P>
   The cabinet is eight feet long and very heavy, so Turkoc built
it in several parts for easy transportation.
</P>
<P>
   One modern concession to the cabinetry is the use of speaker
cloth to cover the speakers. They are set in doors that can be
lifted off, and offer little resistance to sound transmission. What
if the doors shrink and start to rattle? ``We'll tackle that when
it happens, if it happens'' said Turkoc.
</P>
<P>
   While Turkoc used contemporary joinery techniques, he used a
very old technique in mounting the panels in their frames. They are
dry mounted, without glue, and float in the frames. This keeps them
from cracking when they expand and contract.
</P>
<P>
   That is how the panels in the mantelpiece were mounted, and they
have served well, uncracked in 500 years.
</P>
<P>
   So that is how Saint-Saens, the Norman mantelpiece, and an
Amish-trained cabinetmaker combined to produce a cabinet as sublime
as the music it holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't quite understand how music relates to cabinetmaking,
but in my case it does,'' said Turkoc.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because he was making a cabinet for a music maker.
</P>
<P>
   And you ought to hear that Saint-Saens Rhapsody coming from the
speakers in Michael Turkoc's rhapsody in mahogany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
