<HEADLINE>
WHAT WE SEE IS WHAT WE GET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the universe has a slogan, it goes ``Pay attention, stupid!''
</P>
<P>
   Most of us have at one time or another come across the old adage
that what you pay attention to shapes your character, and limits or
expands your capacity to be fully human. I could point to a myriad
examples, but I think it makes more sense for each of you to take a
few moments to wonder: Out of the millions of events taking place
on this planet every day, what do you choose to focus on?
</P>
<P>
   But I recently learned something even more astounding about the
degree to which we are capable of paying careful attention. It
doesn't only shape one's inner landscape; it reveals very different
aspects of external reality to different people.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, my friend Lynn and I took our first trip together. We
spent six days in Belize, which is the closest I have ever gotten
to the Garden of Eden. We traveled on our own, and a series of
seemingly random impulses led us to a fairly inaccessible area in a
part of the country near the border with Guatemala, where we stayed
with a Mayan family. One morning, the eldest son equipped Lynn and
me and several other Americans staying at the Crystal Paradise
Resort with paddles and canoes and dropped us off at a spot on the
Macal River. Jeronie pointed in the direction of a town called San
Ignacio, 9 miles away, where he said he hoped to see us again.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, we were on our own.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn and I did notice a few brightly colored birds when we were
not concentrating on staying afloat through short but somewhat
scary stretches of rapids. There were three canoes in all. The one
in the lead was our least favorite because we had discovered at
dinner the night before that its occupant was an avid hunter who
owned nine guns.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn and I knew we were in a jungle because there were vines,
strange sounds, unfamiliar smells, and oversize office plants all
around, but I was disappointed. Lynn likes flora. I'd come for the
fauna.
</P>
<P>
   John, our sharp-sighted hunter, was the only one of us who saw
the family of otters near some logs and led us to a place where we
could watch the parents trying to restrain a kid who wanted to show
off. I would not have seen the otters in a million years. John also
sighted the iguanas midway up the trees, every one of them a
strange coral color because the males had donned erotic finery for
the mating season. He anticipated the struggle for dominance
between two 4-foot-long specimens that sent both of them plummeting
30 feet to the ground. By paddling his canoe under an oddly shaped
overhang, he set off a flurry of bats we would never have been
aware of otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   I spend a lot of time in nature myself, but I never realized
before this trip that I am nearly blind. I couldn't see the
extremely talkative parrot in the foliage outside our room until
one of the Mayan children led me directly to the right tree and
pointed. I scanned branches where everyone else was watching spider
monkeys, and couldn't pick them out until one of them leaped into
the air. If I had not been accompanied by people whose acuity of
vision astounded me, I swear I would have returned from vacation
asserting as fact that the only visible wild animals in Belize were
the coatimundi that begged for chips at Mayan ruins. I can imagine
myself insisting that most were too deep in the jungle to see.
</P>
<P>
   When you don't pay attention, whole aspects of reality actually
cease to exist. This can happen individually. It can shape whole
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   I've been wondering if this realization has a wider application
_ in matters of divinity, for example. I am positive I would have
noticed if a burning bush had spoken to me or a river parted so
that I could pass through, but there are few if any miracles that
spectacular these days. Still, I wonder. What if the spirit is
whispering to me and I'm not listening carefully enough? What if
some sacred force is clearly active in my life, but I ignore it
because I'm too preoccupied with something else?
</P>
<P>
   What else in this world am I incapable of seeing?
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be ironic if love, or wholeness, or meaning, or
happiness, or friendship, or abundance, or whatever else our heart
most passionately desires were smack dab right here in the middle
of everything and most of us hadn't a clue because, like tourists
set down in an unfamiliar setting of incredible beauty, we were
busily, madly, blindly paddling down the river of life, oblivious?
</P>
<P>
   The Tut family's Crystal Paradise Resort's e-mail address is
cparadise(at)btl.net.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
