<HEADLINE>
SIGNS POINT TO MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who's No. 1? Strange question to be asking about college
football teams in February. But Wednesday it had some meaning.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``National Letter of Intent Day.'' In New England,
it didn't mean all that much if you weren't a Boston College fan or
didn't follow some Division 1-A program from long distance.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout the South, all around the Midwest, down in the
Southwest, and out on the West Coast, it was headline stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on which recruiting guru you believed _ and there are
lots of them _ Texas, Penn State, Miami, or Florida had the No. 1
recruiting class Wednesday after they received official commitments
from the various blue-chip athletes around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Miami may not have won the Big East race last season, but the
Hurricanes and coach Butch Davis took the conference recruiting
honors in a landside, far outdistancing runners-up Virginia Tech,
Syracuse, and Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news for the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news? They might have finished third in their own state,
since Florida and Florida State also had top-10 recruiting classes.
</P>
<P>
   But like some elections that need recounts, the final tallies
are not in. Wednesday was only the first day that recruits could
officially commit to a school in writing.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the player regarded by many as the best prep player
in the country, D.J. Williams, a 6-foot-1-inch, 230-pound
linebacker from Concord, Calif., was hedging his bets as he decided
between Miami, California, and Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spent a lot of time and energy recruiting Williams, and
felt the 'Canes still had the inside track on Williams. But until a
school's fax machine buzzes with Williams's signature, nothing is
official.
</P>
<P>
   So precarious is the balance of power in recruiting that one
player, such as Williams, could vault Miami from somewhere in the
bottom half of the top 10 to the top five, and even No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lemming, who is as respected as anyone in the business,
ranked Florida No. 1 and Tennessee No. 2 using simple logic.
``Florida signed more top 100 players than anyone else,'' said
Lemming, who also had Alabama, Florida State, and Texas in his top
five.
</P>
<P>
   Some others had Texas No. 1, which would make Longhorns coach
Mack Brown 2 for 2 in top recruiting classes in his two years in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the hard part: Brown must coach that talent and get
them to produce on the field.
</P>
<P>
   If you go by position, the balance of power is fairly well
spread out. Assuming Williams commits to Miami, the Hurricanes
would have the top linebacker in the country.
</P>
<P>
   --Safety O.J. Owens, a 6-0, 190-pound speedster from New London,
N.C., committed to Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   --Wide receiver B.J. Johnson, a 6-0, 180-pound wide receiver
from Grand Prairie, Texas, signed with Texas.
</P>
<P>
   --Quarterback Brock Berlin, a 6-2, 202-pound prospect from
Shreveport, La., committed early to Florida. In fact, he's already
enrolled at school and will participate in spring practice with the
Gators.
</P>
<P>
   --Kwame Harris, regarded as the best offensive lineman in the
country, committed early as well. The 6-7 tackle form Newark, Del.,
is going to Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   --The best running back? Arguably it's Willis McGahee, from
Miami Central, who is staying home and playing with the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   So it went as the commitments kept coming in and coaches
announced how delighted they were with their recruiting classes.
</P>
<P>
   As well they should be.
</P>
<P>
   It's February, after all, and hope springs eternal for the haves
and the have-nots of college football.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
