<SLUG> BC-TREK-WILLIAM-GIBSON-WRITES-THE-X-FILES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM GIBSON RETURNS TO ``THE X-FILES'' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of a montage
including author William Gibson and the cast of ``The X-Files.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Just as his characters crave to transcend the flesh, William
Gibson yearns to transcend his status as a living legend.
 &HT;    The author of the ground-breaking ``Neuromancer'' trilogy _
``Neuromancer'' (Ace Books, 1984), ``Count Zero'' (Ace, 1986) and
``Mona Lisa Overdrive'' (Ace, 1988) _ swears that he is not the
godfather of cyberpunk. And virtually no one believes him.
 &HT;    ``Even in the early 1980s, it just seemed to be one of those
weird journalistic feedback loops,'' Gibson says by telephone from
his home in Vancouver, B.C. ``Someone coined a term, and it sounded
good.''
 &HT;    At the very least, however, Gibson ranks as a prophet of the
Internet. His vivid tales depict computer universes run amok,
artificial intelligences giving humankind a run for its money and
virtual reality before the phrase existed. They're violent, sexy,
forward-thinking and scary as hell.
 &HT;    Gibson also has tried his hand at writing for the big screen,
enduring a ``fairly traumatic'' ordeal with the incoherent 1995
thriller ``Johnny Mnemonic.'' Far better was his small-screen
experience with ``Kill Switch,'' an acclaimed fifth-season episode
of ``The X-Files.''
 &HT;    So popular was that episode _ and so pleased was Gibson with the
finished product _ that he agreed to a return engagement. In the
Chris Carter-directed ``First Person Shooter,'' airing Feb. 27,
Mulder (David Duchovny) and Scully (Gillian Anderson) contend with
a lusty, busty and bloodthirsty cyberbabe (Krista Allen) who
appears to be slaying the human players of a soon-to-be-released
video game.
 &HT;    ``We wanted to trap a couple of women in the purest and most
exaggerated testosterone nightmare we could come up with,'' says
Gibson, who co-wrote the hour-long episode with ``Kill Switch''
partner Tom Maddox. ``This is the id's revenge on the boytoy.
 &HT;    ``I like it that the monster is kind of an id figure _ it's sort
of the impossible boy's fantasy of what a woman should be,'' he
says. ``I also liked the sense of big e-bucks that flows through
the episode, the chance of making a zillion bucks on a lucky IPO.''
 &HT;    Gibson thinks there's as much difference between film and
television as there is between the written word and the screen of
either size. Further, he considers writing prose fiction to be an
entirely different art form from writing for the screen.
 &HT;    ``It's like music and sculpture,'' he says. ``They're both
creative activities, but they're just so different.
 &HT;    ``I don't think screenplays are artifacts in the way that novels
are,'' the author says. ``A screenplay is a process, it's evidence
of a process. But it's really nothing in itself.
 &HT;    ``I can never judge what will eventually appear on screen on the
basis of a screenplay,'' he adds. ``I've read scripts I disliked
but liked the movie when I saw it, and they hadn't changed a
word.''
 &HT;    Many moviegoers assumed that Gibson was involved in the making
of last year's blockbuster ``The Matrix.'' Given the film's
hypnotic visuals, A.I. villains and sleek costumes, the confusion
was understandable, but Gibson had nothing to do with the
production.
 &HT;    ``Before I saw it, I assumed it would have all too much to do
with me,'' Gibson says. ``A good friend of mine finally dragged me
kicking and screaming to see it, and I really liked it. Upon
reflection, it probably didn't have all that much to do with me.
 &HT;    ``I thought they digested my work very, very thoroughly, and the
work of a couple of other writers,'' he adds. ``In some ways it was
more like a Philip K. Dick story than a William Gibson story.
 &HT;    ``It was also a remarkably good-hearted movie, which I hadn't
expected at all.''
 &HT;    Gibson's latest novel, ``All Tomorrow's Parties'' (Putnam,
1999), arrived in bookstores in November. The post-Millennium
adventure revisits Colin Laney, a character last seen in the Gibson
best-seller ``Idoru'' (Putnam, 1996).
 &HT;    ``By and large the reaction was very positive,'' the author
says. ``Once my books are published I just let them go. I'm already
thinking about the next one.
 &HT;    ``Maybe I'll read `All Tomorrow's Parties' in a couple of years,
and then I'll see what I did.''
 &HT;    In the meantime, Gibson hopes to write more ``X-Files'' episodes
_ assuming, of course, that the series continues for another
season, contrary to current reports.
 &HT;    As for the big screen, the film rights to ``Count Zero'' and
``Mona Lisa Overdrive'' are ``sold and sitting somewhere,'' he
says. A big-screen version of ``Neuromancer'' seems likely to
emerge eventually, ``but it's too early to talk about.''
 &HT;    As the plug is pulled on this conversation, Gibson muses on the
defining aspects of the fictional cyberspace firmament he helped
establish.
 &HT;    ``I think it derives its strength from providing us with a
metaphor for what we're actually experiencing daily,'' he says.
``In a funny way, what the concept of V.R. did was to give everyone
a really convenient handle for where we live and contemporary
media.
 &HT;    ``It's not really about the future. It's about the present.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The X-Files,'' consult the
official Website at www.thex-files.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5329 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-SUV-SPEED-HNS &LR;      02-03 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUV-SPEED-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     STUDY SAYS SUVs DISTORT DRIVERS' PERCEPTIONS  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ When it comes to cars, perception is everything,
and few autos on the road scream status like the sleek, stark sport
utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   But perceptions can lie. A new study on the psychology of
transportation suggests that because SUV drivers sit higher from
the ground, they have the dangerous illusion of driving slower than
they really are.
</P>
<P>
   The differences can be stark: a person driving a Lincoln
Navigator going 60 mph feels the same sense of speed a Honda Civic
driver has at 40 mph, according to a mathematical formula developed
by Ron Noel of the Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data suggests that SUV drivers underestimate their
speed,'' said Noel, assistant director of RPI's Mind and Machines
Lab and assistant professor of philosophy, psychology and cognitive
science. ``Second of all, when it comes to cornering, it shows they
would take the corners too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, to be presented at the Design of Information Systems
2000 conference in New York City this August, is hardly the SUV's
first brush with controversy. Previous studies, however, have
focused on the impact of SUVs on smaller vehicles, rather than
driver perception.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
estimated that 2,000 people who died in 1996 when their cars
collided with an SUV would have survived had they crashed with
another car, even one as heavy as an SUV. A second federal study
showed that colliding with a light truck (a category including
SUVs, pickups and minivans) produced far more injury and death than
colliding with another car.
</P>
<P>
   Noel's study uses a relatively new field _ ``telepresence,''
which he describes as ``being there without being there.''
Telepresence measures people's subjective responses to real
situations.
</P>
<P>
   In this study, ``real'' meant much smaller than SUV scale. Noel
filmed a toy train going at top-speed of 3.5 mph, with cameras
attached at heights of 2, 1.5 and 1 inch above the ground. In each
case, the train went the same speed, but the subjective eye
revealed unexpected contrasts: a crawl at 2 inches, average speed
at 1.5 and a runaway train at 1.
</P>
<P>
   From his work with small toys, Noel developed a mathematical
model that could apply to vehicles of any size.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a paradox,'' he said. ``You'd expect the
higher up you are, the more you'd feel like you'd tip over going
fast. But the truth is, the closer you are to the ground, the
faster you think you're going. So when you turn, you know to slow
down to avoid tipping over.''
</P>
<P>
   Noel mused that SUV drivers' perceptions may be inherently
flawed. Statistics tend to bear him out: The traffic safety
administration showed last year that SUVs have 98 rollover deaths
per million, compared to 44 fatalities per million for all other
light vehicle types.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Tatchio, director of safety public affairs for the Ford
Motor Co., a major producer of SUVs, had little to say about Noel's
research. ``I'm really surprised to hear it,'' she said. ``But I
think we'd have to do a lot more research to say anything
conclusively.''
</P>
<P>
   Noel, a former Jeep Cherokee driver, also was surprised by the
findings. ``There's something a little perverse to it,'' he said.
``It tells us not to trust our own perceptions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
