<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS ODD COUPLE NEEDS A DIVORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some couples confuse you and make you wonder, ``How do
(itals)they(unitals) ever manage to stay together?'' But in the
case of Antoine Walker and Rick Pitino, the answer to the question
is simple: the NBA salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Mo Vaughn has parted ways with Dan Duquette and John
Harrington, Walker-Pitino is easily the tensest union in Boston pro
sports. At times, relationships can be summarized with words. Not
with these guys; a heart monitor would be more appropriate. Is
there frenzied activity on the screen? Or are we on the verge of
flatlining?
</P>
<P>
   Life truly is not fair, because if it were, the salary cap would
be tossed out of the equation and these two would be granted what
they both deserve: a break from each other. A permanent break. It
is no one's fault. The truth is that they are not now, and may
never be, a good fit for one another. They do an amazing job of
defending one another publicly. But it was just a little more than
two weeks ago, following a home loss to Vancouver, when they
disagreed _ again _ and had an ugly confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Are there no-fault divorces in the NBA?
</P>
<P>
   Walker and Pitino are both smart men. They have to realize that
if they remain employees of the Celtics, they will certainly
disagree again. Just as they did two weeks ago when they argued
over who is responsible for the team's uneven play. Just as they
did last summer when they argued about conditioning. Just as they
did in the summer of 1998 when they disagreed on how a player is to
spend his summer vacation. Just as they did in the spring of '98
when they argued after a game in which Walker had scored 43 points.
</P>
<P>
   The irony here is that Walker and Pitino might be the last two
people to acknowledge that they may never be winners together
again. Their familiar chorus is that they won a national
championship at Kentucky nearly four years ago, when the then
19-year-old Walker was far less mature, so why wouldn't they be
able to repeat now? But other people in the organization have at
least questioned the captain's ability to lead his team to the
playoffs, not to mention a championship.
</P>
<P>
   As the NBA lockout ended last year and teams were permitted to
sign players such as Walker to $71 million contracts, there was
some resistance among the Celtics' decision-makers. At least one of
them did not believe that Walker should be signed before the
season. The theory then was that he should be allowed to play out
the season, become a free agent, and then see what his worth would
be on the open market. (The Celtics would still be able to give him
more money than anyone else.)
</P>
<P>
   Obviously Pitino didn't share that opinion and signed the
6-foot-9-inch forward to the richest contract in Celtics history.
And so now the two are, for better or worse, contractually bound to
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Pitino gave the Walker-Pitino Monitor a jolt.
Responding to yet another Walker trade rumor, the Celtics president
and coach said he would not trade his captain unless Michael Jordan
were included in the deal. I find that hard to believe. Forget
about Michael Jordan. If Pitino could get Michael Finley in a deal
he'd probably do it. And since we're playing the name game, I'm
sure he'd like guys named Shaquille, Kobe, Grant, Kevin, Gary, and
Tim, too.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino doesn't necessarily have history on his side when it
comes to quashing trade rumors. This is the same man who said he
would not trade Ron Mercer and Chauncey Billups, and that he would
take his own life before separating from Bruce Bowen. So, will he
trade Walker? I don't know. But if he plans to fulfill the
remainder of his coaching contract, he should try like hell to do
it if he cares about peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Let me make myself clear here: I do not believe that a top
player and a head coach have to like each other to be successful.
They don't even have to respect each other. What they must have is
a similar philosophy of what it takes to win. To me, that's
one-third of the problem between these two. All you have to do is
analyze their clashes to find the root of their ideological
separation.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, they cannot agree on what kind of player Walker
should be. If that were the only problem, and it isn't, I would
volunteer to be their arbiter, pro bono.
</P>
<P>
   Walker is a 6-9 power forward who happens to have good _ not
great _ ballhandling skills. He cannot play point guard. He has
made 27 percent of his 3-point attempts, so he is not a 3-point
shooter. The fact that he has already attempted 172 3s should be an
embarassment to him and Pitino. He is quicker than most power
forwards and can easily snake around most of them (see Shawn Kemp)
for easy points. It boggles the mind that the Celtics' offense
calls for him to be so far away from the hoop so frequently.
</P>
<P>
   It would also help Pitino and Walker immensely if there were an
accomplished veteran on the roster, someone such as Terry Cummings
or Rick Mahorn. As the Patriots learned this season, you cannot
measure the locker room impact of thoughtful pros who can still
contribute, even if their best days are behind them. The Celtics'
most senior veterans are Pervis Ellison and Dana Barros. Pitino has
all but dismissed the former and doesn't rely enough on the
expertise of the latter.
</P>
<P>
   One issue, though, is inescapable. The coach and the player are
this city's odd couple. Not odd as in eccentric, but odd as in not
professionally compatible. One of them will have to leave the
other. And when that happens, both of them will be happier men
because of it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
