u l BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-ART-BOS &LR;      02-03 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (l and f coding)  
 2000 NISSAN FRONTIER CREW CAB: TIME FOR A CHANGE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For an example of how fast things are changing in the auto
industry, you have to go only as far as the new Frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Models that once had a showroom life of five years _ or seven
for many trucks _ are now evolving in about half that time.
Nissan's Frontier pickup trucks, particularly its four-door Crew
Cab, are glaring examples.
</P>
<P>
   The Frontier, rigid framed and rough riding, was introduced in
1997. Last year, the Crew Cab, the first compact pickup with four
full doors and a real back seat, came to market. Already, Nissan
has acknowledged, the line has to be overhauled. Things are
changing that quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan had hoped to get to 2004 with the Frontier platform but
now it's looking for a remake by 2002, and if they want to stay
competitive in a pickup market that has become a caldron of change,
they'd better make that date.
</P>
<P>
   The platform has been leapfrogged, its engine _ 170 horses from
a V6 _ is too weak in a market where power sells, and others _
Dodge Dakota, Toyota Tundra, Ford F150 SuperCab _ have blown by the
Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   The Frontier Crew Cab is a competent truck, but that's not good
enough anymore. And that's too bad, because stepping out first with
the four-door concept was cutting edge at the time. But it
unfortunately melded that four-door cab, and a tiny bed, with
outdated technology.
</P>
<P>
   Today, other trucks offer far more power, more comfort, a better
ride, and much larger beds.
</P>
<P>
   What does work in Nissan's Xterra _ going retro as a basic SUV _
doesn't work in its truck, which competes in a category where
consumers want truck capabilities coupled with car-like comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the motor. One-hundred-seventy horsepower out
of a V6 is simply not enough _ and it only got 17 miles per gallon
in a week of driving. Nissan makes a truly great V6 that cranks out
222 horsepower and puts it in the Maxima. This truck could use an
engine like that.
</P>
<P>
   It's got decent torque at low RPMs _ up to around 1,600 _ but
the curve flattens fast after that. It'll get your load or your
trailer rolling nicely from a start, but leave you chugging up any
steep grades.
</P>
<P>
   That roar you hear from the engine as you climb? It's not the
comforting rumble of power. It's the sound of an engine working too
hard as the four-speed automatic downshifts to maintain speed.
</P>
<P>
   The truck is still a basic box, square in a day of round, smooth
corners. The bed is only 54.7 inches long. Try carrying lumber in
that. A good option is a bed extender (about $225).
</P>
<P>
   Inside, it doesn't get much better.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is decent room in the rear for three adults, and
though the rear doors are a bit narrow, getting in and out is not
the chore it can be in some trucks with rear seats.
</P>
<P>
   But the seats aren't comfortable. The front buckets are flat and
don't offer much support.
</P>
<P>
   The appointments look cheap and plastic.
</P>
<P>
   I understand this is a truck, and Nissan is trying to sell it at
a good price ($17,000 to upward of $21,000), but folks are looking
for more than utility these days, and when it comes to trucks,
they'll pay extra for comfort and performance.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, at a good price they offer ABS, air conditioning, full
carpets, a sliding rear window, and a center console with sliding
armrest. But it's all only a step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota learned _ after the T100 _ that people want more and so
produced the Tundra, a V8 that is whisper smooth and rolling off
showroom floors as fast as it can be built, even at $5,000 or more
above the Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   The Frontier Crew Cab is available in both two-wheel- and
four-wheel-drive (I tested the two-wheel version) and puts both
models on the rigid 4WD frame.
</P>
<P>
   For suspension, it's got double wishbone, shocks and stabilizer
bar up front, a rigid axle with multileaf springs and stabilizer at
the rear.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan says this is meant to give it a car-like ride. I say it
rides like a truck. On frost heaves and ridged cement stretches of
highway, the empty bed did a skip-to-ma-loo all its own.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan has a fine history in producing trucks, all the way back
to when they were called Datsun. In 1959, they introduced the first
compact pickup in America. In 1975, it was the first long-bed
pickup. Two years later, they made some room behind the front seat
and rolled out the first King Cab. In 1999 it was the four-door,
compact pickup.
</P>
<P>
   But Nissan is a company that got either cautious or stagnant or
both, and today it is in the midst of trying to make a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   They've said they are looking for a fast makeover of three
models, the Altima, the wonderful Maxima, which has been criticized
only for its looks, and the Frontier series.
</P>
<P>
   And like Toyota, they have a full-size V8 pickup in their
sights, scheduled for the 2003 model year.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan is capable of building fine cars and trucks, and if
you're a loyalist, I say give them some time to bounce back from a
less-than-glistening time of design and development.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --The bar that runs beneath the driver's seat, which you can
feel every time you hit a bump.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The overall cab design is very nice, offering easy access and
lots of room in a compact truck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Base price: $17,290 &QL; 
Price as tested: $17,785 &QL; 
Horsepower 170 /Torque: 200 lb-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 116.1 inches / 193.1 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 71.9 inches/ 65.9 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 4,034 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 5 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
