<HEADER>
A5340 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-VALUE-FILENES-BOS &LR;      02-03 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALUE-FILENES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING OPPORTUNITY IN FILENE'S BASEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Value City Department Stores Inc., the Ohio-based retailer that
may be ready to announce a deal to buy ailing Filene's Basement
Corp., has enjoyed recent success by repositioning itself as a sort
of hybrid _ a store that is part Wal-Mart, part deparment store,
and part what Filene's Basement was in its heyday, say analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission is to give the best value on quality merchandise
to our middle-class customers,'' said a Value City spokesman who
asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor a Filene's Basement spokeswoman would comment on
the imminence of a possible sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we have not reached a deal with Value City or
anyone else,'' said Nancy Sterling of Filene's Basement, which has
been in bankruptcy protection since August.
</P>
<P>
   Value City traces its roots to a store founded by the
Schottenstein family in 1909. For much of its history, the retailer
stayed close to its home in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   But since becoming a public company in 1991 _ the Schottenstein
family continues to own a majority interest and Jay L.
Schottenstein serves as Value City's chairman and chief executive _
the company has expanded rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most retailers, which cluster stores within a small
geography, Value City presides over a fairly far-flung empire for a
regional retailer with $1.67 billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Value City operates two chains that together have about 160
stores in more than 15 states. Besides the department store chain,
there's a chain known as DSW Shoe Warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   To plug holes in a company map that stretches from Missouri to
New Jersey and even to Massachusetts in DSW's case, Value City has
been aggressively pursuing an acquisition strategy of buying small
chains on the cheap and folding them into the Value City empire,
according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   But Value City could be ``interested in something that will give
them an immediate entree into a new market'' for less money than it
would cost to open new stores, said analyst Jeffrey S. Stein of
McDonald Investments in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Value City is very ``opportunistic,'' always on the prowl ``for
the best deals,'' said chairman Howard Davidowitz of Davidowitz &AMP;
Associates Inc., a New York retail consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunism may be part of the Schottenstein family philosophy.
The family also has ties to firms that sometimes buy the inventory
of retailers going out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Value City's Department Stores are mostly free-standing big-box
stores with a footprint of about 87,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are nearly 60 DSW Shoe Warehouse stores, including
one in Framingham, Mass.. These roughly 25,000-square-foot stores
are comparable in size to some Filene's Basement satellite stores.
</P>
<P>
   As a separate business, the Schottenstein family also operates a
chain of Value City Furniture stores.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Value City Department Stores has viewed an
acquisition as a ``real estate transaction,'' said analyst Stein.
In other words, the nameplate of the acquired store often
disappears and management is replaced.
</P>
<P>
   But a Filene's Basement deal, if it happens, could be different
story, partly because in the last few years Value City has tried to
become more fashion-conscious, something Filene's Basement once
excelled at.
</P>
<P>
   And because the Filene's Basement name is so well-known in New
England, a possible deal could have Value City retaining the
Basement name and some of its management as well as opening some
new Filene's Basement stores, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Value City hasn't always been known for fashion. For much of the
early and mid-1990s, Value City tried to ``out Wal-Mart Wal-Mart,''
and it lost some of its focus, said Davidowitz.
</P>
<P>
   To improve performance, Value City brought in a new management
team just over two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, most of Value City's apparel department was crammed
with no-name merchandise. Now Value City offers a much broader
selection of branded goods at low prices, the retail formula that
Filene's Basement pioneered.
</P>
<P>
   The chain has now evolved into a sort of hybrid, Davidowitz
said. It's partly a discount store similar to Wal-Mart. There's
some resemblance to a department store and also to an offprice
store, such as Filene's Basement that sells department store brand
names at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   This ``unique'' one-stop-shopping mix allows Value City to
differentiate itself from the competition, Davidowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Value City also sells home furnishings and sporting
goods, the biggest chunk of its sales comes from apparel.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report in the New York Post, Value City also has
expressed some interest in Loehmann's Inc. In many ways, Loehmann's
is similar to Filene's Basement. Both offer fashionable brand-name
clothing at lower prices. Both are operating in bankruptcy
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Loehmann's also is known for fashion, but primarily for women's
fashion. Filene's Basement is known for fashion both in women's and
men's clothing, and that may be one reason Value City may find the
Basement more attractive, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, uniting Filene's Basement's fashion flair to Value
City's greater size and strong management team could make the Ohio
retailer even stronger.
</P>
<P>
   For the most recent quarter Value City reported, profits nearly
doubled to $7.7 million. Sales increased 23.7 percent to $441.3
million. For the month of January, sales at stores open more than a
year were up 20 percent. And since the new management team took
over, Value City's stock price has nearly doubled, up 9/16
Wednesday to close at 15 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Said analyst Stein: ``They really execute well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
