<HEADLINE>
BANK'S VENTURES ARE ADVENTUROUS, IT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The stock market loves the venture capital business. How else
do you explain the incredible values attached to companies like
CMGI and Internet Capital Group, both of which invest in Internet
start-ups?
</P>
<P>
   But take that same venture business, stick it inside a
commercial bank, and investors lose interest fast.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan Corp. has been trying to change the market's
attitude. For the past month, Chase has been talking about its
private equity business, a blend of venture capital and buyout
deals, which is far and away the biggest one like it in the banking
world. Boiled down to basics, the Chase argument goes like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a great unappreciated business here. You guys all
think we are a boring old-economy company, but the truth is we are
big players in the cool new economy. Our stock price should reflect
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, FleetBoston Financial is saying ``Us too.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to private equity, FleetBoston is not in the same
league as Chase. The New York bank has a $7 billion portfolio,
compared to FleetBoston's $2.5 billion. But according to analysts,
FleetBoston is a strong player in the next rank of banks, which
includes Wells Fargo and Citibank.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of underlying value there that is not reflected
in their stock,'' Andrew Collins, an analyst at ING Barings, said
of FleetBoston.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the operation came to the bank through last year's
merger with BankBoston. BancBoston Capital has been in the private
equity business since 1959, practically the Pleistocene Age for
this industry. The bank invests its own money in exchange for
ownership stakes in new and emerging companies.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio has plenty of ``old economy'' holdings, but last
year more than 25 percent of the $800 million the bank invested
went into ``new economy'' companies in health care,
telecommunications, and Internet ventures.
</P>
<P>
   As of September, the bank's Internet holdings included Internet
Capital Group, Allaire, Viant, and Silknet Software. The stock
prices of Allaire and Viant are up sixfold since their initial
public offerings; Silknet is up tenfold; Internet Capital Group,
almost twentyfold.
</P>
<P>
   As a venture investor, the bank bought shares in all those
companies at a fraction of the IPO prices. BancBoston Capital's
president, Rick Fritz, won't say how much the bank made on any one
deal. But ``last year was our best year ever, by any measure you
use,'' he readily conceded.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston earned $212 million in the private equity business
in 1999. On top of that, the bank says it's sitting on more than $1
billion of unrealized gains in its portfolio. In other words, over
time, as the bank sells its holdings, those earnings should make
their way to the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``BancBoston Capital is one of the best, no question,'' said
Steven Galanate, publisher of Private Equity Analyst, a Wellesley
newsletter. Galante likes the fact that the bank's portfolio is
diversified by industry and geopgraphy. This year, the bank expects
to invest $300 million in Europe. Over time, it also expects to
increase its investments in South America, where the old Bank of
Boston is a household name.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Chase's publicity campaign, FleetBoston is starting
to toot its own horn a bit. At a recent Salomon Smith Barney
conference, bank executives talked about their ``new economy''
credentials, pointing to earnings from private equity, investment
bank Robertson Stephens, discount broker Quick &AMP; Reilly, and loans
to emerging companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we don't have a dot-com behind our name there is a
sense that we have missed out on the new economy. Quite the
opposite is true,'' said Gene McQuade, chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, talk isn't necessarily cheap. Since it began
boosting its venture business, Chase's stock price has climbed
smartly. Over the same time, FleetBoston's stock price hasn't
climbed at all. It sells for a distinctly ``old economy'' multiple
of 10 times earnings. FleetBoston has a market value of about $28
billion, roughly the same as CMGI's. FleetBoston earned over $2
billion last year; CMGI lost money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The venture businesses at the banks are ridiculously
undervalued, compared to their pure-play competitors,'' Collins
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even analysts who are less enthusiastic than Collins say
FleetBoston deserves better. ``I don't think they are getting the
bang for the buck that they should,'' said Tom Finucane, of John
Hancock's Regional Bank Fund.
</P>
<P>
   McQuade doesn't expect Wall Street to change its mind overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the frustrations all of us have who work within
large corporate shells,'' he said. ``The challenge we have is to
get people to understand exactly how we participate in the new
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
