<HEADLINE>
READERS HAVE THEIR SAY _ AND HOW! 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVs and ABS, refrigerators and washing machines, clutches and
skid control, gloves and gouging, speed limits, fun, and flattery.
You hit me with everything but the kitchen sink in your most recent
letters and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Provocation can be productive. Insults can be illuminating.
Banter is best. Here's to rounded repartee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why don't you just come out and admit that you hate SUVs?
Today's article was ridiculous. SUVs are top heavy . . . no
kidding. They don't handle like cars . . . wow, what a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   A. Got to admit, you nailed me on that one. I hate SUVs. But I
wonder, if all this is so obvious, why do so many people insist on
driving them as if they were not top heavy and as if they perform
like low-slung cars?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. It is clear from your first few columns this year that you
love SUVs and pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   A. Got to admit, you nailed me on that one. I love SUVs. In
truth, many of them are fine vehicles _ my family cars are a
Chevrolet Suburban and a Toyota Tundra pickup truck. SUVs have
their proper uses; trucks have their proper uses. As with any
vehicle, it's who is behind the wheel that matters most. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You say you hope that ``someday, somewhere, I see a trooper
pull over a car on the highway because the driver was going so slow
(55 or 65 in the passing lane) and impeding the normal flow of
traffic. Do you understand what you are saying?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. I am saying that sometimes common sense ought to prevail
over letter of the law. If an entire highway is flowing at 70-75
miles an hour, and someone gets into the passing lane and
single-handedly tries to enforce the law, that person is a yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Please stick to your grocery list, 10 top washing machines,
10 top refrigerators, 10 top garbage disposals _ you get my drift?
</P>
<P>
   A. Ah, my Florida buddy, who keeps suggesting that I don't know
anything about cars. What, too much time on your hands from sunrise
until that Early Bird Special at Denny's? Maybe we can compromise.
After all, Sears once made motorcycles, International Harvester
made refrigerators, and the new Saab has a refrigerated glove
compartment. I see a kitchen appliance/automotive triathalon in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You say that you base your reviews of cars on what sort of
driver the car is intended for. You should provide considered and
expert advice, not mouth what people want to hear or to make an
advertising point.
</P>
<P>
   A. As far as I am concerned, considered and expert advice takes
into account both the intent for which a car is designed and the
type of driver who might buy that car. Advertising is a whole other
part of this newspaper, and while I will listen to readers complain
about what I write, the folks in advertising get a deaf ear from me
in that regard. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am old enough to remember the panning of the VW Bug by many
automobile writers, including, to its everlasting shame, Consumer
Reports.
</P>
<P>
   A. I like old Bugs. But try to imagine this today: A new car is
introduced. It has a front end that is nothing more than hollow box
that crumples on impact. Inside that box is a tank full of
gasoline. It has a steering column that is a spear in front-end
collisions. Now, try to sell it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I agree with your review on the Volkswagen Eurovan. It can't
compete with better vans being made. Why don't they just build a
minivan?
</P>
<P>
   A. Volkswagen is considering just that _ bringing back a
nostalgic version of the Microbus. But they've got to overcome one
serious design problem: how to keep that distinctive flat nose and
still pass modern head-on crash tests. My guess is they will do it.
Look what they did with the New Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I still consider the glove box to be an anachronism. How many
decades has it been since anyone has seen a pair of gloves in a
glove box?
</P>
<P>
   A. I agree. Let's see if we can't come up with a better name for
that hole in the dash. Stuffbox? Thingholder? Reader input welcome
here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I don't like auto writers who get so jaded they overemphasize
``fun'' in cars, which effectively translates to turbo-charged
engines and low-profile tires.
</P>
<P>
   A. I was jaded long before I got this job, but I do consider
``fun'' to be a factor that many people consider when buying a car.
Still, it doesn't have to mean big power and high-performance
tires. Three of the most ``fun'' cars I drove last year: the Ford
Focus, the Mazda Miata, and the Xterra.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I was surprised by your comments on SUV price gouging. If
consumers are willing to pay tens of thousands of dollars extra for
a gussied-up truck, that's their problem.
</P>
<P>
   A. True, it's their problem. But long range goodwill is wasted
by dealers who gouge folks $3,000-$10,000 for a car and those same
folks see their neighbors buying the same car a year later at true
cost.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We almost purchased a Nissan Xterra, but when we went back to
finally buy we were told that the price that had been written down
was ``incorrect'' and it suddenly was $2,000 higher.
</P>
<P>
   A. And how would you have felt had you paid that extra $2,000
and found out your neighbor got it elsewhere at MSRP? Bet that
would be your last Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several of you wrote to say that I have mentioned ``skid
control'' in reviews of certain cars and some wondered if it helps
you steer. Here's how it works:
</P>
<P>
   Skid control does not ``steer'' you through a turn. Instead, it
applies front and rear brakes, individually, to reduce the rotation
of some tires while letting others gain speed. This controls yaw
and keeps one corner of your vehicle from trying to get ahead of
another. Computers do the work, you just drive.
</P>
<P>
   Another frequent question is whether ABS can stop a car as
quickly as a system that locks up all four brakes and keeps them
that way until it comes to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   There's a swap going on. Straight ahead on a dry road, four
wheels locked up will stop a car faster than ABS, which modulates
braking from wheel-to-wheel so that no wheel locks. Seldom are you
doing an emergency stop under perfect conditions, so the trade-off
_ a slight bit of stopping distance for far more control _ is well
worth it. You can steer a car while its ABS brakes are jammed on;
without ABS, you are steering a log.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
