<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5350 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-PLANET-BOS &LR;      02-03 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PLANET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THIS BASKETBALL DIARY, RACE AND SELF-ABSORPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BLACK PLANET: Facing Race During an NBA Season 
By David Shields 
Crown, 223 pp. $23 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talented writers have followed a big-time basketball team
through a single season before _ David Halberstam and John
Feinstein come to mind _ but surely none has produced a more
bizarre eyewitness account than David Shields has, in his often
tortured, occasionally hilarious chronicle of the Seattle
Supersonics during the 1994-95 NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   In a book that purports to say profound things about
professional sports and racial consciousness in America, and
sometimes succeeds in doing so, Shields ends up saying a good deal
more _ perhaps more than anyone wants to know _ about his own
tortured psyche, the depths of his obsessive fandom, his fawning
over athletes as self-involved as he is, the burden of his white
man's guilt, the view from the NBA cheap seats, and Shields' sex
life with his wife, an accounting of which takes ``hoop dreams''
into what one can only hope are previously uncharted waters. If
you're a basketball fan, beware: This book is at once sillier and
more serious than any 10 other hoop books you're likely to run
across. A cult classic in search of a cult.
</P>
<P>
   During the season in question, the Sonics, led by guard Gary
Payton and forward Shawn Kemp, posted a record of 57-25 and lost to
the Los Angeles Lakers in the first round of the playoffs. For most
fans, end of story. What happened on the court, however, is almost
incidental to what Shields, a novelist and professor at the
University of Washington, aims to get at through his diary of the
team's fortunes. His deeper concern _ the whole conceit of the
book, in fact _ is what white fans think about black athletes, and
vice-versa (envy, scorn, arrogance). It is a topic to which Shields
brings a degree of self-consciousness that, while admirable for its
candor, often reads like a parody of pop psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Shields began the season by applying for regular press
credentials _ and was rebuffed by team management, on the
not-unreasonable grounds that he is not really covering the team
for any entity other than for himself. Forced to buy a pair of
season tickets, he spent much of the season dueling with the
Sonics' PR department _ now he has a pressbox seat, now he doesn't
_ while desperately trying to sell his unused tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, a trash-talking guard on his way to NBA stardom, became
the author's idol and substitute ID as the season unfolded, much as
footballer Frank Gifford did for the narrator of Frederick Exley's
novel ``A Fan's Notes.'' ``Utterly narcissistic,'' as Shields
lovingly describes him, Payton with his flashy style of play and
sharp tongue off the court ``force(d) the racial subtext out in the
open'' while creating, in Shields' mind, anyway, ``a very strong,
very strange, utterly hallucinatory bond'' with the author himself.
No doubt very strange to Payton, anyway, who never gave Shields the
time of day.
</P>
<P>
   Refused all interview requests by other Sonics as well, Shields
gamely hung in there, building his narrative almost entirely out of
found objects. Snippets of sports-talk shows, bits of postgame
radio analysis, game stories from the local newspapers,
conversations overheard in the supermarket and post office _ all
become grist for Shields's racial mill. His take on basketball and
race seemingly boils down to a few points: that society is obsessed
with black-white issues, whether it admits that or not; that every
reference to skin color, however innocuous, merely scratches the
surface of America's festering racial anxiety; and that power and
sexual potency are the two principal subtexts to the racial
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA, he writes, is ``a place where, without ever
acknowledging it _ and because it's never acknowledged, it's that
much more potent and telling _ white fans and black players enact
and quietly explode virtually every racial issue and tension in the
culture at large. Race, the league's taboo topic, is the league's
true subject.'' Taboo topic? Not if you read other authors on the
subject of NBA basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Later on, Shields asks, ``Is race on my brain, or am I screwed
up? Or is it on everyone else's brain, and am I just taking
notes?''
</P>
<P>
   Readers are free to draw their own conclusions _ ``Black
Planet'' is a book that will either grab you or leave you lusting
for old Celtics-Lakers highlight tapes _ but Shields's note-taking
is idiosyncratic, to say the least. He and his wife do not just
watch the Super Bowl telecast, for instance, they ``watch ourselves
watch the Super Bowl.'' Such an observation poses the question:
What was the over/under on self-referential questions in the
Shields household during the three-hour broadcast?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
