<HEADLINE>
MP3.COM'S COOL NEW SERVICE THREATENS MUSIC INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meet Michael Robertson. With his prep-school sartorial style and
his eager aura, he looks like he's selling chances for the senior
class raffle at, say, Deerfield Academy. But Robertson is pitching
something else entirely. The CEO of the Internet start-up MP3.com
is promising to drag the music business _ and anyone who will hear
his spiel _ into the digital age.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so cool,'' he begins, ``it's going to blow you away.''
He borrows a CD (the Foo Fighters's ``The Color and the Shape'')
and pops it into my computer. One click of the mouse and _ voila! _
the music is instantly available in his on-line music account at
MP3.com. He can listen to it on any computer with Internet access,
any time, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's very cool, much faster and more readily accessible
than other systems that allow you to store digital music files
(called MP3s) on line. You can also purchase CDs from on-line music
vendors and receive a virtual copy in your MP3.com account days
before the CD itself actually arrives on your doorstep. Here's how
it works: MP3.com has compiled a library of 45,000 CDs; when you
purchase a CD or place your own CD into the system, it gives you
access to their digital copies.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one little problem with the Foo Fighters episode.
And what would that be, Mr. Robertson? ``It is piracy,'' Robertson,
32, says, his usually determined voice rising to an almost
evangelical roar. ``People are copying CDs like crazy out there.
The question is: How do you create a system that is as secure as
possible?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that is the question (no doubt the Foo Fighters would
agree). It's also the focus of a copyright infringement lawsuit
filed against MP3.com last week by the Recording Industry
Association of America and the major record labels. For the past
year, the association has had litigation fever, trying to use the
courts to stop the inevitable spread of digital music distribution
over the Internet. It hasn't had much luck, and legal experts
contend that the music industry group doesn't have much chance of
winning this latest lawsuit, either.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't just a case of the musclebound music industry
behemoths taking on the scrawny techno-geeks. (MP3.com went public
last year, and despite losses of $36 million in 1999, the company
is worth almost $2 billion on the stock exchange.) The MP3.com
situation is brewing as the $40 billion music business is
struggling to redefine itself in the midst of unprecedented change.
Upstarts like MP3.com are using new technologies to market and
distribute music on the Internet, tapping into territory recently
controlled by the major record companies. At first, the majors
attempted to stop the rate of change by suing these new start-ups,
but that hasn't worked. Now in addition to filing suit, the big
guys are running around playing catchup, trying to figure out how
to adapt to the technology revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, in fact, is the driving force behind the recent
merger mania in the music business. The America Online-Time Warner
marriage is a no-brainer for the entertainment conglomerate, which
was flailing about trying to create a presence in cyberspace. Time
Warner _ and its subsidiary, Warner Music _ can provide what's
called ``content'' for AOL's subscription base. Likewise, Time
Warner's recent marriage with EMI Group gives the combined company
a gigantic music catalogue _ as in, Madonna meets the Beach Boys.
Internet companies are starving for content, and the two struggling
companies are aiming to gain more clout by joining forces.
</P>
<P>
   One former industry insider isn't impressed. ``They're just
circling their wagons,'' says Al Teller, a former record company
executive who is founder of the Internet music start-up, Atomic
Pop. ``They can all combine into one big major, but this revolution
is going to happen and they're not going to be able to control it.
They may control a huge catalogue, but they're never going to
control the individual artist.''
</P>
<P>
   But if they're not ready to join the revolution, they can still
try to postpone it. ``There is a legitimate fear of piracy, but
there is also a fear of being rendered obsolete,'' says Mark
Lemley, a law professor at the University of California at
Berkeley. ``They're afraid of being left out of the loop, and what
they should really be doing is coming up with their own ways of
distributing music on line.''
</P>
<P>
   And MP3.com's ``very cool'' service may foreshadow be the future
of the music industry. It's free  &UR; today &LR; , but Robertson is hoping
to turn it into a subscription service some day. Consumers will pay
for music the same way they pay for cable television, and as the
technology develops, it will be ubiquitious. `` &UR; Today &LR;  it's the PC,
but  &UR; tomorrow &LR;  it's your Palm Pilot, your cell phone, your watch,''
he says, holding his wristwatch to his ear like a digital Dick
Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Robertson is a visionary: Former industry insiders
who have launched Internet music ventures agree that the old ways
of music distribution (as in record stores) are doomed to become
obsolete. But there's that little piracy problem. Marc Geiger, a
founder of Lollapalooza who is now CEO of the Internet start-up
Artistdirect.com, has long championed the concept of a subscription
service like the one Robertson is offering. ``It's an exciting
idea, but you can't just screw the artist. You can't just screw the
industry,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But MP3.com has, in fact, taken some steps to prevent piracy.
Users can only listen to the music on a computer; they can't
download it to a portable MP3 player. Also, all user accounts are
protected by passwords; no two users can listen to the same account
at the same time. And you must either purchase a new CD or have an
actual physical copy of one (as opposed to a computer file) to add
the music to your account. But we saw what happened with the Foo
Fighters CD, didn't we? What's to stop the kids in the dorm from
passing one CD around to every room on the hall?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, answers Robertson. That's not his problem. ``Piracy
happens all the time.'' And he operates at Internet speed: He's not
about to wait for the plodding recording industry to come up with
some failproof security system to protect artists. ``We are
building the railroad system to run the music,'' he says. ``We
don't own the music. We don't own the rights.''
</P>
<P>
   That's precisely the recording industry's point. But legal
experts contend that the industry would have to sue all the
individuals who violate the copyright law, not the company that
provides the conduit to make it possible. ``These lawsuits are
futile,'' says Lemley. ``They're not going to stop the music from
going on line.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the dilemma. Everybody's right, and everybody's
wrong. Companies like MP3.com (and another fledgling start-up
called Napster.com) are forcing change by launching music
distribution systems that challenge the status quo, yet they're not
exactly protecting artists' rights, despite their protestations to
the contrary. And the record industry folks say they are the
champions of artists' rights, even as they use whatever means
possible to protect the power that enables them to milk profits out
of the artists they represent.
</P>
<P>
   Does this sound like an industry in need of an overhaul? You
bet. But the only thing certain is that change is inevitable.
``There will be events that push this revolution forward, and some
of them of them are going to be ugly,'' says Geiger. So what's the
motto of this revolution? Liberty, egality, piracy? Or give MP3 a
chance?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
