<HEADLINE>
PRIME TIME FOR LINUX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ There are no live penguins at the Jacob Javits
Center. Not like the Linux trade show in San Jose last August,
where a hapless pair of flightless birds was forced to stroll among
badly dressed software developers.
</P>
<P>
   This is the big time _ the first LinuxWorld Expo ever held in
Manhattan. So there were a few more suits and ties, and a
statistically significant uptick in the number of spokesmodels on
the show floor. The sort of thing that happens in an industry that
has begun attracting investment dollars by the billions.
</P>
<P>
   LinuxWorld is still a small show, taking up only a fraction of
the Javits Center. But crammed into that space is just about every
major corporation in the computer industry, except Microsoft Corp.
And nobody seems to miss it _ quite the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   There's vehement anti-Microsoft sentiment here; even users of
Apple Computer Inc.'s Macintosh machines aren't quite so hostile.
No surprise, really. For all its recent success, Apple is still a
niche player with designs on a mere sliver of the computer market.
But as for the goals of the Linux boosters _ well, one of the
booths here sells T-shirts with the motto, ``Total World
Domination.'' These guys figure there's only one company on earth
with the power and the desire to thwart that ambition.
</P>
<P>
   The federal antitrust suit against Microsoft has bought the
Linux loyalists some time. When the Linux boom began in earnest
last year, Microsoft was sweltering under the spotlight. The
company didn't dare crush Linux, as it probably could have. And
judging from the products on display here at Javits, Microsoft will
never have that opportunity again.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at IBM Corp. Here's the world's biggest computer
company, a firm that has made Internet commerce the core of its
business strategy. And now they've put the guy who led the charge,
Irving Wladawsky-Berger, in charge of IBM's Linux strategy. You
think the company's serious about Linux? Me too.
</P>
<P>
   And to prove it, IBM announced a flurry of significant moves. It
has ported its ViaVoice speech recognition software to Linux, so
users will be able to talk to IBM machines. It's giving away Linux
versions of its DB2 database software and Lotus Domino server
software to programmers, so they can use it as a basis for new
Linux applications. IBM's also setting up collaboration with
independent Linux programmers to create software that'll let Linux
run better on laptop computers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Intel Corp., along with IBM and computer hardware
makers like VA Linux Systems, are hard at work making sure that
Linux will run on the next generation of Intel processors, due out
later this year. The chips have a ridiculous name _ Itanium _ but
they're expected to offer a major step up in performance from
today's Pentiums.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Intel officials would be sharing Itanium design
secrets only with Microsoft, and perhaps a few hardware vendors
like Compaq and Hewlett-Packard. But there they were at LinuxWorld,
briefing any geek who cared to listen, and passing out free copies
of Linux software tuned to run on Itanium, so programmers could
start learning how to write code for the new chip.
</P>
<P>
   A delightful theme underlies all this activity. Suddenly, the
world's biggest computer firms are desperate to make nice with a
feisty international community of independent programmers. Linus
Torvalds, who founded the community by writing the Linux software
kernel, marvels at the spectacle. ``It's funny to see how worried
some of these big companies are about being viewed badly by the
community,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, perhaps, but eminently sensible. The rise of Linux has
taught the industry titans that thousands of people will cheerfully
write world-class software for free. Many do it because they need
to solve some problem on their company's computer system. Others
just do it because they want to. Both these groups of benign
hackers will share their genius with the world, at no charge. They
don't even mind when Linux companies like Red Hat Software Inc. run
up a $16 billion market capitalization by reselling the work they
did for free.
</P>
<P>
   No, all the geeks want is to write good code, and to be treated
with respect. Microsoft has a problem in both departments. So the
geeks have gravitated to Linux, and now most of the Fortune 500 is
joining them. Will Microsoft see the light? Frankly, at this point,
it doesn't matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
