<HEADLINE>
MILDEW MAKES ITS MARK ON ROOF SHINGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. All the shingles on my roof and on the roofs of many houses
in the Hampton Roads, Va., area are stained by a dark substance,
flowing down from near the peak to the gutter. I noticed this about
a year ago, and it appears to be getting worse. Just about all
roofs show this stain, regardless of the color of the shingle,
except those of my next-door neighbor and two neighbors across the
street; their shingles are not stained. What is the stain, and how
can I clean it off?
</P>
<P>
   EDWARD WILUSZ, Chesapeake, Va.
</P>
<P>
   A. It's an old story, with an old remedy. The black or dark
streaks on your roof shingles are mold, also called mildew, which
grows on any warm, damp surface. But I am stumped as to why there
are no stains on your neighbors' roofs. Suffice it to say that they
lucked out; the rest of you did not.
</P>
<P>
   To kill this mold and get rid of the streaks, try painting them
with a solution of 1 part household bleach and 3 parts water. If
this does not clean the shingles, the stains are not mold but dirt,
and can be cleaned by washing with a strong solution of Spic and
Span and water. The stains are more obvious on a light roof. They
are also more common in the South, where heat and moisture promote
the growth of mold. But other parts of the country that get a
reasonable amount of rain each year are not immune from the stains.
</P>
<P>
   If the stains clean up with the bleach-and-water solution, you
can keep them away by installing a zinc strip near the ridge, under
the next-to-highest row of shingles, with about 2 inches showing.
Rainwater runs down over this zinc strip, picks up minute particles
of the mold-inhibiting metal, and spreads them over the roof.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy these strips in lumber stores. If yours doesn't
carry them, two brands are Shingle Shield, made by Chicago
Metallic, 800-638-5192; and Z-Stop, made by WESPAC of Seattle,
206-244-4013.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My antique bronze pot is 5 inches high and 6 inches wide,
with two dragons on the edge of the bowl. It is a real antique,
from the 14th century. A year ago, blue spots appeared on the
bronze, and later turned white. What happened?
</P>
<P>
   DAVE LIPKE, Brewster, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The blue spots indicate oxidation of copper in the bronze, or
possibly cobalt, which might be a part of the bronze alloy. I don't
know why they turned white; lime might be the cause, or it might
simply be another step in the oxidation process. Before doing
anything about the spots, I suggest you contact a conservator at
the Museum of Fine Arts. The museum has a marvelous collection of
bronzes, so there should be someone there who can help you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The fiberglass or vinyl bottom of my 12-year-old shower stall
used to be white, but now it's gray, dark gray, black, and white.
I've tried several tub-tile cleaners, chlorine, and scrubbing, with
little improvement. Is it too old for keeping clean, or is there
something I haven't tried?
</P>
<P>
   ANTHONY SCHIRALDI, Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   A. For starters, try straight household bleach (wear skin and
eye protection when working with bleach); I know you said you tried
chlorine, but it is worth trying again, straight. The cleaners you
used were appropriate, but you may not have used them correctly.
Put on the cleaner, let it sit on the surface for five minutes or
longer, then scrub and rinse. You want the cleaner to do its work
of dissolving the dirt before it is scrubbed away.
</P>
<P>
   One of these cleaners may help, too: Simple Green, Clean Shower,
or Soft Scrub with bleach. And here is a homemade trick to try:
Smear on Ivory shampoo, liberally, let it sit for as long as you
like, and scrub and rinse.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's an Armstrong product called New Beginning that
is designed for vinyl floors. It's an extra-strength cleaner and
wax remover, and it just might work on your tired shower floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My backyard is only 7 feet deep and sunless, facing north. It
is hosed daily to clean up after our dog, and it develops a green
coating from the dampness. Other than buying a power washer, what
will get that slimy, smelly coating off?
</P>
<P>
   MRS. L. PELLA, San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   A. I must assume your backyard has some kind of paving, such as
brick or stone. Power washing is your best bet, and I highly
recommend it as fast and easy.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't do that, or don't want to, make a solution of 1
part household bleach and 1 part water. Apply this to the yard, and
it will attack the green stuff, which is algae, related to seaweed.
As you apply the bleach, you must scrub the algae with a bristle
brush, because it will not yield readily to the bleach solution. If
you do this once, and the green stuff returns, more bleach and
water should remove it without further scrubbing. Wear skin and eye
protection when working with bleach.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, once you get it all cleaned up, paint vinegar on the
pavement and in any joints. This could deter the algae for a while.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
