<HEADLINE>
A CAT-ALYST FOR SOLVING FENG SHUI WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a new book, ``Feng Shui for You and Your Cat.'' It's not
a parody, like ``Why Cats Paint'' or ``Dancing With Cats.'' The
author, Alison Daniels, is serious.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels is described on the book's jacket as a regular
contributor to The Art of Feng Shui, a monthly magazine. ``She is
also a cat owner and lover,'' according to this minibiography, ``so
this book is an ideal combination of two of her favorite
subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a stroke of marketing genius. Feng shui and cats. With
scores of cute cat photographs. It's a project made in publishing
heaven, if such a place exists anymore. If only they could have
managed to work in Harry Potter, diet and/or fitness, and maybe
golf, they'd have the bestseller to end all bestsellers. ``Golf
Your Way to Fat-Free Fitness the Feng Shui Way with Harry Potter's
Cat''?
</P>
<P>
   Feng shui, (pronounced ``fung shway''), is the ancient art of
balancing the flow of natural energies to create more harmonious
environments. It has flourished in China for at least 4,000 years,
except from 1949 to 1976, when it was outlawed by Chairman Mao. If
feng shui survived the Cultural Revolution then perhaps it may be
able to survive its cultural exploitation in the West, where lately
I've seen it applied to everything from cosmetics to kitchen
appliances to romance to _ no kidding _ colonic irrigation.
</P>
<P>
   But back to ``Feng Shui for You and Your Cat.''
</P>
<P>
   People spend years studying feng shui. It's a complicated art.
And it's a thriving business. You can spend money engaging a feng
shui expert to come to your home and advise you about how to
improve the flow of energy.
</P>
<P>
   Or, according to Daniels at least, you can consult your cat.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a helpful cat in your house there is no need to hire a
feng shui expert,'' Daniels writes. ``Your cat is a natural
practitioner of feng shui, so use her innate skills to make it work
for you.''
</P>
<P>
   In its most basic form, Daniels says, feng shui involves
moderating energy which is too sluggish (si chi) or too fast-moving
(sha chi) and freeing up healthy energy (sheng chi).
</P>
<P>
   Got that? No? Don't worry, because your cat understands. All you
have to do is follow her around the house and take note of where
she likes to spend her time. According to Daniels, cats are
naturally drawn to areas of negative energy so they can try to
counter, or at least neutralize, its influence.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, you may assume your cat likes to hang out in the
bottom of your closet because it's dark and quiet. But you'd be
wrong. Your cat has located an area of stale energy in the bottom
of your closet and is working to dispel it. Your cat is trying to
tell you that it's time to take drastic action to improve the
energy flow in your closet.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels adds, somewhat gratuitously, that the cat cannot
actually help you clean out your closet, ``only bring attention to
areas that need sorting out.''
</P>
<P>
   Does your cat climb the curtains? You may assume she's playing,
or indulging her destructive impulses but, Daniels writes, she's
actually counteracting the straight lines of the curtains that
speed up the flow of chi. She's telling you that you need curtains
that can be looped back to form an undulating line that slows down
the flow of energy in the room. Good kitty!
</P>
<P>
   Does your cat wind around your legs when you're trying to cook?
Or sit in the middle of the kitchen floor? You probably assume
she's hungry. She's not. She's working to lower the high energy
level in your kitchen, calming the sha chi. The next time you're
fixing dinner and you trip over your cat, thank her. Then ask her,
nicely, to go practice her feng shui in another room.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
