<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5365 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILD-GRIEF-ART-BOS &LR;      02-03 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-GRIEF-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MARIA TROZZI HELPS EDUCATE CHILDREN ABOUT DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two little boys collide on hanging rings at an elementary school
playground.
</P>
<P>
   One boy gets up. The other doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The boy on the ground dies several hours later.
</P>
<P>
   How will classmates of this 7-year-old boy cope with such an
unexpected and incomprehensible loss? After all, lots of children
get hurt on playgrounds _ scratched knees, sprained ankles. But
they don't die.
</P>
<P>
   How will the community respond? Where will they turn for help?
</P>
<P>
   One answer is to call Maria Trozzi, 50, director of the Good
Grief Program at Boston Medical Center and author of the recently
published ``Talking With Children About Loss: Words, Strategies,
and Wisdom to Help Children Cope with Death, Divorce, and Other
Difficult Times.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Superintendent Mary Grassa O'Neill did the day
second-grader Sam Cichello was fatally injured on the playground of
the Tucker School in Milton, Mass. last fall. The next evening,
more than 300 parents gathered in the school gym to hear Trozzi
speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maria was brilliant,'' says Grassa O'Neill. ``She was so
uplifting, so solid in her advice and so positive. She gave
everyone an age-appropriate vocabulary _ `A person doesn't pass on,
he dies. Children fall every day on playgrounds so what happened
here is very, very rare . . . I know because I'm an older person
and I've never heard of this happening.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Trozzi, who has a husband and two daughters, is a former math
teacher and Junior League volunteer who thinks of herself as an
educator, not a grief counselor. She's been counseling since 1996,
when Good Grief moved from its original home in the Judge Baker
Children's Center, a mental health facility affiliated with
Children's Hospital in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meeting with parents and teachers must be done as soon as
possible after a death,'' Trozzi says. ``Young children are
egocentric, so they need to be assured that what happened is not
going to `happen to me.' Kids also must be empowered with enough
concrete information to understand exactly what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   And most important, every loss leaves in its wake the
opportunity for growth. Therefore, it is a time for children to
master coping skills that will give them the resilience to get
through future losses and rejections. ``I can't prevent a
tragedy,'' she says, ``but I can give parents and teachers the
information they need during a crisis. And I do it in a very upbeat
way. That's my signature.''
</P>
<P>
   What she does in her book and in her travels around the country
is demystify a grieving process that moves from understanding the
death itself to being able to live with it.
</P>
<P>
   If Trozzi had her way, a Good Grief program would be in place in
every school, day-care center, hospital, and social service agency
nationwide, assuring that the proper caregivers are in place before
a tragedy occurs. Children need familiar and trusted adults around
them during times of loss, she says, not grief counselors who are
strangers to them.
</P>
<P>
   Trozzi, who earned a master's degree in counseling from Boston
University, is also involved with The Circle, a comprehensive
grief-support group for children ages 5 to 13 that meets weekly.
She's received a three-year grant from Columbia Presbyterian
Babies' and Children's Hospital in New York to develop a
bereavement program for hospital professionals working with acutely
ill children and their families. Next month, the Boston Theological
Institute will honor her with its annual award for people who make
significant contributions in the field of bereavement and loss. And
she's become nationally known (she was contacted and went to
Columbine High School after the massacre) through seminars given
with Dr. T. Berry Brazelton of Boston, the renowned pediatrician
and author.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maria is a remarkable person and always wins every audience
over with her directness and valuable information,'' says
Brazelton.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Barry Zuckerman, chief of pediatrics at Boston University
School of Medicine, calls Trozzi ``a natural leader, very
charismatic and thoughtful.''
</P>
<P>
   She also helps staff members at Boston Medical Center when a
child in their care dies. ``Maria is helping our doctors understand
and share the feelings they hold around the death of a child and
thus preventing permanent barriers,'' Zuckerman says.
</P>
<P>
   Trozzi divides the mourning process into four tasks, originally
defined by her mentor and the creator of the Good Grief program,
the late Dr. Sandra Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The first task is understanding what happened to the person who
died and why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children can't feel the pain of grief unless they have an
honest understanding about what it means to die,'' says Trozzi.
</P>
<P>
   Grandpa did not pass on or go away or go to heaven, and the dog
did not go to sleep. Grandpa and the dog died, which means the body
stopped working, like a machine that can't be fixed. Angels did not
come down and swoop Grandpa away _ a concept that can frighten a
young child and prevent him or her from falling asleep at night.
However, Grandpa's spirit can be in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we explain the physical cause of death, we can add our
beliefs about the spirit and the afterlife,'' says Trozzi.
</P>
<P>
   The second task is grieving or experiencing the painful feelings
associated with death and loss. Children grieve in spurts, Trozzi
writes, ``because they have a limited capacity for tolerating
ambivalent feelings and a lower threshold for psychological pain.''
Later they will mourn anew, regrieve the early loss of a mother,
for example, when they marry or have children or reach the age of
the mother when she died.
</P>
<P>
   The third task is commemorating a death and understanding the
rituals involved. The fourth task is going on.
</P>
<P>
   Children must be able to find an inner place for the person they
have lost. Caregivers can help them find this inner connection by
encouraging them to talk about the person who has died, share
memories, and cherish mementos.
</P>
<P>
   ``When kids block or inhibit the heartache accompanying a loss,
they are more likely to endure persistent psychological or physical
symptoms,'' Trozzi writes.
</P>
<P>
   The writer William Styron, she notes, attributes his
incapacitating bouts with depression to ``incomplete grief'' over
the death of his mother when he was 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until he uncovered the root of his sadness,'' writes Trozzi,
``Styron endured profound mental anguish, used alcohol to excess .
. . and contemplated suicide.'' Once he understood the reasons for
his depression, ``he was able to work through his grief and manage
his feelings in a positive way, which included sharing his
experience with us'' in his 1990 autobiographical book, ``Darkness
Visible.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of her book, Trozzi covers other losses, such
as divorce, growing up in a household with a mentally or physically
disabled parent or sibling, moving to another state, not making the
football team or cheerleading squad, or breaking up with a
girlfriend. She also devotes a chapter to stigmatic deaths from
AIDS, suicide, alcohol, and criminal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Trozzi dedicates her book to her brother, Frank, who began to
suffer unexplained seizures when he was 12 that left him with
mental and physical impairments. His illness had a profound effect
on the family, but Trozzi, who was 8 at the time, did not address
her own powerful emotions until her father died when she was 40.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Trozzi's childhood and adolescence, her household
seemed to revolve around Frank and ``his pills, his erratic
behavior, and his seizures.'' She knew her parents had, in a way,
lost the son who was a promising athlete and student. Upon her
father's death, she understood that she had lost the big brother
she once idolized and had buried her feelings of sadness, worry,
jealousy, embarrassment, and fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had great coping skills,'' she says, ``but I never was truly
in touch with the darker side of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
