<SLUG> BC-IVOR-LISA-KUDROW-IN-HANGING-UP-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAYING `FRIENDS': LISA KUDROW'S DOUBLE LIFE ON THE BIG AND SMALL
SCREENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Lisa Kudrow in
a scene from ``Hanging Up.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``I will never desert my `Friends,''' Lisa Kudrow promises.
 &HT;    The star of NBC's hit series admits that she and the rest of the
show's key cast members are fighting for new contracts after their
current arrangements run out later this year. But the slender
actress denies published stories that she'll quit the television
show which made her a star in order to pursue big-screen
opportunities.
 &HT;    ``We've all made a promise to each other,'' she says. ``The six
of us will continue. No one person will jump. There will either be
none of us leaving or all of us leaving _ either no more `Friends'
or another season with all of us on it.''
 &HT;    Wearing a brown leather jacket over a gray silk blouse and tight
black pants, Kudrow has come to Beverly Hills' Four Seasons Hotel
to talk about her role opposite Meg Ryan and Diane Keaton in the
comedy/drama ``Hanging Up,'' which will open Feb. 18. But the
``Friends'' gossip won't be ignored.
 &HT;    It's been rumored that Kudrow and David Schwimmer will be the
first to walk away. Intensive negotiations have been going on for
the past few weeks as Kudrow, Schwimmer and co-stars Jennifer
Aniston, Courteney Cox Arquette, Matt LeBlanc and Matthew Perry
have made it clear that they want a lot more than their current
$125,000 per episode to continue.
 &HT;    After all, NBC pays the cast members on its other long-running
hit, ``ER,'' roughly double that _ not to mention an occasional $1
million bonus.
 &HT;    But the 36-year-old Kudrow, who plays the show's flaky massage
therapist Phoebe Buffay, insists she's concerned about more than
just a fatter pay check.
 &HT;    ``We've just finished a fantastic season, and we need assurances
from the producers that the quality of the show will continue to be
topnotch,'' she says. ``If we are going to end, then we want it to
be on a high note. We'd hate for them to come to us and say,
`Please leave _ the show is embarrassing.'
 &HT;    ``So we want to know that the stories will continue to be the
best in Hollywood and that everyone on the show stays happy.''
 &HT;    Over the course of the series, the producers have brought in new
characters and famous faces such as supermodel Elle MacPherson, Tom
Selleck and Reese Witherspoon. But Kudrow thinks that such stunts
are actually counterproductive.
 &HT;    ``We've learned it's not as much fun when they bring in someone
new to fall in love with one of us,'' she says. ``Fans really just
want the story lines to revolve around the six of us.
 &HT;    ``I hope that in some future episode the writers don't try and
match Phoebe with Joey,'' she adds. ``It's about the only
combination we haven't had.''
 &HT;    Industry insiders believe that the ``Friends'' cast will get
what they're looking for.
 &HT;    ``Right now we're getting `Friends' for bargain-basement
rates,'' one NBC executive admitted recently, ``and so no one wants
to lose them. Now it all boils down to how much extra money they're
willing to settle for.''
 &HT;    Of the actors, Kudrow holds the best bargaining chips, because
she's had the most success on the big screen, scoring with ``Romy
and Michelle's High School Reunion'' (l997), ``The Opposite of
Sex'' (l998) and _ as shrink Billy Crystal's wife _ ``Analyze
This'' (l999).
 &HT;    Cox Arquette has had hits with the ``Scream'' movies, but their
male co-stars have not done so well, with their films generally
heading straight to video.
 &HT;    Actually, Kudrow says, her biggest incentive to move on is the
strain which television's demanding schedule, coupled with her
movie commitments, puts on her family life. She and husband Michael
Stern, a French advertising executive, have a 2-year-old son,
Julian Murray.
 &HT;    ``If we sign new deals,'' Kudrow says, ``it'll mean that I'll
work 11 months of the year, and it's what I'll have to live with.
But if we all decide that we don't want to come back, it'll be fine
with me and I'll just get on with my life.''
 &HT;    Julian got an early introduction to show business on the set of
``Hanging Up,'' in which Kudrow plays a struggling television
soap-opera actress who is also the bubble-headed younger sister of
Ryan and Keaton.
 &HT;    ``I was able to bring Julian to the set with me and spend time
with him in the morning and again at the end of the day,'' she
says. ``I know the bottom line is that, no matter how much I'm
working, I'm better off than most women in America who work and
have kids they don't see all day.
 &HT;    ``I worry about the future,'' she adds, ``when my son is in
school, and whether I have to take him out of school if I go off on
location. It's something I'll decide when it comes along.''
 &HT;    The movie is based on a book by Delia Ephron, and draws on
Ephron's own experiences with her ailing father (Walter Matthau),
who is depicted in the movie as an eccentric boozer.
 &HT;    Like her character, Kudrow was the youngest of three children,
living with her family in the suburbs of Los Angeles. But she says
her relationship with her father, a doctor, was much different from
her ``Hanging Up'' character's.
 &HT;    ``I had a very special relationship with my father, who has just
retired,'' she recalls. ``I was six and eight years younger than my
brother and sister, and was the apple of my father's eye. But,
because I was so young, they often left me out of things and
overprotected me, which wasn't altogether a bad thing.''
 &HT;    Kudrow and Ryan bonded during the making of the film, and the
veteran actress enthuses over Kudrow's potential for film stardom.
 &HT;    ``Lisa is like great jazz,'' Ryan says. ``You never know how
she's going to pull off her ideas, then something in the chemistry
of her brain turns a line into a little jewel. It's been wonderful
to be around somebody with that talent and expertise.''
 &HT;    When they weren't in front of the cameras, producer Bill
Robinson recalls, the two actresses sat in the dressing room with
their makeup woman, playing around with a ouija board in hope of
contacting spirits.
 &HT;    ``Some of the questions Meg and Lisa asked the board were about
bringing kids up,'' he says. ``Some were about how much Lisa should
ask for in negotiating for a new `Friends' contract.''
 &HT;    Kudrow can be forgiven for her ambivalence about continuing
``Friends.'' After all, she's got plenty more on her plate.
 &HT;    Later this year, for example, she'll be seen in another
big-budget film, ``Numbers,'' directed by that other Ephron,
Delia's sister Nora.
 &HT;    ``It's set in the early '80s,'' Kudrow says. ``I'm a Lotto ball
girl, and John Travolta is a weatherman who tries to fix the
Pennsylvania state lottery.''
 &HT;    Somewhere along the way, Kudrow adds, she'd like to have another
baby.
 &HT;    ``But at the moment there just isn't time,'' she says. ``So
we'll just wait and see.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Hanging Up,'' consult the Sony
Pictures Entertainment Website at www.spe.sony.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
