<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5368 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BOAT-PEOPLE-ART-BOS &LR;      02-03 1840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-PEOPLE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THEY WON'T GIVE UP THE SHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Theirs is a shrink-wrapped existence in which the house
often rocks gently, the wind off the ocean rakes the walls, and
anyone with an ounce of sense adds an extra heater or two during
times like these. Just who would want to live like this? ``The kind
of person who likes to take a cold shower,'' replies Pat Gately,
marina manager of Boston Boat Yard &AMP; Marina in East Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Should she care to venture outside her snug office, Gately can
count 22 boats that are serving as year-round homes to their
owners. And they're not alone. About 160 vessels housing
``liveaboards'' are tied up at a half-dozen marinas in Boston's
inner harbor. These are boating's voluntary left-behinds, the folks
who refuse to abandon their boats from October to May in favor of a
cozy house in the suburbs, or who decline to sail southward in
order to spend winter in a toastier port.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the North Atlantic is literally at their doorstep as
they hunker down in a wide variety of dwellings that range in size
from cramped 22-foot sailboats to relatively palatial 70-foot
powerboats. Says Ilya Goldberg, who lives year-round in East Boston
on a 40-foot sailboat with his wife, Cathy Wolkow: ``It may be a
small boat you live in, but you've got a large backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   Liveaboards in warmer climes have a kind of boat-bum image as
well-tanned ne'er-do-wells and gypsies in Top-Siders. And even the
marinas of Boston Harbor, like many neighborhoods on land, contain
their characters, serious drinkers, and perennial searchers who are
passing the winter here before slipping off to someplace else. As
one local liveaboard points out, the lifestyle seems to hold
particular short-term appeal for recently divorced men.
</P>
<P>
   But peek inside one of these boats during the winter _ after
stepping through a door cut in the heat-shrunk clear plastic that
many owners use for insulation and protection the elements _ and
you'll find, say, an attorney, a medical student, a secretary, a
software developer, a research scientist, a temp, an airline pilot,
and an ironworker. The large majority of local liveaboards, who
range in age from their 20s to their 60s, commute daily to
honest-to-God jobs, often reaching them via the MBTA Inner Harbor
Ferry Service. They also, of course, share a love of boats,
although not necessarily of moving boats: Several sheepishly admit
that they haven't piloted their vessels in years except to annually
move them, come winter, from a dock with a view to a dock that
offers a shorter walk to land.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly few ways of life in New England offer a sharper
contrast between February and August. At Constitution Marina in
Charlestown, the residents of ``E-hood'' _ meaning the summer
socializers of E dock _ are long gone. So are their deck chairs,
grills, and margarita parties. There's no sunset chatter, no
moonlight cruises. During the short, hard days of winter,
liveaboards tend to see no more of each other than a gloved wave on
the way to or from work. Many of the folks who remain on their
boats murmur that, to tell the truth, they're glad to see the
crowds go. ``To a certain extent, it's like living on Cape Cod and
saying goodbye and good riddance to the summer people,'' says Bob
Navin, who lives aboard the 41-foot sailboat Mena at Constitution
Marina with his wife, Dot. ``But, of course, you're happy to see
them come back in May.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this is a lifestyle in which three's a crowd. (At
Constitution Marina, 92 winter liveaboards dwell on 68 boats, an
average of fewer than 1.4 people per vessel.) If you're going to
spend winter on your boat in Boston Harbor, some of the activities
you should perhaps enjoy _ besides making repairs _ are the ones at
which other liveaboards claim expertise: reading, renting videos,
dominos, cribbage, Scrabble, and ordering takeout pizza. And don't
expect your home to be a popular destination for your land-loving
friends _ except, of course, on New Year's Eve, when fireworks
light up the harbor sky. ``I just don't have many visitors in the
winter,'' confesses Michael Dimitruk, who resides alone aboard the
52-foot sloop Enchante in Shipyard Quarters marina in Charlestown.
</P>
<P>
   Few people attempt to raise kids on boats here. Rindy and Andrew
Stangel, who live at Constitution Marina aboard the 36-foot
powerboat Sigrid B with their 13-year-old daughter, Elizabeth, are
an exception. ``It's really about the same as raising a daughter on
land, although learning to walk was interesting,'' Rindy Stangel
muses. ``The big difference is, you're much closer to your child on
a boat. She's right there. Sometimes that's great. Sometimes it's
not.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Elizabeth, a seventh grader at Boston Latin School
who often sleeps on the Sigrid B's deck during the summer, claims
her life isn't really much different from her friends'. She's got
her own bedroom, plenty of Marilyn Manson music, a Sony
Playstation, a guitar, and a stash of ``Goosebumps'' books.
``Sometimes I like it here, because nobody bothers me,'' she says.
``Sometimes I'm bored.''
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, living year-round aboard a boat in Boston can seem
just as idyllic as the names of some of the vessels themselves _
What a Life, for instance, or As Time Goes By. Televisions, VCRs,
stereos, microwave ovens, propane stoves, and laptop computers are
common. Hoses bring fresh water, while telephone lines connect to
the outside world. ``This is no different than sitting in the
living room of a condo, is it?'' asks Lois Darby, who lives aboard
the comfortable, thickly carpeted, 44-foot, two-bedroom motor yacht
Her Weigh with her husband, David, at Shipyard Quarters. Answer:
No, not if you discount the occasional bobbing caused by the wakes
of passing boats.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, almost all liveaboards augment their heating
systems with, say, electric space heaters or even small
diesel-fired furnaces. (Fuel for the latter must be hauled by hand.
And when their diesel furnace quit on Christmas Eve, Goldberg and
Wolkow had to drive it to Rhode Island for repair.) On very cold
days _ hello, Winter of 2000 _ the hoses that bring water sometimes
freeze. So do interior pipes. Occasionally the boats draw so much
power for their supplemental heating that they trip marina circuit
breakers and their electricity goes out. And there are lesser
inconveniences, such as a distinct lack of closet space and having
to use marina showers, laundry facilities, and toilets if your boat
isn't fully equipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first did this, I said to my husband, `I don't want to
camp out,' '' Rindy Stangel says. ``But sometimes it seems like
that's what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   (Docked boats are required to discharge their raw sewage into
either pump-out boats or shoreside facilities. The consensus among
local liveaboards is that more of them do it than used to, but that
the procedure is by no means universal and that some sewage is
dumped into the water.)
</P>
<P>
   Paul Sweetnam, who lives in East Boston in a two-story houseboat
_ actually a housebarge, since it has no engine _ with his wife,
Ann, likens living atop the water to the Longfellow poem about the
little girl with the curl: When she was good she was very, very
good, but when she was bad she was horrid. ``Sooner or later,
something's going to break or something's going to freeze'' is
Sweetnam's theory. ``And it's going to be hard to work on. If you
live in a house, you can put up a ladder. But you can't put a
ladder up to a boat.''
</P>
<P>
   The word most often used when the necessary traits of
liveaboards are discussed is ``self-sufficiency.'' Pat Gately of
Boston Boat Yard &AMP; Marine characterizes liveaboards as loners, and
points out that they can get particularly cranky with one another
as the winter wears on. Ironically, they're also folks who are
eager to lend a hose clamp in an emergency or to keep an eye on a
neighbor's empty boat for a few days. ``They're always very willing
to help each other if a line breaks or something,'' Gately says.
``When something goes wrong, they rally 'round.''
</P>
<P>
   For many liveaboards, staying the winter is a matter of pride.
Cold? Ice? Snow? ``The same snow that falls on us falls on you,''
declares feisty Elliot Hammerman, 63, a widower who lives by
himself on a 44-foot powerboat in East Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a liveaboard why he or she prefers year-round dockside
living, and you'll usually get a mixed bag of answers. Some cite
economics. Indeed, boats tend to offer a cheaper life than
waterfront homes, although they're no bargain when you take living
area into account. (See chart, page XX . For people like Mike Dunn,
who lives at Constitution Marina on the Jalan Jalan with his
girlfriend, Alison Moran, being a liveaboard is the only way he can
afford a 41-foot sailboat. ``I'd never be able to own this boat and
a house at the same time,'' he points out.
</P>
<P>
   Others, of course, simply can't get enough of the water. ``I
just hate being inland,'' offers Bruce Laughon, who is spending his
13th winter at Constitution Marina aboard the 42-foot sailboat
Major Chord with his wife, Karen. ``When I get to Brookline, I get
nervous.'' Besides, inland living doesn't offer panoramic skyline
views spiced with sightings of mergansers, cormorants, swans, and
the occasional harbor seal. Arthur Carey and Elaine Ridings, who
live near the Laughons aboard the houseboat Travesty, say they go
through 100 loaves of bread a week feeding waterfowl.
</P>
<P>
   Carey is one of many liveaboards who like to describe the
principal advantage of their lifestyle this way: ``If you don't
like your neighbors, you can move.'' Liveaboards talk a lot about
having the freedom to come and go as they please, even though many
of them have been parked in the same waters for years. ``You feel
you can cast off your lines and leave and never come back,'' Ilya
Goldberg explains, adding with a smile: ``Not that you ever do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But many dream of it. The Laughons, both retired, say they plan
to leave Boston permanently and set sail for Curacao in July. The
Darbys, who are grandparents, talk of taking off for the Bahamas
within a few years. The Navins, who are approaching retirement age,
say they'd eventually like to keep their boat in Boston during the
summers and use it down south during the winters. (Dunn and Moran,
both in their mid-30s, have a different plan, however: They're
saving to buy a house.)
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the inner harbor's 160 liveaboard boats bob in
the icy water and sway in the frigid wind. Life below decks isn't
impossible, but it's no day at the beach, either. Predicts Bob
Navin as he sits in the main salon of the Mena in the company of
three different types of heating systems: ``We'll have fewer people
living here next winter, I'll guarantee that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
