<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5369 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-ANTIQUES-SHOW-2TAKES-     02-03 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-SHOW-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWSING THE WINTER ANTIQUES SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the winning horse on Derby Day, a single American antique
emerges each January as the iconographic center of a frenzied swirl
of activity. This star is taken to heart as the most treasured
object among the many thousands for sale at the citywide shows and
auctions that run during the 10-day Winter Antiques Show, which
ended here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This year's buzz centered on a 20-pound oak cube from Salem that
more closely resembled the cute little R2-D2 of ``Star Wars'' in
stature than it did last year's more traditional star of the
antique wars, a 9-foot mahogany highboy crafted in Colonial Newport
for a Cambridge minister, and sold at Sotheby's for $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dark, squat, and less than 17 inches tall, the little Pope
Valuables Cabinet awaited its new home directly under the
auctioneer's podium at Christie's in Rockefeller Center Jan. 21.
There were plenty of empty chairs, but observers stood three rows
deep in the back, the better to watch the bidding when Lot 111 came
up. The higher the numbers, the smaller the nod, and being able to
figure out who is actually bidding is a source of pride among
spectators at big-time auctions.
</P>
<P>
   They craned their necks when bidding began at $400,000 and
proceeded swiftly to $950,000. There it paused until a new bidder
broke the million-dollar mark.
</P>
<P>
   This was hallowed ground in furniture circles. Only 23 pieces
had ever broken this barrier. So auctioneer John Hays's voice
abruptly shifted from brisk professional enthusiasm to a hushed
monotone as bidders rhythmically volleyed back and forth, $100,000
on each nod. At $2.4 million, a record price for 17th-century
furniture from any country, the Pope Valuables Cabinet went to Dean
Lahikainen, curator of Decorative Arts at the Peabody Essex Museum
in, of all places, Salem.
</P>
<P>
   The cabinet was the oldest piece of American furniture many
observers had ever seen at auction, and it exuded its own sturdy
charisma. It had survived wilderness, witch trials, and 11
generations in one family without falling prey to a single
handyman's repair efforts or coat of shellack.
</P>
<P>
   ``With its integration of American history and art, it's the
most exciting object we've ever had here,'' marveled Hays, the
Boston-born director of American furniture at Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers embellishing its front referred to 1679,
commemorating the wedding of the original owners, Joseph and
Bathsheba Pope of Salem Village (now Danvers), and it also bore
their initials.
</P>
<P>
   It contained interior draws to hold deeds and jewelry. Humble by
today's standards, it was the height of embellishment in its era,
with spindles, carved S-scrolls, a central starburst, and surviving
touches of red paint as proof of prosperity and refinement in the
face of primitive isolation and dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Prejudice and superstition were also threats. Both Joseph and
Bathsheba were Quakers whose parents had been persecuted for their
faith. And yet the Popes themselves became accusers during the
Salem witch trials, which began in 1692.
</P>
<P>
   According to detailed records, Bathsheba Pope was often taken
with fits that she blamed on the supposed witches. She cried out
during the trial of accused witch Martha Corey and, believing
herself to be under Corey's spell, attacked her. First she threw
her muff, but after it missed its target, she removed her shoe and
successfully struck Corey in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Pope testified against John Proctor, popularized as the
leading role in Arthur Miller's ``The Crucible,'' saying Proctor
had offered to perform an exorcism of the ``Divell'' in exchange
for another man's Indian slave. Hays theorized that the Popes, as
members of a suspect sect, may have sought to avoid becoming
targets themselves by joining ranks with the persecutors. Both
Proctor and Corey were hanged.
</P>
<P>
   The cabinet continued as a witness to history when it descended
along family lines to Cornelius Henry DeLamater of New York City,
who built the metal-plated USS Monitor. After it destroyed the
Confederacy's wooden ship the UCS Merrimack in the Civil War's most
famous naval battle, DeLamater's foundry thrived on the publicity
and he built an estate on Long Island where the cabinet remained
for almost a century.
</P>
<P>
   Last year it was inherited by a boatyard worker on Cape Cod and
his sister, a New Hampshire teacher (they wish to remain
anonymous). It had been in their grandmother's hallway, where it
was referred to as ``The Franklin Cabinet'' though no one knew why.
</P>
<P>
   Curious, they took it to a local historical society for
appraisal. Informed it was from the Pilgrim Century, as
antiquarians call the 1600s, they made a dogged project of tracing
their family genealogy to find the original owners, using the
on-line Mormon Church archives, which have made genealogical
detective work possible for anyone with a home computer. Bathsheba
Pope was, it turned out, an aunt of Benjamin Franklin's.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding the cabinet was too valuable to insure, they
commissioned a copy for themselves and sent the original to
Christie's for auction. No one knew what it would fetch. Three
similar cabinets by Salem maker James Symonds survive, but all are
in museums.
</P>
<P>
   However, Christie's was impressed enough to give the cabinet its
own separate catalog, and, as it turned out, the whispered
expectations of the magic million-dollar mark were exceeded. The
last time a high-quality piece of furniture from the 1600s was
auctioned was way back in 1986, when Sotheby's sold an Essex County
carved oak armchair for $528,000.
</P>
<P>
   After all the excitement of the auction, the little cabinet was
going home. According to Peabody Essex executive director Dan
Monroe, it will soon be on public display.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While age before beauty was the byword at the big auctions, the
Hirschl &AMP; Adler Galleries at 21 E. 70th St. was featuring some
relatively ``new'' Boston pieces.
</P>
<P>
   President Stuart P. Feld has organized what may be the first
exhibition solely devoted to the Boston decorative arts between
1810 and 1840. ``Boston in the Age of Neo-Classicism'' is scheduled
to run through Saturday. It contains light fixtures, silver, and
many fine pieces of furniture from the era, including an 1815
neoclassical rosewood card table on a lyre base with gilt brass toe
caps, casters, and brass inlay lyre ``strings.'' Also especially
handsome is a mahogany armchair with scrolled arms. As a proud
young democracy, Americans were emulating the motifs of classical
Greece, the world's first democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Augmented with Boston paintings from the period, the exhibit
boasts a first-rate catalog written by noted scholar Page Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   Feld has been the leading champion of this neglected period,
when Boston decorative arts were generally low on innovation but
high on craftsmanship because they catered to a discriminating but
very homogeneous ruling class of English descent. As a New York
visitor observed of Boston at the time, ``All these people are of
one race. They behave like members of one family, whereas with us a
crowd is an assembly of all the nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Feld began collecting neoclassical Boston furnishings when he
was a Harvard graduate student in the late 1950s and neoclassic
style was even more out of favor. ``I had an active social life and
I was in and out of many of the great houses of Beacon Hill, but I
saw very little of it there. It was in places like in Magnolia,
Manchester, Gloucester, and Essex,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's still a period that people are struggling with. I
had a customer who said, `This is what I want to buy. But I'm told
that if I'm going to be serious, I have to collect older
furniture.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
