<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5371 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-ANTIQUES-SHOW-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     02-03 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-SHOW-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... older furniture.' ''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The auctions and shows of Americana week in New York are built
around the 10-day run of the 46-year-old Winter Antiques Show,
which draws dealers from Europe and the United States, and patrons
from the nation's social elite. Philanthropist Teresa Heinz, wife
of Senator John Kerry, and American Express president Kenneth I.
Chenault served as this year's honorary cochairpersons.
</P>
<P>
   Since Historic Deerfield was featured three years ago, the show
has proven to be such a great attention-getter for small historical
societies that some 30 are now in negotiations to take part as
well.
</P>
<P>
   This year it was the Nantucket Historical Association's turn.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors entering the ornate gothic Seventh Regiment Armory
(which brings to mind Memorial Hall in Cambridge) were greeted by
photos from the HNA's collection of 45,000 images and displays of
70 Nantucket items. These ranged from the diary of a captain's wife
who accompanied her husband on a five-year whaling voyage to a
portrait of African-American leader Absalom F. Boston (1785-1855),
the first captain of an all-black whaling crew and the man behind
desegregating the Nantucket school system in 1846.
</P>
<P>
   The curators also posted the lyrics of ``The Nantucket Girl's
Song'' (``For a clever sailor husband is so seldom at his home /
That a wife can spend the dollars with a will that's all her
own'').
</P>
<P>
   ``We all just like it,'' explained Aimee E. Newell, curator of
collections. ``Nantucket whalers were away at sea so much that the
island bred some very independent women.''
</P>
<P>
   Spending money, and supporting the East Side House Settlement,
were all part of the show.
</P>
<P>
   The Kenneth W. Rendell Gallery of Madison Avenue featured a
portfolio of 15 letters by Albert Einstein for a cool million, but
a better bargain was a Boston petition from the early 1700s asking
Queen Anne for protection for the Massachusetts fishing fleet from
French military boats. Sold for a mere $8,500 at Guthman Americana
of Westport, it contained many signatures of the city's early
residents, including John Corey and Jeremy Dummer, America's first
silversmiths.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne E. Pratt continued the Nantucket theme with a display of
lightship baskets woven to while away the hours by these floating
lighthouse keepers.
</P>
<P>
   The Monitor popped up again at Hyland Granby Antiques of Hyannis
Port, which had a case of ceremonial swords presented by the
citizens of Boston to Lieutenant Louis Napoleon Stodder, who was
injured by a shell while directing the boat's revolving turret in
its fateful battle with the Merrimack. Some people get Long Island
estates, some people get swords.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To a nonhunter, big money for duck decoys can sound a little
goofy. I prefer diamond jewelry myself. But a brief visit to the
Jan. 22-23 auction of the world's best decoy collection at
Sotheby's found collectors flocking and prices soaring.
</P>
<P>
   A uniquely American folk art made to attract game for hunters
(some decoys are riddled with bullets), duck decoys have enjoyed a
spectacular rise in value. A 1917 decoy by Elmer Crowell, an East
Harwich cranberry farmer and market gunner who hunted waterfowl to
sell the meat, shattered records. Crowell himself sold many of his
carved and painted wooden birds at the turn of the century for $2
apiece, and 50 years ago they could still be bought for $50. The
$684,500 paid for Crowell's ``sleeping Canadian goose'' (a
demonstration decoy that never went near the water) by an anonymous
buyer represented by Boston dealer Stephen B. O'Brien Jr. more than
doubled the previous decoy record of two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The goose was one of several hundred decoys in the collection of
Texan James M. McCleery, which sold for a total of $11 million,
twice the presale estimate. A pathologist who enjoyed falconry and
duck hunting as a youth but was confined to a wheelchair in his 20s
by transverse spinal myelitus, McCleery refocused his passion on
decoys.
</P>
<P>
   He sought out the best and when he fell in love with one he
wouldn't rest until he had bagged it. He left the collecting world
shaking its head when he paid $10,500 for a long-billed curlew
decoy in 1973, when other hobbiests were paying three figures for
decoys. Last week that curlew sold for $354,500. Though McCleery
died last January, he's still making people shake their head.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
