<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, Feb. 3, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Editors &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Friday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-TV (Washington) _ Denying accusations that his office
influenced TV scripts, a White House aide says nevertheless that
anti-drug officials will no longer provide ``guidance'' to
television writers. Still, says Alan Levitt, the Office of National
Drug Control Policy will continue its controversial media campaign
that provides financial incentives for networks to include
anti-drug content in their programs. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   PELOSI-PRESS (Washington) _ Rep. Nancy Pelosi, a featured
entertainer at the annual winter bash for Congress and the press,
is assigned to tell why she isn't running for president. ``I
haven't come to that conclusion yet,'' she jokes. By the Hearst
Newspapers. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ In New Hampshire this week the
voters in both parties gave us a 10-strike, producing two
qualified, responsible candidates in each race and setting up
contests that will properly test their readiness for the
presidency. By MARIANNE MEANS
</P>
