<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-`LIES'-SYRIA-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRIA JOINS CHORUS OF JEWISH HOLOCAUST DENIERS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 600-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ A few short months ago, President Hafez Assad of Syria
and Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel were cloaking each other in
words of honor. Trust, strength, courage. American ``peacemakers''
cooed like children.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the Israeli dead are being brought home from Lebanon
again, their allies destroyed daily, their bombs falling again
around the Lebanese hill villages east of Tyre.
</P>
<P>
   And Tishrin, the Syrian government newspaper that has always
praised President Assad's ``strategic choice'' of peace has joined
the chorus of Jewish Holocaust deniers.
</P>
<P>
   The three Israeli troops, a major and two corporals, killed in a
Hezbollah ambush on Monday provoked the usual demands by soldiers'
mothers for an immediate withdrawal from Lebanon _ which is also,
of course, the demand of Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But the extraordinary editorial in Tishrin seemed designed to
infuriate Israel which, according to the paper, had convened the
Stockholm Holocaust conference to further Jewish ``lies'' about the
Holocaust in the face of ``credible'' voices which questioned it.
</P>
<P>
   Among these voices, Tishrin announced, was the British historian
David Irving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does Israel insist on bringing up this alleged Holocaust
policy?'' Mohamed Kheir al-Wadi, the editor, wrote. ``I believe
Israel and the Zionist organizations have two aims: the first is to
receive more money from Germany and other western establishments on
the pretext of compensation for the Holocaust. The second aim is to
benefit from the myth of the Holocaust and accuse anyone opposed to
Zionism and its expansionist policies of anti-Semitism.''
</P>
<P>
   Zionism, al-Wadi added, ``invents stories about the Holocaust
and exaggerates them to astronomical levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli foreign ministry spokesman said that the article did
not deserve a response although U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright called it ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Syria has long denied the facts of the Jewish genocide,
allowing its own defense minister to run a publishing house which
has printed an Arabic edition of that hoary old forgery, ``The
Protocols of the Elders of Zion.''
</P>
<P>
   When a French academic who has questioned the figure of six
million Jewish dead visited Damascus two years ago, he was warmly
embraced by the foreign minister, Farouk al-Shara _ who last month
conducted peace talks with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrians, it seems, believe the Israelis are betraying their
original offer of a retreat from the occupied Golan Heights by
demanding a peace treaty before withdrawal _ the trap into which
PLO Chairman Yassir Arafat fell.
</P>
<P>
   And when Syria is upset, it gets very angry indeed. Hence its
dismissal of Barak's appeal for Syrian restraint on Hezbollah _
though Israel offered no restraint on its own proxy South Lebanon
Army militia. Hence the continued guerrilla attacks in southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Syria was the location for much of the world's first
genocide, the mass murder of one and a half million Armenians by
the Turks in 1915. Syria does not deny this Holocaust, but Turkey
does _ in exactly the same words used by the Syrians about the
Jewish Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish ambassador to Israel says that ``the myth of the
Armenian Holocaust was created... with the hope that the Armenians
could be rewarded for their `sufferings.''' Al-Wadi says the
``myth'' of the Jewish Holocaust was ``to receive more money... on
the pretext of compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   No mention from al-Wadi of a certain Grand Mufti of Jerusalem
who urged Hitler to prevent the Jews of Europe from reaching
Palestine. Nor from the Turkish ambassador is there a squeak about
Turkey's refusal to join the Allied war against Nazi Germany. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 600-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1405EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5378 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-JERUSALEM-$ADV     02-03 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-JERUSALEM-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEXT ISSUE FOR JERUSALEM: How to resolve the disputed city?
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Feb. 6 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABU DIS, West Bank _ The hulking, unfinished building in this
Arab neighborhood holds mysteries that could help make peace.
</P>
<P>
   For example, what is it for, and just what city is it in?
</P>
<P>
   The $5 million shell, built by the Palestinian Authority, is
called an economic studies center. But inside, it has a two-tiered
auditorium that would make a perfect legislative chamber for, say,
a Palestinian capitol building.
</P>
<P>
   It has a view of the shimmering gold Dome of the Rock Mosque,
smack in the center of Jerusalem. But, the construction was allowed
because it is just over the city line, on West Bank land under
partial Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   If peace requires, however, this building could be in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the map, the line is very thick,'' jokes project engineer
Hussam Musa. ``So, the whole building could be in Jerusalem or it
could be in the West Bank, or both.''
</P>
<P>
   The building is the centerpiece of one plan for settling the
dispute over Jerusalem. Let the Palestinians put their capital
here, the idea goes, and call the city by the Arabic name for
Jerusalem, ``Al Quds'' _ the ``Holy.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly and cautiously this month, negotiators are reviewing
these types of options.
</P>
<P>
   They have kept their talks secret. Leaks of concessions by
either side could send their respective publics into a fury that
would set back the whole process. Recent months have seen trial
balloons floated by minor officials and meetings of academics,
exploring possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlines of the Oslo peace process are approaching. The
outline of a deal for Jerusalem and other remaining major issues is
due this month and a final deal is due in September.
</P>
<P>
   The Feb. 13 deadline will almost surely be missed. But, the
activity hints at the possibility of a peaceful solution for what
many have long considered an unsolvable problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that Jerusalem will be a real impediment,''
said Israeli Minister of Justice Yossi Beilin, who helped conceive
the Abu Dis proposal. ``There are about 107 solutions for
Jerusalem. I'm sure that one of them will be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The plans offer a variety of schemes. Some suggest giving Arab
neighborhoods local control, but keeping them formally under
Israeli sovereignty. Some place the ancient, walled Old City of
Jerusalem under international administration. Some cede land, along
with authority, to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Some, such as the Abu Dis plan, are backed by some Israelis as
the so-called ``expand and share'' concept: Widen Jerusalem's
boundaries, then give parts away.
</P>
<P>
   That approach likely won't work with Palestinians, most of whom
aren't willing to base their national dreams on the ``thick line''
of a map.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem is not a building. Jerusalem is all its holy
sites,'' says 52-year-old Palestinian metalworker Abu Khaled
Aloush. ``If the generation of today cannot liberate Jerusalem,
they will accept what is offered sadly and the coming generation
will liberate it.''
</P>
<P>
   If any plan is accepted, it will have to negotiate the seemingly
irreconcilable positions the two sides have staked out. It will
also likely take a change in public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other facets of the peace negotiations, the question of
Jerusalem is not just a security matter that can be solved by
guards and fences.
</P>
<P>
   For Israelis and Palestinians, Jerusalem is a religious focal
point and a cultural touchstone, as well as a political symbol.
Palestinians say there can be no peace until they have part of
Jerusalem. Israelis say all of Jerusalem is theirs forever.
</P>
<P>
   The city's ancient center, the Old City, is home to the site
where two sacred Jewish temples were built and destroyed before 70
A.D. Jews pray now at the sacred Western Wall near the temple site.
</P>
<P>
   That site itself is now home to the Al-Aqsa Mosque, where the
Muslim prophet Mohammed prayed before he is believed to have
ascended to heaven from a spot nearby, now under the Dome of the
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat stresses Jerusalem as the
fulfillment of the national dream. Most Palestinian offices and
stores hang pictures of the dome.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of Jerusalem's approximately 600,000 people are
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has controlled the western half of Jerusalem since the
1948 war. When the United Nations proposed making it an
international city in 1949, the Israelis decided to firm up their
claim by placing their government there, instead of in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, they have called it their ``eternal capital.'' In
1967, they captured the rest of the city from the Jordanians and it
became commonly called the ``eternal, undivided, capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli pollster Hanoch Smith said that about 85 percent of
Israelis favor keeping Jerusalem completely under Israeli control.
But, he said that majority may soften if a specific plan is offered
and peace is the reward.
</P>
<P>
   The minority has been trying to lay the groundwork for a
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-January, 10 Israelis endorsed a joint statement with
Palestinians, Egyptians and Jordanians calling for a shared city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our belief that there is really no hope for
Palestinian-Israeli peace if the rights of the Palestinians in
Jerusalem are not recognized,'' said Shimon Shamir, a member of the
group who has served as Israel's ambassador to Jordan and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Shamir notes that Israelis used to refuse to deal with the
Palestine Liberation Organization, but now they do. They used to
have a large majority against a Palestinian state, now the country
is split on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a member of Israel's Likud Party, long opposed to
sovereignty for Palestinians in Jerusalem, said he could accept an
Abu Dis-type solution.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament Member Michael Eitan said a government center in Abu
Dis would give Palestinians proximity to Jerusalem without actually
giving them a piece of it.
</P>
<P>
   He was quickly rebuked by others in his party. They said the
plan would endanger the safety of Israelis who, over the years,
have wedged their way between Arab neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrible mistake,'' said Jerusalem Mayor Ehud
Olmert. ``This is an invitation for almost inevitable
confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   For those supporting a Jerusalem compromise, the important thing
was that it was being debated.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
