<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5380 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-03 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AWAITING JUSTICE FROM AL SHARPTON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN LYNCH  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Rev. Al Sharpton was saying one of the cops
publicly apologized to the Diallo family. That's fine. But more
than an apology is required.
</P>
<P>
   What are we going to do _ open the jail, let everybody express
regrets and send them home?
</P>
<P>
   This was Tuesday night at Ristorante Pagliacci. Sharpton was
addressing the leftish Robert F. Kennedy Democratic Club. The topic
was the shooting death of an innocent, unarmed man by four New York
City police officers who are on trial for murder at the Albany
County Courthouse, a few blocks away. Sharpton was at his best _
funny, perceptive. He was right, too. Apologies don't restore
lives. They can help, though.
</P>
<P>
   I raised my hand and asked him, ``When are you going to
apologize to Steve Pagones?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't deserve an apology,'' Sharpton snapped back.
Sharpton said he'd believed a 15-year-old girl. He'd acted in good
faith, he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   What does he think today of Steve Pagones' involvement in the
Tawana Brawley case? That's when the facade cracked. Sharpton
flatly refused to answer.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, this guy addressed a flock of jailbirds at
Riker's Island, the biggest New York City jail. Sharpton pleaded
with these kids _ and that's who Rikers inmates tend to be,
minority kids facing a stacked deck. Life is God's most precious
gift, Sharpton told them. Don't create it carelessly. Don't throw
it away on junk and jive. Be men. They were wise words.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton is a uniquely gifted man _ bright, articulate and
shrewd. At the same time, his career as one of the country's
leading spokesmen for the powerless and the oppressed suffers from
root rot. That's the Tawana Brawley case.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago, near Poughkeepsie, N.Y., the girl went to
visit a boyfriend in prison and stayed away three days. When she
came home, she told her parents that she'd been abducted and raped
by white guys. She was pretty sure they were cops.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Alton Maddox and Vernon Mason, New York City lawyers, and
Sharpton, who served as the public voice of the Brawley family and
its legal team. Before long, this crowd was accusing Pagones, a
young Dutchess County assistant district attorney, of kidnapping
and rape.
</P>
<P>
   Although a grand jury found that Brawley had concocted her
story, Sharpton, Mason and Maddox wouldn't recant their baseless
slander against Pagones. They dared him to sue. Finally, fearing
that neither he nor his family would ever really be safe until he
cleared his name, Pagones did just that.
</P>
<P>
   A civil jury awarded Pagones a judgment of several hundred
thousand dollars. Mason and Maddox, by then barred from the
practice of law, didn't have the money, and Sharpton wasn't about
to come up with it. All Pagones really wanted, though, was
vindication.
</P>
<P>
   None of the three would admit that Pagones had been wronged.
None would do the fair and decent thing on behalf of a man who'd
committed no sin against Tawana Brawley or anybody else.
Ultimately, Pagones lost his government job for pursuing the case.
Then his wife left him, fearful for the safety of their children if
the family stayed together.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sharpton defends the false accusation that literally
ruined the life of an honorable man who'd done no wrong. No matter
what else he has done or will do, good or bad, Sharpton always must
be judged by that shameless denial of justice. Jane Fonda went to
Hanoi. George Wallace stood in the schoolhouse door. Al Sharpton
clings to a fallacious, demonstrably evil charge.
</P>
<P>
   That will be Sharpton's lifelong burden unless he decides,
finally, to set it down, recant the false accusation and get right
with the truth. He won't, though. Sharpton lacks the charity,
integrity and character to grant justice to Pagones.
</P>
<P>
   As Sharpton trains his demonstrators to chant, no justice, no
peace.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
