   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Feb. 4:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VODAFONE-MANNESMANN &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-MANNESMANN (Dusseldorf, Germany) _ Two of Europe's
wireless giants, Vodafone AirTouch of Britain and Mannesmann of
Germany agree to a cross-border combination that would have been
unthinkable just a year ago. The deal _ worth at least $180
billion, the biggest corporate deal ever, topping the $165 billion
deal between AOL and Time Warner _ is the starkest illustration yet
of how far Europe has come in terms of embracing an open, regional
economy and the new technologies that are revolutionizing
communications. Vodafone, which only acquired AirTouch of
California about a year ago, will control the new company, and its
executive Chris Gent, will be chief executive. Mannesmann, which
had fought a hostile bid from Vodafone for more than two months,
ends up getting a slightly larger stake than proposed earlier. By
Edmund L. Andrews and Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-DUSSELDORF (Dusseldorf, Germany) _ Dusseldorf, once a
gritty steel town, has transformed itself into a symbol of the
emerging new Germany economy, in large part because of Mannesmann.
Why this deal illustrates Europe's latest transformation: its
economy is undergoing a wave of takeovers that have crossed borders
and have come without political intervention, and is increasingly
being driven by wireless technology and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Looking at the future of wireless
technology. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-DEAL (Dusseldorf, Germany) _ Looking at the bankers and
how the deal got done. Why Gent and his tactics succeeded, while
Esser's strategy failed. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT-LOSSES (Undated) _ The long end of the Treasury market
continues to surge, with the yield on the 30-year bond now at 6.16
percent. Big Treasury investors who had shorted the long end are
sustaining huge losses. By Gretchen Morgenson and Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ In mid-afternoon trading, stocks were mixed.
While the Dow industrials were down 28 points at 2:10 p.m. EST, the
S&AMP;P 500 index was up 6 and the Nasdaq composite was up 79 points.
The long bond was priced to yield 6.16 percent. By Robert D.
Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-RATES (Paris) _ European Central Bank raises its
benchmark interest rate a quarter point, to 3.25 percent, the
second increase in the bank's history. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-COMPUTERS (Detroit) _ Ford Motor will put Hewlett-Packard
personal computers in the homes of about 350,000 employees
worldwide. The deal also includes a Hewlett-Packard color ink jet
printer and Internet access for $5 a month. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The economic column. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-CONFIRM (Washington) _ The Senate votes to confirm
Alan Greenspan for a fourth term as chairman of the Federal
Reserve. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   EDS-EARNINGS (Dallas) _ Electronic Data Systems reports
fourth-quarter earnings. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-U.S.-BEEF (Geneva) _ Looking at Swiss reaction to the news
that United States officials are investigating the shipment of
American beef to Switzerland last year that contained the illegal
hormone known as DES. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   TIMES-EARNINGS (New York) _ The New York Times reports a 25
percent rise in fourth-quarter earnings, better than the consensus
estimate, as increased advertising demand from both traditional and
new media businesses pushed up revenue. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-POLITICS (Vienna) _ The decision on a coalition
government may be delayed until Friday. The two party leaders,
Haider and Schuessel, sign a declaration called ``Responsibility
for Austria _ A future in the heart of Europe,'' intended to
reassure the European Union and others that new government won't be
racist and anti-Semitic. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Erez Corssing, Gaza Strip) _ Israeli and
Palestinian leaders ended a summit meeting here Thursday in
frustration, still bogged down in disagreement over interim issues
and far from bridging gaps on the thorny final issues that stand
between them and a permanent peace. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-TANKER (Washington) _ Folo on the U.S. stopping a
Russian tanker suspected of smuggling Iraqi oil. By Elizabeth
Becker.
