<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5480 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-NUT-MIXES-HNS &LR;      02-03 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUT-MIXES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GREAT NUT MIXES WITHOUT THE CANDY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget those salted peanut and cereal concoctions, the nut mixes
of the new millennium use pungent herbs and spices and leave out
fillers like cereal and candy.
</P>
<P>
   They're trendy and tasteful, showing up in gourmet catalogs and
wine bars. And, most importantly, they can be made at home leaving
out preservatives that may be found in commercial products.
</P>
<P>
   Making nut mixes is relatively easy. You just need a jellyroll
pan, the nuts of your choosing, some spices, and some oil or butter
to hold it all together.
</P>
<P>
   A jellyroll pan, which is nothing more than a cookie sheet with
one-inch-high sides, is essential equipment for making nut mixes
and comes in handy for toasting nuts as well. The sides of the pan
prevent the nuts from slipping onto the oven floor when you put the
pan in and take it out of the oven.
</P>
<P>
   For best results, purchase nuts that are shelled, peeled and
unsalted. Nut peels tend to be bitter, so you want to avoid them
whenever possible. Salt adds flavor and quite likely will throw off
the delicate balancing act between the taste of the nuts and the
spices if there is too much of it around. For the same reason, some
nut mix recipes call for unsalted butter.
</P>
<P>
   Some health-food and grocery stores sell nuts in bulk. These are
usually less expensive than prepackaged nuts and, since they sell
each type from a separate bin, you have the advantage of being able
to buy just the nuts you like.
</P>
<P>
   Toasting brings out the flavor of nuts, and this step is usually
achieved by baking the nuts after they've been coated with
seasoning. However, in some recipes, like the one for Curried Nuts,
the mixture is dried instead of baked. If you have the time, you
can enhance this recipe by toasting the nuts before they are
coated.
</P>
<P>
   Simply place the nuts on a jellyroll pan and place in a
325-degree oven until they become lightly browned and fragrant,
about 10 minutes. Stir every few minutes to prevent the nuts from
burning.
</P>
<P>
   Store nut mixes in airtight containers in a cool, dark, dry
place.
</P>
<P>
   Some nut mix recipes:
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   SPICED MIXED NUTS
</P>
<P>
   (From http://www.foodwine.com)
</P>
<P>
   1 egg white, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon water
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) jar dry-roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup blanched whole almonds
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup walnut or pecan halves
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon pumpkin pie spice
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine egg white and water. Add nuts, toss to
coat. Combine sugar and spice, sprinkle over the nuts and toss
until well coated. Place nuts in a single layer on lightly greased
jellyroll pan. Bake at 300 degrees for 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the nuts to wax paper; cool. Break up any large
clusters. Store in a covered container.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   GARLIC ALMONDS
</P>
<P>
   (From http://www.foodwine.com)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons hot pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 mashed garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 pound blanched whole almonds
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons seasoned pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dried red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Coat a jellyroll pan with butter.
Sprinkle pan with soy sauce, hot pepper sauce and garlic. Scatter
almonds over sheet and stir till coated. Bake 10 minutes. Sprinkle
with seasoned pepper, pepper flakes and salt. Bake 15 minutes.
Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Will keep in tightly covered container for 3 months.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE SPICED NUTS
</P>
<P>
   (From http://www.foodwine.com)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups pecan halves
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   Spread the pecans on a jellyroll pan. Toast at 275 degrees for
10 minutes. Remove from the oven and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan, combine sugar, orange juice, cinnamon, salt and
cloves. Cook and stir over medium heat to the soft-ball stage (236
degrees). Remove from the heat. Stir in the nuts. Using a slotted
spoon, remove the nuts and spread on wax paper.
</P>
<P>
   Separate and let dry 2 hours. Store in airtight container.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   CURRIED NUTS
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Virginia Hospitality,'' by the Junior League of Hampton
Roads, 1975)
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon powdered ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 pound pecans
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons chutney
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 300 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in a large saucepan. Add curry powder, ginger and
sugar. Remove from heat; add pecans and toss. Add chutney and mix.
</P>
<P>
   Cover a jellyroll pan with plain white paper towels. Place nut
mixture on towels. Place in oven and turn off heat. Leave in oven
to dry, 10 to 15 minutes. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Store in an airtight jar.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   HERBED NUTS
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Tidewater on the Half Shell,'' by the Junior League of
Norfolk-Virginia Beach, 1985)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   Dash hot pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 pound pecan halves
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 300 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Mix butter, sauces and spices. Add pecans and toss until coated.
Place nuts in jellyroll pan. Bake at 300 degrees for 20 to 25
minutes, stirring often.
</P>
</TEXT>
