<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Feb. 4:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VODAFONE-MANNESMANN &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-MANNESMANN (Dusseldorf, Germany) _ Two of Europe's
wireless giants, Vodafone AirTouch of Britain and Mannesmann of
Germany agree to a cross-border combination that would have been
unthinkable just a year ago. The deal _ worth at least $180
billion, the biggest corporate deal ever, topping the $165 billion
deal between AOL and Time Warner _ is the starkest illustration yet
of how far Europe has come in terms of embracing an open, regional
economy and the new technologies that are revolutionizing
communications. Vodafone, which only acquired AirTouch of
California about a year ago, will control the new company, and its
executive Chris Gent, will be chief executive. Mannesmann, which
had fought a hostile bid from Vodafone for more than two months,
ends up getting a slightly larger stake than proposed earlier. By
Edmund L. Andrews and Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-DUSSELDORF (Dusseldorf, Germany) _ Dusseldorf, once a
gritty steel town, has transformed itself into a symbol of the
emerging new Germany economy, in large part because of Mannesmann.
Why this deal illustrates Europe's latest transformation: its
economy is undergoing a wave of takeovers that have crossed borders
and have come without political intervention, and is increasingly
being driven by wireless technology and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Looking at the future of wireless
technology. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-DEAL (Dusseldorf, Germany) _ Looking at the bankers and
how the deal got done. Why Gent and his tactics succeeded, while
Esser's strategy failed. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT-LOSSES (Undated) _ The long end of the Treasury market
continues to surge, with the yield on the 30-year bond now at 6.16
percent. Big Treasury investors who had shorted the long end are
sustaining huge losses. By Gretchen Morgenson and Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
