<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SWEEPS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STAY TUNED: Networks Will Do Anything During Sweeps _ Even Kill
a  Neighbor  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Death comes to ``The Simpsons,'' UPN crushes trucks, Mary and
Rhoda re-emerge at ABC, CBS squeezes an old presidential scandal,
and NBC gambles on 10 hours of pure fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, the February sweeps. The theatrical movie industry has its
summer season, with thunder-dumb, mega-budgeted spectacles, and the
TV industry has the big sweeps months in November, February and
May.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, viewers could count on choice cuts of movie meat
during the sweeps _ ``Shogun,'' ``Masada,'' ``The Winds of War,''
``Lonesome Dove,'' ``War and Remembrance.'' Oh hell, even ``The
Thorn Birds.''
</P>
<P>
   That was before the networks pared their way to skinflint
status. Now, generally speaking, the trick is to get the loudest
bang for the fewest bucks. Look at Fox's addiction to all those
sordid ``reality'' specials.
</P>
<P>
   The February sweeps begin Thursday and last for four weeks. The
month's plumpest program is NBC's ``The 10th Kingdom,'' from
prolific producer Robert Halmi. It begins February 27 and consumes
10 hours over five nights; the last two installments are actually
outside of sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 10th Kingdom'' is the story of a young waitress (Kimberly
Williams) who, with her father (John Larroquette), is transported
from New York to a magical kingdom where an evil queen (Dianne
Wiest) is vying for the throne. Camryn Manheim of ``The Practice''
turns up as, ahem, Snow White, and Ann-Margret is a most elderly
Cinderella.
</P>
<P>
   Whether ``The 10th Kingdom'' is a plum as well as plump remains
to be seen. It must be noted that Lindy De Koven was sacked as
NBC's vice president for movies and miniseries about the time ``The
10th Kingdom'' was delivered to the network, and two months after
``Leprechauns'' and ``Y2K'' fizzled in November. Mere coincidence,
NBC insists.
</P>
<P>
   Other high and low points from the grand tour of the February
sweeps:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sunday, February 6: &LR;  James Coburn stars in ``Missing Pieces,''
a ``Hallmark Hall of Fame'' movie on CBS, as a rancher who flies to
Mexico to investigate the death of his estranged son (Paul Kersey).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Monday, February 7: &LR;  Mary Tyler Moore and Valerie Harper are
reunited, as the same characters they played in ``The Mary Tyler
Moore Show,'' in the ABC movie ``Mary and Rhoda.'' Mary is now a
widowed mother, Rhoda a newly divorced mother.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tuesday, February 8: &LR;  CBS' ``JAG'' begins a two-parter shot on
location in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Friday, February 11: &LR;  Walter Cronkite hosts ``Good Grief,
Charlie Brown: A Tribute to Charles Schulz,'' a television
retrospective on the career of the Peanuts creator, who has cancer
and has relinquished the comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sunday, February 13: &LR;  On Fox, a ``Simpsons'' character is due
to die as a sacrifice to the sweeps god. The likely cartoon corpse
is Maude Flanders, wife of the Simpsons' irritatingly effervescent
neighbor, Ned Flanders.
</P>
<P>
   NBC counters that night with ``Homicide: The Movie.'' Most of
the cast of ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' is reunited for the
movie, which concerns the shooting of Lt. Al Giardello (Yaphet
Kotto).
</P>
<P>
   And CBS presents the first half of a two-part miniseries,
``Sally Hemings: An American Scandal.'' Sam Neill stars as Thomas
Jefferson, and Carmen Ejogo (``Metro'') plays Jefferson's slave and
lover, Sally Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tuesday, February 15: &LR;  The contestants in Fox's ``Who Wants to
Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' are 50 women competing to marry a real
multimillionaire whose identity will be kept secret until the end
of the show. Fox says the two-hour special will culminate in an
actual wedding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wednesday, February 16: &LR;  A JonBenet Ramsey movie was
inevitable, and there are two of them in February. Fox's ``The
JonBenet Ramsey Story'' is based on a Vanity Fair article about the
unsolved murder of the 6-year-old Colorado girl. The stylistic
hitch is that Fox bills this as a ``minimovie,'' because it's only
an hour long. All signs point to a stinker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sunday, February 20: &LR;  Leon (just Leon) stars as Richard
Penniman, otherwise known as rock legend Little Richard, in the NBC
movie ``Little Richard.'' It's the story of the Georgia gospel
singer who hit pay dirt with ``Tutti Frutti'' in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Modine stars that same night in ``Flowers for
Algernon,'' a CBS movie about a ``mentally challenged'' bakery
worker who becomes the subject of a lab experiment to raise his IQ
from 68 to genius level.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tuesday, February 22: &LR;  With muted pride, Fox presents the
self-explanatory ``Banned in America: The World's Sexiest
Television.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wednesday, February 23: &LR;  Rosie O'Donnell hosts ``The 42nd
Annual Grammy Awards'' on CBS. It could be a big night for the
resurgent Bay Area musician Carlos Santana, whose 10 nominations
include record of the year and album of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Fox counters with a live special, ``Robbie Knievel Train Jump
Live'' _ he's supposed to jump over a speeding locomotive on his
motorcycle _ and ``Secrets of Street Magicians Finally Revealed.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sunday, February 27: &LR;  ``The 10th Kingdom'' has plenty of
competition, led by the beginning of the ABC two-part miniseries
``The Beach Boys.'' Kevin Dunn (``Godzilla''), Alley Mills (``The
Wonder Years'') and Frederick Weller head the cast in the story of
the surfer rock group and the Wilson brothers' domineering father.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS miniseries ``Perfect Murder, Perfect Town,'' also
beginning on February 27, is the month's second excursion into the
JonBenet Ramsey case. This one stars Marg Helgenberger as Patsy
Ramsey and veteran character actor Ronny Cox as John Ramsey, and is
based on Lawrence Schiller's best-seller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tuesday, February 29: &LR;  On the next-to-last night of the sweeps,
UPN chimes in with its biggest event of the month. A music special?
A big-time movie? No, silly, it's bigger and better than that. It's
``Monster Trux 2000: The New Thrillennium,'' with grinding wheels
and serious fender bending.
</P>
<P>
   It promises to be more excitement than some Arkansas
11-year-olds can stand. Maybe the winner can be in the next version
of ``Flowers for Algernon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
