<HEADER>
A5495 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-BOOKS-GRISHAM-REVIEW-     02-03 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GRISHAM-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN GRISHAM RUSHES IN WHERE TOM CLANCY TREADS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID KIPEN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reading a John Grisham novel is like driving sleepy. By the end,
we're addled, cramped and sheepishly satisfied with ourselves. We
may have little memory of how we got there, but hey, we made great
time.
</P>
<P>
   Grisham's schizoid, occasionally diverting new novel, ``The
Brethren,'' comes across like a typical Grisham legal thriller
that's been infiltrated by a crack team of Tom Clancy frogmen. It
opens with three disbarred judges in a Florida minimum-security
prison, happily entrapping and blackmailing a series of closeted
gay men through an elaborate pen-pal sting. So far, so
jurisprudential, but wait.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to CIA headquarters, where a gnarled, dying agency director
reminiscent of William Casey is recruiting a nice-looking,
personable enigma from Capitol Hill to jump into the presidential
race. Never mind that Rep. Lake is too late to get on the ballot in
New Hampshire. With the CIA in his corner, he'll have the best
opposition-research team in the business, a fortune in soft money
from defense contractors and a mandate to double the Pentagon
budget by November. To the CIA, readiness _ the military kind _ is
all.
</P>
<P>
   Back and forth ``The Brethren'' flits, from Lake's surging
campaign to the three defrocked judges in the pokey, trawling
through gay personals for likely pigeons. It doesn't take a genius
to figure out that the judges' newest pseudonymous pen pal will
turn out to be Lake in the throes of midlife sexual confusion and
that these three blackmailing ``brethren'' have hooked a fish way
too big for their boat.
</P>
<P>
   No one can fault Grisham for wanting to broaden his brand. We're
told at one point that ``Lake loved Clancy novels,'' and it seems
more than plausible that Grisham loves them, too.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason we read Grisham and Clancy, though, and it's
not for their nuanced characterizations or deathless prose. We read
them because they give the impression of knowing something about
courtrooms and geopolitics, two spheres that make many Americans
feel nervous or stupid or both.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Grisham nor Clancy practices his specialty as well as he
used to, but each does it better than the other ever could, and
we've rewarded them handsomely for it. Grisham on spies? We might
as well read Philip Roth on gentiles or John Cheever on Jews.
</P>
<P>
   So ``The Brethren'' gives us the CIA director saying stuff like,
``We have excellent intelligence. If we react to him, then he'll
know that we know. It's the spy game, Mr. Lake.'' Now, maybe real
spooks really talk like this. Everyone's allowed to sound like
people in books once in a while _ except, unfortunately, people in
books.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a bigger problem at work here, and that's ``The
Brethren's'' utter lack of a hero, or an anti-hero, or even a
lovable loser. Great works of fiction can get by without a single
redeemable character, and often do. Great works of popular fiction,
with very few exceptions, can't. ``The Brethren'' has three judges,
a lawyer, umpteen CIA agents and a few stray politicians, and not
one gives a damn about any of them except himself. In a better book
this might have been funny, or sad, but here it's just redundant.
</P>
<P>
   Be assured, ``The Brethren'' doesn't stink. There's a grin or
two, the legal stuff is borderline convincing, and a couple of the
female characters even get last names.
</P>
<P>
   But Grisham can do better _ or at least he wants to. For proof,
pick up the first installment of his lawyerless novel ``A Painted
House'' in the current issue of the Oxford American: The Southern
Magazine of Good Writing, which Grisham bankrolls from Faulkner's
hometown of Oxford, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   It's way too early to tell whether this ambitious coming-of-age
novel will amount to much. But if it succeeds only in exposing the
work of other contributors, such as Barry Gifford, Rick Bass, Vicki
Covington, Roy Blount Jr. and Billy Collins, to a wider readership,
we should still be grateful that Grisham isn't merely diverting his
royalty checks into one of those Bahamian bank accounts his lawyers
are so fond of.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see Grisham as a kind of Ozarks Salieri, gifted
enough to recognize in others the talent he himself lacks. At least
he's using his power, as Maxwell Smart used to say, ``for niceness,
instead of evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, ``The Brethren'' makes the second best-seller in
less than two years _ after Tom Wolfe's ``A Man in Full'' _ to
perpetuate the notion that political operatives still walk into
churches on election day and buy votes for cash on the barrelhead.
Millions of readers have now imbibed this idea from two of our most
popular novelists. With November just nine months away, and no
shortage of nice-looking, personable enigmas on the ballot, does
nobody else wonder exactly how apocryphal this particular urban
legend is?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BRETHREN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By John Grisham &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Doubleday; 366 pages; $27.95 &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
