<SLUG> BC-MARKETING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD DREAMS LEAD TO NEW WEB IDEA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG HASSELL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After he chalked up his 50th birthday, Joel Cohen knew
something had to give.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through career menopause,'' said Cohen, who has toiled
in the advertising and marketing vineyard for the past 25 years.
``The advertising business is always a battle. Your main goal is to
bring in revenues, no matter how. You'll go after any client to get
them.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that relentless pursuit, Cohen was spending all
of his days working on things that needed to be done. He spent very
little time doing things that he actually wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't having any fun,'' he confesses. ``I wasn't doing the
things I had dreamed about when I started out in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of muddling through until retirement, Cohen decided to
find his way back to his original career objectives. Two years ago,
he sold his interest in a small Houston advertising agency and set
out to find a new path to reach an old but unachieved objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made up a dream list of things that would make me happy,
make me money and help me achieve a balance in my personal and
private life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`DREAM PLAN' GUIDES ACTIONS &QL; 
 &QL; 
The first priority was to make a ``dream plan,'' a short list of
things Cohen really wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   Item One: Spend more time on restaurant marketing, an area he
always found to be interesting and rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   Item Two: Do some hockey marketing. A native Canadian, Cohen
wanted an excuse to indulge his love of hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Item Three: Conduct marketing workshops and speaking
engagements.
</P>
<P>
   Item Four: Jump on the Internet bandwagon and find a way to make
technology work for him.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen has made strides at making each objective a reality, but
it is chasing after Item Four that prompted Cohen to do something
groundbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started researching ad agencies on the Web, and very few
sites came up in my searches,'' Cohen said. ``I thought that was
strange.''
</P>
<P>
   So Cohen launched Americanadagencies.com, a listing of Web sites
for agencies in 20 U.S. cities. Agencies sign up for no charge _
unlike many other directories _ and Cohen looks to make his money
off banner ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think its a great idea,'' said Alex Lopez Negrete, who owns
a Houston agency called Lopez Negrete Communications. ``In the
future, clients will want to select agencies in a new way. They
will depend less on the rumor mill and do more of their own
research.''
</P>
<P>
   By using stealthy, discreet methods such as online searches,
clients can avoid attracting a flurry of unwanted attention _
including from legions of hungry agencies eager to snap up any new
business that's up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's healthy for a client to be able to learn what its options
are,'' Lopez Negrete said. ``We agencies like to wave the
e-commerce flag, but you know, that same logic applies to our
business, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HOUSTON SLOW TO RESPOND &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, only 10 agencies _ all of them on the small side _
have signed up with Americanadagencies.com. Oddly, the response has
been much stronger away from Cohen's hometown. It has been
especially strong in Atlanta, Chicago and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The idea did not catch on in Tampa, Fla., or Nashville and
Memphis, Tenn. Cohen shut down the fledgling attempts to create
directories in those midsized cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attitude is, `Why not?''' said Rick Sterling, a principal
owner of the Boulder, Colo.-based Sterling-Rice Group. ``It doesn't
cost us anything. It is a potential source for new business for us.
We got into it as an experiment. It's too early to say how much
business we will ultimately get.''
</P>
<P>
   When combining all of his different business pursuits, Cohen
said he is able to make more income than he did in traditional
agency work. He works for a number of restaurants, a hockey team in
Toledo, Ohio, and gets regular speaking gigs. Better still, he is
having more fun than he used to.
</P>
<P>
   However, what may be more important: Cohen has radically altered
the way he approaches marketing work. He routinely gives advice
that he would have considered heretical 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I no longer do marketing plans. I think they are a waste of
time. They end up in some ring binder, stored on some dusty shelf.
No one ever looks at them,'' Cohen said. ``Now I do `dream plans.'
I ask a client to determine what they want, in what timeframe they
expect to get it, and how they plan to get there. It is amazing how
much that clarifies their thinking. Their eyes actually light up,
because it gets them back to what they wanted to accomplish in the
first place.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
