<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR MIKE LEIGH ON `TOPSY-TURVY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dictionary defines topsy-turvy as ``turned upside down.''
That's how devotees of director Mike Leigh's movies may feel when
they see ``Topsy-Turvy.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that this delicious Victorian-era film about operetta
masters Gilbert and Sullivan will cause any upset. It's a joy from
start to finish, even though the leisurely pacing and minute
details are not anything like the typical U.S. movie.
</P>
<P>
   But dedicated followers of Leigh's very British pictures, such
as ``Secrets &AMP; Lies,'' ``Naked'' and even the recent _ and
relatively upbeat _ ``Career Girls,'' have come to expect dark,
low-budget contemporary films about folks trapped in bleak,
working-class lives.
</P>
<P>
   That's not what they'll find in this colorful bonbon with period
costumes and a lot of clever, understated wit.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1884-85, ``Topsy-Turvy'' follows the famous duo of
comic-opera librettist William S. Gilbert (Jim Broadbent) and
composer Arthur Sullivan (Allan Corduner) through a crisis in their
association. It begins with the lukewarm reception of their
``Princess Ida'' and ends with the creation of ``The Mikado,''
perhaps their most popular and enduring work.
</P>
<P>
   Though just now arriving in most cities, ``Topsy-Turvy'' has
already won best-director and best-film awards for 1999 from both
the New York Film Critics Circle and the National Society of Film
Critics.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Leigh looks at everything in great detail in
``Topsy-Turvy,'' with long and exacting conversations, often over
obscure subjects. But the film's humor is seldom grim, often
sprightly. The detail includes wonderful bits of Victorian life,
such as use of newly invented fountain pens or telephones.
</P>
<P>
   In a call from Los Angeles, Leigh argues that ``Topsy-Turvy'' is
not so very different from what he always does.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you scrape away the very top layer of Topsy-Turvy, you'll
find a regular Mike Leigh film going on underneath the surface,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tension between people enjoying themselves and how tough
life is, is a kind of ongoing theme and preoccupation with me. This
is a film about people trying to give people a bit of joy in their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Leigh admits he's not surprised that his regular viewers
were caught off guard by ``Topsy-Turvy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of the anarchy of doing it, really,'' he says,
sounding quite pleased with himself. ``'Cause I knew everyone would
be surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Why Gilbert and Sullivan? Because he admires their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly couldn't make the film if I wasn't reasonably fond
of them,'' Leigh says.
</P>
<P>
   But his real interest was for the period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gilbert and Sullivan were part of a Victorian culture that
hung in the air when I was growing up in the 1940s and 1950s in
Manchester, which is a great Victorian city,'' the 56-year-old
filmmaker says. ``I read Victorian books and was surrounded by
Victorian architecture and was taught by people born in Victorian
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also wanted to subvert the `period film' by approaching it
in the way I approached contemporary material. I thought it would
be, in some healthy and perhaps naughty way, a good notion to
subvert a `chocolate box' subject.''
</P>
<P>
   As a filmmaker and entertainer, Leigh had a more personal reason
to do a backstage theater story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make a movie about us _ we who, you know, suffer
to hell and back in the cause of amusing other people,'' he says,
chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   In that part of the film, the message seems to be that the more
things change, the more they stay the same. The backstage worries
and conflicts and onstage rivalries would seem familiar to actors
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' Leigh says. ``The main difference between now
and then is that actors and actresses were ladies and gentlemen. I
love that they rehearsed completely done up in their street finery.
Whereas today's actors would show up in work togs. But at the end
of the day, actors are actors.''
</P>
<P>
   And any modern filmmaker would recognize the eternal conflict
that goes on between those putting up the money for a production
and the artists creating it. Gilbert and Sullivan's backers wanted
the Victorian version of ``more sex and violence'' and a happy
ending.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps only purists will care, but Leigh says the film is
faithful to the truth. Mostly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few cheats. It doesn't pretend to be a
documentary,'' he said. ``I'm more concerned with distilling the
essence of the thing. But as it happens, the main thrust of what
happened in 1884-85, from the opening of ''Princess Ida`` through
''The Mikado,`` is pretty much what happens in the movie, with a
few modifications and simplifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Research was intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name it, we were onto it,'' Leigh says. ``I took on a
full-time researcher, who was on it for 18 months. We built a
detailed resource library and were in constant contact with all the
experts everywhere _ quite a lot of whom are on this side of the
Atlantic, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   From the research came not only information about the
characters, but also the period detail, which adds so much to the
texture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most period films, because they are adaptations from novels
and things, don't afford the possibility to enjoy the feeling of
what it was actually like. In that period, there was a sense of
looking forward to the 20th century and a sense of modernity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only have we got the telephone and pen, but also the
modern talk. At one point Sullivan's mistress says, `After all, it
is 1885.'''
</P>
<P>
   Leigh films are famed for the director's collaborative approach
to writing. He begins work with his actors without a script. But
rather than improvise on camera as, say, director John Cassavettes
liked to do, Leigh and his actors improvise during a long rehearsal
process, getting most of their dialogue set before the cameras
roll.
</P>
<P>
   For this film, so carefully constructed, carefully researched,
with a very definite story arc and resolution, it is natural to
assume that this time Leigh used a different approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked on it exactly the same way as usual,'' Leigh insists.
``There was no script.''
</P>
<P>
   By that, Leigh means no script when he began calling the
principal cast together for rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he adds, ``we rehearsed it for seven months.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1529EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
