<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5522 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      02-03 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY'S `TARZAN' DAZZLES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `TARZAN'
</P>
<P>
   Movies have mangled Edgar Rice Burroughs' Tarzan saga ever since
the silent era.
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs wrote 24 adventure novels about a marooned boy, raised
by African apes, who became ``Lord of the Jungle'' _ as well as a
member of the British House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs' Tarzan _ also known as John Clayton, Lord Greystoke _
was a noble, articulate man with wealth and sprawling estates, not
a savage saying ``Me Tarzan,'' as in the early films.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Burroughs immerse Tarzan in such cruel violence and
somber suffering as in 1984's ``Greystoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with its customary kids' bent, Disney has given justice to
the jungle hero. Its animated ``Tarzan'' sticks closely to the
character's origin in story and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The animation dazzles, even if it's prone to hyperbolic
extremes. Burroughs' Tarzan never glided down branches like a
skateboarder. But he was larger than life.
</P>
<P>
   The settings also are spectacular. ``Tarzan's'' verdant vistas
are some of the most handsome backgrounds of Disney's modern era.
</P>
<P>
   The story also is ably driven by Phil Collins' fine pop-rock
songs. No characters sing them _ Collins does. With strong lyrics,
they provide offscreen musical enhancement for the plot and action.
</P>
<P>
   The voice actors are excellent, including Tony Goldwyn as the
grown Tarzan (for the film's first 24 minutes, Tarzan is a child)
and Lance Henrikson and Glenn Close as Tarzan's adoptive ape
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all is Minnie Driver as Jane, the intrepid traveler with
whom Tarzan falls in love. Driver gives the character more
personality than many live-action actors provide.
</P>
<P>
   Not so grand is Rosie O'Donnell as Terk, Tarzan's smart-aleck
ape pal from childhood. Her contemporary sass is jarring for an
otherwise earnest tale, which also happens to be a period piece.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the animals are humanized and sympathetic. Exceptions
are the large jungle cats, whose vicious attacks go far beyond
predatory needs.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they are reduced to heinous villains, which subverts
Burroughs' central premise: Animals are actually civilized, while
humans are the most dangerous beings _ the only creatures who kill
for pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's oversimplifications also extend to an overstated,
pompous, gun-happy hunter. He's an irritating character, much in
the mindless, macho mold of Gaston from ``Beauty and the Beast.''
</P>
<P>
   But these are quibbles. This ``Tarzan'' largely roars and soars
_ especially on DVD, where Disney has provided the most extras for
any of its animated theatrical films.
</P>
<P>
   The studio has reissued eight such films on DVD, where they've
gained at most a trailer or music video.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Tarzan'' is Disney's first new animated film to hit the
home market on DVD at the same time as VHS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan's'' DVD has enough extra material to keep kids occupied
far beyond the film's 88-minute running time.
</P>
<P>
   One feature is a trivia game _ best played after watching the
film _ in which youngsters can choose an answer from three options
to questions such as, ``What object does a baby gorilla take from
Jane?''
</P>
<P>
   You can click on the DVD's remote control to select an answer.
If it's wrong, an elephant will appear to trumpet noisily, or apes
will laugh. If it's correct, Tarzan appears to give his jungle
yell. After about 20 questions, you get a score and rating.
</P>
<P>
   Another addition is a ``Read-Along Story,'' in which the
``Tarzan'' tale is condensed and presented page-by-page in
illustrated book form, with words on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Kids have the option of reading the words themselves or having
them read by an off-screen narrator.
</P>
<P>
   Also featured are the original theatrical trailer, Collins'
music video for the song ``Strangers Like Me'' and a three-minute
clip on Collins recording ``Trashin' the Camp'' with 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   Discs also offer the film in the wide-screen format and have
audio options for Spanish- and French-language tracks and subtitle
options in English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Also, don't miss previews of coming attractions. These include a
five-minute scene from Disney's May release of ``Dinosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with its invasive humans, ``Tarzan'' has a similar purity
and naturalism. It's a classic tale _ not just of adventures, but
of a human bonding with nature.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, G, Disney, CC, VHS $26.99, DVD $34.99
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE `INSIDER' STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're a fan of ``The Insider'' and its revelations of
tobacco-industry conspiracies, put this in your pipe and smoke it:
The 2 1/2-hour film will be even longer when it hits DVD.
</P>
<P>
   Director Michael Mann already has re-edited his movie, adding
scenes for its DVD release later this year and its eventual TV
showings.
</P>
<P>
   On DVD, the extra footage will be separate from the theatrical
cut. On television, it will be worked into the film, to be shown
over two nights.
</P>
<P>
   Mann also revised his 1992 film ``Last of the Mohicans'' for a
recent DVD release (Fox, $34.98), trimming some scenes while adding
others. The resulting movie runs four minutes longer and, Mann
believes, tells a stronger story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE REAL-LIFE `BOYS' STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now that Hilary Swank has won a Golden Globe for ``Boys Don't
Cry,'' you can check out a documentary on the life behind it.
</P>
<P>
   New in stores from Docurama is ``The Brandon Teena Story''
(unrated, VHS $24.95, DVD $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   Shot over four years in Nebraska, the 88-minute film tells the
real-life story of the young woman who posed as a man, dated women
and was persecuted and murdered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys Don't Cry'' does not yet have a video release date.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`JUMANJI' FOR COLLECTORS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robin Williams' ``Jumanji'' has a new ``Collector's Series''
edition on DVD costing $27.95.
</P>
<P>
   The disc includes a making-of documentary, audio commentary, an
art gallery, an isolated music score, a still gallery, storyboards,
talent files, theatrical trailers and featurettes on the fantasy
film's effects and production design.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DEPARDIEU'S `COUNT' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Depardieu's ``The Count of Monte Cristo'' is new in a
four-tape, eight-hour boxed set for $89.98 and a two-disc DVD set
for $59.98.
</P>
<P>
   Also new on DVD is the more than six-hour ``Horatio
Hornblower,'' a four-disc set from A&AMP;E costing $59.95.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`FALCON' SOARS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Maltese Falcon,'' one of the greatest detective films in
history, has a new video edition on tape ($19.98) and DVD ($24.98).
</P>
<P>
   The latter also has a documentary and theatrical trailers.
</P>
<P>
