 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of FRIDAY, Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-MUSIC (New York) _ The world's music has never been more
accessible, speeded to new ears by everything from jet travel to
the Internet. And the whole world comes to New York: if not in
person, then through its songs. Onstage or on CD's, music from
far-flung places offers easy transport to distant lands and times.
The Babel of different musical languages promises not strife but
diverse pleasures, available amazingly close to home. This is the
second annual survey of world-music albums released in the last
year. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MET-EVANS-PHOTOS (New York) _ ``His general note is lyrical
understanding of the street, trained observation of it, special
feeling for patina, eye for revealing detail, over all of which is
thrown a poetry.'' That's the photographer Walker Evans, writing in
1931 about Atget. Later, lecturing in 1964 about Atget and also
about Mathew Brady, another hero, he projected a group of the penny
picture postcards he had collected since he was a child. ``Can you
imagine anything more?'' he asked his audience about his anonymous
little hand-colored images of small-town main streets and trolley
cars. ``A conglomeration of hideous things that come together by
casting a spell of _ I can't call it beauty, but of a certain kind
of silent poetry.'' Twice, poetry. That was what Evans was after in
his own photographs, a poetry that you couldn't call beauty, not
conventional beauty anyway, an art inspired by vernacular subjects
and aspiring to the natural dignity of the street. As the Met's
excellent new retrospective of him reiterates, to the end of his
life (he died in 1975, at 72), Evans had this goal, which in his
case became a distinctly American project. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ENGLAND-CAMPUSES (Undated) _ When winter comes to other
cities of the world, like Helsinki or St. Petersburg, where snows
fall almost daily, the hushed atmosphere of the streets in their
winter whiteness is broken only by the muffled sounds of city life.
Magical winters like these are so rare in New York City that they
form precious memories for people who treasure bundling up for the
adventure in the otherwise quiet month of February before the
awakening of spring. But there is no need to pine. Skiers are not
the only ones who can travel to find ideal snow conditions. For
people whose favorite winter sport is not skiing but hiking along
woodland paths or simply walking on streets in a small town after a
blizzard, to recapture the crunch of snow underfoot that so quickly
disappears in the city, the best choice is to journey to a
university or college town in New England. By Paula Deitz.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move as a travel story, with a ``t'' code.)
</P>
