<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5531 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-GAY-DAD-HNS &LR;      02-03 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GAY-DAD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY DAD: WHAT'S IN A NAME? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Gay Dad.
</P>
<P>
   Give a band a volatile name, and a trail of trials is bound to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of homosexuality within the British band. Suggestions
that Gay Dad isn't really a band at all, but simply a record-label
tool for shock value. Accusations that Gay Dad vocalist Cliff Jones
is actually a journalist, and the band is his fiendish attempt at a
story.
</P>
<P>
   Check. Check. And check. All of these have been trial-ballooned
as sordid buffet gossip for the appetites of the British tabloid
press, according to Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Elton John supposedly loved Gay Dad's dance-pop music, but
thought the band was called Gay Dog. Faux-punks the Stranglers _ in
an act of shameful unpunk behavior _ allegedly kicked Gay Dad off
its tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they weren't going to have a band called `gay'
anything on the road with them,'' Jones says.
</P>
<P>
   If Gay Dad were a scam, it already would have produced the
Spinal Tap-like mayhem many have accused it of. The Brit-pop band
isn't a hoax and has a hit single, ``To Earth With Love,'' to prove
it. A band can't open for Chrissie Hynde and the Pretenders, as Gay
Dad is doing in Houston, if it isn't legit.
</P>
<P>
   Gay Dad's members would love nothing more than for the hubbub
about its name to go away, but they aren't willing to change it to
get there.
</P>
<P>
   To surmise that the point of a name like Gay Dad is to make some
statement about homosexuality or family values is to miss the point
completely. None of the band's members are gay; only one is a dad.
</P>
<P>
   Gay Dad is more like a barometer _ a two-word manifesto stating
that when the world accepts a name like that, we will all be in a
better place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really about being gay. It just has a rhythm that I
love,'' Jones says. ``Blur. Oasis. Pulp. You might as well be
called washing powder. None of them makes a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Allegations that Gay Dad is a hoax band began about a year ago
when a vinyl promo of ``To Earth With Love,'' meant to get the band
a little exposure, started getting frequent spins on English radio
as if it were a single. It soon went Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gay Dad was in the studio laying down the tracks
that would become its debut album, ``Leisure Noise,'' and was
virtually unknown. Jones surmises that the British music media _
which love to control what's listened to and when _ weren't ready
for the band's radio coup d'etat, so they tried to muzzle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We snuck up on the music press, and they didn't appreciate
it,'' Jones says. ``It happened without their permission, so they
wrote a lot of stuff that wasn't true.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones could be passed off as just another rock star peeved at
the press, except that before he was the interviewee, he had a side
career as an interviewer; he wrote some music stories for such
magazines as The Face and Mojo. He is quick to point out that he
never really considered himself a journalist, but wrote music
stories simply because he had access to bands and he needed the
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a musician who happened to get into writing because I
couldn't make anything being a musician,'' Jones says. ``It was how
I paid rent and kept Gay Dad alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's on the other side of the pen and page, how would
he go about an interview with himself?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd ask myself those questions that are really personal,''
Jones laughs. ``Then I'd probably walk out of the room.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth on Gay Dad is almost as interesting as the fiction.
The band was formed by Jones and drummer Nicholas ``Baz'' Crowe
around 1994. Bassist Nigel Hoyle was a medical student; another
member, now gone from the band, was a struggling architect; and
Jones was writing music articles.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, another band member sang lead. It wasn't
until Jones, who plays guitar, also took over vocals that Gay Dad
gained recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know I was a singer, and some would still claim that
I'm not,'' Jones says. ``But the other guy didn't have any soul and
couldn't sing, and I had been writing songs and singing to myself.
I got encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   A favorite Gay Dad myth is that Andrew Loog Oldham, longtime
manager and producer of the Rolling Stones, nearly destroyed the
band with a disastrous mid-'90s recording session.
</P>
<P>
   As Jones tells the story, ``Oldham and (producer Tony) Calder
sat in on one of our sessions and just stared straight ahead with
sunglasses on. At one point they got up, said, `Keep playing the
rock operas, boys,' and walked out,'' says Jones. ``The sessions
were a problem, but it was because our singer at the time couldn't
sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay Dad broke up shortly after the session and reformed minutes
later with Jones taking over vocals. It's interesting that Oldham
referred to the band's songs as ``rock operas.'' ``Leisure Time''
is much more about quick pop hits than a Queen-like concept album.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the recording studio, the band felt pressured after
``To Earth With Love'' became a hit. The song is a burst of British
Invasion jangle pop that doesn't reflect the rest of ``Leisure
Time'' at all. ``Joy'' is a disco-meets-Deee-Lite dance song, while
``Black Ghost'' is a think piece that Jones describes as a ``German
industrial band playing the Eagles.''
</P>
<P>
   Only on ``Dimstar'' does Jones show any penchant for howling
like Freddie Mercury. It's no ``Bohemian Rhapsody,'' but he doesn't
do a half-bad imitation.
</P>
<P>
   The band was nervous about how ``Leisure Time'' would be
received, but has no regrets about its diversity. After a year of
Backstreet Boys and Britney Spears, he says change is exactly what
radio needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick of the boy-band bollocks,'' Jones declares. ``The
time has to be over for the neutral pop star. They are like pizza
with different toppings, but they're still pizza.''
</P>
<P>
   Sort of like All Pizza Radio?
</P>
<P>
   Jones gets excited at the prospect: ``That's what I'm saying.
It's perfect. I'm naming a B-side `All Pizza Radio.' Can I have
that?''
</P>
<P>
   OK, a small thanks in the liner notes is all I ask.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Michael D. Clark can be online at michael.d.clark(at)chron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
