<HEADER>
A5539 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-KIDS-HALL-HNS &LR;      02-03 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-HALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S KIDS' STUFF TO `KIDS IN THE HALL' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editor's note: Reporter Sherry Thomas took a backstage look at the
Kids in the Hall and found plenty of zany Canadian sketch comedy
and even got a little time in the spotlight herself. The following
is her account of her adventure.) 
 
By SHERRY THOMAS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Dave Foley's dressing-room door is locked _ tight.
That means you won't be rehearsing the Mr. Heavyfoot usher sketch
like you planned. That means you're nervous.
</P>
<P>
   It's Friday night, and the Kids are in their Hall. Massey Hall.
This is Toronto _ the fourth stop on the troupe's 25-city North
American reunion tour. The sold-out show, ``Kids in the Hall 2000:
Same Guys ... Different Dresses,'' hits Houston on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, thousands of Kids worshipers (some in kilts and green
hair) queue up to pay homage to the drag gods of Canadian sketch
comedy. These petulant, post-punk pilgrims have been watching
Foley, Bruce McCulloch, Scott Thompson, Kevin McDonald and Mark
McKinney since their live-performance days at the Rivoli on Queen
Street.
</P>
<P>
   That's pre-Lorne Michaels. Pre-HBO. Back when the Kids in the
Hall really were just a bunch of warped kids skewering life in
suburbia, not 30- and 40-something movie and TV stars.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the nice guy at the red door chats you up as you park it
on a hard vinyl chair. In a minute, they'll call you for a
run-through. But for now, you feel like one of the namesakes, one
of the ``kids'' who used to line the halls of 1950 comedy shows,
waiting to pitch their jokes to stars. Only you're dressed like an
usher. Black pants, no pockets, black DKNY brogues and a
no-nonsense white blouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You came all the way from Houston to see these guys?'' the
security guy says.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you tell him. The Kids are big in the States. Besides, not
every Kids fan gets to be a Kid for a day. Gets to work with Foley,
now a hotshot Hollywood star (``Newsradio,'' ``Blast From the
Past,'' ``Dick'' ... ) with a six-figure NBC pilot deal in the
works.
</P>
<P>
   You fiddle with your pen and paper. Finally, they fetch you.
Walking up the stairs and through the hallowed portals of the
backstage area, you pass ``Gavin's bike'' (for McCulloch's
kid-who-asks-too-many-stupid-questions schtick) parked against
another prop and end up in front of the house, to the right.
</P>
<P>
   The show will open with ``The Secretaries,'' a new twist on the
same sketch the Kids closed with when the CBC/CBS TV series went
off the air in 1995. Reunited five years later, Fran (Thompson),
Kathy-with-a-K (that's McCulloch) and the girls discuss life in the
age of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Foley is comely, as usual, as the upwardly mobile secretary who
seems all too willing to sacrifice her friends for success. But his
part in this sketch is small. By the time the others break into
song and dance, he'll be changing into Mr. Heavyfoot.
</P>
<P>
   As the house lights go down on Sketch I, Foley will crouch in
the corner _ near you _ in his gray suit and fedora. (There's a box
of wet wipes just inside the stage door so he can wipe off his
lipstick). The bit is that Mr. Heavyfoot is going to wander into
the audience, try to get into the front row, and then be directed
by an usher to the balcony.
</P>
<P>
   You're the usher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the spotlight comes on him, stand by the gold column,''
Allen Ross, production manager for the tour, explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first cue comes after `Secretaries.''' You breathe. It
will be simple, you are assured.
</P>
<P>
   The house is ready to open, and since you're standing there
looking like an usher (by now, you've added vest and bow tie) with
an armful of programs (to hide the notebook), you have to go
backstage.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-show, a Kids retrospective set to music, blares as you
try to stay invisible in the chair where a properties master lays
out Mr. Heavyfoot's suit and boots.
</P>
<P>
   David Himelfarb, the Toronto attorney (and de facto Kids
manager) responsible for reuniting the Kids for the 2000 tour, is
back there with his children and some business partners. A promoter
from SFX Entertainment is asking about Houston restaurants. They
talk about the bus tour through Texas and ``the film.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been a lot of speculation about the film. About Nicolas
Cage and the possibility of a ``Spinal Tap''-style mockumentary of
the Kids reunion tour. Later, you'll find out more.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the show is ready to start. McCulloch, the quietest of
the Kids, walks by in a robe. Someone pulls you out front.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to see this,'' she says of the opening entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The first generation of American fans of Kids in the Hall were
Gen X hipsters raised on a diet of ``Ministry,'' slam dancing and
Monty Python re-runs. When Lorne Michaels launched the Kids into
the U.S. cable-TV market (they were too risque for network) in
1989, the show appealed to comedy junkies with a sick sense of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   Followers of the TV series will recognize about two-thirds of
the reunion tour's content. Most of it, according to former KITH
lead writer Paul Bellini, is actually from the first season.
</P>
<P>
   It's like seeing Monty Python's Flying Circus do the Spam bit
again _ only live. Many of the sketches are cult classics, like the
one about Gavin, the dorky kid who wants to paint a chair, and
McCulloch's ``sandwich people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing sadder than the sandwich people are the poo
people,'' he says of the people who scoop up after their pets at
the park.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-paced live show trots out all the old favorites: Buddy
Cole, the barfly (and queen of it); McKinney as the head-crusher
(this time, he squares off with a face-crusher); and the ultimate:
McDonald as the (brock!) Chicken Lady. The themes are perfectly
perverted, as always, with lots of drag (Thompson is the only gay
Kid, by the way) and plenty of irreverent R-rated jokes about the
evil of suburban ways.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: If you're a Kids fan, you'll love the show. If
you've never heard of them, why bother? In fact, they don't want
you to. No sense having horrified first-timers covering their eyes
when the Chicken Lady scrambles a plate of eggs for her date
(Foley) _ warm from her ``body.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready. Here you go again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' your personal prompter calls out. ``Stay two steps
behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   This is your second bit. The first one was a blur. Hazed out
with the spotlights and Foley's goofy stare. This time, you'll do
the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   As he stops in front of the audience, walk up and tap him on the
shoulder. Check his ticket and send him up _ far, far and away into
the nose-bleed seats. Sigh for poor Mr. Heavyfoot. The gag never
tires.
</P>
<P>
   And then, in a millisecond, you're done. You can take off the
bow tie and vest and watch the rest of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Before you know it, they're doing the encore sketch, ``Reg,'' an
updated, darkened twist on ``The Wonder Years'' spoof they did in
an early episode. The crowd mills out, and your day as a Kid has
ended.
</P>
<P>
   Almost.
</P>
<P>
   You have a backstage pass to the after-party. You wait while the
Kids give a New York Times reporter his 15 minutes. Chums of the
guys talk about the Toronto opening-night party, the private one
with Mike Myers (also a Toronto native). The Los Angeles bash,
you'll learn later, was also star-studded. Brendan Fraser (who's
working with Foley in the upcoming film ``Monkey Bone'') was there,
along with another name the Kids probably won't mention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica Lewinsky,'' whispers Bellini, who is also Scott
Thompson's best friend from college. ``Scott was out of his mind.
It was the most impressive celebrity he's met since Kato Kaelin.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the film, Bellini says Foley has hired an L.A. film guy
(a would-be Prada poster boy with a rock 'n' roll haircut) to
capture every essence of the reunion tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially the fights,'' he jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Himelfarb confirms it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to do a film,'' he says. ``We're doing a
behind-the-scenes look at the tour. We're filming it ourselves and
financing it ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kids are talking to Cage and his production company about
putting it on the big screen. No deals have been struck yet.
Himelfarb says the Toronto shows were also taped for a pending
album deal.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, Foley and McKinney talk a bit about Texas.
They're excited, really, since it's the first leg of the tour where
they'll be traveling by bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a blast,'' Foley says.
</P>
<P>
   Not too crowded and smelly?
</P>
<P>
   Nah.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, they always did fancy themselves a rock 'n' roll band.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
