<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SIMPATICO-FILM-REVIEW     02-03 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPATICO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIMPATICO': AMERICAN DREAM AS A RIGGED GAME OF CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The playwright Sam Shepard doesn't create characters so much as
conjure up colliding forces of nature. As his cowboys and city
slickers lunge at each other in an American landscape that
resembles a corrupted suburban province of Marlboro country, we
have the sense that they are divided halves of the same soul
groping for an impossible reconciliation in a blighted land.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's metaphorically charged vision of the divided American
spirit doesn't translate easily into the movies because language
matters so much less in film than it does on the stage, and
Shepard's writing is all about the raw American vernacular and its
looming, shadowy resonances. Movies also demand a degree of realism
that the stage doesn't require, and conventional realism has never
been Shepard's game. His fables take big, irrational leaps of faith
whose reasoning is symbolic rather than psychological.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the English director and screenwriter Matthew
Warchus, in filming ``Simpatico,'' the playwright's dark comedy
about horse-racing, has had to sketch in so much of the background
that the play omits. Not content for its characters to refer to a
horse-racing scam they conceived two decades earlier, the movie
gives us flashbacks of the actual race and the youthful con artists
(played by different actors) collecting their winnings. The lurid
details of a sex and blackmail scheme to silence the racing
commissioner who discovered the scam and whose career they ruined
are also shown. But in realistically depicting the sordid events to
which the play's characters allude, the film diminishes their
mythical hold on our imaginations. (Was that all they did?)
</P>
<P>
   The surprise of this offbeat, gawky movie, which has gripping
performances by Nick Nolte and Albert Finney and good ones by Jeff
Bridges, Sharon Stone and Catherine Keener, is that it works at
all. The playwright's language, which Warchus' screenplay
skillfully imitates, retains the force of a calligraphic scrawl
evoking the shadowy primal emotions of stored-up memory.
</P>
<P>
   As wielded by Shepard, horse-racing becomes a potent metaphor
for his notion of the American dream as a rigged, adrenaline-hyped
game of chance. And the play's vision of how people can drive
themselves crazy by obsessively chewing over their missed
opportunities, while others are able to let go of the past and move
on has a semi-tragic ring.
</P>
<P>
   The two clashing halves of ``Simpatico's'' divided soul are Lyle
Carter (Bridges), a wealthy horse breeder and trainer who lives
with his wife, Rosie (Stone), in a palatial estate in Lexington,
Ky., and his old friend Vinnie (Nolte), a down-and-out,
hard-drinking eccentric who rattles around his shack in Cucamonga,
a desolate eastern suburb of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   As the movie opens, Lyle is anxiously negotiating the $30
million sale of his triple-crown winning horse, Simpatico. That
sale involves the concealing of some damaging medical information
about the animal that the movie leaves teasingly ambiguous. Lyle's
deception implies that beneath the suave exterior of this
gentlemanly horse breeder there still beats the heart of a ruthless
con man.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the terms of the sale are being made final, Lyle
receives a threatening collect call from Vinnie, whom he hasn't
seen in years, demanding that he fly to Los Angeles at once. Lyle
reluctantly hustles himself to the West Coast where he encounters
Vinnie, who has kept the evidence of the 20-year-old race-track
scam he concocted with Lyle and Rosie, which involved the
substitution of slow horses for fast ones. Vinnie has also kept the
pornographic evidence of the blackmail scheme in a shoebox. If he
isn't paid off, Vinnie warns, he'll expose the scam.
</P>
<P>
   Vinnie also introduces Lyle to his only friend and confidante,
Cecilia (Keener), a grocery-store clerk whose dream in life is to
attend the Kentucky Derby. While Lyle is squiring her around
Cucamonga and pumping her for information about the whereabouts of
the shoe box, Vinnie steals Lyle's rental car, plane ticket and
identification and flies to Kentucky. Once there, he calls on Rosie
and on the disgraced racing commissioner, Simms (Finney), who is
living under an assumed name.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lyle desperately dispatches Cecilia (with promises of
Kentucky Derby tickets) to locate Simms and pay him off. But once
she departs, Lyle falls apart, languishing in Vinnie's shack,
swilling whiskey and brooding about the past. Like the brothers in
Shepard's play ``True West,'' the former friends mysteriously
change places.
</P>
<P>
   As Vinnie, Nolte paints a tumultuous portrait of an embittered
wild man on fire with rage, self-loathing and animal cunning.
Heightened by the movie, Nolte's fraternal resemblance to Bridges,
whose eyes glint with enough intimations of corruption to lend him
a slightly slippery aura, underscores the visceral force of their
angry bond. As Rosie, Stone makes a grand star entrance very late
in the film and gets to throw a memorable tantrum.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all is Finney's Simms, a flushed, shifty-eyed lecher who
works on the margins of the horse-racing world. In the play's
master stroke, it is this repulsive world-weary lout, reminiscent
of Sidney Greenstreet stripped of grandiosity, who emerges as the
film's only character to have made peace with the past.
</P>
<P>
   For all its flashes of brilliance, ``Simpatico'' never finds a
consistent style. The ominous film noir ambience of Simms' scenes
is broken by the home movie-style flashbacks. The movie is so
careless about its horse-selling subplot that its melodramatic
payoff feels cheap and abrupt.
</P>
<P>
   With all its inconsistencies, ``Simpatico'' at least has
integrity. Far from being a typical Hollywood desecration of a
difficult play, it stays true to the work's quirky, renegade
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Simpatico'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It has strong language and one sex
scene.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SIMPATICO'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Matthew Warchus; written by Warchus and David
Nicholls, based on the play by Sam Shepard; director of
photography, John Toll; edited by Pasquale Buba; music by Stewart
Copeland; production designer, Amy B. Ancona; produced by Dan
Lupovitz, Timm Oberwelland and Jean-Francois Fonlupt; released by
Fine Line Features. Running time: 106 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Nick Nolte (Vinnie), Jeff Bridges (Lyle), Sharon Stone
(Rosie), Catherine Keener (Cecilia), Albert Finney (Simms), Shawn
Hatosy (Young Vinnie), Kimberly Williams (Young Rosie) and Liam
Waite (Young Lyle).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1604EST &QL; 
