<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SHY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-03 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GUN SHY': TOUGH ON THE OUTSIDE, PUDDING ON THE INSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pop culture coincidences can be plainly unnerving. Last spring
saw both a film comedy (``Analyze This'') and a cable series (``The
Sopranos'') about gangsters forcing themselves to unload to a
shrink. This year, in ``Gun Shy,'' we get a shaken undercover Fed,
Charlie Mayo (Liam Neeson), seeing a psychiatrist on the down-low.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to share more than anyone I've ever known,'' his
analyst (Michael Mantell) says softly.
</P>
<P>
   The propensity for crime-infected psychoanalysis and goofily
labyrinthine twists on mob family life has an honorable source: the
1987 crime-stompers' notebook series ``Wiseguy,'' starring Ken Wahl
as an empathetic federal agent who got too close to the criminals
he went under cover to bust. (The show, worth seeking out, is
currently in reruns on Court TV.) And Eric Blakeney, a ``Wiseguy''
writer during the show's early days, has come up with one of the
most subtle and inspired comedies you'll see this year in ``Gun
Shy,'' his feature-film writing and directing debut. The movie is
probably best described as a procedural comedy. During an
undercover operation, Charlie was exposed. His quarry trussed him
up like a pheasant on ``a silver serving tray,'' face down in a
pile of sliced watermelon, before he was rescued. (Flashes of this
obscene torture pop into his head at the most inopportune moments.)
Charlie's a wreck who has lost his nerve. Despite his apparent
calm, he always seems on the verge of dashing out of a room. He's
reshuffling cards in his head. It's Blakeney's way of trumping the
limits of series television, where if the star were to be allowed
to be this damaged, he'd be a ridiculously tragic figure or all
dry-ice cool. Instead, Blakeney uses a matter-of-factness to play
the situation for farce.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie is assigned to a job that involves his acting as an
organized-crime envoy in a money-laundering and illegal stock
scheme. He moves between the preening Fidel (Jose Zuniga), a yuppie
Colombian thug, and Fulvio Nesstra (Oliver Platt), whose vulgar
pride in his violent streak is perverse. Fulvio, a baby-faced bull
who seems to be trying to fight off the effects of a tranquilizer,
lashes out at everyone he comes in contact with except his wife
(Mary McCormack), who's tougher and more unpredictable than he.
Charlie's misery makes him seem even-tempered to Fulvio; Charlie
continues with his job because he has nowhere else to go.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Charlie's wary mendacity, Fulvio is a
passive-aggressive bully. Fulvio admires Charlie for his sanity and
charm. Charlie's sanity, though, consists of him trying to keep his
head together. He learns to do so with the help of a nurse, Judy
(Sandra Bullock), who ministers to Charlie's gastronentrological
problems. She puts her auto-perkiness on hold and registers with
the openness that made her so essential to ``Speed.'' Well, the
first ``Speed'' anyway. She's given better lines here, and she's up
to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie's tense stomach growls like a Rottweiler. It's literally
his gut reaction to the sad duality of his life: he's a man who has
to continually lie to do good and be good at his job. When he
explains his professional dishonesty at his group therapy session,
one of the members _ Elliott (Richard Schiff), who vibrates like a
tuning fork from suppressed rage _ responds: ``It's like a life of
permanent job interviews. You're always on your best phony
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Blakeney has assembled a cast strong enough to keep ``Gun Shy''
going, and he keeps a tight enough ship that no one performer runs
off with the show. Neeson, whose slightly downturned mouth makes
him a big, dour soul, shows adroit comic reflexes. He's never been
given a chance to play something like this before, a man who
desperately wants out of his unhappiness. He uses his big, handsome
slab of a face for the tiniest shifts of expression. As Platt plays
Fulvio, there's something dim and sweet about him. He's unhappy
being a thug. (He wants to be a gentleman farmer, and his wife
chides him for his black thumb.)
</P>
<P>
   The direction is proficient, but Blakeney has made his job look
easy by shaping such a fine script. Good material certainly does a
lot of the work. It gives the actors something to respond to, and
they rise to the challenge. Neeson and Schiff, as well as the other
actors in the group sessions, make the meetings seem realistically
dreary: there's a five-second delay before the next man utters his
thought. And each of them feels that his complaints are just as
valid as Charlie's. The suffering is democratic. As is that of the
vain and sensitive Fidel, who explodes when the oblivious party-boy
stockbroker (Andy Lauer) buys bean futures. Fidel is insulted over
being associated with beans; he can't go back to his
drug-cartel-running father with this information. It's a matter of
taste.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Gun Shy'' is for Sandra Bullock. She is the producer, and
probably got the picture made by appearing in a small part. She
shows brains as well as taste.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Gun Shy'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes baroque incidents of
violence and adult language.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GUN-SHY'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Eric Blakeney; director of photography,
Tom Richmond; edited by Pamela Martin; music by Rolfe Kent;
production designer, Maher Ahmad; produced by Sandra Bullock;
released by Hollywood Pictures. Running time: 102 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Liam Neeson (Charlie), Oliver Platt (Fulvio Nesstra), Jose
Zuniga (Fidel Vaillar), Michael DeLorenzo (Estuvio), Andy Lauer
(Jason Cane), Richard Schiff (Elliott), Paul Ben-Victor (Howard),
Gregg Daniel (Jonathan), Ben Weber (Mark), Sandra Bullock (Judy
Tipp), Mary McCormack (Gloria Nesstra) and Michael Mantell (Dr.
Bleckner).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
