<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5558 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BLACK-WEALTH04-COX     02-03 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-WEALTH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BLACK FAMILY WEALTH FALLING DESPITE ROBUST ECONOMY, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Black family wealth declined over the past five
years despite a booming economy and income growth in most American
homes, an ongoing University of Michigan study has found.
</P>
<P>
   The net worth of the median black household _ half were higher
and half lower _ decreased from $8,400 to $7,500 between 1994 and
1999, according to the university's Panel Survey of Income Dynamics
study, ``Five Years Older: Much Richer or Deeper in Debt?''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the net worth of the median American household
increased 9 percent, to $59,500.
</P>
<P>
   The study also shows that for every dollar of wealth the median
white household had in 1999, the median black household held barely
9 cents. This gap has remained steady for the past 15 years, said
University of Michigan economist Frank Stafford. He heads the
study, which has been surveying 7,056 households every five years
for the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
   The study's findings are shocking, said Joseph Altonji, an
economics professor at Northwestern University in Evanston, Ill. He
said he had expected the study to show a small increase in black
family wealth, since the economy has done so well.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the strong economy is indirectly responsible for the
decline, Stafford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the economy is good, people tend to spend beyond their
income level and save less,'' Stafford said. A good economy also
causes people to borrow more money, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research shows that (Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan)
Greenspan is justified in worrying about too strong a 'wealth
effect,' `` the tendency for people to spend more freely when their
stock holdings or other assets have increased in value, Stafford
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This better job market would then show up as income gains and
wealth declines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All Americans, regardless of race, are guilty of overspending,
Stafford said. However, 84 percent of white households kept some of
their wealth in saving or checking accounts in 1999, compared to 57
percent of black households, the study shows.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, only 17 percent of black families hold
stock or Individual Retirement Accounts, while 71 percent of white
families do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the wide wealth gap between African American and white
families is significantly the result of portfolio choice,''
Stafford said.
</P>
<P>
   Black families tend not to invest in the stock market, he said,
because of a long-standing mistrust of banks and securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done research that shows that when your family didn't
hold stock, it affects what you do,'' Stafford said.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of small businesses and self-employment in the
black community may have also contributed to the decrease in
wealth, Altonji added.
</P>
<P>
   Black families can overcome the wealth deficit, though it might
take some time, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that will be important for African Americans
is to have more involvement in small businesses and
self-employment,'' Altonji said.
</P>
<P>
   Education and more exposure to the stock market, Stafford said,
is the the key. Perhaps when investment companies advertise, he
explained, they should portray blacks as bankers and stockholders.
Schools also need to offer more classes that show children how to
manage their finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't simple, but it's something you can learn,'' Altonji
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1610EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
