<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GIRAFFE-FILM-REVIEW-N     02-03 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRAFFE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GIRAFFE': GRANDPA'S CHOCOLATE BURNS INSIDE A GERMAN POTBOILER
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
By A.O. SCOTT  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To see ``The Giraffe,'' the new film by Dani Levy and Maria
Schrader that anchors this week's retrospective of Levy's work at
New York's Anthology Film Archives, is to be confronted by a series
of mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   The first involves the film's English title, the significance of
which is revealed rather late in the game. In Germany, ``The
Giraffe'' was released as ``Meschugge''; the title comes from a
German word that, like its familiar Yiddish cognate, means, roughly
``nuts,'' and has no particular zoological connotation.
</P>
<P>
   But the conundrum posed by the film's incompatible titles
quickly recedes in the face of a more urgent mystery: what on earth
did Levy and Schrader, who star in the movie and reportedly worked
on its script for 10 years, think they were doing? Most of the
dialogue is, at least arguably, in English, and much of the film
was shot in what is unquestionably New York. But the characters in
``The Giraffe'' seem to have wandered out of a badly translated
German potboiler.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, some are portrayed by gifted American
actors, notably Jeffrey Wright and David Strathairn. Strathairn
plays a paranoid lawyer named Charles Kaminski, who is best
described as William Kunstler with Rabbi Meir Kahane's politics. He
moves with such a fervent sense of purpose, and fulminates with
such demented conviction, that you almost believe he understands
what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   How could he, though? This movie's breathless incoherence is
matched only by its wild implausibility. It opens with arson at a
chocolate factory in a small town in Germany, an event that makes
the front page of The Daily News in New York and brings together
Lena Katz ( Schrader) and David Fish ( Levy).
</P>
<P>
   Lena is a German Jew working as a set designer in New York; her
grandfather owned the factory. David is a New York businessman
whose mother fled Germany in 1941. His relatives are meant to be
Orthodox Jews, which means that the men wear false beards and black
clothes and that the women berate him because he is unmarried and
insufficiently religious.
</P>
<P>
   The plot begins to thicken when Lena's mother apparently kills
David. To reveal any more would not only ruin the suspense (if
that's the word for the hurtling confusion that ensues) but also
take all day. Suffice it to say that the narrative revolves around
stolen identities, forbidden love and the weight of the past on
present-day relations between Germans and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is potentially very interesting. But Schrader and
Levy seem to labor under the assumption that making a film about an
important, politically charged subject is the same as making an
important, politically charged film.
</P>
<P>
   They also seem to think a movie that features people chasing one
another through airports and train stations, exchanging desperate
looks and shouting a lot deserves to be called a psychological
thriller. ``The Giraffe'' no doubt deserves to be called a lot of
things, in any number of languages. Come to think of it, meschugge
might be one of them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE GIRAFFE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Dani Levy; written by Maria Schrader and Levy;
director of photography, Carl F. Koschnick; edited by Sabine
Hoffmann; music by Niki Reiser; production designers, Teresa
Mastropierro and Volker Schaefer; produced by Stefan Amdt and
X-Filme Creative Pool GmbH; released by German Independents and
Bavaria Film International. Running time: 107 minutes. This film is
not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Maria Schrader (Lena Katz), Dani Levy (David Fish), David
Strathairn (Charles Kaminski), Nicole Heesters (Lena's Mother),
Jeffrey Wright (Win), Lynn Cohen (David's Mother) and Lukas Ammann
(Eliah Goldberg). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1613EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LIGHTHOUSE-FILM-REVIE     02-03 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTHOUSE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIGHTHOUSE': SO WHERE'S VIRGINIA WOOLF WHEN YOU NEED HER? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Near the end of ``Lighthouse,'' the grade-C British horror
thriller that sneaks into New York area theaters Friday, its damsel
in distress, Dr. Kirsty McCloud (Rachel Shelley), a comely criminal
psychiatrist, is dangling from a frayed, burning rope on the side
of a lighthouse amid a cloudburst lighted with exploding electrical
fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Lunging at Kirsty through a window is her nemesis and personal
lab experiment, Leo Rook (Chris Adamson), an insatiable killer with
a yellow-toothed wolfman grin who collects the severed heads of his
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Dangling on the same rope while holding her by the hair to keep
her from falling is Kirsty's possible savior, Richard Spader (James
Purefoy), a convicted killer who swears he didn't murder his wife;
he was having an epileptic fit when someone else did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lighthouse'' begins on the Hyperion, a prison ship. Leo and
Richard are among the criminals being transported to a remote
island off the northern English coast. When the ship experiences
navigational problems, Leo escapes to Gehenna Rocks, a desolate
island, in a stolen lifeboat. The ship soon runs aground. Seven
survivors make it to shore, where most are picked off one by one by
the yellow-toothed saber-wielding fiend.
</P>
<P>
   As in most horror thrillers, the scenes that work best are the
creepy-crawly early ones in which the killer stalks his prey. The
most carefully set-up moment involves the ship's drunken captain
(Paul Brooke), who peeks under a lavatory stall to see the killer,
who dresses in black except for his white shoes, pacing several
feet away.
</P>
<P>
   We hear the sound of metal being drawn and watch as those shoes
are spattered with blood from a previous murder. Once the movie
becomes a pitched battle for survival, it disintegrates into a
chaotic, screaming frenzy edited on a butcher block.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lighthouse'' is not without its crude pretensions. Two gory
fantasy montages suggest that Kirsty chose criminal psychiatry as a
profession because as a little girl she witnessed her father slash
her mother to death. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Lighthouse' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It is extremely gory, with severed heads flying
in all directions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LIGHTHOUSE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Simon Hunter; director of photography,
Tony Imi; edited by Paul Green; music by Debbie Wiseman; production
designer, Simon Bowles; produced by Mark Leake and Tim Dennison;
released by Unapix Films. Running time: 95 minutes. This film is
rated R.
</P>
<P>
   With: James Purefoy (Prisoner Richard Spader), Rachel Shelley
(Dr. Kirsty McCloud), Chris Adamson (Leo Rook), Paul Brooke
(Captain Campbell), Don Warrington (Prison Officer Ian Goslet),
Chris Dunne (Chief Prison Officer O'Neil), Bob Goody (Weevil) and
Pat Kelman (Spoons). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1621EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5566 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1S     02-03 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, Feb. 03, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
