<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5567 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SAFIRE-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     02-03 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SCANDALMONGER': THE FOUNDING FATHERS, IN PUBLIC AND PRIVATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes at end) 
Benson Bobrick is the author of ``Angel in the Whirlwind: The
Triumph of the American Revolution.'' 
(jt) 
 By BENSON BOBRICK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Safire, the oft-polemical, sometimes embattled Op-Ed
columnist for The New York Times, is up to mischief in his new
novel, ``Scandalmonger,'' which retells in bitingly embellished yet
reliable detail the muckraking, sordid, yet oddly affecting
wranglings of some of our founding fathers in the wake of the
Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   The story opens in Philadelphia, on Dec. 17, 1792, with
Alexander Hamilton, treasury secretary in Washington's
administration, under a cloud for reportedly speculating in
government securities. Confronted by congressional investigators
(John Beckley, the first Librarian of Congress, Frederick Augustus
Muhlenberg, speaker of the House, and James Monroe), he is obliged
to reveal his private affair with a married woman to clear his
public name.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the public and the private is what this
novel is all about, and in the bitter struggle between the
Federalists (led by Alexander Hamilton and John Adams) and the
Jeffersonian Republicans, fortunes rise and fall as scandals
envelop principals on either side.
</P>
<P>
   The reader is introduced to the makings of the Alien and
Sedition Act (in part a partisan attempt to muzzle the opposition
and deport inconvenient members of the press); the relationship
between Thomas Jefferson and Sally Hemings, his slave; the
remarkable Maria Reynolds, a femme fatale of sorts and the sometime
mistress of both Hamilton and Aaron Burr; the XYZ affair under
Adams, which involved the bribery of American officials in France;
physical violence on the floor of Congress; the medical quackery of
Dr. Benjamin Rush, who had a great gift for bleeding his patients
to death; and (the last shall be first) the scandalmongers William
Cobbett and James Callender, whom Safire nicely describes as
ideological adversaries and vituperative soul mates. It is to them,
as identified by their pen names _ Peter Porcupine and Timothy
Thunderproof _ that the author dedicates his book.
</P>
<P>
   Safire has great fun with all this and tells his story well. And
by not trying to moralize its meaning (the epigraph carries all the
moral weight the tale can bear) he allows the reader to relax into
the amused and theatrical context of all the posturing and slander.
The facts are also accurate, the more so for the clarifying ``Notes
and Sources'' at the end, in which Safire discloses what he has,
and has not, imagined.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out he has not imagined much, and when he has, has
probably got it more or less right. The characters live in the
author's understanding approach to them, more than in his
description of their physical realities or idiosyncratic traits;
but by constructing (or reconstructing) dialogue from sentences
used in their letters, he gives authentic voice to their different
temperaments and a convincing quality to their repartee.
</P>
<P>
   Partisans of Jefferson, Hamilton and others may take issue with
some of the characterizations, but Safire is nothing if not
evenhanded, and some of his most sympathetic writing is inspired by
Maria Reynolds and James Callender, who are usually vilified. Both
are redeemed and redeem each other in an invented but tender
romance, and Callender (the true hero of the story) assumes tragic
stature as his personal life becomes captive to the impersonal
workings of rival political machines.
</P>
<P>
   Safire knows his history inside out, and there is so much of it
in this book that there is almost nothing pertinent to the period
that is not worked in. Every opportunity to fill in the background
and context of events is seized, and this is usually satisfying.
But on occasion dramatic moments list (or are skewed) under the
sheer weight of historical detail.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on the verge of a major seduction, Hamilton, in an
effort to ``keep his expectations down'' about his meeting with
Maria, ``recalled how Congress had passed his bank bill over the
objections of James Madison and the Jeffersonians, who argued that
its powers could not be found in the Constitution. These believers
in a rural society of yeomen and farmers had almost persuaded
Washington to veto the banking legislation designed to finance an
empire based on urban manufactures ... '' And the disquisition goes
on about ``implied powers,'' ``strict construction'' and other
matters for another hundred words.
</P>
<P>
   It is a good synopsis of the facts. But there is quite a bit of
this compendious review of material in odd places, and more timely
ways of placing it might have been found. Still and all, the story
moves grandly forward despite such lapses, and the tease of
historical veracity is one that Safire takes advantage of with
considerable skill.
</P>
<P>
   The epigraph from Juvenal is an apt one:
</P>
<P>
   And there's a Lust in Man no Charm can tame,
</P>
<P>
   Of loudly publishing our Neighbour's Shame;
</P>
<P>
   On Eagles' Wings immortal Scandals fly,
</P>
<P>
   While Virtuous Actions are but Born, and Dye.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of polemical journalism, this is doubtless
axiomatic. But it is not, I think, an aphorism to which Safire
wholly subscribes. His novel, like history itself, takes a longer
view. None of the principal characters, all too human as they are,
emerge diminished. Some, however scandal-prone, still ``mount up
with wings as eagles'' in our recollection of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SCANDALMONGER'
</P>
<P>
   By William Safire
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 496 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $27.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1628EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
