<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FRIEND-FILM-REVIEW-NY     02-03 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEND-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BELOVED/FRIEND': DESIRES THAT FALL BETWEEN THE CHASM OF HEAD AND
HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something going on in the director Ventura Pons'
melodrama ``Beloved/Friend,'' though you've got to work hard to get
past what feel like intentional obstacles that he's set for himself
_ like the score, which drizzles over the picture like a caramel
coating.
</P>
<P>
   And the static setups: the camera perches in front of the
players, resting comfortably in the front row of the theater, as if
recording a play. But Pons has made a career out of drama in plain
sight. He doesn't go for the operatic, but rather a soft
earnestness that could be drab in the hands of the wrong director.
He toys with the chasm between the heart and the head.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Beloved/Friend,'' Jaume (Josep Maria Pou), a gay college
professor, has drifted into middle age, and passes around a
manuscript that he can't get anyone to read. His student, the
cerebrally cold and physically hot David (David Selvas), crumples
the diskette containing the work right in front of Jaume on two
different occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Pere (Mario Gas), Jaume's closest friend, hasn't had time to get
to it; he's too busy dealing with the involvement of his daughter
Alba (Irene Montala) with the callous pinup David.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone is pining for something that can't be had. David, who
also puts in time as a hustler, seems to be looking for love in all
the wrong places.
</P>
<P>
   Jaume is shocked when he dials for a sweaty treat and his
student appears at his door, ready to be unwrapped. ``This is why
you have such a nice apartment,'' the shocked Jaume says of David's
unusual work-study arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   David also seems to be looking for a father figure. His own
father killed himself while in prison because of a drug deal gone
bad.
</P>
<P>
   Fanny (Rosa Maria Sarda), Alba's mother, spins anecdotes about
her days as a pleasure-seeking radical. The pregnant Alba wants
David to commit to her and their baby, though she's considering an
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Pere wants David to disappear from the face of the earth. No one
here seems to have much of a future, not even the young.
</P>
<P>
   And Jaume? Wistful and lost, he wants so much. He wants to rouse
David from his hedonism so he will help raise Alba's baby. He wants
Pere to recognize how close they were to a relationship when they
were younger.
</P>
<P>
   Jaume is dying and at the end of his life he has fallen in love
with another man he cannot have: David. (These contradictions are
responsible for the slightly unwieldy title, ``Beloved/Friend.'')
Jaume's life could be represented by another of Pons' films,
``Damned Misery,'' though that title could easily be applied to a
number of his features.
</P>
<P>
   What Jaume wants for himself and everyone else is salvation.
This element and the thwarted desires that everyone talks about in
``Beloved/Friend'' spell out Pons' affection for Tennessee
Williams. But it's like Williams writ small, with the passion
reduced to one-sixth scale.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand why Jaume is reduced to just dwelling on
his lost loves, but David could have a much bigger presence in the
film. With his heavy boots and jeans as tight as shrink wrap, he is
obviously meant to be a Stanley Kowalski with brains. (Though as
played by Selvas, it's hard to be entirely sure how smart David
is.)
</P>
<P>
   Pons' attempt to dig for a deeper, more refined tear-jerker is
admirable, but like its title, it's a clumsy contraption. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BELOVED/FRIEND'
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Ventura Pons; written (in Spanish, with
English subtitles) by Josep M. Benet I Jornet, based on his play
``Testament''; director of photography, Jesus Escosa; edited by
Pere Abadal; music by Carles Cases; released by Cowboy Booking
International. At the Screening Room, 54 Varick Street, at Canal
Street, TriBeCa. Running time: 90 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Josep Maria Pou (Jaume Clara), Rosa Maria Sarda (Fanny),
Mario Gas (Pere Roure), David Selvas (David Vila) and Irene Montala
(Alba).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1636EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-BUTCHER-0204-     02-03 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BUTCHER-0204-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRITAIN'S WEIGHTY ISSUE OF POUNDS VS METRIC HAS BUTCHER TIPPING
LEGAL SCALES
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A village butcher is waging a full-scale war against
what he sees as the latest and most insidious invasion from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the scale is full of meat _ pounds of it despite
new rules that make the kilogram the only legal measure of the
realm.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us, an ounce is an ounce, and a pound is a pound,''
explained Dave Stephens, the proprietor of Mandy's Chop Shop in the
east England village of Leigh-on-Sea. ``A kilogram is a foreign
measure, and our customers don't understand what it means.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Stephens ignored a deadline imposed on him by
frustrated local officials to convert to metric _ or else. (The
``or else'' in this case is a fine of 2,000 pounds (about US$3,300)
and/or six months in jail.)
</P>
<P>
   Stephens, a burly guy with a powerful voice to match, minces
fine English beef _ always by the pound, never by the kilo _ but he
does not mince words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll fight them on the beaches, I'll fight them in the high
street, and I'll fight them in all the little shops around the
country,'' Stephens said after flagrantly violating the law by
selling a customer a pound of chopped meat. ``I'm doing what I
normally do, weighing up in pounds and ounces and wait for the
officials to come down and either confiscate my scales or to try to
take them a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Stephens said he will continue to use pounds and ounces
and is willing to take his fight to court.
</P>
<P>
   Daunted by Stephens' stubbornness and mindful that his
sentiments resonate widely, officials and their lawyers are
weighing carefully _ presumably in kilos _ what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in England _ Stephens among them _ see the
introduction of new European and American ways as an attack on
their English identity, which has suffered a lot, what with the
loss of the Empire and all.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, resistance to Europe is rising at a time when the
government of Prime Minister Tony Blair and business leaders are
pushing for more integration with the continent. Britain remains
the only big economy in Europe unwilling to replace its national
currency with the euro.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't stop nature but Europe we can do,'' Stephens said.
``I'm going to make my stand now. We're not going to be dictated to
by Europe. Don't forget that Napoleon said that England was an
island of shopkeepers, and we certainly gave them a good showing,
didn't we.''
</P>
<P>
   All but a few imperial measures were to be phased out by the end
of 1999 _ with the major exception being the use of miles for road
distance. Yet, old habits die hard: Despite the switch to a decimal
currency 29 years ago, the term guinea (meaning one pound and one
shilling) is still used by some auction houses. And nearly all
English people weigh themselves in ``stones'' (14 pounds) rather
than pounds or ... shudder, kilograms.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens said he feels for those unfortunates who have fallen
under Europe's spell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had many people come and ask for kilos or grams,''
he said. ``But if someone comes in and asks for a kilo, I'd serve
it to them, because it's only 2.2 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1641EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
