selling a customer a pound of chopped meat. ``I'm doing what I
normally do, weighing up in pounds and ounces and wait for the
officials to come down and either confiscate my scales or to try to
take them a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Stephens said he will continue to use pounds and ounces
and is willing to take his fight to court.
</P>
<P>
   Daunted by Stephens' stubbornness and mindful that his
sentiments resonate widely, officials and their lawyers are
weighing carefully _ presumably in kilos _ what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in England _ Stephens among them _ see the
introduction of new European and American ways as an attack on
their English identity, which has suffered a lot, what with the
loss of the Empire and all.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, resistance to Europe is rising at a time when the
government of Prime Minister Tony Blair and business leaders are
pushing for more integration with the continent. Britain remains
the only big economy in Europe unwilling to replace its national
currency with the euro.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't stop nature but Europe we can do,'' Stephens said.
``I'm going to make my stand now. We're not going to be dictated to
by Europe. Don't forget that Napoleon said that England was an
island of shopkeepers, and we certainly gave them a good showing,
didn't we.''
</P>
<P>
   All but a few imperial measures were to be phased out by the end
of 1999 _ with the major exception being the use of miles for road
distance. Yet, old habits die hard: Despite the switch to a decimal
currency 29 years ago, the term guinea (meaning one pound and one
shilling) is still used by some auction houses. And nearly all
English people weigh themselves in ``stones'' (14 pounds) rather
than pounds or ... shudder, kilograms.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens said he feels for those unfortunates who have fallen
under Europe's spell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had many people come and ask for kilos or grams,''
he said. ``But if someone comes in and asks for a kilo, I'd serve
it to them, because it's only 2.2 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
