A5582 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-MCCAIN-CALIF-HNS &LR;      02-03 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CALIF-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN FACES A BIGGER TEST IN CALIFORNIA  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Despite his commanding victory over Texas
Gov. George W. Bush in the New Hampshire primary, Arizona Sen. John
McCain will have limited time and money to make his case to
California Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Both McCain and Bush will be distracted this month by Republican
primaries and caucuses in seven other states, leaving them limited
time to campaign at length in California. Delaware, South Carolina,
Arizona, Michigan, North Dakota and Virginia all hold Republican
primaries or caucuses this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidates, Vice President Al Gore and former
Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, have an open calendar before March
7, when vote-rich California and New York, along with 13 other
states, hold presidential contests.
</P>
<P>
   The California campaign crush on the Republican side is likely
to favor Bush because he has the resources to spend vast amounts of
money on television advertising in a state that relies heavily on
the electronic media for political information. Bush has the added
advantage of being supported by the state's Republican
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   But if McCain continues his successful run, particularly in
South Carolina in on Feb. 19, his insurgent campaign could create
chaos in the California Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show Bush with a 2-to-1 advantage over McCain in
California. But McCain's campaign believes maverick California
voters could show an independent streak. Although California has
far fewer independent voters by percentage than in New Hampshire,
the numbers are growing.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's reformist platform tends to attract independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is an energy to the McCain campaign, and that
fire could light up California and surprise a few people,'' said
Joel Fox, a California co-chairman of the McCain 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In California, it is possible that McCain could win the popular
vote by attracting independent voters and Democrats. Yet Bush could
still win the race for delegates because only votes from registered
Republicans will count in selecting delegates to the Republican
National Convention this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say if you can't win California, you can't be
president,'' Fox said. ``If the party then denies the nomination to
the candidate who won California, I think there would be a lot of
trouble and a lot of re-examining going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has a county-by-county operation in California, two
campaign headquarters (McCain has none), endorsements from every
major GOP lawmaker, and a record amount of money _ nearly $70
million so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important not to draw erroneous conclusions,''
said state Sen. Jim Brulte, a Bush supporter. ``The McCain campaign
has the luxury of picking and choosing where they want to play.
They've already written off Delaware, and they wrote off Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they have a three-state strategy: New Hampshire,
South Carolina and California,'' Brulte said. ``They have little or
no organization in any other state. ... If you pick and choose five
or six states where you want to play, you can win every delegate in
those states and still be hundreds of delegates short of the
nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has made no secret of his targeted campaign _ do well in
New Hampshire, do well in South Carolina and win in California.
McCain has made 23 campaign trips to California in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   One test for McCain comes this weekend in Burlingame. He is
scheduled to speak Saturday at the state GOP convention, which is
usually populated by the most ardent Republican activists. Bush is
not scheduled to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bush is sending his brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush.
Their father, former President George Bush, is expected to campaign
in California next week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McCain is concentrating his efforts in South
Carolina, which has 37 delegates, by stressing his military
experience. The state has a large veteran population.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has a 2-to-1 advantage in polls taken in South Carolina and
support from the GOP establishment. McCain hopes his big New
Hampshire win will generate enthusiasm in South Carolina and spark
contributions from across the country. He raised $500,000 in
Internet donations in the hours after his victory was announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think McCain's whole candidacy rests on South Carolina,''
said Alan Heslop, a political science professor at Claremont
McKenna College. ``If McCain can't beat Bush there, then it seems
that New Hampshire was simply a bump in the road for Bush.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
