<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-MCENTIRE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCENTIRE'S `SINGER'S DIARY' OPENS THE BOOK ON A REMARKABLE CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oklahoma-bred country star Reba McEntire loves musicals. But
she's never seen ``Oklahoma!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, I never have,'' McEntire says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've never seen `Annie Get Your Gun,' either.''
</P>
<P>
   But this didn't stop McEntire, one of the most successful
country stars of the past two decades, from turning her own life
story into a musical _ and then some.
</P>
<P>
   McEntire is on tour with ``The Singer's Diary,'' a two-for-one
extravaganza that begins with a musical play based on her
remarkable career, followed by a concert of her most
autobiographical songs. The concert portion includes songs from her
latest album, ``So Good Together.''
</P>
<P>
   The touring production made its debut last September and will be
on the road through the end of year.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices in the $60-$70 range reflect the elaborate nature
of the show. Concertgoers also are encouraged to donate
non-perishable food items for U.S. Harvest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Singer's Diary'' features McEntire and her nine-piece
band, plus six dancers and a large crew of stage hands. The sets
and costumes look very theatrical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got backdrops, we've got scrims that fly in, fly out. We
have the curtains that come in, come out. And we have the stage
that moves, separates and comes back together,'' McEntire said by
phone from a tour stop in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Though McEntire is known for her over-the-top concert
productions, ``The Singer's Diary'' is different from anything she
has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the tour, some of my fans didn't know how
to react because it starts out as a play,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we have to sort of prepare the audience when they come to
the theater. I hope my fans enjoy it, and I hope they take the
journey with us.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager, the ranch-raised McEntire dreamed of a
country-music career while competing as a rodeo barrel racer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Singer's Diary'' begins in 1974, the year McEntire wowed
fellow Oklahomans by singing ``The Star Spangled Banner'' at the
National Rodeo Finals. A year later, McEntire signed a recording
contract. But it wasn't until 1981 that she had her first No. 1
country hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, well, the record labels would have dropped me like a
hot potato,'' she said in a tough, self-assured tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God they had the time to work with me then. Country
wasn't booming at that point. But in the '80s, country went through
this huge period of success, from the `Urban Cowboy' craze to the
rise of Garth Brooks. And, boy, if you don't make it quick these
days, the labels don't have much time for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in the show are three songs from McEntire's latest
album, among them her new single, ``What Do You Say.'' The album is
unusual in that it recruited three producers, David Malloy, Keith
Stegall (senior vice president of A&AMP;R at Mercury Records) and Tony
Brown (president of MCA Nashville). The result is more stylistic
breadth than on her previous efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The last song on the album is Rita Coolidge's 1977 hit, ``We're
All Alone,'' recorded as a duet with Brazilian group Chitaozinho
Xororo. McEntire is the latest country artist (Brooks and Alan
Jackson preceded her) to record with a foreign-language group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been wantin' to do something with a foreign-language act
for a long time,'' she said. ``I've gotten to go to Germany and
record `Does He Love You' with a lady named Corina Mae. She sings
in German and I sing in English. And that was a great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Brazilian market, with its cattle ranches and wide-open
spaces, could prove to be a fertile region for American country
artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love the Brazilian people. We had a wonderful time when we
were there last,'' she said. ``So we're really looking forward to
going back.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether she's performing in Brazil or North America, the
pressure is always on to come up with an entertaining, eye-popping
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a challenge. Not only to entertain our fans, but
to entertain ourselves,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
