r e BC-FILM-GUNSHY-SPI &LR;      02-03 0357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GUNSHY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GUN SHY' DOESN'T BLUSH AT BODILY FUNCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Gun Shy,'' a mildly amusing but forgettable and
way-too-scatological black farce, Liam Neeson plays Charlie, an
18-year veteran undercover DEA agent who, after one particularly
traumatic experience, loses his nerve and becomes a physical wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, his stomach is constantly gurgling with gases,
he's lost all control of his bowels, and when not popping pills or
whining to his shrink, he's usually in the act of dropping his
pants and racing for the nearest toilet. Very distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie's chief nemesis is a sadistic Mafioso enforcer (Oliver
Platt) whose life is almost as miserable: He's the son-in-law of a
aging Don (Frank Vincent) who hates his guts, his wife (Mary
McCormack) constantly abuses him, and his tomatoes won't grow.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the mix is a ditzy nurse (Sandra Bullock) whom Charlie
meets one day over a barium enema, a pair of gay Colombian drug
lords (Jose Zuniga and Michael Delorenzo) and a crooked Wall Street
trader (Andy Lauer) trying to put together a money-laundering
operation.
</P>
<P>
   As Charlie joins in as part of a DEA sting, a few honest laughs
emerge between all the flatulence and body functions, and Platt
does his usual good work, consistently funny.
</P>
<P>
   Neeson also has his moments. Few stars have his natural
likability, and his self-deprecating comedy style here is
occasionally engaging _ though the film is unlikely to do much for
his somewhat faltering career (after ``The Haunting'' and poor
reviews for ``Phantom Menace'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Gun Shy'' is also likely to be a bad career move for
producer/co-star Sandra Bullock, who seems bored and distracted,
and for first-time feature writer-director Eric Blakeney, whose
script is sloppy and whose direction is never quite able to make
these elements fly as madcap comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Gun Shy. Directed and written by Eric Blakeney. Cast: Liam
Neeson, Oliver Platt, Sandra Bullock. Hollywood Pictures. 105
minutes. Rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1656EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
