A5590 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-WILLIAMGAY06-CO     02-03 1589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-WILLIAMGAY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author mines dark, hardscrabble truth
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 6.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOHENWALD, Tenn. _ It is a bitterly cold day in this small,
southwestern Tennessee town where explorer Meriwether Lewis
committed suicide. Turning up the collar of his faded denim jacket,
William Gay lopes across a near-deserted main street and ducks into
the local pool hall and cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Nodding briefly to the handful of locals, he waits for the woman
behind the bar to flip a hand-shaped hamburger patty on the grill
and orders a beer.
</P>
<P>
   His agent, Amy Williams, had described him as a cross between
singers Tom Waits and Lyle Lovett, and there is a resemblance. With
a tangled mass of dark hair and a face as lined as a Tennessee
state map, the 56-year-old Gay evokes the image of someone who has
lived hard and driven on a lot of dirt roads.
</P>
<P>
   Most folks in Hohenwald know Gay as a carpenter and drywall
hanger, but in the rest of the South the self-taught writer is
already being talked about as the next Larry Brown or Cormac
McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy has been a major influence, Gay says, sipping his beer
and lighting up what is not his first cigarette of the day. ``I
think he's probably the greatest living writer. I'm flattered by
the comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also a little overwhelmed by the attention he's been
getting lately for his debut novel, ``The Long Home'' (MacMurray &AMP;
Beck, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   Gay's story of a young Tennessee carpenter, an evil bootlegger
and a beautiful girl has been nominated for the Southeastern
Booksellers Association Award for book of the year. Hollywood has
shown some interest as well, and he has sold his next novel to
Doubleday for a substantial six-figure advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty much of a surprise,'' Gay says with typical
understatement. ``I just wanted the book to be well-thought of.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, he's gotten his wish. In a lengthy review in The New
York Times, author Tony Earley described Gay as ``a writer of
remarkable talent and promise. ... At his best, Gay writes with the
wisdom and patience of a man who has witnessed hard times and
learned that panic or hedging won't make better times come any
sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay freely admits there have been hard times. The son of a
sharecropper and laborer, he grew up roaming the woods around
Hohenwald, joined the Navy after high school and spent several
years living on the West Coast and in Chicago working at odd jobs.
Eventually he returned to Hohenwald, married, took up carpentry and
settled down to raise four children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure why I started writing in the beginning,'' Gay
says. ``I was 10 or 12 years old and I thought it would be fun to
make up stories.''
</P>
<P>
   An avid reader, Gay attracted the attention of William Johnson,
his seventh-grade teacher, who gave him copies of books by Faulkner
and Thomas Wolfe. ``I read `Look Homeward, Angel,' at an
impressionable age, I guess. It was a powerful book.''
</P>
<P>
   After he married, Gay continued to write off and on without much
success. He had no idea there were literary journals, and he had
never met a writer. And, he adds, he received little encouragement
at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife was really down on books. She thought that writing was
a waste of time. She said the only thing more foolish than reading
a book was trying to write one.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Gay's wife left him shortly before he sold his
novel. What started out as a relatively simple divorce became more
complicated, Gay says, and he finally gave her the house he had
built himself and moved into a rented cabin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fixed up or nothing,'' he says, finishing his beer,
``but it's quieter there than it is in here.''
</P>
<P>
   `A powerful writer'
</P>
<P>
   Leaving in a white SUV, Gay and his friend Renee Leonard head
out of town for two miles and park in front of a small house set
low to the ground. The blue paint is peeling on the outside, and
inside there are three different kinds of worn linoleum. A
Smith-Corona typewriter sits precariously on a small table beneath
a picture of William Faulkner.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my stuff is still in boxes,'' Gay says, straightening
a row of Bob Dylan CDs on a bookshelf. ``I may not stay here long.
I'm thinking about moving to Oxford (Miss.). I spent some time with
Larry Brown over there recently, and I like it a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, another self-taught writer whose literary landscape is
the hardscrabble, blue-collar South, sees some similarities between
the types of people he and Gay write about in their fiction. ``I
think he writes more like Cormac McCarthy than he does me,'' Brown
says, ``but he's a powerful writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay seems pleased and a bit nonplused to be in such heady
literary company. Taking a seat on the sofa, Gay lights another
cigarette and slowly begins to talk about his 30-year struggle to
get published.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first story I wrote was when I was a kid. I sent a story
to a farm magazine, but they didn't take it. I guess it was because
it was handwritten. I didn't have a typewriter.''
</P>
<P>
   As he matured, he imitated Flannery O'Connor stories and sent
them to Atlantic and Harper's. Form rejections poured in, but
eventually a few of the letters offered constructive criticism and
encouragement. Finally, in 1998, Gay discovered the literary
quarterlies and soon had stories accepted at The Missouri Review
and The Georgia Review.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Michalson, editor of the Missouri Review, remembers the day
``Those Deep Elm Brown's Ferry Blues'' came over the transom.
Michalson, who normally sorts through 10,000 submissions a year to
find 20 or 25 publishable stories, was so impressed he began
passing the story around the office for everyone to read. ``It was
just a magnificent piece of writing,'' he recalls. ``We were bowled
over.''
</P>
<P>
   In his other role as an editor for the Colorado publisher
MacMurray &AMP; Beck, Michalson asked Gay if he had any other work.
``He said he had a novel and sent it to me. It was an extraordinary
read as well. He's got the voice and the craft, and he's got this
sense of being a storyteller.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Gay had tried without success to find a literary
agent. But when New York agent Williams saw his story, ``I Hate to
See That Evening Sun Go Down,'' in the fall 1998 issue of The
Georgia Review, she immediately tried to get in touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so blown away by that story that I went back to my
office and spent a week tracking him down. By that time, he had
sold `The Long Home' to MacMurray &AMP; Beck.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay did, however, have another novel, and Williams lost no time
in negotiating a lucrative deal with Doubleday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 31, who represents 15 mostly young, emerging writers,
was struck by the maturity of Gay's writing. ``He's the real thing.
It was heads above anything else I'd seen. He doesn't dance around
the truth. His characters don't hide from the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   A Faulkner influence
</P>
<P>
   Gay compares his writing process to piecing together a jigsaw
puzzle. He writes a number of scenes, not necessarily in order, and
then tries to fit them together.
</P>
<P>
   Looking in vain for an ashtray, he finally taps the ashes off
his cigarette into the pocket of his denim jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I learned to write by reading,'' he continues. ``I
wasted years trying to write about stuff I didn't know anything
about. I tried to write mystery novels and sophisticated F. Scott
Fitzgerald kind of stuff, but I really didn't know what I was
doing. It only worked when I started writing about my own part of
the country and the people I grew up with. I could hear the
dialogue exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for ``The Long Home'' came from a story he had heard
from an old bootlegger about how people were killed and their
bodies thrown in abandoned wells and cisterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a kind of disquieting thing to think about. I wondered
if it was really true. Hardin (the villain in `The Long Home') sort
of evolved from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Howorth, owner of Square Books in Oxford, loved the book
after being initially astonished that anybody would set a novel in
the 1940s South.
</P>
<P>
   ``That earth has been plowed by others,'' Howorth says, ``but he
managed to write about it successfully. I think he's a terrific
writer. It's clear that he's read Faulkner and Cormac McCarthy, but
his language is rich and original.''
</P>
<P>
   There are pitfalls when it comes to writing about days gone by
in the South, however, and some critics have complained that Gay's
women characters appear to be helpless victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a lot of people don't see is that while some of the women
in `The Long Home' are kind of doormats, this was 40 or 50 years
ago, and most of the women did what their husbands told them to do,
for good or evil,'' Gay says with some annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't have an option since there weren't a lot of jobs.
They were sort of trapped. I don't think you can write something
that's set 50 years ago and make it politically correct for the
1990s. It's absurd, because that's not the way it really was.''
</P>
<P>
   If Gay is overwhelmed by his success, he does not seem surprised
by the praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew my stories were good, even if nobody else thought they
were at the time,'' he says. ``I thought I could write as well as
some of the other writers whose stuff I saw in print. I didn't
think I could be another Faulkner, but I knew I could tell a
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
