<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5596 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-CRUISE-PORTS06-COX     02-03 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-PORTS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alternative ports make cruising convenient for Southern
travelers
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 6.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You've heard of bringing the mountain to Mohammed?
Well, major cruise lines are trying to bring the ocean to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least make it easier for us and our Southern neighbors to
get on their ships. Time was, if you wanted to take a cruise to the
Caribbean or other warm-weather vacation destinations south of the
United States, you had to depart from Miami or Fort Lauderdale. But
thanks to booming business in recent years, major lines have
expanded their Southeastern ports, first to Port Canaveral, about
an hour east of Orlando (it's home to Disney's two ships and
several others), then to Tampa, New Orleans and _ local travelers,
listen up _ Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival Cruise Lines has led the way among the majors in
opening up these ports. In 1994, it began service from Tampa and
New Orleans with its smallest ship, Tropicale (1,022 passengers).
Today, Carnival books weekly trips on two cruisers out of Tampa,
Tropicale and Sensation, and one out of New Orleans, Celebration.
These four-to-seven-day tours hit such hot spots as Grand Cayman,
Cozumel and Jamaica. Last year, the line began offering occasional
sailings to the Bahamas out of Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruises from these ports are definitely on a growth track,''
says Jennifer de la Cruz, a spokeswoman for Carnival. Out of New
Orleans alone, the company's bookings jumped from 28,000 guests in
1994 to 81,500 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this region, you have a huge population that drives to
cruise departures. It's much easier to drive to New Orleans or even
Tampa than Miami,'' de la Cruz explains.
</P>
<P>
   Also, she continues, ``Some people just don't want to come to
South Florida. They feel it will be too congested and not a
positive experience. And these other ports have a lot of tourist
appeal. We have folks who will come to New Orleans and stay a day
or two before leaving on their cruise.''
</P>
<P>
   But before you say ``Miami, Schmiami,'' a word of caution about
the alternative ports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they are not the newest, nicest ships,'' says Carol
Heinrich, a travel agent for Elite Cruise Service in Roswell.
Tropicale, for instance, was built in 1982, Celebration in '87.
Last month, Celebration ran into trouble midcruise. A generator
caught fire, forcing passengers to evacuate in Jamaica. (The
repaired ship is scheduled to relaunch today.)
</P>
<P>
   Heinrich also points out that the Charleston sailings are still
rare _ there are only four scheduled this year _ and they are
sometimes chartered by a single travel agency, which may not offer
the discounts you get when you deal directly with the cruise line
or when the trip is offered to several agencies. ``I just think
people get a better value with the South Florida cruises,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Moses, president of the Cruise Authority in Marietta,
says his agency books few cruises out of the alternative ports, but
he does recommend them for people who don't like to fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have several senior citizens groups that include some
members who won't get on airplanes. They'll charter a bus to New
Orleans and leave from there,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival, at least, is attempting to improve service to these
ports. Two Charleston cruises this fall will be on a brand-new
ship, Victory, and New Orleans' Celebration is being replaced by
the larger, newer Inspiration in September.
</P>
<P>
   But the Miami Convention and Visitors Bureau shouldn't start to
sweat just yet. ``These ports are still a novelty,'' Moses says.
``There's nothing out there to challenge South Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
