<P>
   CALIF-CAMPAIGN (Los Angeles) _ For years, California has been
the overgrown stepchild of presidential nominating politics, the
most populous state with a primary election too late on the
calendar to matter much. For even longer, it has been the state
that the rest of the nation loves to mock as a collection of kooks,
cultists, cranky conservatives and tanned blond airheads that has
produced politicians as diverse as Ronald Reagan and Jerry Brown.
But this year, with its moved-up March 7 primary, California stands
poised to be dispositive in choosing the nominees of both major
parties. And because of a new primary voting system that is, well,
a little bit kooky, California will be something just as important:
the first state where all the candidates appear on the same ballot,
regardless of party, in a preview of where its crucial 54 electoral
votes might go in the general election next fall. By Todd S.
Purdum.
</P>
