<SLUG> BC-GAY-BIO06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    William Gay bio box
 &HT;    Eds: Emabargoed for Sunday, Feb. 6.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  AGE: 56.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BIRTHPLACE:
</P>
<P>
   Hohenwald, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FAMILY: Divorced, four children.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WORK HISTORY: Carpenter, drywall hanger, bricklayer, painter,
roofer, post hole digger and television tube assembly line worker.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  AWARDS: William Peden Prize from The
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Review; nominated for 1999 book of the year by the
Southeastern
</P>
<P>
   Booksellers Association.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NEXT PROJECT: ``Provinces of Night,'' a novel set 10 years
after ``The Long Home,'' set for fall publication from
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST LOOK: An excerpt from ``The Long Home''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Hardin had taken on the lineaments of evil. You
would sometimes see him on a Saturday streetcorner, the center of a
group of men itemizing the faults of the world. When he spoke men
listened. He seldom laughed but when he did the rest of the men
laughed too in sporadic bursts of mirthless noise. No one wanted to
be in his disfavor, it had come to seem that being in his disfavor
was tantamount to being homeless. ...
</P>
<P>
   Hardin's vulpine face was leaner and more cunning than ever, the
cold yellow eyes more reptilian. Or sharklike, perhaps, lifeless
and blank save a perpetual look of avarice. And he went through
life the way a shark feeds, taking into its belly anything that
attracts its attention, sucking it into the hot maw of darkness and
drawing nourishment from that which contained it, expelling what
did not.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
