<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5601 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS06-COX     02-03 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Life Stories' profiles The New Yorker's writerly prowess
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 6
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is February, which means that in a week or two Eustace Tilley
makes his annual appearance on the cover of The New Yorker
magazine, a ritual bow to tradition and to the ghosts of E.B. White
and James Thurber, Joseph Mitchell and founding editor Harold Ross.
Tilley, the fop peering at a butterfly through his monocle, was Rea
Irvin's cover illustration for the magazine's premiere issue on
Feb. 21, 1925.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker would have turned 75 this year _ ``would have''
because a one-time star contributor, Renata Adler, has pronounced
it in rigor mortis. There are those who thought it died years ago,
but the fact is that it still comes out weekly. Premature or not
(and surely it is), Adler's bitter obituary _ ``Gone: The Last Days
of The New Yorker'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) _ and the contretemps
it has provoked suggest that The New Yorker still has what few
publications can ever claim: the capacity to arouse passion.
</P>
<P>
   There are people who cherish The New Yorker for its quirks as
much as for its cartoons, for its fussiness as much as for its
detachment from fashions and trends. Now under only its fifth
editor in 75 years but its third since the sainted William Shawn
was shown the door in 1987, The New Yorker is a different magazine
from the one its most loyal readers remember. But in one respect _
the Profiles that can go on for pages and pages, and sometimes from
one issue to the next _ it is the same.
</P>
<P>
   On its 75th anniversary, a collection of New Yorker profiles,
along with a collection of short fiction, commemorates a form The
New Yorker more than any other publication helped to create. ``Life
Stories: Profiles From The New Yorker'' bridges the magazine's past
and present by displaying what it has always done differently from
any other _ a writer in leisurely immersion in a single subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Profile,'' as David Remnick, the magazine's current
editor, writes, ``is ubiquitous in modern journalism. We are awash
in pieces calling themselves profiles that are about the inner
thoughts of some celebrity; more often than not they are based on
half-hour interviews and the parameters set down by a vigilant
publicist.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the term and the form have become cliches, the one
meaningless shop talk, the other a prisoner of formulaic rules.
Nothing of the sort characterized a New Yorker profile, and this is
what gave it its identity and its strength as a literary form.
</P>
<P>
   Not that a New Yorker profile couldn't, sometimes, present
problems of its own. Joseph Mitchell, whom Malcolm Cowley once
called the best reporter in the country, had the suspicious gift of
recalling page upon page of conversation, years after it took
place. Yet it was Mitchell's understated style and his sense for
physical detail that became hallmarks of the form.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's piece ``Mr. Hunter's Grave,'' whose subject is an
87-year-old widower who tends the graves of his two wives, his name
on the headstone of one, his future resting place beside the other,
is the first of 25 profiles (``because I love it so'') that Remnick
has selected for a book that ranges from Truman Capote on Marlon
Brando to Susan Orlean on a show dog named Biff. (First sentence:
``If I were a bitch, I'd be in love with Biff Truesdale.'') There
are, as Remnick says, profiles whose animating impulse is malice
(Wolcott Gibbs on Time's Henry Luce) or praise (Joan Acocella on
Mikhail Baryshnikov), others whose theme is identity (Henry Louise
Gates Jr. on Anatole Broyard) or ``the strangeness of American
fame'' (Kenneth Tynan on Johnny Carson).
</P>
<P>
   And a few that are just hard to categorize, such as Ian Frazier
on Heloise.
</P>
<P>
   Disparate as their subjects might be, one quality, as Remnick
writes, connects nearly all of them _ ``a sense of obsession.'' The
Chudnovsky brothers, profiled by Richard Preston, are obsessed with
the number pi _ 3.14 _ and with finding a pattern in randomness.
Calvin Trillin's Edna Buchanan is an obsessive crime reporter in
Miami who visits the scenes of disaster four, five times a day.
</P>
<P>
   From piece to piece, the voices are those of a single writer and
his subject. Seldom are third parties summoned from the wings to
provide an obligatory quote or two and then sent on their way. The
result is an intimacy and immediacy that come from the subject
himself, not the chatter of others.
</P>
<P>
   There are results of another kind as well, and a good example is
John McPhee's ``Travels in Georgia.'' Over the years McPhee has
lost some readers with his excursions into plate tectonics and
other geologic arcana, but in this piece he shows how good English
prose is concrete and visual, built from nouns and verbs. He is
with Atlanta natives Carol Ruckdeschel and Sam Candler, a pair of
ecologists out looking for road kill. Here he describes their
coming upon a snapping turtle that has been hit by a pickup:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam reversed. He drove backward rapidly, as fast as the car
would go. He stopped on the shoulder, and we all got out. There was
a pond beyond the turtle. The big, broad head was shining with
blood, but there was, as yet, very little blood on the road. The
big jaws struck as we came near, opened and closed bloodily _ not
the kind of strike that, minutes ago, could have cut off a finger,
but still a strike with power. The bright spots on its marginal
scutes were like light bulbs in a mirror. The neck lunged out.
Carol urged the turtle, with her foot, toward the side of the road.
`I know, big man,' she said to it. `I know it's bad. We're not
tormenting you. Honest, we're not.' Sam asked her if she thought it
had a chance to live and she said she was sure it had no chance at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   In pieces such as these, The New Yorker has been at its most
vital, a magazine that, in Adler's words, neither chased after
readers nor pandered to them. If it ran ``absolutely counter to the
mentality of subscription surveys, focus groups and polls,'' so
much the better. It was what it was, sure of its readers because it
was sure of itself.
</P>
<P>
   MORE ABOUT THE NEW YORKER
</P>
<P>
   Over the past quarter century, dozens of books have been written
about The New Yorker and the personalities that shaped it. To mark
the magazine's 75th anniversary, a few more join the ranks. Among
them:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wonderful Town: New York Stories From The New Yorker, edited
by David Remnick (Random House, $26.95). Short fiction from writers
ranging from John Cheever to Maeve Brennan to Jamaica Kincaid, all
set in the singular city.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About Town: The New Yorker and the World It Made by Ben Yagoda
(Scribner, $27.50). Drawing freely from the magazine's archives and
from hundreds of interviews with editors, writers and longtime
readers, this is an analytical history of the publication itself,
not so much the people behind it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Letters From the Editor: The New Yorker's Harold Ross, edited
by Thomas Kunkel (Random House, $26.95). In hundreds of
fascinating, fierce, funny letters, we witness the magazine founder
</P>
<P>
   ``lecturing Orson Welles, baiting J. Edgar Hoover, inviting Noel
Coward and Ginger Rogers to the circus, wheedling Ernest Hemingway
(`Are you ever going to write any short stories again? My God.'),
offering to sell Harpo Marx a used car ... and
</P>
<P>
   explaining to restaurateur-to-the-stars Dave Chasen, step by
step, how to smoke a turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Some Times in America: And a Life in a Year at The New Yorker
by Alexander Chancellor (Carroll &AMP; Graf, $25). With wry,
self-deprecating wit, the
</P>
<P>
   British journalist recalls his year spent editing Talk of the
Town for Tina Brown.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Janet, My Mother and Me by William Murray
</P>
<P>
   (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $24). Murray, a former staff writer at The
New
</P>
<P>
   Yorker, recounts a childhood spent with his mother, Natalia
Danesi
</P>
<P>
   Murray, and her longtime lover, Janet Flanner, who wrote the
acclaimed ``Letter From Paris'' column.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Life Stories: Profiles From The New Yorker. Edited by David
Remnick. Random House. $26.95.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
