<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5602 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-STYLE-DIAMONDS06-COX     02-03 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-DIAMONDS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The ring's the thing: Use your head, heart when buying diamond
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 6.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hey, fellas, listen up.
</P>
<P>
   The most romantic thing you can give your lady love for
Valentine's Day is a marriage proposal. The next most romantic is a
diamond engagement ring to let her know you're serious.
</P>
<P>
   But buying a diamond on impulse is as risky as rushing to the
altar that way. So it would pay to heed the following pointers,
from local jewelry experts and a groom to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to buy it: ``Shop around,'' advises Bret Cottick, a
29-year-old software consultant from Alpharetta who recently
surprised his girlfriend, Lisa Flaccus, with a solitaire diamond
engagement ring. ``You can find the same types of diamonds with the
same certificate at many, many stores throughout Atlanta. Go with
someone you trust.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What's hot on the market: A colorless or slightly white
diamond in a platinum setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are returning to the classics,'' says Tom Carroll
of Tiffany &AMP; Co. ``Platinum continues to be the (band) color of
choice. It's about 85 percent of what we sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris J. Botnick, owner of Worthmore Jewelers in Atlanta,
agrees. ``Anything platinum is popular,'' he says. ``People realize
it has a lot of advantages over white and yellow gold. Platinum is
more rare, which adds to its popularity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What to look for in a diamond: They're still defined by the
``four C's'':
</P>
<P>
   Carat _ The size of the diamond. It's a matter of budget and
personal preference.
</P>
<P>
   Color _ Diamonds are graded from A to Z. The earlier the letter
in the alphabet, the better the color. For example, stones with a D
to F grade are free of color and fall within the top color range,
because of their rarity. Diamonds graded G to I are in the medium
price range and have a slight white color. Diamonds with J to Z
grades are yellow or brownish in color and are of lower quality.
</P>
<P>
   Clarity _ Refers to the visible marks inside or on the surface
of the diamond. A top-quality stone will have no marks visible to
the naked eye. A diamond with low clarity has prominent markings.
</P>
<P>
   Cut _ Indicates the proportions in which the stone was cut to
make it sparkle. Also consider the shape in which it was cut, such
as marquis, oval, round, square, emerald, pear, heart or
rectangular.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Should you shop for the ring alone or take your intended with
you? It's a matter of personal preference. Many men take their
girlfriends with them to make sure they get a style she likes. But
there are others, such as Cottick, who'd rather pick it out alone,
so the engagement ring comes as a total surprise when they propose.
``I don't think you need to drag her along,'' Cottick says. ``If
you're getting ready to ask someone to marry you and you don't know
what her taste in jewelry is, you should think hard about what
you're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
