<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5604 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-STYLE-DREADLOCKS06-CO     02-03 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-DREADLOCKS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New coffee-table book looks at the intriguing hairstyle called
dreadlocks
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 6.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something both off-putting and intriguing about ``dread
heads.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that duality in attitudes toward dreadlocked hair, combined
with the power of good black-and-white photography and this era's
fascination with testimonials, that could cause you to acquire
``Dreads'' (Artisan, $35), a new coffee-table book by Italian
lensmen Francesco Mastalia and Alfonse Pagano.
</P>
<P>
   As Pulitzer Prize-winning author Alice Walker writes in the
book's foreword, explaining why she dreaded her own hair a decade
ago: ``I wondered what such hair felt like, smelled like.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the hairstyles mankind has manifested, dreadlocks may be
the most curious. And, truly, some of the 100 dreaded hairstyles
that these two shutterbugs immortalized have the look of matted
cats.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, the sight of a dreaded head gets us, as
Walker puts it, ``aroused.'' Mating with someone who chooses a
matted mane, she writes, ``must be like the mating of lions.''
</P>
<P>
   And so we look, stare even, and wonder. Dread heads peer into
the mirror and do the same.
</P>
<P>
   As this book points out, Africans and Asians, Australians,
Caucasians and Jamaicans apply such words as ``sacred,''
``natural'' and ``liberating'' to their unbrushed heads. But dare
to approach a dread and ask for a succinct explanation of why their
hair is that way, and you may get a halting, uncertain response.
</P>
<P>
   The dreadlocked Atlantans we approached and ultimately
photographed were no exception. Some took weeks to form their
responses. Their looks spoke volumes, perhaps more than their
testimonials ever could.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio ``DJ Gato'' Soca, 23
</P>
<P>
   College student, /DJ, 23
</P>
<P>
   ``My locks represent myself and my personality. By no means is
it a hairstyle or fashion statement. I take pride in my dreads;
they aren't the easiest to carry around. There are people who love
to prejudge other people who don't look a certain way or may look a
little out of the ordinary. But people's opinions don't move me at
all. Still I love my locks, and now that my mother does too, it
makes it more enjoyable and worthwhile. The ocean and other dreads'
positive vibes contributed to my decision to undergo lockdown.''
Turtleneck ($60) by Ralph Lauren, from Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Jayne Maxamilliah Noflin, 38
</P>
<P>
   Office administrator, 38
</P>
<P>
   ``I began locking my hair in 1994, which (signaled) the death of
Jannie Marie Noflin-Hegamin and the rebirth of `Maxamilliah.' I
never intended to grow dreadlocks; it seemed to me at the time so
permanent, and I was not willing to make the commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I was residing in Manhattan Beach, Calif. I love
the ocean. My original plan was to embrace my ethnicity by sporting
an Afro and occasionally twisting my hair. However, the combination
of the salt water and my hair fell in love with each other; my hair
naturally started locking. Meanwhile, my spirituality began to
flourish as well. As I stepped into my spirituality and loving
myself, I decided to lock my hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having locks is like removing a veil from my eyes. I see
people and my environment through different eyes. Bottom line:
Having my locks has been a blessed event for me. I am no longer
lost. I am on the path.'' Sweater dress ($400) by Missoni, from
Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Consuela Brooks,
</P>
<P>
   Poet/songwriter, 22
</P>
<P>
   ``As of this month, I've had my dreads for five years. My locks
are a constant reminder of unity. People would say I'm weakening my
locks because I lighten them. But I disagree. To me, it shows my
inner fire.'' Blouse ($35) and skirt ($50) from TriBeCa, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Ase ``Red Wadz'' Anderson,
</P>
<P>
   Entertainer, 27
</P>
<P>
   ``Locks have been with me for eight years and represent my bond
with my mother, nature, and my link to Father Time. They are the
roots that strengthen my life.'' Velvet burnout shirt ($90) from
TriBeCa, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   TO LEARN MORE ABOUT DREADLOCKS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.dreadlocks.com _ A shopping resource for products,
services and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.dreadheading.com _ An outreach site for the dread
community worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.knottyboy.com _ A youth-oriented site with instruction,
bulletin boards, chats and e-tailing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
