<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     02-03 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON A NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DIRECTIONS: ``New Directions'' (Blue Note).
</P>
<P>
   The history of Blue Note Records in the 1950s and '60s is both
routinely fetishized and dulled. There's no other period of jazz
from which the documents are so beautiful: Reid Miles'
constructivist album-cover designs, Francis Wolff's tenebrous
photographs of musicians in the studio, the intimate, resonating
sound created for them by the engineer Rudy Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   And yet when the average group of young jazz musicians these
days decides to play a classic tune associated with the label from
that period, like Lee Morgan's ``Sidewinder'' or Joe Henderson's
``Recorda Me,'' watch out for musical diffidence, the stuff that
gives jazz a stodgy name, with no apparent will to update those
strong little melodies and small-group arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   So what's really impressive about the album by New Directions _
a special band made of current players on the Blue Note label,
including Greg Osby, Stefon Harris, Mark Shim and Jason Moran, who
were given the opportunity to record their choice of tunes from
Blue Note's history _ is how unlabored and efficacious their
reworkings of these tunes are.
</P>
<P>
   This is an album that sets the mark for what cool is in jazz at
the moment, not only in playing but also in conception. Every tune
is reworked from scratch: where there was a vamp in a piano's bass
clef, it has been transferred to a higher register on a different
instrument and reharmonized; where there was a dominant rhythm,
like the bossa nova beat in Horace Silver's ``Song for My Father,''
it's been wiped away without a trace.
</P>
<P>
   Lingering chords from Harris' vibraphone and Moran's piano,
pushing against the time of the rhythm section, add an air of
watery irresolution and mystery to the tunes; Osby and Shim's
saxophone lines are clean and darting, and the drummer Nasheet
Waits maintains a balletic, rising-and-falling stammer on the snare
drum and ride cymbal.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox of this repertory-centered record is that there's a
true group sound at work: there's such an intuitive comfort in the
musicians' interaction that whatever repertory they choose is
ultimately unimportant.
</P>
<P>
   Still, judicious thought was given to material, which ranges
from the hits and modern standards by Morgan, Henderson and Horace
Silver to much lesser known pieces like Sam Rivers' ballad
``Beatrice'' (here done as a duet for piano and vibraphone), Wayne
Shorter's ``Ping Pong,'' and some beguiling originals by members of
the group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1709EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5611 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER04-COX     02-03 1499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: End of the road for Bauer
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, the janitor's son who served in the Reagan White
House and mounted a presidential bid of his own, has decided to
drop out of the race, according to news outlets citing anonymous
sources close to the conservative activist. His campaign said today
that Bauer would hold a news conference Friday morning, but did not
reveal details of the event _ but he is expected to announce his
withdrawal then.
</P>
<P>
   THE REST OF THE FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley was campaigning in San Francisco. Al Gore also was
in California before flying to Washington state for an event in
Olympia. John McCain and Georgia W. Bush were in South Carolina,
with Bush breaking off for an event in Detroit. Steve Forbes was on
a bus tour of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   THE MIDAS TOUCH
</P>
<P>
   Like the fairy tale character who spun straw into gold, John
McCain is turning his New Hampshire win into green. Since Tuesday's
victory, McCain has raised more than $740,000 through his campaign
Web site and thousands more at a fund-raiser in South Carolina. In
addition, the site logged 4,000 new volunteers. ``I'm humbled and
gratified that so many people would support my message of
conservative independent reform,'' McCain said today. At the rate
he's going, McCain could top the million-dollar mark by Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   KERREY KNOWS THE TRUTH WHEN HE HEARS IT
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley is demanding that Al Gore apologize for the actions
of some campaign staffers who reportedly mocked Sen. Bob Kerrey
(D-Neb.), who has been campaigning for Bradley. Bradley: ``Gore
people demeaned him and called him a cripple. They threw mud, and I
think ... he ought to take responsibility for those actions and
ought to apologize.'' Kerrey, who lost a leg in Vietnam, took it a
bit easier, saying that calling him a cripple ``was the only honest
thing they said all day.''
</P>
<P>
   VEGAS COULD HAVE TAKEN A BEATING
</P>
<P>
   Most polls had a pretty good grip on the winners in New
Hampshire, but the margin of victory was a bit slippery. Most
picked Al Gore to win the Democratic primary and John McCain to win
the Republican contest. But almost nobody anticipated McCain's
18-point spread, winning not only the independents but the
registered Republicans, too. Gore's four-point margin was close to
the mark.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE'S GEORGE?
</P>
<P>
   When California Republicans meet this weekend in Sacramento to
size up presidential candidates, there will be a very conspicuous
absence: George W. Bush is skipping the gathering for the third
straight time, sending his brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush to speak
on his behalf. The W. will be in Michigan when the convention opens
Friday, and will spend most of the weekend resting in Texas after
an 18-day sprint through Iowa and New Hampshire. John McCain will
be at the convention, though, speaking on his own behalf.
</P>
<P>
   TWO WEEKS TILL SOUTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   The next crucial decision in the 2000 presidential primary
season will be made Feb. 19 by Republican voters in South Carolina.
It's ``Bush country,'' claims George W. Bush, suddenly struggling
to recover from the whipping by John McCain in New Hampshire. But
with its long military tradition and large military population,
South Carolina really could be McCain country. The state has a
natural place in its heart for the surging war hero and POW in
Vietnam. Two polls released Thursday show the Bush and McCain
statistically even.
</P>
<P>
   LINE THEM UP, SEE WHO SALUTES
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush collected endorsements from retired generals and
war heroes Thursday. His endorsements came from a parade of
veterans' groups, Medal of Honor winners and former general
officers, led by retired Adm. Thomas Moorer. But continuing to
question Bush's fitness to lead, John McCain said he wouldn't need
``on-the-job training'' as commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   HE'S GOT QUAYLE _ THAT SHOULD CLINCH IT
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle threw his support to George W. Bush, describing him
as the candidate with the values as well as the other
qualifications to be president. ``We know that we have prosperity
today, but let us be very clear that prosperity without values is
no prosperity at all,'' Quayle added. Shortly before Quayle dropped
out of the presidential race in August, his South Carolina campaign
aides left him to support John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLY PREPARED
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of just how close Al Gore's advisers thought they were
coming to losing in New Hampshire, ABC reports, his speechwriters
had drafted two versions of a speech for delivery Tuesday night.
Throughout the day, according to ABC, Gore aides were having
heartburn over exit polls that at some points showed Bradley ahead.
The staff was still editing the losing speech even as the winning
results started coming in.
</P>
<P>
   NAUGHTY-NAUGHTY, THEY GOT CAUGHTY
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the New York state GOP answered a challenge by Steve
Forbes by admitting in court that Republicans in Brooklyn and the
Bronx used fraudulent signatures to try to get George W. Bush on
the March 7 presidential primary ballot in their districts. The
admission means no Bush delegates will appear on primary ballots in
the 16th Congressional District, which covers part of the Bronx.
The 10th District frauds were committed only by people seeking to
become alternates, so the regular Bush delegates can remain on the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   JUST INVESTIGATE WHEN DEMOCRATS DO IT
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party is suing the Federal Election Commission
over the agency's decision to drop an investigation of foreign
donations to the Republican Party. At issue is a $2.1 million
donation in 1994 from a Hong Kong businessman, Ambrous Young. The
contribution was solicited by then-party Chairman Haley Barbour.
The FEC's general counsel had recommended proceeding, but the
commission deadlocked 3-3 along party lines and dropped the case,
according to records made public.
</P>
<P>
   THEY'RE JUST BLOWING SMOKE RINGS
</P>
<P>
   John McCain was greeted in South Carolina with ads bashing him
for supporting a tobacco tax increase favored by President Clinton.
The ads by the National Smokers Alliance, based in Alexandria, Va.,
are scheduled to run through the week in Columbia, Charleston and
Florence. ``I'm honored by their opposition,'' McCain said at the
University of South Carolina. ``There's no other group I would
rather be attacked by.''
</P>
<P>
   NO SWIMSUITS OR SASHES
</P>
<P>
   In the world of politics, some presidential primaries and straw
polls are just beauty contests that allow voters to express their
opinions, but have nothing to do with selecting delegates. Delaware
this weekend is an example. The state's Democratic Party is having
a primary Saturday, but won't actually allocate its 22 delegates
until caucuses held throughout the state on March 27.
</P>
<P>
   WITH CATLIKE TREAD, UPON HIS OPPONENT HE STEALS
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Rudy Giuliani has no intention of announcing
that he's running for the Senate from New York. But it's not that
he doesn't want to; it's just that the only time he ever formally
announced an elective run _ in 1989, his first shot at the New York
City mayoralty _ he lost. So he said he plans to stealthily become
a candidate ``in the middle of the night,'' presenting a stark
contrast to Sunday's gala campaign kickoff by adversary Hillary
Rodham Clinton, which he calls a ``Hollywood kind of
extravaganza.''
</P>
<P>
   THE JOYS OF THE COMMUTER SHUTTLE
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service agents called it unprecedented: a vice president
sitting on a commercial flight, snoozing like any other New
York-to-Washington commuter. That was early Wednesday morning, when
Al Gore had to make a mad dash to D.C. for a possible tie-breaking
Senate vote and Air Force Two wasn't ready. But there he was,
trying to sleep with his head tipped against the window, ignoring
the bagel snack on his tray. He also had to ignore the interview
with George W. Bush on the overhead TV. Gore did wake up in time to
bring his seat back into the full upright position, and close and
lock his tray table like a good passenger.
</P>
<P>
   JUST SIMPLE, OLD-FASHIONED MERCHANDIZING
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura's campaign committee, which didn't
hold any traditional fund-raising events last year, took in more
than $137,000 in 1999, most of it from sales of action figures and
other Venturabilia. The fund-raising is modest for a sitting
governor, and the way it was raised is perhaps unprecedented: no
contributions from lobbyists or political action committees, only
about a dozen individual donors who gave more than $100 apiece, and
not one who gave the nonelection-year limit of $500.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
