<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
  
 RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MISSED IT
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1714EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-BOVARY-SPI &LR;      02-03 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BOVARY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MASTERPIECE THEATER' PRODUCTION OF `BOVARY' IS SINFULLY SENSUOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Emma Bovary were around today, what do you suppose she'd be
reading? Cosmopolitan? Victoria's Secret? Architectural Digest?
</P>
<P>
   In Gustave Flaubert's randy tale of a narcissistic, unsatiable
dreamer, the beautiful-but-bored Madame Bovary finds escape in the
romantic novels and society journals of her day _ the mid-19th
century. An early proponent of the school of style that proclaims
it is better to look good than feel good, Emma Bovary is the
reflection of modern-day styloids for whom image is everything.
</P>
<P>
   Without giving away too much of the story in the new ``Madame
Bovary'' for PBS's ``Masterpiece Theatre,'' Emma's mirror
eventually cracks and we are left to assume that shallow
materialism and the preference for beauty over morality are
inadvisable career options.
</P>
<P>
   No big shocker there, but this co-production of WGBH Boston and
the BBC is so sumptuous, so sensuous, that fans of PBS's
``Masterpiece Theatre'' shouldn't mind the fairly obvious track.
Frances O'Connor, currently gracing movie screens in the Miramax
version of Jane Austen's ``Mansfield Park,'' brings such honest
yearning to ``Bovary'' that it's hard not to like her, despite her
cuckolding the devoted but painfully pedestrian country doctor she
married for all the wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that the other man's grass is greener, not to mention
more fun to roll around in, Emma pursues sexual ecstasy the way a
retriever chases a stick. Suffering terminal ennui in a one-sided
marriage, Emma comes back for more, more, more passion because
suitors keep throwing her lifelines a la Regis Philbin. Well, not
exactly. Regis keeps his clothes on in ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so Rodolphe (Greg Wise), the hunky cad who wins Emma's heart
by taking her on a canter through the Norman countryside. A few
grass stains later, Emma is so smitten that reality for her is
forever altered. She has a beautiful daughter, a loving husband
who'll do anything for her and a spacious house that is comfortably
appointed, yet her idea of the perfect life bears no resemblance to
the one she comes home to after her licentious assignations.
</P>
<P>
   The chief catalyst for her domestic dissatisfaction is Charles,
her husband. Although hardly passionless, the affectionate,
attentive Charles is no match for Emma's fantasies. Hugh
Bonneville, who appears with O'Connor in ``Mansfield Park'' as a
well-heeled dandy, plays pretty much the opposite as Charles. The
quintessential ``nice guy'' _ well-meaning, educated, considerate _
Charles is the sort of man some desperate women dream about.
Bonneville plays him not as a one-dimensional dolt but as a simple
man with simple tastes and needs. It's this subtle but important
difference that allows O'Connor to achieve a Madame Bovary who is
at once despicable and delectable. Hugh Dancy, as another of Emma's
lovers, artfully brings the necessary ingredient of youthful
indiscretion to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   The film airs in two 90-minute segments, one this Sunday, the
other Feb. 13. The second half is more satisfying, with faster
pacing and more interesting plot points. But O'Connor and
Bonneville do such faithful justice to Flaubert's main characters
that sitting through a less-than-stellar Part I is hardly a chore.
</P>
<P>
   Madame Bovary. Three-hour ``Masterpiece Theatre'' film about a
middle-class Frenchwoman's quest for passion in her life. Starring
Frances O'Connor, Greg Wise, Hugh Bonneville, Hugh Dancy, Trevor
Peacock and Keith Barron. Airing in two parts, Sunday and Feb. 13,
on PBS. Check local listing. Parental guideline rating: TV-MA.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1714EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VODAFONE-MANNESMANN-A     02-03 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-MANNESMANN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANNESMANN AGREES TO BE ACQUIRED BY VODAFONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN and EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUSSELDORF, Germany _ Ending a brutal struggle to dominate
Europe's insatiable market for wireless communications, a company
that was until recently a relative unknown name outside Britain on
Thursday rammed through the biggest takeover deal in history.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after attempting the biggest hostile takeover bid
in history, Vodafone Airtouch PLC of Britain achieved a stunning
victory Thursday morning when Mannesmann AG of Germany surrendered
and agreed to be acquired for about $170 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   It is the biggest corporate takeover on any continent, eclipsing
the previous record set less than three weeks ago _ America Online
Inc.'s $165 billion deal to buy Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   If consummated, the takeover will create the world's biggest
wireless communications company, one that dominates the European
market and also has major holdings in the United States, Asia and
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal is even more important as a watershed in European
corporate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has a European company carried off a hostile
takeover on such an audacious scale: cross-border, cross-cultural
and financed with shares in a company that most Germans had never
heard of until a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented hostile bid outraged many German leaders,
including Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who attacked it as a
violation of Germany's tradition of consensus that could lead to
the dismantlement of a revered German company.
</P>
<P>
   But in a major departure from traditional European practice,
Mannesmann avoided any attempt to seek political protection and
waged its battle by appealing directly to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   When it became obvious this week that shareholders were ready to
sell out, Mannesmann's embattled chief executive, Klaus Esser,
reluctantly sued for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement reached after hours of bargaining at
Mannesmann headquarters here Wednesday night, Esser agreed to
endorse a peaceful takeover in which Vodafone will issue millions
of new shares to buy out Mannesmann shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes just four days before the expiration of
Vodafone's hostile bid to Mannesmann shareholders. And although it
is nominally a ``friendly'' merger, Esser only capitulated when it
became obvious that a majority of his shareholders were about to
sell out.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann shareholders will end up with about 49.5 percent of
the combined company's stock, and Esser will resign from the
company in favor of Vodafone's chief executive, Chris Gent.
</P>
<P>
   If Vodafone shares hold their value, the agreement will become a
huge bonanza for Mannesmann shareholders. At current stock prices,
the Vodafone offer is worth more than 330 euros per share _ more
than double the price that Mannesmann shares were trading at before
the takeover battle began last fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal is a bitter defeat for Esser, who passionately
fought to preserve his company's independence. It is also a shock
for Mannesmann, an old-line industrial conglomerate that had
brilliantly transformed itself into the biggest provider of
wireless communications in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Gent also outmaneuvered Esser on the chessboard of Europe's
wireless industry, which is based on a handful of immensely
valuable national wireless licenses in each country.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann owns national networks in Germany, Italy and Britain.
Vodafone owns Britain's second-largest network and scores of other
stakes around Europe and on other continents.
</P>
<P>
   Gent's biggest victory came last Sunday, when Vodafone managed
to steal one of Mannesmann's longtime allies _ Vivendi SA of
France.
</P>
<P>
   That move derailed Esser's desperate attempt to hammer out a
merger with Vivendi, which would have given him control of a major
French network and greatly strengthened his position with
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But Gent cut his own deal with Vivendi's chairman, Jean-Marie
Messier, by forming a joint venture in Internet services. That deal
convinced wavering shareholders that Esser had lost the upper hand,
even with his allies, and they immediately began betting on a
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will control wireless networks in Europe's
three biggest markets _ Britain, Germany and Italy _ along with a
45-percent stake in the biggest U.S. network and holdings in more
than 30 other countries from Sweden and Poland to India and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Though Europe has witnessed a surge of big hostile takeovers in
the last two years, the takeover of Mannesmann makes history on
several fronts besides its sheer size.
</P>
<P>
   Though Europe has seen a surge of hostile takeovers, the only
successful ones have occurred between competitors within a single
European nation.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for Mannesmann marks one of the first real battles
for the entire European market, one in which both the combatants
recognized that the economic integration of Europe and the adoption
of a single currency in eleven countries made it crucial to
overcome national boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   The battle also marks one of the first cases in which national
political leaders did not try to interfere in order to protect an
important domestic company.
</P>
<P>
   When three of France's biggest banks plunged into a heated
takeover battle last year, it was largely sanctioned and guided by
the French Ministry of Finance, which wanted to consolidate the
nation's banking industry and keep out foreign bidders.
</P>
<P>
   The same was true when Totalfina SA, the French-Belgian oil
company, launched a successful hostile takeover of Elf Aquitaine
SA. Likewise, Italian political leaders actively opposed the
proposed telephone merger between Deutsche Telekom of Germany and
Telecom Italia in favor of a hostile bid by Italy's Olivetti SPA.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the reaction was entirely different. Despite the
angry rhetoric from German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder about the
dangers of hostile takeovers, the German government stayed out of
the fight entirely.
</P>
<P>
   That reflected a widespread view among German executives that it
was far more dangerous to interfere with a legitimate if hostile
bid and jeopardize the ability of German companies like
DaimlerChrysler to buy up foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Esser and Gent waged their battle almost entirely
through direct appeals to shareholders themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
