<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5618 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-SCREAM-SPI &LR;      02-03 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SCREAM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITTY `SCREAM 3' IS _ OH, YES _ STILL A SLASHER FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM PETERSON  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Kevin Williamson left his screenwriting job after the first
two ``Screams,'' there was worry among fans that ``Scream 3'' could
fall into the dreaded third-movie-in-a-trilogy letdown that not
even director Wes Craven, one of the masters of horror, could save.
</P>
<P>
   However, Craven, who also directed ``Scream'' and ``Scream 2,''
was more than up to the task with new writer Ehren Kruger
(``Arlington Road''), delivering one of the better second sequels
of any genre, not just horror films.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Prescott (Neve Campbell) is back again from her narrow
escapes in the previous two bloodbaths, living and working alone in
the bunker-like conditions of her rural home.
</P>
<P>
   However, in Hollywood on the set of ``Stab 3,'' the second
sequel to the film-within-a-film of ``Scream 2,'' dead bodies are
starting to pile up. The evil cell phone prankster with the ghost
mask seems to be shaking things up yet again in his search for the
ever elusive Sidney.
</P>
<P>
   Other surviving characters who make the return trip include the
overly ambitious TV reporter Gale Weathers (Courtney Cox Arquette)
and the Barney Fife of horror films, former Deputy Dewey Riley
(David Arquette), who is now the technical consultant for ``Stab
3.''
</P>
<P>
   When the original ``Scream'' was released, it set a new standard
for youth horror films, made a killing at the box office and
unfortunately inspired many forgettable knockoffs throughout the
later portion of the 1990s. ``Scream 2'' bucked the trend of hollow
movie sequels by retaining the original's smarts and self-parody by
using a movie-within-a-movie premise that was based on ``Scream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scream 3'' also has wit and intelligence, but at their core
the ``Scream'' movies are still slasher films and this one is no
exception. The usual trimmings are here, with lots of blood, plenty
of screaming and continual checking of the pulses of horribly
eviscerated people to see if they are indeed truly dead.
</P>
<P>
   But what has always set the ``Scream'' movies apart from other
teen horror dreck is their witty dialogue, surprising plot twists
and ability to make fun of themselves. Kruger delivers a clever
script, even if it pales a bit in comparison to Williamson's savvy
writing.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, Cox Arquette and Arquette give convincing performances
as the three people who truly have the worst luck in the known
universe. The true standout of the film, however, is former
indie-queen Parker Posey, showing yet again that her acting chops
are ready for more major studio roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scream 3'' also keeps true to the series' tradition of playing
like a mystery as the plot twists and turns, keeping the audience
in suspense as to who (or what) the killer really is.
</P>
<P>
   Without giving anything away, the ending felt a bit
anti-climactic after the build-up through three movies. To be fair
though, most endings to good series never seem to feel quite right
since our expectations rarely match the result.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Craven hasn't lost his horror film touch. But even
though he is currently moving away from the genre (``Music of the
Heart''), his slasher smarts with Kruger's fun and smart script put
a nice finish on a scary franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Scream 3. Directed by Wes Craven. Written by Ehren Kruger. Cast:
David Arquette, Neve Campbell, Courtney Cox Arquette, Parker Posey.
Dimension Films. 116 minutes. Rated R for graphic violence,
language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1723EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
