<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5619 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-N     02-03 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW FAITH IN MEDIEVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Mich.,   Germany, Austria, Portugal, the Netherlands,
Switzerland, Britain)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By   WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than ever, people seem to be in search of what
is truly ``authentic.'' They want authentic political candidates,
authentic experiences on their adventure vacations and authentic
works of art.
</P>
<P>
   Because most art created in the Middle Ages was made for the
church, not for private patrons, some collectors say that it is
somehow more genuine and less self-conscious than art from other
periods. Precious devotional materials like exquisitely carved
wooden saints, metalwork church vessels, altars, enameled plaques
or ivory crucifixions were made to glorify God. They imply good
faith and sincere intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Not that collectors need be religious to appreciate the appeal
of medieval art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of the work speaks for itself,'' said Tony Blumka,
the owner of Blumka Gallery on East 72nd Street in Manhattan.
Blumka specializes in what is known as early European works of art,
which includes medieval (the 5th to 15th centuries), Renaissance
(15th and 16th centuries) and Baroque (17th century).
</P>
<P>
   Blumka has presented an exhibition of 140 artworks titled
``Collecting Treasures of the Past,'' which runs through next
Friday. (Viewing information: (212) 734-3222.) He organized it with
an old family friend, the dealer Florian Eitle-Boehler of Munich.
Both come from families who have been selling European works of art
for more than 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two families have known each other for a long time,''
Blumka said. He is the fourth-generation Blumka to run his family's
gallery, which was founded in Vienna in the late 1800s. It moved to
New York in 1939, when Blumka's father left Austria.
</P>
<P>
   The Boehler gallery, founded in 1880 in Munich, was named
Purveyor to the Imperial Court of Germany and the Royal Court of
Bavaria in 1900. ``Florian took over his uncle's firm,'' Blumka
said. ``My father did business with his uncle and his uncle's
father.''
</P>
<P>
   The two young men spent a year planning the core of this show:
35 objects from the collection of Ernst and Martha Kofler-Truniger,
a couple from Lucerne, Switzerland, who had bought medieval works
from both galleries. Kofler-Truniger died in 1989 at 90, Blumka
said, and his wife died in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their collection was cream of the cream,'' said Blumka, noting
that the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Detroit Institute of Art
and the Thyssen-Bornemisza Collection in Lugano, Switzerland, have
already acquired works from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pieces we are selling have not been seen on the market for
decades,'' he said. ``They are being offered for the first time and
they are the last group to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The works include a 12th-century oak reliquary casket from
Cologne with applied bone carvings of saints; a tiny 13th-century
ivory statue of the Virgin in prayer; a rare circa 1400 German
bronze aquamanile in the form of a saddled horse (aquamaniles are
water containers used for ritual hand-washing); a large alabaster
St. John the Evangelist made in the Netherlands around 1430, and a
polychrome wood sculpture of St. George on horseback made in Styria
in the 15th century.
</P>
<P>
   These pieces have a genuine freshness. The St. George, for
example, has his sword raised above his head, about to slash the
dragon. Wearing golden armor, he sits on a red saddle. His gray
steed, complete with its original 500-year-old leather reins, rears
above the ferocious dragon, which lies on its back on the ground,
long, curled tail and clawed feet in midair. The saint looks at the
dragon, which has just snapped his lance in two.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can almost date it by its armor,'' Blumka said. ``If the
shoes are pointed, it is pre-1500.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Katz, a London dealer in Renaissance bronzes, bought the
St. George. `It's a gift for my son,'' he said. ``I won't sell
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Hack, an avid New York collector, acquired the alabaster
St. John. The Evangelist rests his face on one hand as if deep in
thought. He has flesh-colored face and hands and wears a deeply
carved white cloak. His brown wavy hair shows traces of gilding.
</P>
<P>
   The price range for such art is wide; at this show, the pieces
go from $3,500 to $500,000 (the top estimate is for an Italian
majolica Apollo plate, circa 1545, that the Blumka Gallery
previously sold at Sotheby's in 1995).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the prices may seem high until they are compared with
those paid for artworks from other periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can buy a first-rate medieval object for a third of the
price of an old master,'' Blumka said. ``Early works of art have
always been comparatively inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand,'' he continued, ``this business has really
changed. Ten years ago, 85 percent of what I sold went to museums.
Now 85 percent goes to the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 26, at Sotheby's auction of European works of art in New
York, a Florentine Renaissance bronze statue of a prancing stallion
was sold to a private collector for $761,500, well above the
pre-sale high estimate of $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the same sale, a bronze bust of Pope Pius V made in Rome in
the late 16th century went to an Italian collector for $96,000
(against a high estimate of $70,000).
</P>
<P>
   A magnificent terra cotta relief depicting the Ecstasy of St.
Theresa of Avila, made by Tommaso Amantini in Rome in the 17th
century, was sold to the Middlebury College Museum of Art for
$123,500, against a high estimate of $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   Blumka credits museums, and particularly the Met, for igniting
the public's interest in early art. He cited the recent Met shows
of Byzantine art and art from the Gulbenkian Museum in Lisbon and
its 1996 ``Enamels of Limoges: 1100 to 1350.'' He timed his current
show to coincide with the opening next week of the Met's exhibition
on Tilman Riemenschneider, the German Renaissance master wood
sculptor.
</P>
<P>
   Such shows, he suggests, create an interest in early art among
clients who previously focused on paintings.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a certain amount of time, many people gravitate to
earlier works,'' he said. ``They are attracted to the simplicity of
the form, the elegance of the materials and the sheer rarity.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out a 10th-century Byzantine ivory relief of the
Crucifixion in his show.
</P>
<P>
   The suffering Christ is flanked by two saints who stand between
pierced open-work columns. Slightly primitive in style, the plaque,
particularly the latticed columns, is meticulously carved.
</P>
<P>
   It is both breathtaking as a work of art and miraculous as a
delicate object that has survived for 1,100 years. It is the
dictionary definition of authentic: real, authoritative, worthy of
acceptance or belief, trustworthy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
