<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5620 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-INTERNET04-COX     02-03 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-INTERNET04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MCCAIN RAISES FUNDS IN INTERNET TIME
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain is using the power of the Internet
to get a new kind of ``bounce'' from his victory this week in New
Hampshire's Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has just changed politics,'' said Max Fose, the
campaign's on-line manager.
</P>
<P>
   Donors had pledged more than $741,000 on McCain's Internet site
by midday Thursday, less than two days after the New Hampshire
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid influx lets the campaign immediately commit new
resources to its battle with Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, rather
than waiting for checks to arrive and clear through traditional
pre-Internet fund-raising methods.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, McCain campaign officials were able to
immediately cite the contributions as evidence of their candidate's
growing momentum in the Republican presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when presidential campaigns were just beginning
to use the Internet and far fewer voters were on line, a winning
campaign would not have been able to exploit its new contributions
and favorable publicity so effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain calls the Internet 'the great equalizer,''' Fose
told FreedomChannel.com, a neutral Web site that covers this year's
political contests. ``With over half a million dollars raised
within 24 hours without doing an event, we've just proved we can be
competitive in South Carolina financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Fose reported that the average online contribution was $105.
Nearly 40 percent of the donors had never given before to a
political campaign, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, the McCain campaign also plans to combine the
old and the new by sending e-mail to online supporters asking them
to telephone 10 people on McCain's behalf. This technique worked
well in New Hampshire; the campaign e-mail roster has risen
steadily and now numbers more than 75,000 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to actively try to expand our e-mail list in South
Carolina,'' Fose said. ``It's the best way to keep people involved
in the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   And next Thursday, the Arizona senator plans to hold an online
fund-raiser that will be the first of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   Contributors who donate $100 or more by punching in their credit
card numbers will be able to pose their questions and comments to
McCain via e-mail and get a direct response on their computer
monitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to put a camera in front of John McCain, and he'll
give a speech (on line) about what's happened and where the
campaign is going,'' Fose said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
