<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5626 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FLOYD-RELIEF04-COX     02-03 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-RELIEF04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ASKS FOR $236 MILLION FOR HURRICANE FLOYD RELIEF
 &HT;    Attn: N.C. points.
 &HT;    By GINGER LIVINGSTON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton plans to include $236 million in
additional Hurricane Floyd relief money in a supplemental budget
request he will send Congress on Monday, Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C.,
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards discussed the funding with White House officials
Thursday. However, a White House spokesman later cautioned that the
$236 million figure is still preliminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's real progress, but I don't think we are
through,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money, $128 million, will be used for the Federal
Emergency Management Agency's housing buyout program and the Small
Business Administration's loan program for individuals and small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining money will be used to help commercial fishermen
replace lost equipment, for economic development needs, repairing
military facilities, rural housing reconstruction, beach
renourishment and repairing damaged park facilities, Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, Hurricane Floyd and subsequent flooding
destroyed or left uninhabitable 24,000 homes in North Carolina and
damaged another 56,000 homes, according to Gov. Jim Hunt's office.
</P>
<P>
   Congress voted last year to send the state $2.2 billion in
federal relief money. But Edwards and North Carolina's 12 House
members wrote Clinton last month asking him to include more relief
funds in a supplemental budget bill for fiscal 2000, which started
Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   That funding bill will be sent to Congress on Monday along with
Clinton's fiscal 2001 budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   This new money will be available to all victims of Hurricane
Floyd, not just North Carolina residents, Edwards said. However,
the senator predicts the bulk of the money will be used in his
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to the Hurricane Floyd-specific money, he will be
asking for significant increases for community development block
grants and (Department of Housing and Urban Development) low-income
housing rental monies,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this clearly shows we're making significant progress
and we are filling in the gaps,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One area still needing funds is farm equipment replacement,
Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the Senate approved $81 million to help farmers
replace equipment damaged by the hurricane, but the money was taken
out of the final budget approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Livingston's e-mail address is gingerl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
