<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5627 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-NEW-ENGLAND-CAMPUSES-     02-03 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ENGLAND-CAMPUSES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOWY IDYLL IN A COLLEGE TOWN (AND NO MIDTERMS) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By PAULA DEITZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When winter comes to other cities of the world, like Helsinki or
St. Petersburg, where snows fall almost daily, the hushed
atmosphere of the streets in their winter whiteness is broken only
by the muffled sounds of city life. In the evenings, deep snow
drifts lining frozen sidewalks glow in intermittent pools of
lamplight from above. Magical winters like these form precious
memories for people who treasure bundling up for the adventure in
the otherwise quiet month of February before the awakening of
spring.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no need to pine. Skiers are not the only ones who
can travel to find ideal snow conditions. For people whose favorite
winter sport is not skiing but hiking along woodland paths or
simply walking on streets in a small town after a blizzard, to
recapture the crunch of snow underfoot that so quickly disappears
in the city, the best choice is to journey to a university or
college town in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Accessible by public transportation or car, the campuses there
provide landscapes that have been designed to enhance their rural
settings. In a commencement address on the virtues of living in New
England that Elizabeth Hardwick once delivered at Smith College in
Northampton, Mass., she referred to universities and colleges as
being ``the dominant aesthetic of Massachusetts.'' ``Here,'' she
said, ``there is a real winter, not the most spectacular in
hardship our country has to offer, but real nevertheless.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to offering country walks in the snow near cozy
inns, these colleges, by virtue of their theater and music
departments, are also thriving performing arts centers where
visitors, after a good lunch or dinner, may attend a theatrical
production or a variety of concerts by outside ensembles as well as
by faculty soloists and student choruses.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly true of the five-college group in the
rolling countryside of Pioneer Valley along the Connecticut River
in western Massachusetts: Amherst College, Hampshire College, Mount
Holyoke College, Smith College and the University of Massachusetts.
And in contrast to frigid temperatures outside, three of these
institutions also provide the perfumed air of tropical greenhouses
as a place to warm up and enjoy exotic blooms.
</P>
<P>
   A ride to Smith College yielded a winter wonderland on a campus
designed in 1892 by Frederick Law Olmsted. By planning a campus
that was both a botanic garden and arboretum with lofty trees, open
greenswards and curvilinear pathways, Olmsted retained the domestic
scale of a New England town surrounded by pastoral scenery. To this
day, the trees and shrubs on the college grounds are labeled with
their botanical names and native regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the tree branches bare and the ground blanketed with
snow,'' said Ann Leone, a Smith professor who is a member of the
college's Landscape Studies Steering Committee, ``Olmsted's vistas
open up to their true perspectives.''
</P>
<P>
   The campus curves around Paradise Pond, a serpentine water
feature that was a former mill pond in the Mill River with a
picturesque island at its center. This prospect possesses the
romantic aura of an 18th-century English landscape, especially in
winter with yellowing branches of weeping willows and the bright
red berries of winterberry shrubs silhouetted against snowy banks.
</P>
<P>
   When frozen solid, the pond's surface is cleared for ice
skating, which adds to the charm of this winter scene.
</P>
<P>
   Walking north from the boathouse, along the riverside path where
the river flows into the pond, one enters a woodland not unlike the
one Robert Frost saw ``fill up with snow/ ... Between the woods and
frozen lake'' in his poem ``Stopping by Woods on a Snowy Evening.''
(Beginning in Amherst, where Frost lived, the public walk linking
conservation areas is called the Robert Frost Trail.)
</P>
<P>
   Deeper into the woods, the fresh snow recently was broken only
by the footsteps of other early walkers, leaving marks Thoreau
referred to in ``Walden'' as ``a meandering dotted line, with wide
intervals between the dots.''
</P>
<P>
   In passing the dark silhouettes of trees, interspersed by the
occasional white birch, one could appreciate anew why Thoreau
wrote, ``I frequently tramped 8 or 10 miles through the deepest
snow to keep an appointment with a beech tree or a yellow birch or
an old acquaintance among the pines.''
</P>
<P>
   As one trudges along, a camaraderie develops with other walkers
pleased to be out in this frosty world seemingly isolated from the
town. Surprisingly, the walk ends on a residential street, and
there is equal pleasure in seeing the old houses and broad porches
of Northampton's side streets in their winter garb. Many of the
rambling houses on Elm Street, the town's main thoroughfare, still
serve as Smith dormitories or as faculty housing. By doubling back
on the woodland path, the hiker arrives directly in front of Lyman
Conservatory, a complex of 12 joined greenhouses completed by Lord
&AMP; Burnham in 1895.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooking Paradise Pond, the Victorian Gothic greenhouses,
incorporating a balloon-shaped palm house trimmed in fleur-de-lis
metalwork, offer immediate refuge from the cold amid the moist
scent of tropical and subtropical blooms. Fragrant orange blossoms
in the warm temperate house, an allee of deep pink Camellia
japonica and a swag of magenta bougainvillea across the upper
reaches of the cool temperate house are only a few of the winter
blooms that thrive inside when there is deep snow outside.
</P>
<P>
   Lyman Conservatory's display reaches its winter crescendo in the
annual Spring Bulb Show, which takes place this year from March 4
to 19. This is an event that has to be experienced to be believed.
While learning bulb ecology, Smith's horticulture students begin
the process in fall by planting more than 5,000 bulbs that are
placed in the cellar's cold storage for 10 to 12 weeks before being
brought up to the greenhouses, thereby forcing the plants to bloom
simultaneously for the show. Tulips, narcissus, hyacinths, crocus,
scilla and muscari, all from the Mediterranean region, are
literally crammed into brilliant mixtures on planting benches
surrounded by white picket fences in two show houses, with
forsythia, azalea, redbud, willow and Canary broom as additional
decor.
</P>
<P>
   To open the door to the bulb show during the weeks often of the
worst snowstorms is to be overwhelmed by the fragrance and the
possibilities of cyclical seasons. Last year more than 13,000
people attended. As an additional treat, when the greenhouses are
illuminated for the evening openings, from a distance Lyman
Conservatory looks like a crystalline brooch in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   For a pause in activities and to satisfy a hearty appetite,
Northampton abounds with good restaurants both near the campus and
in the downtown business district with its historic 19th-century
commercial and civic structures. Afterward one can select any
number of concerts or theatrical performances in the area and take
advantage of the free bus service that links the five college
campuses.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that Smith, with a music department of 40
faculty members, half of whom are well-known performers and the
other half theorists or composers, sponsors 75 concerts a year,
most of them held in Sweeney Concert Hall in Sage Hall, a domed
building designed by Delano &AMP; Aldrich in 1924 as an adaptation of
Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   When college is in session, the frequent noon-hour concerts
offer the opportunity to hear a specialized program. At one
outstanding concert, the soprano Jane Bryden, accompanied by John
Van Buskirk at the fortepiano, sang an entire program devoted to
Robert Schumann, including his song cycle ``Liederkreis'' (Op. 24).
A version of this program has just been released on a CD.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend provided a rich assortment of local musicians. On
Saturday at Sweeney Concert Hall, the visiting Kinor String Quartet
played Schumann's Piano Quintet with a Smith professor, Monica
Jakuc, as pianist, and the Third String Quartet by Donald Wheelock,
another Smith professor. On Sunday afternoon the Arcadia Players,
an independent group specializing in music in the European
tradition of the 17th and 18th centuries, performed an all-Bach
program downtown at the Northampton Center for the Arts that
featured Bryden as well as the flutist Chris Krueger, who teaches
at the University of Massachusetts, and the harpsichordist William
Porter.
</P>
<P>
   Strindberg's ``Julie'' will open at Amherst College's Kirby
Theater on Feb. 24, directed by Peter Lobdell, head of the theater
department. Designed by McKim, Mead &AMP; White in 1938, Kirby is one
of those special theaters that retain an intimacy with the
audience. Memorable past productions have included Sophocles'
``Oedipus Rex'' and Marlowe's ``Doctor Faustus.''
</P>
<P>
   As audiences leave the various theaters and concert halls on a
cold still night, the stars above are spectacularly bright. Edith
Wharton captured this winter phenomenon when she wrote about a
Massachusetts village in ``Ethan Frome'': ``In a sky of iron the
points of the Dipper hung like icicles and Orion flashed his cold
fires.''
</P>
<P>
   For those inspired to take a closer look, the Amherst Astronomy
Association invites visitors to view the winter sky through a
telescope at Wilder Observatory on the Amherst campus at 9 on
Saturday evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Though winter has the feeling of permanence, it is as ephemeral
as other seasons, as witnessed by the jasmine now in flower behind
Lyman Conservatory or the Chinese witch hazel blossoming on the
Smith library lawn.
</P>
<P>
   But no moment is as poignant as the day one sets out on the Mill
River walk during an early spring thaw to discover a new blanket of
whiteness in the thousands of snowdrops in bloom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Northampton, Mass., is about 160 miles northeast of New York
City. Here is a sampling of attractions, along with travel
information: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   AUTUMN INN, 259 Elm St., Northampton, Mass. 01060 (near Smith
College), (413) 584-7660; fax (413) 586-4808. Single rooms, $80;
double rooms, $108. Breakfast served around an open hearth:
weekdays, 7 to 10 a.m.; weekends, 8 to 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL NORTHAMPTON, 36 King St., Northampton, Mass. 01060, (800)
547-3529. Single or double rooms, $160 to $205. Wiggins Tavern
serves Sunday brunch, 10:30 a.m. to 2 p.m., $14.95; dinner,
Tuesdays through Saturdays, 5 to 10 p.m. and Sundays, 4:30 to 9
p.m., $17.95 to $23.95. The Coolidge Park Cafe serves lighter
entrees and sandwiches, Sundays through Thursdays, 7 a.m. to 10
p.m.; Fridays and Saturdays, 7 a.m. to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   LORD JEFFERY INN, 30 Boltwood Ave., Amherst, Mass. 01002 (near
Amherst College), (800) 742-0358. Standard single or double rooms,
$99 to $119 (rates for preferred rooms or suites upon request). The
Windowed Hearth serves dinner Wednesdays through Sundays, 5 to 9
p.m.; $18 to $26. Elijah's Boltwood Tavern serves breakfast daily,
7 to 10 a.m.; lunch, Mondays through Saturdays, 11:30 a.m. to 4
p.m.; Sunday brunch, 11 a.m. to 2 p.m.; dinner daily, 4 to 10 p.m.
Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   GREEN STREET CAFE, 62 Green St., Northampton, (413) 586-5650.
Near Sweeney Concert Hall, Smith College. Winter specialties
include duck breasts cooked over an open fire, cassoulet, homemade
ravioli and vegetarian entrees. Hours: Lunch, Mondays through
Fridays, noon to 2 p.m.; dinner, daily, 5:30 to 10 p.m. Lunch, $5
to $12; dinner entrees, $16 to $26.
</P>
<P>
   DEL RAYE BAR AND GRILL, 1 Bridge St., Northampton, (413)
586-2664. Fine dining. Hours: Mondays through Thursdays, 5:30 to 10
p.m.; Fridays and Saturdays, 5 to 11 p.m.; Sundays, 5 to 9:30 p.m.
Dinner entrees, $16 to $25. Special Sunday buffet dinners with
international cuisines, $40: Feb. 27, Spanish; March 5, German;
March 26, French.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatories
</P>
<P>
   DURFEE CONSERVATORY, off Stockbridge Road, University of
Massachusetts campus, Amherst, (413) 545-5234. More than 500
species are cultivated in this Victorian greenhouse, some dating to
the original 1860s collection. Hours: Mondays through Fridays, 8:30
a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Free.
</P>
<P>
   LYMAN CONSERVATORY, College Lane, Smith College, Northampton,
(413) 585-2740. Hours: Daily, 8:30 a.m to 4 p.m. Free. ``Spring
Bulb Show'': 10 a.m. to 4 p.m from March 4 to 19; also, 6 to 9 p.m.
on March 15. Opening lecture, ``Heirloom Bulbs for Gardens Old and
New,'' by Scott Kunst will be at 7 p.m. on March 3 at Seelye Hall
106, followed by a reception at Lyman Conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   TALCOTT GREENHOUSE, Lower Lake Road, Mount Holyoke College,
South Hadley, (413) 538-2116. Hours: Mondays through Fridays, 9
a.m. to 4 p.m; Saturdays and Sundays, 1 to 4 p.m. Free. ``Spring
Flower Show'': 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. from March 4 to 19. This year's
theme is ``A Walk on the Wild Side,'' featuring species bulb plants
as they grow in the wild along with showy hybrid daffodils, tulips
and others.
</P>
<P>
   Winter Walks
</P>
<P>
   MOUNT HOLYOKE COLLEGE: A milelong woodland walk traces the
perimeter of the campus' Upper Lake and begins at Kendall Sports
and Dance Complex, where parking is available. Campus maps
distributed at the information desk in Blanchard Campus Center, off
Lower Lake Road.
</P>
<P>
   AMHERST: ``Guide to Amherst Conservation Areas and Trails,'' $3,
and ``Guide to the Robert Frost Trail'' (42 miles through 10
towns), $4.95, may be ordered from the Conservation Department of
the Town of Amherst: (413) 256-4045.
</P>
<P>
   SMITH COLLEGE: A campus map may be ordered by calling (413)
585-2170.
</P>
<P>
   Stargazing
</P>
<P>
   AMHERST ASTRONOMY ASSOCIATION, Wilder Observatory, 1403 South
East St., Amherst, (413) 256-6234. Saturdays at 9 p.m. March
through December. Free. Music
</P>
<P>
   BEZANSON RECITAL HALL, University of Massachusetts, Amherst. Box
office: (413) 545-2511. Feb. 22 at 8 p.m.: Jon Humphrey, tenor;
Laura Klock, hornist; Nadine Shank, pianist, and Dorothy Ornest,
reader; works by Britten, Berlioz and Debussy. Feb. 27 at 8 p.m.:
Chamber Music Recital with Charles Treger, violinist; Michelle
