<P>
   These business stories for release Friday, February 4, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-SURVEY _ Delta Air Lines slipped from third to fourth
place in 1999 on-time rankings for major carriers but moved up to
second place in baggage handling. Delta maintained a third-place
standing for its rate of consumer complaints to the U.S. Department
of Transportation, which compiles the rankings. Customer complaints
about all airlines more than doubled in 1999 from 1998, probably in
part because internet filing was available. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-LEGROOM _American announces it will remove several rows of
seats to give passengers 4 or 5 more inches of leg room. Asking
Delta and others if they will follow suit. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TURF _ They can't agree on whose grass is greener. Or softer. Or
safer. Now the Leander-based maker of AstroTurf, pummeled by a
Canadian competitor's accusations of unfair trade practices, is
swinging back with a lawsuit of its own. ``Everyone's allowed their
one cheap shot at the market leader,'' said Reed Seaton, president
of Southwest Recreational Industries in Leander. ``They've had
theirs. This time, we're standing firm.'' (Ball, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HARTSFIELD-FREIGHT _ Hartsfield apparently soon will rival
Miami, JFK, LA and Chicago as the U.S.' top freight-forwarding
center. Atlanta-based developer Seefried Properties plans to build
more than a million square feet of cargo space near the airport.
(Wilbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).12.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-STOCK _ Watching developments at Coca-Cola Co. The
company's stock continues to slide. At midday, it was trading at
$55.50, the lowest it's been since October. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
