<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MISSING PIECES': ALL ACTION, NO CHARACTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's worse than having one of those hostile family
Christmases, ornamented with guilt, sibling rivalry and
intergenerational tension _ the kind during which one person blows
up and leaves the room in a huff, upsetting the children? Answer:
Getting a telephone call shortly afterward announcing that that
person has committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   James Coburn, as Atticus Cody, has that problem in the CBS movie
``Missing Pieces.'' The volatile family member is Atticus' son
Scott (Paul Kersey), a black sheep who is artistic and lives in
Mexico. His situation is summed up by wildly inventive dialogue
like, ``He's wasting his life down there, you know'' (Atticus to
his other son, a senator) and, ``I'm a painter, not a ranch hand''
(Scott to Atticus). Scott would probably have been a rebel anyway,
but things are made worse by the fact that 12 years ago he and his
mother were in a horrible car accident in which she died. He was
driving.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the two-hour film consists of Atticus' stay in Mexico,
where he goes to claim his son's body and investigate the
circumstances of his death. There is definitely a twisted tale to
unravel _ involving a hit-and-run accident, suspicious photographs,
three leftover rifle shells, at least one prowler, a remarkably
observant answering machine and a one-way ticket to Frankfurt,
Germany _ but the plot is all action and no character. When the
film tries to get deep about the father-son relationship, it shows
Scott's gorgeous seaside house filled with huge paintings of
Atticus looking noble.
</P>
<P>
   And the action doesn't always add up. ``I just don't understand
what happened,'' Atticus tells his daughter-in-law when he calls
her from Mexico, referring to his son's suicide. ``It doesn't make
any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it does. Scott had just returned from a miserable holiday
visit home, where he felt like a failure. He was tortured with
guilt about his mother's death. His girlfriend had just announced
that she was marrying somebody else. And he was drunk. People have
killed themselves over a lot less.
</P>
<P>
   A viewer also has to ask if the screenwriters _ any of the
screenwriters (Peachy Markowitz, Philip Rosenberg, Richard Kletter
and D.W. Owen) _ have ever been to Mexico. Atticus arrives by
rickety bus, the kind jam-packed with colorful locals and live
chickens. But flashbacks show Scott spending his time at what looks
like at least a four-star beach resort (actually somewhere in Santa
Barbara, Calif.), so surely there was a hotel shuttle or at least a
few taxis.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn, who won last year's Oscar for best supporting actor in
the devastating father-son drama ``Affliction,'' is always
interesting to watch, but he's stuck with a stunningly trite script
here. (Looking at old photographs, he's moved to say, ``Oh,
Scott.'' Trying to prove to Scott that he accepts him, he
proclaims, ``You paint the truth.'') Kersey seems well cast as the
good-looking bad boy who just wants Dad's love, but he also has
dialogue of unlikely honesty; for instance, ``I don't want you to
be ashamed of me anymore.'' Lisa Zane, as Scott's former
girlfriend, Renata, is cavalier, immediately unlikable
(deliberately, as the film eventually reveals) and competitively
trite. (Scott's way of looking at the world was like a
kaleidoscope, she says.)
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the first shot confuse you. Although Coburn is on a
horse, wearing a cowboy hat, surrounded by majestic mountains,
``Missing Pieces'' is in no way a western.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS: That first year at college is hard, especially
if you keep encountering the girl who died in your dorm room,
looking all drowned and everything. That's the problem Marian
(Julianne Nicholson) faces in the premiere episode of ``The
Others'' (10 p.m. ET Saturdays on NBC), a faintly creepy new
series, aspiring to be a blend of ``The X-Files'' and ``The
Twilight Zone.'' Soon Marian is part of a group of
soap-opera-beautiful young psychics who meet regularly and join
forces to help mere mortals with supernatural problems.
</P>
<P>
   The drowned college student, whose look appears to be inspired
by the drowned hotel guest in ``The Shining,'' turns out to be a
disappointment. A subplot about a recent widow with money problems
is sweet but tired. Next week's episode is better, with a young
woman whose husband goes out jogging with the baby one morning and
never comes back, except as a ghost _ or at least what appears to
be a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   But the young psychics aren't nearly as fascinating as they
think they are, and their elderly leader (Bill Cobbs) is a little
too self-consciously wise and weary. We do learn one thing about
the afterlife from these two episodes: The dead enjoy communicating
through numbers. Luckily, one of the group, Warren (Kevin J.
O'Connor), specializes in that and at one point is seen running
through the street, repeatedly shouting, ``6, 28, 31!'' Hike.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MISSING PIECES'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Sunday on CBS
</P>
<P>
   A Hallmark Hall of Fame production written by Peachy Markowitz,
Philip Rosenberg, Richard Kletter and D.W. Owen, based on a novel
by Ron Hansen. Carl Schenkel, director; Richard Welsh, executive
producer; Brent Shields, co-executive producer; Andrew Gottlieb,
producer; Richard Kletter and D.W. Owen, co-producers. Music by
Lawrence Shragge. Karl Herrmann, director of photography.
</P>
<P>
   With: James Coburn (Atticus Cody), Lisa Zane (Renata), Paul
Kersey (Scott), Finn Carter (Marilyn), William R. Moses (David),
Julio Oscar Mechoso (Hernandez) and Maxwell Caulfield (Stuart).
</P>
