<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5636 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      02-03 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DRAG QUEEN AND A MOBSTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now and then, a movie like ``Mob Queen'' surfaces on video: a
good piece of work turned out by young filmmakers on a shoestring
that finally finds a distributor with an eye for something a little
bizarre and highly viewable.
</P>
<P>
   And in this case, the film, to be released on tape Feb. 15 by
First Run Features, happened to pick up some helpful connections
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   How often does a little movie share cast members and other
parallels with a television show like the ``The Sopranos?'' The
story begins in 1995, when Jon Carnoy, a former film student at New
York University, and his boyhood friend Mike Horelick, a film
graduate of the University of Southern California, began playing
with an idea. ``A drag queen with the mob,'' Horelick said the
other day.
</P>
<P>
   Carnoy wanted to make a drama. ``I said people will be laughing
at us unless we pull it off perfectly,'' Horelick recalled. So they
decided to defuse that danger and do a comedy. Carnoy, now 33,
directed and produced the film, raising the beginnings of the
$200,000 budget from family and friends, and gradually obtained the
rest from other backers as the project moved along. Horelick, 34,
wrote the screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is the Brooklyn waterfront in 1957. The hood George
Gianfranco is more than worried about telling his boss, Joey Aorta,
the shocking truth he has just discovered concerning Glorice, the
prostitute George has presented to Aorta as a birthday present.
</P>
<P>
   As George puts it to Dip, the mob's idiot: ``What do I say:
`Aorta, we cannot tell a lie. We accidentally set you up with a man
dressed in women's clothing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Aorta, who has just beaten up an underling whose sexuality he
suspects because the man ordered a tropical-style drink with an
umbrella in it, is played by Tony Sirico. On ``The Sopranos''
Sirico is the mobster Paulie Walnuts. Gianfranco is portrayed by
David Proval, who began his career in ``Mean Streets'' in 1973 and
made a high-profile entrance in ``The Sopranos'' last Sunday as an
explosive gangster fresh from a 10-year prison stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of ``Mob Queen'' is devoted to keeping Aorta in the
dark about Glorice, played by the drag performer Candis Cayne. That
involves a botched hit and an aborted wedding while neatly avoiding
silliness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult knowing how far to go with the humor,''
Horelick said. ``We kept it at a quiet level, not in your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Dogged by the film's low budget and unknown director, the
casting took a year. ``Jon found Candis in a drag show at the
Barracuda Lounge in New York, doing a `Charlie's Angels'
knockoff,'' Horelick said. Carnoy was looking for celebrities for
bit parts and signed on Gerry Cooney, the former heavyweight
fighter, who plays a baker.
</P>
<P>
   Landing the mob characters was the toughest part. Sirico was in
New York. ``Most mob actors are from New York but live in L.A.,''
Horelock said. There Carnoy found Proval. ``I was attracted to this
'90s dilemma set in the '50s,'' Proval said. ``Plus it was that
particular world. I'm from Brooklyn, East New York. Those guys I
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Marius and Jeannette
</P>
<P>
   As surely as romance develops between Jeannette (Ariane
Ascaride), a supermarket cashier and single mother of two, and
Marius (Gerard Meylan), a security guard, Robert Guediguian's film
becomes a love affair with the working class of Marseilles.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost her job, the resilient Jeannette makes the best of
it amid neighbors who get through hard times by sharing warm
friendships and populist political ideas. One of her sons, by
different men, is Catholic, while the other is Muslim, adding
religious considerations to a warm, rich film with ``a strong,
hearty, down-to-earth spirit throughout,'' Janet Maslin wrote in
The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   1998. New Yorker. $89.98. 102 minutes. French with English
subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Astronaut's Wife
</P>
<P>
   ``They gon' be pilots, honey,'' drawls the astronaut Spencer
Armacost (Johnny Depp) to his wife, Jillian (Charlize Theron), who
is pregnant with twins. Back from a space mission gone wrong,
Spencer isn't his old self, and when Jillian starts wearing a
hairdo straight out of ``Rosemary's Baby,'' it's better than even
money that if the babies do become pilots, they'll be flying for an
alien air force. With Depp carrying on suavely, Rand Ravich's film
is not that bad, but it is ``ridiculously derivative'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1999. New Line. $107.37; DVD, $24.98. 100 minutes. R. Release
date: Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Streak
</P>
<P>
   About to be nabbed by the law, Miles Logan (Martin Lawrence)
races into a building under construction and tapes the $18 million
diamond he has just stolen to the wall of an air-conditioning vent.
After his prison term, he returns for the rock, only to find the
building is now police headquarters, and, to have any chance of
crawling into the ventilating system and retrieving the prize, he
must impersonate a police officer. Using all his criminal savvy,
Logan is soon running the station house, but ``among movies of its
type, `Blue Steak' may be classified among the zircons'' (Lawrence
Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $108.97; DVD, $24.95. 93 minutes.
PG-13. Release date: Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The Swindle
</P>
<P>
   A couple of con artists work so smoothly in Claude Chabrol's
film that one is never sure of their identity and connection. Betty
(Isabelle Huppert) dons wigs and seductive outfits to set up
well-to-do business and professional people for the blandishments
of her partner, Victor (Michel Serrault), who plays an officer and
gentleman with panache. But then at a Swiss resort Betty latches on
to a handsome businessman (Francois Cluzet), who is either a
perfect target or an uninvited third partner in crime. ``Chabrol
keeps curiosity piqued, the actors delightful and the outcome in
sufficient question'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1997. New Yorker. $94.98. 105 minutes. French with English
subtitles. Release date: Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   INTRODUCING DOROTHY DANDRIDGE. When Dandridge (Halle Berry),
star of Otto Preminger's ``Carmen Jones,'' arrives at the 1955
Academy Awards ceremony, she is called ``the first-ever colored
nominee for best actress.'' (Her competition included Audrey
Hepburn and Grace Kelly, who won for ``The Country Girl.'') Caught
in many of the tired conventions of television docudrama, Martha
Coolidge's film for HBO, adapted from Earl Mills' book, only partly
explains the enigmatic singer and actress.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite its flat-footed narrative, the production ``is worth
watching for its affecting performances and for the sheer drama of
Dandridge's life,'' Caryn James wrote in The New York Times in
1999. HBO. $76.12; DVD, $24.98. 115 minutes. R.
</P>
<P>
   NOSFERATU and THE CABINET OF DR. CALIGARI. Unlike Ernst
Lubitsch, Fritz Lang and other directors of the day who erected
landscapes in the studio, F.W. Murnau shot ``Nosferatu'' (1922, 84
minutes), his unauthorized adaptation of Bram Stoker's ``Dracula,''
in the Carpathian Mountains. Robert Wiene's ``Cabinet of Dr.
Caligari'' (1919, 72 minutes) stars Werner Kraus as a hypnotist who
turns a death-dealing ogre (Conrad Veidt) loose on unsuspecting
country folk. Both films are digitally remastered. Kino. $24.95
each.
</P>
<P>
   BESHKEMPIR: THE ADOPTED SON. In the first independent feature
film made in Kyrgyzstan, a young boy grows to adolescence only to
be undone by the news that he is not his parents' biological child.
Winstar. $89.98. 81 minutes. Kyrgyz with English subtitles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1742EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
