<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5638 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-DOT-COM-SIDER-COX     02-03 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOT-COM-SIDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: RUNS WITH DOT-COM-COX
 &HT;    Marketer goes hi-tech
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Five years ago, David Miranda, then a marketer with
Holiday Inns Worldwide, didn't know a dot.com from a dot.con. A
Pentium chip sounded to him like a snack food.
</P>
<P>
   He actually thought he was being conned when he first had a
brush with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out in what I now know as Silicon Valley for a meeting,
and while I was waiting, they gave me a tour, and I go into this
very small office, eight or 10 people in an office that should have
held two,'' said the boyish-looking 51-year-old. ``Everybody looked
like they hadn't bathed in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked what they were doing. ``They said, 'We're on the
Internet.' That was the first time I heard it.'' As a guy who'd
been in the business of scrambling to unload hotel rooms that
hadn't been rented for the night, his ears perked up when they said
they were communicating long-distance by computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'My God, if you're talking to places all over the
world, you must have a hell of a long-distance bill.' They looked
at me like I was a dinosaur. I said, 'What's the Internet?' They
told me, and I thought it must be illegal, that they were tapping
into something they shouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   The techies gave him a crash course, and a light bulb flashed in
his head: There must be a way to book empty hotel rooms this way.
And airline seats. And cruise tickets. And ``just about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He soon began discussions with colleagues in the travel
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone said the same thing. 'David, somebody's got to be
doing this.' ``
</P>
<P>
   He found out that many were, but none like he thought it could
be. So he set out to find a way to sell ``perishable'' airline
seats, hotel rooms and other travel-related offers. And the more he
talked, the more people listened. And offered to invest.
</P>
<P>
   He came up with a company he called LastMinuteTravel. It was a
natural, and he figured somebody must have claimed the Web address.
</P>
<P>
   They hadn't, so he did, for a $75 fee.
</P>
<P>
   He continued raising money by offering a piece of the business
to investors called ``angels'' by entrepreneurs. Angels generally
gamble on many long-shot possibilities, knowing most will fail. But
if they get in on the ground floor of one that works, they stand
</P>
<P>
   to reap huge profits that far offset their losses from ventures
that fail.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Miranda was approaching investors, he went
after travel providers, like hotel chains and airlines, telling
them they could reduce their costs if they'd let him act as a
matchmaker. He had created a Web site, he told them, that would
list ``perishable''
</P>
<P>
   airline seats and rooms and rental cars. He wouldn't charge
consumers, but the travel providers would have to pay a fee to be
listed.
</P>
<P>
   After raising enough capital, he set out to recruit his
marketers and geeks. They rented a small office, and just recently
moved to swanky digs in the Pinnacle Building in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   Total payroll runs $250,000-$300,000 a month, which at this
point comes mostly from the bankroll of angels. Every employee has
a stake in ownership, and if the company turns into a hot stock
issue, each could become an instant millionaire. As befits a
</P>
<P>
   dot.com startup, job titles are nontraditional. Ronald Mulliken
is an eVP. Richard Chen is an eWizard. Ted Perlstein is head
sherpa. Tara Kennelly is manager of the eOffice. Heidi Fraser is
director of eVents.
</P>
<P>
   There are more weird titles, but you don't need to look at a
company flow chart to know this is not your ordinary office. You
get that impression when you enter the front door, where a huge
silver globe weighing 300 pounds rotates on an axis, displaying the
</P>
<P>
   company's name as it turns.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda didn't know a bit from a byte only five years ago. Now,
in kicking off a massive marketing campaign with a Super Bowl ad,
he's ready to take a bite out of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a better way for people to travel at the
last minute,'' Miranda said. ``We're providing it. We've got a
three-lap lead in a four-lap race. We're going to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he smiles. As if he knows something you don't.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
