<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5639 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-DOT-COMS-COX     02-03 1654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOT-COMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is this the era of the dot.coms?
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you build it, they will dot.com.
</P>
<P>
   That's the dream of LastMinuteTravel.com of Atlanta and a bevy
of other newly hatched dot.com companies. And just to make sure the
customers do come, a slew of Internet startups took big gambles on
super-pricey Super Bowl ads.
</P>
<P>
   As with the teams on the field, it was a make-or-break move for
some of the small companies. They realized that unless millions of
viewers remembered their names and Web addresses, their business
plans could die as like the Nashville Titans' hopes did at game's
end.
</P>
<P>
   LastMinuteTravel.com, a book-your-own-travel Web site that was
launched in January, spent about $3 million of the $9 million it's
raised from startup investors on a single 30-second ad in the
fourth quarter. It showed two cowboys waiting until the last minute
_ get it? _ to flee a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see it as a gamble,'' said David Miranda, 51, founder
and
</P>
<P>
   chairman of the company. ``We're not reckless. I would never bet
the company's life on this.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after the ad ran, (the first to air after the game
ended), Miranda claimed his site was getting 5,000 hits a minute
and that the ad had been wildly successful.
</P>
<P>
   But though he didn't see his $3 million ad as a gamble, many
outside observers did. Nine of every 10 new Internet companies will
fail this year, predicted John Antil, a marketing professor at the
University of Delaware and one of the top sports-ad experts in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any way you look at it, it's a crap shoot,'' Antil said.
</P>
<P>
   But he understands why a company like Miranda's would take the
risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a small, unknown company that wants to reach a very large
audience fast to gain brand awareness, which is essential for
growth, it's a crap shoot worth taking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl may be the only true national mass-media event
around, drawing up to 150 million Americans, Antil said, plus
millions more worldwide. And Antil's research shows that many
people tune in to the games _ which tended to be boring until this
year _ not to watch football, but to get a few chuckles from the
innovative commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only broadcast of the year where people are looking
forward to ads,'' Antil said. ``They've developed a reputation.
It's a showcase, and it can pay off big time.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, two dot.coms _ HotJobs.com and Monster.com _ bet the
bank on advertisements, and their gambles paid off.
</P>
<P>
   HotJobs.com, the smallest company in history to buy Super Bowl
airtime, spent $2 million for airtime and production costs. That
from a company with only $4 million in1998 revenues.
</P>
<P>
   People noticed, big time. HotJobs.com's Web site was inundated
with so many hits its computers couldn't handle the load. But it
had gained lasting brand recognition. Revenues shot up, and in
August it sold 3 million shares of its stock to the public for $8
per share. Now it's selling around $35 a share, and many of those
who were in on the ground floor are millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   The story was similar for Monster.com. Traffic on the job-search
Web site skyrocketed 450 percent the first month after the game.
</P>
<P>
   So what did HotJobs.com and Monster.com doing with their
new-found wealth?
</P>
<P>
   Bought more Super Bowl ads.
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com reckons it spent $5.5 million this year for five
30-second spots and production costs. Hotjobs.com figures its tab
ran $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly a third of the 60-odd Super Bowl XXXIV ads were bought
by Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like AutoTrader.com, which is owned in part by Cox
Enterprises (owner of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution and other
businesses), have pockets as deep as the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Comparatively speaking, many others have pockets as deep as a
mud puddle. This year's newcomers included Kforce.com, a job-hunt
site, and OurBeginning.com, which sells party supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much expect a 'Darwinian shakeout,' `` said Luke
Sullivan, creative head of the Atlanta ad firm WestWayne.
``Dot.coms that claim a significant share of mind and market now
are going to have the upper hand in all the struggles to come.''
</P>
<P>
   LastMinuteTravel.com could be one of them, Antil speculates.
``They've got one advantage over others,'' he said. ``Their name
makes sense, and it's easy to remember. Most dot.com names
aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the exposure they provide, one problem with Super Bowl
spots is that, in order to ``break through the clutter,'' many
devote most of their air time to humor, which leaves little time to
explain what the companies actually do. Anheuser-Busch doesn't need
</P>
<P>
   to explain that it sells beer, but the dot.coms are another
story. But can you remember from the ads what Oxygen.com
</P>
<P>
   does? Or computer.com? Or LastMinuteTravel.com, whose name
appeared for a second or two at the end of its ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can watch most Super Bowl ads and have no idea what the
point is or who's doing the advertising,'' Antil said. ``That's
where they go wrong. You can't be effective with humor alone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most dot.com advertising has most consumers wondering, 'What
the hell are they selling?' `` agreed Marian Salzman of Young &AMP;
Rubicam in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes attempts at humor can actually hurt a company. No one
in the ad business can forget an ad that shoe store Just for Feet
ran during last year's Super Bowl. It showed a black runner
sprinting through the African bush, chased by white men in a
military truck. After they snared him, they give him a drink laced
with drugs and put a pair of athletic shoes on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever comedy the agency intended couldn't be discerned by
critics, who quickly dubbed Just for Feet ``Just for Racists.'' Now
Just for Feet has run to court _ both to sue its ad agency and to
file for bankruptcy. It announced just before this year's Super
Bowl it was going out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the message gets through, mass exposure alone isn't
always a recipe for success. Tiny Gardenburger, a meatless-patty
maker, plunked down $1.5 million for an ad during the final episode
of ``Seinfeld'' in 1998. At first, sales went up, but they soon
</P>
<P>
   flagged.
</P>
<P>
   This year some companies paid as little as $1.9 million for a
30-second Super Bowl spot, while late-buyers anted up as much as $3
million. The average was $2.2 million, a big jump from the $1.6
million Fox charged last year.
</P>
<P>
   LastMinuteTravel.com's Miranda, a veteran marketer who spent
most of his career with Holiday Inns Worldwide, is nail-bitingly
aware of the TV costs, as well as the $500,000 it took to produce
his company's humorous spot. But Miranda, a Vietnam veteran used to
taking risks, is convinced it was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important is to create something that can extend beyond
the commercial itself,'' saud Atlanta ad whiz Joel Babbit, owner of
the agency 360. ``By that I mean PR and word of mouth. You need
something people will talk about and read about the next day at the
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Miranda and his marketing VP, Jack Arogeti, aren't arguing with
that. But they plan to keep on advertising as long as there's money
in the till.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep it up,'' Arogeti said. ``There'll be more
ads.''
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to spend another $20 million this year on
additional advertising, which means it's got to keep raising money.
Its posters and billboards, featuring pictures of its own
employees, already are plastered across MARTA stations and buses in
Atlanta and a few other cities.
</P>
<P>
   LastMinuteTravel.com also is betting on its niche in the dot.com
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what we're doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LastMinuteTravel.com differs from other book-your-travel sites
in that it specializes in seats available _ sometimes at a discount
_ in the days or hours before departure. Miranda calls it a ``stock
exchange'' that ``brings together motivated buyers and sellers.''
Travelers can use the site to find the best deals on last-minute
offerings of airline seats, hotel rooms, rental cars, cruises, even
tee times.
</P>
<P>
   The site has signed up more than 100 airlines, hotel chains,
rental-car companies and convention bureaus that pay to use
LastMinuteTravel.com. In most cases, they're charged a monthly fee
for the right to unload ``perishable'' commodities, such as unsold
</P>
<P>
   airline seats.
</P>
<P>
   LastMinuteTravel doesn't promise bargain prices, but Miranda
said they're possible if providers are eager enough to fill hotel
rooms or airline seats that pay nothing if left empty.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda raised his $9 million stake from private investors,
including Ted Turner, Billy Payne and Sergio Zyman, a former
marketing chief for Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``Super Bowl Sunday is the day the advertising business faces
itself,'' Young &AMP; Rubicam's Salzman said. ``If we're about
inventing desire, then it's the most significant prom, and the king
and queen had better exude sex appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey Reiman, Babbit's former partner who now owns the
Brighthouse ad agency in Atlanta, wasn't impressed with
LastMinuteTravel.com's sexiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LastMinuteTravel.com commercial feels like it was created
at the last minute,'' he said. ``The advertiser would have been
better off to offer last minute travel out of Atlanta after the
Super Bowl. That would have demonstrated the speed and the need of
this great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's ads, he said, must be ``deliberate and incredibly
focused. You have to break through the clutter and not be part of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lessons were learned this year, said Fred Allvine, who teaches
E-commerce and marketing at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   And even though he's looking for a major shakeout in dot.coms
this year, he predicts more start-up companies will be staking it
all on Super Bowl ads next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their time has come,'' he said. ``Or at least they think it
has.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
