<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Auctioneers Trading Up
</P>
<P>
   With Sotheby's and Christie's preoccupied with the Justice
Department's criminal antitrust investigation, Phillips, the
world's third largest auction house, is busy trying to make itself
more visible. With deep pockets provided by Bernard Arnault, the
French investor who bought the company in November, it is scouring
Manhattan for bigger, splashier premises.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips owns a building on 79th Street between First and York
Avenues, but it is a small space, with only one combined gallery
and salesroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding an ideal auction site in New York is a nightmare,''
said Dan Klein, Phillips' international executive director. ``It
took Christie's years to find Rockefeller Center.''
</P>
<P>
   While it looks, Phillips will take over the exhibition space at
the American Craft Museum at 40 W. 53rd St. in Manhattan from May
11 to 18 to show and sell 19th- and 20th-century art.
</P>
<P>
   Klein declined to say how much Phillips was paying the museum
but said he considered the fee ``a fair commercial rent.'' People
close to the negotiations who spoke on the condition of anonymity
said that the auction house had agreed to pay the museum $100,000,
which includes the cost of printing a catalog for one of the
museum's exhibitions, ``Defining Craft I.'' Phillips is a sponsor
of the craft exhibition, which opens next week and runs through May
7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a corporate rental program like any other,'' said
Holly Hochner, the American Craft Museum's director. ``But this is
the first time we've done something of this nature.'' Hochner said
that the timing was serendipitous.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has supported 20th-century decorative arts, she said,
and when it approached the museum about renting space, she realized
the auction dates fell between two shows. ``It seemed like a great
marriage of opportunity,'' Hochner said. ``Our whole museum will be
empty, so there won't be any confusion of identify. Even the shop
will be shut.''
</P>
<P>
   For Phillips, the chance to exhibit and sell its goods in a spot
diagonally across the street from the Museum of Modern Art and four
blocks from Christie's was irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we needed to break the mold and to build a more
credible, glamorous image,'' Klein said. ``Being in the heart of
the art district is a way of being taken seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of the Phillips sale include paintings by Monet,
Chagall, Matisse and Braque and sculptures by Henry Moore and de
Chirico. Phillips will also be showing 10 years of French
photography. Viewing is from May 11 to 16, with the sales on May 17
and 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a hurry to make a move,'' Klein said. About
competing with Sotheby's and Christie's he added, ``Maybe we can
drive a wedge between them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning House
</P>
<P>
   In the printmaking world, the name Kenneth Tyler is instantly
recognized. Tyler, a pioneer in developing printmaking techniques
and persuading major artists to devote much of their time to
pushing the limits of the art, began to print for Josef Albers in
1963 and founded Gemini G.E.L. in Los Angeles two years later. By
1973 he had moved to Bedford, N.Y., and begun Tyler Graphics Ltd.
in a carriage house. In 1987 he moved the business to Mount Kisco,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Tyler announced that he was retiring and that he
would sell a selection from his personal collection and inventory
from Tyler Graphics at Sotheby's in New York on May 6. It will be
the most comprehensive sale of postwar prints.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler has worked with artists including Frank Stella, Robert
Motherwell, Roy Lichtenstein and Helen Frankenthaler. Their works
are to be in Sotheby's sale. ``These works go way beyond simple
prints,'' said Christopher Galliard, head of Sotheby's contemporary
print department in New York. ``What makes them so special are the
unusually large presses used to make large-scale prints and the
complex, rich surfaces. It could often take over a year to produce
a print.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Sotheby's star offerings are Frankenthaler's ``Free Fall''
(1993), a woodcut on hand-dyed, handmade paper, estimated to sell
for $20,000 to $25,000; Lichtenstein's ``Reflections on a Girl''
(1990), a lithograph with screen print and relief print, is
estimated at $100,000 to $125,000, and Stella's ``Fountain''
(1993), a woodcut, etching and aquatint relief printed in colors on
three sheets of handmade, hand-colored paper, is estimated at
$100,000 to $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   Restructuring
</P>
<P>
   Christie's is preoccupied with examining its bottom line and
ways it can capitalize on its valuable real estate holdings. The
latest news: an internal staff announcement on Monday that Spink, a
London-based subsidiary of the auction house, is closing its
department of Chinese, Japanese, Korean, South East Asian,
Himalayan and Tibetan art as of Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see a profitable future in this area,' said Edward
Dolman, chief executive of Christie's. ``We've been looking at
Spink for some time, and only last week did we make the decision
final. This is part of an ongoing review to make sure we're trading
as profitably as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Spink's coins and medal department is to move to Southampton
Row, near the British Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1666, Spink has built its reputation by specializing
in Asian art along with British paintings, coins and medals. When
Christie's bought it six years ago, its location next to the
headquarters of Christie's London, on King Street, St. James', gave
it as much as its art trade did.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Spink gave Christie's control of the block bordered by
King, Duke, Ryder and Bury Streets. For months, Christie's has
considered developing the block with an eye toward transforming the
Spink building into a retail and office complex and building a
hotel with an entrance on Ryder Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a property play,'' Dolman said. ``It is a result
of restructuring.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie's plans to keep Spink's Islamic and Indian art
departments, but they will not be based in the Spink building. All
Dolman would say about their new home is that it would be
``somewhere in St. James'.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1749EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
