</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DIRTY BLONDE' HUNTING A HOME  
 AN ACTRESS RETURNS 
A SECRET TREATMENT  
 NINE LIVES FOR GRAY  
 MUSICAL CHAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's got good ink, hot sales and celebrities flocking
in. It's got the money, the talent and the time to perform right
into the summer. So where is Claudia Shear's ``Dirty Blonde'' going
to go _ and when?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question bouncing around Broadway, but so far there
are many possibilities and no clear answer. The show, about Mae
West and a pair of fans obsessed with her, is playing at New York
Theater Workshop in the East Village, where it is scheduled to
close on Feb. 13. But it is an open secret that the workshop and
the Shubert Organization, which helped develop the play, are
looking for another home. An extension at the workshop is not
possible because another production is scheduled to open in March.
</P>
<P>
   So three options are being weighed. The first and most
intriguing possibility is the Criterion Center in Times Square, the
former home of the Roundabout Theater Company, which left in June
after longstanding conflicts with the building's owner, Charles B.
Moss Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Criterion has been dark ever since, and one of its two
theaters is not suitable for performance. But the remaining
theater, the 499-seat Stage Right, is functional. Producers have
been discussing reopening Stage Right for ``Dirty Blonde,'' though
that decision would require restaffing the theater, not to mention
plenty of dusting.
</P>
<P>
   Opening the Criterion would also raise some interesting awards
issues. When it was being run by Roundabout, Stage Right was a
Tony-eligible theater, but it is not clear whether that status
would still hold for another production. Keith Sherman, a spokesman
for the Tony awards, said the issue would have to be sorted out by
the group's administration committee, which has put it on the
agenda for a meeting next week.
</P>
<P>
   (In separate Tony news, Sherman confirmed Thursday that Rosie
O'Donnell would return as this year's host, a move that organizers
hope will reinvigorate the telecast's sagging ratings. The awards
are to be presented on June 4 at Radio City Music Hall.)
</P>
<P>
   If the Criterion doesn't work out for ``Dirty Blonde,'' the play
may try an off-Broadway theater, though few are available, or even
a small Broadway house, like the Helen Hayes or the Golden. In
either case, ``Dirty Blonde'' would need another show to expire,
which producers are loathe to talk about for fear of inviting bad
karma on themselves. Indeed, producers would not comment on any
plans for the show except to say that several alternatives are
being weighed.
</P>
<P>
   All the maneuvering, of course, is in support of a show that is
packing the house downtown, drawing the likes of Glenn Close, Tim
Robbins and Faye Dunaway. David Bowie and his wife, the model Iman,
are on Saturday night's waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I met Paul Newman,'' said Kevin Chamberlin, who plays a
shy fan, Charlie, in the show, ``I said, `It's an honor, Mr.
Newman. And he said, `Call me Paul.'''
</P>
<P>
   An Actress Returns
</P>
<P>
   It's an all-too-familiar story. An actress cuts her teeth in New
York theaters, makes a name for herself, then takes off for
Hollywood and is never seen in these parts again.
</P>
<P>
   But now one's coming back. Beginning in June, Christine
Baranski, who found mainstream fame a few years back in the CBS
sitcom ``Cybill,'' will be back on stage, appearing with Nathan
Lane in a revival of ``The Man Who Came to Dinner'' at the Selwyn
Theater, the new home of the Roundabout. Baranski will be working
once again with the director Jerry Zaks, with whom she teamed up in
``The House of Blue Leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Baranski, who helped make her name with turns in ``Hurlyburly''
and ``Rumors,'' hasn't been completely AWOL; she appeared briefly
in a 1997 concert version of ``Promises, Promises,'' at City
Center.
</P>
<P>
   This time, she says, she'll stick around a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   A Secret Treatment
</P>
<P>
   Beth Henley, whose voice still glimmers with a Southern lilt, is
headed north again. Her newest play, ``Family Week,'' is set to
open in the second week of April at the Century Center for the
Performing Arts on East 15th Street in Manhattan. Ulu Grosbard will
direct.
</P>
<P>
   What's it about? Henley said the five-character play concerns a
weeklong visit to a treatment center by a family visiting a
middle-aged woman. Treatment for what? Henley won't divulge that
secret, but will say it's ``not what you would think.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``It's terrible and hysterical and everybody has a
different take on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine Lives for Gray
</P>
<P>
   The sun just won't set on Spalding Gray's ``Morning, Noon and
Night.'' After a run last fall downtown at P.S. 122 and a current
run uptown at Lincoln Center, Gray's droll new monologue will head
to the Union Square Theater, where it will reside on Sunday and
Monday nights. (``Wit'' is there the rest of the week.)
``Morning,'' about Gray's adventures as a parent, will begin
performances at the Union Square on Feb. 20. David Binder is
producing.
</P>
<P>
   Musical Chairs
</P>
<P>
   Finally, for those who keep score at home: ``Waiting in the
Wings'' will transfer from The Walter Kerr to the Eugene O'Neill on
Feb. 17 to make way for the revival of O'Neill's ``Moon for the
Misbegotten,'' opening at the Kerr on March 19. ``James Joyce's
`The Dead,''' meanwhile, has announced an indefinite extension at
the Belasco Theater, where it has had surprisingly brisk sales. No
replacement yet for Blair Brown, who is going into rehearsals for
``Copenhagen,'' but Christopher Walken is staying put and
apparently loving the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of playing the Belasco, ``The Real Thing'' will play the
Barrymore. And finally, because of knotty scheduling problems and a
scarcity of theaters, it looks increasingly unlikely that ``Boston
Marriage,'' a new play by David Mamet, will reach New York this
spring. Look for it in the fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
