<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Feb. 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clouds, patchy light snow and flurries will linger from southern
New England to the interior Northeast as low pressure moves out to
sea south of Cape Cod. The snow will accumulate an inch or two in
many areas near the southern New England coast during the day,
while little accumulation is expected farther north. Locally,
higher amounts may fall near the immediate coast where winds from
the ocean import additional moisture. Elsewhere across the region,
snow showers will be common near the eastern Great Lakes and
central Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Southeast will be breezy and cool in the wake of a
cold front. Cloudiness will linger near the western slopes of the
southern Appalachians, but sunshine will be plentiful from the
eastern Carolinas to most of the Gulf Coast states. Clouds and
thundershowers will occur in the warmer air over southern Florida
early Friday, but drier air is expected to arrive by afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Expansive high pressure will promote dry weather and plentiful
sunshine over a large area from the Rockies to the Plains.
Temperatures will remain several degrees above normal in northern
areas, while near seasonal conditions prevail farther south.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, clouds will linger from central California to the
coastal Northwest. Light rain will dampen northern California and
coastal Oregon as an offshore front approaches. Intermittent snow
will prevail in the northern Sierra and southern Cascades.
Meanwhile, the interior Western States will be dry with a mixture
of sunshine and clouds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Clockwork Ice
</P>
<P>
   Like clockwork, Lake Erie became covered by ice this week, a
total freezing that happens, on average, the last week of January
or the first week in February. Lake Erie is the only Great Lake to
typically freeze over in winter, a distinction dictated by depth.
Lake Erie is the shallowest of the Great Lakes, with a limited
reservoir of warmth stored beneath its surface. As surface water
cools in winter, it becomes dense and sinks, with slightly warmer
water from below rising to the surface to replace it. By late
January or early February, warmth is exhausted, and the lake
freezes over. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
