<P>
   MCCAIN-POLLSSC _ New polls show McCain actually running ahead of
Bush in South Carolina. Contributions continue to pour in, with
$750,000 since 7 p.m. Tuesday. It's likely to reach a million by
tonight. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-INTERNET _ WASHINGTON _ With his online campaign chief
saying ``the Internet has just changed politics,'' Sen. John McCain
reported Thursday he had
</P>
<P>
   raised nearly as much money online since his New Hampshire
primary victory Tuesday as he had in his entire campaign up to
then. The flood of online money means McCain won't have to wait to
commit resources in his battle against George Bush. In another
innovation, McCain plans a Feb. 10 online fund-raiser accessible
only to those who donate $100 first. (Glass, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ SUMTER, S.C. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush gives an
old-fashioned stump speech at the courthouse here Thursday morning,
then heads to Delaware to campaign. (Greenberger, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-BUSH-SQUABBLE _ Democrats are amused as some of Florida's
top Republicans squabble over plans to allow former President
George Bush to address the state legislature just five days before
the presidential primary. ``Well, it's certainly a plus for George
W., and after what happened to him in New Hampshire he needs all
the help he can get,'' said Charles Whitehead, the Florida
Democratic Party chairman. ``If I were John McCain, I would think
it was a little unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   (Crowley, Palm Beach Post). 12.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-ATTORNEY _ ATLANTA _ Baltimore Ravens' linebacker Ray
Lewis didn't know two people died in a fight that occurred outside
his limo until he saw it on the news, Lewis' new attorney Ed
Garland said Thursday. Lewis, according to Garland, is a peacemaker
who avoids fights or tries to break them up. Also, A.J. Johnson,
sought by police in connection with the killings, said he wasn't
even in Atlanta during the Super Bowl. Checking into whether Lewis
and Kwame King were childhood friends in Florida. Story will
include other news of the day. (Longa, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI-FLAG _Some Mississippi legislators are hoping this
is the year lawmakers at least discuss removing the Confederate
battle flag from the corner of the state flag. Black legislators
have filed two bills that would remove the Confederate battle
symbol, which they feel glorifies the Old South and with it,
slavery. Similar bills have been filed for 20 years in Mississippi,
but they haven't made it past a committee. But this year, it is a
national issue. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DINOSAURS-EXHIBIT _ ATLANTA _ Dinosaur experts say the ambitious
new dinosaur exhibit at Fernbank Science Center in Atlanta is the
first of kind anywhere and will attract scientists from around the
country as eager as kids to see the Argentinosaurus and the
Giganotasaurus. The story will explain the significance of the
discovery of these dinosaurs and the exhibit. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   KY-GA-SCHOOLS _ To see what could be in store at schools all
over Georgia, look at the way teachers and parents sit down
together every month in decision-making bodies called school
councils in almost every school in Kentucky. From the hollows of
Appalachia to cities of the Bluegrass to farmlands on the
Mississippi River, these elected councils are changing the old
relationships of parents, teachers, principals, superintendents and
local school boards with one another. (Cumming, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 57. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-WEALTH _ WASHINGTON _ The net worth of the average
African-American household fell even as the economy boomed over
over the past five years, according to a University of Michigan
study. (Turay, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   RURAL-TV _ WASHINGTON _ THe Senate Agriculture Committee holds a
hearing on a proposed loan guarantee program to provide satellite
and cable systems for rural areas. (Livingston, Cox News Service).
18.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BUTCHER _ DEVON, England _ A short bright on a local
butcher who is refusing to convert to the metric system despite
British law. He says they can come and take his weights and scales,
but he's not giving in to what he considers European imperialism.
It's a revealing look into how many Brits really feel about Europe.
(Roughton, Cox News Service) 12. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
