<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5654 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-03 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AH, DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If all the world's a stage, the crucial role is to
operate the curtain, or better yet, the trap door.
</P>
<P>
   That's what New Hampshire gets to do every four years, and state
voters took their responsibility seriously this week. Their primary
did us all a favor by producing an entirely satisfactory outcome,
setting up a competitive presidential contest between two men in
each party who are experienced political pros sensitive to the
country's philosophical middle-ground instincts.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens next, the country will be in safe hands.
</P>
<P>
   The primary dispatched the notion that either party was headed
for a coronation. Two hundred years ago we taught the British we
don't like crowned heads and we haven't changed our minds since.
Somehow the self-anointed heirs-apparent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
and Vice President Al Gore, initially missed that message.
</P>
<P>
   But we prefer professional wrestling to non-competitive
ceremonies, whether in mud, a roped-off canvas ring or politics.
Grubby work, but it's our specialty.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire gave Arizona Sen. John McCain a spectacular
victory to humble Bush and stop all that premature measuring of the
White House drapes. And the state was kind enough to former Sen.
Bill Bradley that his narrow loss will keep Gore on his toes for a
while yet.
</P>
<P>
   We now have four presidential candidates who are responsible,
qualified and articulate politicians with differing but not
alarmist views of the world. None is likely to take us off on an
unsettling, ideological lurch the way the discredited former GOP
Speaker Newt Gingrich attempted after seizing control of the House
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore can take nothing for granted. If they are to beat
off the insurgents, they must work for it. This is the American
way.
</P>
<P>
   We can mercifully forget the three unworthy Republicans who
cluttered up that party's debates without any elected governmental
experience or sense of our country beyond their own narrow
ideological agendas. One candidate had the mistaken idea that money
is everything and the other two that criminalizing abortion is all
voters care about. Of the latter pair, Gary Bauer is already
leaving, and the remaining Steve Forbes and Alan Keyes are all but
finished. Good riddance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who wised up to Bradley's threat months ago, is a stronger
candidate now than in the days when he expected the nomination
simply because he was next in line as sitting vice president. If he
wins, he will have done it the old-fashioned way: He will have
earned it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's learning curve has been slower. He still seems burdened
with a sense of entitlement that leads him to underestimate the
public desire for the unscripted candor, fresh ideas and strong
voice that propels the McCain candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been running a campaign just like the one that elected
dear old dad to the White House in 1988 _ full of empty patriotic
phrases and establishment endorsements but short on substance. Papa
Bush got away with it because his Democratic opponent was the
hapless Michael Dukakis, who never knew what hit him. But daddy
lost his re-election bid four years later when he tried to run on
the same empty fumes against a more scrappy, policy-oriented rival,
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It is Bush the younger's bad luck to face in McCain a candidate
with an intellect more like that of Clinton than Dukakis. McCain is
personable and out to redefine conservative politics along new,
centrist lines _ much as Clinton reshaped Democratic politics. It
will not be enough for Bush to insist that he is conservative and
McCain is liberal. Voters are bored with ideological games and not
sure about the distinctions that matter so much to purists anyway.
</P>
<P>
   So far, in South Carolina, which holds the next GOP primary,
Bush seems content to rely on labels rather than specifics. He
cites his all-out tax cut plan as the goal of a true conservative
and McCain's tailored tax cut reserving money for Social Security
and Medicare as a liberal big-spending boondoggle. This will not
wash.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's first move in South Carolina was to produce his father's
widely derided vice president Dan Quayle for an endorsement. Quayle
himself tested a presidential campaign last year but gave up for
lack of support. His appearance with Bush in that heavily religious
state was supposedly meant to reinforce the Texas governor's
Christian conservative credentials. But it seemed instead a
desperate tactic. If he's his own man, why does he need Quayle?
</P>
<P>
   The familiar view of South Carolina is that of a state mired in
its past, proud of its conservative traditions and instinctively
bowing to entrenched power. But South Carolina is changing,
becoming a modern center of industry and commerce. McCain is
testing the limits of that change. Bush is clinging to the past.
They both can't be right. That's why we have democratic election
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1805EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
