<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AUTOS-BOOKS-ART-2TAKE     02-03 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-BOOKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK'S PAGES OF CLASSIC GAUGES AND DASHES WITH FLASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've always taken my car's dashboard for granted. Other than
fiddling with the radio or tape player, an occasional glance at a
gauge or warning light is about the extent of my involvement with
that structure between me and the engine.
</P>
<P>
   But after reading ``Dashboards,'' by David Holland (Phaidon
Press, paperback, $19.95), I've found myself stopping at
interesting-looking parked cars, particularly older ones, to peek
at their arrangements of gauges and dials on the other side of the
steering wheel. That's because Holland's lavish coffee-table book,
with photographs by Colin Turner and Ken Kirkwood, conveys a
fascinating tale of the evolution of the automobile dashboard, even
to those with only a passing interest in cars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is accomplished with photographs of 52 vehicles and their
dashes, ranging from the 1904 Panhard et Levassor of France to the
1973 BMW 2002 Turbo of Germany. There is a minimum of text, but
it's enough. The pictures do the job. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an introduction, Holland, a British automobile collector and
restorer, explains why he did not go beyond 1973: ``I have
deliberately stopped at the point where natural evolution has
brought all to the same bland conclusion _ the padded facia
containing near-identical instruments and controls in standardized
positions. The dashboards selected for this book come from the days
when a dash was still a dash. These dashboards have character.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess that accounts for the lack of interest I have shown in
the dash of my 1991 Saab.
</P>
<P>
   The dashboard, as Holland explains it, was originally the
foremost part of a horse-drawn carriage that prevented mud or
stones from being thrown onto the passengers. By the early 1900s,
similar boards, or sometimes a leather apron, were used for the
same purpose in horseless carriages. Pretty soon carmakers began
hanging gadgets and gauges on these boards and they evolved into
the modern dashboard with which we are all familiar. And while the
dashboard comes between the driver and the engine, it is at the
same time the driver's vital link to the machinery he or she is
operating, providing important data like engine temperature or oil
pressure. Of course, modern electronics have made the post-1973
dash a virtual cornucopia of data _ from door-ajar warning lights
to electronic maps _ compared with the simple panels pictured in
``Dashboards.'' But the book is a paean to aesthetics, not
technology. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, readers will be drawn to those cars in the book that
they remember or have had some experience with. Your reaction to
the pictures will date you as surely as growth rings reveal the age
of a fallen tree. One of my earliest childhood memories is riding
on my father's lap in Kentucky in 1948 as he let me ``drive'' an
Army surplus Jeep whose engine he had overhauled. And there,
starting on page 150 of ``Dashboards,'' are photos of a 1943 Willys
Jeep, looking just like my father's _ down to the olive-drab paint,
the round gearshift knob and the fold-down windshield. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The dash of the 1958 Edsel, Ford Motor Co.'s $350 million
failure, is pictured, along with the horse-collar grille that
surrounded the car's name in vertical lettering. Despite its
failure, the Edsel had some flash: a rotating-drum speedometer that
looks a bit like a ship's compass and ``teletouch'' buttons in the
center of the steering wheel to engage the automatic transmission.
But, alas, the car never engaged the buying public.
</P>
<P>
   For chrome-dripping opulence, few cars can match the 1959
Cadillac Eldorado with its distinctively high tailfins, boatlike
proportions and full-width grille. But surprisingly, the dashboard
is more spartan than the exterior would suggest. Holland describes
the dash as a prelude to modern design because it features cruise
control, electric windows and air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   The dash of the 1955 Chevrolet Corvette, America's answer to the
sports cars of Europe, seems odd by today's standards. It is nearly
symmetrical, with instruments radiating both left and right from
the center rather than being clustered in front of the driver. The
radio speaker on the right matches the shape of the speedometer on
the left; the tachometer is in the center, under the radio itself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My favorite photographs are of a 1950 Chrysler Town &AMP; Country
``woodie'' and the 1951 Buick Le Sabre concept car. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysler's dash is surprisingly modern, with a hooded
speedometer and instruments clustered directly in front of the
driver. But it's the car's exterior wood trim that captivates. A
close-up photo shows the quality of the wood and carpentry, right
down to a carefully mitered joint.
</P>
<P>
   The Le Sabre was a monster of a dream car created by Harley
Earl, the legendary General Motors designer. It looks like a rocket
with its mammoth fins and big central taillight. The
black-and-chrome dash, embedded with exotic instrumentation, seems
ready for Buck Rogers to jump in and roar off. In fact, the car
stands as a symbol of what futurists of the early 1950s thought
we'd be driving by 2000. They were wrong, but they sure had fun.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Two other new books look into the future, not the past, of the
automobile, toward a time when the internal-combustion engine and
its pollution are gone. That may be sooner than you think,
according to ``Forward Drive'' by Jim Motavalli (Sierra Club Books,
$25) and ``Powering the Future: The Ballard Fuel Cell and the Race
to Change the World'' by Tom Koppel (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $27.95).
Hybrid cars are already in production that combine electric and
gasoline engines, and cars run by fuel cells _ which mix hydrogen
and oxygen to produce electricity, with clean water the sole
byproduct _ seem only a few years off. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ``Forward Drive,'' which will not go on sale until March,
Motavalli deals more broadly with alternative power and takes the
automotive press to task for its continued fascination with the
internal-combustion engine. The author is editor of E: The
Environmental Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Powering the Future'' is mainly about Ballard Power Systems of
Burnaby, British Columbia, which has done pioneering work on fuel
cells. Koppel, a Canadian freelance writer, tells how Geoffrey
Ballard and his colleagues took an exotic, space-age technology and
adapted it for use in automobiles. Ballard's rise from its humble
beginnings in a makeshift lab in Arizona in the 1970s to its
pivotal position today _ DaimlerChrysler and Ford both hold stakes
in it _ makes compelling reading. And Koppel explains the
technology in a way that the average reader can understand.
</P>
<P>
   These are among other recently published books with an
automotive bent:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Deal Maker,'' by Axel Madsen (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $30). A
well-written biography of William C. Durant, who founded General
Motors in 1908 but declared bankruptcy in 1936, listing assets of
$250.
</P>
<P>
   _  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Road Rage to Road-Wise,'' by John Larson, M.D., with Carol
Rodriguez (Forge, paperback, $11.95). A psychiatrist's somewhat
overblown response to a somewhat overblown problem. But such a book
clearly has its place in driver education courses or for those with
a history of traffic violations.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Selling Dreams: How to Make Any Product Irresistible,'' by
Gian Luigi Longinotti-Buitoni with Kip Longinotti-Buitoni (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $26). This book explains how you've been manipulated into
lusting for a $10,000 watch that doesn't tell time any better than
a $50 Timex. The author knows a thing or two about marketing
expensive goods: He is president and chief executive of Ferrari
North America. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
