<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5682 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BABITSKY-BOS &LR;      02-03 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BABITSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KREMLIN SAYS IT HAS SWAPPED MISSING JOURNALIST FOR 3 POWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The case of missing journalist Andrei Babitsky took a
strange twist Thursday as the Kremlin announced it had turned the
crusading reporter over to Chechen rebels in exchange for three
Russian prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that Russian authorities were trying to either silence
or discredit Babitsky, who infuriated the Kremlin with his critical
coverage of the war in Chechnya, his family and colleagues reacted
to the announcement with suspicion, fear and anger. Some said they
feared for his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is awful. I am very worried about Andrei's safety,''
Babitsky's wife, Lyudmila Babitskaya, said in an interview. ``I
don't know what kind of condition he is in, if he has been beaten
or worse. I don't know what to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   A reporter for US-funded Radio Liberty, Babitsky, 35,
disappeared while leaving Chechnya's capital of Grozny on Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, officials in Moscow said Russian forces had detained
him for lacking accreditation to work in the war zone and on
suspicion of joining the Chechen rebels. On Wednesday,
law-enforcement officials said Babitsky, who had not been allowed
to contact his family or his colleagues, would be released and
returned to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Kremlin spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky said
Babitsky had instead been exchanged for three Russian prisoners of
war and was in the hands of the Chechen rebels. Yastrzhembsky added
that Babitsky had agreed to the exchange and that Russian
authorities were no longer responsible for his safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very serious blow to journalism and free speech in
Russia,'' said Savik Shuster, Radio Liberty's Moscow bureau chief.
``When a journalist is taken hostage and he is then exchanged for
other hostages, what can we expect next?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very worried about Andrei's safety. Until I see him I
cannot be certain that he is alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio Liberty's broadcast director, Jeff Trimble, said that
Thursday's news came as a shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is incredible and unacceptable that a man who has been held
without the ability to communicate with his family should be used
in this way,'' Trimble said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharip Yusupov, a Moscow-based spokesman for the Chechen
government, said that Babitsky was with the rebels, that he was
safe and would soon be returning to Moscow. The claim, however,
could not be independently confirmed, and a Chechen representative
in Washington said he had not heard of it.
</P>
<P>
   As the day progressed, suspicion about Babitsky's whereabouts
increased when he failed to contact his colleagues or his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Igor Yakovenko, head of the Russian Journalists' Union, said in
a statement that he held the Russian government responsible for
Babitsky's safety. He also called accusations that he had joined
the Chechen militants ``wild and absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid of my own suspicions. I sincerely hope I am wrong
but I am very worried that Andrei may not be alive,'' said Oleg
Panfilov of the Glasnost Defense Fund, a Moscow-based free press
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian media have been mostly supportive of Russia's battle
against separatist militants in Chechnya, which began in September.
Mindful of how critical media reports turned public opinion against
Russia's previous, unsuccessful attempt to defeat the rebels in
1994-96, the Kremlin has gone to great lengths to control
information this time around.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, Babitsky's witheringly critical reports on high
Russian casualties and the plight of Chechnya's civilians iritated
officials in Mosccow. On Jan. 8, police raided the reporter's
Moscow apartment and confiscated photographs he had taken of a
battle in Grozny in which Russian soldiers were routed by Chechen
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generals wanted to remove Andrei. If you look at the first
Chechen war it is clear that the journalists were the winners,''
Panfilov said. ``They stopped the war.''
</P>
<P>
   In a televised interview, Russia's Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev showed open disdain for Babitsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would trade 10 Babitskys for one soldier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While most of Russia's state-controlled media has branded
Babitsky a traitor, the privately owned NTV television station _
which has also criticized the war and has used Babitsky's material
in its reports _ has been supportive of his plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of Boris Yeltsin's first decisions as president was to
grant Radio Liberty the right to work officially in our country,''
NTV anchor Yevgeny Kisselyev said in a broadcast Sunday. ``Now,
after Yeltsin's resignation, one of the first journalists to suffer
repression is a Radio Liberty correspondent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
