<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE HAMMERS AWAY AT BRADLEY ON HEALTH CARE, EDUCATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After a whirlwind cross-country trip and a
marathon town hall meeting that dragged on until 1 a.m. Thursday,
Vice President Al Gore hit the ground running later in the day,
telling employees at a Los Angeles visual effects company that Bill
Bradley's health care plan would squander the surplus and cheat
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that surplus is gone, he can't put anything into
education,'' Gore said. ``That's why he has not put forward a
comprehensive education plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has made several education proposals, which include: an
early care and education partnership program with local businesses,
fully funding Head Start, training and recruiting 60,000 teachers,
forming scholarship and loan programs, improving access to
community colleges and improving after-school care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I invite you to contrast the positions that I've put forward
on this (education) with the positions put forward by (Bradley),''
Gore said.``If you look at his proposals, here's what you find: no
comprehensive education plan, not one penny to help middle income
families pay for college ... It is not a priority to his campaign.
It is the No. 1 priority for me,'' Gore said at Digital Domain.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposals are similar to Bradley's, but his includes a
plan for smaller classes and schools, tutoring for failing
students, tripling the number of charter schools by 2010, new
buildings and higher academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also was in California, holding a rally Thursday with
supporters at San Francisco's Fisherman's Wharf.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's message that education should be America's No. 1 priority
in the information economy appeared to strike a chord with computer
specialists at Digital Domain, the multimedia company that provided
visual effects for such movies as ``Titanic,'' ``Apollo 13'' and
``What Dreams May Come.''
</P>
<P>
   An official with Digital Domain said 40 percent of its employees
were foreign nationals, because the company could not find
qualified Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``is speaking the same language,'' said Joanne Capitano,
the company's marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   Gore pointed out that the Venice, Calif., company, which also
works on visual effects for theme parks and computer games, has 30
well-paid jobs that it can't fill because it can't find enough
qualified workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not limited by much here,'' Gore said, ``but you are
limited by the substandard performance of our public schools.``
</P>
<P>
   Gore was accompanied by California Gov. Gray Davis, who told a
crowd of about 50 employees that Gore's experience is key to
providing leadership from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to give a speech and another thing to make
something happen in your life,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Gore traveled from New Hampshire to New York to
Washington, D.C., to Ohio before recharging on the flight to Los
Angeles and then engaged voters in a town hall meeting that dragged
on for 3 hours and 18 minutes, just a few minutes short of his
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry. I promise you I won't leave until every question
is answered,'' Gore told undecided voters gathered at Los Angeles
City College. ``I'll stay here until March 7 if that's what it
takes.``
</P>
<P>
   More than an hour after Gore finally closed the formal question
and answer session, dozens of people hung around to shake his hand
and ask questions ranging from his religious beliefs to gay rights
to welfare reform to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
