<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5694 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-CAFE04-COX     02-03 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CAFE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    See you at the bookstore, our living room away from home
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Duane Brantley leans on a magazine rack at
Borders bookstore, his head buried in Mountain Bike Action
magazine. He's happily oblivious to the passage of time, to his
fellow magazine browsers, to the live jazz band playing in the
cafe. A few feet away, Yiannis Pavlou, 28, a four-times-a-week
regular, is sitting at a table, using his laptop to catch up on
work. Across the room, Thays Glasgow is knitting a sweater for her
9-year-old daughter, Daphne, who is reading ``Lacey's Crush,'' the
sixth in the Sweet Valley Jr. High Series. The only thing missing
is a fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the magazine rack, Tsambika Bakiris, 20, who believes
there is no such thing as too many books, is carting an arm load of
psychology texts. Mingling at Borders provides ``balance'' in her
busy collegiate life. Later, she's going dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys would rather go have a drink after work. I like to
come look at computer books, listen to the music, relax and have a
cup of hot chocolate,'' says Brantley, 34.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the new town square. Or public meeting hall. Or
watering hole. Whatever it is you're looking for, chances are you
can find it at the Borders and Barnes &AMP; Noble bookstore/cafe
behemoths that have sprung up in metropolises across the country.
Mix live music, coffee, food and bibliophiles in a comfortable
atmosphere. Shake them around. Chill out. What you get is a place _
maybe even a community _ where people want to hang out for hours,
browsing through bookshelves, sipping coffee, eyeing the seemingly
single.
</P>
<P>
   It's coming together at a local Borders, which Glasgow, husband
David and daughter Daphne patronize every Friday and Saturday night
and sometimes Sunday afternoons. ``We make dates with other
families,'' she says. ``I'll talk to someone and say, `Oh, you're
going to Borders tonight? We'll see you there.' We spend little
money for good entertainment here. We can easily spend four hours
on two cups of coffee, and this is a good place for Daphne because
she loves to read.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the large chains that are attracting customers who
are looking for the extras. Eddie Tennison and Anne Cook are hooked
on Adventures In Crime &AMP; Space Books, a small bookseller that makes
up in hometown feel what it lacks in big store amenities. They
frequently dine in nearby restaurants and complete the evening with
a visit to the bookstore, where they browse and pick owner Willie
Siros' brain about mystery and science fiction books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie's is a special event for us,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   They also spend a lot of time at Book People down the street
from Adventures, and Barnes &AMP; Noble in Westlake, where their
teen-age daughter likes to study. Cook says Barnes &AMP; Noble, which
is near their home, has turned into a weeknight homework haven for
high school students.
</P>
<P>
   Serving customers' needs is important to a store's place in the
community. Yes, community _ the big chain stores want to be
involved in the schools and neighborhoods around them. Take the
Borders near the new southern branch of Central Market. It has its
own community relations coordinator, Sharon Mays, who visits
schools, lines up live music and last month organized group
discussions on exercising, losing weight, traveling and balancing
the family budget. As a result, outside groups, not just book
clubs, are meeting at the cafe. She calls her store a community
events center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers told us they wanted live music in the afternoons, so
we switched it (from nights). They asked for children's storyteller
Lisa Baker twice a month, so we booked her. We're buying a piano
for the cafe that anyone can use. Why? Because people expect more
than books,'' says Mays.
</P>
<P>
   It's an expectation that was created years ago not by the
mammoth chains, but by the scrappy independents.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1976, Edward Morrow, the owner of The Northshire
Bookstore in Manchester, Vt., began occasionally serving hot malt
cider and scones to his customers. They loved it. Then he moved his
store across the street to bigger quarters, sans the drinks and
pastries. Now, he's adding a cafe to his expanding store. ``People
are now expecting first-rate stores to have a a place to sit and
drink coffee,'' says Morrow, who served as president of the
American Booksellers Association from 1989 to 1990. ``The chain
stores picked up the idea from successful small independents like
Kramerbooks &AMP; Afterwords in Washington, D.C., and went to Wall
Street for financing. Then they rolled out the stores across the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely even their investors foresaw what was coming.
Local artwork on the walls. Pokemon card trading clubs. Brunch. And
the unwritten invitation to browse. The stores don't care if you
buy something (well, they sort of do), they just want you there.
Borders is confident that customers who spend a lot of time at a
store sipping coffee or browsing are also impulse buyers. ``It's a
whole shopping experience,'' explains Mays. ``Even the people who
come for just an event or hang out will buy a book, or music or
merchandise that day or return another day to buy. We know these
people are regulars who come in four times a month. They will
buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they've got something to sell. Bob and Carrie Barnstien
show up at Borders on a Saturday night to listen to the Java Jazz
band and tell people the good news. ``We came here to speak God's
word. We'll tell people what God has done for us,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Brantley, the bike magazine browser, says the environment is
conducive to entrepreneurship. ``I see people jotting things down
on paper napkins. New ideas are being created. The possibilities
are endless,'' he says. ``The next great widget could be coming
from a guy sitting over there listening to the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the guy who's probably making the biggest killing is
whoever took out a patent on big, cushy chairs. At the Barnes &AMP;
Noble near the University of Texas, students loiter in various
states of sprawl. Shaw Lash, 19, and Kimberly Jarboe, 21, are
draped on chairs and chatting over coffee. Classical music is
playing softly on the intercom. ``It feels like home,'' says
Jarboe.
</P>
<P>
   Home, meeting room, study hall, library with very strict
checkout policies _ the new bookstores are all of these things, and
more. But one thing they're not are singles bars for the brainiac
set. At least not yet, says Borders customer Melanie Thompson, 21.
``They could be. I met a nice guy here last week with the same
literary interests as me. I was hoping he'd be here tonight, but oh
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she's off to the travel section to visit faraway places.
``I want to go to China, and here I can do it,'' she says.
``Without anyone telling me I have to buy the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
