A5704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-RURAL-TV04-COX     02-03 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RURAL-TV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATORS DEBATE LOANS TO IMPROVE RURAL TV PROGRAMMING
 &HT;    By GINGER LIVINGSTON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rural communities would have better access to local
television channels under a $1 billion federal loan guarantee
program for satellite broadcasting, the Senate Agriculture
Committee was told Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small-scale, low-density settlement patterns make it costly to
deliver these types of services to rural Americans,'' said Sen.
Richard Lugar, R-Ind., chairman of the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite television industry, originally created to serve
rural America, told the committee that economic considerations
force it to concentrate on the nation's largest television markets.
</P>
<P>
   About 800 television stations serve the nation's 66 largest
television markets and reach 80 percent of its households, said
John Hutchison, chief operating officer of LTVS, a Raleigh, N.C.,
satellite broadcasting company.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 800 U.S. stations serve the remaining 144
television markets, but reach only 20 percent of the nation's
households, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The loan guarantee would support up to $1 billion in loans to
provide a satellite that would beam local broadcasts to those rural
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max S. Baucus, D-Mont., proposed the loan guarantees last
fall as part of the Satellite Home Viewer Improvement Act, but the
provision was removed from the final version of that bill.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, whose Banking Committee also held
hearings on the issue this week, was among the lawmakers who
opposed the Baucus provision.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm believes the legislation should provide for a greater
financial investment by the private sector, plus guarantees that
taxpayers could recoup losses if there is a default on the loan,
said Christi Harlan, the banking committee's communications
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm also wants an advisory panel that will oversee the
management of loans.
</P>
<P>
   Lugar said Thursday that creating a new oversight committee
would delay implementation of the program. He is proposing that the
U.S. Department of Agriculture's Rural Utilities Service agency
oversee the loan's management.
</P>
<P>
   The Banking Committee will take the issue up again next week
when its hears from Montana's other senator, Tom Burns, who is
drafting legislation that will incorporate Gramm's proposal into
Baucus's original legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Livingston's e-mail address is gingerl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
