<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5708 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV10-     02-03 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV10-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW KIND OF FULL DISCLOSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Feb. 10.)  
(lh) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have to hand it to the bold women in Rylstone, England, who
decided to do a nude calendar and raise money for leukemia
research. Certainly, baring one's buns for charity beats holding an
everyday bake sale.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did standing there facing the world wearing only their
pearls yield this innovative group a whopping $550,000 in calendar
sales, they performed a great public service _ to middle aged
bodies around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you love to read the minutes from the brainstorming
meeting when their Women's Institute, which normally meets to make
jam and do crafts, came up with a new fund-raiser: ``It has been
moved by Moyra and second by Lynda that we all take our knickers
off and pose starkers.''
</P>
<P>
   I haven't seen the calendar. Their Web site reports they're sold
out. But the newspaper photo of the group, in which they're fully
clothed, shows them looking like nice, ordinary women. Like
someone's book club.
</P>
<P>
   The telling thing is that even out of their neat suits and
turtleneck sweaters they apparently look equally ordinary. And this
made them more a hit than a disappointment. They look like us,
meaning ``us'' as in real flesh and blood types. No celebrity
tushes here. No Golden Globe bosoms. Just your average naked
grown-up body that has been around for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The response was the British equivalent of ``you go, girl'' and
respectful applause. Uplifting, said one reviewer. How wonderful to
see real women, wrote one man, ``instead of stick insects with
pouty lips and pipe cleaners for legs.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a bit harsh, but it was jolly good of him to appreciate
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   How refreshing to see ripe, middle-aged bodies whose hills and
valleys you can relate to. The problem with going around with
clothes on all the time is that everyone's hiding everything, so
after a while we begin to think that we're the only ones whose
bodies don't match the ones in magazines and those taut ones on the
movie screen getting all the good sex. Real women can use the
validation.
</P>
<P>
   In the old movie ``Harold and Maude'' in which young Harold
cavorts with much older Maude a priest shudders over the mere
thought of her nakedness next to his.
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much how it has been with the media, making it
tough to be comfortable in our own skins when we're told all the
time that the only flesh worth looking at belongs to a certain age
and skin tone.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, said the women of Rylstone, England, and their fans.
What's wrong with ripe flesh? Who says smooth is better than
wrinkled? Hip, hip, hooray for a round belly and un-perky breasts.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, who can believe in celebrity flesh anyhow, with all the
plumping, enhancing, implanting and sucking out that is routinely
done on actresses and models. With digital photography, even those
bodies we futilely compare our own against may be artificially put
together from various real ones.
</P>
<P>
   Better for your self esteem to go with the real women of
Rylstone whose dimples you can trust as much as your own.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural ideal of beauty being a ``non-threatening girl's
body rather than a woman's body'' serves to keep women pre-occupied
with body-hating, says Carol H. Munter who co-authored the book,
``When Women Stop Hating Their Bodies.'' Munter says that when we
complain non-stop about our bodies we perpetuate the belief that
the female body is never entirely acceptable. Then we end up
spending all our time trying to change the way we look rather than
trying to change the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think would happen if all the women in the world
suddenly stopped hating their bodies?'' Munter ask groups of women
who come to her talks. And the reply, she says, is, ``We'd have so
much energy, we'd take over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark that down on your calendar.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 1839EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
