<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5715 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FASHION-KORS04-COX     02-03 1811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-KORS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kors' fashion picks make him Goodwill ambassador
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Stand back. Hold on to children and
small pets.
</P>
<P>
   Keep elbows and feet out of the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kors is shopping, and no item of clothing is safe from
his dead-on sense of style, eye for quality and quick wit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love a baby T. How much is it? A dollar? Excuse me! The
Gap's too high.''
</P>
<P>
   The designer, visiting Palm Beach for a personal appearance at
Saks and a charity fashion show at a private home, has one hour to
pull together three outfits from the thousands of mismatched pieces
at the South Dixie Goodwill. It's a gauntlet that we've thrown down
and he has gamely picked up.
</P>
<P>
   Sound easy? Ha! His mission is rife with danger: A thrift store
can be a minefield of fashion disasters waiting to explode. Again.
</P>
<P>
   A chunky pair of maroon corduroy shirts catches his eye. ``How
fat do you think someone will look in these? She bought them, she
took them home, and she always regretted the day of purchase.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his Seventh Avenue credentials, Kors is no stranger to
the often strange world of thrift, where Calvin Klein sweaters can
rub worn elbows with college sweatshirts. ``Fashion people love to
forage and love to shop,'' Kors says. ``This is really what I do
for a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that and design critically acclaimed clothes for his own
label and the French fashion house Celine. His fun, sexy, colorful
sportswear _ seen regularly in the pages of Vogue and Harper's
Bazaar and on the backs of celebs such as Gwyneth Paltrow and
Courtney Love _ helped him snag fashion's most prestigious prize
last year, the CFDA Award for Women's Wear Designer of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Kors divides his time between New York and Paris, but on a
recent Friday afternoon he arrives at the pink stucco Goodwill,
looking very fashionable in Banana Republic khakis and a black
long-sleeved T from the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, it's department-store thrift,'' he gushes,
surveying the Goodwill. ``This is the biggest thrift I've ever been
in! It's enormous. ... This isn't like some of them I've been in
where it's like dragging through a box.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes to get his bearings, Kors plunges into the
skirt section, partly because it's easier for women to get a proper
fit in a skirt than in a pair of pants. (``I don't trust pants,''
he says.)
</P>
<P>
   Kors says he's looking for natural fibers and classic shapes,
and each piece has only seconds to impress.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny wrap skirt in a bold print: ``A little Heather Graham.
Someone was flirty.''
</P>
<P>
   A gingham skirt: ``This looks like Michael Kors from the '80s. I
always did a lot of chocolate-and-white gingham.''
</P>
<P>
   A corduroy skirt with ruffled hem: ``I think someone in Paris
just showed that skirt! You have to understand, fashion moves so
fast now we're soon going to have an early '90s revival.''
</P>
<P>
   Kors briefly considers tooling through the menswear department,
where women can find timeless basics such as plain white shirts.
(``Men think it's a badge of honor to tell you they've been wearing
the same thing for 30 years. But just because you can get it on
your body doesn't necessarily mean it still fits.'')
</P>
<P>
   But he never makes it to men's, with so many shorts, dresses and
shirts to size up. Coats beckon to him, PJs ``depress'' him. The
'80s-ness of so much of the inventory is almost unbearable. The
good, the bad and the hideously ugly is each summed up with a quip.
</P>
<P>
   A sundress: ``Get ready for full Melanie Griffith! She's
flowered. She's strappy.''
</P>
<P>
   A pair of short shorts: ``Someone had a little hot pant thing
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   A white boatneck shirt: ``That's fabulous. Excuse me, it's
probably on Worth Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   A menswear-inspired vest: ``It's gray flannel, so it sells me.''
</P>
<P>
   A striped boatneck tee: ``A Marimekko moment! We love
nautical!''
</P>
<P>
   A fire-engine red crocheted top: ``Very Jan Brady. I think my
mother wore it as a coverup over her swimsuit. It's a little
acrylic for me.''
</P>
<P>
   After 45 minutes, his shopping cart is overflowing and Kors is
satisfied that he's seen enough. The clothes are laid out in the
furniture department on a sectional sofa that the designer
describes as ``very `Boogie Nights'.''
</P>
<P>
   The Melanie Griffith dress gets tossed for being ``too funny,''
a basic white shirt is declared ``too boring,'' and the Marimekko
top is just too large compared with the other pieces.
</P>
<P>
   A '50s fur-collared coat, although it had sent him scurrying
across the floor when he first spotted it, gets the cold shoulder
because of a damaged spot on the arm. A pair of white jeans has a
tiny stain that Kors thinks would be impossible to remove. In
total, 30 pieces receive a one-way ticket back to the racks, and
three modern outfits are created using yesterday's castoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fun thing about going into a thrift shop is you can buy it
and wear it once. If you had to pay $1,200 for that dress, you'd be
annoyed. But, for $3.85, it's a date dress.''
</P>
<P>
   FOUR LOOKS FOR FIFTY BUCKS!
</P>
<P>
   Surveying his final choices, Michael Kors is pleased and, he
admits, pleasantly surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is literally how all the supermodels dress. ... Amber
Valetta would not be seen in a new dress. It has to be vintage.''
</P>
<P>
   In just three outfits, Kors has covered every season and every
time of day _ work, weekend, evening. Plus, he has built one outfit
around black, one around brown and one around vivid colors _ a
smart strategy that could be expanded wardrobe-wide. The price tag
on so much style? A measly $52.75.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saved all this money,'' Kors says, ``you could afford
to go buy one expensive thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. We hear this fellow Michael Kors makes some fabulous
frocks ...
</P>
<P>
   THE PALM BEACHER: $15.44!
</P>
<P>
   ``How Palm Beach is this?'' Kors says. ``With the green pants, a
fuchsia turtleneck and a yellow cardigan, she could go insane.''
</P>
<P>
   The pants are a men's 30 _ roughly a women's size 8. But Kors
says they're worth altering, and he'd hem them into capris. (``The
ankles are the one part of the body that doesn't age.'')
</P>
<P>
   When dressing casually, you can choose shoes on the cheapy side,
Kors says. For this outfit, he suggests Dr. Scholl's, flip-flops in
a bright color or a pair of white leather loafers. His final
choice, however, is this pair of yellow heels: ``How good are
these? These are heaven!''
</P>
<P>
   Lined in canary yellow, the purse is a last-minute find. ``Oh,
here's my bag. She's been hiding. She's so good. You can't go wrong
_ it's straw,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Green pants (never worn!): $2.85
</P>
<P>
   Pink Land's End turtleneck: $2.85
</P>
<P>
   Yellow lambswool sweater: $2.85
</P>
<P>
   Yellow leather shoes: $2.85
</P>
<P>
   Straw purse with yellow lining: $2.19
</P>
<P>
   Straw hat: $1.85
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL: $15.44
</P>
<P>
   THE CAREER GIRL: $19.23!
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for this outfit is Mary Tyler Moore, a '70s
fashion icon who continues to serve as muse for designers today.
``The whole working-girl thing is coming back,'' Kors says.
</P>
<P>
   The A-line tweed skirt was the first item Kors spied when his
spree began. ``This skirt is heavenly. Right off the bat!'' (He
points out that it would also look good with a snug turtleneck.)
</P>
<P>
   The blouse ``is full-on Prada this season'' _ with one small
fix, the removal of ``the really ugly button'' at the collar.
</P>
<P>
   And the trench coat is pivotal because it will go with anything.
``I literally showed this coat,'' Kors says. ``This is the most
perfect piece in the whole store.''
</P>
<P>
   (Note: Don't go looking for the trench at Goodwill. The Palm
Beach Post fashion editor bought it for herself.)
</P>
<P>
   Trench coat: $8.49
</P>
<P>
   Ivory blouse: $2.85
</P>
<P>
   Plaid tweed skirt: $2.85
</P>
<P>
   Open-toed pumps: $2.85
</P>
<P>
   Clutch purse: $2.19
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL: $19.23
</P>
<P>
   THE LADY: $15.23
</P>
<P>
   Despite its clear retro influences, this feminine ensemble is
very, very now.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer black dress ``looks just like Prada this season,''
Kors says.
</P>
<P>
   And the shrunken, velvet jacket? ``I think we're showing this
jacket in New York in a month.'' (If a jacket's sleeves are too
short for you, cut them off to bracelet length to make them look
purposefully short, Kors suggests. Think of the way Jackie Kennedy
used to wear her suits.)
</P>
<P>
   Kors calls the T-straps with skinny heels ``fabulous and sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it's a timely look. ``There's a return to `The
Lady,''' Kors says. ``Something a little more Grace Kelly is
popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheer, pleated dress: $3.85
</P>
<P>
   Fitted velvet jacket: $5.49
</P>
<P>
   Patent-leather belt: $.85
</P>
<P>
   T-strap heels: $2.85
</P>
<P>
   Deco-inspired purse: $2.19
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL: $15.23
</P>
<P>
   BONUS OUTFIT!
</P>
<P>
   Kors' task was to assemble three ensembles, but he was compelled
to create one more when it came time to toss a DKNY houndstooth
skirt into the discard pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's asking to be put in,'' said Kors, matching the
wool/cashmere skirt with the velvet jacket from the evening outfit
and the ivory blouse from the work category.
</P>
<P>
   And for $2.85, who can resist?
</P>
<P>
   BUYING POWER
</P>
<P>
   Designer Michael Kors makes thrift-shopping look remarkably easy
and incredibly fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have an eye, you can do it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He shared some tips on developing that eye and shopping smarter,
whether at Goodwill or Bergdorf Goodman:
</P>
<P>
   _ Go natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wools hold up. They last. Cottons and linens do too.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid sticker shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get caught up in the bargain of it if it truly isn't a
usable piece. But if it has possibilities, for $3 you can take a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Gather, then edit.
</P>
<P>
   Kors paid little mind to whether separates would match as he
piled his shopping cart high. He spent 3/4 of his time at the
Goodwill gathering items, and the last 25 percent deciding what to
keep and what to toss.
</P>
<P>
   _ Invest in small changes.
</P>
<P>
   Big shoulder pads bugging you? Replace them with smaller pads or
rip 'em out all together. Love the dress but hate the buttons?
Change them. The shoes fit but they're a little rough around the
edges? Have them reheeled and resoled.
</P>
<P>
   _ That said, carefully consider footwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not normally a believer that you can fake it on shoes. You
can pay a dollar for a dress, but spend the money on the feet.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep it simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have a tendency to pile on too much,'' Kors says.
``Take it off.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Take care of the basics.
</P>
<P>
   A good haircut, a manicure and professional alterations are the
foundation of looking stylish, no matter how much you spend on your
wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   THE KORS LOOK
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for Michael Kors' Spring 2000 collection was the
preppy glamour of early '70s Palm Beach: crisp colors, clean lines
and a certain sex appeal. As for the Barbie-doll models, their hair
was big, and their fake lashes were bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
