<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-PEBBLE-SECURITY-NYTR &LR;      02-03 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEBBLE-SECURITY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPARATING PLAYERS FROM THE FANS AT PEBBLE BEACH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BRUCE MEADOWS   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ When it comes to security for players at
a PGA tournament, especially one like this week's AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach
National Pro-Am, how much is too much?
</P>
<P>
   ``It might come to the point where it might be like a high
school, where you have to have metal detectors in order to go in,''
said Tiger Woods, who is going for his sixth consecutive victory at
Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had a gallery-sized entourage of security people when he
played at the Williams World Challenge in January in Arizona that
included two Scottsdale police officers along with security
officers hired by the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all the various bodies _ the PGA, the USGA and PGA of
America _ have to wrestle with the reality,'' said Ric Clarson, PGA
business affairs spokesman. ``And I can tell you, the Tour has gone
to great lengths to address the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tournaments like this week's AT&AMP;T, the Bob Hope two weeks ago
and last week's Phoenix Open are all popular events that draw
crowds who come not only for the golfers, but the celebrities as
well.
</P>
<P>
   At the Phoenix Open, David Duval was so upset by heckling on
Saturday, that he cleared out his locker and appeared ready to quit
the event. PGA officials coaxed the world's No. 2 player to come
back on Sunday, when he shot a 69 to finish tied for 30th at 5
under par.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's irrelevant,'' Duval said when asked about whether he
had planned to pull out. ``But I think we as players deserve to be
treated with a bit more respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Galleries in Phoenix are among the rowdiest on the PGA Tour, but
Duval was bothered by some specific comments about him personally.
</P>
<P>
   He raised some hackles in the gallery when he raised his finger
to the crowd on the 12th hole. Observers differed on whether it was
an obscene gesture or an effort to quiet the spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't there myself,'' Phil Mickelson said. ``But I was
disappointed that some people continued heckling him. That was
uncalled for.'' Mickelson said fans who harass players should be
kicked off the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the marshals there for?'' he asked. ``As many times
as he got heckled, I can't believe the marshals or somebody didn't
get rid of somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second episode in as many years at Phoenix. The
previous year, an inebriated spectator following Woods' group was
arrested and a loaded gun was found in his backpack.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Duval and Woods incidents happened near the 15th and
16th holes at Phoenix, where large groups of fans gather around
tents that dispense booze.
</P>
<P>
   There are other recent incidents as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 Greater Hartford Open, Scott Hoch came to blows with
a heckler when he walked off the 18th green after comments had left
Hoch's wife in tears.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999 Anderson Consulting World Match-Play event, Nick
Faldo topped a tee shot, hitting it 100 yards when a cell phone
went off during his downswing.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones are banned at PGA events, but you don't have to look
hard to find them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago there were no cell phones, so it wasn't a
problem,'' said pro Jim Furyk. ``But now, people are so blatant
about it ... they talk on the phone while you're 10 feet away
trying to hit off the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 Players Championship, Steve Elkington enjoyed a
five-stroke lead when a drunken fan yelled out: ``Hey Elk, how
about a couple of double-bogeys to make it interesting?''
Elkington's caddy later got in a confrontation with the spectator.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA is well aware of the growing problems, many of them
directly tied to the sale of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   At the AT&AMP;T, a 4 1/2-foot chain-link security fence was erected
between the 18th green and the bleachers to keep fans at a
distance. The PGA also is enforcing more strictly a policy of
searching handbags and other such items carried by fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour has created a full-time security force at PGA and
Senior PGA events, including personnel in civilian clothes as well
as uniformed officers, and has urged tournament officials to beef
up their own security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like to publicly state the exact measures we're
taking, for obvious reasons,'' said PGA spokesman Dave Lancer.
``But we're dealing with the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Some changes include banning beer sales at historic ``trouble
holes,'' and moving beer stands several hundred yards away from
tees.
</P>
<P>
   If a fan brings a cell phone or pager to a PGA event, he or she
will have to hand it over to security and pick it up from security
when the round is over.
</P>
<P>
   But with spectators able to smuggle just about anything on the
course _ including weapons _ with relative ease, it's not a stretch
to foresee something truly unfortunate happening to a player,
spectator or marshal.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for PGA commissioner Tim Finchem told the PGA Policy
Board that the only way to control the Phoenix Open _ which drew
close to 500,000 spectators last week _ is ``to reduce the size of
crowds significantly, like they did in Dallas'' for the Byron
Nelson Classic.
</P>
<P>
   One way would be to limit daily ticket sales _ like it's done at
the U.S. Open _ or eliminating daily tickets entirely, opting for a
weekly badge that could cost as much as $150.
</P>
<P>
   But when you're talking about taking money out of the cash
register, tournament officials would quickly point out, that you're
taking away money from the charities that benefit greatly from the
PGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the answer is,'' Mickelson said. ``But
something needs to change.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
