<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAIL-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS COUNTY PLEADS FOR HELP AS SUSPECTED PAROLE VIOLATORS FILLING
UP JAIL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A Harris County Jail official Thursday pleaded
for state help in dealing with the costly, steadily increasing
number of suspected parole violators temporarily locked up in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   More than 550 suspected parole violators are in custody in
Harris County awaiting hearings, up from about 200 less than a year
ago, said Sheriff's Maj. Mark Kellar. Their upkeep costs the county
about $50 a day per inmate, he estimated.
</P>
<P>
   The state needs to speed up parole revocation hearings and
dedicate more prison space to parole violators, Kellar told the
Texas Commission on Jail Standards, which regulates crowding in
local lockups.
</P>
<P>
   With the Harris County Jail barely under its capacity of 8,600
inmates, jailers have been nervously watching increases in the
number of parole violators since last spring. If unabated, the
trend could cost local taxpayers about $10 million a year, Kellar
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to identify why is this number growing. Quite
frankly, I don't think we have an adequate explanation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and experts said a possible cause is an effort by the
Board of Pardons and Paroles to deal with backlogged parole
violation charges, coupled with a space crunch in some state
prisons. Other causes cited were bureaucratic inefficiencies and
delayed impact from the restructuring of the criminal justice
system in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Though counties and the state used to feud openly about the
state's duty to house sentenced offenders, this quandary will be
fixed with state and local cooperation, Kellar predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to get into drawing lines in the sand and
chaining inmates to fences. We are approaching it from good
faith,'' Keller said, adding that parole and prison officials have
been ``very encouraging'' in recent meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state has a responsibility in this issue,'' Kellar
emphasized. ``These are state inmates who have been convicted of
state crimes in state district courts, sentenced to terms in the
state penitentiary and paroled to a state agency, with the rules
and regulations developed by another state agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Collin County Sheriff Terry Box, a commission member,
sympathized with his colleague's plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very large number of inmates without any local
charges,'' Box observed. ``It's really hurting the bigger urban
counties.''
</P>
<P>
   One defense lawyer suspects the numbers are swelling because the
state is tackling a long-standing backlog of unserved ``blue
warrants'' for parole violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely out of control,'' said Huntsville lawyer Bill
Habern, who said he has won cases recently in which blue warrants
were not served deligently and were based on long-expired parole
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
