<HEADER>
A5730 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA-SURVEY04-COX     02-03 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-SURVEY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta rank for on-time arrivals dips, report shows
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines slipped from third to fourth place in
1999 for on-time rankings for major carriers but moved up two spots
to second place for fewest mishandled bags.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta also maintained a third-place standing for
its rate of consumer complaints to the U.S. Department of
Transportation, which compiles the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's year-end Air Travel Consumer Report reflects
airlines' poor year for customer relations, which saw the industry
come under fire in Congress and issue voluntary service standards
to avoid government intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers filed 20,495 complaints to the DOT about airline
service, more than double the 9,608 complaints of 1998. Part of the
reason, however, may lie in easier methods of filing, including an
electronic complaint form now posted at the DOT Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint total translated to a rate of 2.48 complaints per
100,000 enplanements, up from 1.08 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But for Delta specifically, the results ``confirm our ongoing
commitment to customer service,'' said spokesman John Kennedy. He
noted that Delta was the only hub-and-spoke carrier that finished
among the top four in all three service rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Delta had consistently ranked near the bottom of the industry
for on-time arrivals _ including a last-place finish in 1997 _
before the carrier's new management team started a concerted effort
to improve. That led to a third-place finish in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Delta backtracked only slightly in 1999, with 78 percent of
flights arriving within 15 minutes of the scheduled time, down from
79.6 percent in 1998. TWA showed the biggest on-time improvement,
jumping from fifth to first, while American and USAirways fell to
the bottom tier.
</P>
<P>
   Delta improved its luggage handling rank despite a slight
increase in its rate of mishandled bags to 4.39 per 10,000
customers vs. 4.27 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers filed 1,916 complaints to the DOT against Delta,
giving it the lowest rate except for Southwest and Alaska. AirTran,
Delta's much smaller rival in Atlanta, was the subject of 267
complaints, but it is not ranked by rate because it is not
classified as a major carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the complaints about both Delta and AirTran were about
flight delays, cancellations or unspecified ``customer service''
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
