<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5738 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-FLA-BUSH-SQUABBLE04-C     02-03 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-BUSH-SQUABBLE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former President Bush's planned speech raises some GOP eyebrows
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Democrats are amused as some of
Florida's top Republicans squabble over plans to allow former
President George Bush to address the state Legislature just five
days before the presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's certainly a plus for George W., and after what
happened to him in New Hampshire he needs all the help he can
get,'' said Charles Whitehead, the Florida Democratic Party
chairman. ``If I were John McCain, I would think it was a little
unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling it ``political elitism,'' state Comptroller Robert
Milligan, who is state chairman for McCain's presidential campaign,
said the Arizona senator is a victim of ``power politics made worse
by its use against a member of the same party.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who overwhelmingly defeated Texas Gov. Bush in the New
Hampshire primary Tuesday, has not been invited to speak to the
Legislature. The Florida primary is March 14 and Bush is to speak
on March 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no occasion for such a speech at this time other than
an effort to rub the former president's popularity in Florida off
on his son just before the primary election,'' said Milligan.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Florida's Republican leadership is backing the Texas
governor. His brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, is using his
formidable resources to help George W. Bush's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Making the effort here additionally daunting for McCain is the
support George W. Bush is getting from the state Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a crucial time in our history and we have to do all we
can to make sure Republicans win this election,'' said Al Cardenas,
the state GOP chairman who, rather than remain neutral as has been
custom, has endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker John Thrasher
</P>
<P>
   (R-Orange Park), who campaigned for Bush in New Hampshire,
insists that the timing of the elder Bush's speech is largely
coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, President Clinton and then-Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas
spoke to the Democratic-controlled legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Republican legislature, so I guess if they want
President Bush to come by, he can come by,'' said Sen. Tom Rossin,
the Democrat leader. ``I'm not sure it will really accomplish
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
