A5742 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-SEVENTH-DISTRICT04-CO     02-03 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEVENTH-DISTRICT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's 7th District race sparks $2 million
 &HT;    By Richard Whitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Leading Republican and Democrat candidates in the 7th
Congressional District race raised more than $2 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbent Republican Bob Barr reported collecting $1,286,000 in
1999. He spent $572,000 and has $714,000 on hand, according to
Federal Election Commission reports.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta businessman Roger Kahn, Barr's likely Democrat opponent
in November, reported contributions of $750,000 with more than
$500,000 on hand. Thus far, Kahn has opposition in the Democratic
primary from former Polk County Commissioner Jim Williams, who got
45 percent of the vote as the Democratic nominee in 1998, and
Charles ``Chip'' Warren, a former Atlanta police officer who is
president of the International Brotherhood of Police Officers.
</P>
<P>
   Although incumbency gives Barr a clear advantage, Kahn's
fund-raising appears to be enough to make a competitive race, said
Merle Black, Emory University political science professor. ``People
don't give that kind of money for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barr has represented his district in such a way as to make it
possible for him to be unseated. He has been very visible and very
involved in political causes. That is a style that unites a
hard-core conservative base but does little to enlarge that base,''
said Black. ``Someone like Barr will always be vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia residents accounted for 60 percent of the itemized
contributions received by Barr, who aims to raise $2 million for
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
