<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5744 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-(TRIMS)     02-03 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-(TRIMS)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI-PALESTINIAN SUMMIT CONFERENCE ENDS WITHOUT PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EREZ CROSSING, Gaza Strip _ Israeli and Palestinian leaders
ended a summit meeting here Thursday in frustration, still bogged
down in disagreement over interim issues and far from bridging gaps
on the thorny final issues that stand between them and a permanent
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the meeting began, there seemed little chance that
the Israelis and the Palestinians would meet their written goal of
reaching a framework for a final status accord by Feb. 13. But the
two-and-a-half-hour meeting, reportedly tense, did not produce even
enough understanding for the two sides to announce a deferral of
the deadline, as had been expected, or any other plans for the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the parties went backward and became mired in rehashing
an interim agreement that they signed in September. Specifically,
the Palestinians expressed anger that the Israelis had not
accommodated Palestinian requests to gain control of villages near
Jerusalem when the Israelis drew up the maps for their next
withdrawal from the West Bank, which was supposed to have proceeded
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the two sides did quietly acknowledge to each other
that the deadline would be broken, although no new date was set,
said a spokesman for Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a kind of mutual understanding that by Feb. 13 there
will be no detailed framework agreement,'' the spokesman, Gadi
Baltiansky, said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials declared a crisis in the negotiations,
saying their leader, Yasser Arafat, whom Barak walked to his car,
had left in anger. A news conference scheduled at the end of the
session was abruptly canceled. Arafat and his aides drove off
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials were left to shrug and raise their eyebrows
and put a positive spin on a clearly disappointing meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there is no crisis,'' Barak's senior diplomatic and
security adviser, Danny Yatom, said as he denied reports that
Arafat had stormed out. ``There are some disputes between the
Israelis and the Palestinians, especially concerning the contents
of the land that we committed ourselves to hand over to the
Palestinians. But the meeting went as planned, and everybody was
patient enough to sit in the room to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   When Barak and Arafat arrived, local photographers called out to
request a handshake. A good body's length away from each other,
they extended their arms and shook for the cameras. But it was
decidedly forced, just as the setting was both more formal and more
public than that of many of their previous unpublicized late-night
meetings in private houses or unmarked office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting Thursday, the two were accompanied by phalanxes
of advisers but spent a brief period face to face. Their encounter
ended while journalists were gathered in a conference room for the
news conference that never occurred.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, plans for the next negotiating round, scheduled for
Sunday, were not canceled. So despite the disappointments of the
day, the process is generally expected to continue.
</P>
<P>
   What the parties labeled ``intensive negotiations'' on the
substantive issues of a permanent peace _ borders, the status of
Jerusalem, the future of the Jewish settlements and the Palestinian
refugees _ began last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. peace envoy, Dennis Ross, arrived Wednesday to assist
the effort. But a spat over what was to have been Israel's third
and final land transfer to the Palestinians under the interim
agreement of September has marred progress on the talks for a
permanent peace. As during the second Israeli land handover, the
Palestinians objected to the ``quality'' of the transfer, having
requested control of some Arab towns on the outskirts of Jerusalem.
They strongly objected to the process, which they think should be
more collaborative.
</P>
<P>
   And they protested Barak's reluctance to discuss yet another
Israeli redeployment, beyond the three mapped out in the September
accord, in the interim period. Barak contends that the status of
the remaining territory should be debated in the context of a final
pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real crisis is the crisis of trust, which is growing
larger,'' said Palestinian minister of Jerusalem affairs, Ziad Abu
Ziad. ``It seems that the Israeli government does not view the
peace process as a process that involves two parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters after Arafat had left, Foreign Minister
David Levy of Israel said he had no doubt that the matter of the
maps and the land transfer would be resolved. A similar dispute
over the second withdrawal, at the end of last year, was resolved
despite Palestinian predictions that Israel's behavior would be a
deal-breaker. But Palestinian officials were led to believe that
they would be more satisfied this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in the interest of both parties to solve the problem,
and not to remain in an argument over the interim agreement,'' Levy
said. ``Because that which awaits us is the thing that counts and
is the work in which we have to invest all of our efforts. The
attempt to delay is simply not productive and will not be
productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials said they would ask Ross and the Americans
``to pressure Israel to implement the signed agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis prefer to solve issues bilaterally. Levy said that
the Americans ``enjoy the faith of both parties,'' but that the
Americans could not be substitutes for a real dialogue between the
parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
