<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROGERS04-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three legends reunite in booth
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For college basketball fans whose memories date to a time when
Ronald Reagan was president, the CBS coverage of Connecticut and
Michigan State on Saturday will be like a reunion of their favorite
band.
</P>
<P>
   After a playful suggestion that the return of Dick Enberg, Billy
Packer and Al McGuire as a three-man booth was akin to a Beatles
reunion, McGuire said, ``I don't think you can return. It was a
happening at the time, like the Amboy Dukes. But we won't try to
recapture anything. We'll just be ourselves in the year 2000, and
it will be three guys who leave their egos in their cars in the
parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   And if McGuire is to be taken at face value, this reunion will
also be part of his farewell tour to broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely my last year,'' McGuire said. ``I don't
want to have to start a third safety-deposit box.''
</P>
<P>
   However, McGuire, 71, has not told CBS formally that he is
quitting after this season, and, for the moment, the network does
not expect McGuire's ninth year at CBS to be his last.
</P>
<P>
   Neither do Enberg and Packer. Instead, they spoke about looking
forward to their first game with McGuire since the 1981
championship between Indiana and North Carolina on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick and I worked together last week for the first time in 20
years, and it took us a half to figure out where we were,'' Packer
said. ``This is something I never expected to happen, and it's
rather incredible that our great friendship and relationship will
have a chance to get together at least for one game.''
</P>
<P>
   Although two decades have passed since Enberg, Packer and
McGuire were a team, they still rank as one of the best three-man
booths in the history of sports television. Their last telecast
together was significant for another reason. President Reagan was
shot that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people were stunned they didn't postpone the game,''
Enberg said. ``Our enthusiasm and the enthusiasm of the crowd were
drained away. There's not much I remember about that game....
</P>
<P>
   ``But Saturday's game between Connecticut and Michigan State is
still the thing, and we're not going to let a chance to take an
encore bow get in the way of the game. But you know there will
probably be some disagreement between Billy and Al in the first 10
minutes. Our reportage won't be set to soft violin music.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A weekend for star gazing
</P>
<P>
   Between the CBS coverage of the Pebble Beach National Pro-Am and
ABC's hockey-football doubleheader Sunday, plenty of star power
will be on display. ``A lot of people who come here do not want to
watch the golfers,'' CBS golf analyst David Feherty said. ``They're
not here to see Tiger Woods; they're here to see Kevin Costner.''
Meanwhile, ABC will showcase hockey's best in the NHL All-Star Game
at 2:30 p.m. Sunday, followed by the NFL's best in the Pro Bowl at
5:30 p.m.... For further proof of the Kings' star power in the NBA,
their game against the Pacers at 8 tonight on TNT replaces the
Rockets and Timberwolves, and NBC will show the Kings and 76ers to
more of the country Sunday than it will the Spurs and Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
