<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DEMOCRATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SEEKS CALIFORNIA WIN AS BRADLEY KNOCKOUT PUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore is looking to delegate-rich
California to help him knock Bill Bradley out of the race, and he
has spent an enormous amount of time and energy here raising money
and cultivating support, particularly among minorities, organized
labor and women.
</P>
<P>
   After a long day Wednesday that began in New York and included
stops in Washington, D.C., and Columbus, Ohio, Gore arrived at the
Burbank Airport, where he was greeted by a about 400 supporters,
including comedian Jay Leno, and a few protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Then he conducted a 3-hour, 18 minute town hall-style meeting
with undecided voters, who were very different from those in Iowa
and New Hampshire _ not only more diverse but also more personal in
their probing of the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Are he and Tipper born-again Christians? (They are, Gore said).
Does he support marriages bewteen homosexuals? (He does not, but he
also opposes the Knight Amendment, a March 7 ballot inititiative
designed to invalidate gay marriages considered legal in any other
state).
</P>
<P>
   James Thomas, a 37-year-old minister, lectured Gore on the vice
president's support for welfare reform. He also told Gore, ``You
have mentioned slavery many times. Affirmative action is in no way
a remedy for slavery.'' He then called on Gore ``to not only
declare war on the environment, but to declare war on people who
continue to oppress people of color'' if Gore is elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore responded, ``I have it in my heart to do exactly that and
to lead to the kind of changes in the way people think and feel.''
He also defended his views on welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Thomas said he was still ``ambivalent'' about Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Gore spoke to about 50 employees at Digital Domain, a
multimedia company in Venice, near Los Angeles, that does special
effects for movies. Tweaking his message somewhat, he focused on
education and the economy, and also sought to distinquish himself
from Bradley, talking about improving schools and repeating his
refrain about the former New Jersey Senator being a ``good man with
a bad plan'' on providing universal health care.
</P>
<P>
   Before Gore arrived in the renovated warehouse, a small sign
that said ``Nader 2000,'' referring to the consumer advocate Ralph
Nader, was removed from the wall. Afterward, Gore stopped at a
resturant to shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   Gore plans to return to California next week. He also plans to
hold at least one debate with Bradley in the state, said Gore
campaign chairman, Tony Coelho.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has attributed his win in the first caucus and primary
states to a series of such interminable town hall-style meetings,
ususally with undecided voters, where he stays until the last
audience member is left standing.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho said Gore's strategy for California and the 14 other
states that will hold primaries March 7 will obviously differ from
the tact taken in New Hampshire and Iowa, though he refused to be
specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the national campaign has started,'' Coelho said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore left Los Angeles for a campaign stop in Olympia, Wash.,
before returning to Washington, D.C., early Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
