<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-EVENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE DETAIL SERIES OF EVENTS IN FATAL SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ ``Oh, that's one of ours.''
</P>
<P>
   With those words, a Providence police officer leaning over a
bleeding body last Friday made the shocking discovery that
patrolman Cornel Young Jr. had been mortally wounded by friendly
fire.
</P>
<P>
   That tragic revelation, publicly detailed Thursday for the first
time, was the end of a lightning-quick series of ugly events
outside Fidas Restaurant _ and the beginning of what could be a
prolonged period of racial friction in Providence.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Young, dressed in civilian clothes, did not identify
himself as a police officer and did not respond to several shouted
commands to drop his .40-caliber Beretta pistol.
</P>
<P>
   Off-duty and wearing casual clothes and a baseball cap over a
stocking cap, Young had rushed outside the restaurant to help his
fellow officers as they confronted an armed man at the center of a
late-night fracas.
</P>
<P>
   Many black leaders are questioning whether a snap act of racial
profiling led to the death of Young, the son of the highest-ranking
black officer in the Providence Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   But according to a report in the Providence Jounal-Bulletin,
some members of the department now believe the decision of two
officers to fire six bullets at Young appears to have been
justified.
</P>
<P>
   After he had closed to within 5 feet of the armed man _ who had
just dropped his gun on police orders _ Young was struck by three
bullets to the head, chest and stomach, according to sources quoted
in the report. Police said that the man who released his weapon,
Aldrin Diaz of Providence, believed Young was from the group with
whom he had been fighting and that Young intended to shoot him.
</P>
<P>
   Police also said that, in the chaos outside the restaurant, a
woman from the rival group believed Young to be her boyfriend. She
rushed to Young, but was pulled away by police an instant before
they made their shocking identification, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the investigation told the newspaper that
police Officer Carlos A. Saraiva yelled at least twice for Young to
drop his weapon as he walked toward Diaz. Rookie police Officer
Michael Solitro 3d is also reported by those sources as yelling the
command.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Horton, a longtime friend of Young's who had been with
the officer earlier in the evening, told The Boston Globe Thursday
he is suspicious about the police version of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's accurate,'' Horton said. ``It doesn't sound
like something he'd do. He'd identify himself as soon as the
uniformed police came on the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Horton had been with Young at Gerardo's Alternative Nightclub,
where he said they had seen a dance-floor fight that he believes
involved a female member of Diaz's group. That fight, between two
women, might have been the genesis for the later brawl at Fidas
Restaurant, Horton said.
</P>
<P>
   Young rose to help break up the nightclub fight, Horton said,
but security separated the women before he was needed. Ironically,
Horton said, Diaz was also at the nightclub, and at one point stood
only a few feet from Young.
</P>
<P>
   Horton said he made plans to meet Young later at the restaurant,
where the officer's brief stop for a takeout steak-club sandwich
spun tragically out of control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
