<SLUG> BC-MET-EVANS-PHOTOS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVANS NOT EASY TO LIKE, IMPOSSIBLE TO FORGET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``His general note is lyrical understanding of the
street, trained observation of it, special feeling for patina, eye
for revealing detail, over all of which is thrown a poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Walker Evans, writing in 1931 about Atget. Later,
lecturing in 1964 about Atget and also about Mathew Brady, another
hero, he projected a group of the penny picture postcards he had
collected since he was a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine anything more?'' he asked his audience about
his anonymous little hand-colored images of small-town main streets
and trolley cars. ``A conglomeration of hideous things that come
together by casting a spell of _ I can't call it beauty, but of a
certain kind of silent poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice, poetry. That was what Evans was after in his own
photographs, a poetry that you couldn't call beauty, not
conventional beauty anyway, an art inspired by vernacular subjects
and aspiring to the natural dignity of the street. To the end of
his life (he died in 1975, at 72), Evans had this goal, which in
his case became a distinctly American project.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of him during his last years make him out to be an
ironic, oblique conversationalist, funny, insecure, vulnerable,
weakened. His best work was years behind him. He had trouble
understanding why people were no longer interested in what he was
doing, but he had been out of the spotlight for a long time. Some
people thought he was already dead when he had his last
retrospective in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The list of people he couldn't abide or about whom he made
nasty, unbecoming cracks is well known. About Ralph Steiner, the
photographer who generously offered to teach him photography, Evans
commented, ``He is a bitter little Jew, intelligent, whose
limitations are skillfully blurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans despised Victorian proprieties, which he associated with
his parents. He hated all do-gooders and ideologues, whether they
were limousine liberals or far-right-wingers, and he especially
disliked ``artistes.'' ``Too much exposure to art is not very good
for an artist,'' he told his students. He couldn't stand the idea
that he might be linked with somebody like Alfred Stieglitz, who
represented what might be called official bohemianism, which to him
was as bad as the old academy.
</P>
<P>
   As Douglas Eklund puts it in the catalog for the outstanding new
Evans retrospective at the Metropolitan, ``In all of those circles
Evans the man moved quite comfortably but with a residue of
free-floating negativity; the uniquely subdued, dispassionate tone
(and some might argue the chilling effect) of his photographs came
from this sustained and critical refusal to join.''
</P>
<P>
   The Met's survey, organized by Jeff L. Rosenheim, a curator in
the museum's photography department, sweeps skillfully through six
decades of Evans' career, with 175 vintage photographs and other
objects and documents. The stress on vintage photographs means that
there's a patina to his early work, now 70 or so years old, which
is an interesting counterpoint to the astringency.
</P>
<P>
   The documents and objects come from Evans' archives, which the
Met owns. They include ``Pictures of the Time,'' a rarity of sorts:
a splenetic, witty scrapbook of clippings from newspapers and
magazines that Evans compiled with the writer James Agee. It
consisted of what they hated about commercial photography and
photojournalism, like celebrity portraits and soft-core
bathing-beauty advertisements, but also what they liked, like crime
scene photos and ethnographic documents: all straight,
unpretentious pictures. You see clearly what Evans became when you
look at what he did and didn't admire.
</P>
<P>
   There are also copies of Fortune magazine, where he was a
longtime editor, with Evans' photo spreads in them, a slide show of
his great color pictures of railroad cars, which he did for
Fortune, and postcards and old road signs.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Evans was fascinated by lettered signs, and
he emphasized the obvious connection between language and
photography: they were two surrogates of reality, words and
pictures each being meaningful but incomplete and often misleading
by themselves. Signs, like photographs, were to him specifically a
form of poetry, and his photographs of isolated words or letters
read as a kind of abstract language.
</P>
<P>
   He collected road signs, even pilfered them: he would drive
around rural Connecticut with students who would unscrew the signs
he liked most when the coast was clear.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first complete retrospective of Evans. The 1971
overview, at the Museum of Modern Art, came before he worked with
the Polaroid SX-70, with which he took his last photographs. Those
are minor pictures, mostly, but intriguing. A mass-market gadget
given to him and a few other prominent photographers by Polaroid to
help publicize its product, the SX-70 gave Evans a new lease on
life.
</P>
<P>
   It spit out palm-size glossy images in saturated colors. It was
for casual snapshot portraits. Evans had trouble wielding bigger
cameras by then. Now he could work again, and no doubt he relished
working with a tool as mundane and populist as the SX-70. It
involved photography at its most basic level: point and shoot. He
had always tried to show what was distinguished in what other
people overlooked, and now he was making art, or at least trying
to, with a tool that sophisticated photographers generally wouldn't
take notice of.
</P>
<P>
   He took 2,600 pictures with the new camera, lots of fish-eye
close-ups of friends, and especially of young women he was trying
to impress, but also tightly cropped abstract vignettes that
reprise basic themes from the 1920s and '30s, now in the SX-70's
garish colors, which he clearly embraced. The late street-sign
pictures are derivative and unremarkable. But one Polaroid recalls
his best work: a junked pink Ford in the weeds, the grill a toothy
smile. Typical of Evans, the car is a ready-made American beauty.
</P>
<P>
   We see basically what was already clear before this exhibition:
that American documentary photography is synonymous with Evans. It
is built on his belligerent independence (this was his most truly
American trait), his elevation of the everyday, his open eye, his
mordant concentration and deliberate organization, his slow,
razor-sharp, deadpan gaze.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
