<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5774 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MET-EVANS-PHOTOS-ART-     02-03 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-EVANS-PHOTOS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: deadpan gaze. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was also something particularly American about him: his
lean, laconic scrutiny of the world. His pictures are called
elegies, but they're elegies devoid of nostalgia. They are
difficult to like at first, they're so austere. Gradually one can
be moved by them because their construction _ often head on,
seemingly uncomplicated, sometimes as if the images are not really
even composed _ comes across as plain, eternal truth. Evans
photographed disappearing national icons, like old Model Ts and
gingerbread houses, but no matter what his subject was, his
pictures always connoted the world out of time. Not just time
stopped, which is the condition imposed by all photographs, but
objects held in a kind of supreme suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Disorder is suddenly made to seem like order, the timeworn and
commonplace looks extraordinary, and everything briefly snaps into
focus. Call it a natural state of grace, which gives inherent
dignity to all the ephemeral subjects Evans shot.
</P>
<P>
   You see his elegance of vision in his famous pictures of
sharecroppers' and tenant farmers' cabins in Alabama for ``Let Us
Now Praise Famous Men.'' These may be even better than his
portraits of the Burroughs and Tingle families. The portraits are
ingrained in the American psyche basically because Evans, in a
photographic style as spare as James Agee's writing was the
opposite, denied us what we expected: he short-circuited pity for
those people by cutting out the charm and anecdote. We stare
level-eyed, and as if without any distance from his subjects, who
gaze _ squint really _ at us as if demanding to know who are we to
look at them. Lionel Trilling, observing the portrait of Allie Mae
Burroughs, put it this way: she ``simply refuses to be an object of
your `social consciousness,''' he wrote. ``She refuses to be an
object at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the cabin interiors may be closer to the core of Evans'
achievement, because in essence he was always a still-life
photographer, even when he was photographing street scenes or
people. Still life implies an art of inanimate objects, of objects
made into archetypes. Evans constantly implied that the things and
people in his pictures had symbolic roles. They never seemed to
exist in the here and now, just through Evans' lens.
</P>
<P>
   So the few spare objects that the Burroughs family possessed _
table, towel, jug, bowl, kerosene lamp _ as in a Vermeer, are each
given a separate weight, purity and value. Together they
nonetheless look isolated and self-contained. No doubt this quality
was an expression of Evans' own feeling of separateness.
</P>
<P>
   His history is familiar: born in St. Louis to an advertising
executive and a housewife; boarding school in the East; rebellious
adolescence; Williams College briefly; literary aspirations; Paris
in the mid-1920s, too shy to meet Joyce; makes photographs in the
'20s in an abstract, Cubist-inspired mode; documents the South in
the '30s for the Resettlement Administration of the Department of
Agriculture, then with Agee; ``American Photographs'' show at the
Museum of Modern Art in 1938 establishes his early fame.
</P>
<P>
   It can be useful to read Evans, not just see his pictures. As a
writer he was lean and fastidious. The second edition of ``Let Us
Now Praise Famous Men'' has just been republished with his brief
memoir of Agee. Evans managed in prose something of what he
achieved in his pictures: concision, clarity, no pretense, dry wit.
Critics and historians, starting with Lincoln Kirstein in the essay
he wrote 62 years ago for ``American Photographs,'' have stressed
Evans' literary connections for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway's writing showed him the virtues of economy. Cummings
showed him how to make fun of stuffy social conventions and vapid
consumerism. Eliot showed how to express emotion in a chilly,
oblique style, which came naturally to Evans.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a modern visual grammar of forms that, in picture
after picture, resists easy absorption. They take time to sink in.
The more we look at an Evans photograph, the more his language
elaborates itself through essential details: the sliver of light
through the shutters of the plantation house in Louisiana; the
lovers at Coney Island whose forms echo the column and tower behind
them; the light reflected above the man in the subway, who is
absorbed in thought, his face in shadow; the menu of the sandwich
shop that we read over the shoulder of the cook and his pal; the
three men outside the barber shop in Vicksburg, Miss.,
serendipitously posed.
</P>
<P>
   It is curious that such a prickly man could have made such
moving, ultimately optimistic pictures. But maybe that's why
they're moving, because sentiment is checked by dispassion. The
world is a beautiful place, Evans keeps telling us _ often despite
itself.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his best-known photographs, of rain-slicked Main
Street in Saratoga Springs, the street's slow arc is picked out, as
if in black outlines, by parallel rows of identical parked cars.
The geometry of the scene is neatly complicated by a scrim of Dutch
elms in silhouette. America is freshly born. Everything is
complete. Nothing is hackneyed or maudlin, just straight. Typical
Evans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
