<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COX-BRITAIN-WALMART-$     02-03 1420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-BRITAIN-WALMART-$ADV06 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN COX EDs: updating, re-sending for those that didn't use it.
 &HT;    WAL-MART TAKING ITS GOOD SERVICE, LOW PRICES TO BRITAIN'S HIGH
STREETS
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    EDs: With box attached at end of story.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUTTON, England _ Shoppers are not greeted by pleasant folks
wearing yellow happy face pins, but the spirit of Sam Walton
abides.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Asda superstore in this leafy London suburb, the
familiar philosophy of the late Wal-Mart founder is etched _
literally _ in stone: ``Permanently Low Prices Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The simple, yet potent ethos that changed America now is working
its way through Britain _ and is poised to sweep the rest of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, Bentonville, Ark.-based Wal-Mart purchased Asda,
Britain's No. 3 grocery story chain for $10.8 billion. The stage
was set for a retail revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart has been warmly welcomed by British shoppers, who pay
up to 40 percent more at the market than their European and
American counterparts. A 1997 survey found that Britons paid US$138
for a shopping cart of groceries that would cost about $96 in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are all a bit weary of these truly horrible
prices,'' said Fiona Brindle, a housewife who drove eight miles
from the town of Bookham here, to Sutton to save on her weekly
grocery bill. ``We all know what people pay in America for things.
I've been to a Wal-Mart in Florida, so I know how it can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after Wal-Mart took control, prices at Asda's 229
stores plummeted. A 2-litre bottle of Coca-Cola dropped from the
equivalent of US$2.10 to US$1.06. A bottle of Pantene shampoo
dropped from US$3.28 to US$2.05. The company says it is slashing
its prices nearly US$170 million to attract customers.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the company dispatched 250 store managers to the
United States to meet with their counterparts and to be schooled in
the American model of customer service - an alien concept to many
British store clerks who often seem to loathe customers.
</P>
<P>
   This all sends shivers down the spine of traditional British
retailers, who long have enjoyed high profit margins and only
modest competition. When the Wal-Mart deal was announced last
summer, Tesco, the country's No. 1 grocery chain, immediately
slashed prices and launched its own internet marketing service.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hyman, managing director of Verdict, the retail
analysts, said the American retailer's arrival on the British
shopping scene already has changed the landscape. ``It has raised
the ante,'' Hyman said ``(The atmosphere has) become far more
aggressive. It's injected a new level of price-led competition into
UK retailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Auberon Waugh, the columnist for the Independent, took note of
the depth of the cultural change required for British
businesspeople to embrace discount retailing. ``This must be seen
as deeply 'un-British,''' Waugh wrote. ``Prices in Britain are so
much higher than anywhere in the rest of Europe, let alone America,
because our government is greedy and nobody believes in
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   While Wal-Mart has a firm grip on the principals of retail
competition, its British juggernaut faces a more concrete obstacle:
The stores here are too small for high-volume sales.
</P>
<P>
   British stores tend to be about 50,000 square feet _ about a
quarter the size of an American Wal-Mart _ and are surrounded by
complicated, cramped parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Wal-Mart's practice is to obtain a huge
tract in a small town or at the edges of urban development. This
land tends to be cheap, taxed modestly and regulated minimally.
</P>
<P>
   But, such parcels are rare in Britain, which is a densely
developed island that is fiercely protective of its countryside.
Since 1996, British land-use laws have effectively contained new
development in central business districts.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Wal-Mart's move to replicate its American stores
probably would prick fears about the future of city shopping
districts, known as the High Streets. These remain the prevalent,
if endangered shopping areas across Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Spencer, the city planner in the central England town of
Gloucester, is decidedly cool to allowing a Wal-Mart into his
community. His concerns would sound familiar to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may offer cheaper prices in the short term, but as
planners we have to cater for our children's children,'' Spencer
said. ``Wal-Mart sells everything from cigarettes to cars. Every
shop in the city center would suffer. It would change the tone of
the city. We've got flower sellers and musicians on our streets.
There is a rejuvenation of civic pride. A retail conglomerate which
excludes people without cars, the young and those with rough edges
would change all that.''
</P>
<P>
   One potential way around British planning rules is for Wal-Mart
to buy existing retail parks and convert them into mega-stores.
Britain has an estimated 500 out-of-town retail parks, a third of
which are already authorized to sell both food and non-food items.
ASDA has stores at only three of these sites.
</P>
<P>
   The response at these sites is likely to be mixed. Norman
Davies, the deputy chief planner in Merthyr Tydfil, South Wales,
said Wal-Mart could expect few problems if it were to obtain that
town's office park and seek to convert it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's irrelevant who trades there and what they do with the
buildings so long as what they sell represents a similar range of
goods as before,'' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart entered the European market in 1997 with the US$880
million acquisition of Wertkauf hypermarkets in Germany. Last year,
the company added the US$660 million Spar Handels chain, giving it
a total of 95 stores throughout Germany. The retailer also is
reportedly looking to buy Metro, Germany's biggest retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its aggressive foreign expansion, the company still
derives only 13 percent of its revenues from overseas. The
Economist, Europe's most respected business publication, last week
expressed doubts about Wal-Mart's ability to take control of the
continent's retailing. The magazine contends that the market
already has entrenched retailers and that Wal-Mart will find it
difficult to find its own sources of inexpensive merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the specter of Wal-Mart's moving into France was enough
to drive that country's big rival retailers _ Carrefour and
Promodes _ into one another's arms in a proposed merger. The
European Commission approved the merger on Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
   For now, shoppers here seem to welcome a break from the
tradition of high prices and rude service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's brilliant,'' said Margaret Phillips as she waits to
unload her cart at the Sutton Asda. ``It's all great to talk about
British and the High Streets, but we all have families to provide
for, don't we?''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, a male voice came on the store's public address
system to inform shoppers that pizzas were - for a limited time -
two for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that's brilliant!'' said Phillips, as she pulls out of
line to follow the lure of free pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------------------
