</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-CONFIRM-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE OVERWHELMINGLY BACKS GREENSPAN FOR FOURTH TERM AS FED
CHAIRMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, N.D., Minn., Nev.)  (bl) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate overwhelmingly confirmed Alan
Greenspan's nomination to his fourth term as chairman of the
Federal Reserve on Thursday after members of both parties lauded
his performance over the last dozen years in nurturing the
economy's long expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 89-4.
</P>
<P>
   The action gave Greenspan, 73, another four-year term as head of
the nation's central bank, a post that makes him one of the most
powerful policy-makers in an increasingly interconnected global
economy. It came a day after Greenspan raised interest rates by a
quarter of a point to slow the fast-growing economy in an effort to
head off the possibility of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, whose administration has had a close working
relationship with Greenspan, a Republican, said he was pleased by
the Senate's action, especially in light of the Fed chairman's role
in allowing the current expansion to become the longest on record
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chairman Greenspan's wise and steady leadership has inspired
confidence here in America and around the world,'' Clinton said in
a statement. ``He has made a truly remarkable contribution in
helping lead our nation to the longest economic expansion in
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan was first appointed to the Fed by President Ronald
Reagan in 1987, after Paul Volcker resigned as chairman. He was
subsequently reappointed by President George Bush, and now twice by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who is chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee, said Greenspan is the only person who could have won
such broad bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   ``And why have three successive administrations appointed Alan
Greenspan to be chairman of the board of governors of the Federal
Reserve system?'' Gramm asked during Senate debate on the
nomination Wednesday. ``Because he is the best central banker we
have ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   The four votes against Greenspan came from liberal Democrats who
said he was too focused on fighting an inflation threat that was
more theoretical than real, and doing so behind a cloak of
excessive secrecy at the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   They were Sens. Tom Harkin of Iowa; Byron Dorgan of North
Dakota; Harry Reid of Nevada; and Paul Wellstone of Minnesota.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During the debate, Harkin said that in focusing singlemindedly
on the ``specter of inflation,'' the Fed was paying too little
attention to its legislated mandate of encouraging full employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Greenspan and the Federal Reserve Board seemed to think
they needed to make a preemptive strike on inflation before we see
clear signs of inflation our there,'' Harkin said. ``This view, if
aggressively acted upon, would place an absolute cap on our
economy's ability to grow. It would destroy much of our potential
for growth. That is a tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised rates four times in quarter point increments
since June, pushing its benchmark federal funds target rate to 5.75
percent. Most analysts expect the central bank to tighten policy at
least two more times in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed released the minutes of its policy-setting meeting of
Dec. 21 on Thursday, at which it voted unanimously to hold interest
rates steady. The minutes showed that Fed officials were concerned
about continuing signs of incipient inflationary pressures in
December, but that they were primarily focused on guiding the
economy smoothly through the year 2000 computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said at the meeting that the three rate increases
they had approved over the previous six months had had relatively
little effect up until that point in slowing the economy. But they
agreed that it would be prudent to delay any action on rates, in
part because waiting would give the central bank further time ``to
assess the delayed effects of its earlier tightening actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed concluded this week that its prior rate increases had
not been enough. In explaining its decision on Wednesday to raise
rates again, the Fed said the risks to the economy ``are weighted
mainly toward conditions that may generate heightened inflation
pressures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
