<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-IPOS-NORRIS-COLUMN-NY     02-03 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPOS-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORRIS COLUMN: A PARENT'S DREAM, CIRCA 2000: BE THE NEXT DENISE
SAVOIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when children were told they could hope to be
president, but for many Americans the envied footsteps are no
longer those of Al Gore or George W. Bush. Now people dream of
being like P. Kingston Duffie, Richard N. Tinsley or M. Denise
Savoie.
</P>
<P>
   Never heard of them? Two years ago they invested almost $8,500
as they founded Turnstone Systems to design products that help
local phone companies provide DSL lines, which allow rapid Internet
communications. The company looks like it may succeed, having so
far sold $27 million in products. Last year, it almost broke even.
</P>
<P>
   This week Turnstone went public, selling stock to the public at
$29 a share, compared with the tenth of a cent a share that the
founders paid. Investors fell all over themselves to buy the stock,
and Thursday Turnstone closed at $132. The shares bought by the
three founders, who range in age from 35 to 44, now are worth $1.1
billion. The company, in which about $100 million has been invested
_ including the $87 million put up by public investors this week _
has a market capitalization of $4.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Turnstone saga so impressive is that it is not
all that extraordinary. Seven American companies have gone public
this week. Besides Turnstone, they are SkilSoft, a provider of
corporate training courses; Sequenom, a biotechnology company;
Quantum Effect Devices, a semiconductor company; Telaxis
Communications, a wireless equipment company; Centra Software, an
Internet company; and Alamosa PCS, a cell phone company.
</P>
<P>
   The seven sport a total market capitalization of $13.4 billion,
equal to 16 times the amount of money that equity investors put
into them and more than 170 times the $78 million in combined
annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures reflect the wealth effect in action. The Federal
Reserve, which has now raised the federal funds rate four times
since last summer, is expected to raise it two or three more times
before this year is out. That has put a damper on some old stocks,
but it has not damaged the market for companies like these.
</P>
<P>
   An initial public offering that immediately doubled in price
used to be an amazing phenomenon. Now it is almost taken for
granted that new offerings will soar. Of the seven, all but
SkilSoft traded at twice the offering price or better the first
day, although Alamosa faded to close with a gain of just 66
percent. But none got much attention.
</P>
<P>
   Those doubles benefit the lucky people who got in on the public
offering. Those who got in earlier do much better. All told,
insiders _ including founders, employees and the venture
capitalists who financed these seven companies _ have put $257
million into their equity investments. Their stakes are now worth
$11.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That wealth is created not by the success of the companies _
none are now profitable _ but by the enthusiasm and hope of
investors. It is a virtuous circle, in which optimistic investors
produce higher share prices that justify the optimism and draw in
more investors.
</P>
<P>
   All this is possible because many companies have a shot at being
winners in an era in which technology is changing the economic
landscape. But while some companies may prove to be great
successes, there is no way that the economy will produce enough
profits to justify all the optimism now being shown. Someday, when
enough companies have fallen by the wayside, investors will grow
hostile and even promising ventures will find it hard to raise
capital. There are no signs that day is near.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
