<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5794 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HARTSFIELD-FREIGHT04-     02-03 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARTSFIELD-FREIGHT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Warehouse developer likes Atlanta airport's cargo potential
 &HT;    By Tony Wilbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A developer believes Hartsfield International Airport
will become one of the nation's top air cargo centers in the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Seefried Properties is so confident about the growth of air
cargo that it will spend $45 million to develop more than 1 million
square feet of space near the airport to accommodate the world's
top freight-forwarding companies.
</P>
<P>
   Freight forwarders pick up goods from manufacturers and deliver
them to destinations around the world. They use warehouses such as
those built by Atlanta-based Seefried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to build at Hartsfield because we believe its
importance as an air cargo hub will increase in the coming years,''
Seefried President Ferdinand Seefried said Thursday. ``It will be a
first-tier air cargo hub in the next five years.''
</P>
<P>
   The country's top freight-forwarding airports include Miami, Los
Angeles, JFK in New York and Chicago's O'Hare.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Hartsfield ranked in the lower end of the top 20 cargo
airports in the world with 907,000 metric tons of freight and mail.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, however, international cargo at
Hartsfield has grown considerably. It increased from 212,000 metric
tons in 1997 to 242,000 metric tons in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Global air cargo traffic is expected to grow by 6.4 percent a
year through 2017, according to the 1998-1999 Boeing World Air
Cargo Forecast. Air cargo accounts for 13 percent of passenger
airlines' revenue, according to the forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Seefried plans to develop 350,000 square feet of space for
freight forwarders at Interstate 285 and Old Dixie Road. The
developer has contracted to buy about 20 acres and hopes to start
construction on an 180,000-square-foot building within 90 days. It
will be completed seven to eight months later.
</P>
<P>
   At Airport South industrial park, Seefried will develop 660,000
square feet in a freight-distribution park with partner Kollmann AG
of Germany, said Tom Ellis, a Seefried vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The developer already has completed three of the seven buildings
it plans for the 53-acre distribution park at Ga. 85 and Rock Hill
Drive.
</P>
<P>
   David Garrett III, president of Airis Corp., an Atlanta
developer, also believes air cargo traffic will grow at Hartsfield,
although it likely will not be on the level of the top air cargo
airports any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can expect to see a lot of cargo opportunities become
available at Hartsfield,'' said Garrett, whose father is a former
Delta Air Lines chairman and chief executive. ``Hartsfield has
absolutely the right fundamentals.''
</P>
<P>
   The fundamentals include location, a large export business and
the right leadership. Garrett said Hartsfield's top management
promotes air cargo traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
