unsatiable dreamer, the beautiful-but-bored Madame Bovary finds
escape in the romantic novels and society journals of her day. An
early proponent of the school of style that proclaims it is better
to look good than feel good, Emma Bovary is the reflection of
modern-day styloids for whom image is everything. In the new
``Madame Bovary'' for PBS's ``Masterpiece Theatre'' starting
Sunday, Emma's mirror eventually cracks and we are left to assume
that shallow materialism and the preference for beauty over
morality are inadvisable career options.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
