A5806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MISSISSIPPI-FLAG04-CO     02-03 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSISSIPPI-FLAG04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mississippi foes of Rebel flag crank up campaign
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some Mississippi legislators are hoping this is the
year lawmakers at least discuss removing the Confederate battle
flag from the corner of the state flag.
</P>
<P>
   Black legislators have filed two bills that would remove the
Confederate battle symbol, which they feel glorifies the Old South
and, with it, slavery. Similar bills have been filed for 20 years
in Mississippi, but none has made it past a committee.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, it is a national issue.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50,000 people marched on Columbia last month to
protest the flying of the Confederate battle flag over South
Carolina's Capitol. It is the only state in the nation that flies
the flag. A boycott by the National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People has been in effect there for months. During the
Super Bowl last weekend, the Rev. Jesse Jackson brought attention
to Georgia's use of the Confederate symbol in its state flag.
Georgia and Mississippi are the only states that incorporate the
flag in their state banners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that with public awareness, we'll begin to get a
better response to the bill,'' said Mississippi state Rep. Edward
Blackmon, author of one of the bills to change the flag. He wants
the Confederate symbol replaced by a magnolia, the state flower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's going on in South Carolina will have a great
deal of influence,'' Blackmon said. ``It would be difficult for us
to silently sit by and do nothing if other states take positive
steps to remove it. We don't want to be the last ones with it.''
</P>
<P>
   A 6-year-old lawsuit in which the NAACP challenges the
Mississippi flag was resurrected last year and is pending before
the state Supreme Court. The court will consider written arguments
filed by the state, which is defending the flag, and by the NAACP
and other black plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hankins, a Mississippian and member of the Sons of
Confederate Veterans, said the flag has been misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War was really a states' rights issue rather than
about so-called slavery,'' he said. ``My ancestors did not own any
slaves, and they fought in the war. We look at it more as a
heritage issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not think the flag, which was adopted by the state
Legislature in 1894, should be changed. He said the American flag
flew over slave-owning states for 150 years but no one tries to
take it down or change it.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Wiseman, director of the Stennis Institute at Mississippi
State University, said the state is still ``fatigued by the public
relations nightmare'' of the civil rights era and may want to avoid
being portrayed in a negative light on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think more people are willing to see some change,'' he said.
Moreover, he added, the Mississippi Legislature has a very large
and influential black caucus: Forty-seven of the 174
representatives and senators are black, and many of them have
seniority.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will change the nature of the debate,'' Wiseman said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
