<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-STEVESMITH04-COX     02-03 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-STEVESMITH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smith blazing a new trail
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When guard Steve Smith sat down with Hawks president
Stan Kasten to sign a seven-year, $50.7 million contract in the
summer of 1996, he was startled by his boss' candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will never play out this contract in a Hawks uniform,''
Kasten told Smith. ``It's too much money, and we'll have to trade
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith laughed. But exactly three years after signing, Smith
learned, while playing for the U.S. men's Olympic basketball team
in Puerto Rico, that Kasten had kept his promise. The
well-respected and highly popular guard had been shipped to
Portland, with a bottomless pocketbook, by a team with grave
salary-cap concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks felt compelled to make the deal, but they weren't
happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most difficult deals I've ever made,'' general
manager Pete Babcock said. ``I don't regret it, because we did it
for reasons that made sense then and now. But any time you have to
trade someone of Steve's caliber _ both as a player and a person _
it's very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Hawks have not played well this season, and Isaiah
Rider has not completed the transformation _ hoped for, but not
expected _ into a team player.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's return tonight as member of the league's deepest and
best team takes the spotlight away from the Hawks' efforts to get
their season pointed in the right direction before next week's
all-star break.
</P>
<P>
   It is a homecoming for Smith in every sense. He played five
seasons in a Hawks uniform, annually led his team in scoring and
built a permanent home in the northern suburbs to which he will one
day retire.
</P>
<P>
   As much as he did not want the trade, and as often as he feels
compelled to reminisce with his friend Dikembe Mutombo, Smith
welcomes an opportunity to try to win a championship. He knows that
it could not have happened with a Hawks organization that lacked
reserve strength and was strangled by salary-cap constraints.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is Portland's No. 2 scorer at 15.4 points per game, down
about 5 from what he gave the Hawks each game. He plays 34 minutes,
down four to five from the burden he accepted in Atlanta while
nursing a chronic knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't gloat about what's happened to me and what's happened
to that team,'' Smith said. ``I talk to Dikembe a lot, but I don't
bring up what's going on here or ask about what's going on there.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as his second trade hurt _ he was dealt by Miami to
Atlanta two games into the 1994-95 season _ Smith is a realist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no depth there last season,'' he said. ``I'm not one to
complain, but that took its toll on me in the playoffs, especially
against New York. That's why I was so happy when I heard I was
going to Portland. In Atlanta, I had to do it all, in terms of
playing time and scoring. Here, we're so talented and deep, the
burden isn't all on me.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what to expect from Smith tonight? Probably a little
something extra, although only an improbable circumstance would
allow him to approximate what he did in a game at Miami a few
months after the Heat traded him.
</P>
<P>
   In that game, Jan. 30, 1995, Atlanta was down 19 with 10 1/2
minutes to play when Smith re-entered the game. He brought his team
back with a blistering display of shooting. Inside the final
half-minute, in a one-point game, he had the ball in front of the
Heat bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``You so hot, shoot it from there,'' Miami's Harold Miner
hollered.
</P>
<P>
   Smith checked his spot about 28 feet from the hoop and let fly a
3-pointer that won the game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
