r p BC-BUSH-McCAIN-HNS &LR;      02-03 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-McCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN DISMISSES ATTACKS ON HIS VOTING RECORD ON MILITARY ISSUES   
 (Eds.: Tod Harris is cq)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By R.G. RATCLIFFE and GREG McDONALD   
 c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUMTER, S.C. _ George W. Bush prompted an attack Thursday from
military heroes, activists and a former Joint Chiefs of Staff
chairman on rival John McCain's voting record on veterans and
POW/MIA issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bush refused to criticize McCain, but stood alongside the
veterans' activist who made the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came home. He forgot us,'' J. Thomas Burch Jr., chairman of
the National Vietnam &AMP; Gulf War Veterans Coalition said of McCain,
who spent nearly six years as a prisoner of war in North Vietnam
before his elections to the U.S. House and Senate from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   McCain dismissed the attack as ``foolishness'' brought on by
Bush's 19-point loss Tuesday in New Hampshire and a new poll
showing McCain with a 5-point lead over Bush in South Carolina. A
Time-CNN poll conducted Jan. 26-27 showed Bush leading McCain in
South Carolina by 52 percent to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina, with 400,000 residents either on active military
duty or retired from the armed services, is another state crucial
to McCain's underdog presidential effort. Its Republican primary is
Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's maybe a little bit of foolishness going on here,''
McCain said in Charleston, S.C., with Fort Sumter and a
decommissioned aircraft carrier as his backdrop. Citing his
endorsement by the Veterans of Foreign Wars and other major
veterans organizations, McCain said, ``Of all the people they could
attack on veteran's issues, they're attacking me?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain officials also challenged the Bush campaign to a debate
on military and veterans issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be happy to debate the governor any time, any place and
stick our record against his ... We hope to God this campaign
centers on which candidate is more committed to defense issue and
veterans affairs,'' said McCain spokesman Tod Harris.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's personal history as a naval aviator who was shot down
and tortured in North Vietnam has been one of the most compelling
attributes of his candidacy. The Texas governor served in the Texas
Air National Guard in Houston during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Burch said McCain has opposed legislation related to Agent
Orange, Gulf War-related health care and the plight of other
Vietnam-era prisoners of war and those missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain camp challenged those assertions about his support
for veterans health legislation.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, records show, was a co-sponsor in 1991 of the Agent
Orange Act that became law and testified in Congress in 1994 urging
swift action on legislation to provide compensation to Gulf War
veterans suffering from mysterious illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Burch said McCain, a member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, opposed the Bring Them Back Alive Bill of 1995 to grant
immigrant status to any Asian who brought an MIA serviceman out of
Asia alive. He said McCain also opposed the Missing Persons
Personnel Act of 1997 to make it easier for family members to get
their missing relatives declared dead.
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides said those bills were attached to unrelated
measures that McCain opposed. The Senate never took up those bills
on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Burch said McCain also supported normalizing relations with
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Burch said relations should not be normalized until there is a
full accounting of all the men still missing from the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did support normalizing relations with Vietnam, a
diplomatic process begun by President Bush. Other Vietnam veterans
in the Senate also backed that effort.
</P>
<P>
   On that issue, Bush said, ``I have no problem with normalization
so long as I was confident there was a full accounting.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush in his speech to about 400 people said he wants to improve
military pay and redesign its mission. He said he also wants to
overhaul the Department of Veterans Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a commander in chief who respects the men and women in
uniform,'' Bush said. ``That is the kind of commander in chief I
will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Bush on stage were three Medal of Honor winners from
South Carolina plus Adm. Thomas Moorer, chairman of the joint
chiefs of staff during the Nixon administration.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on McCain came as both men tried to pick up support
from the state's large military population.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning along the South Carolina coast, home to the Paris
Island Marine Base and hundreds of retirement communities, McCain
stressed not only his military background, but his 13 years in the
Senate as a ``fighter'' for veterans on issues, ranging from health
care to retirement pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am fully prepared to take over right now - this moment - as
commander in chief,'' McCain said to cheers as he addressed
retirees at several rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Bush tried to distance himself from any personal responsibility
for the veteran group attacks on McCain's record on veterans
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I stand by is the fact they've looked at both of us and
they've chosen me to be the nominee,'' Bush told a news conference.
``John McCain served our country well. He was a warrior on behalf
of America ... Let them speak. I appreciate their support.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Marine Col. Dave Townsend, who now lives in Beaufort,
S.C., said he knows McCain ``has got what it takes, despite what
Bush or anyone else may say about him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need someone who understands what duty and country and
morality means ... If we've got somebody up there who has courage
of convictions it will begin to rub off,'' Said Townsend. ``I don't
have anything against the other candidates. I just think he's it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
