<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN WILL SUSPEND HOME RULE IF IRA DOESN'T MOVE TO DISARM
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain moved Thursday night to suspend the
power-sharing government in Northern Ireland by next week, but said
it would intensify efforts to get paramilitary groups to begin
disarming before using that authority.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a somber session of the House of Commons, the
Northern Ireland secretary, Peter Mandelson, said he would
introduce emergency legislation Friday to establish the power to
shut down the two-month old Ulster government and restore direct
rule from London.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he did not ``relish'' the prospect of bringing
self-government to an end so soon after it had been established,
but that course might end up being the best option for preserving
the fragile new political institutions for eventual revival.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was obliged to take the action because of the
``totally unacceptable'' resistance of the Irish Republican Army to
begin dismantling its arsenal. He said the expectation that there
would be some weapons surrender by now was ``completely
unambiguous'' and that the failure was ``deeply disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson called the group's stance ``a betrayal of every
community in Northern Ireland,'' and said Britain's decision next
week would turn entirely on whether the paramilitary groups
recognized the urgency of demands to start disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appeal to the paramilitaries to heed the will of the people
and get cracking and enable local self-government in Northern
Ireland to flourish once and for all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that intensive contacts would continue for that purpose,
and Thursday night Prime Minister Bertie Ahern of Ireland flew to
England to meet with Tony Blair in Cornwall where the British prime
minister was on a two-day swing through farm communities.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson's call for contingency legislation was an effort to
buy time and to spare David Trimble, first minister of the Northern
Ireland Assembly and leader of the Ulster Unionist Party, from
having to carry through on a pledge to quit as head of the
legislature and, most likely, his party. A postdated letter of
resignation, to be put into effect in the absence of any progress
on paramilitary disarmament, falls due Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing Trimble in the hushed hall, Mandelson said that the
government would be depending upon his ``strength and courage'' in
the days to come. He urged Trimble's restive party members not to
take any ``precipitate action.''
</P>
<P>
   What brought on Thursday night's announcement was a confidential
report by Gen. John de Chastelain of Canada, head of the panel
charged with supervising disarmament, that offered no evidence that
the IRA and other groups had made any move to begin turning in
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   It was delivered to the British and Irish governments shortly
before a midnight deadline Monday and has been the subject of
intense discussions since then between Blair, Ahern, President
Clinton in Washington and the leaders of the Catholic and
Protestant political parties in Belfast that signed the peace pact
nearly two years ago that established the basis for the home rule
government.
</P>
<P>
   The conversations this week were aimed at persuading the IRA to
make a move on weapons or issue a declaration that their war with
Britain and its Protestant sympathizers was over. The IRA did make
a statement noting that its cease-fire was holding and its
commitment to peace was firm, but it sidestepped the central issue
of disarmament that has continually stalled progress in bringing
stability to Ulster. ``The IRA's guns are silent and there is no
threat to the peace process from the IRA,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson's praise for Trimble in the House of Commons reflected
the government's regard for his indispensability to the effort to
bring peace to Ulster. A onetime intransigent Protestant leader, he
has been transformed in recent years into a persuasive deal broker
within his quarrelsome party. He shared the 1998 Nobel Peace Prize
with John Hume, the head of the moderate Catholic Social Democratic
and Labor Party, who is seen as the original inspiration for the
peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble's resignation would require a new election for first
minister whenever the assembly resumed its functions, and it is
doubtful now that his party would back him for the top office.
Those in line to succeed him are less committed to sharing power
with their Catholic rivals and would be less willing partners with
Britain and Ireland in trying to set up a governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Trimble took a gamble in persuading his party to
enter government with Sinn Fein, the political representatives of
the IRA, even though there had been no turnover of guerrilla arms.
To persuade his party members to abandon what had become a
bottom-line demand, he promised he would resign his position as
first minister of the assembly in February if there was no matching
IRA move by then.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When the IRA simultaneously appointed representatives to de
Chastelain's commission, there was widespread expectation that
moves on arms would follow, allowing the arms monitoring agency to
issue a positive report this week.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland had a rare moment of hope for a secure future
with the start-up of the coalition government with its carefully
constructed mechanisms for assuring Catholics and Protestants an
equal say in affairs of the province. Men known to have been
members of Catholic and Protestant paramilitary groups suddenly
found themselves running ministries and dealing with issues like
school lunches, farm prices, education and health.
</P>
<P>
   Citing that experience, ``this augurs well for the long-term
future of devolved government in Northern Ireland,'' Mandelson told
the House of Commons Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing,
warned during the week that the entire peace undertaking would be
in jeopardy if Britain mothballed the new political institutions.
Turning aside accusations that the setback was due to his party's
failure to deliver, he said, ``If the Ulster Unionist Party either
walks away from the process or forces the governments to collapse
this process, then I don't see how we are going to put it together
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams contests Trimble's claim that the IRA is obliged to start
disarming now, saying that the only operative deadline is the May
22 date in the original agreement. Mandelson rejected that argument
Thursday night, saying it was clear to everyone that progress on
disarmament was expected by now in response to Trimble's decision
of November to take a chance on entering the government without any
arms being turned in first.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
