u i BC-NIRELAND-2TAKES(TRIMS     02-03 0174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LONDON: in first. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   London and Dublin are sponsors of the 1998 peace agreement
brokered by George Mitchell, the former U.S. senator, that created
the assembly in Belfast and a group of other governmental bodies
intended to balance the desires of the Protestant majority that
wants Ulster to remain part of Britain and of the Catholic minority
that wants the province to establish closer links with Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing political stability to the province where more than
3,300 lives have been lost in 30 years of sectarian violence has
produced repeated false starts and disappointments followed by 11th
hour rescue measures sustained by spiteful and begrudging
compromises that inevitably break down.
</P>
<P>
   Seamus Mallon, a senior member of the Social Democratic and
Labor Party and the deputy first minister of the assembly, said he
hoped that once again ``we can pull a rabbit out of the hat.'' He
added, ``So many times in Northern Ireland the possible happened
when things seemed most impossible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
