<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Lion's Game' author pounces on critic in latest
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Nelson DeMille's novel ``The General's Daughter'' hit the
big screen last year, some of the movie reviews were very critical,
including one by Janet Maslin of The New York Times. Well, DeMille
gets a small measure of revenge in his new best seller, ``The
Lion's Game,'' by having his character John Corey refer to Maslin's
``tortured'' syntax. ``Some days I do the Times crossword puzzle,''
Corey says, ``other days I try to understand what Ms. Maslin is
trying to say. I can't do both on the same day without getting a
headache.''
</P>
<P>
   But Maslin may have another shot or two at the Long Island,
N.Y., writer. Columbia Pictures has bought ``The Lion's Game'' and
``Plum Island'' for $1 million each, and DeMille is at work on a
sequel to ``The General's Daughter'' in which John Travolta's
character, Pete Brenner, goes back to Vietnam to investigate a
30-year-old murder involving a U.S. Senate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wasn't planning to bring Brenner back,'' DeMille said
in a telephone interview, ``but Paramount came to me and asked if I
would do a sequel because they have a possibility of getting
Travolta again.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing about a recurring character is not something that
interests DeMille, although he brought back ``Plum Island''
protagonist John Corey in ``The Lion's Game.'' In the new novel,
Corey, a wisecracking, politically incorrect former New York
homicide cop, must track down a Libyan terrorist who has killed a
planeload of passengers in New York and intends to kill all the
pilots who took part in a 1986 raid that killed his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may seem easy to keep using the same character, but it's
difficult to re-create him. I had to go back and reread `Plum
Island' to see how he spoke and acted.''
</P>
<P>
   To research the sequel to ``The General's Daughter,'' DeMille,
55, returned to Vietnam last year to visit the places where he
fought and served in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sad in a lot of ways,'' he said. ``Part of the sadness
is that we realized we were not young kids anymore. The same ground
we covered 30 years ago with 70-pound packs was not so easy now.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMille will sign books at 7 p.m. Monday at Chapter 11 bookstore
at Peachtree Battle Shopping Center. 2345-A Peachtree Road N.E.,
404-237-7199.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fact and fiction: Richard Price, the best-selling author of
``Freedomland'' and ``Clockers,'' has signed a deal with Alfred A.
Knopf to write a novel based on the murder of Jonathan Levin, son
of Time-Warner chairman Gerald Levin. Levin, a popular teacher at a
Bronx high school, was tortured and killed in his apartment in 1997
by one of his students.
</P>
<P>
   Price, who used the Susan Smith case as the inspiration for
``Freedomland,'' plans to do something similar with the Levin case,
Knopf editor Robin Desser told the New York Daily News. ``It's a
book inspired by the themes inherent in the case, which have come
up often for Richard in his years working with underprivileged and
poor kids.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that the book will explore ``whether there's a dark
side to being a saint and about who holds up someone as a saint.
The way Levin was portrayed made Richard think a lot about those
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Literary event: Frederick Busch, whose novel ``The Night
Inspector'' has been nominated for a National Book Critics Circle
Award, will read from his works at two events Wednesday at Emory
University. A colloquium is scheduled at 2 p.m. in the Joseph Jones
Room of the Robert Woodruff Library, 540 Asbury Circle N.E., with a
reading in the same location at 8:15 p.m. As the author of ``A
Dangerous Profession: A Book About the Writing Life,'' Busch also
is expected to talk about what he learned by exploring the careers
of Ernest Hemingway, Franz Kafka, Herman Melville, Charles Dickens,
John O'Hara and others. Both events are free and open to the
public. Information: 404-727-4683.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail:dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
