<HEADER>
A5840 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-PARKS-QA04-COX     02-03 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKS-QA04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The heart and soul of Gordon Parks' photography
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Photographer. Poet. Film director. Novelist. If there
is a Renaissance man in American arts, it is Gordon Parks.
</P>
<P>
   As a hard-hitting photojournalist for Life magazine, he gave
bigotry and poverty a human face. But he also has made voluptuous
photos in which beauty is the subject. The breadth of his
photographic career, which will be evident in ``Half Past Autumn:
The Art of Gordon Parks,'' opening Saturday at Emory University's
Michael C. Carlos Museum, would have been achievement enough for
any artist. But not for Parks. In the course of his 87 years, the
Kansas native's creative impulses have resulted in five books,
volumes of poetry, 11 films _ including the landmark Hollywood hit
``Shaft'' _ sonatas, concertos and a ballet.
</P>
<P>
   His mane and signature moustache are white, and Parks looks a
bit frail, but he is still hard at work. Taking a break from the
sonata he is composing for his four children in his Manhattan
apartment, Parks came to Atlanta this week for the Carlos opening
and found time to answer some questions about his life and career.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You seem to have been a mature photographer from your very
first picture. How did you get interested in photography and how
did you learn your medium?
</P>
<P>
   A: I picked it up accidentally after seeing a newsreel in
Chicago, where I was a waiter on the railway. I bought a camera for
$7.50, and I was off. I didn't even know how to unload it. (After
shooting a roll and leaving it at the camera shop to be developed),
I picked up the pictures and told them it was my first roll. They
said, ``If you keep this up, we'll give you a show in our window,''
and they did. It was instinctive. I had seen the work of the
photographers of the Farm Security Administration, the best
documentary photographers in the world. When I saw what was being
accomplished with a camera against poverty, I thought perhaps I
could do the same thing against racism.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have a favorite photo?
</P>
<P>
   A: My signature picture was my first official picture for the
Farm Security Administration in 1942, ``American Gothic.'' When I
went to Washington D.C., I was confronted with the worst sort of
discrimination, which I didn't expect here of all places. I met
Ella Watson, a charwoman. I put a broom and a mop in her hand and
stood her in front of the American flag. It was an indictment of
the government. They didn't want it in government files. I had
thought it was destroyed. Then one day, I was on a plane to New
York and saw that it had been published in The Washington Post. I
didn't go home when I got to New York. I took the shuttle to D.C.
immediately and got the negative.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've dealt with such polarities in your work, from fashion
to crime. What did it mean to you?
</P>
<P>
   A: I was experimenting. I had a yen toward fashion photography.
It intrigued me. There is nothing more beautiful than a beautiful
woman in a beautiful outfit. I didn't have any trouble getting in
that line of work.
</P>
<P>
   After working at the Farm Security Administration, I went to
Harper's Bazaar and showed my pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The art director liked it but told me the magazine didn't hire
black people. Then I went to (then Conde Nast editorial director)
Alexander Liberman at Vogue. I thought, ``Here it comes again,''
but he gave me a try. I worked for Vogue for five years. I learned
a lot, and it eventually helped me get my job at Life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After returning from your Paris assignments with Life, you
threw yourself into some tough assignments on the civil rights
movement and Harlem gangs. Were you ever afraid?
</P>
<P>
   A: I wasn't afraid. I was concerned. It's difficult to get into
a gang. They had to have faith in you. And I had to have faith in
them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you make the transition from still photography to
moving pictures?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually, it came out of my first novel, ``The Learning
Tree.'' (Film director) John Cassavetes read the book and called
and asked me to do a movie of my book. I said, ``There aren't any
black directors in Hollywood,'' but he convinced me to come. Warner
Bros. asked me to write the screenplay, direct, write the music and
produce. It was all new to me, but the screenplay was not that
difficult and the music was in my soul and heart.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You often credit your
</P>
<P>
   background for your success in life. Family is important to you,
isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   A: I was blessed with a wonderful mother and father. They
encouraged me not to let discrimination stop me. My dad said, ``You
waltz around your enemies and do a fox trot on their backs.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: So many photographers idolize you. Do you feel like a hero?
</P>
<P>
   A: I feel as though what I've done was for survival. There's no
genius to it. A lot of people limit themselves as to what they can
or can't do. I realized that I was suffering under the woes of
discrimination, poverty and bigotry, but I had to leave a channel
open. As each success came, I became more confident. I freed
myself. ... Photography comes from the heart. If you don't have it
there, it won't work.
</P>
<P>
   A PLETHORA OF PARKS
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBIT: ``Half Past Autumn: The Art of Gordon Parks.'' Through
April 30. 10 a.m.-5 p.m., Mondays-Saturdays; noon-5 p.m. Sundays.
$5 suggested donation. Michael C. Carlos Museum, Emory University.
571 S. Kilgo St. N.E. 404-727-4282.
</P>
<P>
   A CONVERSATION with Gordon Parks. 6 p.m. today. Glenn
Auditorium, Emory University. $6; $4, students and museum members;
$12 for prime seating and admission to a reception at the Carlos
Museum following the event. 404-727-5050.
</P>
<P>
   REMARKABLE LIVES: A four-part photography workshop for children
ages 9-12. 2-5 p.m. Sunday, Feb. 13, 20, 27. Carlos Museum, Tate
Room. Participants must be able to attend all four sessions. $32;
$24, museum members, Emory University faculty and staff.
404-727-0519.
</P>
<P>
   PANEL DISCUSSIONS: Reception Hall, Carlos Museum. Free.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Perspectives on the photography of Gordon Parks. 7 p.m. Feb.
29.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parks as filmmaker. 7 p.m. March 27.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parks as composer and musician. 7 p.m. April 3.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parks as writer. 7 p.m. April 5.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An Evening for Educators.
</P>
<P>
   7 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Food for Thought. Discussion of Isaac Hayes and the cultural
influence of the ``Shaft'' soundtrack. Noon March 21.
</P>
<P>
   FILM SCREENINGS:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Learning Tree'' (1969) 7:30 p.m. Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Shaft'' (1971) 7:30 p.m. March 21.
</P>
<P>
   Rialto Center for the Performing Arts, 80 Forsyth St. N.E. $5;
$4, Signature Series subscribers. 404-651-4727.
www.rialtocenter.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Martin'' (1989) 2 p.m. April 16. Carlos Museum Reception
Hall. A production of his ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
