r e BC-TV-OTHERS04-COX     02-03 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OTHERS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Others' reach beyond predictable thriller
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Others'' starts off on familiar slasher-movie turf: a
female college student at night, a bathtub, a great ``gotcha!''
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Others'' isn't like the others. This new NBC series (a
tryout for a few weeks) about a small group of low-rent
Ghostbusters keeps heading off in unforeseen directions,
confounding expectations. It may not always please an audience
looking for simple thrills on a Saturday night, but there's some
emotional heft here, some interesting performances, some nuance
(for TV, anyway).
</P>
<P>
   The Others are a band of folks with extrasensory powers who can
see into other worlds, particularly the spirit world of the
recently dead. In Saturday's pilot, a newcomer reluctantly joins
the group: Marian (Julianne Nicholson, with the looks and appeal of
the young Shirley MacLaine), a college student who doesn't want her
``fearsome talent'' to communicate with ghosts. But the ghosts want
her, so she joins this disparate little group.
</P>
<P>
   They're led by Elmer (Bill Cobbs, the great black actor of many
films, such as ``The Bodyguard''), a wise but physically failing
elder. Satori is a New Age seer; Mark, a med student and
``empathic''; Albert (John Aylward, who was Dr. Anspaugh on
``ER''), a blind, crotchety visionary; and Warren, a jittery guy
who can't control his talent.
</P>
<P>
   These guys don't just see dead people, a la Haley Joel Osment in
``The Sixth Sense.'' They're more like grief counselors for the
living, de-haunting houses and helping those left behind to move on
emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Others'' is being promoted as a straight thriller, from
two former ``X-Files'' writers and the writers of the Michael
Douglas movie ``The Game.'' But like ``The Game,'' it's more than
it initially appears to be. Tonight's show looks like it's going
stalker-vs.-student, but changes course. An upcoming episode, about
a wife grieving for her dead husband and baby, is poignant,
bordering on tear-jerking (think Demi Moore in ``Ghost,'' only
without the potter's wheel).
</P>
<P>
   There's a tendency for the show to dip into what might be called
parapsychobabble, as well as some scenes that come perilously close
to over-the-top camp, like the guy who gets a premonition and is
knocked backward as if pole-axed in the forehead. But there's an
offbeat sensibility at work here, as you would expect from writers
who came up with ``The Game'' and numerous ``X-Files'' episodes. It
has an other-ness that makes it worth checking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Others''
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. Saturday on NBC
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
