<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-MITCHELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRACE L. MITCHELL, AT 91; MOTHER OF F. LEE BAILEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grace L. Mitchell, a pioneering day care provider who embarked
on her career to remain close to her young son, lawyer F. Lee
Bailey, died Jan. 27 in her home in Delray Beach, Fla. She was 91.
</P>
<P>
   A former elementary school teacher, Mrs. Mitchell founded Green
Acres Day School in her apartment in Waltham, Mass. in 1933 in
order to remain close to her son and continue her career in
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Lee was only 5 weeks old, I was already missing
teaching,'' she said in a story published in The Boston Globe May
17, 1976. ``I said OK, that's it, I'll start a nursery school. I
didn't even know what a nursery school was.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later she was an adviser to the US government's World
War II ``war nursery'' program.
</P>
<P>
   She owned and operated Green Acres Day School until 1988. She
was also a founder of the Living and Learning Centers, a chain of
more than 25 day care centers throughout New England.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mitchell earned a bachelor's degree at Tufts University
when she was in her mid-40s, a master's degree at Harvard
University when she was 55, and a doctorate at Antioch College when
she was 70 years old.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, she summed up her educational philosophy as ``I am, I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   She said ``Life is a process of becoming. My greatest
satisfaction is the joy of having been a part in helping other
people grow.''
</P>
<P>
   In a story published in the Boston Herald on June 10, 1979, she
said it was never necessary for day care to be traumatic for
children. ``Children learn more about emotions by experiencing them
in a day care setting than they ever could from a textbook,'' she
said, and described the sound of children running and playing as a
``good noise'' and a positive indication of the health of any day
care center.
</P>
<P>
   Besides F. Lee, son, who lives in Palm Beach, Fla., she leaves a
daughter, Nancy C., of West Palm Beach; another son, William E., of
Boston; five grandchildren; and four great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0334 </DOCNO>
