<P>
   &UR; RICKY MARTIN MEETS WITH THE PRESIDENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Heartthrob-of-the-moment  &UR; Ricky Martin &LR;  stopped by the White
House on Tuesday night to talk about serious matters with an aide
to the president and make chitchat with the
Vida-Loca-liver-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with aide  &UR; Maria Echaveste &LR;  to tell her that he
was worried about naval bombing exercises on a Puerto Rican island,
Martin stopped by the Oval Office. ``The substance of the
conversation that he had was with Maria,'' said White House
spokesman  &UR; Joe Lockhart &LR; . ``The visit with the president was
social.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Supermodel  &UR; Naomi Campbell &LR;  has pleaded guilty in Toronto to
beating her assistant while making a movie in Canada and, by prior
legal agreement, has ``expressed remorse'' as punishment.
 &UR; Georgina Galanis &LR; , who worked for Campbell for nine days in 1998,
said Campbell hit her in the head with a phone, punched her
shoulder, grabbed her neck and shook her head. Galanis has filed a
lawsuit in New York against Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   - Asked the ``most shocking thing you have ever done,'' bad-boy
designer  &UR; Alexander McQueen &LR;  told V magazine that he had drawn an
image of a male sexual organ ``inside the  &UR; Prince of &LR; 
 &UR; Wales &LR; ' jacket I made at Savile Row.'' The deed gave the
mischief-maker ``an internal smile'' every time the prince was on
the news.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Patrick Robertson &LR; , PR man for  &UR; Gen. Augusto Pinochet &LR; , has
been signed by  &UR; Crown Prince Alexander &LR;  of Yugoslavia, says the
Times of London. Robertson is supposed to help Alexander persuade
 &UR; Slobodan Milosevic &LR;  to allow the royals to return to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   - A study taken by SxSports Med.com found that 78 percent of
people suffering a sports injury ``had less sex compared to before
they were injured.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SETTING THE MUSICAL RECORD STRAIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Deborah Meier &LR; , who used to be director of the Central Park
East I elementary school in East Harlem, has strong objections to
``Music of the Heart,'' the movie set at that school.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is advertised by Miramax as the true story of Roberta
Guaspari, the music teacher who brought violin lessons to what's
portrayed as a stereotypical inner-city urban school. In the movie,
Guaspari _ with the principal as her ally and another music teacher
as her foe _ single-handedly turns the program into a success.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, Meier writes in Brill's Content, the school that
hired  &UR; Roberta Tzavaras &LR;  (the real name of ``Guaspari'') was
already a highly successful alternative public school and Meier,
its founding director, received a MacArthur fellowship for her work
at the time the film is set. Only a small percentage of students
were affected by Tzavaras' program, Meier writes, and the music
teacher on staff before her ``was the conductor of three large
choruses that performed citywide, expertly taught large numbers of
children the recorder, produced an annual opera that brought much
acclaim to the school and staged an occasional Broadway-style
musical.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Meier, ``The reputation of the school and many of
its teachers were ... harmed in order to tell a story that, by
confirming prejudices about public schools, Miramax knew it could
sell. ... What gives Hollywood the right to play loose with the
real lives of real people _ and real schools _ just to tickle the
heartstrings of a sentimental public?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STAMPING OUT ERRORS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After destroying 100 million Grand Canyon stamps because their
captions had mistakenly placed the natural wonder in Colorado, not
Arizona, the Postal Service has admitted that the corrected version
has the image flipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sticking with it,'' said Postal Service spokesman  &UR; Don &LR; 
 &UR; Smeraldi &LR; . ``No matter how you look at it, the Grand Canyon makes a
beautiful postage stamp.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're used to seeing are big, movie-like sex scenes; on
