<HEADER>
A5857 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-VALUE-FILENES-BOS &LR;      02-03 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALUE-FILENES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALUE CITY TO BUY FILENE'S BASEMENT FOR ABOUT $15 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Troubled Filene's Basement Corp., once a retail legend,
was seemingly spared Thursday from a worse fate by Value City
Department Stores Inc. of Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Filene's Basement has been doing business in Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection since August, and its most recently released
sales figures were cause for alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Value City agreed to buy Filene's Basement assets
for about $15 million in cash and stock. It also agreed to assume
roughly $74 million in the chain's liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new beginning,'' said Samuel J. Gerson, Filene's
Basement chairman and chief executive, who said he will continue to
run a 14-store chain under the Filene's Basement name as a separate
division of Value City.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal goes through, it's likely local shoppers will see
few immediate changes at the Basement's eight Massachusetts stores.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what might have happened if Value City's offer hadn't
materialized, Gerson said of Filene's Basement, ``There was a
possibility it could have gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The sales agreement must be approved by the US Bankruptcy Court,
something Gerson said he expects to happen shortly. He said he
hopes the deal will be completed by mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   Filene's Basement's new beginning will not come without pain.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few weeks, the Wellesley, Mass. company expects to
close its eight Aisle 3 stores. Open only on weekends, Aisle 3
employs a part-time work force.
</P>
<P>
   Still, another 700 jobs will be eliminated, though none in
Massachusetts. The reductions come on top of what resulted from 35
previous store closings in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   At one point last year, the Basement operated 59 stores and
employed 4,300 people. While many cuts came from layoffs, another
600 jobs were reduced by attrition, retirement, or voluntary
departure. After the Aisle 3 closings, Filene's Basement will
operate 14 stores and employ about 1,700 people.
</P>
<P>
   As Value City finds overlap between its operations and the
Basement's, small additional layoffs could hit the Basement's
remaining work force, Gerson said. But the ``vast majority'' of the
remaining jobs will be saved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gerson, Value City chairman and chief executive Jay
L. Schottenstein is considering reopening three Basement stores
that had closed in or near Washington, D.C. Value City might open
new Basement stores as well in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a man who wants to build another business,'' Gerson
said of Schottenstein, a member of Value City's founding family,
widely regarded in retail circles.
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, Filene's Basement was the place to go for
bargains on name-brand clothing. Indeed, some of its famous sales
on bridal gowns and designer suits helped turn shopping into a
contact sport.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, the company lost its way. As competition
intensified, Filene's Basement expanded too rapidly and its
financial resources couldn't support the growth.
</P>
<P>
   While its bargain formula found favor with urban customers,
surburbanites seemed to prefer finding their bargains at T.J. Maxx
and Marshalls, chains owned by the TJX Cos. of Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   Once an upstart, TJX now dwarfs the Basement.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, department stores that the Basement had always
depended on for much of its brand-name merchandise found better
ways to get rid of last year's styles. As more and more outlet
stores opened, the Basement found it harder to stock its racks with
the designer apparel that made it famous.
</P>
<P>
   Then came casual Fridays _ bad news for a place like Filene's
Basement that specialized in suits and dressy attire. Throw in Y2K
problems with the company's computer system, and the Basement was a
retailer in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   All those changes meant big losses for Filene's Basement and,
facing cash-flow problems, forced the retailer to file for
bankruptcy protection in August.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the Basement's most recently disclosed financial
information, A.G. Edwards analyst Robert F. Buchanan wondered why
Value City would want to buy such an ailing retailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, Value City is inheriting a busted mouse trap,'' he
said. ``I'm adopting a show-me attitude (about this acquisition). I
think there's an element of risk here.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Value City thinks Filene's Basement is a good risk.
In its 105 big-box stores, Value City now sells much of the same
brand-name clothing as Filene's Basement.
</P>
<P>
   By adding the Basement's best locations to a company that
already enjoys $1.67 billion in annual sales, Value City will have
more muscle to get better deals from its vendors, said company
president Mike Tanner. ``This union will strengthen our
merchandising team and give us greater buying power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gerson, acquiring Filene's Basement could add $300
million in additional sales to Value City. The union will also mean
shoppers will see better-quality goods at lower prices at Filene's
Basement stores, Gerson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay's (Schottenstein) a very good merchant, a real deal
maker,'' said George Iacono, a former Value City president who now
runs TJX's A.J. Wright division.
</P>
<P>
   In Value City, Filene's Basement is getting a parent with deep
pockets, said Stewart Cohen, chief executive of Paragon Capital LLC
of Needham, one of the Basement's main lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Combine Value City's resources and Schottenstein's savvy with
Gerson's merchandising skills and ``watch what Sam can
accomplish,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Basement's recent history, ``this is a
better-than-expected outcome,'' he said of Value City's proposed
purchase. ``I can only see win-win for both companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Value City's planned acquisition of Filene's Basement isn't
win-win for everybody. Investors who bought Filene's Basement stock
are likely to get nothing for their shares.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors said they felt misled by ``rosy'' predictions the
Basement made shortly before it filed for Chaper 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel this company has not been managed for shareholders but
for the benefit of upper management,'' said Scott Poague, a Kansas
investor who said he bought 13,000 shares a few weeks before the
bankruptcy filing.
</P>
<P>
   But as a result of the Value City deal, Gerson said, Filene's
Basement ``will continue. It will flourish. And it will grow.''
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, shares of Value City rose 1/2 to
close at 16 7/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
