<SLUG> BC-LINUX-ANDOVERNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA FIRM TO ACQUIRE ANDOVER.NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andover.net of Acton, Mass., a leading producer of Linux-related
Internet sites, is being acquired for about $1 billion by VA Linux
Systems Inc. of Sunnyvale, Calif., a leading maker of Linux-based
computer systems, in a bid to create the world's leading source of
Linux computer hardware, software and support.
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux went public in December, rising from $30 to $239 in its
first day of trading. Since, the stock's value has declined
sharply, closing Thursday at 128 on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop VA Linux and Andover.net from coming to
terms. Shareholders of Andover.net, which closed at 45 1/8 on
Nasdaq, will get .425 share of VA Linux for each of their
Andover.net shares. The deal works out to $968 million, based on
the closing prices, for Andover.net's 17.8 million shares
outstanding. As part of the purchase price, Andover.net investors
will receive $60 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux shares dropped 8 7/8 while Andover.net's stock rose 9
1/8.
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux was one of the first companies to specialize in making
computers specifically tailored to run Linux, an operating system
that is being rapidly adopted in corporate America as an
alternative to Microsoft Corp.'s Windows software.
</P>
<P>
   Linux is open source software, in which the raw source code is
made available to the public free of charge, making it easy for
users to introduce their own modifications.
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux is a major booster of Linux and other open source
products. The company operates Linux.com, a Web site popular among
open source programmers. In addition, VA Linux recently launched
SourceForge, a site where open source programmers can publish their
code and work jointly on software projects.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Andover.net runs a number of popular open source
Web sites, including Slashdot, a discussion forum for open source
programmers, and Freshmeat, a guide to new open source programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This acquisition moves VA Linux forward on the path to being
the biggest name in Linux and open source,'' said VA Linux chief
executive Larry Augustin.
</P>
<P>
   Andover.net chief executive Bruce Twickler said he was attracted
to the deal partly due to the popularity of linux.com, which
attracts about 12 million page views per month. Twickler said the
combination of linux.com with Andover.net's popular sites, like
Slashdot and Freshmeat, would create the leading on-line source of
news and information about Linux and other open source software
projects. ``We go from 51 percent to 67 percent of Linux traffic
share,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Twickler wanted to drive Andover.net into the
software consulting business. Andover.net recently purchased
QuestionExchange, a Web site where companies post offers to pay for
solutions to specific technical problems. But Andover.net has
little visibility in corporate America, while VA Linux has
developed a following there through its sales of Linux hardware.
Twickler hopes that the combined companies will be able to offer a
complete hardware, support and consulting service for businesses
interested in open source solutions.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Kusnetzky, an analyst with International Data Corp.,
questioned the wisdom of the deal. ``It looks like quite a bit of
money to spend on a Web publishing organization,'' Kusnetzky said.
He worries that VA Linux faces fierce competition in its core
business, as IBM Corp., Dell Computer Corp, Hewlett-Packard Co. and
other major firms all begin making Linux computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have looked at their portfolio and said `what are the
things that would further their success?' '' said Kusnetzky, who
thinks VA Linux should be buying firms that develop enhanced
services for high-end corporate users. ``I never would have thought
of a publication business,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
