<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TAXCUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR SAYS $1.1B TAX-CUT PLAN WILL PROCEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Governor Paul Cellucci Thursday vowed to press on with
his $1.1 billion tax cut plan despite the stunning news that the
cost of the massive Big Dig project is expected to jump $1.4
billion to $12.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, making his first public comments since the new price
tag was announced this week, also expressed confidence that
managers of the Central Artery/Ted Williams Tunnel project can
absorb the additional costs without needing state funds.
</P>
<P>
   But plans by Big Dig officials to raise tolls on the
Massachusetts Turnpike and the Logan Airport tunnels to cover
skyrocketing project costs is drawing the ire of businesses that
depend on the highway and the tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   James T. Wall, president of US Shuttle of Boston, a van company
that carries about 30,000 passengers a month to and from Logan,
said his company will see operating costs rise from $400,000 to
more than $1 million. Company vans, he said, will be forced to use
more sidestreets.
</P>
<P>
   Already, about one-third of the company's fleet uses side
streets in Chelsea, Everett, Medford and Somerville in order to
avoid tolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this happens, our only alternative will be to divert 100
percent to the streets in the suburbs,'' Wall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really disheartened by this whole thing,'' Wall said,
saying his company's increasing costs will be passed onto
customers. ``We think it a phony scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he had full confidence that James Kerasiotes, the
Massachusetts Turnpike Chairman who is overseeing the project, and
Patrick Moynihan, the project director, will develop a financing
scheme to handle the cost hikes.
</P>
<P>
   He referred to the two men as ``some of the best managers.'' and
said he was sure they
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci also insisted that he was telling the truth in his 1998
gubernatorial campaign when he said the Big Dig -- which then
carried a $10.8 billion price tag -- would be finished ``on time
and on budget.'' He said the additional costs had only become
evident in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said what the case was at the time,'' Cellucci told
reporters at a State House news conference Thursday. ``I gave the
situation at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci, who had been in Washington testifying against an
Internet sales tax when news of the cost overruns was made public
on Tuesday, skirted questions raised by some fiscal watchdogs and
other Beacon Hill leaders about the impact of nearly $2 billion in
tax cuts winning approval from voters in November.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Cellucci's ballot initiative calling for a $1.1
billion tax cut, voters also will decide another ballot question
that would create tax credits for tolls and auto excise taxes. That
plan, if passed, would cost the state as much as $700 million
annually, according to the Massachusetts Taxpayers Assocation.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed to explain the fiscal consequences if both ballot
questions are approved, Cellucci refused to comment on the tax
credit issue, saying he would not be ``diverted'' from focusing on
his income tax cut proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But he dismissed arguments that the new Big Dig cost should
raise questions about the fiscal prudence of his tax cut plan,
which would be phased in over three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it stengthens our arguments for our tax cut,''
Cellucci said, claiming that the reduction of the income tax rate
from 5.85 percent to 5 percent would be a boost for the state's
economy and would, in the long run, increase state revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci also said the financing plan for the highway project
had for some years included hikes in turnpike and tunnel tolls.
``The question of toll hikes has always been part of the finance
plan,'' he said. ``It should be of no suprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor insisted that the Massachusetts Turnpike Authority,
through toll hikes and other revenue-generating moves, will not
need state funds to meet Central Artery cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   But some Democratic legislative leaders have called on the
governor to acknowledge that state funds will have to be used to
pay for the project, which is scheduled for completion in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker Thomas F. Finneran, who has opposed Cellucci's
tax cut plan, said the administration should be given time to prove
its case that the tunrpike authority can develop a plan to cover
the newest cost estimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the revelation of the overrun doesn't necssarily detract
from the governor to make an argument for his tax cut,'' said
Finneran.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci also said he was sure the state's bond ratings would
not be affected by the new Big Dig price tag. He said he and his
financial advisers had made it clear to Wall Street bond rating
agencies last December that the Central Artery project would face
``additional costs,'' though they did not have exact figures at
that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was absolutely discussed,'' Cellucci said. ``This was a
full disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   State Treasurer Shannon O'Brien appears to have forced the
administration to disclose the $1.4 billion cost increase this week
because she was refusing to sign off on a $500 million bond issue
the administration needs for capital projects. The bond will be
offerred on the open market in several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, O'Brien said the administraton's decision to publicly
reveal the additional costs ``was the first step.'' She said state
officials must now develop a ``long term plan'' that takes into
account the potential fiscal impact if voters approve both ballot
questions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2019EST &QL; 
