<HEADER>
A5866 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-03 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GUYS JUST WANT TO GET VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON, S.C. _ ``LAAAAADIES and gentlemen. Would you please
welcome. The winner of the New Hampshire primary by a landslide ...
JOOOOOOHN MCCAIN!!!'' Several hundred college students begin to
stamp their feet. Cue the heavy metal music.
</P>
<P>
   What does this remind us of, people? I swear, the McCain
campaign is beginning to sound a little like a World Wrestling
Federation match. The courtship of the soccer moms is over. Meet
the new, improved version of the Guy Candidate.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot tell you how much McCain hates this concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for that theory,'' he said dryly, as his bus rolled
through South Carolina. ``Please, let me have both genders.
Please.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was wrestling with a serious gender gap as he headed into
the stretch in the New Hampshire primary. In the end, of course, he
did well among men, women, college graduates, high school dropouts
and the Italian-American senior-citizen snowmobilers. He now claims
that the enormous margin of his victory was due to previously
apathetic young people who didn't show up on the pollster's radar,
then turned out in droves to toss him a vote.
</P>
<P>
   That's more of a vision than an analysis. But there is something
about McCain that appeals to the Jesse Ventura crowd. When he flew
into South Carolina at 3 a.m. Wednesday, he was greeted by several
hundred rowdy college students, who had been dancing and partying
in an airport hanger since midnight. McCain was ecstatic, and to
tell the truth, the kids won many hearts when they yelled so loud
the local congressman was unable to tell a charming story about
Strom Thurmond he'd prepared for his introductory remarks.
</P>
<P>
   If McCain does well in South Carolina, I have a sneaking
suspicion the new voter du jour is going to be the Steel Cage Death
Match fan. We were due for a change. Politicians have fixated on
suburban women for several election cycles, and the wooing of the
woman's vote is getting stale in the worst possible way. It's
suffering from death by pandering, in much the same way that
concern about the angry white male succumbed to testosterone
overkill from the likes of Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, you will remember, was going to be the
Republican Who Could Talk to Females. He started out with an
interest in fixing the schools and a speech that stressed the
importance of making sure ``no child is left behind.'' But by New
Hampshire he had become so intent on proving to the party's
conservative wing that he would not turn into a presidential
``superintendent of schools.'' He kept warning audiences against
``people who come to your state saying, `Elect me, I'll build you
more classrooms, elect me, I'll pay your teachers more money.'
That's not a federal prerogative.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what the experts call going off message. VOTE FOR BUSH.
HELP COMBAT CLASSROOM SPRAWL.
</P>
<P>
   To compensate for the shift in emphasis, Bush larded his
speeches with odes to The Family. ``If I'm elected president, I'm
going to tell all the moms and dads we need to redouble our love
for our children,'' he informed a crowd, the weekend before the
Mauling in Manchester. Now, how many people out there think it is
possible to love their kids more than they already do?
</P>
<P>
   The difference between women's voting patterns and men's was
always about serious matters. Women tend to worry about the social
safety net, to favor government programs to improve health,
education and the environment. Politicians who labor under the
delusion that all suburban matrons want is a better husband in the
White House are cruising for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has never been particularly fixated on domestic policy;
anybody shopping for a candidate who will improve public schools,
let alone protect abortion rights, had better look for another
market. His top staff has about as high a percentage of women as
the Vatican. But his big issue, campaign finance reform, has
universal appeal. And this is a campaign that's still evolving,
inventing itself as it goes along. If things were carefully
scripted, you would probably not have the senator arriving at a
rally to the tune of ``Play that Funky Music (White Boy).''
</P>
<P>
   It is, at least, a Guy Campaign that respects the audience. And
if you see Bush on TV wearing spangled tights and a cape, you'll
know there's some serious repositioning at work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
