<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5869 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ALASKA-CRASH-ART-NYT &LR;      02-03 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-CRASH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DATA RECORDER RECOVERED IN ALASKA AIRLINES CRASH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Ariz.)   (ART ADV: Photos NYT1,3 are being sent to NYT photo clients. Map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT HUENEME, Calif. _ The mechanical problem in the MD-83 jet
that led it to turn upside down and corkscrew into the Pacific
Ocean on Monday came in a tail system that is supposed to withstand
failures, engineers at Boeing said Thursday, speaking as searchers
recovered the second of the jet's ``black boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   The second box, the flight data recorder, keeps track of the
position of the horizontal stabilizer, the part that jammed,
according to radio messages from the crew of the Alaska Airlines
jet to air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
   The first box, the cockpit voice recorder, recovered Wednesday
and played by investigators in Washington Thursday, captured the
two pilots discussing a problem with the horizontal stabilizer at
the beginning of the tape, more than 30 minutes before the crash.
Investigators said previously that the crew had first raised the
problem with air traffic controllers about 11 minutes before the
crash, after dropping rapidly from their assigned altitude.
</P>
<P>
   All 88 people aboard the jet bound from Puerto Vallarta, Mexico,
to San Francisco were killed; searchers have found the remains of
four of them.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Washington, James Hall, the chairman of the National
Transportation Safety Board, said the voice tape showed that the
plane was pitching nose down. ``The crew was able to arrest the
descent,'' he said, and ``continued trouble-shooting and preparing
the airplane for landing'' in Los Angeles. But then, he said,
``control was suddenly lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The preparations and the loss of control may be related. Boeing
engineers and pilots of the MD-80 series airplane say the airplane
tends to pitch up or down in response to changes in its speed or
fuel consumption or changes in the position of the flaps and the
slats, devices on the wings that are used on takeoff and landing.
Extending the slats and flaps, as a pilot would do while preparing
to land, would aggravate the nose-down tendency.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing engineers Thursday described a detailed emergency
procedure for coping with a malfunctioning stabilizer system. The
stabilizer, which makes up the front two-thirds of the horizontal
tail, can be angled up or down to keep the nose at the desired
angle and is typically adjusted hundreds of times in a flight, they
said. It is moved on its hinge by a jack screw, similar to the
long, thick screw that raises or lowers a garage door. Two motors
drive the screw, one at the command of the pilots and the other
when the auto pilot is in charge, although pilots can operate that
one as well, if needed. The emergency procedure involves switching
off the circuit breakers on each motor, in alternation, to figure
out which one has a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The stabilizer system includes both motors and brakes, and both
would have to fail for the part to move in an undesired manner,
according to the Boeing engineers.
</P>
<P>
   The plane is supposed to be flyable even if the stabilizer is
immobilized, although engineers said it might require the pilots to
pull hard on their control yokes, possibly both at once.
</P>
<P>
   Being stuck in a nose-down position is considered the worst
case, because pilots need to pull the nose up before touchdown, to
dissipate some of the plane's energy. But this plane did not make
it that far.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators hope the flight data recorder will provide a
clearer picture of what happened. The recorder captures data on
about 25 hours of flight time, ending at the time of the crash.
Investigators said it would show the movements of the stabilizer on
the fatal flight and also whether the stabilizer had any erratic
behavior earlier, on the flight into Puerto Vallarta.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the Seattle Times reported that the crew that flew
the plane into Puerto Vallarta said the stabilizer had a problem.
Thursday, Hall made no direct comment on whether the safety board
had heard such reports and said that anyone with such information
should bring it to the board. He said it was ``quite frankly
irresponsible'' to do otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Hall also said that engineers had played the flight data
recorder from another MD-83, an American Airlines flight that took
off from Phoenix on Wednesday and made an emergency return because
of a problem with its stabilizer. But he said, ``we cannot say if
there are any common elements'' with the Alaska Airlines flight.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Loeb, the board's top aviation safety official, said,
``It's premature at this time to conclude there is any kind of
systemic issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
