u i BC-IRELAND-ULSTER-BOS &LR;      02-03 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-ULSTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN TO SEEK SUSPENSION OF LOCAL RULE IN ULSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain will introduce legislation Friday to suspend
the fledgling power-sharing government in Northern Ireland and
reimpose direct rule from London in an attempt to encourage an IRA
handover of weapons and avert a Protestant Unionist walkout from
the Belfast assemply.
</P>
<P>
   A suspension of the power-sharing assembly would be a
devastating blow to the peace process, coming just two months after
local government was returned to Northern Ireland for the first
time in 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mandelson, Britain's secretary of state for Northern
Ireland, told the House of Commons Thursday that the British and
Irish governments would continue to seek a commitment from the
Irish Republican Army to disarm before the legislation is approved
late next week. The governments are buying time, hoping for a
last-minute gesture or pledge from the IRA, which seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Irish premier Bertie Ahern flew late Thursday to meet British
Prime Minister Tony Blair in Cornwall, trying to find a
breakthrough. Ahern said progress had been made, but did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   While Dublin remains reluctant to go along with a suspension of
the fledgling government in Belfast, Britain was determined not to
allow Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble to walk out, as he had
vowed to do Friday unless London agreed to suspend the political
institutions created by the Good Friday Agreement of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble and his party, which represents most Protestants in
Northern Ireland, agreed to form a government that includes two
Cabinet ministers from Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing, but
only with the understanding that the IRA begin turning in its
arsenal, or at least commit to doing so, by the end of January.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams said Trimble had no right to set
deadlines unilaterally, and accused the British government of
acting illegally by allowing Trimble to alter the terms of the Good
Friday Agreement. That 1998 agreement stated that paramilitary
groups should finish disarming by this May, but it set no date for
the process to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Adams argued that his party needs more time to persuade the IRA
to voluntarily disarm, and said unilateral demands by unionists
were making that task harder. He said the British decision to back
the unionist demands to suspend the power-sharing government will
probably lead the IRA to break off its contact with the
international commission overseeing the disarming of paramilitary
groups. The IRA agreed to appoint a representative to speak to the
commission in return for the creation of the power-sharing
government.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in the House of Commons, Mandelson confirmed that a
report by the commission concluded neither the IRA nor its loyalist
adversaries had agreed to disarm. While the loyalists are as
reluctant to start disarming, it is the IRA's refusal to commit to
turning in weapons that threatens to bring down Northern Ireland's
government, which for the first time includes unionists who want to
retain the union with Britain and hardline Irish Catholic
nationalists who want to merge with the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the IRA are opposed to making even a token gesture on
weapons, seeing it as an act of surrender. IRA leaders are
determined to avoid a split over weapons. But Trimble said the bulk
of his party will not take part in a government that includes Sinn
Fein while it maintains ``a private army.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the timetable announced by Mandelson, the legislation will
be passed and the institutions suspended before the end of next
week, avoiding a walkout by Trimble which the British believe would
make getting the government back up and running more difficult
procedurally and politically. The British fear Trimble would be
pushed aside by more intransigent unionists.
</P>
<P>
   Seamus Mallon, the leading nationalist and deputy leader of the
power-sharing government, argued against suspension, saying it
should be delayed until the chairman of the commission overseeing
disarming, Canadian General John de Chastelain, was allowed to get
the IRA and loyalist paramilitary groups to answer two questions:
will they disarm, and if so, when?
</P>
<P>
   But Mandelson called suspension ``the better of the two
options'' and said the IRA's refusal to disarm amounted to ``a
betrayal of the entire community of Northern Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last thing I want to see happen,'' Mandelson said of
the suspension. But, he added, ``there comes a time when we have to
express our impatience and intolerance'' over the refusal of
paramilitary groups to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the IRA issued a statement insisting that it would
continue to observe its cease-fire and that it was committed to a
``permanent peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson praised that IRA commitment, but said it wasn't
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The institutions can only work on the basis of cross-community
confidence,'' said Mandelson. ``Without clarity over
decommissioning, I have no doubt that this confidence will ebb
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson said he did not want to suspend the institutions, but
was determined ``to preserve them from collapse and to create the
time and space in which to rebuild the confidence required to
sustain them.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Irish foreign ministry acknowledged that
the Dublin government was less enthusiastic about beginning the
legislative process to suspend the power-sharing government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as a last resort,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
