<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-TANKER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SEIZES RUSSIAN TANKER SAID TO CARRY OIL FROM IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two U.S. warships enforcing U.N. sanctions against
Iraq seized a Russian tanker in the Persian Gulf on Thursday after
boarding it and discovering evidence that it might be smuggling oil
out of southern Iraq, a Pentagon spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   A lightly armed boarding party from the guided missile cruiser
Monterey landed on the tanker by helicopter Wednesday after
repeated attempts to get the tanker to respond to radio queries
about its cargo, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no incidents of violence whatsoever,'' said Rear
Adm. Craig Quigley. The Americans reviewed the tanker's
navigational equipment and documents, including bills of lading.
They also took samples of the cargo of gas oil to determine whether
the petroleum had originated in Iraq. As of late Thursday, the
analysis of the petroleum _ and the sediment carried in it, which
should indicate its source _ had not been completed, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Volgoneft-147 tanker, flying a Russian flag, is only the
second Russian vessel stopped by the international patrols since
1990, when Iraq was prohibited from selling oil on the open market
as punishment for its invasion of Kuwait, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For the past month, the United States has warned the Russian
government of its monitoring of two Russian tankers that had
arrived on the Iraqi coast and appeared to be involved in smuggling
oil. The Russian ambassador to the United States was briefed
regularly on the issue, and U.S. diplomats in Moscow have discussed
it with the government there, said James P. Foley, a State
Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian government has told us that this ship is privately
owned and that an investigation on the Russian side is under way,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of ships trying to smuggle oil out of Iraq has risen
dramatically with the increase in oil prices to $27 a barrel from
$11 a year ago, a senior Pentagon official said. But the unusual
presence of Russian vessels pushed the United States to involve the
Moscow government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get the Russians to police this ship themselves,''
the Pentagon official said, ``but I guess with oil prices so high
it's hard to stop these entrepreneurs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
