<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE A BALL IS STRUCK, ZIMBABWE FEELS A LIFT
</HEADLINE>
   (See also TEN-ARATON-COLUMN) 
(rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ The No. 1 player in Zimbabwe stood shoulder
to shoulder with No. 1 in the world here Thursday. At the Davis Cup
draw to determine the pairings for Friday's opening matches,
Zimbabwe's president, Robert Mugabe, might have been hoping that
Andre Agassi's magic is contagious.
</P>
<P>
   With lines for gasoline lengthening, unemployment, inflation and
HIV infection rates soaring, and parliamentary elections coming,
the beleaguered president made sure that Agassi was right next to
him for the group photo at the statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've read the papers, Zimbabwe is going through a bit of
a rough time right now, and I think this is a bit of a breath of
fresh air,'' said Byron Black, who plays the American Chris
Woodruff in the second match at the Harare Sports Center. Black's
brother, Wayne, will play Agassi in the first match.
</P>
<P>
   There are seven other first-round matchups in the World Group:
Australia, the defending champion, at Switzerland; Britain at the
Czech Republic; Italy at Spain; Belgium at Russia; Austria at
Slovakia; Brazil at France, and Netherlands at Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe called Zimbabwe's encounter with the United States ``the
dwarfs against the giants.'' But Woodruff did not want to hear
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I told you I didn't feel any pressure,'' he
said. ``This is a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   He was home in Knoxville, Tenn., when the U.S. captain, John
McEnroe, called last Friday to inform him that he had been drafted
by Uncle Sam. Here he is, at 27, set up as the biggest target in
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre is playing the best tennis of anyone on the planet right
now,'' Byron Black said. ``Obviously, the guy we're aiming to beat
is the No. 2 player, Woodruff. Hopefully, the doubles could be the
crucial decider.''
</P>
<P>
   If that occurs, McEnroe may run out of hairs that have not
turned gray. The U.S. team of Alex O'Brien and Rick Leach has never
played together. The Zimbabwe captain, Gavin Sinney, is pairing
Wayne Black with Kevin Ullyett for Saturday's doubles, and engaging
in some playful warfare with McEnroe.
</P>
<P>
   ``America, with the players they've got, should win the Davis
Cup every year for the next few years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, speaking for the depleted Americans, said ``I think
we'll be fortunate to get through this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   One singles victory by Woodruff would pretty much assure a
second-round match against England or the Czech Republic in Los
Angeles. But Woodruff has no Davis Cup experience other than being
a practice partner. His best ranking was 25, three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He soon hurt his wrist, then tore up his knee just fooling
around, kicking field goals with the tour veteran Richey Reneberg
at a high school field in Atlanta. He was out for almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 6-4, good agility, big hitter,'' said Paul Goldstein, one
of the team's practice players. ``At the Australian Open, he beat
Tim Henman, didn't lose a set for three rounds, lost to Sampras in
the quarters. He's playing good ball.''
</P>
<P>
   How that translates here, in the nearly mile-high altitude and
under extreme Davis Cup conditions, who knows? Byron Black Thursday
was promising more noise than even McEnroe might be able to bear.
There will be ``a lot of drums,'' Black said, possibly _ by
coincidence, of course _ right behind McEnroe.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time Zimbabwe has ever engaged an American
team, a situation that makes Byron Black something of a prophet. A
couple of years ago, when Zimbabwe had qualified for the World
Group, the tennis federation president, Paul Chinoka, asked him if
he and his brother could help bring famous American players like
Agassi, Sampras or even the retired McEnroe to Harare to play
exhibitions and promote the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, well, this could be a bit expensive,'' Black said.
``I said, `Maybe you should wait for Davis Cup. We'll get them for
free.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
