<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5874 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-BOS &LR;      02-03 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY CROWD DEMANDS FIRING OF 2 WHO SHOT FELLOW OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMAL E. WATSON AND BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Restraint over the slaying of police Sergeant
Cornel Young Jr. erupted into protest Thursday as 200 noisy
demonstrators marched into City Hall and black clergy demanded that
the two officers who gunned down Young last Friday be fired.
</P>
<P>
   In a day filled with angry demands and cross-city meetings,
minority leaders who suspect that Young's death might be linked to
racial profiling met with Mayor Vincent A. Cianci Jr. and state
Attorney General Sheldon Whitehouse to air their concerns and seek
an independent investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after Young was buried with full honors in an
emotional funeral, about 200 chanting protesters, banging pots,
converged on City Hall to present their demands to Cianci.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators want police Officers Carlos A. Saraiva and
Michael Solitro 3d to hand in their badges, an outside review of
Young's shooting, and that felony murder charge withdrawn against
Aldrin Diaz, whom police holding responsible for the death even
though he dropped his weapon before the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning,'' said Melvin Carter, an organizer
of the protest. ``We want to see things change.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, 29, the son of the highest-ranking black officer in the
Providence Police Department, was shot three times as he rushed to
aid Saraiva and Solitro as they confronted an armed man in a
late-night fracas. Young, who was off-duty, carrying a gun and
dressed in civilian clothes, did not identify himself as a police
officer and did not drop his weapon when ordered, authorities have
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police have not identified the races of Saraiva and Solitro, but
others say they are white. Cianci said Thursday that Saraiva is
Latino.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, many of whom wore three red stickers to
symbolize the number of times Young was shot, urged Cianci to
appoint a civilian review board to investigate other complaints of
police misconduct in the city. Direct Action for Race and Equality,
a grass-roots community group, organized the multi-racial
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the racism to stop, and we want the police brutality
to stop,'' said Ben Moses. ``We're here to hold the mayor and the
Police Department accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is there aren't enough facts to be conclusive
about what happened, but it's likely that racism played a part in
that the officers may have shot sooner than they might have
otherwise had Young been white,'' said Derek P. Ellerman, executive
director of the Providence-based Center for Police and Community.
</P>
<P>
   Cianci, in an interview, said he is being targeted unfairly by
protesters, who chanted ``No justice, no peace!'' and ``Stop police
brutality!''
</P>
<P>
   Cianci cited his administration's work in the minority
community, and said that he appointed Cornel Young Sr. from a
patrolman to major of the community policing division despite
objections from other officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a liberal city,'' said Cianci, who has been mayor for
the last 19 years. ``We believe in and support diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his goals, the mayor said, has been to encourage the
Police Department to hire more black officers. Currently, there are
35 black officers on the 440-member force.
</P>
<P>
   Jody Greene and David Rosen, two first-year students at Brown
University, missed classes to join in the demand that the charges
against Diaz be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wrong to scapegoat this man,'' said Rosen, 19.
``He didn't shoot the officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid shouts and chants, Cianci emerged from his office to
address the protesters about a half-hour after the demonstration
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one who is sadder than I am to have lost a police
officer,'' he said to a heckling crowd. ``But we have to wait and
let the investigation take place.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cianci refused to accept the protesters' demands and
quickly retreated into his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's doing the right thing,'' said Claudia Bellussio,
a chief clerk in the city registrar's office. ``It's a shame that
this has happened, but the protesters don't want to listen to the
mayor. My God, it's one day after the funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   Cianci, who had been under attack for appearing to downplay a
racial possibility in the shooting, said Thursday he supports a
broad investigation that will consider whether racial profiling _
the practice of assigning greater criminal suspicion based on race
_ played a role in Young's death. Some had demanded Cianci retract
his earlier statements about that aspect of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing to retract,'' Cianci said just before the
protest. ``I said at the time that all aspects of the case should
be investigated, including race.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he has no power to grant another demand: an
independent inquiry into Young's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to contribute to the investigation,'' he said.
``At this time it is being handled by the attorney general's
office. I have no control over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Cianci met privately with black ministers who
said they believed race had been a factor in the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no evidence whether there was race involved or no race
involved, but I think a full investigation ought to be carried
out,'' Cianci said outside the Allen A.M.E. Church, where the
ministers met.
</P>
<P>
   Black leaders from the Ministers' Alliance of Rhode Island and
the Urban League have requested that an outside agency, such as the
Federal Bureau of Investigation, handle the probe of Young's death.
The state attorney general will examine Young's death before any
evidence is presented to a grand jury for possible indictment.
</P>
<P>
   However, many minority activists are skeptical that state
government can objectively investigate the case _ and is
sufficiently autonomous from Providence affairs in this small
state.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz has been charged with felony murder, which can be filed
against someone committing a felony when a death occurs. Diaz had
waved a .22-caliber pistol outside an automobile during the
altercation at the Fidas Restaurant, but dropped the gun when
confronted by Saraiva and Solitro.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Whitehouse said Thursday that his office will
pursue its investigation vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the beginning of our process to get to the bottom of
what happened,'' he said. ``I understand the community's needs for
answers. I want answers as well, but I need to remain dedicated to
deriving those answers through the deliberate and sound grand jury
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Clifford R. Montiero, president of the Providence chapter of the
NAACP, has pledged to meet with minority officers from other states
who have been injured by fellow officers in cases of mistaken
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Montiero, like nearly all black leaders in the city, had
refrained from criticizing the police until Young was buried. The
victim's father, Major Cornel Young Sr., had asked that the
community respect the family's wish to grieve before turning its
attention to questions of police conduct.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
