A5876 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AIR-LEGROOM04-COX     02-03 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-LEGROOM04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American Airlines program to boost legroom
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An airline industry giant is trying a novel concept to
boost passenger satisfaction: more legroom in coach.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines said Thursday it will remove 7,200 coach seats
from its fleet of jets, boosting typical legroom by about 3 inches.
</P>
<P>
   American executives trumpeted the plan at a news conference in
Washington, D.C., where airline service gripes provoked hearings in
Congress last year.
</P>
<P>
   Adding coach legroom ``makes good business sense and is the
right thing to do in today's competitive environment,'' said Donald
Carty, American's chief executive. He suggested the industry has
too long ignored basic physical comfort, at least in coach, while
trying to mollify fliers with new snacks and video programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some degree, this is an industry that has lately been in
denial,'' Carty said.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3 CEO posed for pictures in a mock-up of the new
seating plan, his knees conspicuously not jammed against the next
seatback.
</P>
<P>
   American's move follows a more limited gambit by United
Airlines. Last year United added legroom to the first few rows of
coach on some planes, reserving them for passengers paying higher,
short-notice fares.
</P>
<P>
   The trend could force Atlanta giant Delta Air Lines, the third
member of the industry's so-called Big Three, to add coach legroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts real pressure on Delta to come up with something,''
said Ed Perkins, retired editor of Consumer Reports Travel Letter.
``For that matter, it puts pressure on Northwest, Continental and
USAirways, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The downside of added legroom? ``Cutting seat capacity means the
cost per seat goes up,'' said Perkins. He said big carriers that
join the trend may offer fewer seats at the lowest prices to offset
the economic penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokesman John Kennedy said the airline is studying
American's plan. ``Seating space is important and we're reviewing
our options in this area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta generally has reserved its seat space initiatives for
front-cabin passengers. Its BusinessElite international cabin
offers unusually generous legroom to fliers who can afford to
upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But those benefits don't reach the huddled masses in coach. In
fact, Delta's version of the Boeing 777, its new international
widebody, has coach seats that are 1 inch narrower than those on
the MD-11s it will eventually replace, while legroom is unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines can adjust legroom without great technical difficulty,
since seats are installed along rails. Various extra-legroom
programs in the past _ TWA and the now-defunct Kiwi are among
carriers that tried them _ eventually succumbed to pack-'em-in
financial imperatives.
</P>
<P>
   American heralded its coach plan as one that will ``change the
face of domestic and international coach travel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Their surveys I'm sure are telling them that people hate the
tight seating, which has really been made worse by the heavy loads
on most flights,'' said Perkins. He said seat dimensions haven't
changed much in the past 15 years, but it seems that way because
passenger loads have gotten heavier _ in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loads are bigger and the people are bigger, too,'' he
noted. ``It's not so bad if there's an empty seat next to you, but
that's a luxury anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   American, based in Dallas-Fort Worth, said it will remove about
6.4 percent of the coach seats in its 700-plane fleet. For
instance, the airline will remove two rows totaling 10 seats from
its MD-80 narrowbody jets, cutting capacity to 129 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, average seat pitch will expand ``from the present
industry standard of 31 and 32 inches to a predominant level of 34
and 35 inches of space, with some reaching as much as 36 inches,''
the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   Seat pitch is not a literal measure of legroom but rather the
amount of space from a point on one seat to the same point on a
seat in front or behind.
</P>
<P>
   American said that when the project is finished, about 58
percent of its coach seats will have a pitch of 34 or more inches,
while 98 percent will have seat room ``greater than today's
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline said the project dovetails with an ongoing one to
install new space-saving ``slimline'' coach seats with adjustable
leather headrests.
</P>
<P>
   The American plan does nothing to add elbow room, which is
dictated chiefly by fuselage width. However, Hotard said the new
seats have slightly narrower armrests, providing an extra sliver of
width.
</P>
<P>
   American said it will complete the project on its domestic jets
by November and on international planes next year.
</P>
<P>
   The project will cost the airline an estimated $70 million. Some
analysts fear the reduced seat capacity could mean lower profits at
American and other carriers that follow suit. The move comes amid
concern that profits will be under pressure anyway because of
rising fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   But Hotard said American believes the benefit to its service
image offsets capacity loss.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
