<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-CONGRESS-     02-03 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Ohio, Ariz., Tenn., Utah, Neb., Ga.)  
 McCAIN'S VICTORY UNNERVES SOME SENATE COLLEAGUES  
(See related stories, SC-REPUBS, McCAIN-FUNDRAISING,
NY-McCAIN-BALLOT) 
(bl) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once again John McCain has managed to irk his
Senate Republican colleagues, and he was not even in town to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Mulling over McCain's walloping victory in the New Hampshire
primary, Senate Republicans said they were startled by his margin
of victory over the party's favorite, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
But rather than drop their heads and shuffle their feet, many of
them agreed that, if anything, Bush's resounding loss would bolster
their commitment to him, and they predicted that it would help Bush
in the long run, just as a tighter race between the Democratic
candidates, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley of
New Jersey, revved up Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably will re-energize him,'' Sen. Trent Lott of
Mississippi, the majority leader and a Bush supporter, said of
Bush. ``He will learn from what he experienced in New Hampshire. As
he said, he's running a 50-state campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing his best game-day face, Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who
is considered to be McCain's chief foe in the Senate, said bluntly,
``We'll see who the nominee is.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the senior senator from Arizona, has always had a knack
for unnerving his Republican colleagues with his blustery style and
renegade crusades. His eagerness to overhaul the nation's campaign
finance laws, a move that Republicans say would hurt their party
the most, turned him into a political pariah among the party's
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But after New Hampshire, even some who disagree with him tipped
their hats and proclaimed his message a possible winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more than a small blow,'' said Sen. Robert
Bennett, R-Utah, who has endorsed Bush. ``There is no question that
John McCain has captured the essence of a message that could win
this year. That is: `I am not Bill Clinton.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett added: ``He comes across as the ultimate anti-Clinton.
He's a war hero; Clinton is a draft dodger. He insists he wants to
reform a corrupt system, and Clinton represents a corrupt system.
McCain calls his campaign the Straight Talk Express; Clinton is the
epitome of twisted talk.''
</P>
<P>
   A few Republican senators smiled through clenched teeth as they
talked about the New Hampshire results, then quickly recalled Pat
Buchanan's victory in the New Hampshire primary four years ago.
This was the man, they reminded others, whom quirky New Hampshire
Republican voters once wanted to crown president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outsider tone of his message appeals to independents, and
independents is where the core of the victory was,'' Sen. Paul
Coverdell, R-Ga., who is Bush's chief congressional liaison, said
of McCain. ``But then that's what Buchanan was doing, too, and the
door closed in the South. And I think it will again.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's supporters in the Senate _ all four of them _ exulted
in his victory. And Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., the majority whip
who has not endorsed any candidate, broke the ice at a morning
meeting this week when he asked Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., where the
line began to join the McCain administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``What our focus has been on is the people,'' said Hagel, who,
along with Sens. Mike DeWine of Ohio, Jon Kyl of Arizona and Fred
Thompson of Tennessee, is a McCain supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the people who will elect the next president and
determine our party's nominee,'' Hagel added. ``Thirty-five
senators won't do that. Thirty governors won't do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
