<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     02-03 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TENNIS IS PART OF FARMER'S CHARMED LIFE
</HEADLINE>
   (With TEN-DAVIS-CUP) 
(rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANDARA, Zimbabwe _ The grounds are out of a dusty colonial
storybook, from another time and a privileged place. This is where
Don Black raised a tennis family, where the grass is lush and the
fruits are plenty and labor was love.
</P>
<P>
   Here, on 22 acres rife with avocado pear trees and vegetation
that sways to a gentle breeze as if it were music, Don Black
awakened his sons, Byron and Wayne, and later daughter Cara, to the
first sign of dawn. School days, every day, they would all hit
barefoot on grass moistened by dew.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the fruit, Black grew three tennis pros. The
boys, no physical specimens, always went along with what the father
called ``the contract.'' They became tour veterans, and something
of a local Davis Cup dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if I'd had an athlete to work with,'' Don Black said,
half-kidding. ``If I had one like Michael Jordan, he could have
killed Sampras.''
</P>
<P>
   The Black brothers don't have to worry about Pete Sampras this
weekend. Only Andre Agassi, whom Wayne will try his luck with
Friday in what the country's president, Robert Mugabe, is calling
``the dwarfs versus the giants,'' Zimbabwe hosting the United
States, in the first round of the Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Don Black was also a tennis player, once a match point from
Wimbledon's fourth round. Then he returned to his native Rhodesia
and became a teacher, like his English mother, and a farmer, like
his Scottish father, who came to this former British colony in
1913.
</P>
<P>
   What a charmed life the 72-year-old Black has led on this
fertile African land, a straight shot from downtown along
Enterprise Road. He retired, at 40, from teaching with a full
pension. He was too young to fight in World War II and too old, by
three weeks, to be drafted by the colonial regime during the
revolution that resulted in independent Zimbabwe in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of my friends were gone to war and I was over there
working on the kids' strokes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over there'' was the grass court he had just stepped off,
after finishing a lesson in an unobtrusive rain. From the veranda,
his bare feet resting on the dry stone floor, he pointed to where
Roy Emerson had climbed the fence and collapsed a rail now known as
``Emmo's Bend.'' All of his old Aussie friends had visited him
here, in fact, and hit on his well-manicured lawns. He and Rod
Laver became good friends.
</P>
<P>
   From his hideaway outside Harare, Black tended to his fruit,
read books and corresponded anonymously (he forgot to sign his
name) with the likes of Bertrand Russell. He constructed four grass
courts, one hard court surrounded by banana trees. He married ``the
girl living two miles down the road.'' Velia Black wrote letters to
her family in England, and they subsequently became a book,
``Growing Up in Rhodesia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Black kids were raised in a very different place than the
ones who beg for money downtown, or even those visited Wednesday by
John McEnroe. In Chitungwiza Township, where unemployment is
roughly 50 percent, some of the kids also played barefoot, only it
was on sun-drenched cement.
</P>
<P>
   While Velia Black has offered scholarships for a few talented
children there, it is hard to connect or comprehend such disparate
worlds. When he schooled his own children, Don would set up a
bucket and the kids would aim for it with the serve. An African
gardener whom the family only knows as Madala _ Old Man _ would
retrieve the balls.
</P>
<P>
   The gardener, still with the family, was once going blind from
cataracts. An Australian eye surgeon teaching in Harare sent a car.
Old Man was fearful, Don said, and wouldn't get in. They plied him
with brandy, and off he went, returning the next day, eyesight
restored.
</P>
<P>
   Don Black opened his historical storybook and even Byron's
scrapbook for visitors Thursday. Inside, he played a musical video
called ``It's the Blacks,'' composed by a local performer named
Fungai Malianga. There is no disputing the Black family's
popularity here, but the economy is failing, the government is
wheezing and turmoil may be brewing.
</P>
<P>
   While two-thirds of the white population left after 1980, Don
Black stayed. He wouldn't even travel to watch his kids play. ``How
the hell could I leave all this?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Off in the distance, his wife was teaching tennis to a
diplomat's kids. A servant was cleaning the first-floor windows.
Old Man was strolling across the avocado fields.
</P>
<P>
   The breeze was, at once, calming and intoxicating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll die here, whatever happens,'' Don Black said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
