r p BC-BUSH-TOBACCO-TEX     02-03 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TOBACCO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SUPPORTED TOBACCO TAXES, A BIG CONCERN FOR SOUTH CAROLINA
VOTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sen. John McCain was being criticized on
Thursday in South Carolina for his support of higher tobacco taxes,
but Gov. George W. Bush in the past has endorsed similar
initiatives in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Bush backed a tax overhaul that contained a
20-cent-per-pack increase in cigarette taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good plan. It's exactly what I hoped would happen,''
Bush declared when the legislation cleared a House committee.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of tobacco taxes has arisen in South Carolina, one of
the nation's largest tobacco producers and site of the next hotly
contested GOP presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   A pro-industry group, the National Smokers Alliance, has begun
running ads criticizing McCain's sponsorship of legislation that
would have raised tobacco taxes and given the federal government
new power to regulate nicotine. That bill also failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saying one thing and doing another, that's the real John
McCain,'' the ad says in part.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Humber, president of the smokers alliance, said his group
opposed the effort in Texas to hike cigarette taxes, but he
applauded Bush for remaining consistent on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   He said McCain's insistence that he had never supported tax
increases in the U.S. Senate contradicts his record.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about misrepresenting the record. To the best of my
knowledge, Governor Bush has never misrepresented the record
regarding that,'' Humber said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the governor's endorsement of the House legislation in
1997, Bush spokesman Scott McClellan would not say whether Bush
liked the tobacco tax being included in it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not in his plan that he proposed,'' said McClellan.
As for the House plan, McClellan said: ``He supported the effort to
move it to the Senate.'' That's where the legislation died.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Hugo Berlanga, D-Corpus Christi, now a lobbyist who
has been friendly with the governor, said Bush never expressed any
opposition to the tobacco tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed the money and the money was going to go to cover
other health care programs,'' Berlanga recalled. ``I think the
governor clearly understood what that meant, and there was never
any resistance from his office regarding that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a win-win for him,'' Berlanga said. ``He was smart
enough to understand that in the overall scheme there were some
additional dollars that were going to take care of some worthy
programs, and at the same time achieve his goal of overall tax
cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's critics have in the past criticized the large
number of donations he has received from the industry.
</P>
<P>
   According to federal election records, Bush has accepted more
than $50,000 from industry executives. In addition, his chief
political strategist, Karl Rove, was once on the payroll of tobacco
giant Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
