<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5890 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-POLLSC04-COX     02-03 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-POLLSC04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poll shows slight McCain lead over Bush in S.C.; Bauer may drop
out of race
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Money, volunteers and a favorable poll came
Sen. John McCain's way Thursday as he campaigned along the
picturesque Atlantic coast, battling Texas Gov. George W. Bush for
South Carolina's large military vote.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that the Republican presidential field was about to
become one candidate smaller, with indications that Gary Bauer
would announce his withdrawal at a news conference today. Bauer
would be the sixth Republican dropout, leaving four in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary is having a news conference on Friday. That's all we're
saying about it,'' said spokesman Tim Goeglein.
</P>
<P>
   A new survey by independent pollster John Zogby released
Thursday gives McCain about a five-point lead over Bush in South
Carolina, 44 percent to 39.3 percent. It is the first time an
independent poll has shown him ahead in the state, which holds its
Republican primary Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   The Zogby poll has a 4.4 percentage point margin of error, so
McCain's lead would be three-tenths outside that.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator said he was happy, but wary of the new Zogby
poll. ``The polls will bounce up and down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, still riding high from Tuesday's 19-point victory over
Bush in the New Hampshire primary, directed his harshest words at
President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore. He barely mentioned
Bush at three stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton and Gore debased every institution of government in
1996,'' McCain said, referring to Democratic fund-raising abuses in
the last election.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also poked fun at Bush for calling his loss in New
Hampshire ``a bump in the road.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They call it a bump in the road. I'm telling you my friends,
it was a land mine,'' McCain said on Seabrook Island, the calm
waters of the Edisto River behind him.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign continued trying to take advantage of the
New Hampshire results.
</P>
<P>
   The underdog senator has raised more than $1 million and
attracted 4,000 new volunteers via the Internet in the past two
days. More than 1,000 people heard McCain speak on the Charleston
waterfront. Hundreds more attended events in Beaufort and on
Seabrook Island.
</P>
<P>
   The last public poll in South Carolina, released before the New
Hampshire primary, put Bush up by 20 points. But the McCain
campaign had a poll of its own last week that gave Bush only a
nine-point margin, a campaign official said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain's gain in the polls is dramatic in a state that is
crucial to his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the poll is right, it seems as though McCain is a genuine
mass phenomenon right now,'' said Merle Black, a political science
professor at Emory University. ``And at the moment, Bush is coming
across as a highly scripted candidate who can't make a persuasive
argument about where he wants to take the country.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is hoping to string together victories in primaries in
different regions of the country. With New Hampshire behind him,
McCain is targeting South Carolina, which will be closely followed
on the primary calendar by Michigan and his home state of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to determine our party's nominee,'' Rep. Lindsey
Graham (R-S.C.) said while campaigning with McCain in Beaufort.
``Let me be blunt. If we lose here, it's going to be very
difficult.'' Meanwhile in New York, Republican Gov. George Pataki,
who is supporting Bush, waved the white flag and dropped the state
GOP's court battle to keep McCain off the state's primary ballot.
Pataki said Bush agreed with him.
</P>
<P>
   McCain began his day Thursday at S.C. Mayor Bill Rouch's
antebellum house in Beaufort, beneath a giant water oak dripping
with Spanish moss.
</P>
<P>
   Rouch once served as press secretary to former New York Mayor Ed
Koch, a Democrat. He is not affiliated with either major party, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man's fearless,'' Rouch said as he introduced McCain on a
sunny but chilly morning.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he is ``fully prepared to lead'' as a result of his
military service and the expertise on foreign policy that he
developed in 17 years in Congress. ``I do not need on-the-job
training,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He paid homage to the ``patriotism and sacrifice'' of South
Carolinians, part of his emphasis on the military in a state with
400,000 veterans. There are more veterans per capita in South
Carolina than in any other state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also appealed for South Carolina veterans' support
Thursday. He made a pointed reference to McCain as a potential
leader, saying, ``There is a big difference between being somebody
who had a distinguished military record and being someone who's
trying to lead the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared in Sumter with Adm. Thomas Moorer, who served as
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff during the Nixon
administration, and Thomas Burch Jr., chairman of the National
Vietnam and Gulf War Veterans Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   McCain ``came home and forgot us,'' Burch said. Afterward, Burch
said the senator hadn't supported his group's efforts on Agent
Orange, Gulf War Syndrome and support for families of soldiers
missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   McCain dismissed the criticism as ``bizarre. To say that somehow
I would not be doing everything that I can flies in the face of
facts,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator has a large network of veterans supporting him,
including several men held with him as prisoners of war in North
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, a janitor's son and conservative activist who served as a
domestic policy aide the the Reagan White House, chiefly stressed
opposition to abortion and China policy during his campaign. But
Bauer was unable to gain much support. He drew 9 percent of the
Republican vote in Iowa, and just 1 percent in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
