<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-ATTORNEY04-COX     02-03 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-ATTORNEY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police seeking statements from two Lewis friends
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa and By Don Fernandez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A.J. Johnson, one of the two men wanted for
questioning in the double slaying that landed NFL star Ray Lewis in
the Atlanta City Jail, says he wasn't even in Atlanta the night of
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The second man, Kwame King, a longtime friend of the football
player, hasn't been seen by friends and relatives since he left his
home in Florida to meet Lewis for the big game.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police said they believe the two men were inside the
black stretch limousine that sped away from the intersection where
the bodies of Jacinth Baker, 21, and Richard Lollar, 24, lay in a
pool of blood, police spokesman John Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe they were present in the limousine, and we're
interested in anybody that was with the limousine at that time,''
Quigley said Thursday evening. ``We are waiting for them to call
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a student at the University of Maryland, hadn't called
police as of Thursday evening. But he told reporters he watched the
Super Bowl on television with friends in his Baltimore apartment.
He said Thursday that he had socialized with Lewis occasionally,
but never considered him a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine, he can say that,'' Quigley said Thursday evening
referring to Johnson's comments. ``We we want to talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and King were much closer.
</P>
<P>
   The two men grew up separated by a strip of asphalt in Lakeland,
Fla. They became teammates on the Kathleen High School football
team, the Red Devils. Both grew up in single-parent homes without a
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray and Kwame are close friends,'' said Chuck Greene, King's
roommate and friend in Tallahassee. ``They grew up in the same
small town, they lived by each other. Kwame's like an older brother
to Ray.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, King's mother, Simone Brewer, said she hasn't
heard from her son recently and wasn't aware of a trip to the Super
Bowl last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about that,'' she said from the door of
her Lakeland home.
</P>
<P>
   Greene said he last spoke to King, a doctoral student at Florida
A&AMP;M University in Tallahassee, a little more than a week ago. The
plan, he said, was for King to go to the Super Bowl and meet Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   He said King hasn't returned from Atlanta and he's spoken with
others who feel sure the 26-year-old was in no way involved with
the murders. King has avoided trouble, he said, and is an
``outstanding'' person.
</P>
<P>
   At Kathleen High School in Lakeland, King is remembered as smart
and sharp, with a theatrical flair. His senior yearbook photo shows
him posed with a blond, circular streak in his hair against a
zebra-striped background. He also sang in the school chorus.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddox, former head football coach at Kathleen, worked with
both Lewis and King during his tenure. King, he said, came from a
troubled home but was well behaved and well liked. He recalled that
Lewis was grouped with a harder crowd when he first joined the
squad but Maddox sat him down and encouraged discipline to
complement his talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all got into little problems but nothing like this,''
Maddox said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is having a hard time adjusting to life in jail, his agent
Roosevelt Barnes said Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes and Lewis' personal attorney, Ron Cherry, visit Lewis
daily at the city jail. They said afternoons and nights are hardest
for the athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very upbeat during the day because he has a lot of
visitors, like his mom and his friends,'' Barnes said. ``But when
it starts getting close to the afternoon, he starts getting mellow
and depressed because he knows his visitors have to go and he'll be
left alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is being held with other inmates at the Atlanta Pretrial
Detention Center, Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his client watched the Super Bowl on television with
friends Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, Lewis' new attorney, Ed Garland, proclaimed
his client's innocence at a news conference packed with media from
around the country: ``He is as innocent as all of you in this room.
Ray Lewis did not shoot, strike or stab anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland said an arrest warrant drawn up by Atlanta homicide
investigators stating Lewis ``repeatedly stabbed Baker and
Lollar,'' is inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very disappointed in the Atlanta Police Department,''
Garland said. ``They have made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland said Lewis was inside the black stretch Lincoln
Navigator limousine that police have said was at the scene of the
killings early Jan. 31. However, Garland said Lewis was trying to
stop the fight and get some of the participants in the car. He said
eight people were in the limousine that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never knew people were killed,'' Garland said. ``He found
that out later in the news.''
</P>
<P>
   Duane Fassett, the driver of the 40-foot-long limousine, would
not talk to reporters Thursday. Police interviewed him for more
than 10 hours Monday.
</P>
<P>
   David B. Irwin, Fassett's attorney in Maryland, would not say
whether Fassett actually saw the stabbing. He declined to give any
details about the incident or the events that followed.
</P>
<P>
   He said Fassett drove on and off for Lewis for about a year and
a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks the world of Ray Lewis. He's very sad about it,''
Irwin said. ``He wishes the whole thing would go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Frankston contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
