<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5907 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-HAIL-ALMIGHTY-DOLLAR-     02-03 1560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIL-ALMIGHTY-DOLLAR-750&AMP;add-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN EUROPE EVER CATCH BOOMING AMERICA?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from Feb. 1 for those needing)   (This pithy ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS AN EDITOR-FRIENDLY 300-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 750. TOTAL
UNCUT IS 1,300 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``f'' financial
news files.)  
  
 By HAMISH MCRAE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can Europe, or indeed Japan and the rest of Asia, ever catch up?
</P>
<P>
   Last week the American boom becomes the longest in the country's
history. It is an interesting statistic for Britons, because we
experienced that particular delight _ our longest boom _ in the
middle of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, hardly anybody noticed. But it is a statistic that raises
fundamental questions about the changing nature of economic
success, as well, of course, as about the durability of the
American boom.
</P>
<P>
   It also, as the euro falls ever lower against the dollar, raises
uncomfortable questions about Europe's future economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The discomfort is all the greater because that is not as it was
meant to be. Put aside the plight of the euro, because at some
stage it will eventually recover, and recall the dismissive
attitude to the U.S. that was prevalent on the Continent for most
of the Nineties.
</P>
<P>
   In the early part of the decade, most Europeans criticized
American business for its lack of dynamism, its failure to invest
enough and its emphasis on price rather than quality.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of the decade, the line of attack shifted to
criticizing American corporate brutality, the ways in which
businesses were bought and sold and the way workers were ``let
go.'' Yes, the U.S. might be becoming more competitive, but it was
at unacceptable social costs.
</P>
<P>
   You still hear the second line of attack now, though it has been
blunted by the success of the U.S. in creating new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   What, one may ask, is more brutal: making people shift jobs
frequently or condemning them to unemployment? But the European
perception now seems to have shifted to one of bewilderment and
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   What on earth are the Americans doing that has enabled them to
be so successful, and surely that success cannot really last? There
seem to me to be three elements to the American success story that
continental Europeans in particular would be wise to note.
</P>
<P>
   Not Britons? Well, yes, we need to note, too, but we are already
something of a halfway house between the Continent and the U.S.,
not just culturally but in the performance of the economy. Ours has
grown more rapidly than any big European economy over the last
eight years, but more slowly than the American.
</P>
<P>
   The first element of U.S. success is that the key difference
between the States and everyone else is not in the quality of its
big businesses but rather in its ability to create new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Look at, say, Procter &AMP; Gamble and Unilever: there is not that
big a difference between them. If, on the other hand, you look at
new businesses, there is a radical difference.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not just that in Europe we create fewer new
businesses, it is also that very few of the ones we do create grow
to be really big, at least on the time-scale of the U.S. We have no
Microsoft, no Intel, no AOL.
</P>
<P>
   The high performance of the U.S. has been driven, more than
anything else, by such hi-tech companies. If you can create a few
of them, they will pull along the rest. Roughly three-quarters of
U.S. growth last year came from sectors of the economy that barely
existed a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   That leads to the second element of U.S. success: the ability to
develop commercial applications for new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans, to generalize, would rather have the kudos of
inventing something than the dosh from applying it. Sadly, it is
the applications that drive economies forward, not the inventions.
</P>
<P>
   Third, the growing importance of the English language. Look
around the world _ virtually all English-speaking economies are
growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the native speakers, though, countries that speak
English well (Sweden, the Netherlands) are storming along, while
those that speak it badly (most notably Japan) are struggling. It
is wholly unfair, but during the Nineties English quite became the
default language for the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   If that is right, what are the lessons? I think that the
non-American world has to accept that the U.S. will remain the
dominant economy for the next 20 years, maybe longer.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the U.S. boom will come to an end, as will ours. But the
forces that created the success story will continue, so when the
U.S. economy recovers it will experience another burst of growth. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (300-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 750) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If that is right, there is a choice for the rest of us. Do we
cooperate or do we compete?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we should try to imitate the reasons for America's
success: create a tax and regulatory climate that encourages
business start-ups and, if we can, a culture that seeks commercial
applications for new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   And for countries that do not speak English, they had better
learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooperate or compete?'' is the great strategic issue and one
that is of particular importance to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The instinct of much of continental Europe is to compete: to
create, in the EU, a counterbalance to American economic power.
Some Europeans are quite explicit about that. For example, the
advocates of the euro seek to create a rival to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   A large section of the British establishment also takes that
line, believing that the best economic option for Britain is to
compete against the U.S., using the much larger European market as
a base. Under that strategy, Britain should try to help Europe to
catch up with the U.S. by trying to teach it Anglo-Saxon ways.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative view is that we should cooperate with the U.S.,
acting, so to speak, as the chief subcontractor for America in the
European time zone.
</P>
<P>
   In practice we already do that, being the chief recipient for
U.S. investment in Europe. During the last year, such a view has
tended to gain ground as the U.S. boom has continued and the
British economy has again outpaced the German and Italian
economies.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of actual GDP at market prices, we will also have
become larger than France, though whether that position will last
will depend on the durability of the present sterling exchange
rate. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF 300-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,300) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, there is one other reason to believe that
America's out-performance will continue, maybe not every year, but
on average through the next two decades. It is demography.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. will gradually become the youngest of the Group of
Seven nations over the next 20 years, while Germany and Italy, with
their very low birth rates, become very old.
</P>
<P>
   Young countries tend to grow faster than old ones, as countries
with a high proportion of retired people have to spend more and
more of their income on supporting the old, instead of investing in
future growth.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is somewhere in between continental Europe and the U.S.
in its demographic profile: our traditional mid-Atlantic status
applies even to demography.
</P>
<P>
   From a UK point of view, therefore, it seems most rational to
celebrate the long American boom and to regard as irrelevant
whether Europe and Japan catch up or not.
</P>
<P>
   If continental Europe does recover a bit of ground vis-a-vis the
U.S., that is great, because as the most U.S.-oriented European
economy, we will be pulled along by that progress.
</P>
<P>
   If it does not, we have plan B: promote our role as
subcontractor to American business, acting as the best entry point
into the European market but also creating intellectual products
that we can sell into the North American one.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the U.S. boom surely conveys one overriding message:
somehow or other we should continue to hitch our wagon to the
American star. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this insightful 1,000-word (trimmed) article from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
