<HEADER>
A5909 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-CREDIT-LOSSES-ART-NYT     02-03 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-LOSSES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONDS' RISE PUTS TRADERS IN TURMOIL
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON and PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chaos swept through the bond market Thursday as traders and
investors tried to make sense of a spectacular and damaging rise in
the prices of longer-term Treasury bonds. Rumors of significant
losses sustained by banks, brokerage firms and hedge funds said to
be on the wrong side of the Treasury market's move roiled the
market, reminding many participants of the crisis created by the
near collapse of the Long-Term Capital Management hedge fund that
gripped the market in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Tripping over themselves to buy 30-year bonds, investors and
traders drove the price of the bonds up an unusual 3 percent early
in the morning. The yield on the bond fell from its Wednesday close
of 6.28 percent to as low as 5.93 percent before settling at 6.13
percent at the end of the day. The yield on the 10-year note fell
from 6.57 percent Wednesday to 6.44 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Market participants were stunned by the action. ``The government
bond market is trading with an extraordinary amount of stress,''
said Tom Juterbock, head of government bond trading at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. ``I can't recall a time when this market
had this much stress. This is without historical precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Bank of New York issued a statement in the
early afternoon denying a rumor that a special emergency meeting
had been called by the Fed to assess the damage caused by the move
in the market. Such a meeting was convened when Long-Term Capital
Management was teetering and resulted in a Fed-assisted bailout of
the hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   But bond traders at banks and brokerage firms across Wall Street
said Thursday that losses were surely large at many institutions
this time around because of the nature of the bets that had been
made by these firms in recent weeks. Once again, as was the case
with Long-Term Capital Management, the majority of bond market
participants are finding themselves all in the same troubling
trades.
</P>
<P>
   The root of the recent trouble is the Treasury's plan to reduce
its issuance of long-term debt and to buy back a good deal of the
debt that is outstanding. Worried about a shortage of Treasury debt
to be traded, investors who need to own high-quality long-term
government securities _ managers of pension funds and insurance
company portfolios who offset their long-term obligations with
assets of similar maturities _ surged into the market.
</P>
<P>
   As these investors scrambled to buy long-term Treasuries,
traders who had sold those securities short faced mounting losses.
Because banks and brokerage firms typically offset the potential
risk in their sizable holdings in mortgages or corporate bonds by
selling government bonds they do not own, a process known as
selling short, the move had punishing effects on firms' positions
up and down Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about possible trading losses, investors pounded the
shares of two Wall Street firms known for their bond trading
operations. Goldman Sachs Group's stock fell 6.3 percent, to
$85.375, one of its biggest one-day declines since the firm went
public in May, while shares in Lehman Brothers Holdings dropped 2.5
percent, to $70.4375.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lehman Brothers said, ``We're not having any
problems as a result of the Treasury market moves.'' A spokeswoman
for Goldman Sachs declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Treasury announced its buyback plan on Jan. 13, the
reality of its effects were not fully recognized by bond traders
until recently. As the meaning of the reduction in supply sank in
among investors, the rush into the bond market began.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Treasury said that it would retire $17 billion
of its debt in the first three months of this year. Most of the
buybacks are to be focused on debt with maturities of 10 years or
more. In addition, the Treasury said its most recent auction of
securities would raise $32 billion, almost 14 percent less than the
$37 billion analysts had been expecting.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Parkhurst, managing director of government bond trading
at Salomon Smith Barney, said that it was troubling that the
Treasury had led the market to believe that the 30-year bond was a
dinosaur and would be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   What traders find particularly maddening about the action in the
market is that many of the trades that are causing the greatest
woes are not especially speculative. In fact, they are fairly
ordinary. It is simply that the Treasury's debt reduction plan has
turned the market on its head.
</P>
<P>
   Although no bank or brokerage firm came forward with reports of
losses, the carnage in the market will most likely push brokerage
firms and banks to reassess their heavy reliance on Treasuries to
hedge their corporate bond or mortgage holdings. The U.S. Treasury
market is the largest and most liquid in the world, but now that
this market will be shrinking, traders will look for new securities
to use as hedging vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, these traders are exiting their troubled short
positions, which are sizable, buying long-term Treasuries to cover
those they had sold short. One trader said a conservative estimate
of the Treasuries sold short is twice the securities available for
trading, indicating that the pain in the bond market could continue
for some time.
</P>
<P>
   A senior executive at a commercial bank said, ``This started
last Friday afternoon and all the trading floors are shaken.'' The
executive added that because no one knew which firms had been hit
the hardest, anxiety levels throughout the market would remain
high.
</P>
<P>
   The rally in bonds has exacerbated an unusual occurrence in the
market: short-term interest rates are considerably higher than
those on long-term securities. That is unusual because investors
are traditionally paid more to hold long-term instruments because
they are taking on more risk than those investors who buy
short-term securities. When short-term yields rise above those of
long-term instruments, Wall Street traders say the yield curve is
inverted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we have changes in the structure of the yield curve,
it has taken about six months for the market to assimilate the
changes,'' said Gemma Wright, senior interest rate strategist at
Aubrey G. Lanston, an investment firm in New York. ``This is not
going to be any different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
