<HEADLINE>
JORDAN LINKS TERRORIST PLOT TO BIN LADEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Jordanian security agents said this week that 13
men imprisoned here on charges of plotting terrorist attacks in
Jordan were trained in Afghan camps operated by Osama bin Laden,
the Saudi fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   The men were arrested in December after Jordanian officials say
they uncovered a plot to blow up a U.S.-owned hotel in Amman and to
machine-gun tourists visiting several popular religious sites.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Jordanian officials said the group's travels to
Afghanistan for training were arranged by Khalil Deek, a
naturalized U.S. citizen of Palestinian descent who is also in
prison in Jordan. One U.S. official said Deek had been acting as a
kind of ``concierge/travel agent'' for the worldwide network
directed by bin Laden, who has been charged with masterminding the
1998 bombings of two U.S. embassies in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Deek, interviewed at a prison on the outskirts of Amman, the
Jordanian capital, insists that he is guilty only of possessing and
copying information about bomb-making that is freely available on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a victim of circumstance,'' Deek said. ``If there is a
fair trial, it will be perfectly clear that there is no evidence to
connect me to planning or committing any act of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The other 13 men have been charged with planning to carry out
the plot, which the authorities say Deek helped organize.
</P>
<P>
   ``We captured these men before they were able to take executive
action, but the attacks they were planning would have been very
serious,'' said a senior Jordanian intelligence officer. ``These
people had done a lot of homework, but we also do our homework.
That is why this country remains a safe environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they found a cache of explosives buried near
a farmhouse outside Amman that was used by several of the jailed
men. They said the explosives were the same type as those used in
the bombings in Africa.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Deek, 41, is from a Palestinian family that fled its home in
what is now Israel in 1948, and was displaced a second time when
Israel captured the West Bank in 1967. Speaking through a wire
partition at the prison where he is being held, he insisted that
his only work in Peshawar, Pakistan, where he was arrested, was
running a small computer business.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man asked me to copy a disk called the Jihad Encyclopedia,
which had information about bombs and many other things,'' he said.
``But I had never met the man before. I think that when he came
back to Jordan, the police found that disk and asked him where he
got it. He gave my name, and that's why I was arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Deek, who moved to California as a young man and became a U.S.
citizen in the 1980s, denied any connection to bin Laden or to any
plans of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't lived in Jordan for years, and I don't know a single
person here other than my own family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Deek's lawyer, Younis Arab, said he views the case as ``dealing
with the possession of information from the Internet, which is
going to be the basis for many criminal cases in the years ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This disk they found may contain terrible things, but it is
available at grocery stores in Peshawar,'' Arab said. ``We have
found more than 1,500 Internet sites that give information about
making explosives. Maybe someone is interested in these things, but
that cannot be considered a crime in itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the arrests six weeks ago, remarkably little has been
reported in Jordan about the case. Some politicians and private
analysts said they doubted that the plot, if it existed, was as
serious as U.S. and Jordanian officials have alleged.
</P>
<P>
   They wondered why terrorists would plot to blow up the Radisson
Hotel in Amman, as is charged, considering the hotel attracts far
fewer guests than other hotels in Amman. As for tourist sites here,
they attract mostly Japanese and European visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is not known to have been a target for serious terrorist
plots in the past, though its friendship with both the United
States and Israel might make it an appealing target to some
militants.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are very quick to jump at any hint of a threat,
because all it takes is one bomb and our tourist business is dead
for a year,'' said Nasser Lozi, a prominent political figure who
held a series of ministerial posts from 1996 until he left the
government in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of tension in the air at the time these people
were arrested,'' Lozi said. ``You had fears coming out of the
millennium celebration, you had the Y2K fears, and you even had a
specific warning from Washington that there were going to be
terrorist attacks. Maybe there was an exaggeration.''
</P>
<P>
   Deek and the 13 other men are to be tried within a few months.
The trial is expected to be open to the public, and the
government's evidence will be displayed there for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   A foreign specialist who is closely monitoring the investigation
said that doubts about the case may stem from the fact that
Jordanian officials, wary of upsetting the tourist trade or
spreading fear at home, have revealed little of what they know.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very sophisticated operation that had gotten to the
stage of detailed planning,'' the specialist said. ``It clearly
could have done serious damage to many people. The effectiveness of
the security service here saved a lot of lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
