<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5913 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-LIGTENBERG04-COX     02-03 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LIGTENBERG04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ligtenberg's elbow rehab on schedule,
 &HT;    but relief ace post premature
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kerry Ligtenberg knows what you want to know, and he
wishes he could tell you.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves reliever is just like everybody else who wonders
when he'll be ready to pitch _ especially with John Rocker facing a
suspension until May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's asking where I'm at and how I feel,'' said
Ligtenberg, who had ligament transplant surgery on his right elbow
in April. ``I don't know what else to tell them, except that I'm
real happy about where I'm at, and in about a month we'll see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg joined the posse of Braves pitchers at ``Camp Leo''
Thursday at Turner Field, throwing 20 pitches off the mound at
about 75 percent effort. It was the third time he has thrown off
the mound since he resumed such throwing last week. He is scheduled
to see Dr. James Andrews in Birmingham, Ala., next week and hopes
to face hitters in spring training next month.
</P>
<P>
   How soon he'll be ready to pitch this season is another
question, and nobody knows the answer. Recovering from such surgery
is projected to take 12 to 18 months, but the time frame that
applies to Ligtenberg is not known yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going with the approach that there's no need to rush it,
and I tend to agree with that,'' he said. ``It doesn't hurt, which
is one of the best things about it. I have no pain whatsoever. I've
been doing a lot of long-tossing so my shoulder feels strong, my
elbow feels strong, but it's still not the same thing as throwing
to live hitters. ... If it feels bad, take a day off, but so far I
haven't had any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Ligtenberg was about to begin his second year as the
Braves' closer, as Mark Wohlers continued to have control problems.
Rocker was still an untested young arm. Then Ligtenberg suffered a
torn medial collateral ligament in his right elbow in a spring
training game.
</P>
<P>
   While he could be the ideal choice to replace Rocker as closer,
Ligtenberg isn't going to put extra pressure on himself to make it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a sense of urgency,'' said Ligtenberg,
who had 30 saves in 34 chances in 1998, his rookie season. ``If I
don't come back right away, I'm sure they'll find somebody to do
it. I feel like I can come back and really help this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg said he would have approached the season the same,
even if Rocker were available from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the approach that I was going to come in and do what
I've done in the past, and whatever role I end up in, that's the
role I end up in,'' Ligtenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   As different as the two pitchers are in temperament and
demeanor, they both are learning a little about restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm ready right now,'' Ligtenberg said. ``I want
them to let me push it just to see. I'm starting to lose patience.
... I've waited a whole year, now I just have to wait a little bit
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg said he's in the best shape he's ever been in, body
and arm. Meanwhile, he has taken some advice from former Braves
reliever Alan Embree, who underwent the same type of surgery in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Embree ``told me, when he came back, the toughest thing was he
didn't know what kind of velocity he would have or what was going
to happen until he faced hitters,'' Ligtenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said once you throw a fastball by a hitter, then it's like
you know everything came back,'' Ligtenberg said. ``He said there
will be days where you don't feel that good and you have to get
through it. ...When I get out there, I think it's going to be more
fun than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was a step in that direction, as it was for fellow
reliever Rudy Seanez. Seanez said he is fully recovered from a
stress fracture in his elbow and from bone-spur surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm used to get sore (during offseason workouts), and they
told me it had a lot to do with the bone spur,'' Seanez said. ``My
arm was sore only once this offseason. Now I just have to be
careful that, since I'm feeling so good, I don't push it too hard
too soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Each threw five-minute sessions off the mound and played
long-toss in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see him and Rudy out there,'' pitching coach Leo
Mazzone said. ``It was great to see life on their pitches while
being effortless. That's huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
