<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5914 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-BUSH-WHACKED-NH-RESEN     02-03 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-WHACKED-NH-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSHWHACKED: MCCAIN'S STUNNING WIN EXPOSES BUSH WEAKNESSES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors)   (RESENDING from Feb. 2 for those needing)  
  
 (This timely 1,000-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ A triumphant Senator John McCain stormed back on
to the presidential campaign trail Wednesday after inflicting a
crushing defeat on the Governor of Texas, George W. Bush, in
Tuesday's New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   His 18-point victory over the out and out front-runner for the
Republican Party's nomination burst the race wide open and made
Bush look vulnerable for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   After celebrating his victory at his New Hampshire headquarters,
McCain flew direct to South Carolina where more than 800 supporters
held an impromptu victory rally in his honor at 2:00 in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina primary, which takes place on Feb. 19, is
seen as the next crucial test for McCain. A conservative state,
with a strong record of support for George W. Bush's father, former
President George Bush, South Carolina is a state in which McCain
must do well if he is to have a chance of taking his campaign
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire Wednesday, McCain's victory was compared to
that of Ronald Reagan in 1980, whose trouncing of the establishment
favorite and victor in Iowa, George Bush, Sr., became the
springboard for his successful national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Voters, said the local Concord paper Wednesday, had ``rushed to
Reagan like iron filings to a magnet'' in the final week of the New
Hampshire campaign, and McCain had drawn people in much the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   After his win, McCain alluded to the straight-talking
meet-the-people strategy that had brought him such success,
greeting cheering fans: ``Welcome to my 115th town meeting. We
finally have a poll without a margin of error.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator from Arizona had held 114 question-and-answer
meetings in six months of campaigning in New Hampshire, and it was
reckoned that one in four voters had seen him in person by election
day.
</P>
<P>
   He had held his final such meeting on Sunday, in the town of
Peterborough, where he also held his first, attracting more than
1,000 people, in contrast to the 40 who had turned up in the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   In his victory speech, he paid tribute to the reception he had
received from New Hampshire's famously independent voters, and
hammered away at the theme he placed at the center of his campaign:
``The Washington iron triangle of money, lobbyists and legislation,
which for so long has put special interests above the national
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Sniping at the current administration _ and his possible
opponent further down the line _ he said it was ``the beginning of
the end for the truth-twisting politics of Bill Clinton and Al
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain concluded with this rallying cry: ``Our wonderful New
Hampshire campaign has come to an end. The great national crusade
has just begun.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, gave a gracious concession speech, looking
forward to victory in South Carolina and beyond. While giving
credit to McCain's strong campaign, he explained his defeat also by
the shorter time he had spent in New Hampshire _ partly because he,
unlike McCain, contested the Iowa caucuses _ and the singularity of
the state of New Hampshire and its voters.
</P>
<P>
   The implication was that the qualities that had won New
Hampshire for McCain would not translate onto the national stage.
</P>
<P>
   This argument, however, disregards the strong record of New
Hampshire in giving future winners their first unexpected break.
And, as with Ronald Reagan's win here, it was not only the size of
McCain's win that confounded all forecasts, but its shape.
</P>
<P>
   Establishment Republicans who were expected to follow the party
line and vote for George Bush were split evenly between the two.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also attracted the bulk of independent votes, many of the
notoriously fickle under-30 voters, and even some Democrats who
switched party allegiance to vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   The youth vote for McCain _ as for the Democratic challenger,
Bill Bradley _ was particularly striking, given the recent
handwringing in political circles about the apathy and cynicism of
the young people towards all things and people political.
</P>
<P>
   They attended his rallies in force, listened intently to his
forceful and unscripted answers and cheered him to the rafters,
emerging with the joyful judgment that ``he would make a great
president, someone I could respect.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's personal history as a military hero and Vietnamese
prisoner of war, his readiness to take on the all-powerful
Washington establishment and the great and the good of the
Republican Party all contributed to his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the directness, frankness and transparent
truthfulness of his responses that came as such a refreshing change
for the voters and took New Hampshire by storm.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters admitted that they disagreed with some of his
positions, against abortion, for instance, but their confidence in
him personally outweighed such misgivings. In a national climate
where voters are jaded, these qualities could prove transferable.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside McCain, Bush came across as charming, but weak and
immature. New Hampshirites can pass on the charm, but they admire
character, and they found Bush wanting.
</P>
<P>
   His spontaneity was limited to hand-shaking; his speeches were
multiple variations on his original declaration speech from the
early summer.
</P>
<P>
   And the Texan just failed to connect _ a problem that also
afflicted his father, whose family estate at Kennebunkport is only
just over the border in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of George Bush, Sr. to campaign for his son over the
final weekend only underlined to many the aspects of George W. Bush
that New Hampshire least likes: his money and his establishment
lineage.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will not be able to count on similar disaffection with
the party establishment elsewhere in the country. Money and
organization count, and Bush has them in spades. But they may not
count for everything.
</P>
<P>
   The next two weeks will show whether McCain's New Hampshire
victory will remain, as he stated Wednesday, ``the greatest moment
of my political career,'' or whether there is more to come. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 1,000-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
