<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5919 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-SEC-ANALYSIS04-CO     02-03 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-ANALYSIS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC signee analysis
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA
</P>
<P>
   The defending conference champions appear to have helped
themselves in every area and could be poised to make a run at the
national championship. The Tide signed three blue-chip defensive
linemen from Alabama schools _ Mac Tyler of Bessemer, Anthony
Bryant of Newbern and Antwan Odom of Bayou La Batre. Thirteen of 26
signees are offensive or defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ARKANSAS
</P>
<P>
   Coach Houston Nutt continues to bring in solid classes, the
latest headed by cornerback Lawrence Richardson of Galveston,
Texas. Defensive end Jason Peters of Queen City, Texas, is another
talented player, along with cornerback Bo Mosely from Osceola, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   AUBURN
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers did exceptionally well, signing 10 athletes and
helping themselves at every position. Running back Rudi Johnson
from Butler Community College in Kansas and defensive end Alton
Moore from Southwest Mississippi are among the best in the nation.
Running back Ronnie Brown from Cartersville and quarterback Jason
Campbell of Taylorsville, Miss., could make an immediate impact.
Former Georgia player Daniel Cobb gives the Tigers great depth at
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   Steve Spurrier seemed to get everything on his list. The
nation's No. 1-rated quarterback, Brock Berlin, already is in
school. The Gators beat several other schools for four key players
_ offensive linemen Jonathan Colon and Max Starks, receiver Kelvin
Kight of Lithonia and safety Tre Orr. The class was rated anywhere
from first to third by several recruiting publications.
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY
</P>
<P>
   Offensive lineman Antonio Hall from Canton, Ohio, is rated the
No. 1 prospect in the nation. Defensive tackle Jeremy Caudill from
Prestonsburg, Ky., is an elite player, as is safety Antwoine Lias
of Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   LSU
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers, with new coach Nick Saban, made a remarkable
recovery after a slow start. Heading the class of 25 signees are
defensive tackle John Paul Jones from Carencro, La., running back
Derron Parquet from Metairie, La., offensive lineman Kade Comeaux
from Crowley, La., and safety Adrian Mayes from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI
</P>
<P>
   The Rebels started out fast and finished slow, but took a medium
step toward regaining respectability. Offensive lineman Doug
Buckles from Madison, Miss., is an excellent player, and Jason
Youngs, a junior college All-American from College of the Canyons
in Santa Cerrida, Calif., is outstanding. Cornerback Tavarus Horne
from Hattiesburg, Miss., is probably the best of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   MISS. STATE
</P>
<P>
   Just the opposite of Mississippi, the Bulldogs started slowly
and finished with a rush. Four excellent players committed to
Jackie Sherrill _ wide receiver Antonio Hargro of Gautier, Miss.,
defensive end Demotto Youngblood from Hargraves Military, safety
Jonathan Bell from Tupelo, Miss., and cornerback Bryan Shumaker
from Ackerman, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   Coach Lou Holtz has found recruiting to be a little tougher in
Columbia than it was in South Bend. Mitchell-Baker quarterback
Dondrial Pinkins signed with the Gamecocks, and the team might have
found a pair of sleepers in cornerback Gorzie Gray from Waldorf,
Md., and quarterback Rodriques Wilson from Cross, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   The Vols have one of the top recruiting classes in the nation.
O.J. Owens of New London, N.C., is one of the top safeties in the
country. Quarterbacks Casey Clausen and John Rattay and receiver
Rashad Baker are highly rated players at their positions. The top
offensive lineman is 6-foot-7, 285-pound Michael Munoz of
Cincinnati, son of NFL Hall of Famer Anthony Munoz.
</P>
<P>
   VANDERBILT
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to put a tag on the Commodores' class because
academic requirements force them to go for a different breed of
scholar-athlete. Safety Chris Young from Batesville, Miss., and
linebacker Pat Brunner from Cincinnati are solid players, but the
other 13 prospects remain prospects for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
