Hampshire in giving future winners their first unexpected break.
And, as with Ronald Reagan's win here, it was not only the size of
McCain's win that confounded all forecasts, but its shape.
</P>
<P>
   Establishment Republicans who were expected to follow the party
line and vote for George Bush were split evenly between the two.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also attracted the bulk of independent votes, many of the
notoriously fickle under-30 voters, and even some Democrats who
switched party allegiance to vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   The youth vote for McCain _ as for the Democratic challenger,
Bill Bradley _ was particularly striking, given the recent
handwringing in political circles about the apathy and cynicism of
the young people towards all things and people political.
</P>
<P>
   They attended his rallies in force, listened intently to his
forceful and unscripted answers and cheered him to the rafters,
emerging with the joyful judgment that ``he would make a great
president, someone I could respect.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's personal history as a military hero and Vietnamese
prisoner of war, his readiness to take on the all-powerful
Washington establishment and the great and the good of the
Republican Party all contributed to his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the directness, frankness and transparent
truthfulness of his responses that came as such a refreshing change
for the voters and took New Hampshire by storm.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters admitted that they disagreed with some of his
positions, against abortion, for instance, but their confidence in
him personally outweighed such misgivings. In a national climate
where voters are jaded, these qualities could prove transferable.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside McCain, Bush came across as charming, but weak and
immature. New Hampshirites can pass on the charm, but they admire
character, and they found Bush wanting.
</P>
<P>
   His spontaneity was limited to hand-shaking; his speeches were
multiple variations on his original declaration speech from the
early summer.
</P>
<P>
   And the Texan just failed to connect _ a problem that also
afflicted his father, whose family estate at Kennebunkport is only
just over the border in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of George Bush, Sr. to campaign for his son over the
final weekend only underlined to many the aspects of George W. Bush
that New Hampshire least likes: his money and his establishment
lineage.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will not be able to count on similar disaffection with
the party establishment elsewhere in the country. Money and
organization count, and Bush has them in spades. But they may not
count for everything.
</P>
<P>
   The next two weeks will show whether McCain's New Hampshire
victory will remain, as he stated Wednesday, ``the greatest moment
of my political career,'' or whether there is more to come. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
