<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5923 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-ACC-ANALYSIS04-CO     02-03 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ACC-ANALYSIS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACC signee analysis
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   CLEMSON
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers appear to have strengthened their offense, with nine
offensive signees. The top recruits include tight end Todd
McClinton, wide receiver Derrick Hamilton, and running back Keith
Kelly, all from South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   DUKE
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils signed 21 players, but the one with the most
name-recognition is receiver Jeremy Battier, the younger brother of
Duke basketball player Shane Battier. Offensive lineman Patrick
Worsham of Daytona Beach, Fla., and tight end Reggie Love of
Charlotte have impressive credentials.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA STATE
</P>
<P>
   Another strong Seminoles class. Two top-rated defensive backs,
cornerback Bryant McFadden of Hollywood, Fla., and strong safety
Yohance Buchanan of Douglass High, and linebackers Eric Moore of
Pahokee, Fla., and Michael Boulware, brother of former Seminole and
current Baltimore Ravens linebacker Peter Boulware, enter the
program, along with receiver Javon Walker of Jones County Junior
College in Mississippi and talented offensive lineman Alex Barron
from Orangeburg, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ron Vanderlinden had an impressive recruiting effort.
Chris Kelley of Germantown, Md., was rated by some as one of the
top 10 passers. Hampton (Va.) High receiver Maurice Shanks should
add some firepower.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   The recruiting class was headed by two in-state gems _
quarterback Aaron Alston of Durham and defensive end Clarence Gaddy
of Lillington. Brandon Russell of Marist, and Andre Williams of
Durham are talented running backs.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. STATE
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack fell behind in the recruiting race after coach
Chuck Amato was hired more than one month after the firing of
former coach Mike O'Cain. The class is topped by 6-foot-5
quarterback Phillips Rivers of Athens, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA
</P>
<P>
   Coach George Welsh and his staff bring in another solid class.
Linebacker Ray Mann from Hampton High and running back Art Thomas
of Fork Union Military Academy, both Virginia schools, are touted
players at their positions. Running back Marquis Weeks from Berwyn,
Pa., might be a sleeper.
</P>
<P>
   WAKE FOREST
</P>
<P>
   The Deacons didn't do well. The top two signees are running back
Fred Staton of Charlotte and defensive end R.D. Montgomery of
Wilmington, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
