 (PLEASE NOTE: This editorial has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``p'' political
news files.)  
  
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The self-frustrating attempts of Tony Blair's government to
foist its favored candidates upon unwilling party members in Wales,
and London, have made us familiar with the dynamics that helped to
determine the outcome of America's New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Their status as crown princes waiting for coronation is surely
one reason why Republican and Democratic voters in the ``granite
state'' failed to give George W. Bush and Al Gore the ecstatic
support they may once have expected in the opening round of this
year's presidential primaries. But the natural desire to kick over
the traces tells only part of the story.
</P>
<P>
   A virtue of the primary system is that it forces would-be
candidates to face ``real'' voters, not just party hacks and those
with strong affiliations to a cause or a movement.
</P>
<P>
   That is particularly important at a time when there is a
practical consensus on most of the main issues of the day, so that
the character of the candidates comes to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   Take the contest among the Democrats first. A few months ago, as
vice president in an administration that was presiding over a
period of unparalleled national prosperity, Gore was the
unchallenged heir apparent to President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But when the former New Jersey senator and one-time star
basketball player Bill Bradley entered the lists under the flag of
reform, Gore found his opinion poll ratings sagging badly.
</P>
<P>
   His response _ to move his election headquarters from Washington
to his home state of Tennessee and to start wearing cowboy boots
and shouting a lot _ may seem a little obvious to worldly-wise
British eyes, but it seems to have done him a lot of good.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore once planned to see off his rival's challenge early in
the season, thus sparing his party much expenditure in dollars and
bad blood, New Hampshire will have disappointed him.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's 47 percent of the vote is enough to encourage him to
carry his challenge forward, and he has already raised nearly as
much campaigning money as the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore may have failed to score the clean knockout he
desired, on the Republican side Bush was battered badly by his
challenger, Senator John McCain, who took five votes for every
three that went to Bush. (The remaining three Republican hopefuls,
who shared 14 percent of the vote between them, would be well
advised to abandon all hope for this year's nomination.)
</P>
<P>
   As Bush's main claim to the nomination was the huge popular lead
he held in early polling, it was a particularly bad result for him.
The debates so far have shown that there is strangely little of
substance in his thought, beyond a blatant appeal to religious
fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   His sole remaining advantage is the $69 million war chest he has
amassed, which will be crucial in paying for TV advertising in the
big states, where person-to-person campaigning is fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Senator McCain, by ironic contrast, has made so much of his
desire to take the influence of big money out of politics, that he
may have a hard time raising the funds he will need to compete in
the remaining primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, if he does well on Feb. 19 in South Carolina (a
Southern state proclaimed ``Bush country'' by Bush himself), we may
yet see one of the great political upsets.
</P>
<P>
   We would not be unhappy to see the crumpling of that cardboard
figure. And a presidential race that pits a crusading outsider
against a veteran Washington insider such as Gore could present the
American voter with a genuine choice this November. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
