<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-ANALYSIS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite losses, a solid haul for Dogs
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ College football coaches don't announce that they
had a bad recruiting class. But Georgia coach Jim Donnan came close
to such an admission when he spoke about the Bulldogs' latest group
of recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a bad recruiting year from the standpoint that we
didn't get the players in the state that we went after,'' Donnan
said. ``But we got enough players when you look at some of the
out-of-state guys we were able to pick up. And a lot of the players
that we lost were at positions where maybe we could afford to lose
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Donnan was probably a little hard on himself and his
staff. Granted, the Bulldogs didn't rack up the majority of the top
players in the state, as they have the previous two seasons. But
they did bring in a solid group of 18 prospects, eight to 10 of
whom have a realistic chance of contributing immediately.
</P>
<P>
   _ Strengths: Georgia's 2000 class has two major strengths: It
helps to address some immediate needs, and it is solid
academically.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs needed quarterbacks and defensive backs and they
got three and four, respectively. They also needed to boost their
potential at running back, which they did by signing a pair of high
school All-Americans, and to gain depth in the defensive line,
which they did with four players there.
</P>
<P>
   As of signing day, Georgia had only three signees who had not
met entrance requirements, and it expects that number to decrease _
perhaps to zero _ by August.
</P>
<P>
   _ Weaknessess: The Bulldogs did not sign a single offensive
lineman, they signed only two linebackers, and they didn't get the
blockbuster defensive lineman, linebacker or defensive back they
were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   With 16 offensive linemen on scholarship next year, Georgia
didn't make that position a priority. Instead, the Bulldogs
concentrated on recruiting the best players around.
</P>
<P>
   _ One that got away: Losing offensive lineman Sean Young to
Tennessee is difficult to understand. The 6-foot-8, 295-pound high
school All-American is the younger brother of Chad Young, a rising
sophomore lineman at Georgia. The boys' parents were outspoken that
Sean should join his brother in Athens and were clear in their
disdain for the Bulldogs' rivals to the north. Even so, Young chose
to sign with the Vols.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was concerned he wouldn't get a whole lot of playing time
here,'' Donnan said. ``He knows a lot about our program, and he
knows we have 16 linemen on scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Can't miss: Both of Georgia's running backs are good ones.
Albert Hollis II of Sacramento, Calif., was a consensus high school
All-American and is one of the fastest prospects in the country.
Musa Smith of Elliottsburg, Pa., is a big, strong back who averaged
more than 9 yards a carry and scored 31 touchdowns as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sleeper(s): Three to watch out for are quarterback David
Greene, defensive lineman Johnathan Sullivan and defensive end
Arnold Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA SIGNEES
</P>
