<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Ye Profit, So Shall Ye Pay &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the number of Americans who own stock has reached record
levels, capital gains have grown as a share of all income, but
dividends have not. Tax policy is a major factor for these events.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, just before the long bull market began, capital gains
were reported by 11.4 percent of taxpayers. But that share grew to
16.1 percent of taxpayers by 1997, according to data released
recently by the Internal Revenue Service. (Capital gains are
reported only when stocks and other capital assets are sold.)
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the share of income attributable to capital
gains has also rose. In 1997, capital gains accounted for 7.4
percent of adjusted gross income _ the last figure on the front
page of a Form 1040 tax return _ up from 2.4 percent in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   During that period, companies increasingly held down the growth
of dividends, with many paying none at all, partly to save cash for
expansion. Dividends in 1997 equaled about 1.6 percent of the value
of large stocks, down from 4.5 percent in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   That lower distribution rate explains how dividends accounted
for just 2.4 percent of adjusted gross incomes, according to tax
return data, the same share as in 1980, despite the growth in stock
ownership. Half of all American households now own equities.
</P>
<P>
   Federal tax law discourages dividends in two ways.
</P>
<P>
   First, dividends are taxed twice, because they are paid out of
after-tax corporate earnings and then must be reported as taxable
income by individuals. And dividends are taxed at ordinary income
rates, which can be as high as 39.6 percent, while long-term
capital gains are taxed at no more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _David Cay Johnston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cupid at the Water Cooler &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The workplace can indeed be cozy. At some point in their
careers, 59 percent of workers have had an office romance,
according to a recent survey of 1,118 people by Vault.com, an
online career information site.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four percent said they had not indulged in a romantic
relationship at work, nor did they care to. The remaining 17
percent said they had never dated a co-worker, but they expressed a
willingness to do so if the opportunity arose.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, an office romance, like any other, can end
badly. Even so, 76 percent of those surveyed said that finding love
at work was worth the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' was the feedback from one worker who obviously
had taken the chance. ``Where else can you meet so many people?
We're heading for our 25th wedding anniversary.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Valentine's Day conjures up images of a candlelight dinner
with a special someone, research from American Greetings and the
International Mass Retailers Association shows that more than 80
percent of all valentine cards bought this year will be given to
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Men will spend more on gifts and cards than women _ $100, on
average, compared with $60. The men are more likely to spend the
money on significant others, the research found, while women will
spread their money around, also including gifts for children,
grandchildren and parents.
</P>
<P>
   More than one billion valentines will be exchanged in the United
States this year, American Greetings predicts, making Valentine's
Day the second most popular occasion for holiday greeting cards,
after Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
