<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN INTERVIEWS, FEW VOTERS SHARE CANDIDATES' PASSIONS ON ABORTION
ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ill., Wis.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 37 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich _ Solidly in the Republican camp, Tom Miller
rattled off the issues most important to him: taxes, the economy,
health care.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion was nowhere near the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I just put that one aside,'' said Miller, a 36-year-old
engineer, waving a hand in the air, as if to dismiss a troublesome
topic. ``The politicians talk a lot about abortion, but it's not
something that's going to decide my vote.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the passionate debate over abortion among presidential
candidates, interviews with more than 50 voters in Michigan,
Illinois and Wisconsin found that it was the rare voter who saw the
issue as pivotal.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about abortion evoked a welter of complicated feelings
that left many people uneasy about even discussing it, preferring
instead to focus on tax policy, or the trustworthiness of
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Manning, a 46-year-old corporate manager in Naperville,
Ill., who is the bishop of his Mormon ward, said that while he held
``strong personal views about abortion,'' he preferred that the
issue remain outside the political debate. It was a position he
said was common among his Republican acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I run with a pretty conservative group of people,'' Manning
said, ``and I don't think they're basing their votes on abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a core of deeply committed voters see abortion as
the overriding issue in American politics. Patricia Gantz, 59, who
lives in Dewitt, Mich., said she wanted to see abortion ``outlawed
in all cases,'' and could not fathom casting a ballot for a
candidate who supported a woman's right to choose abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But a far greater number of voters, including those on both
sides of the abortion debate, said it was just one of many issues
to be considered. Moreover, voters expressed a skepticism about the
hard-line statements against abortion by some candidates,
particularly Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, saying they could be
merely an effort to win ardently conservative voters in the
Republican primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a big share of voters said they did not believe it was
likely that any president could overturn laws that protect abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Heinke Hoenck, a retired secretary in
Janesville, Wis., said she could vote for Bush in the fall, even
though she disagreed with his opposition to the Roe vs. Wade
decision by the Supreme Court in 1973 that gave constitutional
protection to abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came right down to it, there would be an uproar in
this country'' if abortion were made illegal, Hoenck said. ``It
would be very hard for a president to change the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Harvey, a 38-year-old engineer in Chicago, expressed a
similar view, saying that government would ultimately find it
impossible to stop abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very religious, and I do not believe in abortion,'' Harvey
said. ``But to me, all this talk about abortion is beside the
point. If people want to have abortions, they're going to have
them.''
</P>
<P>
   President Ronald Reagan consistently sided with forces opposed
to legal abortion, Harvey noted, but failed during his two terms as
president to make it illegal.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was also voiced by strong opponents of abortion,
like Herb Dowman, a 37-year-old environmental engineer in Dewitt,
Mich. ``I'm going to vote for an anti-abortion candidate,'' he
said, ``but I don't expect anything to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Smith, a 41-year-old secretary for an insurance company
in Fort Atkinson, Wis., said that while she opposed the late-term
procedure that opponents call partial-birth abortion, she favored
keeping abortions legal in the early term.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, when she talked about the issues that would
determine her vote, Smith mentioned taxes and help for farmers,
among other things. Abortion was simply ``not that high on the
list,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to look at the total package,'' Smith said. ``One issue
is not going to decide my vote. There are too many important things
to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Liz Schweitzer, an administrator at St. John's Student Parish in
East Lansing, a center for Roman Catholic college students, said
abortion did not dominate the political discussion, even among
people who tried to adhere to church teachings on government
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abortion gets a lot of press, but it is just one of the church
teachings on life and social justice issues,'' Schweitzer said,
noting that Catholic leaders, while opposing abortion, also
espoused many positions that seemed at odds with Republican
politicians, like greater help for immigrants and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan, which holds a primary in March, has demonstrated a
penchant for surprise. The state's Democratic voters, for example,
have in the past supported George C. Wallace and the Rev. Jesse
Jackson in primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The willingness of many voters to support candidates regardless
of their views on abortion concerns Marie Jones, a 32-year-old
research scientist at Michigan State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worries me that maybe they could make it illegal,'' Jones
said, noting that many states had enacted restrictions on abortion,
like 24-hour waiting periods and requirements for parental
notification.
</P>
<P>
   The same concern was voiced by Laurie Stephens, a 26-year-old
factory worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they say they're going to outlaw abortion, maybe we ought
to take it seriously,'' Stephens said as she walked down a
department-store aisle with her 4-year-old daughter, Kristin.
``What if it goes through, and we're back to illegal abortions?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
