A5940 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH04-COX     02-03 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush vows to battle McCain for S.C. military votes
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUMTER, S.C. _ With new polls showing George W. Bush tied _ or
even behind _ Arizona Sen. John McCain in this crucial primary
state, Bush on Thursday made it clear that he will fight for a
critical voting bloc that has a natural affinity for his war hero
rival: veterans.
</P>
<P>
   The votes of military men and women, veterans, and their
families will be crucial in the Feb. 19 primary. Almost one in 10
residents are veterans, and there are three major military
installations here.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' efforts to woo them are likely to intensify in a
race that is suddenly extremely close. Late last month, Bush had a
51 percent to 29 percent lead over McCain, whom he led by 33 points
in December and 47 points in November. But polls released today,
the first since McCain's 19-point New Hampshire victory, tell a
different story: One shows McCain with a slight lead, while another
indicates that the two candidates are virtually tied.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina GOP Chairman Henry McMaster, who has not endorsed
either candidate, said he expected McCain's poll numbers to rise,
``but I don't know if anybody expected this.'' The new polls also
compounded the jitters that began among Bush supporters after his
New Hampshire loss. While many of those Bush backers noted that the
Texas governor still leads in money and organizational support,
they said he needs to change his campaign tactics to deal with
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, who dropped out of the presidential
race in July and endorsed Bush, said the governor must be more
critical of McCain. ``Bush is going to have to get up and fight,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, who has not endorsed a
candidate, said Bush needs ``to bone up on a tremendous number of
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire GOP Chairman Steve Duprey said Bush ``was
overhandled and overscripted.''
</P>
<P>
   One Republican strategist said phone lines have been buzzing as
key Bush financial backers, angry about the New Hampshire defeat,
try to figure out what went wrong. ``Oh, they're puckered up,'' the
strategist said, adding that Bush needs to ``throw away the cue
cards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The contrast of MccCain standing in front of a crowd with a
mike and Bush standing in front of a podium with white guys behind
him, that needs to change,'' the GOP strategist said.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates, however, dismissed the numbers, with Bush saying
``the prop-wash of defeat is going to be around a while.'' McCain,
saying ``the polls will bounce up and down,'' seemed more serious
about the prospect of leading the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am fully prepared to be commander in chief,'' McCain, a
former Navy pilot and Vietnam prisoner of war, told an audience
outside a waterfront home in Beaufort. ``I do not need on-the-job
training.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning veterans' votes from McCain, a bonafide war hero, won't
be easy for Bush, who served stateside in the Texas Air National
Guard during Vietnam. But he's determined to try. Bush has matched
McCain by appointing a ``veteran chairman'' in every one of South
Carolina's 46 counties. Both candidates have promised to raise
active duty pay. McCain says he'll improve education and health
benefits for veterans, while Bush promised Thursday to speed their
claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The burden of proof should not be on those who've worn the
uniforms. The burden of proof must be on the bureaucracy,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Currey was one of the veterans who stood behind Bush on
the steps of the courthouse here. Currey said he's impressed by the
heroism of McCain, who spent five and a half years in the infamous
Hanoi Hilton. After all, Currey knows what heroism is all about _
he earned the Medal of Honor for taking out four German tanks in
Belgium during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But Currey, who was courted by both campaigns, said he's backing
Bush because he has been a chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a broken pipe in your basement, and there were two
guys who said they could fix it, one who wasn't in the military but
was a good plumber, and the other who had a great military record
but didn't know anything about plumbing, who would you pick?''
Currey said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Vietnam and Gulf War Veterans Coalition and the
Coalition of Retired Military Benefits, which is based in Sumter,
also endorsed Bush on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Burch Jr., chairman of the National Vietnam and Gulf War
Veterans Coalition, said of McCain: ``He came home and forgot us.''
Afterward, Burch said the senator hadn't supported his group's
efforts on Agent Orange, Gulf War Syndrome and support for families
of soldiers missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   McCain fired back that some other veterans' groups have backed
him and given him their highest awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have I fooled the veterans' organizations, or is there a
little foolishness going on here?'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, McMaster said, issues take a back seat to personal
history when it comes to McCain and veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others appeal to them on issues. McCain appeals to them on
brotherhood, camaraderie and shared experiences,'' McMaster said.
</P>
<P>
   This article contains material from Jena Heath of the Austin
American-Statesman Washington staff and The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
