<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURF04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Makers of faux turf to square off in court
 &HT;    By Andrea Ball
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ They can't agree on whose grass is greener. Or
softer. Or safer.
</P>
<P>
   And now the maker of AstroTurf, pummeled by a Canadian
competitor's accusations of unfair trade practices, is swinging
back with a lawsuit of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's allowed their one cheap shot at the market
leader,'' said Reed Seaton, president of Southwest Recreational
Industries in Leander. ``They've had theirs. This time, we're
standing firm.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 19-page federal lawsuit filed in Austin, Southwest accuses
its smaller rival, Montreal-based FieldTurf Inc., of unfairly
wielding a high-tech weapon: the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   FieldTurf is improperly using the AstroTurf trademark to attract
visitors to its Web site, the lawsuit claims. Search engines given
the word ``AstroTurf'' will link Web surfers to FieldTurf's site,
where they are met with an AstroTurf smear campaign, Seaton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the classic bait-and-switch,'' he said. ``It's, `Don't
look at our product. Look how bad their product is.'''
</P>
<P>
   FieldTurf attorney Arthur Beeman would not comment on the
details of the lawsuit. ``I'm not going to respond to allegations
in a public forum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest's lawsuit accuses FieldTurf of trademark infringement,
unfair competition and commercial disparagement and defamation.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks to bar FieldTurf from using the AstroTurf
name, in addition to seeking an unspecified amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies make synthetic fields for sports and other
recreational activities.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest, the world's largest manufacturer of turf and running
tracks, employs about 500 people at its Leander facility and last
year generated $150 million in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   FieldTurf earned $19 million during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest's lawsuit, filed last week, isn't the first time the
competitors have faced off in court.
</P>
<P>
   FieldTurf sued Southwest in 1998, claiming the Leander company
copied its design for an artificial turf FieldTurf claims offers
improved drainage, better traction and a more natural feel. The
parties settled last spring in a confidential agreement.
</P>
<P>
   FieldTurf resumed the battle last month, filing a lawsuit in
Kentucky that accused Southwest of maintaining a monopoly through
patent infringement and predatory pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to comment on the specific allegations, but the
lawsuit filed in Austin was clearly a reaction to the lawsuit we
filed in Lexington, Ky., and it's clearly retaliatory,'' said
Beeman, FieldTurf's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest denied it is trying to mow down the competition,
calling the suit a ploy to generate media attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically harassment by publicity,'' Seaton said.
</P>
<P>
   AstroTurf, the first artificial playing field surface, was
created more than 30 years ago after studies showed urban children
were in poorer physical condition than rural children. Monsanto Co.
developed a soft, cheap playing surface that could transform urban
rooftops and asphalt lots into playing fields.
</P>
<P>
   Artificial turf came to professional sports in 1966 when it was
used to carpet the Astrodome, inspiring the AstroTurf brand name.
Southwest, which entered the artificial turf business in 1989,
bought AstroTurf Industries Inc. in 1994 for $9.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
