<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-ANALYSIS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Immediate help on the way for Georgia Tech
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech's diverse recruiting haul of 22 players _
plus holdover DL Jamey Hamilton from last season _ could produce
some immediate dividends, especially on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in are three outstanding linebackers, two quality
quarterbacks, six linemen, two fullback/H-backs, three defensive
backs, three wide receiver/athletes and a big, fast tailback.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis throughout the class is on speed and athleticism.
The Yellow Jackets have it in virtually every area of need.
</P>
<P>
   _ Strengths: The linebacker trio of Hobie Holiday, Daryl Smith
and Keyaron Fox joins outside linebacker Recardo Wimbush, who led
the team in tackles last season as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss of middle linebacker Matt Uremovich to a
career-ending neck injury, immediate help will be needed in support
of Ross Mitchell, especially if Matt Miller does not fully recover
from a knee injury that sidelined him all of last season.
</P>
<P>
   In the secondary, Jonathan Cox and Tony Hollings bring
man-to-man coverage skills that Tech lacked a year ago. Up front,
Reggie Koon (6 feet 4, 275 pounds) will be hard to keep off the
field, while Alfred Malone (6-4, 240) and Chirod Williams (6-4,
235), have been clocked in the 40-yard dash in 4.8 and 4.7 seconds,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, although Tech already had nine running backs
currently on scholarship, Jimmy Dixon (6-2, 210) should be a factor
early. Linemen Jeremy Phillips (6-7, 295), Leon Robinson (6-4, 275)
and Matt Graviet (6-2, 265) have solid credentials. Tech usually
redshirts offensive linemen, although freshman Raymond
Roberts-Blake played in four games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Tight ends Darius Williams and J.P. Foschi could add depth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Weakness: None is apparent. The team appears to have filled
all of its needs with players who could contribute immediately.
</P>
<P>
   _ One that got away: Marcus Jasmine, a defensive lineman from
New Orleans, signed with Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   _ Can't miss: Holiday was on everyone's wish list, while
Hollings, Daryl Smith, Koon and Dixon, along with quarterbacks Mark
Logan and Brandon Sumner, passed up shots at possible early
starting roles at other schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sleepers: Jonathan Smith played quarterback, wide receiver and
defensive back at Clinch County, and had near-equal success at all
spots. With 4.4 speed in the 40, Smith will find a spot.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was underrated most of the season at Westlake High, but once
recruiters took a closer look, the chase was on. As a junior, the
linebacker had 20 sacks and eight interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Lumar, from Edgard, La., was a regular at LSU's football
camp. There, he caught the eye of David Kelly, who was an assistant
with the Tigers and now is Tech's receivers coach. Although the
Jackets are loaded at wide receiver, they couldn't afford to pass
on Lumar.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA TECH SIGNEES
</P>
