<HEADLINE>
HAIDER: `WAIT AND SEE' WAS WRONG IN 1933. IT'S STILL WRONG TODAY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editorial)   (This compelling 425-word ``separate-buy'' commentary is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And the news gets worse...
</P>
<P>
   The way is now clear for Jorg Haider and his far-right Freedom
Party to become part of the new Austrian government.
</P>
<P>
   The Austrian president, Thomas Klestil, has publicly expressed
his queasiness. But, like Britain's Queen Elizabeth, he is
powerless to prevent the formation of a government whose politics
he himself dislikes.
</P>
<P>
   That responsibility lies with other elected politicians, most
notably Wolfgang Schussel, leader of the conservative People's
Party, which wants to form a coalition with Haider.
</P>
<P>
   The forthright criticism from the European Union has fallen on
deaf ears in Austria itself, where the ``gross interference'' is
resented. The danger that Austrians may withdraw into a defiant
bunker is real. Turning a blind eye is, however, impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of Haider's party has partly been based on the
growing dislike of the cozy consensus in Austria that has operated
for so long, not just a liking for his extreme policies. But the
underlying xenophobia is undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   Haider put his name Thursday to a declaration that the new
government wants an Austria ``in which xenophobia, anti-Semitism
and racism have no place.''
</P>
<P>
   In the circumstances, however _ given that Haider has made
little attempt to distance himself from his previous statements _
such assurances are meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   If Haider were merely a flash in the populist pan, it would
matter less. But there is no reason to suppose that his rise to
power will stop here. He would like to be chancellor. On present
form, he could succeed.
</P>
<P>
   If that happened, Austria's continued membership of the European
Union would make no sense at all. As Romano Prodi, president of the
European Commission, told The Independent Thursday: ``If we are not
vigilant, the basic democratic foundations of Europe are in
danger.''
</P>
<P>
   East European countries that bid to join the EU are rebuffed if
they show intolerance at home. It would be illogical for a
different set of values to be applied to countries that are already
members of the club.
</P>
<P>
   Haider will not be a second Hitler. There will be no new
concentration camps, but his populist xenophobia presents real
dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is ready to withdraw its ambassador. Joschka Fischer, the
German Foreign Minister, insists: ``We cannot go on as if this were
normal.''
</P>
<P>
   In the European Parliament, British Labor MEPs have talked of
suspending Austria from the EU. But from the Foreign Office,
silence _ described as ``wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait and see was wrong in 1933; and it is wrong today. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 425-word editorial from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
