</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-EUROPE-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU MEMBERS SET TO TAKE ACTION AGAINST AUSTRIA
</HEADLINE>
   (See also AUSTRIA-POLITICS, AUSTRIA-VOICES) 
(sw) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The European Union, which warned that it would shun
Austria if the far-right Freedom Party joined the government there,
is now preparing to carry out its threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Portuguese prime minister, Antonio Guterres, whose country
holds the rotating European Union presidency, said on Thursday
night that members would begin curtailing relations with Austria on
Friday, the day the Freedom Party will be sworn into the Austrian
government.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a bold, almost impulsive effort to thwart what
critics see as a neo-fascist sentiment rising in Austria has
developed into one of the most serious crises in the 40 years that
Europe has taken steps toward political and economic unity.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders will now feel compelled to prove their resolve,
without so isolating and alienating Austria that it only
strengthens the position of Joerg Haider, the far-right populist
whom European leaders hoped to exclude from their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 European leaders said they would cut bilateral ties to
Austria and blackball Austrian officials from assuming leadership
positions in international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini spoke before
Italy's Parliament about Europe's tightrope. ``We need to be
consistent with the action taken by the European Union,'' he said,
but he warned that punishing Austria would be ``risky.''
</P>
<P>
   And former Prime Minister Romano Prodi, who heads the European
Commission, delicately expressed disagreement with European
leaders. A trans-European government body, he said on Wednesday,
has a duty ``not to isolate one of its members but to bind them
inextricably to its basic values.''
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by memories of World War II, Germany and France led the
revolt against what they described as an intolerable and all too
reminiscent xenophobia of Haider.
</P>
<P>
   Their alarm was heightened by fears that an empowered Haider
could infect Germany, where the scandals swirling around Helmet
Kohl, the former chancellor, have weakened his Christian Democratic
Union, a party that contains and tames the German far right. Some
people worry that a German could rise up to tap the same
anti-immigration sentiments that swelled the ranks of the Freedom
Party.
</P>
<P>
   France, which has had difficulty containing the far-right party
of Jean-Marie Le Pen, shares similar concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium's center-left government stepped ahead of the others on
Thursday and suggested that Austria should actually be expelled
from the European Union. In Belgium, extreme nationalist parties
have grown powerful by exploiting tensions between Flemish and
French citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In France and Britain, the threat to freeze relations with
Austria had mostly bipartisan support, though in Germany the
Christian Democrats did not support the government's program.
</P>
<P>
   Italy also was politically torn. Center-right opposition leaders
fiercely criticized the action as both a violation of Austrian
sovereignty and a tactical misstep that would backfire by
heightening Haider's popularity. And those arguments were echoed in
parliaments and editorial pages all across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Countries with center-right governments, like Spain, relished
the chance to distance themselves from Haider.
</P>
<P>
   Many politicians felt that Europe had to take the risk of
sanctions to ensure that other members did not follow suit. The
stand against Austria had particular meaning in Denmark, where the
anti-immigration Danish People's Party is the country's third most
popular.
</P>
<P>
   Henning Gjellerod, a member of the Danish Parliament and vice
president of the parliamentary assembly of the Council of Europe,
said the European Union's reprisals make it less likely that the
Danish People's Party would ever be invited to govern with a
conservative coalition.
</P>
<P>
   And the message was also aimed at applicants to the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe cannot really afford to sit back and accept what is
happening in Austria at the same time it is lecturing would-be
applicants to the European Union like Hungary and Turkey on the
need for democratic principles and respect for its ethnic
minorities,'' said Anand Menon, a lecturer on European politics at
Oxford who is currently teaching at New York University. ``They
would rightly be accused of hypocrisy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Turkey, certainly, paid heed to the dispute. ``Can the EU
interfere in the internal affairs of a member state?'' Semih Idiz,
a columnist for the newspaper The Star, wrote on Thursday. ``The
answer to this question, which is very important to Turkey, is now
very clear: Yes, it can, without a doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   The past, however, molded the decision as much as concerns about
the future. ``This is the first time an anti-European, xenophobic
party with a very dubious relationship toward the Nazi past has
come into the government of a member state,'' Germany's foreign
minister, Joschka Fischer, said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The temptation to paint Haider as a reincarnation of Hitler has
its own satisfactions, almost as if many Europeans were welcoming a
chance to rewrite the sins of omission of a generation ago. The
historian Peter Gay, who fled Nazi Germany as a child, commented
dryly, ``I was surprised when I heard about the European Union's
action, but then I thought, of course, it is high time we did
something about 1933.''
</P>
<P>
   To some Americans, drilled in the bedrock principle of free
speech, Europe's attempt to muzzle a politician elected with 27
percent of the popular vote seemed puzzling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There does seem to be a paradox,'' said Nadine Stossner,
president of the American Civil Liberties Union, which successfully
defended the right of American neo-Nazis to parade in Skokie, Ill.,
in 1977. ``To protect democracy and human rights, the Europeans
have adopted the very authoritarian methods that they say they are
acting to forestall.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``In Europe, people are always telling me I just
don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Many European countries have anti-fascist laws that restrict
free speech and freedom of association. Germany's Constitution,
which the United States helped draft, bans the Nazi Party.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler's ``Mein Kampf'' is banned, as are Nazi insignia and
uniforms. Germany, France and Holland have laws to prevent people
from asserting that the Holocaust never took place. Austria itself
has taken legal steps to rein in any return of Nazi sentiment. For
example it outlawed statements denying the existence of Auschwitz's
gas chambers.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, where Mussolini ruled for 21 years, the Constitution
forbids the resurrection of the Fascist Party. Fascist symbols and
anti-Semitic statements are also illegal.
</P>
<P>
   At a soccer match in Rome on Sunday, extremist fans held up
pictures of Mussolini and banners honoring Zeljko Raznatovic, the
Serbian paramiliary leader and war-crimes suspect known as Arkan,
who was recently assassinated. The Italian government warned that
if those gestures were repeated this weekend, the soccer match
would be halted and police would tear down the banners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole business of building the European Union was based on
the notion of `never again,''' said Pierre Lellouche, a Gaullist
member of the French Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not for hampering Haider's free speech or even
questioning the right of Austrians to vote for him,'' he said.
``But I do not want to sleep in the same bed and make legislation
with him for Europe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
