<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VODAFONE-DUESSELDORF-     02-03 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-DUESSELDORF-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BLOW TO DUESSELDORF, BUT HARDLY A FATAL ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With VODAFONE-MANNESMANN, VODAFONE-OUTLOOK)  
(lh) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUESSELDORF, Germany _ Had it not been in large part for
Mannesmann, this old industrial city might well have suffered a
decline similar to that of Gary, Ind., or Birmingham, England.
</P>
<P>
   Yet just as Mannesmann reinvented itself from a producer of
seamless steel pipe to a fast-growing telecommunications company,
Duesseldorf has reinvented itself as a prosperous center of high
technology and services. Both the city and the company at its heart
achieved what countless other cities in Europe and elsewhere only
talk about: They moved beyond their history, embraced change and
fostered entirely new jobs based on fast-growing advanced
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   And despite all that, the most important company here is now
succumbing to a $183 billion hostile takeover by the British
telecommunications giant Vodafone AirTouch, which seems intent on
running the company from London.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is as if a German company decided to come along and buy
General Electric, only to sell off all the parts it didn't want,''
said Christoph Blume, Duesseldorf's director of economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   Yet business executives and political leaders here seem to share
an overwhelming view that there is no turning back. To the extent
that Duesseldorf and Mannesmann have achieved new prosperity, they
have done so by embracing high technology and ignoring national
borders, so they could tap into international trade and foreign
capital markets.
</P>
<P>
   City officials publicly decried Vodafone's bid for Mannesmann,
but no one tried to stop it. And in Germany's once-protective
financial circles, bankers argue that it would be far more
dangerous to block Vodafone than to let shareholders decide for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is apparent on the streets of this city: It is packed
with foreign companies, many of them providing highly paid jobs in
technology and management. Duesseldorf has shed 125,000 industrial
jobs since the early 1960s. But it has added almost the same number
in fields like accounting, management consulting, software
development, advertising and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up,'' said Michael Moenks, the leader of
the workers' council at Mannesmann's mobile phone subsidiary here,
``people called this the writing desk for the Ruhr Valley _ the
headquarters for heavy industry.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't anymore. The crumbling wharf along the Rhine River,
rusting and dormant 10 years ago, has been redeveloped as a ``media
harbor'' and now boasts gleaming buildings packed with new
companies and trendy restaurants. Nokia of Finland and Ericsson of
Sweden, two of the world's leading mobile telephone manufacturers,
have research and business centers here. The electronics
conglomerate Siemens AG has a development center here for computer
chips.
</P>
<P>
   And at least half a dozen telecommunications companies have
installed fiber optic networks to provide high-speed data
communications through the main business areas. Mannesmann is at
the core of this new population of communications companies; others
include MCI Worldcom, Esprit Telecom of Britain and Isis Multimedia
of France.
</P>
<P>
   Few companies have become more entwined with the international
economy than Mannesmann itself. The company was founded more than a
century ago by two brothers who came up with a method for making
seamless steel pipe. Later, it branched out into engineering
services, auto parts and electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Since obtaining a license to supply mobile phone service
throughout Germany in 1989, Mannesmann has evolved into one of
Europe's most successful and internationally active competitors.
Until now the biggest mobile phone carrier in Germany, with
slightly more customers than Deutsche Telekom, Mannesmann has spent
tens of billions acquiring wireless businesses in Italy and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Such an enormous transformation required foreign partners and
foreign capital. Airtouch Communications, formerly the wireless arm
of the Pacific Telesis Group of San Francisco, provided money and
technical expertise from the very beginning. Mannesmann also raised
billions through international bond markets and attracted scores of
foreign shareholders. About 60 percent of Mannesmann's shares are
in non-German hands, and at least 40 percent are held by American
or British institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   And Mannesmann is not unique.
</P>
<P>
   Werner Seifert, president of the Frankfurt stock exchange,
estimates that two of every five shares traded in the DAX index of
leading German stocks are held by foreigners. Far from viewing that
as a threat to German jobs and stability, Seifert argues that it
makes companies healthier by forcing them to compete in the global
markets. And takeovers, he said, are part of the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States, the target companies in corporate
takeovers are usually companies in old industries that have not
been producing jobs,'' Seifert said. ``The market was punishing
companies that had not been able to create jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The economic unification of western Europe _ where trade
barriers have all but disappeared and eleven countries including
Germany have adopted the euro as a common currency _ has added to
the pressure for mergers as well as openness. ``In the past, you
might have dominated your domestic market, but now you are just one
of many players, and you must build up your position across
borders,'' said Theodor Baums, a professor of banking and finance
at the University of Osnabruck. ``If you want to have operations
abroad, you have to recognize the rights of companies in other
countries to come in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann, in sharp contrast to companies embroiled in takeover
battles in France or Italy, was careful never to deviate from that
standard. In his three-month barnstorming campaign to defeat
Vodafone's hostile bid, Mannesmann's chief executive, Klaus Esser,
never invoked political defenses and trained all his efforts on
convincing Mannesmann shareholders that Vodafone's offer was simply
too low.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final decision belongs to shareholders,'' he said again
and again. And though he might have grimaced at the results, Esser
generally acted in accordance with that belief.
</P>
<P>
   Joerg Pluta, director of the Deutsche Schutsverein fuer
Wertpapierbesitz, an advocacy group for individual investors,
praised Esser for his openness. ``I would give him an A for
transparency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That may come as cold comfort to people here. Several recent
surveys have found that the overwhelming majority of individual
investors in Germany opposed selling out their Mannesmann shares to
Vodafone.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, employees at Mannesmann's wireless business say
they are not worried about their future. The wireless business,
which employs 8,000 people around the country, is growing rapidly
and is almost certain to need more rather than fewer people.
</P>
<P>
   But many people fret that Vodafone will move to sever ties
quickly with Mannesmann's older businesses, such as steel pipes and
auto components. While both companies had planned to spin off the
older businesses, Vodafone's Gent is widely expected to be harsher
than Esser in closing down older factories. ``All the evidence thus
far suggests that foreign takeovers lead to the disposal of
management functions and jobs,'' said Udo Siepmann, head of the
Duesseldorf Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
   Others business leaders are more sanguine. ``This city has shown
that it can go through a huge transformation,'' said Hans Georg
Crone-Erdmann, head of the Association of Chambers of Commerce for
North Rhine Westphalia. ``I have absolutely no worries about the
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
