<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: ELECTION REFORM VOTE
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional court gave the go-ahead to seven referendums
between April and June, including one that its supporters say would
end political instability by abolishing election by proportional
representation to a quarter of the seats in Parliament's 630-member
lower house. In a vote last April, some 90 percent favored doing
away with proportional representation. But the ballot was declared
void when the turnout reached only 49.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: FIVE BASQUES SEIZED
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested Juan Carlos Iglesias Chouzas, 36, considered
a top commander of the Basque separatist group ETA, and four other
suspected Basque separatists in a two-day sweep. It came just days
after Spain detained eight people, including four leftist
politicians, on charges of providing logistical aid to the rebels.
The Spanish government holds ETA rebels responsible for a bombing
in Madrid that killed an army officer.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: TURK VISITS
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Cem, the first Turkish foreign minister to visit Greece
in 40 years, arrived in Athens to sign five accords and discuss the
next steps for easing tensions between Greece and Turkey. During
his three-day stay, Cem will try to persuade Greece to endorse
joint military maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: GOVERNOR FACES TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court approved an impeachment trial of Gov. Jorge
Carrillo Olea of Morelos, who took a leave of absence in May 1998
after two top aides were jailed in connection with the torture
death of a kidnapping suspect. The Morelos legislature voted to
impeach him last June, but the top state court said governors could
not be put on trial.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: TAX FRAUD DRIVE
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando de la Rua showed his determination for
cracking down on tax fraud by starting a sweeping sting operation
in which 72 tax officials coordinated raids on various businesses
to find workers who are off the books and do not pay income tax. An
estimated $20 billion a year is lost in taxes due to fraud.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: SECURITY ALERT
</P>
<P>
   Security was expected to be stepped up for President Thabo
Mbeki's address to the opening session of Parliament in Cape Town
Friday. Bombings have plagued the seaside city over the last couple
of years, including a spate of attacks during the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: KARMAPA LEADS PRAYERS
</P>
<P>
   Ugyen Trinley Dorje, the 14-year-old Karmapa who arrived in
India this year after escaping from China, led a five-minute prayer
session at the Gyodo Monastery in Dharamsala, home of Tibet's
government-in-exile. Indian paramilitary troops were stationed
around the grounds and visitors had to pass through two separate
security checks.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: KASHMIR HOLIDAY
</P>
<P>
   The military rulers have declared Saturday a public holiday in
solidarity with militants fighting in Indian-controlled Kashmir.
Rallies are planned and all government offices, banks and
businesses will be closed. The Harkat-ul-Mujahedeen group said it
would celebrate by stepping up attacks, to ``send gifts of bodies
to Indian oppressor beasts.''
</P>
<P>
   BANGLADESH: STRIKES' TOLL
</P>
<P>
   As the nation was paralyzed by a second day of political
strikes, the Bangladesh Road Transport Authority reported that such
commonplace work stoppages cost the country $3 million a day in
lost tolls, fees and taxes, severely hampering the nation's
economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
