<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5959 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-BOBJONES04-COX     02-03 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BOBJONES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush opponents describe campaign stop at college as 'racist'
 &HT;    By S.V. Date
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ If Flordia Gov. Jeb Bush and his
Mexican-born wife, Columba, had met as students at Bob Jones
University, they would have been expelled for interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that didn't stop his big brother, George W. Bush, from
kicking off his South Carolina campaign there Wednesday, telling
his fundamentalist Christian audience that he ``shares their
values.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit _ coming a day before younger brother Jeb attended a
stormy hearing in Miami over his plan to revamp affirmative action
_ quickly led to charges by Democrats that the whole Bush family
theme of ``compassionate conservatism'' was little more than
warmed-over racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to call that policy but racist,'' said Florida
Democratic Party spokesman Tony Welch of the school's interracial
dating ban. ``And there's nothing to call his support of that
policy but racist.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bush spokesman said Thursday the Texas governor does not agree
with the school's policy, but that he went to the Greenville campus
to spread his message and values to potential voters, ``not the
other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has a proven inclusiveness record of reaching
out to people in all walks of life,'' said campaign spokesman Scott
McClellen.
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, that wasn't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's doublespeak,'' Welch said, adding that using that
logic, it would be OK to address a Ku Klux Klan rally, too. ``His
own brother could not be a student at that university!''
</P>
<P>
   The 5,000-student school banned blacks until the federal
government threatened to take away its tax-exempt status in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The university's community relations coordinator, Jonathon Pait,
explained the school's position on interracial relations in a 1998
letter to a prospective applicant:
</P>
<P>
   ``God has made people different from one another and intends
those differences to remain. Bob Jones University is opposed to
intermarriage of the races because it breaks down the barriers God
has established,'' Pait wrote. ``When Jesus Christ returns to the
earth, He will establish world unity, but until then, a divided
earth seems to be His plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Pait would not take phone calls Thursday asking him to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Attorney General Bob Butterworth, state campaign
chairman for Vice President Al Gore, was astounded by Bush's
appearance there. ``That's amazing. That's absolutely amazing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are a candidate for office, you choose very carefully
where you speak,'' said Butterworth, speaking from Gore's national
headquarters in Nashville, Tenn. He said he was also personally
offended because his wife of 15 years was born in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush, who was attending the heated hearing on his One
Florida plan in Miami on Thursday, did not respond to e-mails
Thursday seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth, though, predicted that candidate Bush's attempt to
court the Christian conservatives in South Carolina could come back
to haunt him. ``Sometimes when you get involved in a highly
contested primary you do things that'll hurt you in the general
election,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Marcia Gelbart contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
