<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 02/03/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. -- Feb. 3, 2000 --
NY-DUTCHESS-POLITICS-2 -- William L. Paroli Sr. - a Republican
elections commissioner and the former Dutchess County Republican
leader - is under investigation. This is a cautionary tale about
politics and power, since much of upstate New York is dominated by
the cozy world of one-party politics to the point where local
elections often have all the suspense of a Chinese politburo
meeting. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) MILLERTON, N.Y. -- Feb. 3, 2000 --
NY-DUTCHESS-POLITICS-1 -- Richard Anderson, the Democratic
candidate for Dutchess County clerk, left; William L. Paroli Jr.,
the incumbent. Paroli lost to Anderson in his re-election race by
59 votes, then forced an unprecedented do-over vote in one remote
town with the support of the Republican elections commissioner, who
happens to be his father. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- KLEINDIENST-OBIT-B&AMP;W --
Richard G. Kleindienst testifying before Congress in 1973.
Kleindienst, who was President Richard M. Nixon's attorney general
for less than a year in the Watergate era and who pleaded guilty to
a crime in a peripheral scandal, died Thursday at his home in
Prescott, Ariz. He was 76. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) WINFIELD, Ill. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ABORTION-POLITICS --
Tony Harvey, at home in Winfield, opposes abortion, but says that
government will never be able to eliminate it. ``I'm very
religious, and I do not believe in abortion,'' says Harvey, a
38-year-old engineer in Chicago. ``But to me, all this talk about
abortion is beside the point. If people want to have abortions,
they're going to have them.'' (Steve Kagan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) ARGUN, Russia -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- CHECHNYA-PRESS -- A
Russian television crew working recently near the Chechen southern
front interviews a soldier selected by the official military press
service about a battle that took place almost a week earlier. Every
day, Russia's journalists do battle with the military press
service, which regulates access to the battlefield and is
determined to put out the message that the Kremlin's war is going
according to plan. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 6 --
COCA-COLA-DAFT -- Douglas N. Daft has shaken up Coca-Cola with a
radical restructuring plan even before he officially takes the helm
at the company. ``We were very ubiquitous and decentralized in
where we sold, but we had a very large central core,'' he says of
Coke's old corporate structure. The changes he has made ``allow us
to focus on growth now.'' (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) ATLANTA -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- OBIT-WILLIEB-COX -- Willie
B., surely the best-loved Atlanta citizen of any species, died of
heart failure during a peaceful nap Wednesday afternoon. He was 41.
The 6-foot, 400-pound lowland gorilla, named after former Atlanta
Mayor William B. Hartsfield, was born in the wild and became the
star of Zoo Atlanta from his arrival in 1961. He leaves behind four
daughters and a 2-year-old son, Kidogo - who will be renamed Willie
B. Jr. (Johnny Crawford/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) SLEPTSOVSK, Russia -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
FEB. 6 -- RUSSIA-REFUGEE-2-COX -- 14-year-old Yusup Magomedov lies
on a table in a refugee hospital in Sleptsovsk a week after a
Russian artillary shell slammed into the town square in Novi
Sharoi, Chechnya, killing seven children and wounded 14 others,
including Yusup, who lost his legs. Russian authorities will not
say whether the shell that hit Yusup on Oct. 23 was an accident or
part of a planned strike. (Yuri Kazlov/Cox Newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) MOSCOW -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 6 --
RUSSIA-REFUGEE-1-COX -- 14-year-old Yusup Magomedov trys out his
new prosthetic limbs in a Moscow hospital. Yusup lost his legs on
Oct. 23rd when a Russian artillary shell slammed into the town
square in Novi Sharoi, Chechnya, where he was playing soccer with
friends. The explosion killed seven children and wounded 14 others,
including Yusup. (Maragret Coker/Cox Newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) SUTTON, England -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 6
-- BRITAIN-WALMART-COX -- Shoppers leave an Asda store recently.
Last June, Wal-Mart, based in Bentonville, Ark., purchased Asda,
Britain's No. 3 grocery story chain for $10.8 billion. Wal-Mart has
been warmly welcomed by British shoppers, who pay up to 40 percent
more at the market than their European and American counterparts.
(Bert Roughton/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) UNDATED -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 6 --
ABOUT-CARS-SAAB -- Saab's 9-5 Aero, top, is less rowdy and more
polished than its 9-3 Viggen, below. Though very different cars,
they share the company's trademarks: an off-the-beaten path design,
remarkable pep, surprising versatility. Both are niche vehicles for
affluent drivers who value being different almost as much as they
covet performance and comfort. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) CHESHIRE, Conn. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 6
-- BIZ-TUFTE -- Flash and dash substituting for real analysis of
information in graphic presentations is the bane of Edward R.
Tufte, considered the guru of visual explanations. He says such
graphics - low in information, confused in display, muddled in
thinking - can have catastrophic consequences. (George Ruhe/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) SPRING VALLEY, N.Y. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- NY-FORECLOSURE --
Mireille Leroy outside her home on Thursday. Leroy, who 17 years
ago came to the United States from Haiti and three years ago earned
her American citizenship, lost her $114,000 house in a foreclosure
proceeding after being short on a tax payment of $58. (Joyce
Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 6 --
BIZ-PROFILE-AUGUSTIN -- Larry Augustin, founder of VA Linux, the
operating-system maker whose shares soared at their initial
offering, wants to free computer users from proprietary operating
systems like Windows. ``What we offer to our customers is not just
a system,'' he says. ``It's full service, a single point of
contact, service and support for building their entire
infrastructure.'' (Barbara Alper/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- PARKEHARRISON-PHOTOS-B&AMP;W --
``Mending the Earth'' (1999) in ``Robert ParkeHarrison: Earth
Elegies,'' at the Bonni Benrubi Gallery. ParkeHarrison comes down
on the side of lamentation but expresses it with an unusual
combination of poetic license, laboriously constructed props and a
wry and melancholy, vaguely allusive sense of myth. (Bonni Benrubi
Gallery/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ART-NOTES -- ``Reflections on
a Girl'' by Roy Lichtenstein is to be auctioned at Sotheby's in May
and is estimated to sell at $100,000 to $125,000. Among Sotheby's
other star offerings are Helen Frankenthaler's ``Free Fall''
(1993), a woodcut on hand-dyed, handmade paper, estimated at
$20,000 to $25,000; and Frank Stella's ``Fountain'' (1993), a
woodcut, etching and aquatint relief on handmade, hand-colored
paper, estimated at $100,000 to $125,000. (Sotheby's/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- JOYCE-THEATER-REVIEW --
Brian Davies, left, Alice Ripley and Stephen Spinella in ``James
Joyce's 'The Dead' `` at the Belasco. While this adaptation
diverges in marked ways from Joyce's original tale, it captures in
its very form the story's modernist essence: a sense of individuals
alone, confined by their separate consciousnesses. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- AUTOS-BOOKS -- The instrument
panel of a '55 Corvette from ``Dashboards'' by David Holland, one
of several new books with an automotive slant. Holland's lavish
coffee-table book, with photographs by Colin Turner and Ken
Kirkwood, conveys a fascinating tale of the evolution of the
automobile dashboard, even to those with only a passing interest in
cars. (Naum Kazhdan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- MET-EVANS-PHOTOS-B&AMP;W-3 --
``Couple at Coney Island, New York'' (1928), by Walker Evans, from
his retrospective at the Met. As Douglas Eklund puts it in the
catalog for the show, ``In all of those circles Evans the man moved
quite comfortably but with a residue of free-floating negativity;
the uniquely subdued, dispassionate tone (and some might argue the
chilling effect) of his photographs came from this sustained and
critical refusal to join.'' (Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- MET-EVANS-PHOTOS-2-B&AMP;W --
Walker Evans' ``Main Street, Saratoga Springs'' (1931), at the Met.
His photos exhibit a poetry that couldn't be called beauty, not
conventional beauty anyway, an art inspired by vernacular subjects
and aspiring to the natural dignity of the street. (Metropolitan
Museum of Art/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- MET-EVANS-PHOTOS-B&AMP;W --
``Burroughs Family Cabin, Hale County'' (1936), by Walker Evans, at
the Met. His portraits are ingrained in the American psyche
basically because Evans, in a photographic style as spare as James
Agee's writing was the opposite, denied us what we expected: he
short-circuited pity for those people by cutting out the charm and
anecdote. (Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ANTIQUES-COLUMN -- Detail of
a circa 1400 German bronze aquamanile as a saddled horse in
``Collecting Treasures of the Past'' at the Blumka Gallery in
Manhattan. Because most art created in the Middle Ages was made for
the church, not for private patrons, some collectors say that it is
somehow more genuine and less self-conscious than art from other
periods. (Blumka Gallery/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- WORLD-MUSIC -- Ibrahim
Ferrer and Omara Portuondo of Cuba's Buena Vista Social Club will
be performing this weekend in Manhattan. The world's music has
never been more accessible, speeded to new ears by everything from
jet travel to the Internet. (Nancy Siesel/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) EL SEGUNDO, Calif. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- MATTELL-RESIGN --
Jill Barad, chief executive of Mattel, stands next to lifesize
versions of ``Ken'' and ``Barbie'' in her office in October, 1999.
Barad, the woman who turned Barbie into a $1.7 billion business,
stepped down on Thursday as chairwoman and chief executive of
Mattel Inc. after a botched acquisition led to a string of
disappointing quarters. Barad's resignation, effective Thursday,
came after a meeting of the board of the world's largest toymaker
in New York and as Mattel reported a loss of $18.4 million for the
latest quarter. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SUMTER, S.C. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- BUSH-CAMPAIGN -- Gov.
George W. Bush escorts retired Adm. Thomas Moore, a former chairman
of the Joints Chief of Staff, down the steps of the courthouse
where Bush addressed supporters and listened to the endorsement
speeches of several military groups. Bush courted South Carolina's
large population of veterans Thursday, refusing to concede their
votes to any other candidate including former Navy pilot and POW
John McCain. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEAR DANSKAMMER POINT, N.Y. -- Feb. 3, 2000 --
ICEBREAKER-2 -- The Coast Guard icebreaker Penobscot Bay,
foreground, clears a path for tugboats pushing barges of heating
oil up the Hudson River on Thursday. While most other areas of the
state are fed by pipelines, the region from Westchester to Albany,
N.Y., and farther north, gets nearly all its heating oil, gasoline,
diesel fuel and kerosene from the hulking barges that float up and
down the Hudson River. When the river is clear, the 126-mile trip
from the George Washington Bridge to Albany, the main port, takes
20 to 24 hours. When parts of the river are covered in ice, the
trip could take almost twice as long. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEAR DANSKAMMER POINT, N.Y. -- Feb. 3, 2000 --
ICEBREAKER-1 -- The Coast Guard icebreaker Penobscot Bay,
foreground, clears a path for a tugboat pushing a barge of heating
oil up the Hudson River on Thursday. While most other areas of the
state are fed by pipelines, the region from Westchester to Albany,
N.Y., and farther north, gets nearly all its heating oil, gasoline,
diesel fuel and kerosene from the hulking barges that float up and
down the Hudson River. When the river is clear, the 126-mile trip
from the George Washington Bridge to Albany, the main port, takes
20 to 24 hours. When parts of the river are covered in ice, the
trip could take almost twice as long. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CHARLESTON, S.C. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- MCCAIN-FUNDRAISING-2
-- Sen. John McCain greets supporters before speaking at the
Charleston Maritime Center on Thursday. Since Tuesday's victory in
New Hampshire's primary, McCain has raised more than $740,000
through his campaign Web site and thousands more at an evening
fund-raiser in South Carolina. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) CHARLESTON, S.C. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- MCCAIN-FUNDRAISING-1
-- Sen. John McCain during the Pledge of Allegiance before speaking
at the Charleston Maritime Center on Thursday. Since Tuesday's
victory in New Hampshire's primary, McCain has raised more than
$740,000 through his campaign Web site and thousands more at an
evening fund-raiser in South Carolina. (Monica Almeida/The New York
Times)
