   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 02/03/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. -- Feb. 3, 2000 --
NY-DUTCHESS-POLITICS-2 -- William L. Paroli Sr. - a Republican
elections commissioner and the former Dutchess County Republican
leader - is under investigation. This is a cautionary tale about
politics and power, since much of upstate New York is dominated by
the cozy world of one-party politics to the point where local
elections often have all the suspense of a Chinese politburo
meeting. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) MILLERTON, N.Y. -- Feb. 3, 2000 --
NY-DUTCHESS-POLITICS-1 -- Richard Anderson, the Democratic
candidate for Dutchess County clerk, left; William L. Paroli Jr.,
the incumbent. Paroli lost to Anderson in his re-election race by
59 votes, then forced an unprecedented do-over vote in one remote
town with the support of the Republican elections commissioner, who
happens to be his father. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- KLEINDIENST-OBIT-B&AMP;W --
Richard G. Kleindienst testifying before Congress in 1973.
Kleindienst, who was President Richard M. Nixon's attorney general
for less than a year in the Watergate era and who pleaded guilty to
a crime in a peripheral scandal, died Thursday at his home in
Prescott, Ariz. He was 76. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) WINFIELD, Ill. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ABORTION-POLITICS --
Tony Harvey, at home in Winfield, opposes abortion, but says that
government will never be able to eliminate it. ``I'm very
religious, and I do not believe in abortion,'' says Harvey, a
38-year-old engineer in Chicago. ``But to me, all this talk about
abortion is beside the point. If people want to have abortions,
they're going to have them.'' (Steve Kagan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) ARGUN, Russia -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- CHECHNYA-PRESS -- A
Russian television crew working recently near the Chechen southern
front interviews a soldier selected by the official military press
service about a battle that took place almost a week earlier. Every
day, Russia's journalists do battle with the military press
service, which regulates access to the battlefield and is
determined to put out the message that the Kremlin's war is going
according to plan. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 6 --
COCA-COLA-DAFT -- Douglas N. Daft has shaken up Coca-Cola with a
radical restructuring plan even before he officially takes the helm
at the company. ``We were very ubiquitous and decentralized in
where we sold, but we had a very large central core,'' he says of
Coke's old corporate structure. The changes he has made ``allow us
to focus on growth now.'' (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) ATLANTA -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- OBIT-WILLIEB-COX -- Willie
B., surely the best-loved Atlanta citizen of any species, died of
heart failure during a peaceful nap Wednesday afternoon. He was 41.
The 6-foot, 400-pound lowland gorilla, named after former Atlanta
Mayor William B. Hartsfield, was born in the wild and became the
star of Zoo Atlanta from his arrival in 1961. He leaves behind four
daughters and a 2-year-old son, Kidogo - who will be renamed Willie
B. Jr. (Johnny Crawford/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) SLEPTSOVSK, Russia -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
FEB. 6 -- RUSSIA-REFUGEE-2-COX -- 14-year-old Yusup Magomedov lies
on a table in a refugee hospital in Sleptsovsk a week after a
Russian artillary shell slammed into the town square in Novi
Sharoi, Chechnya, killing seven children and wounded 14 others,
including Yusup, who lost his legs. Russian authorities will not
say whether the shell that hit Yusup on Oct. 23 was an accident or
part of a planned strike. (Yuri Kazlov/Cox Newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) MOSCOW -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 6 --
RUSSIA-REFUGEE-1-COX -- 14-year-old Yusup Magomedov trys out his
new prosthetic limbs in a Moscow hospital. Yusup lost his legs on
Oct. 23rd when a Russian artillary shell slammed into the town
square in Novi Sharoi, Chechnya, where he was playing soccer with
friends. The explosion killed seven children and wounded 14 others,
including Yusup. (Maragret Coker/Cox Newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) SUTTON, England -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 6
-- BRITAIN-WALMART-COX -- Shoppers leave an Asda store recently.
Last June, Wal-Mart, based in Bentonville, Ark., purchased Asda,
Britain's No. 3 grocery story chain for $10.8 billion. Wal-Mart has
been warmly welcomed by British shoppers, who pay up to 40 percent
more at the market than their European and American counterparts.
(Bert Roughton/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) UNDATED -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 6 --
ABOUT-CARS-SAAB -- Saab's 9-5 Aero, top, is less rowdy and more
polished than its 9-3 Viggen, below. Though very different cars,
they share the company's trademarks: an off-the-beaten path design,
remarkable pep, surprising versatility. Both are niche vehicles for
affluent drivers who value being different almost as much as they
covet performance and comfort. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) CHESHIRE, Conn. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 6
-- BIZ-TUFTE -- Flash and dash substituting for real analysis of
information in graphic presentations is the bane of Edward R.
Tufte, considered the guru of visual explanations. He says such
graphics - low in information, confused in display, muddled in
thinking - can have catastrophic consequences. (George Ruhe/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) SPRING VALLEY, N.Y. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- NY-FORECLOSURE --
Mireille Leroy outside her home on Thursday. Leroy, who 17 years
ago came to the United States from Haiti and three years ago earned
her American citizenship, lost her $114,000 house in a foreclosure
proceeding after being short on a tax payment of $58. (Joyce
Dopkeen/The New York Times)
