<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 6 --
BIZ-PROFILE-AUGUSTIN -- Larry Augustin, founder of VA Linux, the
operating-system maker whose shares soared at their initial
offering, wants to free computer users from proprietary operating
systems like Windows. ``What we offer to our customers is not just
a system,'' he says. ``It's full service, a single point of
contact, service and support for building their entire
infrastructure.'' (Barbara Alper/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- PARKEHARRISON-PHOTOS-B&AMP;W --
``Mending the Earth'' (1999) in ``Robert ParkeHarrison: Earth
Elegies,'' at the Bonni Benrubi Gallery. ParkeHarrison comes down
on the side of lamentation but expresses it with an unusual
combination of poetic license, laboriously constructed props and a
wry and melancholy, vaguely allusive sense of myth. (Bonni Benrubi
Gallery/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ART-NOTES -- ``Reflections on
a Girl'' by Roy Lichtenstein is to be auctioned at Sotheby's in May
and is estimated to sell at $100,000 to $125,000. Among Sotheby's
other star offerings are Helen Frankenthaler's ``Free Fall''
(1993), a woodcut on hand-dyed, handmade paper, estimated at
$20,000 to $25,000; and Frank Stella's ``Fountain'' (1993), a
woodcut, etching and aquatint relief on handmade, hand-colored
paper, estimated at $100,000 to $125,000. (Sotheby's/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- JOYCE-THEATER-REVIEW --
Brian Davies, left, Alice Ripley and Stephen Spinella in ``James
Joyce's 'The Dead' `` at the Belasco. While this adaptation
diverges in marked ways from Joyce's original tale, it captures in
its very form the story's modernist essence: a sense of individuals
alone, confined by their separate consciousnesses. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- AUTOS-BOOKS -- The instrument
panel of a '55 Corvette from ``Dashboards'' by David Holland, one
of several new books with an automotive slant. Holland's lavish
coffee-table book, with photographs by Colin Turner and Ken
Kirkwood, conveys a fascinating tale of the evolution of the
automobile dashboard, even to those with only a passing interest in
cars. (Naum Kazhdan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- MET-EVANS-PHOTOS-B&AMP;W-3 --
``Couple at Coney Island, New York'' (1928), by Walker Evans, from
his retrospective at the Met. As Douglas Eklund puts it in the
catalog for the show, ``In all of those circles Evans the man moved
quite comfortably but with a residue of free-floating negativity;
the uniquely subdued, dispassionate tone (and some might argue the
chilling effect) of his photographs came from this sustained and
critical refusal to join.'' (Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- MET-EVANS-PHOTOS-2-B&AMP;W --
Walker Evans' ``Main Street, Saratoga Springs'' (1931), at the Met.
His photos exhibit a poetry that couldn't be called beauty, not
conventional beauty anyway, an art inspired by vernacular subjects
and aspiring to the natural dignity of the street. (Metropolitan
Museum of Art/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- MET-EVANS-PHOTOS-B&AMP;W --
``Burroughs Family Cabin, Hale County'' (1936), by Walker Evans, at
the Met. His portraits are ingrained in the American psyche
basically because Evans, in a photographic style as spare as James
Agee's writing was the opposite, denied us what we expected: he
short-circuited pity for those people by cutting out the charm and
anecdote. (Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ANTIQUES-COLUMN -- Detail of
a circa 1400 German bronze aquamanile as a saddled horse in
``Collecting Treasures of the Past'' at the Blumka Gallery in
Manhattan. Because most art created in the Middle Ages was made for
the church, not for private patrons, some collectors say that it is
somehow more genuine and less self-conscious than art from other
periods. (Blumka Gallery/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
