<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD     02-03 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA TRADES DETAINED JOURNALIST FOR TWO CAPTURED SOLDIERS
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS spelling of Said Usykhodzhiyev in 6th graf) 
(See also CHECHNYA-PRESS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a bizarre episode that underscores the limits the
Kremlin has imposed on reporting from Chechnya, Russian authorities
Thursday handed over a Radio Liberty correspondent to Chechen
rebels in exchange for two captured Russian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian authorities had detained Andrei Babitsky, a Russian
citizen who is a correspondent for the U.S.-funded Radio Liberty,
on Jan. 16 as he was leaving the rebel-controlled section of
Grozny, the Chechen capital. He was later charged with ``membership
in an illegal, armed group.''
</P>
<P>
   The detention of Babitsky seems to reflect a shrinking tolerance
for a free press since Vladimir Putin became acting president.
</P>
<P>
   At first it appeared that the Kremlin had grudgingly yielded to
appeals by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and a variety of
press freedom organizations to set Babitsky free. Russian officials
suggested that he would be returned to Moscow and released on his
own recognizance pending further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday Sergei Yastrzhembsky, the Russian government's new
spokesman for the war in Chechnya, announced that Babitsky had been
traded to the Chechens Thursday afternoon at the crossroads between
the towns of Argun and Shali.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unexpected development,'' Yastrzhembsky conceded.
Then he read two statements, asserting that they were from Babitsky
and Said Usykhodzhiyev, whom the spokesman identified as a Chechen
field commander. The statement from Babitsky, dated Jan. 31, said
he had agreed to the swap to secure the release of the Russian
soldiers. The statement from the field commander said he had
proposed the swap and praised Babitsky as a ``friend.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ilyas Akhmadov, foreign minister of the breakaway Chechen
republic, said that no one in the Chechen government had heard of
the commander.
</P>
<P>
   Yastrzhembsky said a videotape had been made of the exchange and
would be made available. Thursday night, however, Babitsky's
whereabouts were unknown and some of his friends said they feared
for his safety. Radio Liberty executives deplored the Russian
government's handling of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man was held for more than two weeks with no access to a
telephone or access to legal representation,'' said Jeff Trimble,
Radio Liberty's director of broadcasting. ``That raises very
serious concern about the Russian government's attitude toward the
press. And the announcement that he has been exchanged for Russian
prisoners has made a bad situation worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky, 36, was one of a handful of reporters who ventured
into the rebel-controlled areas of Grozny. His reports irritated
Russian authorities, who have sharply restricted access to the
battlefield and sought to discourage reporting from the Chechen
side.
</P>
<P>
   He was seen on Jan. 16 on the northern outskirts of Grozny in
the custody of Russian authorities. Nonetheless, Yastrzhembsky
insisted last week that Moscow had no knowledge of his whereabouts.
Radio Liberty was officially informed on Monday that Babitsky had
been detained.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky was a human rights activist during the Soviet era and
worked for the magazine Glasnost. He has worked since 1989 for
Radio Liberty, which was established by the United States during
the Cold War to broadcast news to the Soviet Union and East
European nations.
</P>
<P>
   When Chechen rebels seized a hospital in the southern Russian
town of Budyonnovsk during the first war in Chechnya, Babitsky
agreed to take the place of some of the rebels' hostages, a deed
that suggested to some of his associates that he might in the
current case have agreed to the exchange for Russian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, feared that the decision was made under duress.
</P>
<P>
   Some challenged the Russian account of the exchange. Babitsky's
wife, Lyudmila, who has not been able to talk to her husband for 19
days, said the Kremlin was trying to discredit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who were the people they gave Andrei to?'' she said in an
interview. ``Nobody knowns a Chechen field commander by this
name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
