<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5966 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLA-SCHOOLBOMB04-COX     02-03 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SCHOOLBOMB04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teen's plans to plant bombs at school revealed by peers he tried
to recruit
 &HT;    By Sonja Isger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROYAL PALM BEACH, Fla. _ He had a floor plan of Royal Palm Beach
High School, an Internet cookbook for making bombs and a diary
detailing plans to come on campus shooting. The one thing the
17-year-old student didn't have is willing accomplices. The three
boys he tried to recruit became his undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, Derek Lehman's plans to launch an assault at
school were foiled when his would-be accomplices and their parents
alerted Principal Brenda Montgomery. By the end of the day, police
had scoured his house and Lehman was in custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great deal of animosity and anger towards other
students and had been harassed in the past,'' schools Police Chief
Jim Kelly said Thursday. Yet, up to now the boy had not displayed
any behavior that would have led administrators to suspect he might
do something violent, Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   The students told police they came forward because they feared
for their and others' safety. They said he warned them that on
Wednesday they should stay away from building No. 3, Kelly said.
The building is full of classrooms, including the room where Lehman
had his first period English class, according to a teacher who
wished to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman's plans were elaborate, but so far it appears he hadn't
gotten his hands on any weapons, Kelly said. Police found no guns
or bomb-making materials in his house, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But according to his diary and subsequent police interviews, it
wasn't for lack of trying, Kelly said. ``He was trying to get them
from kids and anybody he knew,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   The high school junior's plans unraveled Thursday morning before
the first bell rang. Three students and a father approached
Montgomery as she headed for the courtyard to monitor students
arriving for the day. They told her their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   She called in school police and pulled Lehman, clad head to toe
in black, out of class, Kelly said. He told police he had a plan, a
diary and a map of the school at home. Police then called the boy's
parents, who allowed them to search their home. Kelly wouldn't
disclose whether Lehman's plans targeted specific students, but
they did mention a school police officer, Kelly said. All Palm
Beach County high schools have armed, uniformed police on campus.
Two are stationed at Royal Palm, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the search, police returned to the school and took Lehman
to a local hospital where he is being held for examination under
the state's Baker Act, a law that requires a person's mental health
be evaluated. His parents did not return phone calls Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Lehman was pulled from class, administrators and
a crisis team of faculty at the school were alerted, Montgomery
said.
</P>
<P>
   But many teachers and students didn't learn about the incident
until Thursday, about five minutes before the 2:50 p.m. school
dismissal. Montgomery told students over the public address system
that there indeed had been a threat, but that it had been handled.
After school Thursday, Montgomery followed up with a faculty
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a panic situation,'' said Martin Walsh, a physics
teacher. ``Everything was handled remarkably well.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some teachers voiced concern Thursday that they should
have been clued in when police picked up Lehman.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Montgomery has requested counselors be available for any
students who need to talk about the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a principal's worst nightmare to have this kind of
allegation or incident occur,'' Montgomery said. ``We're
responsible for 2,100 students. That's quite a burden. Every time I
leave campus I'm thankful when everyone is all right.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most important message from these events is that
students can and do act responsibly when confronted with something
they know is wrong, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so thankful that these three young men came forth. They
did the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post staff writer Stephanie Desmon contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
