   (NYT14) NEAR DANSKAMMER POINT, N.Y. -- Feb. 3, 2000 --
ICEBREAKER-1 -- The Coast Guard icebreaker Penobscot Bay,
foreground, clears a path for a tugboat pushing a barge of heating
oil up the Hudson River on Thursday. While most other areas of the
state are fed by pipelines, the region from Westchester to Albany,
N.Y., and farther north, gets nearly all its heating oil, gasoline,
diesel fuel and kerosene from the hulking barges that float up and
down the Hudson River. When the river is clear, the 126-mile trip
from the George Washington Bridge to Albany, the main port, takes
20 to 24 hours. When parts of the river are covered in ice, the
trip could take almost twice as long. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CHARLESTON, S.C. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- MCCAIN-FUNDRAISING-2
-- Sen. John McCain greets supporters before speaking at the
Charleston Maritime Center on Thursday. Since Tuesday's victory in
New Hampshire's primary, McCain has raised more than $740,000
through his campaign Web site and thousands more at an evening
fund-raiser in South Carolina. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) CHARLESTON, S.C. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- MCCAIN-FUNDRAISING-1
-- Sen. John McCain during the Pledge of Allegiance before speaking
at the Charleston Maritime Center on Thursday. Since Tuesday's
victory in New Hampshire's primary, McCain has raised more than
$740,000 through his campaign Web site and thousands more at an
evening fund-raiser in South Carolina. (Monica Almeida/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SUVO GRLO, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- KOSOVO-ATTACK-2
-- Milomirka Tomasevic, 52, who survived an attack Wednesday on a
U.N. bus transporting her and several other Serbs to a village, in
a camp on Thursday. The bus was part of a weekly service operated
by the United Nations High commissioner for refugees which took
Serbs to the Serb district of Mitrovica. Two Serbs on the bus were
killed. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) VITAK, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- KOSOVO-ATTACK-1 --
A United Nations police officer walks Thursday past a window from a
bus which was attacked on Wednesday in northern Kosovo. The bus was
part of a weekly service operated by the United Nations High
commissioner for refugees which took Serbs to the Serb district of
Mitrovica. Two Serbs on the bus were killed. (Andrew Testa/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- ALASKA-AIRLINES-CRASH-2 --
James Hall, left, chairman of the National Transportation Safety
Board, points to cockpit voice recorder from Alaska Airlines Flight
261 during a news conference on Thursday. Vern Ellingstad, center,
director of the Office of Resource and Engineering, holds up the
pinger which enabled the U.S. Navy to find the device in the
Pacific Ocean just north of Los Angeles. At right is Bernard Loeb,
director of the Office of Aviation Safety. The Alaska Airlines
MD-83 crashed while trying to make an emergency landing in Los
Angeles on Monday. All 88 people aboard the plane were killed.
(Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- MONUMENT-FLOATER -- Workers
remove part of the scaffolding designed by Michael Graves from the
Washington Monument, Thursday. Though renovations are finished, the
monument will not open to the public until July 4. (Shana Raab/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CHARLESTOWN, Mass. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- BOAT-PEOPLE-2-BOS
-- Bruce Laughon aboard his sailboat, Majorchord, protected with
shrink-wrap, at Constitution Marina. About 160 vessels housing
``liveaboards'' are tied up at a half-dozen marinas in Boston's
inner harbor. These are boating's voluntary left-behinds, the folks
who refuse to abandon their boats from October to May in favor of a
cozy house in the suburbs, or who decline to sail southward in
order to spend winter in a toastier port. (Wendy Maeda/The Boston
Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CHARLESTOWN, Mass. -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- BOAT-PEOPLE-1-BOS
-- Bruce Laughon pushes his wheelbarrow to bring supplies to his
shrink-wrapped sailboat, Majorchord, docked at Constitution Marina.
About 160 vessels housing ``liveaboards'' are tied up at a
half-dozen marinas in Boston's inner harbor. These are boating's
voluntary left-behinds, the folks who refuse to abandon their boats
from October to May in favor of a cozy house in the suburbs, or who
decline to sail southward in order to spend winter in a toastier
port. (Wendy Maeda/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Feb. 3, 2000 -- -AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS -- The 2000
