<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-RAC-JOCKEY-BEASLEY-HN     02-03 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-JOCKEY-BEASLEY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Imagine if NBA rookies could shoot 3-pointers from an arc one foot
closer to the basket than the one the veterans use. Or if Major
League Baseball let rookies swing corked bats.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As absurd and unlikely as those scenarios may be, they're not so
far-fetched to a fan of horse racing. In this sport, all first-year
``apprentice'' jockeys are granted a five-pound weight allowance.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if NASCAR gave rookie drivers a bigger engine to make up
for their lack of experience at using it.
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing is especially kind to newcomers by extending the
apprentice year in cases of injury. Because he missed seven months
recovering from thumb surgery, Jeremy Beasley, who began riding
professionally in the summer of 1998, is still an apprentice at Sam
Houston Race Park,
</P>
<P>
   But only until Saturday. That will be the last day he rides at
cut-weight.
</P>
<P>
   Even a lengthy honeymoon must end, and when it does, Beasley
realizes, ``The reality can be harsh.''
</P>
<P>
   The death of his ``bug'' (racing parlance for the five-pound
break) is a sad day for any jockey. Often it's the prelude to
oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, the jockey becomes devalued. The quality of his (or
her) riding stock plummets, so the athlete's winning percentage
dwindles and a downward spiral develops. The more successful the
apprentice, the further the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Beasley, who rode at Sam Houston for three glorious
months last year before moving up to New York, was one of three
finalists for the Eclipse Award as the nation's top apprentice. He
didn't win, but he figures it's just as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of good riders never got it,'' he points out. ``And a
lot of riders have won the Eclipse Award and have never won
anything after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many racing fans have forgotten Eclipse-winning
apprentices of recent vintages. Juan Umana? Steve Capanas? Ramon
Perez? Roberto Rosado? These once-hot jockeys are now hanging on at
second- and third-rate tracks.
</P>
<P>
   That does not necessarily bode well for the 20-year-old Beasley,
who ranks 12th nationally with 19 wins this year. But if ever a
jockey appeared immune to the sophomore jinx, it is Beasley.
</P>
<P>
   On the elite New York circuit, the loss of the bug would be more
problematic. But at Sam Houston, where he mucked stalls as a
teen-ager, the 5-4, 109-pound Beasley is king. And probably will
continue to be, regardless of the weight in his saddle.
</P>
<P>
   John Adger, racing manager for the nation's 13th-ranked stable _
Bob McNair's Stonerside _ said, ``At Sam Houston he'll keep getting
good mounts, with the competition not as stiff. He'll keep winning,
and that will give him confidence. He's a fine, aggressive rider,
very athletic, and he's a nice young man. I think the real good
jockeys go forward after their apprentice years, and that's what
he'll do.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mid-1970s, I was part-owner of a filly, a claimer named
Out of Order,'' Adger recalls. ``I have a picture of an apprentice
named Steve Cauthen in the winner's circle with her. He was 16, and
he looked like he was about 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Cauthen, the No. 1 apprentice in 1977, went on to win the Triple
Crown on Affirmed the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley's return to Sam Houston last month surprised many in the
industry. At that time, he ranked among Aqueduct's top 10 jockeys
and was winning 14.4 percent of his starts.
</P>
<P>
   But he may have made a shrewd career move _ into a market he can
dominate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really want to be part of making horse racing grow in this
state,'' he says. ``I plan on winning the Kentucky Derby with a
Texas-bred horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, the money's better in New York, but down here I still
make as much as any doctor. And the cost of living makes up a lot
of the difference. While I make less money here, I actually put
more away. Up there I had to spend $2,000 to put heating oil in my
house for two months.''
</P>
<P>
   However, economics had little to do with his decision to come
back to Houston, where he was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was family first, plain and simple,'' he says. His father,
mother and grandfather reside in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horse racing is my passion, but my grandfather needed me at
the moment, and I wanted to be with him,'' Beasley says. ``He's
always been my best friend. He means the world to me.''
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather, Hector Gonzalez, is 65 and ailing. Beasley
won't discuss the illness publicly, but he says, ``I think he'll
get better, God willing. Right now my priority is my family. As
soon as my grandfather's better, I'll be open to new
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   It was with that sort of adventurous spirit that Beasley set out
for Aqueduct at this time last year. Because he was a hot bug boy _
winning 22 percent of his races here _ bigger tracts were
beckoning.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley had assured trainers here he would stay through the end
of the meet. But one of the nation's most respected jockeys, Jerry
Bailey, was calling him repeatedly and advising him not to let an
opportunity pass that might not come again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very bad about leaving like that,'' Beasley says. ``I
felt like I turned my back on the trainers here. But I felt it was
the right thing for my career, and I'm glad I went.''
</P>
<P>
   He adapted easily to New York. He rented a house ``on the
Atlantic beach, with a pier going out into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like New York,'' he says. ``You get a taste of
every culture _ cultures I never knew existed. I took total
advantage of New York. I tried to see as much as I could _ the
theater shows, the comedy clubs. And I loved going to Saratoga and
upstate New York; it's gorgeous.''
</P>
<P>
   He was an instant sensation on the racetrack, even while
hampered by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   On his last day of riding at Sam Houston last winter, a horse
kicked him in the chest, fracturing his sternum. When he fell,
Beasley injured tendons in his right thumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove to New York the next day,'' he remembers, ``and the
following Sunday, my third day riding in New York, I got into a bad
spill. That's when I really messed myself up. I totally crushed my
thumb and dislocated it.''
</P>
<P>
   He feared that if the trainers knew the extent of his injury, he
wouldn't be offered many mounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a glove on my hand to hide it,'' he says. ``I did really
well, but the thumb kept getting worse. I had doctors telling me I
needed to stop, but I was being stubborn. It got to the point where
I was dangerous to myself and other people. I was having a hard
time controlling difficult horses.''
</P>
<P>
   So last spring he submitted to surgery. He's fully recovered
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seven months off helped me tremendously,'' he says, ``even
though it denied me a chance to win the Eclipse. I got to sit back
and think about all the things that had happened to me. I made
adjustments in my thinking, fine-tuned myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came back from my injury I was a fan favorite in New
York. They called me, `Stevie Cauthen.' They'd be yelling,
`Stee-vie, Stee-vie.'''
</P>
<P>
   Beasley impressed New Yorkers, the same way he has Texans, with
his work ethic (he eagerly gallops horses in the early mornings)
and his confident yet humble manner; he welcomes criticism.
</P>
<P>
   He's especially grateful for critiques from Jose Santos, winner
of last year's Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the jockeys, Santos probably helped me the most,''
Beasley says. ``He was right there, telling me, `Look, you need to
change this.' One day he said, `Hey, you looked like a monkey on
that horse.' But he saw I had some talent, and he told me how it is
because he wanted to help me better myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hudson, the former Super Bowl safety who trains horses at
Sam Houston and also at the major tracks of Kentucky, says,
``Jeremy has a lot of talent, as well as good work habits. He can
be one of the top 10 riders in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommie Morgan, Sam Houston's leading trainer, sees little
significance to the debugging. ``The weight is not going to make a
difference for me naming him to ride my horses,'' Morgan says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bug opened doors for me,'' Beasley says. ``It got me the
invitation. But I think I'll continue to get my chances. I think
I'm 10 times the rider I was last year.''
</P>
<P>
   At even weight, there's little doubt he still has the edge over
the competition _ at least in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
