<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5972 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-SAAB-ART-2     02-03 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-SAAB-ART-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAAB 9-5 AERO AND 9-3 VIGGEN: NEW TURBO JETS FROM AIR SAAB  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I bought a new 900 Turbo in 1985, Saab was basking in its
image as the purveyor of eccentric Swedish sports sedans for
30-somethings who couldn't afford BMWs and couldn't abide anything
as sensible as a Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   Economic realities have since driven Saab up the luxury scale
and toward the conventional. Saab shares a lot of parts with Opel,
its buttoned-down cousin in General Motors' global family. And it
now costs almost as much to own a Saab as a BMW.
</P>
<P>
   But the old fire occasionally still shows. Nowhere is it more
evident than in the company's flagships, the 9-3 Viggen and the 9-5
Aero. Though very different cars, they share Saab trademarks: an
off-the-beaten-path design, remarkable pep and surprising
versatility. In short, both the Viggen and the Aero are niche
vehicles for affluent drivers who value being different almost as
much as they like performance and comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the Viggen, named for the delta-wing jet fighter made
by the Saab aerospace company. Introduced in the United States in
the 1999 model year, the Viggen can be distinguished from Saab's
standard 9-3 midsize car by the front and rear spoilers. Saab
insists, by the way, that the bad-boy styling is more than a
marketing ploy, that it reduces wind resistance by 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Complementing the modifications are jazzy 17-inch alloy wheels
that show off the disk brakes and low-profile Dunlop tires (with a
Z, or high-speed, rating). And the eye-catching package is rounded
out with special colors: ``lightning blue,'' silver or black. For
2000, a Viggen sedan and convertible join the coupe.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the Viggen has terrific front bucket seats in leather
with supportive side bolsters, eight-way power adjustments and
optional heating elements. The rest of the interior accoutrements,
more or less what you'd expect on ``near luxury'' cars these days,
are borrowed from the 9-3 SE. These include an excellent sound
system, automatic climate control, automatic-dimming rear-view
mirror, trip computer and antitheft system with keyless locking.
OnStar, General Motors' concierge in the sky, is an $895 option.
</P>
<P>
   The list of safety features common to all 2000 Saabs borders on
the obsessive: antilock brakes, front air bags and belt tensioners,
side air bags for the front seat, head restraints that cradle the
head in a crash, side window defrosters, daytime running lights,
audio controls on the steering wheel, headlamp washers and wipers.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a night-panel button that shuts off the instrument
panel illumination to minimize glare but pops awake on a
need-to-know basis _ say, when the engine is revving near the red
line or the fuel is low.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the market is crowded with safe, luxurious, well-made
cars, many for less than $38,000. Apart from its innate Saab-ness,
the Viggen's main selling point is performance, and here the
verdict is mixed.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, there's the engine. Everyone knows that
Americans like cylinders: six good, eight better. Four-cylinder
powerplants seem indelibly associated with vibration, weak
acceleration and save-the-planet bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   Saab learned this the hard way in the early 1990s when it was
forced to discount deeply to move its big 9000 model, the
forerunner to the 9-5. Today you can buy the 9-5 with a
200-horsepower V6. But Saab engineers' hearts are still in
four-cylinder engines, and both the Viggen and the Aero get along
nicely with 2.3-liter, dual-overhead-cam versions equipped with
potent turbochargers that yield 230 horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the monster turbocharger and fancy electronics, this
pocket workhorse produces 258 foot-pounds of torque at a modest
2,500 engine revolutions per minute, with no discernable ``turbo
lag.'' That means the relatively light (3,100 pounds) Viggen is a
rocket ship _ a jet fighter? _ when it counts: passing on a
two-lane road or merging with high-speed traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the turbo's kick in third gear at 60 mph provided one of
the most satisfying driving experiences I can remember.
</P>
<P>
   Car and Driver magazine pushed the Viggen from a stop to 60
miles an hour is 6.5 seconds. And, not that many Americans care
these days, the combination of big turbocharger and little engine
also produces pretty good mileage figures: 20 mpg in town, 29 on
the highway. I averaged 24 while pushing the car hard every chance
I got.
</P>
<P>
   In most circumstances, the handling is up to the standard set by
the engine. The brakes feel great. And while the suspension is
softer and busier more than one might expect of a serious road car,
it does the job.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So, why am I less than than ecstatic over the Viggen? One might
quibble about the vague five-speed shifter and clutch. Or the
limited visibility: The high hood and rear deck make parallel
parking a challenge. Or the rear seat: Getting in the back isn't
easy and the legroom is tight.
</P>
<P>
   My real beef, though, is with the steering. The Viggen usually
goes where it's pointed, and the power assist is nicely tempered to
allow adequate road feel. But with the pedal to the metal in second
or third gear, the Viggen exhibits the classic systems of ``torque
steer'' _ the tendency of high-powered front-drive cars to veer
erratically to the left or right under heavy acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   The Saab people try to make a virtue of torque steer, saying
that it adds to the excitement of driving the Viggen. Even so, the
company has set the engine's computer to take the edge off the
torque steer by limiting the power available in first and second
gear.
</P>
<P>
   Is the Viggen worth $38,000 and change? For about the same money
you could take home the far more polished and only slightly less
peppy BMW 328i. But the BMW makes your upward mobility all too
obvious; a Viggen will have your friends and neighbors scratching
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   With the Aero, there is both less pain and less gain. The
steering manners in the version I drove were impeccable, most
likely because the Aero weighed 400 pounds more than the Viggen,
had wider tires and came with a slightly detuned four-speed
automatic transmission. The cabin is huge with big, ergonomically
correct seats up front, a back seat that is adequate for three
adults and a trunk that almost looks as though it could hold an old
VW Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   But every Saab 9-5 is big and comfy. The real question here is
what you get in the Aero for the $2,000 premium over the
dressed-for-success 9-5 SE.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there is the trim: The Aero has a ground-effects chin
spoiler plus minor modifications to the lower body to offset the
extra drag created by that spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the engine: The 2.3-liter four-cylinder is a bit
noisier than the 3-liter V6 in the 9-5 SE, but it manages 30 more
horsepower. More important, the torque is a bit higher over a
broader range of engine speeds, though the Aero's transmission
limits peak torque to 243 foot-pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the wheel-tire combination. The Aero comes with
17-inch alloy wheels, as opposed to the SE's 16-inchers, and the
fatter, lower-profile tires are rated for higher speeds. The
suspension has been tuned for surer footing on curves.
</P>
<P>
   All this adds up to a noticeable improvement in an already
excellent sport sedan. The low-profile tires felt surprisingly
good, with none of the ride harshness usually found in rubber
designed for maximum performance. And though the car dives a bit
more than expected in heavy braking and leans a bit more than
expected in hard turns, the handling is a pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   With the 400-pound weight disadvantage, the Aero is noticeably
tamer than the Viggen. But again, the turbo offers punch when you
need it. And with the smooth automatic set to ``sport'' mode, a
nudge of the throttle brings forth the turbo boost.
</P>
<P>
   The Aero is too close to a normal car in looks and performance
to attract the dyed-in-the-wool Saab crowd drawn to the Viggen. But
at a shade above $40,000, it is arguably a better buy. Like the
other 9-5s, the Aero is a practical luxury sedan with more interior
room than, say, the Mercedes E-Class. But unlike the other 9-5s,
its acceleration can make you feel young again. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Small is beautiful, as long as it's turbocharged. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
