<HEADLINE>
MANUFACTURERS' DRIVING SCHOOLS: THE HOMEWORK IS IN YOUR CAR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JIM McCRAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you had your last driving lesson just before you got a
license, you may be ready for a refresher course. Four European
carmakers are offering instruction: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BMW
</P>
<P>
   This German manufacturer of high-performance cars now has a
high-performance driving school at a track near its factory in
Spartanburg, S.C. BMW offers six schools: for new drivers; for
car-control skills; for advanced car-control skills; a
performance-driving ``M school'' for owners of BMW M3 coupes and M
roadsters; an M5 school starting for owners of its new M5 sedan;
and an off-roading curriculum for buyers of its X5 sport utility.
</P>
<P>
   BMW's instructors emphasize skills used in everyday driving.
They take students through maneuvers intended to increase awareness
and control in extraordinary situations, like fast cornering,
driving through a wall of water or over a wet skid pad.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition is free with the purchase of an M5; the other courses
range in price from $495 to $895, including the use of 3-Series
cars provided by the school. (Participants do not use their own
cars.) Detailed information is available at (888) 345-4269. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAND ROVER
</P>
<P>
   This was the first car company in the United States to offer
structured driver education. The original school, at the Equinox
resort in Manchester, Vt., opened in 1997; a second school has been
added at the Greenbrier in White Sulphur Springs, W. Va.
Instructors at both teach techniques for off-road driving; in the
winter, extra attention is given to driving on ice and snow.
</P>
<P>
   The school is open to all licensed and insured drivers, whether
or not they own a Land Rover. Tuition is $150 for a one-hour
session for up to three persons, and $100 for each additional hour,
with a $50 discount for four to eight hours of instruction. Land
Rover owners get a 10 percent discount.
</P>
<P>
   More information is available at (800) 346-3493 or
www.LandRover.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MERCEDES-BENZ
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, the company began a training course for owners
of its M-Class utility vehicles near its factory in Tuscaloosa,
Ala. The emphasis is on off-road maneuvering. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAAB
</P>
<P>
   Buyers of the 9-3 Viggen are invited to a special course at the
challenging Road Atlanta racetrack, near Saab's American
headquarters in Norcross, Ga. Because Saab builds aircraft with the
same name, the school is called the Viggen Flight Academy. The free
course is taught by instructors at the Panoz high-performance
school.
</P>
<P>
   Saab's school concentrates on steering, shifting and braking
maneuvers, skid control, slaloms and evasive techniques; it
concludes with an autocross and dinner with Saab management.
Information is available at www.saabusa.com/viggen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
