<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MATTEL-RESIGN-ART-NYT     02-03 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTEL-RESIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATTEL CHAIRMAN STEPS DOWN AFTER REPORTING LOSS IN 1999 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The executive who made Barbie into a mega-brand stepped down
from the top post at Mattel Thursday as the toy maker reported a
loss for 1999 and continuing problems in its software unit.
</P>
<P>
   Jill E. Barad, chairman and chief executive of Mattel Inc. for
three years, announced her resignation after an unscheduled meeting
in New York of Mattel's directors. The board said it was searching
for a replacement for Barad and that two directors would serve as
top officers in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in El Segundo, Calif., has been struggling
for the last couple of years to broaden its offerings beyond dolls,
cars and preschool toys. Last May, it acquired Learning Co. for
$3.8 million in an attempt to broaden its software and interactive
game offerings. But the price proved far too high since the unit
not only failed to meet sales projections but dragged down the rest
of the company's performance.
</P>
<P>
   By acting ahead of the scheduled board meeting next week, the
company's board appeared to be trying to put its problems aside in
time for Toy Fair, which starts on Feb. 14 and is the biggest event
in the industry. Toy manufacturers use the event to showcase their
offerings for the next holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Barad was steadily criticized for her acquisition of Learning
Co., which failed to improve the company's bottom line despite her
repeated assurances that it was on the verge of doing so. Last
month, Mattel announced that it had hired Bernard Stolar, a
respected software executive, to turn around the unit, known for
its Reader Rabbit and Carmen Sandiego titles.
</P>
<P>
   The company still has to rebuild its credibility with Wall
Street. Stock analysts lost faith in Mattel's pronouncements
because earnings repeatedly fell short of what the company
estimated. For example, Mattel said in October that earnings for
the fourth quarter of last year would be 70 cents to 80 cents a
share. Instead, the company said Thursday that it lost 4 cents a
share, or $184 million, because of a one-time charge and sales
declines at Learning Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time, it was the last time, and it wasn't going to happen
again,'' said Martin Romm, an analyst for Credit Suisse First
Boston. ``Lo and behold, it did happen again. Unfortunately, Jill
went to the well a couple of times too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Learning Co., which lost $183 million in the quarter and $206
million for the year, erased profits at the parent company, despite
strong sales of Fisher-Price and Pleasant Co. products. For the
full year, Mattel lost $82 million, or 21 cents a shares, compared
with a $206 million gain, or 51 cents a share in 1998, as
calculated to include the Learning Co. acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the problems are not over. Mattel said Thursday
that it would take another revamping charge of $75 million to $100
million in the first quarter to reflect continuing problems at the
software maker.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that two of its directors, William D. Rollnick
and Ronald M. Loeb, would serve as chairman and acting chief
executive officer, respectively. The company said that Richard
Ferry of Korn/Ferry International was conducting a search for a new
chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts late Thursday, Barad, 48,
said she was leaving because of the unacceptable results at
Learning Co., but she insisted that other divisions, including
Barbie, Pleasant Co. and Fisher-Price, were doing better than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Barad joined Mattel 20 years ago as a product manager. She was
named marketing director for Barbie in 1982, expanding what had
been a somewhat tired line into one that featured an entire
universe of cars, houses, pets and siblings for the surreally
sculpted, perpetually cheerful plastic doll.
</P>
<P>
   Largely on the strength of her success with Barbie, which
enjoyed little competition until the mid-1990s, Barad rose to
become chief operating officer before taking over as chief
executive in January 1997. She was one of just four women heading
major American corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Her first year was a stellar one for Mattel. The company's sales
rose 6.6 percent, and earnings increased by 24.5 percent. But in
1998, the company reported declining sales, its first such report
in a decade. It was alarming for a company whose annual sales
growth had averaged 21 percent, with 35.7 percent annual earnings
growth, over the five years before Barad became chief executive.
Sales continued to decline last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel's share price rose to a high of $45.625 in March 1998,
but plunged late last year. On Thursday, the stock closed at
$11.9375, but then fell 13 percent to $10.825 in after-hours
trading after the company's earnings report.
</P>
<P>
   Barad is known as a keen marketer and brilliant presenter, but
her critics have said she failed in important management areas,
including financial matters and diplomacy. Even after she became
chief operating officer, she continued to keep close watch on the
Barbie division, monitoring doll designs down to minor details on
the dolls' faces. Sales began to trail off in 1994, as Beanie
Babies and other toys began to nibble away market share, and in
response, Mattel began producing thousands of Barbies from its
collectors' line _ angering collectors who had paid $50 to $100 for
the dolls, believing that they were limited editions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing I can say to gloss over how devastating the
Learning Co.'s results have been to Mattel's overall performance,''
Barad said. ``Because there must be accountability, I and the board
agree that I must resign today as chairman and chief executive and
from the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Silver, publisher of the Toy Book, an industry journal,
said, ``They overpaid severely for a company that they felt was on
the way up, and it really wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties at Learning Co. have to do with slowing sales
in the CD-ROM business in general, a Mattel spokesman said. But one
analyst said the problem was a lack of new offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't developed any new titles, and their business is
old and tired,'' Romm of Credit Suisse First Boston said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that it was unfortunate Barad would be remembered for
the debacle in the software division, since she had made other
useful acquisitions, including the Pleasant Co. line of dolls and
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Her tenure was tumultuous, with several key executives resigning
over what one executive called ``the Jill Factor,'' an oblique
reference to her volatile management style. For that reason, the
board had little choice but to appoint directors to manage the
company while it conducts an outside search for a replacement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
