<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIRREFFS A QUIET WINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ John Shirreffs maintains a high winning
percentage and low profile. You'd get long odds on that double.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old former Marine saddled 28 winners in only 69
tries on the Southern California circuit in 1998-99, including 10
for 21 a year ago at Santa Anita and an unbelievable 7 for 10 at
the autumn Hollywood Park meet. His stakes winners, since becoming
the private trainer for Marshall Naify's 505 Farms in 1994, include
Bertrando and the enormous mare, Manistique.
</P>
<P>
   Yet few bettors would recognize Shirreffs under his baseball
cap.
</P>
<P>
   He's rarely seen on intertrack television interviews. He rarely
lingers in the winner's circle to talk to writers.
</P>
<P>
   After victories, he prefers to walk the horse back to his stall,
a task most trainers leave to a lowly groom. It's not as if he's
unfriendly or inarticulate. He just likes it better this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is the training of the horses,'' Shirreffs explained
Thursday by phone from his Hollywood Park barn. ``I try not to get
distracted by things.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirreffs also sounds as if he's afraid he'd anger the racing
gods if he basked in his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know that as great as things may seem at the time,
things can run in cycles. I think it's best to keep things in
perspective,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the El Segundo resident's talent for avoiding the spotlight
is about to be tested, beginning Saturday at Santa Anita, when
he'll run California-bred Cliquot in the $500,000 Strub Stakes for
4-year-olds and million-dollar yearling purchase Malabar Gold in
the $150,000 San Vicente for 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Malabar Gold, who'll be ridden by leading Santa Anita jockey
Corey Nakatani in the 7-furlong San Vicente, is one of several 505
Farms-owned prospects for the April 8 Santa Anita Derby and the May
6 Kentucky Derby. Too many to count on one hand.
</P>
<P>
   Shirreffs will hope Malabar Gold, a son of 1990 Kentucky Derby
winner Unbridled, runs as he did in a 12-length maiden victory at
Hollywood Park on Nov. 20, not as he did in a fade from first to
last in the Hollywood Futurity on Dec. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always try to look on the positive side of things,''
Shirreffs said of the decision to jump Malabar Gold up to the Grade
I stakes level after two starts. ``Probably, it was a great wakeup
call, (a signal to) not get carried away, and get back to the
things that make horses run better.''
</P>
<P>
   For Malabar Gold, those things include fitting him with a
stronger bit and training him harder. The former should allow
Nakatani more control than Eddie Delahoussaye had in the Futurity,
and the latter should rid the colt of the freshness that plagued
him that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After an awkward start, Delahoussaye sent him through traffic,
and then Malabar Gold ran off, leading by 4 lengths after
one-quarter mile.
</P>
<P>
   He wound up 29 tired lengths behind winner Captain Steve at the
end of the 1 1/16-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody gets excited about a young horse with a lot of
ability. We tried to take a giant leap and it didn't work out,''
Shirreffs said.
</P>
<P>
   Malabar Gold will face five other 3-year-olds in the San
Vicente, which has sent five winners on to Kentucky Derby
victories, most recently Silver Charm in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents include Gibson County, winner of a Cal-bred stakes
for Bob Baffert; Joopy Doopy, third behind Shirreffs' Swept
Overboard in the San Miguel; and Tavasco, coming off his Remington
Park Futurity victory in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Shirreffs doubts Swept Overboard is cut out for the Derby
distances. Hook and Ladder, a 5-length maiden winner at Hollywood
Park, is sidelined with a foot injury. The trainer is playing wait
and see with I've Decided, who lost a shoe when he ran seventh in
the Golden Gate Derby. David Copperfield, another Shirreffs
3-year-old with promise, will point for the March 4 San Rafael, the
next stepping stone to the Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Shirreffs isn't boasting about his Derby possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a mistake to say, `We're going to do this, we're
going to do that,''' he said with an audible shrug. ``We have some
nice 3-year-olds if they continue to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Shirreffs' only experience with the Kentucky Derby
has been watching it on TV. A New Hampshire farm boy whose father
bred horses, Shirreffs served in Vietnam, then was on his way to
Hawaii to become a surfer when he stopped in California, as he
tells the story.
</P>
<P>
   He began his racing career as a stable hand for Gene Cleveland
in the early 1970s and worked as an assistant to Brian Mayberry and
Bill Spawr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Naify picked me out of nowhere (to be his trainer),''
Shirreffs said. ``I've never thought I'd be in this position.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an ideal situation for him. The private training job
relieves him of a major headache, the worry about attracting and
keeping clients with different agendas.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who'd prefer to avoid the media distraction will
have his work cut out for him if he takes a horse to Churchill
Downs in May.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend: Shirreffs' Cliquot, fifth behind winner Saint's
Honor and fourth-place General Challenge in the San Fernando
Stakes, will face them as well as Cape Canaveral and Luftikus in
the Strub.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Cat Thief, second in the San Fernando, takes on older
horses in the $300,000 San Antonio Handicap, carrying a pound less
than top-weighted Budroyale (121) while Dixie Dot Com (119),
Elaborate (114) and Moore's Flat (113) are also expected to enter.
</P>
<P>
   The Strub and the San Antonio are preps for the March 4 Santa
Anita Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the East Coast's top older horses are entered in the
$500,000 Donn Handicap on Saturday at Gulfstream Park: The entry of
Behrens (121) and Pleasant Breeze (112) is a 2-1 morning-line
favorite; Almutawakel (120) is 3-1. Trainer Jim Bond said Behrens
or Pleasant Breeze will start but not both; Jorge Chavez will
ride. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES &QL; 
Santa Anita leaders: Jockeys (through Wednesday): Corey Nakatani,
34 wins; Kent Desormeaux and Alex Solis, 22; David Flores, 17; Pat
Valenzuela, 16. Trainers: Bobby Frankel, 16; Bob Baffert, 14; Ron
McAnally, 8; Ron Ellis and Richard Mandella, 7. &QL; 
Pincay update: Laffit Pincay rode two winners Wednesday at Santa
Anita, giving him 15 at the meet, tying Chris McCarron for sixth in
the standings. Pincay's record win total is 8,859. He'll ride on
the Super Saturday card at Turf Paradise. &QL; 
On the stakes schedule: At Santa Anita: Saturday, $500,000 Strub
Stakes, 4-year-olds, 1 miles, $150,000 San Vicente, 3-year-olds, 7
furlongs, and $150,000 Pro or Con Handicap, California-bred fillies
and mares, 1 mile on turf; Sunday, $300,000 San Antonio Handicap,
4-year-olds and up, 1 miles, and $200,000 La Canada, 4-year-old
fillies, 1 miles. At Gulfstream Park: Saturday, $500,000 Donn
Handicap, 3-year-olds and up, 1 miles. &QL; 
Mileposts: Chris Antley's return to the saddle is delayed until
late February. The two-time Kentucky Derby-winning jockey, who has
taken a three-month break, hurt a knee while exercising a horse
last week at Santa Anita.... Captain Steve, third as the favorite
in the Santa Catalina Stakes on Sunday, will race next in the Risen
Star at the New Orleans Fair Grounds on Feb. 20, trainer Bob
Baffert said.... Another 3-year-old heading out of town is War
Chant. Neil Drysdale is sending the allowance winner to the Feb. 12
Golden State Mile at Bay Meadows.... Corey Nakatani and Bobby
Frankel, the hottest jockey-trainer combination at Santa Anita,
also led their divisions nationally at the end of January....
Thursday marked the 10th anniversary of Bill Shoemaker's farewell
as a jockey, a fourth-place finish aboard Patchy Groundfog in a
Santa Anita stakes called the Legend's Last Ride.... Oaklawn Park
in Arkansas opens today, Remington Park in Oklahoma on Saturday....
Washington state officials have banned equine nasal strips, citing
the possibility they'll fall off in post parades and races.
California will start to permit the breathing aids March 1.... Alex
Solis has been away from Santa Anita this week, riding in a big
race in Saudi Arabia.... Da Hoss trainer Michael Dickinson appealed
a 30-day suspension for a clenbuterol positive at Charles Town
racetrack in West Virginia.... Edward Petracco, a New Jersey-based
trainer, received a five-year suspension after two of his horses
tested positive for clenbuterol and four other drugs following
races at Philadelphia Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
