<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vodafone and Mannesmann In $183 Billion Merger Deal
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone AirTouch of Britain is buying Mannesmann of Germany in
an all-stock transaction worth $183 billion. If consummated, the
takeover will vastly expand the geographic reach of Vodafone, which
already is the world's biggest wireless telephone company, giving
it dominance in the European market and a global base of more than
50 million customers. Vodafone already has a major presence in the
United States and two dozen countries in Asia and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan Nomination Confirmed
</P>
<P>
   The Senate overwhelmingly confirmed Alan Greenspan's nomination
to a fourth term as chairman of the Federal Reserve after members
of both parties lauded his performance over the last dozen years in
nurturing the economy's long expansion. The action gave Greenspan,
who is 73, another four-year term as head of the central bank. The
vote was 89-4.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Offers Its Workers Computers
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor announced that each of its 350,000 employees would be
offered a high-speed desktop computer made by Hewlett-Packard, a
color printer and unlimited Internet access for just $5 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Technology Shares Climb Sharply
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks bounded higher, but blue chips were little
changed. The Nasdaq composite index rose 137.02 points, or 3.36
percent, to 4,210.98, its third biggest point gain in history. The
Dow Jones industrial average increased 10.24 points, to 11,013.44,
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index jumped 15.85 points, to
1,424.97.
</P>
<P>
   Europe Raises Interest Rates
</P>
<P>
   The European Central Bank raised interest rates for the second
time in three months, declaring that the weakness of Europe's
year-old single currency had created concern about price stability.
</P>
<P>
   EDS Reports Strong Quarter
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Data Systems, still rebounding from two disastrous
years, reported fourth-quarter earnings that beat estimates, and it
announced a more than fourfold increase in new contracts during the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak and Hewlett Form Venture
</P>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak and Hewlett-Packard announced a joint venture to
develop and market retail and consumer photofinishing products
using the Internet and Hewlett-Packard's inkjet printer technology.
The company is expected to generate between $500 million and $1
billion in sales by 2005. Shares of Hewlett-Packard closed at
$113.50, up $2.9375. Kodak shares closed at $63.125, up $2.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Big Law Firm Joins Salary Frenzy
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy over law firm salaries spread to the nation's largest
firm, Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom, which told associates
that they would receive raises of about 40 percent. First-year
associates will now make $140,000 a year in base salary.
</P>
<P>
   Factory Orders Surged in December
</P>
<P>
   A surge in factory orders in December gave manufacturers their
best year since 1995. That, plus big sales gains at retailers and a
surprise dip in unemployment applications all show the economy is
starting 2000 with plenty of momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales rose 4.9 percent in January as a brisk economy
fueled spending on clothing, home furnishings and appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Spice Maker Reaches Settlement
</P>
<P>
   McCormick &AMP; Co., the spice maker, agreed to let antitrust
enforcers review its sales contracts for 10 years to head off a
lawsuit contending that it had illegally charged some grocers more
than others.
</P>
</TEXT>
