<HEADLINE>
SOUTH CAROLINA: TOO CLOSE TO CALL? 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ An influential South Carolina pollster whose
poll recently showed Gov. George W. Bush with a 20-point lead here,
said Thursday that far more independents and Democrats may vote in
the Feb. 19 Republican primary than he had earlier anticipated. As
a result, he said, the race may now be too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   The pollster, David Woodard, a political science professor at
Clemson University who conducts the Palmetto Poll, said Thursday
that since his poll was conducted last month the Democratic party
canceled its March 9 primary and will hold only caucuses, which
will probably free many Democrats to cast a vote for McCain in the
open Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, he said, McCain's double-digit victory in
New Hampshire on Tuesday will energize South Carolina independents
in large numbers to vote for him, a factor that he said was not
anticipated in his earlier poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best polling minds in the country didn't anticipate the
size of the independent vote in New Hampshire,'' he said. ``If you
told me right now that the race was even, I would say that could
very well be possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Two polls taken in South Carolina since the New Hampshire
primary, in fact, showed a much closer race than previously.
</P>
<P>
   Any registered voter can participate in the primary, regardless
of party affiliation. Although independents have traditionally not
been a factor in previous primaries, which tend to be dominated by
Republican regulars, Woodard said McCain may be the candidate to
change that tradition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
