<SLUG> BC-TIMES-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4TH-QUARTER EARNINGS ROSE 24 PERCENT AT THE TIMES COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Times Co. reported a rise of 24 percent
in fourth-quarter earnings Thursday, exceeding analysts' estimates,
on gains in advertising for technology products, financial services
and Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   At the company's flagship newspaper, The New York Times,
advertising revenue growth continued to accelerate as the year
ended, increasing 35.5 percent in December, compared with December
1998.
</P>
<P>
   As an industry, newspapers have long been classed by investors
as mature, with limited growth potential. Reflecting investors'
surprise that even the optimistic December revenue estimates had
understated the 1999 performance of several newspaper companies,
Kevin Gruneich, an analyst with Bear Stearns, said: ``You call this
mature media? It's going through the ceiling. These are the good
old days.''
</P>
<P>
   Excluding one-time charges, the Times Co. earned $108.4 million,
or 61 cents a share, compared with $87.3 million, or 47 cents a
share, in the quarter a year earlier. The company took a charge of
$3.1 million after taxes to pay for expenses related to work-force
reductions at The Boston Globe and at the company's regional
newspaper group. Revenue rose 12.8 percent, to $882.5 million for
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected the company to earn 57 cents a share,
according to a survey by First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks
corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Class A shares of the Times company rose $1.75, or 3.8 percent,
to $47.625 in trading Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of strength in the industry during the fourth quarter
was help-wanted classified advertising, which provides high-margin
revenue. For six quarters, beginning in early 1998, classified
advertising had suffered significant downturns at newspapers like
The San Jose Mercury, which is owned by Knight Ridder, and The
Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fourth quarter of 1999, analysts said, The Mercury
and The Globe, both based in high-technology centers, saw steady
rises in their help-wanted advertising revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Co. became the latest major newspaper company to
report strong double-digit percentile growth in fourth-quarter
earnings, following the Gannett Co., Knight Ridder and Dow Jones &AMP;
Co. The profits were buoyed in part by continuing declines in the
price of newsprint.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Co.'s Internet properties, including The New York
Times on the Web (nytimes.com), boston.com and nytoday.com, all
showed increases in the number of sessions each day in December,
compared with the same month a year earlier. For 1999, average
daily page views at boston.com were up 44.5 percent; at nytimes.com
the increase was 59.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, the Times Co. said it would issue a new class of
stock to track the value of the company's Internet properties.
Times Company Digital, the unit that operates those properties,
includes the three sites mentioned above, and others like
winetoday.com, abuzz.com and golfdigest.com.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the
company reported that Times Company Digital had revenue of $15.3
million, up 48 percent from the first nine months of 1998. Its net
losses were $11.7 million, up 108 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas M. Arthur, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
offered a note of caution Thbursday, saying that the company's
strong advertising revenue growth in the second half of 1999 would
provide a tough basis for comparison in this year's second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are really obviously outstanding, particularly
December,'' he said. ``The question is: Is this the peak?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
