<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MCCAIN-BALLOT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUSH AND PATAKI HALT EFFORTS TO KEEP McCAIN OFF N.Y. BALLOT  
(subs to delete extra `the' from lede graf, `...the presidential
primary...') 
(bl) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fearing that they were energizing Sen. John McCain's
candidacy, Gov. George W. Bush and his chief supporter in New York,
Gov. George Pataki, on Thursday abandoned their efforts to keep
McCain out of the presidential primary and said they would insure
that he is on the ballot statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Pataki, who both had insisted for weeks that the
primary rules were not burdensome, reversed themselves after
McCain's landslide victory in New Hampshire had increasingly
exposed them to criticism that they were rigging the New York
contest to halt McCain's advance.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the governors sensed the skirmish over the primary
ballot was giving McCain powerful ammunition in the upcoming
contests in South Carolina and Michigan to portray himself as an
outsider crusading against a corrupt political system. McCain, who
had qualified for the New York primary in only 19 of the state's 31
congressional districts, has also made overhauling the campaign
finance laws a cornerstone of his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Pataki conceded that the campaign leading to the
March 7 New York primary ``should be about ideas and issues, not
about technicalities. Gov. Bush will win that campaign because he
has the ideas and he has the vision.''
</P>
<P>
   The surrender by Bush and Pataki over the ballot issue adds even
more luster to a McCain campaign that is on a remarkable upswing
this week, and hopes to continue its surge as it heads to the South
Carolina primary on Feb. 19, and then to Arizona and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has repeatedly demanded that Bush rein in the state
party, hailed the decision to let him on the ballot statewide.
``Republicans of New York, rejoice! You're free!'' he said while
campaigning in South Carolina on Thursday. ``I always thought
Texans wanted a fair fight, and he obviously didn't want one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has sought to distance himself from the dispute, saying
that it was up to the New York Republican State Committee to
determine how to handle the challenges to the McCain candidacy and
that everyone had to play by the same rules. But hours after Bush's
loss in New Hampshire, his chief strategist, Karl Rove, called
Republican leaders in New York on Wednesday and urged them to quell
what had been transformed into a David-and-Goliath fight and to
stem the political damage it had wrought.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters Thursday night on his campaign plane on a
tarmac in Dover, Del., before leaving for Michigan, Bush said
Pataki had informed Rove on Thursday afternoon that the party would
let McCain on the ballot in New York, which has the third-largest
number of delegates to the party convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard that this was a decision that he and the party
made,'' Bush said, referring to Pataki. ``We said, `That's the
right decision.' I welcome the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In an odd coda to the fight, McCain spoke by phone with former
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., who had been Pataki's political
patron but had spoken out in recent weeks in favor of letting
McCain on the ballot statewide. ``Hey Alfonse, how are you doing,
pal?'' McCain told D'Amato. ``I understand you've been doing the
Lord's work for me.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain still faces uphill battles in states like South Carolina
and New York, where the Republican establishment stands solidly
behind Bush. Despite an influx of donations after his success in
New Hampshire, the senator's war chest is tens of millions of
dollars smaller than Bush's. And even with the burst of publicity
from New Hampshire and the ballot fight in New York, McCain still
confronts the daunting task of trying to finance increasingly
expensive campaigns in much larger states than New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Thursday ended a lengthy battle that had
focused widespread attention on New York's rules, which are the
toughest in the country, requiring campaigns to circulate petitions
in each of the state's 31 congressional districts while adhering to
a bevy of do's and don't's. The rules heavily favor the candidate
backed by the state party _ in this case, Bush _ because underdogs
do not have the party foot soldiers to collect signatures and
weather the inevitable legal challenges to petitions.
</P>
<P>
   With a shoe-string organization that hardly crosses the whole
state, McCain had sought to get on the ballot, but after petition
challenges by the party, he had qualified in only 19 of the 31
districts. McCain's lawyers sued in federal court to overturn the
system, and a judge had been expected to rule soon in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   How Pataki will engineer getting McCain on the ballot statewide
was a question that Pataki aides declined to discuss Thursday
night. It may require that Pataki ask the Legislature to approve a
special bill putting the three major contenders _ Bush, McCain and
Steve Forbes _ on the ballot. Forbes has already qualified across
the state, while Bush is on the ballot in all but one district,
having been thrown off in the South Bronx because campaign workers
committed petition fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the state party were engaged in talks with McCain's
lawyers Thursday night, hoping to settle the case without having
the precedent of a legal ruling by the federal court that could
affect future elections.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's lawyers were adamant that they would not simply
accept a deal that placed McCain on the ballot without overturning
many of the rules they believe are unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain didn't fight this hard to get on the ballot just
for himself,'' said one of the lawyers, Burt Neuborne, legal
director at the Brennan Center for Justice at New York University
School of Law. ``One of the thing he wants is to reform the system.
Until they are willing to acknowledge that the system is
unconstitutional, I have nothing to say to them.''
</P>
<P>
   If some of the election rules are abolished, the outcome of the
legal case and the settlement talks could thus influence future
presidential primaries and other New York elections.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Pataki has been on the defensive over the ballot
challenges in recent weeks, his aides Thursday night sought to turn
the tables on McCain once again. ``We are going to make sure that
they focus on ideas and issues, not on ballot access,'' said Zenia
Mucha, a spokeswoman for Pataki. ``The fact of the matter is they
are hiding behind this issue because they are devoid of ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   But the head of the McCain campaign in New York, Guy Molinari,
the Staten Island borough president, said that no matter how the
Bush partisans depicted the shift, their candidate had been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never understood why they would allow this thing to occur as
long as it had,'' Molinari said. ``It has helped our campaign
enormously. It is a great issue for us, but it's not an issue that
we wanted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
