<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-COLUMN-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEARING YOUR HEART ON YOUR PORTFOLIO  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're interested in security, get a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of that advice during a seminar I conducted last
month in Florida. An irate investor yelled at me, accusing me of
being a liar.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment of his outburst, I was contrasting the short- and
long-term performances of Michael Murphy, editor of the
one-year-old Technology Investing newsletter and the
longer-established California Technology Stock Letter, of Half Moon
Bay, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Those two letters performed extraordinarily well in 1999,
earning 157 percent and 119.7 percent, respectively, enough to win
the No. 1 and No. 6 places among the 150 letters I monitor. But
even after 1999s blowout performance, the California Technology
Stock Letter had returned just 6.9 percent, annualized, since the
end of 1982, when I started tracking it. That is less than a
percentage point ahead of a money market fund over that time.
</P>
<P>
   The angry investor said that he made a lot of money in 1999 by
following Murphy's advice, and that my criticisms of the editor's
long-term record therefore had to be wrong. I might have argued
with his line of reasoning, but he stomped out.
</P>
<P>
   Had this investor found the results of my research threatening?
It wasn't that he needed a scorekeeper to tell him how much money
he made last year. He already knew that he did very well. And he
should have been happy that I was waving others away from his
preferred stock picker. After all, I have found that people receive
less favorable prices when trading on the advice of the most
popular letters than they do using less exposed ones.
</P>
<P>
   I'm convinced that this investor wanted some reassurance that he
was doing the right thing. And I suspect that he was also seeking
peer approval, in this case from the thousands of other investors
attending the conference. Instead of finding his psychological
needs met, he heard me criticize his investment adviser's record.
No wonder he might have felt so threatened.
</P>
<P>
   His reaction would be of little interest if it were isolated and
unique. But it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from my workshops over the years, such strong emotional
impulses are quite widespread _ even if this fellow's reactions
were a mite extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Investors often develop a cultlike devotion to one investment
guru or another. And when they do so, objectivity goes out the
window. That isn't to say that the investors' psychological needs
should be dismissed. After all, investing is an arena filled with
uncertainty; it's only natural for people to seek approval and
affirmation in such an environment. But it is hazardous to one's
wealth to seek such psychological security at the price of
objectivity.
</P>
<P>
   I have two suggestions to help investors keep their cool:
</P>
<P>
   _ Take only those risks that are within your psychological
comfort zone. That can be tough in a bull market, when risk is an
abstract notion. But try this: Spend an hour or two at your local
library, reading the business pages of a newspaper from 1973 or
1974, during the last major bear market for stocks. Imagine your
current portfolio in such an era, when each market decline, far
from presaging a renewal of an up trend, precipitated yet another
decline. If you conclude that you're too heavily invested to
stomach such a market, reduce your exposure. Don't wait until the
bottom of the next bear market to discover your true comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Subscribe to an investment letter with which you strongly
disagree. If you have convincing responses to each of its
arguments, fine. But take it as a warning if you find that the
letter's positions eventually become as compelling as your own.
That can mean that you are not being entirely objective in your
assessments, and that you should scrutinize your reasoning more
closely. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of The Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Annandale, Va. His column on investment
strategies appears every other week. E-mail:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
