<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-CRASH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST BEFORE JET CRASH, PILOTS CALLED MECHANIC FOR HELP
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wash., Ariz.) (REWRITES head; UPDATES thruout; DELETES map note) 
 (rk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT HUENEME, Calif. _ A few minutes before an Alaska Airlines
jet crashed offshore here on Monday night, the crew radioed a
company mechanic in Los Angeles that the device that forms most of
the horizontal section of the tail was pushing the nose down and
asked if there was a way to cut power to the device.
</P>
<P>
   The crew had apparently run through its emergency procedures,
which included pulling out circuit breakers to try to cut off power
to the two motors that control the horizontal stabilizer, and they
asked the mechanic if he knew of any ``hidden circuit breakers,''
said John Hammerschmidt, a member of the National Transportation
Safety Board assigned to the crash. All 88 people aboard the MD-83
were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Hammerschmidt, relating a summary of his investigators'
interview with the mechanic, said, ``The flight crew stated
something like, `We are in a worse situation than we were.''' But
the mechanic told the two pilots that he knew of no hidden circuit
breakers.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, which had left Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, for San
Francisco and Seattle but was preparing for an emergency landing at
Los Angeles when the mechanic was called, crashed a few minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanical problem in the tail of the plane, which led it to
turn upside down and corkscrew into the water, came in a system
that is supposed to withstand failures, engineers at Boeing said
Thursday, speaking as searchers recovered the second ``black box,''
which they hope will give them a clearer picture of what happened.
</P>
<P>
   The second box, the flight data recorder, which was put on a
late afternoon flight to the board's headquarters in Washington,
keeps track of the position of the horizontal stabilizer, along
with other data. The first box, the cockpit voice recorder, was
recovered on Wednesday. When it was played by investigators in
Washington Thursday, it showed that the two pilots were in the
midst of discussing a problem with the horizontal stabilizer at the
beginning of the tape, more than 30 minutes before the crash.
Investigators said previously that the crew had first raised their
problem with air traffic controllers about 11 minutes before the
crash, after dropping rapidly from their assigned altitude. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Washington, James Hall, the chairman of the National
Transportation Safety Board, said the voice tape showed that the
plane was pitching nose down. ``The crew was able to arrest the
descent,'' Hall said, and ``continued trouble-shooting and
preparing the airplane for landing'' in Los Angeles. But then, he
said, ``control was suddenly lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The preparations and the loss of control may be related. Boeing
engineers and pilots of the MD-80 series airplane say the airplane
tends to pitch up or down in response to changes in its speed or
fuel consumption or changes in the position of the flaps and the
slats, devices on the wings that are used on takeoff and landing.
Extending the slats and flaps, as a pilot would do while preparing
to land, would aggravate the nose-down tendency.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing engineers Thursday described a detailed emergency
procedure for coping with a malfunctioning stabilizer system. The
stabilizer, which makes up the front two-thirds of the horizontal
tail, can be angled up or down to keep the nose at the desired
angle and is typically adjusted hundreds of times in a flight, they
said. It is moved on its hinge by a jack screw, similar to the
long, thick screw that raises or lowers a garage door. Two motors
drive the screw, one at the command of the pilots and the other
when the autopilot is in charge, although pilots can operate that
one as well, if needed. The emergency procedure involves switching
off the circuit breakers on each motor, in alternation, to figure
out which one has a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The stabilizer system includes both motors and brakes, and both
would have to fail for the part to move in an undesired manner, the
Boeing engineers said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane is supposed to be flyable even if the stabilizer is
immobilized, although engineers said it might require the pilots to
pull hard on their control yokes, possibly both at once.
Hammerschmidt also said Thursday evening that investigators had
interviewed the crew that flew the plane into Puerto Vallarta
earlier on Monday and that they reported the plane had operated
without any problem between Seattle and San Francisco, and again
from San Francisco to Puerto Vallarta. A newspaper report had said
that the plane experienced problems with the horizontal control
system in its last completed leg.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that large parts of the tail section had been
spotted by a robot submarine, and that searchers had found the
aircraft's log book, floating on the water.
</P>
<P>
   Hammerschmidt also said that an American Airlines flight that
left Phoenix on Wednesday but returned quickly because of a problem
with its horizontal stabilizer had been found to have a
short-circuit in a cockpit switch. That plane was also an MD-83,
but whether there was a connection between the incidents remained
unclear.
</P>
</TEXT>
