<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-PACBELL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Pac Bell Accuses AT&AMP;T of Slamming Customers  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A month after AT&AMP;T bashed Pacific Bell for ``slamming'' 80,000 of
its local-toll customers _ or switching their service without
permission _ Pac Bell now claims it was AT&AMP;T who was responsible
for the foul play.
<P>
   In a complaint filed with the California Public Utilities
Commission yesterday, Pac Bell accused AT&AMP;T of engaging in a
``systematic and deceptive campaign to illegally switch customers'
local toll service away from Pacific Bell to AT&AMP;T.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Pac Bell officials said one other company,
which it declined to name, was guilty of slamming more local-toll
customers than AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint is strikingly similar to one filed by AT&AMP;T against
Pac Bell with the PUC in late December. At the time, AT&AMP;T chastised
Pac Bell for leading a ``systematic and fraudulent campaign'' of
misleading customers into switching to Pac Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like they took my press release (and rewrote it),''
said AT&AMP;T spokesman James Peterson. ``That's my language.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pac Bell's Catherine McGreevy said, ``The difference is that
we handled the complaints'' from customers who said they'd been
slammed. McGreevy, the company's director of consumer protection,
said all of the 80,000 customers told Pac Bell telemarketers or
customer service representatives that they never wanted to be
switched to AT&AMP;T for local-toll calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were alarmed,'' she said. ``I don't know how AT&AMP;T can
blame us for slamming when it (involves) our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a customer switches to AT&AMP;T, Pac Bell sends the
customer ``Win Back'' letters and sometimes has telemarketers
follow up, asking whether the customer really wanted to drop Pac
Bell as their service provider. AT&AMP;T claims such practices are
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The wrestling match is a byproduct of regulators' decision to
open up the California telecommunications market to competition.
Before May, only Pac Bell was able to directly handle local toll
calls, usually between 12 and 25 miles, too far for local service,
but too close for long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Billingsley, a telecommunications expert with the PUC's
Office of Ratepayer Advocates, said she wasn't surprised by Pac
Bell's response to AT&AMP;T's complaint. ``Pacific Bell is very
aggressive about defending its market share in all things,''
Billingsley said.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell was apparently the first to raise the slamming
accusation. In its original complaint, AT&AMP;T said Pac Bell tried to
charge AT&AMP;T $1 million to recover the cost of switching the
customers back to Pac Bell by saying the customers were slammed.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell executives yesterday said they wanted to settle the
issue directly with AT&AMP;T, but were forced to complain to the PUC
after AT&AMP;T filed its complaint.
</P>
<P>
   In general, slamming is one of the biggest sources of complaints
with the PUC. But Linda Woods, a manager at the consumer services
division, said only a small number of the gripes involve local-toll
calling. Woods said she wasn't sure whether AT&AMP;T or Pac Bell had
drawn more complaints.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
