<SLUG> BC-SC-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 ON THE DEFENSIVE, BUSH TALKS TOUGH AS McCAIN RIDES HIGH ON (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI and MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUMTER, S.C. _ Gov. George W. Bush struck an unusually combative
posture toward Sen. John McCain on Thursday, accusing him of
running misleading television commercials and insinuating that he
had not lived up to his own call for integrity in government.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McCain, buoyed by a surge of fund-raising over the
Internet, moved through South Carolina with the air of a
front-runner, speaking to overflow crowds.
</P>
<P>
   At an oceanside rally in the retirement haven of Seabrook
Island, he touted his big victory in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Tuesday night we interfered with a coronation,'' McCain
said. ``They call it a bump in the road. My friends, it was a land
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush invoked McCain's crusade to diminish the influence of money
in Washington and said there were questions McCain needed to answer
about whether his own actions matched his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to let him explain,'' Bush told reporters at a news
conference in Sumter, ``how receiving people before his committee
who then contribute to his campaign is consistent.'' Bush was
referring to the Arizona senator's chairmanship of the Senate
Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the commercial, which Bush characterized as an
unwarranted assertion that his proposal for a tax cut would
endanger Social Security, Bush began the news conference with a
sort of declaration of political war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to start right now by saying that any ad that's
being run by John McCain that infers, implies or says that I don't
reserve money for Social Security is Washington-style politics,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in this state are going to hear what the facts
are,'' Bush added. ``The people in South Carolina want an honest
campaign. They want an open campaign. They don't want
Washington-style politics.''
</P>
<P>
   It was arguably the toughest talk that Bush had directed at
McCain and it reflected the defensive position in which Bush
suddenly found himself.
</P>
<P>
   He was trounced by McCain in the New Hampshire primary Tuesday,
and two polls released Thursday suggested that in South Carolina,
which holds its primary Feb. 19, McCain and Bush were now in a
close race. Before Tuesday, polls showed McCain trailing Bush by
margins of 20 percentage points or more.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally in Sumter on Thursday morning that preceded the news
conference, Bush went directly after McCain's claim, as a military
hero and former prisoner of war in North Vietnam, to the hearts and
votes of veterans. Veterans represent a disproportionately large
percentage of the population in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Bush surrounded himself on the steps of an old, picturesque
courthouse with crisply uniformed veterans whose medals glinted
brightly on their chests. They included six medal of honor
recipients, five retired generals and Adm. Thomas Moorer, a former
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff under President Richard M.
Nixon. All were throwing their formal support behind Bush.
</P>
<P>
   An enormous American flag hovered over Bush. The six white
pillars flanking him were festooned in red, white and blue bunting.
A marching band played.
</P>
<P>
   One of the veterans, J. Thomas Burch Jr., chairman of the
National Vietnam and Gulf War Veterans Committee, which was
formally endorsing Bush, listed several recent pieces of
legislation involving Vietnam or the Persian Gulf war that he said
McCain had not supported.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the power to help these veterans,'' Burch said. ``He
came home, forgot us. But, fortunately, we found a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush then delivered remarks that promised not only a stronger
military but also better treatment of the men and women who served
in it.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain dismissed the criticism and Bush's effort to appeal
to veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every major veterans group in American has given me their
highest award,'' McCain said in an interview. ``Here's the
question: Have I fooled all these veterans, or is there a little
bit of foolishness going on?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain strategists laughed off the accusations, saying they
showed the Bush campaign's desperation. But eager to shoot down the
assertions before they stick, McCain aides released a list of his
veterans awards, as well as legislation that the senator has backed
dealing with Agent Orange and gulf war syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bush is talking about the military, our strength, it
shows chaos over there,'' Michael Murphy, a McCain strategist, said
in an interview. ``It would be like me saying, `Mike Tyson, I want
you in the ring.'''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy added, ``Next thing, we'll see Bush in his Air National
Guard uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Opinsky, a spokesman for McCain, disputed Bush's
accusation that McCain was running a commercial that unfairly
characterized Bush's position on Social Security. Opinsky noted
that while the spot maintains that McCain is the Republican
presidential candidate who would most strenuously safeguard Social
Security, it does not mention Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments about McCain's ethics were restrained, but
stronger than those he made last month, when McCain faced several
days of tough questions from reporters and extensive news coverage
about the relationship between people who had given money to his
campaign and those who had business before the Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, he said: ``I'm not making any allegations at all. I am
just suggesting that his claim that he is the outsider is a claim
I'm not going to let him get away with.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush kept hammering at the point that he had given McCain too
wide a berth and too free a pass in New Hampshire and that McCain's
committee chairmanship reflected nearly two decades in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, in the course of the debate, I'm tagged with
being the Washington guy,'' Bush told reporters, attacking McCain's
descriptions of himself as an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that he's the person who's been the Washington
insider,'' Bush said. ``He's the person who's a chairman of a
committee, and I'm the person who has a reform agenda.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
