<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FDA-PREGNANCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA DRAWS FIRE FOR A RULE ON SUPPLEMENTS AND PREGNANCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying they feared dietary supplements' unknown
effects on fetuses, two leading experts in birth defects asked the
Food and Drug Administration Thursday to revoke a new rule that
allows supplement manufacturers to market products for morning
sickness and leg swelling in pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The rule, to take effect on Monday, permits the makers to sell
herbal products and other supplements for those pregnancy-related
conditions without subjecting them to the safety and effectiveness
testing that is required of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the public health community, the rules should not be in the
direction of promoting the use of untested products for women
during pregnancy,'' said Dr. Godfrey Oakley, who retired in 1998
after 15 years as director of the division of birth defects at the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. ``It's a setup for a
problem for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley and the other scholar, Dr. Philip J. Landrigan of the
Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York, said they had been
unaware of the rule, announced last month, until the advocacy group
Public Citizen brought it to their attention.
</P>
<P>
   What effect they will have is unclear. An FDA spokesman said
only that the agency would ``carefully consider'' their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The rule stems from a 1994 law, the Dietary Supplement Health
and Education Act, which severely restricts the FDA's authority to
regulate herbal products and other supplements. The law
distinguishes between supplements, which ``affect the structure or
function of the body,'' and drugs, which prevent, treat or cure
disease.
</P>
<P>
   In interpreting the law, the FDA has reasoned that because
pregnancy is a natural life process and not a disease, supplements
may be marketed for ``ordinary morning sickness'' and for swelling,
or edema, without prior review of their safety or effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to the agency, Landrigan wrote that its decision
``has the potential to put pregnant women and their offspring at
serious risk of unwitting exposure to chemical teratogens'' _
substances that cause birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   ``To any pediatrician of my generation,'' he wrote, ``this
statement calls powerfully to mind the chilling story of the
teratogen thalidomide that 40 years ago was specifically
recommended for the treatment of morning sickness.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only because the FDA refused to approve the drug, he
said, that thousands of babies in this country were spared
deformity, a fate that befell many in Europe, Canada, Australia and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the current debate is only academic: because the new
rule is just now taking effect, no supplements have yet been
marketed for morning sickness or any other pregnancy-related
condition, said a spokeswoman for the Consumer Products Healthcare
Association, which represents dietary supplement manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bill Soller, the association's director of science and
technology, noted that if the FDA determined that a supplement was
unsafe, it could take the product off the market. But Oakley said
it could take years of using a product before evidence of birth
defects emerged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
