<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-RATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING CURRENCY WEAKNESS, EUROPEANS RAISE KEY RATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Declaring that the weakness of Europe's year-old single
currency had created concern about price stability, the European
Central Bank raised interest rates Thursday for the second time in
three months.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in the benchmark refinancing rate, to 3.25 percent from
3 percent, came the day after the Federal Reserve increased
interest rates in the United States and indicated that further
rises might be necessary to keep America's strong economy from
producing inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and investors had expected the European rate
increase, though many said they had not expected it before the
spring. The timing led some economists to express fear that
Europe's fledgling central bank would be seen as sailing in the
wake of the Federal Reserve. But financial markets in Europe
appeared, for the moment at least, to welcome the move.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the European Central Bank, Wim Duisenberg,
maintained that the timing of the move after the Federal Reserve
action was coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   Share prices reacted favorably, with the benchmark index of the
Paris stock exchange closing up 3.41 percent and that in Frankfurt
rising 2.54 percent. In Britain, which has not adopted the single
currency, the euro, and sets monetary rates independently, stocks
gained one-third of a percent.
</P>
<P>
   The euro rose as well, settling in New York late in the day at
98.85 cents, up from 97.57 cents on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hints of Thursday's increase in the interest rate the European
Central Bank charges commercial banks for short-term loans had come
on Monday, when Duisenberg suggested that continued weakness of the
euro threatened to generate inflation. At a news conference at the
bank's headquarters in Frankfurt Thursday, Duisenberg repeated that
reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   The euro's drop in value compared with the dollar, he said, was
becoming a ``cause of concern with regard to future price
stability.'' As the euro weakens, the prices Europeans pay for
goods they import from the United States or pay for in dollars,
such as oil, increase. So, Duisenberg said, ``import prices can be
expected to rise further, thereby increasing the risk that upward
pressure on consumer-price inflation might materialize in the
medium term.''
</P>
<P>
   An increase in interest rates tends to strengthen a currency by
making deposits denominated in that currency more attractive. Even
with the euro's improvement in trading Thursday, it has been
languishing below $1 for much of the last week.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of January, the European currency was valued almost
12 percent below its average worth during the first quarter of
1999, and it has continued to erode since then.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank, before increasing rates in November, to 3
percent from 2.5 percent, had been primarily concerned with stoking
sluggish European economies, which have shown less vigor than the
American economy through most of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But in raising rates Thursday, the central bank put its emphasis
clearly on avoiding inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Though evidence of inflation in European countries is sketchy,
Duisenberg said that the bank's principal yardstick for growth in
the supply of money, which is an inflation barometer, showed an
annual increase of 6.1 percent in the last quarter of 1999, well
above its 1999 target of 4.5 percent. Duisenberg said long-term
bond rates in Europe, another inflation signpost, showed evidence
of continued strong increases, reaching the highest level at the
end of January since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Though economic growth has been strong in France and Spain, and
in several smaller European countries like Ireland and the
Netherlands, it remains fitful in Germany and Italy, which with
France form the core of the continent's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's move drew mixed reactions from economists. Many said
the rate increase was premature and the evidence of inflationary
danger cited by Duisenberg was overdrawn. Some accused the central
bank of acting primarily to slow or reverse the euro's slide
against the dollar, and said the move appeared to be a reaction to
the Fed's move on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   `With their timing, they threw into question their
independence,'' said Ulrich Ramm, chief economist at Commerzbank in
Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Ramm said he saw little danger in the move for European growth
prospects, since many economists had expected a rate increase
within the next six to eight weeks. But he added, ``It would be a
real embarrassment if the euro fell further.''
</P>
</TEXT>
