<HEADER>
A6012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-NYT &LR;      02-03 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG DAY'S JOURNEY INTO MORNING FINDS GORE LONG ON TALK
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even with Michael Dukakis nodding off in the
second row, Al Gore kept talking. One of the Secret Service agents
standing at the edge of the crowd had his eyes closed, too, and the
press corps was literally moaning for mercy _ so loudly, in fact,
that many of the real people at the town hall meeting here at Los
Angeles City College turned around to look.
</P>
<P>
   But until nearly 1 o'clock Thursday morning _ or 4 a.m. back in
New York, where his day had begun _ the vice president stood close
to his questioners, looked straight into their eyes and tried to
close the sale, finally wrapping up after 3 hours 18 minutes (just
a few minutes shy, aides said, of his personal record, 3:24).
</P>
<P>
   He had warned them, though, telling the crowd of about 200
straight away that he would stay to answer all questions, until
California's presidential primary on March 7 if necessary. Often
his answers were so comprehensive that they seemed to begin with
the creation of the earth _ the biblical version of which, he
happened to mention, he does not believe should be taught in
science class.
</P>
<P>
   Though California is not considered a state where retail
politics works particularly well, the audience here, mostly
undecided Democrats, not only rewarded the candidate's endurance
but stayed afterward and asked him to elaborate on a variety of
answers.
</P>
<P>
   Several people said later that they particularly appreciated his
not always giving the answer that his questioner seemed to want.
When a retired evangelist asked the vice president if he was a
born-again Christian, he said yes, but went on to say that this did
not mean he wanted to be associated with what he called the
intolerance of Jerry Falwell. ``I'm sorry to be long-winded,'' Gore
said by way of finishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am, too,'' replied the man, who, having had a little fun at
Gore's expense, added that ``America needs to get back on its
knees.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president made clear that he did not agree with the
questioner's support for prayer in schools, and he also defended
the welfare overhaul to a man who said many people had been hurt by
it.
</P>
<P>
   He did not, however, correct a young man who said, ``Many years
ago you wrote books about the Internet.'' Instead, he joked about
having stretched the truth on that topic some time back: ``You
notice he didn't say I invented the Internet; I didn't say that
this evening either, did I?''
</P>
<P>
   He may have made a teensy overstatement, though, when he told
the crowd that ``we had a huge event with 3,000 people at Ohio
State University'' earlier in the day. Officials at that rally said
the room where it had taken place did not hold more than 1,200
people, and, given the area needed for the staging erected for the
occasion, they estimated the crowd at 500.
</P>
<P>
   In another answer, about how to keep youths from joining gangs,
Gore said the whole idea that quality time spent with children
could make up for a shortage of time with them ``is a lie,'' but
then added, ``There is some truth to that lie.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 10-minute answer to the young man's question about the
future of the Internet, Gore was nothing if not thorough. He began
with a description of ``stagflation'' caused by the oil crisis of
1973. Eventually moving into the present, he said, ``Now, instead
of big price increases, we have a price decrease for processing
information, low unemployment and low inflation because the price
of processing information is cut in half every 18 months.''
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, he worked in a statement of support for
universal preschool and for smaller class sizes before finally
wrapping up that same answer about the Internet by admitting,
``I've given you a mouthful there.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Gore seemed to go out of his way to state the obvious.
To a woman who told him that she was disabled and that she and her
three children had previously been homeless, he said, ``I'm glad
you have a home.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience, though, seemed quite moved by his attentions.
</P>
<P>
   A man who spoke passionately about his work with children,
trying to keep them out of gangs, said he was holding down two jobs
and volunteering a lot of his time to help others in his community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need support,'' the man said. ``Jesus Christ, we need more
people up there helping, and when you become president _ and I hope
you're not doubting yourself that you will become president _
hopefully you will remember what we said here at LACC''
</P>
<P>
   After the marathon, Brian Price, a previously undecided
screenwriter in the audience, said: ``I saw two things I hadn't
seen on television _ a plan and passion. I want somebody who can
take on the anti-gun-control morons on the other side, and I saw
somebody who looks like they have the pluck to fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
