<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6014 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-TUFTE-ART-2TAKES-     02-03 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TUFTE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGNING FOR THE CHARTS THAT TEACH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Mass., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 6)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID CORCORAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESHIRE, Conn. _ Professor Edward R. Tufte's books have a
certain austere elegance about them, starting with ``The Visual
Display of Quantitative Information'' (1983), which sold hundreds
of thousands of copies and established his reputation as a guru of
information graphics.
</P>
<P>
   So when Tufte was surfing Amazon.com recently for books about
business graphics presentations, he was perversely delighted with
what he found.
</P>
<P>
   ``The titles are so wonderfully bad,'' he said one gray morning
last month, sitting in the vast open kitchen of his low-slung house
in the hills north of New Haven. He waved a hand at a stack of new
books, their covers ablaze with rainbow-colored charts and
sock-you-in-the-face titles like ``Power Pitches,'' ``Creating Cool
PowerPoint 97 Presentations'' and ``Point, Click &AMP; Wow!''
</P>
<P>
   Tufte opened a book more or less at random to a chart with the
headline ``U.S. &AMP; Canada: Sales Growth %.'' On a shimmering purple
background were maps of the United States in red and Canada in
bright green; alongside that, two rows of nine three-dimensional
bars, one red and one green, unlabeled except for the puzzling
caption ``To May 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a nice example of a very dopey graphic,'' he said.
``No scales; the variables aren't clear; three phony dimensions for
one-dimensional data. You could make an argument that graphics like
this actually subtract from the sum of human knowledge, by making
people stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   To Tufte (pronounced TUF-tee), that chart exemplifies a
dismaying pattern in the way data are presented in too many
business meetings, especially those dominated by ``the overhead
projector that magically rises out of the rosewood table'' or its
electronic successor, a computer linked to a projector and equipped
with a presentation program, like Microsoft's PowerPoint.
</P>
<P>
   In these presentations, he says, visual flash and dash
substitute for real analysis of useful information. The images are
by nature ``low resolution'': they must be drawn big and bold to be
visible across a room, so the amount of information conveyed in any
one image is scant.
</P>
<P>
   And the resolution is driven even lower by what Tufte calls
chart junk: meaningless tricks done only because the software makes
them possible, like turning a one-dimensional piece of information
(a sales figure) into a three-dimensional bar, as if it were a
stack of potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   He says such graphics _ low in information, confused in display,
muddled in thinking _ can have catastrophic consequences. A chapter
in his latest book, ``Visual Explanations'' (1997; published, like
his others, by his own company, Graphics Press), is devoted to a
particularly hapless collection of charts and tables prepared by
frantic engineers for Morton Thiokol, which makes solid-fuel rocket
boosters for the space shuttle, as they tried unsuccessfully to
dissuade NASA from launching the shuttle Challenger in January
1986.
</P>
<P>
   Buried in those tables, he said, were statistics that would have
made a more compelling case, if anyone had managed to display them
properly: the rubber O-ring seals in the boosters tended to leak at
low temperatures. The morning after those charts were faxed to NASA
at Cape Canaveral, the Challenger was launched during a rare
Florida freeze. An O-ring failed, and the rocket blew up 73 seconds
after liftoff, killing all seven astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   More often, the consequences of poorly presented graphics are
mundane _ wasted time and an audience bored into cynicism or
slumber. Typically, Tufte said, a presentation begins with an
overhead projection of ``the dreaded bullet list'' _ generic
objectives that resemble the automatic mission statements that you
can generate with a mouse-click on the ``Dilbert'' Web site. (``It
is our mission to enthusiastically maintain quality paradigms.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``The pompous, inflated, generic thought gives you no leverage
on actually analyzing and solving a business situation,'' he said.
``And the problems with the bullet list and the overhead are
identically reproduced in PowerPoint. It's just that now we go
through a computer, and we're thankful if the presentation doesn't
crash.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That view is hardly uncontroversial. Brian Reilly, president of
a computer consulting company in Manhattan and the author of one of
the books in Tufte's pile, ``Create PowerPoint Presentations in a
Weekend'' (Prima Publishing, 1997), acknowledges that
do-it-yourself graphics programs like PowerPoint have their
limitations.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``In the hands of a skilled designer, it's
fabulous. In the hands of an unskilled designer, a book is a
disaster, too. Anything can be misused.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the latest technology could overcome the problem of big,
fat, vacuous images: ``The new projectors can be very high
resolution. If you can see it on your monitor, you can see it on
the projector.''
</P>
<P>
   And not everyone agrees that low-resolution, high-impact visuals
are an inferior way to communicate. ``I hate to sound trite, but
sometimes less is more,'' said Stephen M. Kosslyn, a professor of
psychology at Harvard and the author of ``Elements of Graph
Design'' (W.H. Freeman, 1994). ``We need to respect the limitations
of our perception and memory systems. It's often better to have a
series of simple displays that can be taken in at a glance than to
try to pack everything into one graphic.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tufte, 57, who taught in Yale's political science
department for 22 years before assuming emeritus status last year,
favors a different model. ``The task is not to have `high-impact
presentations,' or `point, click, wow!' or `power pitches,''' he
said. ``The point is to explain something. The right metaphor for
presentations is not power or PowerPoint. It's not television or
theater. It's teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   He likes the way teachers often start their classes with
handouts. ``Handouts _ pieces of paper _ are by far the
highest-resolution means of information transfer,'' he said. ``A
good meeting probably begins with a handout. You might spend the
first 10 or 15 minutes of a meeting reading it, before anyone says
a thing. Then you use your talk for the reasoning about the
high-resolution material that's in front of us, instead of somebody
reading aloud from the bullet list.''
</P>
<P>
   He would eliminate meetings that result in no exchange of useful
information, as Louis V. Gerstner Jr. sought to do when he took
over as chief executive of IBM in 1993. ``Ask yourself, as they're
reading aloud: `Why are we having this meeting? The rate of
information transfer is just too low,''' Tufte said. ``The virtue
of this advice is it probably eliminates about half of all
corporate meetings, which would probably be the most profound
money-saving piece of advice ever given in the history of corporate
consulting.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosslyn, the Harvard psychologist, doubted that it would ever be
that simple. ``I think his books are gorgeous,'' he said of Tufte.
``He's done a huge service to the field by making people aware of
the importance of graphic displays. But that's not business
graphics. His graphics are often for explanatory data analysis _
not the same as crisp, clear communication.''
</P>
<P>
   To Tufte, business graphics are no different from any other
kind, because the goals are ultimately the same: exchanging
information, reasoning, problem-solving. ``Good design is clear
thinking made visible, and bad design is stupidity made visible,''
he said. ``So when you see a display filled with chart junk,
there's a deeper corruption: they don't know what they're talking
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6017 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-AUSTRIA-POLITICS-1STL     02-03 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIA'S NEW GOVERNMENT WILL INCLUDE FREEDOM PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Phrase added at end of lede graf to spell out European
Union's concerns, and the 2nd sentence of graf 6 clarified.)  
(See also AUSTRIA-EUROPE, AUSTRIA-VOICES) 
(lh) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Austria's president announced Thursday that he
would swear in a new government on Friday that includes Joerg
Haider's anti-immigrant Freedom Party, setting the country on a
collision course with the European Union, which regards Haider's
party as xenophobic and extremist.
</P>
<P>
   President Thomas Klestil announced the decision after a final
day of hesitation that was marked by objections to two proposed
Freedom Party members as cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Klestil's decision bowed to the logic of Austrian democracy,
since the Freedom Party and the conservative People's Party led by
Wolfgang Schuessel won enough seats in elections in October to
govern. But it also gave stature to a rightist party that has not
hesitated to employ bigotry and racist vitriol.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a last-minute declaration by the coalition promising to
work ``for an Austria in which xenophobia, anti-Semitism and racism
have no place,'' reaction was swift. The other 14 governments of
the European Union confirmed that they would downgrade diplomatic
relations with Vienna and isolate the nation, as they had
threatened on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Israel said it would recall its ambassador as soon as the
swearing-in is completed. France and Portugal announced that they
would impose sanctions on Friday. And in Washington, a State
Department spokesman, James Foley, reiterated warnings that the
United States would review its relationship with Austria as soon as
Haider's party joined the government.
</P>
<P>
   In the new government, Schuessel will be chancellor. The
sensitive ministries of justice and defense will go to the Freedom
Party, but Haider himself will not be in the government. He has
made it clear that he prefers to remain out of national office
until he is strong enough to become chancellor. Haider's party got
the chance to join a coalition cabinet after talks between
Schuessel and the Social Democrats collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   In the election in October, the Social Democrats emerged as the
strongest party, but Haider's Freedom Party came in second for the
first time. The right-wing coalition has 104 seats in the
183-member Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union stand is based on the view that Haider's
politics, including isolated and subsequently regretted expressions
of sympathy for aspects of Hitler's rule, make him incompatible
with the values of the European Union, and on the pragmatic concern
that other extreme-right parties may benefit from his party's
inclusion in the Austrian government.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Haider's arrival in power has set up a highly charged
test of the respective powers of nations and the embryonic
government of the European Union. How the test is resolved will
weigh heavily on Europe's unity and Europe's future, issues that in
turn affect the United States directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is too simplistic to say that we must keep Austria in
Europe at all costs,'' Belgium's foreign minister, Louis Michel,
said Thursday in a statement indicating the passions Haider's rise
have ignited. ``I think Europe can very well do without Austria. We
don't need it.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, dressed in an uncharacteristically sober dark suit
and tie, Haider, 50, appeared in a vast hall of the gilt-dripping
Hofburg Palace and sat beneath the European Union's blue-and-gold
flag as he signed the declaration committing Austria to ``respect,
tolerance and understanding for all human beings irrespective of
their origin.''
</P>
<P>
   The declaration, drafted in part by Klestil, amounted to a
bizarre list of democratic commitments and mea culpas for the
prospective government of a modern European state to be signing.
But it reflected the degree of alarm that Haider's entry into
government has provoked in European nations governed mainly by the
center-left.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Austria accepts her responsibility arising out the tragic
history of the 20th century and the horrendous crimes of the
National Socialist regime,'' it said, referring to the Nazis
alongside whom many Austrians fought.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, the son of a virulently Nazi family and owner of an
estate that once belonged to a Jewish family that fled, had
expressed admiration for the Waffen SS and for Hitler's labor
policies, before retracting the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's declaration continued: ``Nationalism, dictatorship
and intolerance brought war, xenophobia, bondage, racism and mass
murder. The singularity of the crimes of the Holocaust, which are
without precedent in history, are an exhortation to permanent
alertness against all forms of dictatorship and totalitarianism.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel described the text as a ``pre-emptive political
strike'' intended to reassure the world about Austria's commitment
to human rights. ``This declaration is very important because it
deals with the fears of many friends at home and abroad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel, who was foreign minister in the outgoing coalition of
Social Democratic and People's parties, has portrayed himself as
the guarantor of the presentability of the restless, chameleonic
Haider.
</P>
<P>
   But the statement, for all its evident worthiness, could not
conjure away the fact that Haider ran an election campaign last
year that included posters suggesting that most black people in
Austria are drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, the governor of the southern province of Carinthia, has
been a consistent opponent of immigration and has somehow combined
his professed commitment to freedom with the view that Winston
Churchill was as evil as Stalin.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1988 and 1998, an estimated 405,000 immigrants entered
Austria, a country of 8 million people. Many came from the wartorn
Balkans, newly free countries in Eastern Europe and Turkey. Some
neighborhoods in Vienna have changed radically in appearance and
atmosphere, creating unease.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, Austria's immigration policy, at least with
respect to Balkan refugees, has been more open than those of most
of its European critics. But the sudden arrival of many foreigners
bolstered Haider's political message among Austrians who are afraid
of losing jobs or are put off by schools in which most children are
foreign.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A brief statement from Klestil's office, issued after a second
meeting Thursday with Haider and Schuessel, said: ``President
Thomas Klestil informed Wolfgang Schuessel that he should appear
tomorrow, Friday, Feb. 4, 2000, at 12 o'clock with his government
team in the president's official chambers to be sworn in.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement went on to say that two proposed Freedom Party
members of the government _ Thomas Prinzhorn and Hilmar Kabas _ had
been rejected as minister of innovation and defense respectively.
</P>
<P>
   In language typical of the regular excesses of Haider's
movement, Prinzhorn recently threatened to give Klestil ``a bloody
head'' if he did not approve the right-wing coalition. This is the
sort of tone that was also apparent in Haider's recent description
of the French president, Jacques Chirac, as a ``megalomaniac.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Freedom Party leader in Vienna, Kabas was immediately
responsible for the xenophobic election posters that clearly sought
to play on fears and misgivings over immigration in changing
neighborhoods of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Kabas was replaced as defense minister by Herbert Scheibner, the
36-year-old spokesman for defense in the Freedom Party. The highly
sensitive justice ministry, which has some power to direct the
thrust of prosecutors' activities, went to another Freedom Party
member, Michael Kruger.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Heinz Grasser, a Freedom Party member and spokesman for the
Canadian automotive parts supplier Magna International, will become
finance minister. He will have the delicate task of working closely
with European Union partners, who seem likely to shun him, on
Europe's shared currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Benita Ferrero-Waldner, a member of the People's Party and state
secretary at the Foreign Ministry in the outgoing government, was
promoted to foreign minister. She will clearly seek to mollify the
European Union, but it was not immediately clear how Austria could
circumvent its looming isolation.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 European governments that issued the statement committing
themselves to punitive measures against Austria have said they will
avoid bilateral meetings with Austrian ministers. But the
governments stopped short of barring them from European Union
meetings for the simple reason that nothing has happened in Austria
that could legally justify such a step.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
