<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6021 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-ALASKA-CRASH-SEARCH-S     02-03 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-CRASH-SEARCH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALVAGE SHIPS PLAY KEY ROLE IN RECOVERY EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The summer of 1998 found the salvage ship M/V Kellie Chouest
trolling the waters off North Carolina, searching for the bones of
the Union Navy's first ironclad, the Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Chouest was pushing through the choppy waters off
Port Hueneme, Calif., looking for the remains of Alaska Airlines
Flight 261.
</P>
<P>
   Orange-painted and with cranes extending into the sea, the
Chouest has excelled at its gruesome task: Wednesday evening, the
ship's remote-operated vehicle _ a remote-controlled unmanned
submarine named Scorpio I _ found the plane's cockpit voice
recorder in nearly 700 feet of water. Thursday morning, it found
the flight-data recorder at a similar depth.
</P>
<P>
   The civilian-owned, Navy-contracted salvage ship is one of a
virtual armada combing the seas off the southern California coast
for clues to Flight 261's crash into the sea. It has been grueling.
Crews aboard the Chouest spent 15 hours ordering Scorpio I to pick
through the debris on the ocean floor with its manipulator arm
before finding the data recorder covered in pieces of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important phase to any investigation is to conduct a
survey of the debris field,'' said Capt. Joe Leidig, commander of
the Navy's Submarine Development Squadron Five, which is assisting
in the salvage operation for the National Transportation Safety
Board. ``We've already done that, in a sense, to find the
recorders. The recorders are our first priority. After we find
them, then the NTSB can direct us to what we need to survey next.''
</P>
<P>
   Both recorders were found in the midst of the plane's debris
field, the inevitable result of a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   When a plane falls from a high altitude into water, it will
break apart wherever the forces of physics are strongest. As it
falls to the seabed, different pieces of the plane are caught by
currents, and litter the sea floor.
</P>
<P>
   That litter can greatly complicate things. When oceanographer
Robert Ballard discovered the RMS Titanic in the 1980s, the ship's
debris field took up countless square miles of the North Atlantic
seabed, sending Ballard off in the wrong direction several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take an airplane and drop it in water 700 feet down,''
said Rick Benson, president of Ballard Dive and Salvage in Seattle,
who has been salvaging ships for 25 years, ``and look at what your
debris field looks like. It's going to be a pretty good-sized
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the recorders had ``pingers,'' noisemakers that give
off a signal so ships or planes can find them, and so the plane's
debris field was only an issue in that part of the search because
pieces of fractured jetliner covered the data-recorder on the sea
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The search for Flight 261's flight and data recorders was the
first objective of the recovery mission. The recorders, which
contain the last 30 minutes of cockpit conversation and hours of
data from sensors around the aircraft. The recorders, sometimes
known as ``black boxes,'' can quickly tell investigators what went
wrong with a plane, often saving lengthy and costly recovery
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In separate 1996 incidents, two Boeing 757s crashed, once off
the coast of Peru, once off the coast of the Dominican Republic.
Like Flight 261, both planes crashed in deep water that made
recovery difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``pingers'' paid off, and investigators were able to
recover the black boxes, hastening the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, the hard work begins. The rest of the wreckage has
no pingers attached. The NTSB will tell the Navy what the next
salvage priority is. And the Navy will send Scorpio I to the seabed
to recover the engines, the stabilizers, pieces of the fuselage,
pieces of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   It will send the Klein 2000 down, too. The Klein 2000 is another
remote-operated vehicle, but instead of carrying a manipulator arm,
spotlights and video cameras, it carries a sonar rig.
</P>
<P>
   The Klein 2000 bounces sound waves off the sea floor to draw a
silhouette of the seabed. It's very effective in locating large
pieces of metal, but far less effective when the seabed is covered
in metal. Everything generates a return, and the Klein 2000's ocean
floor imagery needs to be supplemented by the Scorpio I's cameras
so investigators can bring the right pieces to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   When the pieces are identified on the ocean floor, the Scorpio I
is able to lift up to 250 pounds on its own, or can place a large
basket on the ocean bed and sweep debris into it, as if it were a
broom, and the basket a dustpan.
</P>
<P>
   The depth of the wreckage presents its own problem: because of
the water pressure and the lack of any light, divers can only work
for short times on the wreck without needing to rest. So the
Scorpio I must come down and put straps under large pieces of the
wreck, so they can be lifted out of the water by the Kellie
Chouest's two cranes.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't happened, yet. The NTSB and Navy are still
planning, and while the search area hasn't been defined exactly,
yet, every time a ship passes over the area and films the seabed or
paints a sonar image, the area becomes more defined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the NTSB tells us what to do, we'll bring up everything
they ask us to,'' Leidig said. ``We'll do what they ask us to.
Parts of the plane, eventually, the victims.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
