<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER OUTSHINES FILM STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The hottest celebrity playing in this weekend's
Pebble Beach National Pro-Am golf tournament hasn't been an ``Am''
since his Nike-commercial debut, when he proclaimed to the world
``I Am Tiger Woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, he's only gotten bigger since.
</P>
<P>
   So while Saturday's traditional TV day to gawk at club-carrying
Kevin Costner might be upstaged by an even bigger story _ Tiger's
pursuit of six PGA Tour wins in a row it really wouldn't be
improper for CBS' cameras to stay fixed on the Southern
California-native megastar and his entourage for every possible
second of scenic coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Tin Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime Tiger plays in a tournament, he's part of the story,''
said CBS golf coordinating producer Lance Barrow. ``This tournament
is different in that Saturday all the celebrities come out and
people want to see Clint Eastwood and Andy Garcia and Kevin
Costner. It's always one of our highest-rated shows of the year.
But Sunday it really becomes a professional tournament. We won't
let him get in the way Saturday, but you can't help but watch Tiger
if he's anywhere close.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS golf analyst Gary McCord, who with partner David Feherty
started his late-night 15-minute highlight package/comedy routine
and continues it tonight at 12:35 a.m., has boldly gone on the
record as saying Woods will not break Byron Nelson's streak of 11
tour wins in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going with the odds, based on the pure fact no one
can win six in a row under these conditions and against these
players today,'' said McCord, who last year joined the PGA Senior
Tour and surprised many with a couple of victories, including the
Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Feherty, who usually has the on-course assignment of following
Woods, says if anyone can catch 11 in a row or more, it's Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played for 25 years as a pro at the highest level and I can
honestly tell you there are some situations he finds himself that
there isn't another human on the planet who can do what he's
capable of doing,'' said Feherty. ``He's so far ahead of the rest
of the field. ... It's like you're watching a different species.''
</P>
<P>
   An issue of trust: Having reached the punitive phase in John
Rocker's slams-across-America case _ he has the players' union
appealing the one-month suspension and $20,000 fine handed down by
from Major League Baseball on Monday we'd like to take a moment to
assess the damage.
</P>
<P>
   The damage, that is, on the media's side.
</P>
<P>
   If you can detour past what the Atlanta Braves reliever said,
some could interpret this as another shameful hit-and-run,
media-created event.
</P>
<P>
   Since the article by baseball beat reporter Jeff Pearlman ran in
the Dec.27 Sports Illustrated, sports-talk radio hosts and TV
commentators have had no problem counter-attacking Rocker. But
there hasn't been much revealed about the other side of the story.
Pearlman has done only a couple of radio interviews, none out here,
and has since stopped because he feels the story stands on its own
and he didn't want to get in the way of it, said an SI spokesman.
That's unfortunate, because it leaves more questions than answers.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker said what he said about minorities, homosexuals and
whatever else was flying through his mind during a car ride with
the reporter. Assuming it was all on the record _ Rocker never said
it wasn't or retracted what was printed, only apologized for it _
then, sure, it was probably fair game to include in the story. And
you have to assume that since the reporter spent six or seven hours
with Rocker, it was a fair representation of Rocker's personality,
not something taken out of context.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, we didn't get to see the interview take place.
This wasn't Ted Koppel with Al Campanis, giving him second and
third chances to clarify or recant his statements.
</P>
<P>
   What this might lead to, however, is print journalists needing
to explain the process to the skeptical readers, to stop hiding
behind these walls that tend to separate rather than protect.
</P>
<P>
   Until that perception is clarified, readers are likely to
continue a love/hate relationship with the media, and athletes will
rely more on using their Web sites to filter their own words. And
interviews with athletes who feel there's even greater potential of
being set up won't happen. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
__The Three Tenors of College Basketball _ Dick Enberg with Billy
Packer and Al McGuire _ might tour only once this year, namely
Saturday for CBS' coverage of the UConn-Michigan State game.
McGuire, 71, has even said this will be his last year of
broadcasting. So sports-media nostalgia buffs best have the tape
machine working. Said Enberg of the game he did two weeks ago with
Packer for his CBS debut: ``I felt I was stumbling around because
we didn't know the timing of each other. It was like driving an old
pickup and we found all the old gears. Now, how are we going to
make up 19, 20 years in a two-hour telecast? We won't let an encore
bow to get in the way of the game, though. But you know within 10
minutes, Al and Billy will get into some disagreement because when
Al says `black,' Billy says `white.' Our reportage won't be to soft
violin music.' '' &QL; 
__Cincinnati Reds play-by-play man Marty Brenneman was named
recipient of the Ford Frick Award and will be inducted into
Baseball's Hall of Fame. &QL; 
Dick Vermeil, a guest tonight with Jay Leno, is such an obvious
choice for ABC to add to the ``Monday Night Football'' booth that
they might as well go ahead and announce it. &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
__The history of sportscasting in a one-hour show? The documentary
called ``The Sportscasters: Behind the Mike,'' which debuts Monday
on The History Channel, manages to include interviews with all the
top names in the business. But it's only nicking the surface with
that kind of self-imposed time restriction. Maybe it's the way to
package for the masses today. But maybe this Frank Deford-narrated
piece that glosses over and includes Vin Scully and Al Michaels
should inspire someone to do a three- or four-part series on the
subject. Let it breathe, give it some depth. &QL; 
__Trying to take a well-worn topic _ gambling on the Super Bowl _
and give it a fresh spin is the purpose of today's ``Outside the
Lines Presented by AT&AMP;T'' on ESPN. And, yes, that's the official
name of the show now. So you know there won't be any commercial
influence or any attempt to show how a simple phone line can be
used to place bets. Next up: Fox Sports Net's ``Goin' Deep Dish
Pizza from Little Caesars'' show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2258EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6136 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-PEBBLEBEACH-HNS &LR;      02-03 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PEBBLEBEACH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Neither rain nor wind nor the bogeyman's
bite can make Tiger Woods go away, although the first two problems
did keep him and everybody else from making their appointed rounds
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The rain came Thursday at the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am.
So did the wind, which was more responsible than the wet stuff for
stopping play on the Monterey Peninsula before most players had
completed nine holes.
</P>
<P>
   Woods wasn't in the lead during the tournament's infancy. But he
wasn't far from it. He survived three early bogeys to get back to
even-par after 10 holes at Poppy Hills Golf Club, four strokes
behind David Duval and three behind Vijay Singh, both also playing
at Poppy in the tournament, which is spread over three courses in
the Del Monte Forest and on the rocky points along the Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   It was the exposed midsection of Pebble Beach Golf Links that
led tournament organizers to stop play at 11:27 a.m. PST. Players
were buffeted by a consistent 40-mph wind that had gusts to 50 mph,
according to tournament officials.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament will resume today at 10 a.m. PST, with players
continuing where they picked up on Thursday. All players completed
at least one hole, but nobody made it past more than 12.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament then will proceed with 18 holes each day,
concluding with the final round Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Which means we will find out if Woods is as tough on Mondays as
he has been on Sundays for the past six months. He's going for his
sixth win in a row, something that hasn't been done since Ben Hogan
ran off six straight in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Though there wasn't enough golf played Thursday for any trends
to develop, Woods is solidly in the hunt after making three birdies
in six holes before play was called.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger story, however, was the revelation that Monterey
Peninsula's weathermen have even tougher duty than Houston
meteorologists.
</P>
<P>
   In the span of seven hours, Pebble Beach showed a rainbow of
emotions. At 9 a.m., the weather was sunny and breezy. Two hours
later, the rain had started and the wind had kicked up to 30 mph.
Moments later, it was whipping hard enough to blow the pants legs
off of fans and golfers alike.
</P>
<P>
   The rain pelted the coast for several hours. But by
midafternoon, there wasn't a breath of wind and the sun had
returned.
</P>
<P>
   However, by that time the damage had been done. The drenched
greens had small lakes in their low spots, and the bunkers were a
mess. There was no chance of playing any golf after the storm blew
through. Tournament officials postponed play at 2:10 p.m. and made
the decision for a Monday finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was blowing at 40 mph when we suspended play,'' said
Mark Russell, a tournament director for the PGA Tour. ``At that
point, out there on parts of Pebble Beach, you had trouble just
standing, much less marking your ball. We had several rulings that
were asked for by players. When they were marking their ball, once
they replaced it, it would blow totally off the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Problems on the greens were numerous. Houston's Steve Elkington
hit his tee shot on the 106-yard par-3 seventh at Pebble Beach onto
the back of the green. But the postage-stamp hole plays dead into
the wind, and Elkington's ball came to a temporary stop, then was
pushed by the wind off the front of the green.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Stewart Cink had his ball blow from one side of the
fourth green to the other after it had come to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those days that everybody talks about for the
rest of their careers,'' said Lee Janzen, who was even-par after
five holes at Pebble Beach. ``No. 7 must have been a 5-iron from
100 yards downhill. The group in front of us, Stewart Cink and
Justin Leonard, both their balls had stopped on the green on No. 4,
and while they were walking to the green, a gust picked up and the
balls started rolling toward the front. Both balls were still
rolling as they got to the green.''
</P>
<P>
   Horror stories such as these are rare on the PGA Tour. But
weather problems have too often become the story of the AT&AMP;T
Pro-Am. The tournament was rained out completely in 1996, and in
the past two years it has been shortened to 54 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the weather was beautiful Tuesday and Wednesday,
tournament organizers were prepared for the worst this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had pin placements on high parts of the greens in most
cases, expecting some rain,'' Janzen said. ``But when you do that,
the wind gets to be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell said there was no thought given to trying to finish the
first round and play the second round today, because players would
have to change courses after they complete round one. In addition,
grounds crews have to make the entire courses playable at the start
since players are scattered throughout, rather than starting on No.
1 or No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions Thursday were as brutal as anybody could recall
on Pebble Beach. But in 1990, when Cypress Point still was in the
playing rotation, the wind was so stiff on the 17th hole, Ed
Dougherty needed 11 shots to get his ball into the hole after
reaching the green in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the show will go on this week, even though it
means going to Monday.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
