u a BC-NY-HOSPITALS-SANCTION     02-03 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOSPITALS-SANCTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH OFFICIALS FINE HOSPITAL WHERE DOCTOR CARVED PATIENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The State Department of Health fined Beth Israel
Medical Center $14,000 Thursday and ordered it to improve its
oversight of doctors after an inquiry into a hospital obstetrician
who carved his initials into a patient's belly.
</P>
<P>
   The seven citations issued against Beth Israel, each carrying
the maximum fine of $2,000, are one of the harshest rebukes against
a New York hospital in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the hospital failed to file proper reports with
the state after the carving and did not sufficiently monitor the
doctor, Allan Zarkin, despite earlier complaints by hospital
workers about the doctor's erratic behavior, which included pulling
on the arms of newborn infants.
</P>
<P>
   The citations conclude a state investigation into the events of
Sept. 7, when Zarkin, 61, sliced his initials into the patient, Dr.
Liana Gedz, after delivering her first child via Caesarean section.
Lawyers for Zarkin, whose license was revoked Thursday, have
defended him by saying that he has a frontal lobe dementia similar
to Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   The state penalty is the second in two years citing major flaws
in Beth Israel's administration and, in particular, its obstetrics
and gynecology department. State officials said that department,
which was faulted two years ago for its role in a 1997 patient
death, needs major improvements and tighter oversight.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, the state is requiring that Beth Israel hire
an independent consultant to come up with recommendations, within
two months, on how to improve the department, particularly in
quality control and employee screening. The consultant must also
suggest hospitalwide improvements in those two areas within three
months. The hospital must make all changes within a month of
receiving the reports, pending approval by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many moments in the system where this could have
been halted, and something somewhere broke,'' said Dr. Antonia C.
Novello, the state health commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the Health Department noted that administrators
had failed to properly document several complaints by nurses and
doctors regarding Zarkin's behavior in the year before the carving.
The report detailed complaints that Zarkin was screaming at workers
and ``pulling and yanking on newborn infants' arms after
delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the hospital failed to report the carving incident
to the Health Department's hospital oversight division, even though
a report is required in such cases. The state report also faulted
the hospital's record-keeping, noting that the plastic surgeon
examining Gedz after her operation failed to even mention the
carving in his files.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials said in a written statement that the hospital
had already ``implemented changes of procedure'' to ``strengthen
the monitoring of physician activities, and ensure consistent
adherence to the spirit as well as the letter of all reporting
requirements.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
