<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FINALLY, AN OPEN PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, Feb. 4: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Without begrudging how long it has taken Govs. George Pataki and
George W. Bush to recognize the need for an open presidential
primary in New York, it is time to celebrate the news that the
state's March 7 vote is now likely to be open to all major national
contenders. Bush, after being trounced by Sen. John McCain in New
Hampshire this week, has finally said the right thing _ that it is
time ``to put him (McCain) on the ballot.'' Pataki did much the
same, saying, ``I believe that John McCain should be on the
ballot.'' His communications director, Zenia Mucha, added that the
New York governor will ``take appropriate steps'' to make certain
that McCain is on all the ballots around the state.
</P>
<P>
   With the nation's most difficult rules for running in a
presidential primary, New York state has presented the country with
an antiquated display of machine politics in recent weeks, as
swarms of ward-style lawyers tripped over each other to bump the
opposition off the ballots. By nitpicking every signature on
candidates' petitions and challenging each other in court, New
York's Republicans have presented a national audience with an
alarmingly anti-democratic spectacle. It has not been a good move
for Pataki, who has shown his own interest in stepping onto the
national stage. Still, he has time to recoup.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage in this sticky process, Federal District Court
Judge Edward Korman is still mulling over ways to remedy this
unconstitutional mess. For now, Steve Forbes is the only Republican
on ballots statewide. Despite Bush's support from Pataki and other
key Republicans, his petitions have been invalidated in one
congressional district. McCain's name is missing in almost a dozen
congressional districts. Bush and Pataki Thursday made clear they
would not appeal a decision by Korman to restore McCain's name in
most areas of the state. They should also decline to challenge any
new signatures if Korman gives candidates more time to comply with
the rules. Any settlement of the federal case should make it clear
this law is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than letting a federal court bring democracy to New
York, Pataki should take the initiative by pressing for an
immediate change in the law. All the Republican leaders and lawyers
who have been working feverishly to rig the election for Bush
should turn their attention to figuring out a quick legislative
remedy that insures that all nationally recognized candidates
appear on all ballots in all 31 congressional districts in the
state. It is time to end the comparisons to Iran or the old Soviet
Union once and for all. Pataki, Joseph Bruno, the State Senate
majority leader, and Sheldon Silver, the Assembly speaker, should
simply replace this national embarrassment with a system that
allows New York voters, not party leaders, to choose presidential
candidates. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
