<HEADLINE>
FRANK MORRIS, 75, EX-PRESIDENT OF BOSTON FEDERAL RESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Mass., Fla.)   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank E. Morris, who was president of the Federal Reserve Bank
of Boston from 1968 to 1988, died Jan. 31 at his home in Naples,
Fla. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Morris was an economist with the Federal Office of
Price Stabilization and the CIA, an assistant to the secretary of
the Treasury in the Kennedy administration and a vice president of
Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co., an investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the Federal Reserve, Morris taught economics and
finance for five years at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Eugene Morris was born in Detroit on Dec. 30, 1924,
graduated from Wayne State University and served in the Air Force
during World War II. He earned a master's degree and doctorate in
economics at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Geraldine; three daughters, Susan
Carlson, of Acton, Mass.; Lisa Grobar, of La Crescenta, Calif.; and
Betsy Rosen of Wellesley, Mass.; a sister, Dorothy Green, of Fort
Lauderdale, Fla.; and six grandchildren.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
