<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6151 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-LIMITS04-COX     02-03 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-LIMITS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Texas A&AMP;M president in 1990 urged reduction of bonfire's
size, alcohol limits
 &HT;    By Suzanne Gamboa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A former president of Texas A&AMP;M University told
an A&AMP;M regent in 1990 that he supported reducing the size of the
Aggie bonfire and limiting alcohol consumption, new documents
released Thursday say.
</P>
<P>
   Former President William Mobley _ who went on to become A&AMP;M
System chancellor _ wrote in a May 22, 1990, memo to former regent
Ross D. Margraves Jr. that he concurred with a faculty and staff
recommendation that the size of the stack be reduced from 55 to 44
feet and that alcohol be limited.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that officials were concerned about alcohol
consumption during the bonfire's lighting. What is clear is that
university officials in later years worked to limit alcohol
consumption during both lighting and construction.
</P>
<P>
   However, documents suggest that the size of the stack in some
years actually grew beyond its allowable height, including last
year. At the time of the deadly Nov. 18 collapse, the bonfire was
about 60 feet tall and on its way toward topping out near 75 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The documents show that on at least three occasions more than a
decade before the fatal collapse, the university was urged to
reduce the height of the stack.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, university officials said reducing the size would
draw ``negative reaction'' from students. Another time _ when
Mobley weighed in _ the university instead moved the bonfire and
considered the safety concerns related to its size moot.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how the university responded the third time.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley was reacting to a report issued in 1990 by a committee
that was considering moving the bonfire because of complaints by
university neighbors. The committee looking at this question also
considered safety, environmental and even academic issues, the
documents show.
</P>
<P>
   ``By reducing the size of Bonfire, fewer trees would need to be
cut and burned, less student time would be required for its
construction, and risks both of injury during construction and
property damage during burning would be reduced,'' the committee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Mobley's support, the committee's suggestion to reduce
the bonfire's size was not implemented, former and current faculty
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just looking at it, it wasn't obvious to me that (the
recommendation) was being followed,'' said Richard Shumway, a
former A&AMP;M faculty member who helped write the report and is now at
Washington State University.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kibler, A&AMP;M associate vice president for student affairs,
said it's likely the recommendation became moot after the bonfire
stack was moved in 1992. The new Polo Field location _ where the
bonfire is now built _ was not as close to neighborhoods, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Robert H. Stiteler, then the university's safety and
health officer, also suggested that the height be reduced,
documents released earlier show.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Stiteler, Kibler wrote that he had ``serious
concerns about such a drastic reduction in the size of Bonfire''
and that it would ``almost assuredly result in extremely negative
reaction and protest from a significant portion of the student body
...''
</P>
<P>
   A third recommendation to reduce the height came in 1989 from
James Reynolds, then the Memorial Student Center Director.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
