<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-HARDY-RADIO04-COX     02-03 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARDY-RADIO04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beach music is love, living for Hardy
 &HT;    By Christine Moran
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ He grew up shaggin' to music by the Four
Tops, the Isley Brothers and The Temptations.
</P>
<P>
   Not much has changed over the last 35 years. Songs like ``Can't
Help Myself,'' ``This Old Heart of Mine'' and ``My Girl'' still get
his feet dancing and his arms swinging. His love for beach music
goes deep. So deep, that he has made a living sharing the songs
with much of eastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hardy, 53, has been in the radio business since 1971. His
show, ``Steve Hardy's Original Beach Party,'' is a request show
playing beach music and rhythm and blues. The show airs from 5 to
10 p.m. Sundays on WNCT-FM (Oldies 107.9). Tens of thousands of
listeners join him, dedicating songs to loved ones or requesting
songs for special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's meeting new people and making new friends that make my
job worthwhile,'' said Hardy, during a telephone interview from his
home in Greene County. ``I love the personal, one-on-one contact. I
love being able to promote my listeners and their feelings on the
air.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is a radio personality, Hardy spends much of his
time in the public eye. When he has not on the air, he is out
promoting his show. He is his own advertising agent. He calls
clients and goes door-to-door visiting customers.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy doesn't have a degree in communications. He attended a
community college, but never graduated. Instead, he joined the Air
Force. Four years later, he got a job at a radio station in
Farmville. After he worked behind the scenes for two days, the
station's producer put him on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Success didn't come right away. It took years before Hardy's
name became a household name in many homes in eastern North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   When he thinks about his life, he smiles. He feels fortunate he
has been able to make a living doing what he loves. It is something
he hoped for, but never expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music has been my livelihood and my life,'' Hardy said. ``I
feel fortunate and blessed that something like this has gone on
this good for so long. I can only hope it lasts.''
</P>
<P>
   On the radio for 25 years, Hardy's program is the longest
running radio beach show.
</P>
<P>
   As a spin-off from the radio show, Hardy takes his music on the
road and plays at private parties and nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Hardy's accomplishments include being voted a member of
the Beach Music Hall of Fame, being voted disc jockey of the year
twice at beach music's Cammy Awards and being a recipient of the
Billy Scott Lifetime Achievement Award at the Cammy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy also lends his hand to promote a variety of charities,
including the American Cancer Society and a charity golf tournament
for the Cystic Fibrosis Foundation which bears his name. The event
has special meaning to Hardy; his nephew suffers from cystic
fibrosis.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy doesn't know where time will take him. He'd like to stay
in the music business for as long as he can. But if he were to
explore another medium, he says it would have to be newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any chance I can get of interacting with others I'll take,''
Hardy said. ``With newspapers, just like music, you have the
opportunity to reach so many people and greatly impact their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
