<HEADLINE>
NO WARNING BY POLICE TO DIALLO, WITNESS SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JANE FRITSCH and AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A woman who lived across the street from Amadou
Diallo in the Bronx testified Thursday that she saw four white men
in casual clothes approach Diallo's building early last Feb. 4,
and, moments later, heard a volley of rapid gunfire. She did not,
she said, hear the men shout out any warning.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Debbie Rivera, was the first witness at the trial of
four police officers charged with Diallo's murder who was near the
scene at the time of the shooting. But on cross-examination,
defense lawyers suggested that she had been too far away to hear
voices, and pointed out apparent inconsistencies and omissions in
her several statements to the police since the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   It was an emotional day for Diallo's mother, Kadiatou, who wept
as her son's roommate choked up and cried on the witness stand when
Diallo's photo ID card was flashed on a courtroom screen. The
roommate, Momodou Kujabi, had fallen asleep just before Diallo was
shot to death in the lobby of their apartment building. Kujabi was
awakened by the police banging on the door and was then taken to
identify the body.
</P>
<P>
   For prosecutors, the testimony of a police supervisor they
called to the witness stand raised a problem that they will face
throughout their case: the police witnesses can also be good
defense witnesses. On cross-examination, the supervisor, Lt. Kevin
Cantwell, said the four were dazed and unable to speak when he
arrived on the scene. When he finished testifying for the
prosecution, he was made a defense witness and continued
testifying.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera's testimony was intended, in part, to shore up the
prosecution's contention that the officers did not identify
themselves to Diallo or shout any warnings before they began
shooting. He was hit by 19 of 41 shots fired at him as he stood,
unarmed, in the vestibule of his building at 1157 Wheeler Ave. in
the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The officers _ Kenneth Boss, Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon and
Richard Murphy _ acknowledge firing the shots but said they thought
Diallo was carrying a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera said she heard a car engine sometime after midnight and,
because she was expecting her husband, went to a bedroom window in
their second-floor apartment to look for him. Instead, she saw four
white men in casual clothes, one with a hat, standing near a
double-parked maroon car. She returned to the living room, she
said, and a short time later heard two bursts of rapid gunfire
separated by a pause of not more than a second, according to her
re-creation of the sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Next, she said, she ran back into the bedroom to move her two
sleeping children and two sisters to safety in the living room.
When the shooting stopped, she said, she returned to the bedroom
window from which she had first seen the four men. The outside pane
of one of three double-hung windows in the room was open, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a man walking in the street, looking under the cars,''
she said. The man, in a T-shirt, jeans and dark jacket with a
police badge hanging in front, removed a baseball cap from his
head, threw it into the street and swore, she said. Then he stopped
and leaned against a parked car.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, defense lawyers pointed to inconsistencies
between Rivera's testimony Thursday and previous statements made to
investigators and under oath. She had told the grand jury, for
example, that the officer she saw out her window was ``shaking'';
Thursday, she denied that was the case.
</P>
<P>
   If one issue crucial to both sides is what orders the officers
did or did not give Diallo, the other is how much light there was
in the vestibule.
</P>
<P>
   Kujabi, Diallo's roommate, testified that all of the lights in
the vestibule and hallway were on when he came home and were still
on when he was led out of his apartment after the shooting.
Cantwell also said the light was on as he approached the vestibule
after the shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
