<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AUSTRIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN UNWELCOME AUSTRIAN GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, Feb. 4: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now that Austria's president has approved formation of a new
government that includes an intolerant far-right party, the rest of
the world has to decide how to respond. The appropriate reaction is
to cool relations with Austria, which is what the European Union,
the United States and Israel seem prepared to do.
</P>
<P>
   The Austrian people have a right to vote for whatever parties
they choose, and the 27 percent support won by the Freedom Party
made it the second-largest group in parliament. But Austria's
neighbors and friends are not obliged to conduct business as usual
with a government that will now include a xenophobic anti-immigrant
party whose leader has expressed admiration for Nazi labor policies
and praised veterans of the murderous Waffen SS.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fears that international criticism would fuel a
nationalist backlash in Austria, warnings from abroad already
appear to have done some good. President Thomas Klestil, through
his statements and delays in accepting the new coalition, made
clear his own view that including Haider's party in the government
is bad for Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Freedom Party, with its mainstream conservative
partner, issued a statement pledging devotion to tolerance and
human rights and proclaiming Austria's need to face up to its own
responsibility for Nazi-era crimes. The Freedom Party has made
insincere protestations of good intentions in the past and Haider's
retractions of his comments about Nazi Germany have been
unconvincing. But if he and his party now intend to be guided by
the principles of this statement, there are at least some grounds
for encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is rightly recalling its ambassador to signal its disgust
at Haider's equivocations over Holocaust crimes. Washington should
consider doing the same. Further steps should be based on the new
government's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Austria's fellow members in the EU face a particularly difficult
challenge, since in the normal course of events top officials from
all member governments meet with each other all the time. But
European governments should be able to proceed with EU meetings
while minimizing direct government-to-government contacts with
Vienna and refusing to back Austrian candidates for international
positions. The European Union's founding treaty condemns racial and
ethnic discrimination and envisions measures to combat these evils,
which brought Europe so much suffering in the past. Austria's
partners can honor the treaty's principles by distancing themselves
from the new government in Vienna.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
