<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBS-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS REPORTED READY TO NAME CNN EXECUTIVE TO TOP POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Public Broadcasting Service has chosen Pat Mitchell, a
longtime program executive for Turner Broadcasting, to take the job
of president, a PBS executive said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If elected at a meeting of the PBS board this weekend, Mitchell,
who is now the president of CNN Productions, will succeed Ervin
Duggan, who resigned in September. Her appointment is expected to
be announced officially at a news conference in Washington on
Monday afternoon. The executive who disclosed Mitchell's selection
spoke on condition he not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who declined to comment on the prospective
appointment, would become the fourth president in PBS history.
Duggan served for five and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   At Turner, Mitchell has held a range of positions, mostly in the
area of news and documentaries. She is perhaps best known for
supervising two of the biggest projects ever undertaken by CNN, the
24-hour documentary series ``Cold War'' and the recent 10-hour
series ``Millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   But Turner quickly shut down Mitchell's most ambitious project,
a Women's Network cable channel. She was named as the executive in
charge of the channel last June but Turner scrapped the project
only weeks after it had been announced.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell has an extensive background as a producer of
non-fiction television, and has also worked in front of the camera.
She has been a correspondent for the ``Today'' show on NBC, and an
arts correspondent for ``Sunday Morning'' on CBS. She was also host
of her own nationally syndicated talk show ``Woman to Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Duggan left PBS at the end of October amid reports that he had
been opposed by the managers of some PBS stations for pushing too
hard to concentrate power in the national organization. That
problem has been frequently mentioned as a source of conflict
between PBS and its member stations.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the acting president of PBS, John Swope, said at a
news conference in California that finding a new president who
would work to build a better relationship with station managers was
a chief priority.
</P>
<P>
   PBS has also been without a chief programmer since May when
Kathy Quattrone left the network to join Discovery Communications.
Tom Epstein, the vice president for communications at PBS, would
not comment on Mitchell's possible appointment but said that
selecting a new programming chief would probably be a priority for
the new president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0474 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6162 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-CAMPAIGN-     02-03 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MEMO: PRESIDENT'S PLANS PUT GIULIANI ON SPOT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Hillary Rodham Clinton begins her official U.S.
Senate campaign, her husband has presented Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
with two disagreeable alternatives: Criticize billions of dollars
in Clinton education and anti-crime initiatives that would help New
York City, or praise the husband of his political enemy.
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union speech last month and in his 2001
budget to be released next week, President Clinton is offering up a
cornucopia of popular programs aimed at bolstering Democrats, but
chiefly Al Gore and the first lady. Some are already bringing in
millions of dollars for new teachers and after-school programs in
Harlem and the Hunts Point section of the Bronx. Others, like gun
control, are issues on which Giuliani, Clinton's opponent, has
aligned himself with the president in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, in fact, the mayor infuriated his fellow Republicans by
flying with Mr. Clinton to Minnesota on Air Force One to campaign
for the president's anti-crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   But how times have changed. Giuliani's new approach is to be
more of a Republican, and embrace the proposals in principle, but
belittle them in practice. He also suggests that Congress is
unlikely to pass much of what the president wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give you an example,'' Giuliani said at a news briefing
this week. ``The president offered a billion dollars more for the
Head Start program. New York City's school budget in a given year
is $11 billion. The amount of money involved in those programs
would have very little significance for a city the size of New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   Such programs ``sound good,'' the mayor added, ``but nobody
should have the false illusion that this is a substantial amount of
money when it gets translated into New York City with a million
schoolchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kharfen, a spokesman for the Department of Health and
Human Services, which administers Head Start, said he did not
understand why the Head Start money the federal government was
sending to New York City was not considered substantial. For this
school year, he said, the city received $136 million for Head Start
preschool programs for 20,000 children aged 3 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not insubstantial to the lives of those
children and their families,'' Kharfen said. New York City, he
added, received the bulk of the $305 million in Head Start money
that went to New York state this year, and has one of the country's
largest Head Start programs. Clinton's proposal, which, if passed
by Congress, would be the largest expansion of Head Start in
history, calls for the state to receive $411 million in Head Start
money in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also dismissed Clinton's proposal to spend $1 billion
in 2001 to hire new teachers to reduce class size. ``The State of
the Union in previous years has offered lots of money, and then by
the time you get to the budget, that money isn't there, or it's
one-tenth of what it was exaggerated to be,'' Giuliani said. ``So
we're going to have to wait some months to find out are their
programs really there and can we access it?''
</P>
<P>
   This school year the city received $61.2 million in a Clinton
initiative to reduce class size, which allowed the Board of
Education to hire 800 new teachers. Along with a state program that
provided money for 800 more teachers, the board was able to create
900 new classes with an average size of 20 for children in
kindergarten through third grade, plus add a second teacher to
other classes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident that Mrs. Clinton's latest radio commercial,
broadcast statewide this week, echoes the same programs as the
president's State of the Union speech. The commercial intersperses
Mrs. Clinton's voice with the voices of two women, a man and a
child, and has them finishing one another's sentences about the
need for health insurance, after-school programs, money for school
construction and tax deductions for college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should also be a $10,000 college tuition ... '' Mrs.
Clinton says in the ad, trailing off so that a woman's voice
immediately finishes her sentence with `` ... tax cut so we can
afford to send every child to college.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the president's speech called for a $10,000 tax
deduction for college tuition for families making up to $100,000
annually, and smaller deductions for families making up to $120,000
a year. The plan is similar to a bipartisan bill introduced last
year by Sen. Charles Schumer of New York. ``Whether Hillary was
running or not, the president would have proposed almost all of
this budget,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the Clinton tuition tax credit proposal ``does
help Hillary,'' particularly among suburban voters with college-age
children who make more money than allowed under an existing Clinton
tuition program. Under that program, families with less than
$80,000 in annual income can take up to $1,500 in tax credits for
the first two years of college, plus a $5,000 tax credit for
additional schooling or retraining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000203.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-$58-FORECLOSURE-AR     02-03 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-$58-FORECLOSURE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMEOWNER'S NONPAYMENT OF $58 LEADS TO FORECLOSURE AND AUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT28 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By LISA W. FODERARO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRING VALLEY, N.Y. _ It is a real estate story that Franz Kafka
might have concocted.
</P>
<P>
   A homeowner here for four years makes all of her mortgage
payments on time, throwing in an extra $400 a month so she can own
her neat, brown-shingled town house outright even sooner. In turn,
the mortgage company distributes all property tax payments for her
from an escrow account, as it does for many clients. Those payments
are up to date _ except for one: a $58 straggler that somehow falls
through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   And for $58, Mireille Leroy, a 38-year-old registered nurse and
mother who 17 years ago immigrated to the United States from Haiti
and 3 years ago became a U.S. citizen, loses a $114,000 house in a
foreclosure proceeding without knowing about it.
</P>
<P>
   Leroy first learned of her transformation from homeowner to
tenant two Saturdays ago when a county sheriff showed up at her
door at 9 a.m. with an eviction notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started laughing,'' she said in an interview Wednesday in
her living room. ``I thought it was a joke. I said, `It's a
mistake.' When I'm in shock, I laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days, Leroy, who lives with her 14-year-old daughter, was
no longer laughing, but rather trying to unravel the events that
led to the auction of her house last fall by Rockland County.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are calls by the County Legislature to restore Leroy's
homeowner status and to change the way the county handles
foreclosures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an immigrant woman who came to the United States to
realize the American dream, and the Rockland Department of Finance
took it away from her without even a phone call,'' said Ryan S.
Karben, a county legislator who chairs the Tax Delinquency
Committee. ``It's appalling. It can happen to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite abundant finger-pointing from all corners, county and
town officials, as well as spokesmen for Leroy's bank, seem to
agree that her plight is highly unusual, the consequence of a
series of fateful missteps.
</P>
<P>
   It all started with the previous owner, who had a special tax
exemption for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   When Leroy bought the house, at 73 Sharon Drive, that exemption
was in effect for the remaining months of 1996. In 1997, the town
of Ramapo, which includes the village of Spring Valley, sent her a
bill for $58, which represented the portion of the exemption that
had not applied to her.
</P>
<P>
   Ramapo did not send a copy of the bill to her mortgage company.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Oberman, Ramapo's tax receiver, said the town now
includes such bills in the ``general tax bill'' given to the
mortgage company because ``it was a problem for other people as
well.'' But, he added, ``No one lost their house over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leroy contended that she never received that bill, or anything
else in the mail from either the town or the county regarding the
delinquent $58 and the impending foreclosure proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, after a Ramapo reminder notice went unanswered, the
town turned the matter over to the county's Department of Finance,
which is responsible for collecting unpaid taxes. A spokeswoman for
the county, Susan Tolve, said the department sent ``at least four
notices'' to Leroy's address, and none were returned. The notices
are sent by first class mail, but are not certified, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Rockland County began notifying the mortgage
company of the delinquent tax bill, which had increased to $270
with penalties. But in what is now a common practice, Leroy's
mortgage had already been sold twice to other lenders.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Finance relies on records in the county
clerk's office to determine the name and address of the current
mortgage company, Tolve said, but that information had not been
updated by the new mortgage holder. As a result, the notices went
to the wrong company.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the delinquent bill never made it to Norwest Mortgage,
the final company to hold Leroy's loan. ``We consider her a stellar
customer,'' said Jon Ferchen, a company spokesman. ``She's made all
her payments on time. Norwest Mortgage was never notified of this
delinquency. Our records indicate all taxes are current on this
loan.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is investigating when it updated the county's
records, Ferchen said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Leroy tossed the notices out or did not grasp their
import, county legislators say at the very least the county should
have called her or made a personal visit before auctioning her
house. ``This is what happens when a bureaucracy views people as
numbers on a list rather than human beings,'' Karben said.
</P>
<P>
   The county legislator is working on two fronts: to have the sale
declared void or to have the county buy the house back from the new
owner, a local real estate investor who agreed to halt the
eviction.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Finance Department insists that it abided by
the state statute governing foreclosures, and it noted that the
Legislature itself approved the sale of Leroy's house along with
other foreclosed properties. But the county, too, is exploring ways
to help Leroy, who says she has lost five pounds from stress since
her ordeal began. ``We followed the law,'' Tolve said, ``but that
doesn't mean we feel OK about the way this worked out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
