<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6166 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-ETHICS-$ADV06-NYT     02-03 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ETHICS-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET WHAT PSYCHICS SEE. AT LEAST THEY LISTEN.  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DANIEL AKST   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the news broke recently that New York City, in its zeal to
place welfare recipients in jobs, was sending some of them to work
at a psychic hot line, the future was easy to divine. Embarrassed
city officials promptly called a halt, leaving some low-income New
Yorkers with reduced employment prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers have accused some telephone psychic services of
padding phone charges and the like, but there's no evidence of such
complaints against the company that was involved with the city.
</P>
<P>
   So assume for now an honestly run psychic hot line _ one that,
if perhaps not truly psychic, is at least not thieving. The
question is, what exactly is wrong with placing workers in a
company like that?
</P>
<P>
   To an atheist, a job at a religious organization must seem no
less bizarre. And to someone who wants to get through dinner
someday without being assailed by telemarketers, the psychics, at
least, have the virtue of waiting for you to call them.
</P>
<P>
   But law-abiding telephone psychics are not merely harmless. They
perform a public service _ maybe even several _ for which customers
appear glad to pay.
</P>
<P>
   First, they provide entertainment, which is how their lawyers
make them describe what they do in their ads. Like dressing up as
Donald Duck at Disney World or selling lottery tickets at the
corner store, offering psychic consultations is a relatively
harmless means of conspiring with your customers in a brief escape
from the suffocating weight of the here and now.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, telephone psychics appear to serve as a
fiber optic lifeline of sorts for people nobody else wants to pay
attention to. They may even save lives now and then.
</P>
<P>
   One woman who worked as a telephone psychic for a Florida
company reported that many of her callers were poor people ``with
problems that not even a soap opera can list.''
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there. We all need someone to tell our troubles to,
after all. Who knows how many suicides have been averted by calls
to sympathetic psychics?
</P>
<P>
   It is easy for the affluent to scoff at all this. For them,
high-priced therapists have shouldered aside clergy and even
friends in the brutal competition for market share in tears.
</P>
<P>
   If you are poor, however, it's a different story. Life is
harder, your troubles are probably worse, yet there is precious
little money to pay for a sympathetic ear.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to afford years on the couch with a devout Freudian,
maybe you dial a psychic help line instead. Are you thereby
receiving the services of a trained professional? Well, sort of.
Obviously, $4.99-a-minute psychics can't really see the future; if
they could, they'd be cleaning up as bond traders. Their real skill
is in listening to people's troubles, intuiting their situation and
helping them feel better.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the recruitment flier from the city made no mention of
clairvoyance, but it did cite the need for ``a caring and
compassionate personality.'' Such personality types enjoy a
time-honored position in the marketplace _ think of bartenders, for
instance. And didn't Charles Revson say of the cosmetics industry
that it amounted to selling a jar of hope?
</P>
<P>
   The readiness of desperate people to reach out and touch a
dial-a-seer suggests a market demand that can't be made to vanish
simply by eliminating psychics.
</P>
<P>
   The poor, in fact, must make do in a number of analogous ways
that are equally frowned upon by the well-intentioned affluent.
They pay high interest rates on loans, for example, to unofficial
credit sources, because no one else will lend them money; critics
call this usury. Often, it's against the law, but borrowers in
desperate need are undeterred by a lender's obvious dorsal fin.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, while prosperous types take advantage of the bulk
discounts at warehouse clubs, there's usually a store in the
poorest neighborhoods selling cigarettes one at a time, just as
telephone psychics dispense comfort by the minute.
</P>
<P>
   The psychics are criticized for trying to stretch out each call
and pump up the bill, but therapists with doctoral degrees charge
by the clock, too _ for a 50-minute ``hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe instead of shutting down the welfare-to-psychic pipeline,
public officials ought to order up some research on whether
psychics and therapists, given the same constraints, achieve
measurably different outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   The results may save health insurers a lot of money. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Akst's column tilts at conventional business wisdom and
appears the first Sunday of each month. E-mail:
culmoney(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
