u f BC-ANTISMOKING-AD-COLUMN     02-03 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTISMOKING-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: A NEW NATIONAL CAMPAIGN AGAINST SMOKING GENERATES
DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ill., Del.)  (js) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is intended as the largest single national anti-smoking
initiative starts Friday amid continuing debate over some
commercials that are to be part of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is sponsored by the American Legacy Foundation in
Washington, which was financed by the recent $206 billion
settlement reached by 46 state attorneys general and the tobacco
industry. The advertising, marketing and public relations campaign
_ developed by teen-agers in partnership with Madison Avenue
professionals _ is meant to ``unsell'' cigarette smoking to young
people ages 12 to 17 by countering the tactics the tobacco makers
have long used to peddle their best-selling brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the capacity to create a classic social marketing
program that will reduce the prevalence of youth tobacco use,''
Cheryl Healton, president and chief executive of the foundation,
said in a telephone interview Thursday. ``I'm incredibly confident
the ads, in combination with other work of the foundation, will
achieve our primary goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial element of the initiative, which will have a
first-year budget of about $185 million, is a Web site that is
expected to go up Friday at www.thetruth.com. ``Truth'' is the
theme of the campaign, with the word presented as if it was the
name of a product being pitched to counteract the effect of
cigarette advertising on teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are launching a brand, and the brand has a name, and the
name is `Truth,''' said Healton, who is also a professor of public
health at Columbia University. The concept is based on a campaign
produced in 1997 for the Florida Department of Public Health by
Crispin Porter &AMP; Bogusky in Miami. That agency is one of nine in a
consortium that is creating the national initiative; the agencies
were selected in September after a long review process.
</P>
<P>
   The next step in the introduction of the campaign is scheduled
to take place on Monday, when a commercial is planned to run on TV.
Six networks have agreed to accept at least one commercial from the
campaign, Healton said, adding that it was still being decided
which commercial would be the first to run on which network.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has had some difficulty in gaining acceptance for
its spots from the three largest broadcast TV networks _ ABC, CBS
and NBC _ which initially rejected concepts submitted for approval
in the form of story boards by Crispin Porter and by Arnold
Communications in Boston, a unit of Snyder Communications that is
also a member of the consortium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very optimistic our advertising will clear the
networks,'' Healton said. ``It's my understanding from the people
we're working with that what we're going through with the networks
is the same process of negotiations that others go through.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade publications Advertising Age and Adweek reported that
the networks had objected to the commercial proposals for
content-related reasons. There were concerns, for example, that one
spot that showed a teen-ager actually smoking would glamorize what
it was seeking to disparage.
</P>
<P>
   Another spot used a name for an imaginary product ``that sounded
too much like Clorox,'' Healton said.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Kaino, a spokeswoman for NBC, which is part of General
Electric Co., said one commercial was accepted after the proposed
script was revised. Healton said it would appear during an NBC
Sports program with a predominantly teen-age viewership.
</P>
<P>
   Dana McClintock, a spokesman for CBS, owned by CBS Corp., said
the foundation's commercials ``continue to remain under review.''
Julie Hoover, a spokeswoman for ABC, part of Walt Disney Co., said
the network's policy opposed the public discussion of business
matters.
</P>
<P>
   The other networks listed by Healton as agreeing to run at least
one commercial are youth-focused; they include Fox Broadcasting
Co., part of News Corp. That emphasis is no accident because of the
campaign's intended audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're helping with marketing strategies, what kinds of shows
the commercials should be in, what kinds of shows should be
avoided,'' said Jason Chase of Dover, Del., a 17-year-old high
school senior who is among the teen-agers working on developing the
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to keep everything at a teen's perspective, in a
teen's voice,'' he added, ``because teens understand how to speak
to other teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Delaware, I'm the chair of a group called the Delaware
Kick Butts Generation,'' Chase said, ``and a lot of time we hear
people call us `window dressing.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But with the legacy foundation and the Truth campaign, we are
the ones calling the shots. We talk directly to the agency people,
give them ideas, get back story boards. I've seen story boards
tossed if kids didn't like them.''
</P>
<P>
   The other agencies in the consortium include Bromley
Communications in San Antonio, part of BDM, for youth marketing and
ads aimed at Spanish-speaking consumers; Burrell Communications
Group in Chicago, which is 49 percent owned by Publicis S.A., for
youth marketing and ads aimed at blacks; and Porter Novelli in
Washington, a unit of the Omnicom Group, for public relations and
social marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will also include print ads, radio commercials, a
youth meeting in Seattle in June and a ``Truth truck tour'' that
will travel across the country, concluding at the World Tobacco
Conference in Chicago in August. The initiative, which is to
supplement anti-smoking campaigns at the state level, is scheduled
to be financed for $1.5 billion through 2004.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2330EST &QL; 
