<HEADLINE>
BALLOT FUROR MIGHT HURT NEW YORK GOVERNOR
</HEADLINE>
  (with McCain-Ballot) 
 (rk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In the end, the word came from the office of the
man who had insisted that the dispute had nothing to do with him.
Aides to Gov. George Pataki announced Thursday that Sen. John
McCain would be on New York's presidential primary ballot after
all.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki had said all along that it was the Republican State
Committee, not he, who was trying to keep McCain off the March 7
ballot, and that he could not tell the party and its powerful
chairman, Bill Powers, what to do. But it was the governor's aides
who publicly defended the party's position, and Thursday it was
they who told reporters that the party had done an about-face.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the party's decision, not ours,'' said Zenia Mucha,
Pataki's communications chief.
</P>
<P>
   But few people in politics or government doubted that Powers was
acting with the governor's full support, or that Pataki wielded
great influence over the party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a booster of the party favorite, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, has made no secret of his desire to be considered for the
vice presidential nomination. He was always considered a long shot,
and the fight over ballot access may have hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pataki might have thought he was ingratiating himself with
Bush with this ballot stuff,'' said a prominent Republican
political consultant, ``but this has become an embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor is the public personification of the state party,
and to the extent that the party has made itself look
anti-democratic, the governor cannot benefit. Pataki clearly wants
to be seen as a power in national Republican circles, and losing
the fight over ballot access hurts there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole episode is a black mark on Pataki, and more so if
McCain now does well in New York,'' said John Zogby, a pollster.
``It makes the governor and the party look bad and, more important,
look weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of New York's most prominent Republicans, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani of New York City and former Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato, have
said publicly that the state rules that make it hard to get on the
ballot _ and easy to knock an underdog off _ were wrong. In fact,
McCain thanked D'Amato Thursday night for helping him get on the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the state party tried _ and failed _ to keep Steve
Forbes off the primary ballot in favor of the establishment choice,
Bob Dole. The publicity was so negative that the Republicans agreed
to change the state law governing ballot access, though the rules
remain the toughest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, everyone knew that D'Amato dominated the party.
These days, voters looking for the face of the state party have
nowhere to turn but to Pataki.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
