u a BC-NC-STORM-RECOVER-NYT &LR;      02-03 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-STORM-RECOVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDSHIPS TEACH A NORTH CAROLINA GIRL LESSONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Most afternoons 13-year-old Cherrie Redwine
goes outside to do her homework, even when the temperature is in
the 40s and snow is on the ground, as it was this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't hardly breathe with five people living inside
there,'' she said, as she sat outside her family's one-bedroom
trailer at the temporary housing site for displaced victims of the
September floods that followed Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Residents throughout North Carolina dug out from one of the
worst snowstorms in state history this week. About 20 inches fell
in the Raleigh area, and 4 to 10 inches fell here to the east.
Coming only five months after the state's worst flooding, the snow
just added to the myriad troubles facing those displaced by the
flood.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest practical problems from the recent snowstorm were
occasional frozen pipes and lack of heating. But the more insidious
effect was psychological. The threat of bad weather seemed to bring
back memories of the flood for many people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really gives you a flashback, especially for those of us
who were flooded out,'' said Earl Parker, a 37-year-old barber who
used to live in Tarboro. ``When you look at the news and see bad
weather, you think, `Oh Lord, what's going to happen now?'''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nowhere is the mix of frustration, longing and gratitude
that the flood victims have experienced more evident than in the
eight temporary trailer parks, like this one in Rocky Mount, set up
by the state and federal emergency management agencies. Altogether,
more than 9,000 people who lost homes in the flooding from
Hurricane Floyd live in the parks, scattered throughout the
hard-hit areas of eastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 400 families have been living in 310 one-bedroom trailers
and 74 larger mobile homes at the Fountain Park site here for
almost five months. About 25 families have taken their
state-supplied trailers back to the property where their houses are
being rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   The state Emergency Response Team and the Federal Emergency
Management Agency have set an 18-month deadline for residents at
the trailer parks to get back on their feet in rebuilt houses or
new apartments. ``I don't think anyone wants to live in those
travel trailers forever,'' said Jay Acre, a spokesman for FEMA,
``although it is rent free.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Allen, 62, a cashier at a restaurant in Rocky Mount, is one
of the lucky ones. She found an apartment this week despite the
tight market created by the flood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking since Christmas,'' she said, sitting in her
neatly kept trailer. ``It's hard to find a nice place to live. But
I know I can't stay here, so I don't want to wait until the last
minute.''
</P>
<P>
   For others who are rebuilding houses, the wait will be longer.
Before the flooding, Cherrie Redwine lived in Princeville with her
mother, her 10-year-old sister, her 7-year-old brother and her
mother's boyfriend in their own house. Since October, they have all
been living in the 240-square-foot trailer. Her neighbors' trailers
on each side are inches away.
</P>
<P>
   Each trailer is heated by two 30-pound propane gas tanks, and
none of the trailers have telephones. The gas tanks last about two
days in the cold weather and cost $12 to refill.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I had a house, we weren't so smushed up together,''
Cherrie said. ``I could walk to stores close by. I could ride my
bike. I had my own room. I had my clothes, a phone, a stereo. And
we had central heat and air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   The trailer park is behind a women's prison, and many people
must rely on public transportation to get out of the area because
they also lost their cars in the flood. Rows of trailers line
streets of packed dirt, so when it rains or the snow melts, mud is
everywhere, and children track it into the trailers.
</P>
<P>
   Cherrie said she did not realize how good she had it before her
family lost everything it owned. ``I didn't appreciate anything,''
she said. ``If I got something, I wanted more. Now I appreciate
what I get.''
</P>
<P>
   In the months before Christmas, donations flowed freely to the
flood victims, many of whom were not used to accepting help. But as
the months have passed, there is less help. Some church groups have
adopted flooded-out families for the duration, and many others have
come to help in the rebuilding. But some people here are looking at
another year or more before they get back into their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   One of Cherrie's homework assignments this week was to write a
poem for English class about what it is like to be a flood victim
and live in the trailer park. So she was thinking hard about the
past five months and how her life had changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the flood, I used to be a mean little girl,'' she said.
``I used to make fun of people for the way they looked and always
pick on people about wearing Kmart clothes. But then I started
wearing Kmart clothes. After the flood, I turned out to be just
like them. I reaped what I sowed.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Exum, 35, an Edgecombe County deputy sheriff, who patrols
the park as part of his beat, has known Cherrie for many years. ``I
knew her before the flood, and she has changed,'' Exum said. ``I've
seen a lot of people do that. People have really come together to
help everyone in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Another effect of the flood is that Cherrie has grown to love
reading, especially mysteries. She used to hate reading, but after
the flood she said she found it was one of her favorite ways to
escape boredom.
</P>
<P>
   After many versions, Cherrie, who said she plans to be a nurse,
not a writer, came up with the final draft of her poem for English
class:
</P>
<P>
   Today as I sit here, I begin to think about all the things I've
been through.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I hate myself because of the things I used to do.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, I be so happy that I have learned from these things.
</P>
<P>
   Every day I pray to God to help me through.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
