u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-BLAZERS-NY     02-03 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-BLAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING SAVES HIS SEASON'S BEST TO BEAT THE BLAZERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are times when Patrick Ewing's tireless pride
can overcome age, injury and odds, and when his desire to prove he
is not done in this league emanates through on a night like
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   After his name was kicked around in trade discussions between
the Knicks and the Washington Wizards, after his dedication to the
game had been questioned, Ewing unearthed his most impressive
performance since his return from injury 24 games ago. As he faded
away for an array of jumpers, he tortured the league's best team,
the Portland Trail Blazers, for 20 points and 9 rebounds in the
Knicks' 98-88 victory at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   It was an awakening for a Knick team that had slumbered through
its game on Tuesday against the Orlando Magic. The Knicks held the
Trail Blazers to 42 percent shooting from the field and forced them
into 14 turnovers while committing only 8 themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, led by Allan Houston's 22 points, shot 41.8 percent
and were outrebounded, 48-38. The key was the Knicks' getting to
the free-throw line 35 times while the Trail Blazers went 13 times.
</P>
<P>
   Portland was led by Steve Smith's 18 points but could not get
anyone else in the mix except for the reserve Bonzi Wells, who
scored 18 off the bench. The Blazers were a frustrated group,
evident when Rasheed Wallace, sitting on the bench, was tossed from
the game after his second technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks led by 79-71 with 8 minutes 5 seconds left in the
game, but Wells came out of nowhere to unleash a stream of jumpers
to pull the Trail Blazers to within 4 points, at 81-77, with 6:06
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But then Coach Jeff Van Gundy, who has been prone to benching
Ewing in the final minutes, put him back in with 4:58 left and
watched him sink a baseline jumper three seconds later. He led the
Knicks the rest of the way, and they built a 12-point lead with
less than three minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   The victory should give the Knicks confidence should these two
teams make their way to meet in the National Basketball Association
finals.
</P>
<P>
   For two days, the Knicks had to live with their inept and
uninspired performance against the Magic. Usually, the Knicks
respond well when given a second chance to redeem themselves. But
Thursday night required more than just a higher plane of
preparation and focus against a team that is leading the mighty
Pacific Division and swaggered into town with the best record in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   During the Trail Blazers' six-game winning streak, they had
beaten the Spurs, the Jazz and the Lakers. Not only did they
possess stars like Scottie Pippen, Smith and Wallace, they came
with a loaded bench as well. Not only can they shoot for a high
percentage, they also came in holding opponents to a league-low 88
points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just another game,'' Latrell Sprewell said. ``It's a
challenge for us. This is another elite team, and we want to see
where we stand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks held their own at halftime, down by 46-45. But every
point, every rebound was a struggle for the Knicks while the Trail
Blazers seemed to be pacing themselves. At one point, Portland held
the Knicks without a field goal for four minutes of the second
quarter. With the Knicks down by 41-35, Houston broke the drought
and scored on a 3-pointer as a part of his 12 first-half points in
the face of his defender, Bonzi Wells.
</P>
<P>
   But Houston was about the only Knick going. Sprewell, struggling
to find air against Pippen, finished the first half shooting 1 for
5 but was part of a third-quarter surge that irritated and
surprised the Trail Blazers. Sprewell hit a 3-pointer with 6:40
left in the third to give the Knicks a 56-55 lead. The Knicks
finished out the third quarter on a 17-9 run and took a 73-64 lead
entering the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were getting under the skin of Portland's big men.
After Wallace was called on a foul for pushing off on Sprewell for
a rebound, the volatile forward lost his temper and was called for
a technical foul. The Knicks then pumped up their lead to 61-56
when Ewing sprang free for a smooth baseline jumper, proving he
still has a little magic left in his fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing tried to be everywhere. He was fighting for rebounds and
leaping to keep the ball alive. But after expending all of that
energy, he had nothing left when he went to the free-throw line
with 7:04 left in the third and came up empty on two attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Where there was life, there was Sprewell. He came flying down
the lane on a fast-break layup to give the Knicks a 68-62 lead with
1:30 remaining in the third period. He had found a way to beat
Pippen: outrun him. With Sprewell running and Ewing picking up
fouls in the post, the Knicks held a 73-64 lead at the end of the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Until the third quarter, the Trail Blazers were playing it cool.
Before Houston started feeling his groove in the second quarter,
the Knicks went through a two-minute spell in which they turned the
ball over twice and Houston blew a dunk as he drove right down the
lane. But once Houston began to feel his jumper again, the Knicks
also began to mix it up and bang inside. They got to the free-throw
line five times in the last 3:14 of the half, but Marcus Camby,
Houston and Ewing combined to hit just 3 of 9 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Knicks had scraped up enough points to stay close to
the Trail Blazers despite being outrebounded, 25-18, and outshot,
41.9 percent to 38.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Knicks' inability to score could be attributed to
the matchup of Pippen, a sinewy 6 feet 7 inches, overshadowing the
6-5 Sprewell. It was a rough situation for Sprewell, but the tone
of that matchup changed in the third quarter when Sprewell began to
make an impact. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
