<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI FAULTS MRS. CLINTON ON TRIP COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani accused Hillary Rodham
Clinton Thursday of failing to fully reimburse taxpayers for the
cost of using government airplanes on political trips to New York
and elsewhere. The White House and Clinton's campaign said prompt
reimbursements had been made.
</P>
<P>
   In campaign finance filings made public on Wednesday, Clinton
reported reimbursing $34,000 in travel costs. Under federal law,
Clinton, as a candidate for the U.S. Senate, must pay the
government the equivalent of a first-class commercial airline
ticket for herself and any political staff members traveling with
her.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's security detail is paid for by the government, and as
first lady, she may be accompanied by one government aide at
taxpayers' expense. But even given these allowances, Giuliani and
the manager of his Senate campaign, Bruce Teitelbaum, suggested,
Clinton made more trips and took along a bigger entourage than
accounted for in the figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like that deal, not only for my campaign but for my
vacation,'' Giuliani said Thursday. ``I mean if you can get that
deal for you and your family, take it, because Disneyland, here I
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton's campaign nor the White House would provide a
detailed accounting of the trips she had taken or how much her
campaign, the Democratic National Committee or other organizations
had been billed for them.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kennedy, a White House spokesman, said the White House
counsel's office determines billing for political travel. ``We in
fact bill in a timely fashion,'' he said, ``and any suggestion to
the contrary is partisan and untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Clinton's spokesman, said that her campaign pays
all bills from the White House and suggested that Giuliani was
trying to divert attention from this week's allegations of illegal
city welfare contracts. ``The mayor should explain why he is giving
no-bid contracts to his political cronies,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-00 2346EST &QL; 
