<HEADER>
A6188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-WINE-SUIT-NYT &LR;      02-03 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WINE-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT SEEKS TO OVERTURN A WINE LAW IN NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Calif.)  (rk) 
 By HOWARD G. GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Washington law firm sued Thursday to overturn New
York laws prohibiting direct shipments of wine by out-of-state
wineries to New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Representing three New York consumers and two small wineries in
Virginia and California, the Institute for Justice, which calls
itself a libertarian law firm, also seeks repeal of a law that
limits the advertising of wines by producers outside the state.
That law, it says, violates First Amendment free speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The firm chose New York for a national test case because the
state is the second biggest wine market in the country after
California, and is a major wine-growing state. It has 140 producers
in four regions: Long Island, the Finger Lakes, the Hudson Valley
and Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   In suing the state Liquor Authority, which enforces the law, the
institute argues that the legislation discriminates against sellers
and buyers and provides unconstitutional protectionism. Clint
Bolick, the director of litigation, said in a statement that the
legislation was ``designed to preserve the monopoly of liquor
wholesalers who control all out-of-state wine in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs include Juanita Swedenburg, proprietor of the
Swedenburg Winery in Virginia, and David Lucas, owner of the Lucas
Winery in California. They are joined in the suit by New Yorkers
who, the institute said, are wine enthusiasts who tried to order
bottles from them ``for direct shipment, furnishing proper
identification that they are adult consumers.'' Because of the law,
the institute said, ``the wineries were compelled to decline their
orders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet opened up a fantastic new way for boutique
wineries to find new customers,'' Bolick said. But, he added, under
New York laws, every out-of-state winery or retailer who advertises
on the Internet is an outlaw.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Violette, a spokesman for the state attorney general's
office in Albany, which would defend the legislation, said, ``We'll
wait to be served with papers, analyze the lawsuit and then comment
appropriately at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty states bar direct wine sales from out-of-state producers
to consumers, and seven of those treat such transactions as
felonies.
</P>
<P>
   Since the repeal of Prohibition in 1933, regulation of alcoholic
beverages has been left to the states. The lawsuit seeks to weaken
the power held by wholesalers in many states under the so-called
three-tiered system, under which producers must sell wine to
wholesalers, who add a markup and sell it to stores and
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   New York law does not bar shipments by New York producers and
merchants inside the state. This, the law firm argues, give them an
unfair, privileged position.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Pellegrini Vineyards, in Cutchogue on the North
Fork of Long Island, established a wine club under which it ships
New Yorkers bottles four times a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to open the club to people in Ohio who say, `We'd
like to have your wine' and we have to say, `Sorry, you can't,'''
said Joyce Pellegrini, an owner. ``People can get flowers and books
by the month. Why not wine?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
