<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6190 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-COLUMN-DIALLO-NYT &LR;      02-03 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-DIALLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
41 SHOTS BELIE ANY DANGER FROM POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On this, the first anniversary of Amadou Diallo's
shocking death at police hands, the city weeps for its adopted son.
But through the tears, and certainly through the shouts of the many
anti-police protesters over the last year, a significant fact tends
to be obscured. It is this:
</P>
<P>
   New York police officers are firing less often at civilians _
black, white, brown or any other shade _ than at any point in
recent history. Not only that, but when they do shoot, it is at a
rate appreciably lower than found in many other major cities.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir credits better firearms
training, which includes role playing and video simulators to
create ``many, many scenarios of shoot-or-don't-shoot situations.''
He and others who make it their business to analyze police
practices say it also does not hurt that crime is way down from its
early '90s peaks. Officers are less likely these days to run into
situations that lead them to pull out their guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, when it comes to the use of firearms, we are the
most restrained large city police department in the United
States,'' Safir said. ``But you wouldn't know that from reading you
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Being generous souls, we will let that personal attack slide.
The more important point is that shootings by the police have
starkly declined no matter how you measure them: number of
incidents, bullets fired, civilians wounded or, obviously the most
critical category, civilians killed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the police say, 11 people were shot to death by
officers, including Diallo and the victim in another controversial
case, Gidone Busch of Borough Park, Brooklyn. The 1998 body count
was 19. The number of wounded fell to 31 last year from 43 in 1998.
Incidents dropped to 155 from 249, and bullets fired to 477 from
526. Bear in mind that the 1999 figure included the extraordinary
41 shots fired at Diallo last Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts suspect that the Diallo killing and the subsequent
protests traumatized the police somewhat, producing a high degree
of self-restraint and, with it, the eye-catching dip in numbers.
Safir rejects the idea of a Post-Diallo Syndrome in shooting
situations. It must be said that, while the 1999 decline was
uncommonly steep, the indicators were already heading the right way
before anyone here heard of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, for example, 31 people were fatally shot by the police
and 48 were wounded. The number of shooting incidents that year was
317 and bullets fired, 894, figures roughly double those last year.
</P>
<P>
   And if you go further back in time _ say, to the early 1970s,
when the number of civilians shot to death by the police averaged
63 a year _ you can see that the rules of engagement for officers
have been considerably tightened. While the death toll has
fluctuated over the years, it is far from what it was in the '70s
or even as recently as 1990, when crime was rampant and 41
civilians were shot dead by the police.
</P>
<P>
   In comparing this city with others, Safir likes to single out
Washington, where officers fire their weapons five times more per
capita than the New York police do. Maybe the commissioner mentions
the capital because he is from there. Or maybe it is because
Washington's police force, like its population, is largely black,
blunting the argument that race is by definition the key factor
when the police open fire.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, there would seem to be little in New York's
numbers to support a claim that ``it is open season on blacks,'' as
the Rev. Jesse Jackson said after the Diallo killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic message in the Police Academy is that you shoot in
defense of life, and it better be something that a reasonable
person would do,'' said Thomas A. Repetto, president of the
Citizens Crime Commission, a police watchdog group. Professor Eli
Silverman of John Jay College of Criminal Justice added: ``Most
officers don't ever want to shoot. They don't want to live that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   No one argues that 11 deaths represent perfection. Some
reporters who cover police matters say that officers' performance
could be better evaluated if the department would only provide
detailed tactical information on firearms use.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, a case like the Diallo shooting overwhelms
statistics. An inevitable result, said City Councilman Sheldon
Leffler, chairman of the council's Public Safety Committee, is that
``people conclude officers are too quick on the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the available numbers are hard to ignore. ``They are what
they are,'' Safir said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
