<HEADER>
A6199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-HEALTH-AIDES-NYT     02-03 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HEALTH-AIDES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SHORTAGE OF HEALTH AIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Feb. 4:
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of workers willing to bathe, dress, feed, clean and
care for the elderly, in their homes and in nursing homes, has
grown worse in the last two years as the economy has continued to
soar, creating many other jobs that pay as well or better for much
less demanding work. Fast-food restaurants and Target stores now
may offer equal wages, steadier work and better benefits, and
zookeepers, toll-takers and manicurists actually earn more.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, as was reported in The New York Times recently, is
in part a result of economic and demographic trends. But it is also
the product of public attitudes and government policies that place
little value on the comfort and dignity of the oldest, most
vulnerable citizens, and on the labor of those who keep them safe.
The lack of care, by a work force stretched too thin, results in
accidents, malnutrition and bedsores, which are painful and can
lead to death.
</P>
<P>
   The very old now form the nation's fastest-growing population.
They are the parents, grandparents, aunts and uncles of the
boomers, but in two decades, they will begin to include the boomers
themselves. Ninety percent of the hired care those old people get
is given by nurses aides.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the jobs that are now so hard to fill. The sheer
number of aides needed is expected to grow by 76 percent from 1996
to 2006. Yet ombudsmen in 41 states already report that nursing
homes cannot recruit or retain the aides they need.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of the nation's 1.6 million nursing home
residents are poor old women who do not vote and are likely to be
senile. Ninety-three per cent of the aides who care for them are
female and poor. Most are between 25 and 44, and 30 percent are
black, Asian or Hispanic. They are thought to earn between $7 and
$8 an hour, and the aides who work in home health care even less.
</P>
<P>
   Their wages are held at such low levels in part because of cuts
in Medicare, which pays for some home health care, and because
state legislatures have been determined to hold down the cost of
Medicaid, which pays for two-thirds of all nursing home care.
Legislators are prudent to try to contain costs, but not if it
produces a system that encourages the neglect and abuse of the old.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
