u k BC-EDIT-TOBACCO-TAX-NYT &LR;      02-03 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TOBACCO-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CALIFORNIA'S TOBACCO TAX 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Feb. 4:
</P>
<P>
   On the March 7 ballot, California voters will be asked to repeal
Proposition 10, a groundbreaking anti-tobacco initiative that
raised the state cigarette tax by 50 cents per pack. Nullifying
Proposition 10 would be a serious public-health mistake. In 1998,
Californians set an admirable example for the rest of the nation by
passing this measure, which generates about $680 million a year to
pay for smoking prevention programs and an array of early childhood
education and health programs.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important, that tax increase is helping to reduce
tobacco consumption. Health experts have long argued that the best
way to cut smoking rates, particularly among teen-agers, is to
raise the cost of cigarettes. California officials report that the
Proposition 10 tax increase along with higher prices charged by
tobacco manufacturers have caused cigarette sales to fall by 30
percent, a drop that, if sustained, can substantially reduce the
number of young people becoming hooked on tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   But the supporters of the repeal measure, Proposition 28,
spearheaded by a national chain of retail cigarette stores called
``Cigarettes Cheaper!,'' want to stop the impressive progress
California is making. Proposition 10 squeaked through with a tiny 1
percent approval margin, even though the tobacco industry spent $30
million in a media blitz to attack the measure. The Proposition 28
supporters think that the small margin gives them a chance to turn
the vote around. But this time, the big tobacco manufacturers,
perhaps chastened by public dismay at the industry's tactics and
the fact that they lost in 1998 despite their heavy spending, are
apparently not financing the repeal effort. Even without that
infusion of tobacco cash, the ballot fight will be tough.
California voters did the right thing in approving Proposition 10.
They should reaffirm that vote by turning down Proposition 28.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
