<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EDS-EARNINGS-490&AMP;ADD-     02-03 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDS-EARNINGS-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOURFOLD RISE IN CONTRACTS HIGHLIGHTS EDS EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (js) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Electronic Data Systems, the Texas computer services
concern that is rebounding from two disastrous years, reported
fourth-quarter earnings Thursday that topped Wall Street estimates,
and announced a more than fourfold increase in new contracts during
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   EDS, based in Plano, Texas, said it earned 61 cents a share, or
$295 million, during the three months ended Dec. 31, up from 53
cents a share, or $264.1 million, the year earlier. Both numbers
exclude special gains and charges, including $422.2 million in
pretax revamping charges during the fourth quarter of 1999, which
was attributed mainly to a continued reduction in the number of
employees. Revenue for the quarter rose 11 percent from the
year-earlier quarter, to $4.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, who said the results appeared to indicate the
company's turnaround was progressing faster than anticipated, had
expected earnings of 59 cents a share, and several said Thursday
that the consensus forecast for full-year 2000 earnings of $2.26 a
share now appeared too conservative. But Wall Street seemed to be
more surprised by the $11.2 billion in new contract signings during
the quarter. Total new signings for the year were $24.9 billion,
double the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Burns, a PaineWebber analyst, said he expected to
increase his estimates for earnings this year to around $2.30 a
share from $2.25, and that there might still be ``upside to those
numbers as well.'' At Merrill Lynch, Stephen McClellan said his
estimate of $2.30 a share this year now appeared conservative given
the results, and he said the amount of new bookings exceeded even
bullish estimates. ``It's quite a nice confirmation of a building
momentum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stock rose strongly in trading Thursday morning before the
results were officially released, touching highs above $73, after
partial information appeared on the company's Web page because of
what EDS officials said was human error. After trading was halted
and the earnings report was released in full, shares resumed
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, finishing at $69.9375, up
$1.5625.
</P>
<P>
   EDS was demoralized and in disarray during much of 1997 and
1998, as both customers and investors viewed the company as
rudderless. It repeatedly missed earnings estimates amid what EDS
officials said was an increasingly competitive market as well as
the discovery that a number of contracts would be less profitable
than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The company's operating profit margin rose to 9.7 percent for
the quarter, from 8.9 percent during the same period in 1998. In an
interview, Richard H. Brown, the company's chief executive officer,
whom the board hired late in 1998, attributed the increase in the
profit margin to the reduction of employees and other measures.
``This is proof that our cost-reduction efforts and other
improvements we promised are clearly taking traction,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Brown said the company's total backlog of contracts now stood at
well more than $60 billion, an increase of more than 20 percent
from last year, and that excluding revenue from General Motors
Corp., which used to own EDS, the company would post revenue growth
of at least 14 percent to 16 percent this year. But he also said
investors should not expect a big gain in revenue during the first
quarter, because it usually takes several quarters for the effect
of new contract bookings to be fully felt.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which now has revenue of more than $1 billion
annually from Internet business, also said it had started a $1.5
billion venture fund to invest in Internet-related companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
