<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DUTCHESS-POLITICS-     02-03 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DUTCHESS-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RACE FOR COUNTY CLERK LIES A TALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT40 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ For those who thought the fight to keep
John McCain off the Republican ballot played out like a grand
political potboiler, try this one.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Republican boss who resembles a latter-day Marlon
Brando is indicted on corruption charges. One of the boss's former
allies drowns in the Hudson River. Another former ally videotapes
two women engaged in lesbian trysts at a water-pumping station,
later asks one to murder the other, according to court documents,
then tries to commit suicide himself.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and the boss' son? He loses to an unknown Democrat in his
re-election race for county clerk by 59 votes, then forces an
unprecedented do-over vote in one remote town with the support of
the Republican elections commissioner, who happens to be his
father.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing Thursday in Brooklyn, a state appellate court heard
arguments from lawyers for the Democratic candidate for county
clerk, Richard Anderson, to reverse a lower court's decision and
let the November results stand, canceling the repeat vote in the
town of Northeast scheduled for Tuesday. A decision is expected on
Friday, and further appeals are still possible.
</P>
<P>
   A new election would give a second chance to the Republican
incumbent, William L. Paroli Jr., the son of William L. Paroli Sr.,
the former county Republican leader who is under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   It adds up to a baroque tale of exurban intrigue, made all the
more incongruous by its pastoral and genteel setting. But it is
also a cautionary tale about politics and power, since much of
upstate New York is dominated by the cozy world of one-party
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the cast as minor characters, are big names from both
parties who are trying to frame the events of the last year or so
to serve their political interests.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George E. Pataki, for one, has responded to the drumbeat of
concerns that Paroli may be a liability to the Republicans,
appointing a New York City lawyer to investigate the removal of
Paroli as elections commissioner. Most Republicans here, meanwhile,
have distanced themselves from Paroli, even though Paroli has
always maintained his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Most people expected that Anderson, a 57-year-old retired IBM
employee, would be routed in his race for county clerk against
Paroli, a 49-year-old former sales manager who had easily won his
two previous races. But, shocker of shockers, Anderson edged Paroli
by 59 votes out of 47,000 cast.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for an unfamiliar political dogfight in a
county accustomed to Republican sweeps. The repercussions included,
among other twists, the attempt by Paroli's father to schedule an
extra day of voting once the results had come in, citing bad
weather on Election Day. Ultimately, Judge John LaCava of state
Supreme Court, a Republican, ordered a special election only in the
town of Northeast, where Anderson had prevailed 308-294, saying
that the ballot had been confusing.
</P>
<P>
   The net effect has been an odd spectacle: a nonprimary race in
February in which Anderson and Paroli have been campaigning door to
door in order to capture an $85,000-a-year post overseeing motor
vehicle registrations and maintaining tax, land and other official
records.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has not been shy about linking Paroli pere and fils;
Paroli, on the other hand, has been trying to run on his record.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to confuse me with my father, and it's
frustrating,'' Paroli said during a recent visit to the dairy farm
of Northeast's Republican leader, John J. Perotti. ``But I'm
telling people: Should you visit the alleged sins of the father on
the son, or vote for the best man with the best record?''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Paroli, 71, a retired police detective, has developed
a reputation for being a tenacious, Boss Tweed-like party figure.
</P>
<P>
   But last year he was indicted by federal authorities on 16
counts of corruption that contend that he forced developers to make
payments to the local Republican party and himself totaling more
than $100,000 over a six-year period, in exchange for permits and
tax breaks. Paroli's case is scheduled to go to trial late next
month, but four others have been convicted on federal charges
stemming from the same investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at his house here, Paroli, an affable man with a
gravelly voice, repeated that he is innocent, and that his current
quagmire is the work of enemies.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Paroli blamed two of his former Republican
friends: Basil Raucci, Poughkeepsie's former tax assessor, and Fred
Andros, Poughkeepsie's former water superintendent. Paroli saved
his harshest words for Andros, who pleaded guilty in U.S. District
Court in White Plains in May to collecting bribes for Paroli.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a small man with a Napoleonic complex who wants to be
bigger than he is,'' Paroli said. ``These guys were really out
there, shaking the trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Raucci and Andros are not exactly in a position to
defend themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Raucci was found drowned in 1997 in the Hudson River. His death
was ruled a suicide, but rumors of foul play have never dissipated.
Andros, meanwhile, is in the Dutchess County jail's infirmary ward,
recovering from a self-inflicted gunshot wound.
</P>
<P>
   Andros shot himself just before police were going to charge him
in connection with the shooting death of Susan Fassett, 48,
Poughkeepsie's former personnel director. The police also arrested
Dawn Silvernail, 50, of upstate Greene County, for shooting Fassett
in a church parking lot in October. Silvernail and Andros have both
been charged with second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   In court documents released last week, Silvernail was quoted by
the police as saying that Andros _ her former lover _ had coerced
her into shooting Fassett. She also said that Andros had paid her
to have sex with Fassett on several occasions inside a town
water-pumping station.
</P>
<P>
   Andros, she added, videotaped the encounters, then joined them.
</P>
<P>
   How all of this will register for voters of Northeast,
population 3,000, in Tuesday's scheduled election is anybody's
guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just talking to people, I think there's a general sense of
`Geez, isn't this over yet? What's going on?''' said Steve
Utterback, news director of WKZE in Sharon, Conn., across the
border from Northeast. ``People see it as a soap opera playing down
in Poughkeepsie. It's like, `Oh, those people from the big city
again.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
